<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU INSIST, BOSS, I'LL TELECOMMUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Thousands of Valley residents thumbed their noses at
freeways Tuesday, firing up their modems and working at home to
celebrate Telework Greater Phoenix Day.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Phoenix area residents today are begging their
bosses to let them work at home every day. Why? One telecommuter's
diary:
</P>
<P>
   7 a.m.: Bolt upright in bed, brimming with energy inspired by
exciting new way of working. Run through quick mental checklist of
all the things that will be accomplished today without the
distractions of . . .
</P>
<P>
   7:34 a.m.: Wake up again. Feel gnawing in stomach, thinking of
ugly commute on Phoenix area freeways. Wait! What commute? I'm
telecommuting, baby!
</P>
<P>
   7:35 a.m.: Decline customary shower. No one else around to
notice stench.
</P>
<P>
   7:36 a.m.: Decline customary pants. No one else around to notice
underwear.
</P>
<P>
   7:37 a.m.: Decline customary shirt. No one else around to notice
gut.
</P>
<P>
   7:38 a.m.: See self in mirror.
</P>
<P>
   7:39 a.m.: Quickly shower, put on pants and shirt.
</P>
<P>
   7:42 a.m.: Listen to radio for traffic report. Laugh heartily at
mindless recreants crawling to work on freeways.
</P>
<P>
   8 a.m.: Put biscuits in oven. Hearty breakfast crucial. Much
work to be done _ sustenance is important.
</P>
<P>
   8:15 a.m.: Turn on computer. Arrange desk with memos, pens,
notebooks, other necessary work items. Dash off e-mail to boss _
doubtless stuck in cruel traffic jam _ about how much you're
accomplishing by working at home.
</P>
<P>
   8:18 a.m.: Smell smoke. Remember biscuits. Sprint to stove. Toss
flaming black hunks of coal into sink. Extinguish.
</P>
<P>
   8:20 a.m.: Eat bowl of cereal.
</P>
<P>
   8:25 a.m.: Begin working in earnest. Log on to Internet for sole
purpose of reading nation's newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   10:30 a.m.: Log off Internet after spending five minutes reading
random headlines in three papers. Balance of time spent crying with
laughter over theonion.com, ordering six books at amazon.com,
navigating labyrinth of distracting Web sites devoted to
quasi-religion of skateboarding.
</P>
<P>
   10:32 a.m.: Snack. Much work to be done _ sustenance is
important.
</P>
<P>
   10:40 a.m.: Buckle down. Nose to grindstone. Give 110 percent.
</P>
<P>
   10:41 a.m.: Search Internet for Web sites devoted to cliches.
</P>
<P>
   11:55 a.m.: Log off Internet after spending 30 seconds looking
at cliche site. Balance of time spent in fruitless pursuit of
lyrics to ``Willie Claus,'' an obscure novelty Christmas song.
</P>
<P>
   Noon: Lunch. Much work to be done _ sustenance is important.
</P>
<P>
   12:30 p.m.: Turn on television _ CNN only.
</P>
<P>
   12:21 p.m.: Distracted by yokel asking idiotic question about
Kosovo on ``Talk Back Live!'' Make quick switch to ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   1:15 p.m.: Wake up. Refreshed. Eager to begin work.
</P>
<P>
   1:20 p.m.: Start 15 minutes of honest-to-goodness, uninterrupted
work.
</P>
<P>
   1:30 p.m.: OK, 10. Reward self by eating low-fat yogurt directly
from container. Without spoon.
</P>
<P>
   1:40 p.m.: Play with dogs in back yard in attempt to get
creative juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   1:45 p.m.: Attempt to clean disgusting dog mess off shoe.
</P>
<P>
   1:48 p.m.: Throw shoe away.
</P>
<P>
   2:10 p.m.: Work for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2:40 p.m.: Reward self with nap, setting 15-minute time limit.
</P>
<P>
   3:45 p.m.: Wake up. Feel guilt. Banish with Hershey bar.
</P>
<P>
   3:50 p.m.: Work effort derailed by sound of children home from
school playing Wiffle ball in street.
</P>
<P>
   3:55 p.m.: Ask biggest kid for three cuts. Decline to rent
Playboy's Girls Next Door for him in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   4:15 p.m.: Check e-mail. Reply to boss' inquiry by saying you
can't remember feeling so refreshed and well-rested.
</P>
<P>
   4:30 p.m.: Snack. Much work to be done _ sustenance is
important.
</P>
<P>
   4:45 p.m.: More work.
</P>
<P>
   5 p.m.: Switch on radio. Scoff at commuters sweltering in
gridlock, exhausted from hard day's work.
</P>
<P>
   5:15 p.m.: Knock off for day. Note time; consider putting in for
overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m. today: Get to office early. Hope to catch up. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828 or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
