<SLUG> BC-`I-WAS-RIGHT'-MASSACRE-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO OWNS UP TO CONVOY MASSACRE _ SORT OF  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: Follow-up to BC-PROOF-NATO-GUILTY-FISK, moved 4-17)   (This 600-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ At last, NATO has owned up to the Kosovo convoy
massacre _ but grudgingly, without any real expression of sorrow
and with a lot of unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   Brigadier General Leaf referred only to ``the accident scene''
while NATO's spokesmen _ asked Monday what he felt on watching
video of a bomb explosion that killed innocent civilians _ replied
with stunning inadequacy: ``I felt a sense that this is
regrettable.''
</P>
<P>
   This hardly matched the human misery and torn corpses we saw on
the road between Prizren and Djakovica last week.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was General Leaf's presentation entirely accurate. Reporters
did not claim refugees had been killed by machine-gun fire, only
that there were signs they may have been straffed by cannon or
machine-gun fire; we were not told if the A-10s _ which carry
cannons and were present at the scene _ opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did we learn where the mysterious ``intelligence
information'' suggesting the refugee convoy was a ``VJ'' (Yugoslav
army) column came from.
</P>
<P>
   From America's new friends in the Kosovo Liberation Army,
perhaps? And why did the later ``intelligence'' _ to the effect
that the Serb military do not usually travel in long convoys _
reach the American F-16s too late to stop the attacks?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Clinton told the world only one NATO bomb
was dropped. Monday, we learned that nine GBU-12 500-lb. bombs had
been dropped on the Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   We also learned that the markings of bomb parts found at the
scene by the ``Independent of London'' corresponded exactly to the
NATO ordnance dropped on April 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible that there were civilian casualties at both
locations,'' General Leaf said, referring to the four attack areas.
``Possible'' was not the word to cover the reality of the burned
skeletons and eviscerated civilians we saw last week.
</P>
<P>
   Were there Serb military vehicles mixed up in the convoy, as
General Leaf suggested? If there were, none were hit _ for the only
wreckage marks on the tarmac were those of tractors and trailers
that still stood on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   I did see Serb special forces and police using civilian cars on
that same highway the following day _ and General Leaf was correct
when he said the Serb military use civilian vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But what does that imply? That NATO can open fire on every milk
float driving through Kosovo?
</P>
<P>
   The general did his best to prove the pilots had ``acted in good
faith.'' He pointed out the horror felt by an F-16 pilot who saw
house-burning on the ground before he attacked.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO pilots are not supposed to drop bombs according to
their emotions _ and the impression General Leaf left behind was of
a gung-ho air force whose intelligence was first wrong and then _
when it was right _ came too late to avoid the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite ``reports'' that survivors claimed they were attacked by
Serb aircraft, the general admitted there was no military
verification of this.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, NATO came clean _ up to a point _ which is something the
Serbs would not have done; and if the purpose of the briefing was
to put the convoy massacre behind it before NATO celebrated its
50th birthday, the tactic was probably successful.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's admissions would have carried more moral weight if
they had included some remorse for the terrible thing that was done
on the road to Prizren last week.
</P>
<P>
   The final message was simple: we did it _ but don't blame us. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 600-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
