<HEADER>
A6777 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-21 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 IN COLO. SCHOOL SAID TO GUN DOWN AS MANY AS 23, THEN KILL
THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 1st take to change to `young men' in lede, sted
`teen-age boys,' UPDATE with two students being held for
questioning, RAISE background on group, recast chronology of
shooting in grafs 2-3, ADD fresh student quotes; 2nd take stands.) 
(With COLO-SCHOOL-SCENE, COLO-SCHOOL-SUSPECTS) 
 (mb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ In the deadliest school massacre in the
nation's history, two young men stormed into a suburban high school
here at lunch time Tuesday with guns and explosives and killed as
many as 23 people and wounded at least 20 in a six-hour siege, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 11:15 a.m., the gunmen, wearing ski masks, stalked
through Columbine High School as they shot semiautomatic weapons
and tossed explosives at students and teachers, with one student
being hit nine times in the chest by shrapnel, the authorities
said. Gunshots continued to ring out at the school for hours, and a
bomb exploded in the school parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   At about 3 p.m., hundreds of police officers evacuated the
building and searched for the suspected gunmen _ both juniors at
the school _ who were found dead of self-inflicted gunshot wounds
in the library, with what appeared to be bombs around their bodies,
a sheriff's spokesman, Steve Davis, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to be a suicide mission,'' Sheriff John Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaleb Newberry, 16, said: ``I was in class and one teacher came
in and basically told us to run for our lives, I saw a girl maybe
five paces behind me fall. She was shot in the leg, but a teacher
helped her. It was so scary, so close to home.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, 14-year-old Katie Corona, said she was trapped
in a classroom with her teacher and about 30 classmates for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' she said. ``I really didn't
think I was going to make it. We would hear shots, then we heard
crying. We had no clue what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Some victims were forced to wait inside the school for rescue.
By early evening, bodies had not been removed because of the crime
scene investigation and the possible presence of explosives, a
spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department said. No
precise death toll was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said at a news conference Tuesday night that two other
students at the school, thought to be friends of the gunmen, were
in custody for questioning in connection with the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Students said the gunmen were part of a group of misfits who
called themselves the trench coat mafia and appeared to aim at
minority members and athletes at the 1,800 student school, as well
as peers who had poked fun at them in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone around me got shot and I begged him for 10 minutes
not to shoot me,'' one young woman, who was not identified, said in
an interview broadcast on CNN Tuesday night. ``And he just put the
gun in my face and started bleeding everywhere and stared laughing
and saying it was all because people were mean to him last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, who said she heard more gunshots while hiding
in the closet with a teacher and some friends, said she kept
thinking to herself: ``This can't be happening to our school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be safe at school,'' added a second young woman,
who also was not identified. ``This should be a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   The mass shooting was the first at an American school during
this academic year, but revived memories of similar tragedies that
struck six different communities last year and set off national
alarms about teen-age violence. The nation's previous worst school
shooting occurred last March when four girls and a teacher were
shot to death and 10 people were wounded during a false fire alarm
at a middle school in Jonesboro, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, President Clinton dispatched a crisis-response team to
aid the Littleton community and the victim's families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know yet all the hows or whys of this tragedy;
perhaps we will never fully understand it,'' the president said in
a nationally televised news conference. ``St. Paul reminds us that
we all see things in life darkly, that we only partly understand
what is happening.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We do know that we must do more to reach out to our
children and teach them to express their anger and to resolve their
conflicts with words, not weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   A sunny spring day turned into a bloody nightmare for this
suburb of 35,000 people southwest of Denver, as ambulances ferried
the injured past tennis courts, a baseball diamond and a packed
student parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic parents swarmed at a nearby elementary school after the
police secured the high school; one woman was crying into her cell
phone: ``Her name is not on any list. They don't know where she
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Appleton, 16, a sophomore, waited in front of the
elementary school just before 8 p.m. for news of her best friend,
Julie Toms, who had been missing since students began leaving the
school. ``I can't even feel it,'' she said. ``There's no way to
know whether she's dead or alive.''
</P>
<P>
   At about 3 p.m., SWAT team police officers used a fire truck and
an armored car to get close to the building, and dozens of students
raced out of the two-story building, some slipping in the mud,
others holding up their hands in the air or behind their heads. The
police said they feared that the gunmen would try to escape by
mingling with the trapped students.
</P>
<P>
   One bloodied student broke out a second-floor window, and
climbed down into the hands of the police.
</P>
<P>
   As police officers established a wide perimeter around the
school, stunned students and school workers gathered on nearby
tree-lined streets and told of the chaos and horror inside the
building.
</P>
<P>
   As fire alarms rang in the halls, students who had seen the
gunmen trampled each other to get out of the building, running
through one exit where three bodies lay on a staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped inside, others took refuge in classrooms, bathrooms, and
a choir room, frantically barricading doors with desks and file
cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood was going all over,'' a shaken girl said, as she was
comforted by her father outside the school.
</P>
<P>
   One cafeteria worker who had barricaded herself in a woman's
bathroom, said, ``We could hear them blowing the heck out of the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Ladd, a student, said, ``I heard gunshots going off,
bullets ricocheting off lockers.''
</P>
<P>
   Several trapped students used their cellular telephones to call
television stations when they could not get through on 911 lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a couple of gunshots, people running up and down,'' a
student said in a frightened whisper to KUSA-TV, a Denver
television station. Identifying himself only as James, he added,
``There are a bunch of kids downstairs, I can hear them crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly aware that the gunmen might be watching on a classroom
television set, he said ``I am staying upstairs,'' and then hung
up.
</P>
<P>
   In a state with a relatively low crime rate, the siege after the
shootings was broadcast live on television all afternoon and into
the evening without commercial breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cultural virus,'' Gov. Bill Owens of Colorado said
before hurrying to the scene. Noting that he felt particularly
affected by the tragedy because his 16-year-old daughter goes to a
suburban Denver high school, he said, ``We have to ask ourselves
what kind of children we are raising.''
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon, police officers detained three young white men
wearing camouflage pants and black jackets after spotting them in a
park next to the high school. Later, they said they knew the gunmen
inside the high school. Emblazoned on the back of one man's jacket
were the words, ``Ban Religion'' and a red-painted stop sign
printed over a cross.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Trench Coat Mafia is a small band of about a dozen juniors
and seniors at Columbine who are easily recognized yet little
feared, according to people who live in the neighborhood near the
school. Regardless of the weather, they favor long black coats and
the Gothic look popularized by the rock singer Marilyn Manson,
neighbors said. Some even wear white pancake makeup and dark
eyeliner, according to one student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that devilish, half-dead, half-alive look,'' said Bret,
a 16-year-old sophomore who spoke on the condition that only his
first name be used.
</P>
<P>
   The group often gathered in the cafeteria after school. Chris
McCaffrey, manager of Angie's Restaurant a few blocks from the
school, said that residents have known about the group for about
five years, and that no one considered it a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly it was just kids who nobody wanted to have anything to
do with,'' McCaffrey said. ``They weren't particularly feared. They
were just a bunch of punks who kind of hang around the school.''
</P>
<P>
   Students said the group was mostly boys, but that some girls
appeared to be closely associated with it. One student described
the group as ``nerds, geeks and dweebs trying to find someplace to
fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret suggested the gunmen might have targeted athletes out of
resentment for their own lack of popularity and success at school.
</P>
<P>
   The students ``weren't really accepted as younger kids and as
they got older they were accepted by this group,'' Bret said.
``They got their fair share of being picked on. I could understand
that they might have targeted some of the more popular kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Those here were reminded of other school shooting incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the seventh time it has happened,'' Bob Sapin, a
shaken student told a television station minutes after watching two
young men shoot students. ``I just can't believe it is happening at
my school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
