<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: PASSENGERS TO EUROPE BE DELAYED BY TROOP
MOVEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code) 
 (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the Clinton administration has said it has no plans to
send U.S. troops to the Balkans, if in fact it does order large
numbers of troops there, many GIs as well as tons of cargo will
likely be airlifted on civilian planes. And depending on the
duration of the airlift, travelers bound even for Western Europe
can probably expect delays and inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   The troop transport plan involving civil aircraft, named Civil
Reserve Air Fleet, was devised by the Pentagon and the airline
industry in 1952. As Robert J. Serling explains in his book, ``When
the Airlines Went to War'' (Kensington Books, 1997), although the
plan was drawn up during the Korean War, it was not used until the
1960s, when airlines assisted the rapid military buildup in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines were used again during the Persian Gulf war, during
an even faster buildup. At that time, 11 civilian airlines, 3
overnight delivery airlines and 13 supplemental airlines answered
the call. They flew more than 5,300 missions, carried 64 percent of
the troops and just under 27 percent of the war cargo. Planes from
the overnight delivery fleets flew almost 900 of those flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many commercial pilots come from a military background, and if
they're in the Reserves and they're called to duty that could lead
to some crew scheduling headaches at major airlines,'' said Tim
Smith of American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Serling, speaking by phone Tuesday from his home in Arizona,
said: ``The civil planes have already been allocated for possible
use by the military in Yugoslavia. If they're needed, they'll be
pulled out of the fleets in stages and turned over to the Pentagon,
which will assign their routes and destinations.''
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE BOOKINGS AFFECTED BY KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   The current NATO bombing campaign in the Balkans, meanwhile, is
exacting a growing toll on the travel industry. Carnival Corp. said
Monday that the conflict was hurting its cruise bookings to the
eastern Mediterranean, causing cancellations that would likely
affect its earnings. That same day Celebrity and Costa Cruises said
they would change some of their itineraries because of the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   While few Americans have canceled reservations for late spring
or summer trips to Western Europe, travel agents worry that many
more will do so if hostilities drag on.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity, owned by Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd., has made
changes to two of the Celebrity Century's Adriatic cruises. Its
15-night trans-Atlantic crossing starting from Fort Lauderdale,
Fla., this Saturday will now end in Genoa, Italy, instead of
Venice, which is closer to the fighting. And its 12-day eastern
Mediterranean cruise scheduled to depart from Venice on May 16 will
instead leave from Savona, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Costa, owned by Carnival, will move its Costa Classica and Costa
Victoria ships to Genoa from their Venice home port. In addition,
the Costa Victoria's seven-night cruises to Greece and Turkey,
scheduled to operate from May 9 through Oct. 31, have been changed
to a Greek island itinerary, departing from Genoa and returning to
Naples. Costa Classica's seven-night Greek island cruises from May
31 through Oct. 18 have been changed to a western Mediterranean
itinerary departing from Genoa and returning to Naples. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
