<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL WHERE KILLINGS OCCURRED IS IN RELATIVELY NEW COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING and related stories) 
(mk) 
 By MARK PARGAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the late 1960s and early 1970s, many residents of Denver
began to consider a move to the country, with the promise of new
schools, ranch-style homes with big back yards and a glorious view
of the Front Range of the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine High School, situated in an unincorporated part of
southern Jefferson County, was built in that era. The school and
surrounding housing tracts have Littleton addresses, but little
else in common with that quaint Arapahoe County town of 35,000 just
15 miles southwest of downtown Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The high school, with an enrollment of 1,800, draws from the
largely white, middle-class housing developments that roll
southwest toward Bear Creek and the foothill town of Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County, formerly the western frontier of Denver,
experienced rapid growth in the '60s and '70s, decades in which
housing developments with names like Columbine Knolls, Columbine
Hills and Ken Caryl Ranch brought Windsor and Kentucky Bluegrass
lawns to replace the brush at the foot of the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Racial issues in the Denver public schools helped both push the
first residents into the area and set a pace of growth that
accelerated until the oil bust years of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   A resurgent economy and the completion of State Highway 470,
designed to take motorists around the southwest suburbs and allow
them to avoid the snarl of Interstates 25 and 70 that intersect in
the city of Denver, helped fuel more housing development in a
region that still draws many from California with the lure of large
lots and great views.
</P>
<P>
   The region's sprawling housing pattern share the look and feel
of areas like the San Fernando Valley and Orange County in
California, the northern and eastern suburbs of Seattle and much of
the west valley of Salt Lake City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
