A6800 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-PLAYOFFS-TE     04-21 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SAY PLUSES WILL OFFSET MINUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ken Hitchcock's not worried so much about what's
missing from the Stars' lineup. He's more excited about what has
been added.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will be without suspended captain Derian Hatcher for
the first five games of their best-of-seven Western Conference
quarterfinals series with the Edmonton Oilers, which starts tonight
at 7:30 at Reunion Arena. But the focus hasn't been on the loss of
their best defenseman, the Stars coach said; it has been, instead,
on the wealth of talent the Stars have added to their offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at the lineup that played against Edmonton last
year, there's a huge difference,'' Hitchcock said. ``We think we're
a better offensive team. We're quicker than we were last year;
we're more skilled than we were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   While fans across the NHL gaped in awe when the Colorado
Avalanche added Theo Fleury and the Detroit Red Wings added Chris
Chelios and Wendel Clark, few recognize just how much the Stars
have added. With the free-agent signing of Brett Hull over the
summer and the renewed health of Joe Nieuwendyk, who missed last
season's playoffs with a knee injury, the Stars have injected an
additional 60 goals into their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   That's significant, considering they averaged only 2.1 goals per
game in the playoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a better team and we should be a better team,''
defenseman Craig Ludwig said. ``We've added people every season,
and we expect to be better every season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers also have improved, making numerous trades and
rearranging their lineup. Goalie Tommy Salo is 8-2-2 since being
acquired in a March trade and has helped the Oilers finally find a
replacement for Curtis Joseph, who left as a free agent in the
off-season. In addition, the Oilers almost completely reworked
their defense. Gone are Boris Mironov, Drake Berehowsky, Bobby
Dollas and Greg deVries. In are Christian LaFlamme, Tom Poti, Jason
Smith and Marty McSorley.
</P>
<P>
   That means the battle of the Stars' offense vs. the Oilers'
defense and goaltending could be the wild card that swings the
first-round series. But equally important could be the Stars' skill
vs. the Oilers' strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers already have vowed to play a physical series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the type of team that forces turnovers,'' McSorley said.
``The best way to force turnovers is by being physical.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Oilers err on the side of being too physical, the
Stars have to be prepared to make them pay with a revamped power
play led by Hull's 15 man-advantage goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be better, it has to be there,'' Nieuwendyk said of
a power play that operated at a paltry 10 percent in last season's
playoffs and was often blamed for taking energy out of the Stars.
``I think all of us think it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   By adding Hull and Nieuwendyk, the Stars have more depth and
more options with the man advantage. Hull can score from a distance
with a startling one-timer that gives the Stars ``something we've
never had before,'' Hitchcock said. Hull's booming shot is the home
run punch, the 3-point shot, the long pass threat that can open up
the rest of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Add that to Nieuwendyk's ability to mix in tactical
goal-scoring, and leading goal scorer Mike Modano all of the sudden
gets a whole lot less attention from opposing checkers. With
Nieuwendyk scoring 15 goals in the final 21 games, he'll be the
kind of player that opponents will have to consider in drawing up
their defensive assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say how much it means to have all three of them in
the lineup at one time,'' center Guy Carbonneau said. ``If we have
those three healthy, we're a team that can score goals.''
</P>
<P>
   And that might be the Stars' biggest goal for the playoffs this
season. In their elimination series the previous two seasons, the
Stars have been shut down on offense and shut down on the power
play. At no time, have they lost their defensive compass.
</P>
<P>
   So, even with Hatcher out, the Stars expect to be a team that
can rely on their depth of defensemen, the play of their defensive
forwards and strong goaltending. But can they become a team that
develops a killer instinct on offense? Can they become a team that
can draw back and put the dagger through an opponent with a
well-placed goal ... or two ...or three?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got people who can score goals,'' Hitchcock said. ``And
if we're going to win this series, our people who are very capable
of doing things offensively are going to have to be big factors.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
