<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BONDS-INJURED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONDS JOINS LONG LIST OF STARS OUT OF ACTION
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barry Bonds, the pivotal player on the first-place San Francisco
Giants, Tuesday joined a growing roster of star players who are out
of action and on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor to the disabled list only once in his first 13 years
in the major leagues, Bonds had surgery on his left elbow and
triceps tendon and is expected to miss at least 10 weeks. His
absence will be a blow to the Giants because he was enjoying a
particularly strong start, leading the National League with a
slugging percentage of .805 and hitting .366 with 12 runs batted in
and four home runs in 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark, Baltimore's first baseman, was also placed on the
disabled list Tuesday. He has a fractured left thumb and is
expected to miss four weeks. Cal Ripken, his teammate, who had
never been on the disabled list, is there with nerve irritation in
his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds, Anaheim's center fielder, is out for four months
with a shoulder injury, and Alex Rodriguez, Seattle's shortstop,
had surgery for torn knee cartilage earlier this month and was
expected to face four to six weeks in rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of injuries to star players began just before spring
training when Moises Alou of Houston tore a knee ligament. He hopes
to return for the last month of the season. Kerry Wood of the
Chicago Cubs, an instant star as a rookie last season with a
torrent of strikeouts, tore an elbow ligament during spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants said Bonds' problems did not stem from one incident.
Manager Dusty Baker blamed it on ``20 years of throwing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds told Baker last Friday night during batting practice that
his elbow was bothering him. ``Barry's not one to complain,'' Baker
said Tuesday in San Francisco. ``He knew something was wrong _ and
something was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds, a 34-year-old left-handed hitter and thrower, played
Friday night and Saturday against Arizona, getting a double in
seven times at bat. He missed Sunday's game against the
Diamondbacks and Monday night's game against Florida. A magnetic
resonance imaging test done Monday showed bone spurs in his elbow.
Additional tests found a damaged triceps tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur Ting, the team orthopedist for the San Jose Sharks
hockey team, performed the operation. Dr. William Montgomery, the
Giants' physician, observed the operation and said: ``The prognosis
is that Barry may return to competition in a minimum of 10 weeks'
time. Given his history of recovery from previous surgeries, we're
very optimistic that he will return without incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Conte, the Giants' assistant athletic trainer who also
observed the surgery, said the bone spur and damaged tendon tissue
were right on top of each other. ``The tissue looked better than we
feared, but not as good as we hoped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds is a three-time winner of the Most Valuable Player award,
an eight-time all-star and a seven-time Gold Glove winner. ``It's
probably one of the largest challenges I've faced since I've been
manager here,'' Baker said of running the club in Bonds' absence.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had a surplus of outfielders in spring training and
considered trading one, perhaps Stan Javier. But they decided to
keep their outfield platoon intact, and Javier will replace the
best left fielder in baseball. The Giants will look for increased
production from Ellis Burks, the right fielder, who hit a three-run
homer in the first inning Monday in San Francisco's 5-4 victory
over the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who last year lost to the Chicago Cubs in a one-game
playoff for the National League's wild-card spot, had been
considered a wild-card candidate at best this season. However, the
Giants got off to a fast start and have been in first place in the
National League West every day so far this season. Bonds hit his
four home runs in the first nine games, six of which the Giants
won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BLOWOUTS-NYT &LR;      04-21 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BLOWOUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: A MODEST SUGGESTION FROM A BLOWOUT VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees' 4-0 victory over the Texas Rangers at
Yankee Stadium on Tuesday night did not qualify for the 10-run rule
that Rangers manager Johnny Oates talked about before the game. But
it might as well have, so dominant was David Cone. The Rangers,
with three harmless singles against Cone in eight innings, did not
have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   That basically was what Oates had been discussing earlier, games
that reach a point where one of the teams has no chance. Major
League Baseball, he suggested, may want to consider instituting a
10-run rule. If one team is ahead by 10 or more runs after seven
innings, he said, the game should end.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like an idea borrowed from softball, it's because
the team that Oates manages, the Texas Rangers, has played some
games this young season that have resembled slow-pitch games. The
Rangers are eminently capable of scoring 10 or more runs in the
first seven innings, but they also are eminently capable of giving
up 10 or more runs in the first seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times does the lead change hands after that?'' Oates
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Based on this season's experience, none. The American League has
had seven games and the National League four games in which the run
differential has been 10 or more after seven innings (10 times) or
eight innings (once). In every instance, the lead did not change;
in most cases, it didn't even shrink much, and the games might as
well have been ended before the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans will get their money's worth,'' Oates said. ``They've
seen three and a half hours of knocking heads. You don't have to
worry about them. You want to speed the game up? The game's been
decided. It's not going to change hands.''
</P>
<P>
   If one-sided games were halted, the former catcher explained,
managers wouldn't be put in the position of using up more pitchers
and possibly calling on a utility player to mop up in the ninth
inning. The rule also would eliminate the chance of brawls caused
when the winning team runs up the score.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, who admitted that as a young fan he prayed for extra
innings so he could see longer games, added one possible exception
to his 10-run rule, at least for current events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire might get two more at-bats in the eighth and
ninth inning,'' he said. ``Fans would want to see that. Maybe the
Cardinals could play nine and everybody else play seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates knows about one-sided games because three of the Rangers'
first eight games featured leads of 10 runs after seven innings.
The Rangers were on the losing end in the first two, against
Detroit opening day and against Anaheim five days later.
Embarrassingly for the Rangers, Rick Helling, their 20-game winner
in 1998, was the starting pitcher in both games.
</P>
<P>
   Helling has not been alone in starting poorly. The Rangers' five
starters have a 7.66 earned run average, next to worst in the
American League, better only than the 8.45 the Minnesota Twins'
starters have amassed.
</P>
<P>
   John Burkett, who lasted only into the third inning Tuesday
night and gave up two home runs to Paul O'Neill after O'Neill had
failed to get a hit in the previous four games, has the worst ERA
on the entire Texas staff, a nice round 12.00. He has pitched a
total of nine innings in his first three starts. Mark Clark has a
10.67 ERA in three starts, and Helling, after making a strong third
start, has an 8.59 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele has been the staff ``ace'' in the early weeks with a
3.78 ERA Mike Morgan, pitching for his major league-record 11th
team in an 18-year career, has been the staff surprise with a 3-0
record in two starts and three relief appearances and a 3.72 ERA
(5.11 as a starter).
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't buy a stock after studying it for only seven or
eight days,'' Oates said. ``We have watched these pitchers for a
long time. We know what they're capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who tried but failed over the winter to sign Randy
Johnson or trade for Roger Clemens, knew going in that their
starting rotation wouldn't be one of the best in the league. But
they also didn't expect their pitchers to be battered the way they
have been. Oates, however, remained confident they would settle
down and provide a much more respectable performance before long.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had these games in July, you wouldn't think twice
about it,'' he said. ``Their earned run averages wouldn't even go
up that much then. But it's the beginning of the season, so it's
much more noticeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, on the way to their second division championship in
three years, the Rangers had a 4.99 staff ERA, just missing the
5.00 plateau that two other teams reached. Oates said he wasn't
sure his pitchers would miss it again this season, but he believed
they would be closer to 5.00 than their present 6.31 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Their chances would probably be better if some of the Rangers'
games ended after seven innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
