<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE'S ARM PUTS END TO YANKS' SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It rained for most of the day before sunlight peeked
briefly over Yankee Stadium, about 90 minutes before Tuesday
night's first pitch. That was about the time David Cone strolled
casually into the clubhouse, looking as if he could take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   This is supposed to be the kind of inclement weather that
challenges Cone, makes his valuable fingers tingle and makes the
Yankees worry a bit. It was a raw 48 degrees at game time, and the
flags perched high above the outfield fence were fluttering. Could
Cone thrive in the chilly conditions and in the panicky conditions
that exist only for the Yankees after a four-game losing streak? Of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Cone continued to baffle opponents with a wider array of pitches
and arm angles than found in some teams' rotations, and Paul
O'Neill ended an 0-for-15 drought with two home runs to power the
Yankees to a much-needed 4-0 victory over the Rangers. It was
necessary for the Yankees to prevail and resume playing like the
formidable team they are, not that anyone suddenly doubts that they
will be playing in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big,'' Cone admitted. ``It was an awful weekend in
Detroit. No one was happy. Maybe it was a wake-up call for us.''
</P>
<P>
   With Cone retiring 16 of the first 18 batters he faced and
O'Neill treating John Burkett like a batting-practice pitcher, the
Yankees rolled. Cone used fastballs and curveballs early and
injected his slider and split-finger pitch a little later to tame
the Rangers on three hits and three walks over eight innings, with
seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill went deep in his first two at-bats and also whacked a
fly ball to the left-field warning track. Things were back to
normal for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beginning of the story, the end of the story and
everything in between was David Cone tonight,'' said Texas manager
Johnny Oates. ``That's as well as I've ever seen him pitch. He had
everything working.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who allowed one hit over five and one-third innings in the
extremely wet conditions of the home opener against the Tigers, was
immune to the cold again Tuesday night and raised his record to 3-0
with an 0.93 earned run average. The 36-year-old right-hander
admits that he has been spurred on by questions about his
surgically repaired shoulder and whether he could pitch splendidly
for another season.
</P>
<P>
   Cone is eliminating the questions and, for now, is the most
reliable starter in the rotation. Opponents have 8 hits in 66
at-bats, an anemic .121 average. Forget the weather, forget the
shoulder and forget Cone's brutal beginning from last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to me,'' Cone said. ``I know I'm going to get
scrutinized after what I've been through. I don't take any offense
to the questions. I use it as motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Cone has never pitched a shutout while going 51-17 with
the Yankees, the interim manager Don Zimmer removed him after 100
pitches and used Mariano Rivera to finish the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him if he got a bonus if he pitches a shutout and he
said no,'' Zimmer said. ``I told him, `You're gone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who knows the season is long and perilous, said, ``It was
the right move.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been almost nine years since the Yankees went four
straight games in which they scored one run or fewer, and they were
in danger of equaling that mark Tuesday night. For about 10
minutes. Then O'Neill crushed Burkett's 2-0 changeup over the
right-center-field fence to knock in Derek Jeter, who had singled,
and give the revived Yankees a 2-0 lead in the first.
</P>
<P>
   After smashing his 0-for-15 slide, O'Neill never even smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief,'' O'Neill said. ``No one wants to go 0 for 5 or
0 for 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer joked, ``He might come in smiling tomorrow. It would be
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees stranded three against Burkett in the second,
O'Neill victimized the laboring right-hander in the third. Burkett
tossed another changeup, and O'Neill drilled it into the first row
of seats about 50 feet from the foul pole in right. It was
O'Neill's fifth homer in 43 at-bats against Burkett, who left two
batters later because Cone's pitching gave Oates no choice.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees' losing streak over, Zimmer should be able to
go out in public today without getting badgered. He was getting his
one-minute haircut in Rye Brook, N.Y., on Monday when, he said, a
75-year-old customer snapped, ``What the heck happened to the
Yankees?''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer said he thought about the two titles the Yankees have won
in the last three years and barked back, ``You're spoiled.'' That
was especially true for fans Tuesday night because of Cone and
O'Neill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
