<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGENDS MUST REALIZE WHEN IT'S TIME TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the summer of 1996, when jockey Julie Krone was
just a few years past her best riding and her most serious
injuries, she got whacked with another career setback.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Saratoga meet was heating up in upstate New York,
one local horse racing writer wrote in his column about a rumor he
had heard concerning Krone.
</P>
<P>
   There are always a lot of rumors around horse racing, one of the
most cutthroat sports in the galaxy, but this one took the prize:
Krone was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the article's publication, the backstretch and
the jockey quarters and the bars around Saratoga were buzzing with
the rumor, which was not true.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take but a day for Krone, her husband and her attorney
to make a speedy trip to the newspaper's managing editor to demand
this rumor be quashed and a correction printed. Krone and her
entourage were justifiably incensed, since the mere hint of a
pregnancy had stopped trainers and owners from asking Krone to ride
their mounts.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, Krone's experience as one of sport's most
accomplished superstars differs from that of Wayne Gretzky, Michael
Jordan, John Elway or Cal Ripken. None of those guys ever had a bad
game or weight gain ``blamed'' on being pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   But for a jockey as fiery, as fearless, as unstoppable as Krone
_ a pixie whirling dervish who became racing's all-time winning
female jockey back in 1988 with her 1,205th win and who is the only
woman to ever ride a Triple Crown winner (Colonial Affair at the
Belmont Stakes in 1993) _ the idea that Krone was being denied the
chance to race was blisteringly infuriating.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, all of these athletic luminaries are exactly the
same:
</P>
<P>
   Losing is unthinkable. Giving less than 100 percent is
incomprehensible. Standing in their way, doubting them or telling
them no will only get you in major trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That's why this all stinks. First it was Jordan, who is 99.99
percent sure he won't ever play another NBA game. Then Gretzky and
Krone, who both retired Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Now Elway is deciding when he'll decide, and Ripken has gone
from baseball's Ironman to the Orioles' disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   If only Dennis Rodman would do us all a favor and take his shoes
and socks _ if he can find them _ and crawl off into the retirement
sunset. His final days in the NBA were far less than glorious,
ending in a pink slip from the fed-up Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gretzky got his final assist, feeding Ranger teammate
Brian Leetch for a thunderous Madison Square Garden goal to put a
fitting end to this prolific, artistic scorer's career. Leetch
decided against taking the souvenir goal-scoring stick back onto
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Krone, in Texas, rode three winners to end her illustrious
career with 3,546 wins, finishing No. 16 among racing's all-time
money winners with $81 million in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitive side of me wanted to go out a winner,'' Krone
said at Lone Star Park, adding her reason for retirement was
because ``I'm tired of getting hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   At 35, her body studded with enough surgical screws and hardware
to set off metal detectors from here to Timbuktu, Krone was right
to call it a career. Horses had thrown her and trampled her, and
the industry wasn't that much nicer. Krone said she had nothing
left to prove _ quite a feat for a woman who had to battle
stereotypes in addition to everything else it takes to become one
of the best riders in horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gretzky, who at 38 knew it was not worth risking his neck
anymore to play the game he elevated and helped bring to the
American masses, Krone's body said she was done.
</P>
<P>
   Like Jordan, Gretzky knew that his all-time greatest status put
a premium on him making the right decision to leave before the game
crushed him.
</P>
<P>
   That is what Elway is grappling with now. In Denver, citizens
are on Elway Alert _ a drill practiced last spring when Elway
deliberated long and hard before deciding to play again in 1998.
Now, though, the end could be for real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you've got to listen to your body,'' Elway said
after beating the Falcons in the Super Bowl, winning the MVP award
and limping off to his Miami hotel for a victory cigar.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing Elway and the Broncos execute so well at the Super
Bowl, it was impossible not to suggest Elway should come back for a
chance at a third consecutive Super Bowl. With Bubby Brister at
backup and the Broncos prepared to run an offense to protect and
best use Elway, why not? It would be history.
</P>
<P>
   But that is where Ripken's plight comes into consideration. Why
risk your legacy?
</P>
<P>
   After never missing a start in 2,632 games, Ripken is now on the
disabled list for the first time in his 19-year career. If his
tortoise-like runs to first base and his faltering batting average
weren't enough to signal the end last season, his now very bad back
has seriously diminished Ripken's ability at third base and at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons are pretty simple. It takes courage to keep on
playing, year after year, battling injuries and advancing age. It
takes even more courage to walk away, head held high, knowing the
decision was on your terms.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
