<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKETT FAILS AGAIN; RANGERS MULL OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Right-hander John Burkett's days as a member of the
Rangers' rotation appear to be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's 4-0 defeat to the defending World Series champion
New York Yankees only strengthened the possibility of it occurring
before the Rangers return to Texas from this 13-day, 12-game road
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, who allowed 10 of 14 batters to reach safely in his
two-inning stint, failed to pitch five innings for the third time
in as many starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always thinking about alternatives, but I can't start
talking about it publicly,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
``I'll do it privately first.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Esteban Loaiza, who pitched himself out of the
rotation with his performance this spring, appears to be on the
verge of regaining his once-lost opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza inherited Burkett's third-inning jam and kept the Rangers
within striking distance by surrendering only one run on four hits
in a 3 2/3-inning appearance that included four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loaiza looked like he wanted to change his job description,''
Oates said. ``He had a look in his eyes tonight. He doesn't like
sitting down there \Rin the bullpen\S that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Performance, though, might not be the only reason for what could
be Burkett's exit from the rotation. Burkett experienced tightness
in his right shoulder after his departure and planned to return to
Texas this morning to be examined by Dr. John Conway, the Rangers'
orthopedic consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Among Burkett's many failures last night included two home runs
surrendered to right fielder Paul O'Neill, who entered the game
mired in an 0-for-15 slump. O'Neill's two-run, first-inning home
run came on a 2-0 changeup thrown up in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether that was a changeup or a fastball,'' said
Oates, who indicated that there might not be enough difference in
velocity between the two pitches to make the changeup an effective
pitch for Burkett.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's first home run gave the Yankees a 2-0 lead, and his
third-inning blast put the Rangers at a three-run disadvantage.
Burkett then surrendered a single to center fielder Bernie
Williams, and an ensuing walk to first baseman Tino Martinez
brought Oates from the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the rotation, Oates said: ``... we're still
evaluating that and see where we want to go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Loaiza, left-hander Eric Gunderson and right-hander Danny
Patterson kept the Rangers in the game with six innings of solid
relief. The lineup, though, mustered only three singles and three
walks against right-hander David Cone (3-0), who never allowed a
runner beyond second base during eight scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup, though, does not present the concern that Burkett
does, and only three options appear to exist:
</P>
<P>
   Leave Burkett in the rotation. That appears unlikely. Burkett
departed Yankee Stadium with an 0-2 record and 12.00 earned-run
average through three starts covering only nine innings, and
opponents are hitting .468 (22-for-47) against him.
</P>
<P>
   Banish Burkett to the bullpen and insert Loaiza into the
rotation. A National League scout who attended last night's game
raved about Loaiza's sinker-slider combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two sliders were as good as you'll ever want to see,''
the scout said of Loaiza's third-inning pitches to catcher Jorge
Posada and left fielder Ricky Ledee. ``He's got a great arm, but
that's why he's such a tease. You know how many great arms have
been in the major leagues over the past five or six years? A lot,
and they don't stick around. They just don't know how to pitch, and
they never learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Release Burkett. The 34-year-old pitcher's $4 million salary
this season is guaranteed, but releasing him would prevent an
option year from vesting. The two-year, $8.45 million contract
extension Burkett signed in April 1997 included options for the
2000 and 2001 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers can purchase the option for 2000 for $450,000, but
the contract vests if Burkett makes 30 starts or pitches 195
innings this season. Releasing Burkett, though, likely would force
the Rangers into promoting a pitcher from their minor-league
system.
</P>
<P>
   None of the options appears attractive. The decision, though,
belongs to the Rangers.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
