<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG TREATMENT LAW WORKS, SUPREME COURT STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Arizona Supreme Court says hundreds of drug
abusers have been cleaned up and more than $2.5 million in prison
costs have been saved by the state's new medical marijuana law.
</P>
<P>
   But a top aide to Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley says
Proposition 200 is doing a less effective job than the decade-old
``Do Drugs, Do Time'' diversion program.
</P>
<P>
   Approved by the voters in 1996, Proposition 200 provided more
than $2 million in liquor tax money last fiscal year for treatment.
The law requires probation instead of prison for non-violent first-
and second-time drug offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Drug Treatment and Education Fund kept 551 people from going
to prison _ saving taxpayers $50 a day for each of them, according
to the report by the Administrative Office of the Courts.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnett Lotstein, special assistant to the county attorney,
said these people would not have gone to prison anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is sent to prison for mere possession of drugs,''
Lotstein said. ``The savings are illusory.''
</P>
<P>
   The report says another 2,071 people on probation under
provisions other than Proposition 200 received drug treatment
funded by the new law between July 1, 1997, and June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   About 61 percent of the total completed drug treatment
successfully, and they did not disappear, get arrested or have
their probation revoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like an A-plus to me,'' said Sam Vagenas, director of
Arizonans for Drug Policy Reform, who coordinated the Proposition
200 initiative campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Lotstein said the 61 percent success rate is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to the other 39 percent?'' he asked. ``Did they
just thumb their nose at the system? Under Proposition 200, they
can't be put in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Under ``Do Drugs, Do Time,'' those who failed to complete
treatment faced a prison term, Lotstein said. And he claimed a 92
percent success rate, saying only 8 percent were rearrested within
two years of completing that diversion program.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court report, required by Proposition 200, did not
compare programs. Analysts found that more than 77 percent of
participants in drug treatment under Proposition 200 had clean
urine samples when tested. The same percentage made at least one
required co-payment for services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is in the forefront,'' said Chuck Blanchard, a former
state lawmaker from Phoenix who now is the top attorney for the
White House Office of National Drug Control Policy. He said the
Supreme Court report on Proposition 200 is sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that was forced on them by Proposition
200,'' Blanchard said. ``The fact that it's a positive report can
be taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Helber, Maricopa County's chief adult probation officer,
said Proposition 200 provides alternatives other than jail or
prison when probationers abuse drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to tell them, `We can put you in jail in a week or
prison in a month but residential treatment _ it's a six- to
eight-month wait,' '' Helber said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wealthy went to Betty Ford (treatment center), and the
poor went to jail. Now we've got money for the people who can't pay
for treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 200 requires that drug abusers be screened for
psychological problems, literacy and other needs, and that only
proven treatment programs be used. The Supreme Court found that the
recommended treatment was provided in 98 percent of all cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the driver's seat,'' Helber proclaimed. But he said
Proposition 200 should be expanded to require treatment in prisons.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 20,000 of the 26,000 inmates in Arizona prisons are
drug abusers, but no law requires treatment, said Gail Rittenhouse
of the Department of Corrections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
