<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SUSPECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS ON FRINGE FOUND WAY TO STAND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rendered virtually invisible among the athletes and popular
classmates who surrounded them, a small group of students at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., found their way out of
anonymity by banding together and dressing in gothic-style clothing
highlighted by long, black coats. They dubbed themselves ``the
trench coat mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   The group was easy to notice among the 1,870 students at the
school, because every day, no matter the weather, they wore their
coats.
</P>
<P>
   According to fellow students and people in the surrounding
neighborhood, the faces of the group's members were often covered
with white makeup and dark eyeliner, and sometimes their tongues
were dripping with hatred for racial minorities and athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just full of hate,'' said Chris McCaffrey, manager
of Angie's Restaurant, located a few blocks from the school. ``They
weren't particularly feared. They were just a bunch of punks who
kind of hung around the school.''
</P>
<P>
   But investigators now believe that from among the ranks of the
dozen or so students who made up the group were the people
responsible for Tuesday's mass shooting at the high school, which
left an estimated 25 people dead and 20 others wounded. Two
suspects, who had not been identified late Tuesday night, were
found dead among the carnage, and two others students identified by
the Jefferson County Sheriff's Departments as friends of the gunmen
were in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that the two gunmen pulled weapons and explosives
from beneath their black trench coats, and appeared to be aiming
specifically at racial minorities and athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people in the so-called ``trench coat mafia,''
according to other students, were boys but a few girls also
appeared to be closely associated with them. Many of them were, as
one student put it, ``nerds, geeks and dweebs trying to find some
place to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of the group kept mostly to themselves, listening to
German rock music and bragging about owning guns. But with their
bizarre style, patterned after the popular Gothic look made famous
by people like the rock musician Marilyn Manson, they stuck out in
Littleton, a middle-class suburb of 41,000 people located southwest
of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that kind of devilish, half-dead, half-alive look,''
said Bret, a 16-year-old Columbine sophomore who refused to give
his last name. Asked why the gunmen might have targeted athletes
and popular students, he said, because ``they got their fair share
of being picked on.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Nick Zupancic, an 18-year-old senior, agreed
that the members of the group were often scorned by other students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were outcast,'' Zupancic said as he stood outside Leawood
Elementary School, where some students parents gathered to receive
information on the shootings. ``Kids would make fun of them. They
would rip on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
