<HEADLINE>
POINT-GUARD POSITION UP IN AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Seven games until the postseason and the Lakers aren't
sure who their starting point guard is. Or even who the primary
backup will be.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher started his fourth straight game Tuesday as the
Lakers continued their Preserve Harp campaign with Derek Harper.
And rookie Tyronn Lue again played big minutes off the bench while
Harper rested, a towel pulled firmly over his head.
</P>
<P>
   Harper figures to play a primary role come playoff time,
probably starting again. In the meantime, Rambis has to decide who
will back him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to play both of them,'' Rambis said of Lue and
Fisher. ``Foul trouble and certain game-situation needs may dictate
who gets a certain period of time. But it's an adjustment. I'm
gonna have to see and try and make the best adjustment on what
direction I go and who gets most of the minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real tough to have a three-guy rotation, so we'll
probably have two guys and one guy will be a spot guy who might
come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis also said he wasn't worried about the play of Fisher, the
current starter, who netted no points and no assists in 10 minutes
Monday against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need my point guards scoring,'' he said. ``Their role
is to initiate our defense, get us into our offense, pass the ball
in our offense. The way we do things, especially the way teams play
us, they may not get assists. . . . They may not be the one who
directly makes the pass. They may be second in line. He gets the
ball to somebody who passes to somebody else . . . and that guy
gets the assist. So I don't look at whether he comes up with zeroes
to determine whether he played a good game or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher has the same outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall for me, I don't really pay a lot of attention to the
stat sheet, except for assist-to-turnover ratio,'' he said. ``I was
happier (Monday) night than I would have been if I'd scored 20
points. It just felt great to get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Say good-night, Dennis: In the unlikely event any team was
desperate enough to sign ex-Laker Dennis Rodman, he wouldn't be
able to play in the postseason, according to the league.
</P>
<P>
   Under NBA rules, a player waived after midnight March 18 is
ineligible for the playoffs, unless the team that signs him has had
its active roster reduced to eight players due to injury or
illness.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Rick Fox missed his second straight game Tuesday
because of a sore right knee suffered at Utah on Saturday. He is
questionable, at best, for tonight's game at Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Harper is recovered from a sore right foot, was available
Tuesday and could have played Monday against Vancouver, team
officials said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
