<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     04-21 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORCE WITH COLISEUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the deepest apologies to George Lucas and the
Star Wars universe, the National Football League is the real
Phantom Menace in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL might be a rumor to a generation of youngsters in
greater Los Angeles, but it is all too real and Machiavellian among
adults who recall the league sitting idly by as Georgia Frontiere
and Al Davis shipped their teams out of town. The only NFL fingers
raised over the Rams departure were by owners counting their share
of relocation (i.e., extortion) money.
</P>
<P>
   And among the expansion committee members who visited Los
Angeles this week, one could find Bud Adams (left Houston for
Nashville), Bill Bidwell (left St. Louis for Phoenix), David Modell
(dad Art left Cleveland for Baltimore) and Dolphins owner Wayne
Huizenga (trashed the Florida Marlins).
</P>
<P>
   So it is difficult to accept at face value the league's apparent
new generosity of spirit toward L.A.'s bid for expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The league has rarely sounded as deferential as it did Tuesday
during a press conference to announce it has chosen the Coliseum as
conditional site for an expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the NFL's support for the Coliseum is a stunning
reversal of fortune. A year ago, NFL owners would have been more
inclined to grant a franchise to Baghdad or Belgrade than the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of choosing the Coliseum, Tagliabue said the
league is willing to consider a different form of public investment
than the kind it usually prefers _ cash _ in returning to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of an auction, he said the league will set a
franchise fee by its May meetings so that the interested parties,
Ed Roski/Eli Broad and Michael Ovitz/Ron Burkle and anyone else who
wants to play, could have a set figure around which to build a
business plan.
</P>
<P>
   These were very impressive words for a group prone to lip
service. It amounts to the first real sign that the league realizes
it needs to have a franchise in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view today as an exceptionally productive day,'' said
Carolina Panthers owner Jerry Richardson, the chairman of the
expansion committee who played in the Coliseum when he was a
Baltimore Colts lineman. ``We have created the best opportunity to
develop a franchise in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to rekindle interest in the NFL with the
fans here, and an obligation to our sponsors, advertisers and
broadcast partners to bring a successful team back here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the emphasis is on successful. The fact is, two teams left
this stadium. We can't ignore that and we have to address the
issues we think would prevent us from getting in that situation
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson thus far has been L.A.'s biggest benefactor. He
sounded a clarion last August by informing L.A. that Houston was 95
percent complete in its expansion bid, or 95 percent further along
than anyone in L.A. He's been instrumental since in keeping the
L.A. expansion flag flying to this point.
</P>
<P>
   But he's also blunt about how things need to be done. He made it
clear that L.A. needs to get all remaining priorities in order if
it wants this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if everyone gets bogged down in a Roski vs. Ovitz
Celebrity Death Match for control of the opportunity, he said, L.A.
will suffer the same fate as St. Louis once did. Factions there
warred about control of a franchise, and the NFL wound up giving an
expansion franchise instead to Richardson. That, of course, begat
the St. Louis Rams option play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles would be in a better position if Roski, Broad,
Ovitz and Burkle worked together to resolve the issues,'' he said.
``We're not trying to create competition. We're trying to get a
franchise in L.A. But these are grown men. They'll have to figure
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, Richardson is in Ovitz's corner. They
walked into the press conference together and went to lunch
together afterwards. While Roski and Broad said they would extend
an invitation for Ovitz to join their group, the NFL might want
Roski and Broad to join Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   The league seems to like Ovitz's big-picture vision and his
natural affinity for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about putting the groups together,''
said Ovitz, who withdrew his Carson proposal last week when it
became clear that was the league's wishes. ``I know what we've been
charged with individually. We both had separate meetings (with the
committee) this morning, and we're going to focus on (our own)
business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The other priority will be a willingness on the part of city
officials to be a bit more creative.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum/Roski proposal includes $387 million in public
participation, but most of it comes via the already completed
infrastructure. There's only $40 million of new cash in the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue sounded accepting of that reality as long as city
officials can find other ways to generate revenue and improve upon
the park at the same time. The league, for example, wants a parking
structure in Exposition Park and other developments on the south
end of the Figueroa corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the reality of taxes in California,'' Tagliabue
said. ``In this day and age, there are ways to look at incremental
types of financing, ways to involve a public investment with a
broad public benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no change in our fundamental policy: No new tax
dollars,'' said L.A. City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas. ``But we
never said there would be no public dollars. We can invest in our
asset (the Coliseum), if it's defendable, justifiable and
prudent.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a potential hiccup here, it revolves around the lack
of a relationship between Ovitz and the city. Ridley-Thomas
admitted this is new terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz said, ``I can work with anybody. Now we have a single site
and a mayor who's involved. We're pretty well teed up.''
</P>
<P>
   And keyed up. L.A. Mayor Richard Riordan showed up for the press
conference with Cardinal Roger Mahoney at his side, invoking Hail
Mary images. Asked why he was on hand, Mahoney said, ``Man does not
live by Dodger dogs alone.'' What a card.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Riordan tossed a football around with some aides. ``The
NFL is the most prestigious club in America,'' he said during the
press conference, ``and we want to be a member of that club.''
</P>
<P>
   Against all odds, the opportunity appears to be there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
