<HEADER>
A6829 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-BLINEBURY-RIPKEN-     04-21 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BLINEBURY-RIPKEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FIRST Michael Jordan made the driving layup. He sneaked in from
behind to strip the ball away from the unsuspecting Karl Malone. He
gave Bryon Russell one more head fake and gave the rest of us one
more unforgettable memory, pulling up to the left of the key and
burying the jump shot to win one more championship for the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan did not officially announce his retirement until after
the stubbornness and ugliness of the NBA lockout had ended in
January. But the truth is, he knew right then and right there on
that night last June in Salt Lake City that the moment had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky did not get the storybook ending he wanted. He
passed to Brian Leetch for one last assist on one last goal, but he
never won another Stanley Cup after he left Edmonton. There were
all those years of falling short in Los Angeles, St. Louis and,
finally, New York.
</P>
<P>
   He reflected on his first year with the Rangers and how he
thought that team had a shot. Now he was going to be left out of
the playoffs for the second year in a row. He was hurt this season
and finished with just nine goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Michael Jordan retired too soon,'' said The Great
One, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky did not want to retire too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there was nothing his wife, his agent, the Rangers' brass,
NHL commissioner Gary Bettman or his legion of fans could say to
change that.
</P>
<P>
   What the best of them have, as much as all that talent and drive
that resonates inside of them, is a sense of timing. When to make
the basket or the goal or the play that will mean all the
difference when it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   What they too often don't know is when it's time to leave the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Think of Willie Mays stumbling around in the outfield with the
Mets. Think of Muhammad Ali being pummeled by Larry Holmes in a
portable ring set up in the parking lot of a Las Vegas casino.
</P>
<P>
   Now think of Cal Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's iron man has been placed on the disabled list for the
first time in his 19-year career because of a nerve irritation in
his lower back. He is 38 years old and is batting .179 with five
errors in eight games. The man who broke Lou Gehrig's
``unbreakable'' record by playing in 2,632 consecutive games now is
taking cortisone shots and has trouble getting out of his bed in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to see this. Nobody wants to see Ripken _ the
epitome of class and determination and working-class ethic _
embarrassed. Nobody wants to see a great player struggle and
stumble to the finish line of a wonderful and historic career.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it just yesterday that Ripken was an intimidating
offensive force, driving balls into the gaps, hitting home runs and
delivering the big hits and the clutch RBIs?
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it only yesterday that Ripken was one of the game's
finest defensive players, gobbling up every ground ball hit in his
direction, chasing pop flies into the shallow outfield and into
foul territory, making those strong and accurate throws?
</P>
<P>
   That Ripken has suddenly vanished like a magician in a puff of
smoke this season. But this disappearing act brings a sense of
sadness rather than awe.
</P>
<P>
   We are loath to push the great ones off to pasture too soon,
always wishing and hoping for one more season, one more game, one
more magical play to remember. Yet it is a tightrope walk where one
trip too many out on the wire can leave us with an entirely
different kind of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's pride in the image he had built wouldn't let us see him
at anything less than his very best. He could feel the hot breath
of young contenders on his neck. He could hear the footsteps of
time and couldn't bear the thought of them passing him. So he never
gave them the chance. He buried the jumper, buried the Jazz and
left unblemished.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky could feel himself slowing down, unable to slip all of
the big hits on his willowy body, and he got out before the scars
could turn into fractures or worse. They begged him to make one
last ceremonial trip around the rinks of the NHL. But he wanted to
go out as a player, not a traveling relic on skates, displayed like
the Stanley Cup itself.
</P>
<P>
   Now the clock ticks on Cal Ripken Jr., who already this spring
has had to deal with the death of his father, a difficult emotional
burden at a time when his body and his skills have eroded.
</P>
<P>
   You know what drives him. He needs 117 hits for 3,000 and 16
homers for 400 in a splendid career. But those are just numbers and
no reason to hang on. Like Air Jordan and The Great One, he is
bigger than all that.
</P>
<P>
   As Gretzky said: ``It's time.''
</P>
<P>
   For the iron man to leave with his respect, not our sympathy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
