<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6853 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-21 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ Maybe the drenching rains that soaked Wrigley Field on
Tuesday night were like a cleansing rinse.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they were the splash of cold water in the face, the
wake-up shower that revives the senses, after two weeks of the
Astros walking through the season in an inexplicable fog.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' bats certainly were there through the first 12
games, but big-time production in the clutch like the Astros knew
in 1998 had yet to show itself. The Astros entered this series
against the division-rival Cubs a mediocre 6-6, mostly because even
though they led the league in hitting at .292, they ranked 15th of
16 NL teams in runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what has killed us,'' said hitting coach Tom McCraw.
``Our guys are in shape to hit, and they're ready to hit, and
they've hit the ball. But we're not getting the big hits with
runners on base. That's been the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, it was the difference again. This time it was for
the better. This time it was for a 10-4 win that lifted the Astros
back above .500 and looked an awful lot like 1998 revisited.
</P>
<P>
   There were clutch singles, doubles and a big two-run triple by
Carl Everett, who went 3-for-5 and yet again showed signs of
building his way to a huge year. There were impressive
hit-and-runs, aggressive baserunning and offensive production from
every spot on Larry Dierker's lineup card but Craig Biggio leading
off.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether there were 16 hits and 19 Astros reaching base. Six
players scored. The Astros scored at least one run in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   It easily was the most impressive offensive output of the season
for the Astros and included the kind of decisive heavy-hitting
rally in the seventh that mostly had been missing in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a cold plunge, a trip back to the kind of timely
hitting and overwhelming offensive efforts that helped the Astros
to 48 come-from-behind victories a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   While this one might not have been a comeback win on the
scorecard, it was indeed a game that was in doubt into the late
innings. And it was impressive in the way the win came against a
pitcher who had mastered Astros bats in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Astros faced Cubs starter Jon Lieber, he gave
up five hits and no walks and struck out six in eight innings of a
2-1 Cubs win in the season's third game.
</P>
<P>
   This time, eight baserunners reached for the Astros in the first
four innings against Lieber. The 5-1 lead in the fifth looked
formidable, especially with Lieber chased to the showers and Astros
starter Jose Lima keeping the Cubs quiet.
</P>
<P>
   But then, even as Lima refused to groove a pitch to his
Dominican countryman, Sammy Sosa, it didn't matter. Sosa drove a
huge home run onto Waveland Avenue _ Sosa's third of the season _
sparking a three-run fifth inning that brought the Cubs back to
within 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   It was here where the Astros' bats might have most resembled
last season's big run: They were clutch. And unrelenting.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the famed Wrigley wind blew in hard from right field and
the rains that delayed this one nearly 1{ hours returned, the
Astros built a cushion and then made sure Dierker slept easy.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo crushed a home run over the left-field wall and
rookie Mitch Meluskey followed with his first major-league homer in
the seventh, giving the Astros a three-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, three runs came home, with a pair of doubles by
Ken Caminiti and Hidalgo and an RBI single by Everett the big
blows.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows if such an overwhelming display again will become the
Astros' constant. But after two weeks of saying the big hits would
come, hoping they would come, they finally did.
</P>
<P>
   After talking about it being only a matter of time for such
phenomenal talents as Hidalgo and Meluskey to show how impressive
they are at the plate, they were. Hidalgo was 3-for-5 with a
double, a home run, two RBIs and two runs scored. Meluskey was
3-for-4 with a home run and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   It was an Astros downpour. If they keep it up, the forecast for
the division might be for even more Astros reign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
