</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SUSPECTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS ON THE FRINGE FOUND WAY TO STAND OUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rendered virtually invisible among the athletes and popular
classmates who surrounded them, a small group of students at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., found their way out of
anonymity by banding together and dressing in Gothic-style clothing
highlighted by long, black coats.
</P>
<P>
   They dubbed themselves ``the trench coat mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   The group was easy to notice among the 1,870 students at the
school, because every day, no matter the weather, they wore their
coats.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow students and people in the surrounding neighborhood said
the faces of the group's members were often covered with white
makeup and dark eyeliner, and sometimes their tongues were dripping
with hatred for racial minorities and athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just full of hate,'' said Chris McCaffrey, manager
of Angie's Restaurant, a few blocks from the school. ``They weren't
particularly feared. They were just a bunch of punks who kind of
hung around the school.''
</P>
<P>
   But investigators now believe that among the dozen or so
students in the group were the people responsible for Tuesday's
mass shooting at the high school, which left an estimated 25 people
dead and at least 20 others wounded. Two suspects were identified
by the Jefferson County Sheriff's Department as Eric Harris, 18,
and Dylan Klebold, 17, who were found dead among the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   Two other people were being held in custody.
</P>
<P>
   A police officer answered the telephone late on Tuesday night at
the home of Klebold in the Deer Creek Mesa neighborhood. He said
the family was not at home and he refused to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that the two gunmen pulled weapons and explosives
from beneath their black trench coats, and appeared to be aiming
specifically at racial minorities and athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people in the trench coat mafia, other students
said, were boys but a few girls also appeared to be closely
associated with them.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them were, as one student put it, ``nerds, geeks and
dweebs trying to find some place to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of the group kept mostly to themselves, listening to
German rock music and bragging about owning guns. But with their
bizarre style, patterned after the popular Gothic look made famous
by people like the rock musician Marilyn Manson, they stuck out in
Littleton, a middle-class suburb of 41,000 people southwest of
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that kind of devilish, half-dead, half-alive look,''
said Bret, a 16-year-old Columbine sophomore who refused to give
his last name. Asked why the gunmen might have targeted athletes
and popular students, he said, because ``they got their fair share
of being picked on.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Nick Zupancic, an 18-year-old senior, agreed
that the members of the group were often scorned by other students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were outcast,'' Zupancic said as he stood outside Leawood
Elementary School, where some students parents gathered to receive
information on the shootings. ``Kids would make fun of them. They
would rip on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      04-21 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ Enough rain fell in the vicinity of Wrigley Field on
Tuesday night to fill a wishing well, and this may have qualified
as a good thing for the Astros, considering the way their luck has
gone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of what they might have wished for came to pass in a 10-4
victory over the Chicago Cubs that evened the Astros' record
against National League Central opponents at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive efficiency would rank at the top of the wish list for
the Astros, who entered Tuesday's game as the NL's top hitting team
but ranked next to last in scoring. Tuesday's scoring outburst was
a season high, and it came on the heels of an eight-run effort in
their previous game.
</P>
<P>
   Big contributions by struggling youngsters Richard Hidalgo and
Mitch Meluskey no doubt answered a prayer or two in the Astros'
clubhouse. Hidalgo (batting .239 for the season) was 3-for-5 with
two RBIs and his team-leading third homer. Meluskey (.259) was
3-for-4 with the first home run of his fledgling big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of offense from some guys who haven't been
hitting, and that was good to see,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``It was great to see them finally break out. Maybe that will
give them some confidence and they can build from this.''
</P>
<P>
   No Astros wish list would be complete without hopes for a solid
effort from the bullpen. Scott Elarton, who notched his first save,
extended his scoreless-innings streak to nine, but the more
pleasant pair of innings came from struggling righthander Brian
Williams, who matched zeros with Elarton.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker planned to use Williams only in the sixth inning, but he
pitched so well that the skipper decided to give him the seventh
inning, too. That allowed Dierker to use Elarton over the final two
innings and save closer Billy Wagner for another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williams did a great job,'' Dierker said. ``We needed that
bridge to get us to our late-inning guys, and he did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Williams pitched like one of those ``late-inning
guys,'' retiring each of the six batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they needed to see that from me,'' said Williams, who
lowered his ERA from 6.43 to 5.00. ``So far, those situations have
only been for Elarton, Jay (Powell) and Wagner. Maybe they'll have
a little more confidence in me now.''
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case after a rain delay _ the start time was
pushed back by an hour and 17 minutes _ neither starting pitcher
was particularly sharp. Jose Lima (2-1) earned his second victory
with a laborious 105-pitch effort that barely got him through five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Astros faced Cubs starter Jon Lieber, they
looked as dazed and confused as a punch-drunk fighter, managing
just five baserunners in eight innings on April 8. On Tuesday, they
delivered one body blow after another and eventually knocked out
Lieber in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worried about our offense,'' Astros hitting
instructor Tom McCraw said. ``We've got guys who are proven run
producers, and it's just a matter of time before we put it all
together. It's coming around.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros center fielder Carl Everett was 3-for-5 with three RBIs,
while Jeff Bagwell and Ken Caminiti each had two hits in the
Astros' 16-hit attack. Everett, who has hit safely in 12 of the
Astros' 13 games, led off the second inning with a single and
scored on Ricky Gutierrez's 500th career hit _ a broken-bat single
to left.
</P>
<P>
   Lieber (2-1), who had walked one batter in 16 innings prior to
Tuesday, issued a one-out free pass to Bill Spiers in the third
inning, and the Astros made Lieber pay for the rare walk. Spiers
advanced to third on Bagwell's double and scored on a groundout by
Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   An error by Astros second baseman Craig Biggio helped the Cubs
get on the scoreboard in the bottom of third. Center fielder Lance
Johnson singled, stole second and scored on a sharp grounder by
Mickey Morandini that Biggio was unable to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough field,'' said Biggio, whose error was one of
11 the Astros have made this season. ``Errors are a part of a game;
it just depends on how you get them. If you get them by being
aggressive, that's easier to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Astros benefited from putting the leadoff runner
on base in the fourth inning. Hidalgo reached on an infield single
and eventually scored on a sacrifice fly by Gutierrez. Everett's
two-run triple in the fifth pushed the Astros' lead to 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs closed the gap against Lima in the bottom of the fifth,
scoring three runs on four hits, including Sammy Sosa's third homer
_ a long solo blast across Waveland Avenue. Catcher Benito Santiago
had an RBI single in the inning, and another run scored on Gary
Gaetti's bad-hop double to left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to go with a fastball away,'' Lima said of his gopher
ball to Sosa. ``I made the mistake of leaving the pitch in the
middle of the plate, and you know what Sammy is going to do if you
do that. You have to give him his credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Elarton held the Cubs to just one hit and two
baserunners over the final four innings. Elarton struck out four
batters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
