<HEADER>
A6860 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     04-21 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN MINUS O'NEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ All Lakers coach Kurt Rambis wants is for his
floundering team to get better. Does performing miracles signal
significant improvement?
</P>
<P>
   All the Lakers did Tuesday night against the Golden State
Warriors was fall behind by 28 points in the first half, watch
their top scorer get ejected, take a 20-point deficit into the
fourth quarter and somehow pull out a wild, crazy, incredible,
almost ridiculous comeback that sent the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later they had pulled out a 106-102 victory in
front of 20,108, the largest crowd in the history of the Oakland
Coliseum Arena. At least half of them were screaming in ecstasy for
the visitors and their miracle-working 20-year-old, Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's 16-point fourth quarter brought the Lakers back from
the edge, and his hand-of-God-guided tip-in at the final buzzer of
regulation sent the game into overtime. And sent the Oakland fans
into a ``Ko-be'' chant frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant finished with 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had trailed since early in the first quarter and
didn't take the lead again until Tyronn Lue's bucket to open
overtime. A Robert Horry 3-pointer and a Bryant put-back jam gave
the Lakers their biggest lead of the game at 99-91.
</P>
<P>
   But the Warriors weren't finished, fouling and cutting the lead
to 102-99 with less than a minute to go. But rookie Antawn Jamison
gave the Lakers a gift, chasing a defensive rebound out of bounds
and tossing it back in to Horry for an easy dunk that made it
104-99 with 46.5 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison atoned with a 3-pointer to cut it to 104-102, but Travis
Knight blocked a John Starks baseline lean-in and the Warriors had
to foul. Horry made two free throws to seal the improbable victory.
</P>
<P>
   The incremental improvement the Lakers had showed in Monday's
victory over Vancouver faded away in a horrible first half that saw
the Warriors take a 28-point lead and O'Neal get tossed.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers combined their worst first quarter of the season (10
points), their worst half of the season (33 points) and the most
ill-timed ejection of the season (O'Neal, second quarter).
</P>
<P>
   Without their leading scorer and rebounder, the Lakers mounted a
furious fourth-quarter comeback, closing to within 88-87 with 4.2
seconds to go _ the closest they had been since the start of the
game. Bryant's 26-foot 3-pointer reduced the lead to one point.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal could have been the one to reverse the Lakers' fate, but
he almost guaranteed a loss by getting ejected with an uncalled-for
shove to the back of Bimbo Coles.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were down 24 points at the time, with 3:29 to go in
the first half. Coles and Robert Horry had just exchanged words,
and Coles pushed Horry away _ then got nailed in the back by
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   That gave O'Neal his second technical foul of the night, and an
automatic ejection _ but not before trying to go after Coles again.
Teammates and officials restrained him from committing any further
pointless acts, the kind that would draw a suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers scored the first two points of the game on O'Neal
free throws, then went six minutes without scoring as the Warriors
took a 16-2 lead. The Lakers didn't make their first field goal
until the 5:24 mark of the first quarter and ended the period down
32-10.
</P>
<P>
   All this with the Trail Blazers awaiting them tonight in
Portland for the third game in three nights.
</P>
<P>
   And these are the alleged heirs to Michael Jordan's Bulls? MJ,
sitting courtside (flanked by Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown and
sportscaster Joe Morgan), must have chuckled or choked at the
thought.
</P>
<P>
   After everything the Lakers have been through this season _ the
coaching change, the blockbuster trade, the Dennis Rodman fiasco
and all the losses in between _ coach Kurt Rambis said wins and
losses can no longer be the measure of his team's progress.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs are all that matter, and with virtually no practice
time to prepare for them, that leaves only games to work on the
finer details.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I'm not worried about who we're playing or whether
we win or lose the ballgames. It's more important for us to
improve,'' Rambis said. ``That's what's going to give us the best
chance in the playoffs, if we improve in these ballgames. So that's
what I'm trying to encourage and that's what I'm trying to develop
in these guys and get them to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the win-loss count, or playoff seeding are unimportant,
but Rambis figures such things will ``take care of themselves, if
we play hard and improve and do all the things we're capable of
doing. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's the only logical way of doing it. Since we don't
have the practice time to develop it and show them (their) mistakes
. . . you gotta do it in the game. And they've gotta learn while
they're actually trying to win basketball games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
