<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-TIGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ It was only the fourth inning Tuesday night when Troy
O'Leary's line drive disappeared into the upper deck of Tiger
Stadium, so Mike Stanley thought he was only kidding about Pedro
Martinez when he muttered to Red Sox coach Jim Rice, ``There's your
run, Petey, go get 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the Red Sox ace, with the able assistance of relievers
Rheal Cormier and Derek Lowe, shut out the Detroit Tigers on three
hits, 1-0, Stanley recalled how he once relied on another pitcher
to make even the thinnest of margins hold up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we used to say to Nolan any time we got him an
early run,'' said Stanley, who played with Hall of Famer Nolan Ryan
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Petey will pretty much keep us in any ballgame every time he
toes the rubber if we score some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of runs put up on the board Tuesday night by the Sox,
who had just three hits and have scored two or fewer runs in five
of their last six games, matched the number of vulgar balloons
tossed onto the field by the meager crowd of 12,558.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of that flesh-colored, ahem, object, sailing onto the
center-field grass gave Martinez his one moment of comic relief
(``I was laughing'') on a night when the Red Sox ace had trouble
concealing his fury when manager Jimy Williams came to fetch him
after Gregg Jefferies's two-out single in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (3-1), who rang up 10 strikeouts for the second
straight game and had set down 13 in a row until Jefferies stuck
out his bat and dropped a ball in front of center fielder Darren
Lewis, thought Williams was approaching with words of
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Williams, mindful that Martinez already had expended
130 pitches, came bearing a hook, summoning lefthander Cormier to
face lefthanded-hitting Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was coming out to talk to me since we don't have
Flash,'' said Martinez, alluding to the absence of injured closer
Tom Gordon. ``So did Val (John Valentin). Val said, `Naw, aren't
you going to give him a chance to get one more batter?' I gave Jimy
a little fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox manager didn't take it personally, and Martinez's wrath
subsided quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a competitor, I'll take 25 like him,'' Williams
said. ``A manager has decisions he has to make, that he has to live
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier made the livin' easy. After Jefferies stole second on
his first pitch, Cormier ended the eighth by retiring Higginson on
a tapper to Stanley at first, then started the ninth by striking
out the unfortunate Tony Clark, who already had gone down swinging
three times against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Out popped Williams again, this time to summon Lowe, the
suburban homeboy (Dearborn) who as a kid used to shag balls in the
left-field seats here and was a big fan of Black Jack Morris. Lowe,
who not only had 50 family members and relatives watching but was
mindful that this was his first audition as Gordon's stand-in, fell
behind 3-and-0 on the first batter he faced, Dean Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowe came back to strike out the third baseman, then fanned
Damion Easley for the save, which made it a lot easier for him to
look toward Martinez's locker after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, because I was on the other end, I used to be a starter
so I know how hard it is to get wins,'' Lowe said. ``When a starter
is pitching that good, you want to get the win for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one Tiger advanced to third against Martinez in the first
seven innings. That was in the second, when rising young star Juan
Encarnacion followed his single by stealing second and taking third
on an error by shortstop Nomar Garciaparra, who bounced his throw
to Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Haselman, who reached on the error, stole second
uncontested as the Sox didn't bite at Tiger manager Larry Parrish's
designs on a double steal. Deivi Cruz, the overmatched No. 9
hitter, tapped out to third to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the ball O'Leary hit upstairs for his fourth home run
on a 2-and-0 fastball, the Sox did little against Tigers prized
rookie Jeff Weaver (out of Williams's alma mater, Fresno State),
who dazzled Boston with his 95 mile-an-hour fastball until leaving
after the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   How does Weaver compare with Williams in the Fresno State
pecking order? Williams answered with a little Jimywocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm way, way down that totem pole,'' he said, ``and I'm not
even an Indian.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Indians, this was the Sox' first 1-0 win since
Martinez outdueled Cleveland's Bartolo Colon last July 15 _ a game
decided on a home run by the since-discarded Midre Cummings _ and
first on the road since May 30, 1995, a game started by Tim
Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't matter if it's 1-0 or 8-0,'' Stanley said. ``A win's a
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
