<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6866 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-WHITESOX     04-21 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-WHITE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX'S DURHAM SPOILS STRONG SHOWING BY FASSERO 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In three of Jim Parque's innings Tuesday night, the
Chicago White Sox left-hander set the Mariners down in order. In
each of the other three, he left two men on base.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners couldn't come through when it counted, and it
doomed them to a 3-1 loss to the White Sox in the opener of a
three-game series at Comiskey Park. Only 8,980 fans bought tickets
for a game delayed 1 hour and 10 minutes by rain, and considerably
fewer showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the ballgame we had a few chances, and we just didn't
come through,'' said Mariners manager Lou Piniella. ``But it was a
tough night to hit, too. This was the first time we've played in
cold weather. Up until now, we've played in the Dome and in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the 47-degree weather chilled the Mariners' offense, it
didn't seem to bother Jeff Fassero. The loss ran Fassero's record
to 0-3 for the first time in his career, but Tuesdayu's defeat
can't be blamed on the left-hander. He went seven innings, allowing
three runs on eight hits and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second solid outing in a row for Fassero, who gave up
three runs in eight innings last Thursday in a no-decision against
the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a little stiff when I threw my first warm-up pitches,
but then I got a little sweat going and it wasn't too bad,''
Fassero said. ``I felt good. I thought I threw the ball well,
location was good, we got some double plays when I needed them. The
last two games, I've thrown well enough to win them both.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have won this time were it not for Ray Durham, who is
never a pleasant sight for Fassero. Durham greeted Fassero's '99
season with a triple on opening day, and with three hits Tuesday
the White Sox second baseman is batting .452 off him lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Durham singled to lead off the game, but Fassero induced a
double play with the bases loaded to get out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, he reached on an infield single, stole second and
scored on a Frank Thomas double. In the seventh, with Fassero one
pitch from escaping the inning, Durham slammed a solo homer to put
the Sox up, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Durham's just a good hitter,'' Fassero said. ``You throw him
inside, he gets a hit; you throw him away, he gets a hit. He's just
a patient hitter. He doesn't swing at a lot of bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's other run came in the second, when Darrin Jackson led
off with a double that eluded left fielder Butch Huskey and scored
on a single by Brook Fordyce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had it judged and I had it on a line,'' Huskey
said. ``But I misjudged it. It had a lot more carry than I
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's, meanwhile, scored only on Russ Davis' second-inning
double. They had runners on second and third with one out after
Davis' hit, but Dan Wilson lined out and Domingo Cedeno flied out.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, after singles by David Segui and Ken Griffey Jr.
and a walk by Edgar Martinez, Jay Buhner grounded into an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Huskey and Davis batted with one out and runners
at first and second, but neither could advance the runners. Though
the M's entered the game batting .317 with runners in scoring
position, they were 1-for-7 in that situation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After Parque departed, relievers Keith Foulke, Bryan Ward, Bill
Simas and Bob Howry finished off Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The loss left Piniella toying with lineup changes. He said he
may put shortstop Domingo Cedeno in the leadoff spot, where second
baseman David Bell has hit since Carlos Guillen's season-ending
knee injury on April 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing with the idea that he could work the
pitchers,'' Piniella said of Cedeno. ``David's an aggressive
hitter. He doesn't take many pitches. We don't have what you would
call a classic leadoff hitter at all. We make do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
