</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ A comprehensive new analysis by U.S.
intelligence officials has concluded that China stole design
information related to the United States' most advanced nuclear
warhead from a government nuclear weapons laboratory, government
officials said. By James Risen and Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FAMILY (Kukes, Albania) _ For every one of the more than
600,000 Kosovo Albanians expelled by the Serbs, the escape was but
a single point in a long exodus of terror and pain, preceded by
months of anxiety and followed by long days of disappointment and
vulnerability. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FUEL (Washington) _ Some military experts dispute NATO's
ability to easily choke off the Serb fuel supplies. By Elizabeth
Becker.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul) _ Several of Turkey's veteran
political leaders are under growing pressure to resign following
poor showings in the national election Sunday. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SHOOTING-SCENE (Undated) _ In a violent instant, routine
gives way to panic. By James Barron with Mindy Sink.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SUSPECTS (Undated) _ Rendered virtually invisible
among the athletes and popular classmates who surrounded them, a
small group of students at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., found their way out of anonymity by banding together and
dressing in Gothic-style clothing highlighted by long, black coats.
They dubbed themselves ``the trench coat mafia.'' By Brent Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZ-DRUGS (Undated) _ A study of Arizona's new policy of
treating rather than imprisoning non-violent drug offenders shows
it saves money. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   RADCLIFFE-HARVARD (Boston) _ It's official, Radcliffe is being
swallowed by Harvard. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHIPPING-COMPETE (Los Angeles) _ Come May 1, the ocean-shipping
business will be largely deregulated, setting off a scramble among
shipping lines to lure customers with discounts. The same day,
however, virtually all ships carrying goods from Asia to the United
States plan to raise their rates by the same, mutually agreed,
amount. This contradictory state of affairs reflects the forces
buffeting the shipping business, which is now going through some of
the biggest changes in its history. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM (Rome) _ Before announcing an agreement to merge and
form the world's largest telecommunications company, Telecom Italia
and Deutsche Telekom are demanding that the German Government give
assurances that it will not exercise its voting rights in the
combined company. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   NEWAIR-AIRBUS (Undated) _ New Air, a start-up airline that plans
to offer low-fare service from Kennedy Airport in New York
beginning early next year, has decided to buy narrow-body jets made
by Airbus Industrie, dealing a blow to Boeing Corp.'s competing 737
jet. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   INFLATION-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The rate of inflation, as
measured by the Consumer Price Index, is likely to jump this year,
from the exceedingly comfortable 1.6 percent of last year to more
than 2 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   MULTICULTURAL-AD-COLUMN (Undated ) _ Efforts to increase the
consideration given to multicultural consumers are gaining momentum
as one of the 10 largest agency companies takes big steps to
embrace media outlets and agencies specializing in advertising
aimed at members of minorities. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
