 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 429 - April 21, 1999  ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 429 -- April 21, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. AFTERLIFE : BILL WYMAN ON MUSIC, THE STONES
</P>
<P>
   AND THE REST OF THE WORLD Bill Wyman quit the Rolling Stones
seven years ago after 31 years, but he's still a Stone at heart.
He's still the unofficial historian for a group that has plenty of
history. ``I think they appreciate that someone keeps a record for
posterity,'' Wyman says. His collection of Stones memorabilia was a
great source for his 1990 memoir, ``Stone Alone,'' and it also
decorates the walls of Wyman's three British restaurants. By Scott
Cooper. 1,500 words + photo. 2. STAR WARS COUNTDOWN PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   Ian Spelling, who writes the ``Inside Trek'' column for The New
York Times Syndicate, is doing a special series of stories on the
new and much-anticipated ``Star Wars'' prequel film, ``The Phantom
Menace,'' which premieres in the U.S. on May 19. (Fans there have
been going to cinemas just to see the trailer for the film.)
</P>
<P>
   A. Interview with Samuel L. Jackson (who plays Mace Windu); B.
Interview with Ewan McGregor (who plays Obi-Wan Kenobi; C.
Interview with Liam Neeson (who plays Kenobi's mentor, Qui-Gon.) D.
Feature about the crazy antics of ``Star Wars'' fans E. ``Star
Wars'' Trivia Quiz Art is available. Please contact us for more
details. 3. NEW BLUE : RICK SCHRODERIS 'NYPD BLUE'S' LATEST ROOKIE
Eyebrows were raised across America when producer Steven Bochco
announced that Rick Schroder would replace Jimmy Smits on the
long-running ABC hit, ``NYTPD Blue.'' Right from his first entrance
as Detective Danny Sorensen, Schroder vividly brought to life a cop
who was young, but old enough to have demons of his own. The show's
ratings have actually risen since his arrival, which Schroder
writes off to people's curiosity about impending disaster. By David
Kronke. From TV Guide Canada. 1,200 words + photo. 4. KEEPING UP
WITH THE JONES' : CATHERINE ZETA-JONES IS MAKING STARDOM WORK THE
SECOND TIME AROUND Five years after she completed a fairly
traditional 15 minutes of fame and saw herself consigned to
washed-up status, Catherine Zeta-Jones doesn't look like a
has-been. Last summer's ``The Mask of Zorro'' paid her way onto the
Hollywood hot list and two films in the next four months should
tell whether she has what it takes to stay there. In ``Entrapment''
she will appear opposite Sean Connery (as rival art thieves who
team up in business and romance,) and with Liam Neeson in the ghost
story ``The Haunting.'' By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 5. AN
ACTOR'S ACTOR TAKES A BOW This year, Dustin Hoffman, now 61, joined
film legends such as Elizabeth Taylor, Orson Welles, John Wayne and
John Huston as a recipient of the American Film Institute's
prestigious Life Achievement Award. The award is well-deserved. It
is difficult to think of another actor who so well articulates the
complicated, angst-ridden, ego-driven urban man of the late 20th
century. By Ivor Davis. 1,000 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain
and Australia.)
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
HOLLYWOOD GETS SERIOUS ABOUT VIDEO PIRATES Bill Shannon, a
highly-decorated 30-year veteran of the New York Police Department,
is no longer a police detective but he's still conducting
investigations. Now, as chief of the Motion Picture Association of
America's New York anti-piracy office, Shannon and his team of 22
investigators attempt to make the burgeoning illegal video business
so costly that pirates will look elsewhere. By Brooks Boliek. From
The Hollywood Reporter. 2,000 words + photo. 7. HIS PEN IS MIGHTY
In the past decade, no one has left a more indelible signature on
prime time television than David E. Kelly, a lawyer who turned
prodigiously prolific writer-producer. Nor does Kelley show any
signs of reducing a workload that still makes jaws drop in the TV
industry. With Kelley-created dramas already airing - ``The
Practice,'' ``Ally McBeal'' and ``Chicago Hope,'' he is at work on
yet another show, this time about high-tech detectives. By Don
Aucoin. From The Boston Globe. 1,400 words + photo. Please fax to
Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81
</P>
