</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7031 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-FOOD-$ADV09-     04-21 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-FOOD-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FROM UPSCALE TO DOWN-HOME, SOUTHERN COOKING ABOUNDS IN CAPITAL
 &HT;    With SOUTHERN-FOOD-LIST. Moving in (t) travel and (d) food
categories for release Sunday, May 9.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George Strait's picture is on the wall and his
voice is on the jukebox. A plaster of Paris catfish hangs from the
skylight and gospel singers make a joyful noise during Sunday
brunch. But it's the skillet cornbread that draws transplanted
Southerners to the Music City Roadhouse in trendy Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   The Roadhouse is among an assortment of restaurants in and
around the nation's capital that cater to expatriates of Dixie.
These folks crave the victuals they were reared on and savor the
memories resurrected by heaping helpings of collards, fried green
tomatoes and sweet potato pie.
</P>
<P>
   People are what they eat _ culturally as well as nutritionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food is absolutely the backbone of culture,'' explained
William Ferris, chairman of the National Endowment for the
Humanities and former director of the Center for the Study of
Southern Culture at the University of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every region, every ethnic group resonates to food,'' he said.
``Foods really are symbolic _ making you remember not only the
eating but also the family conversations and bonding at the dinner
table.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ferris, a political appointee who recalls his rural
upbringing when he sips buttermilk, the nostalgia of down-home
cooking is hardly a dispassionate intellectual pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss my grits and bacon and fried chicken and fried okra,
sweet potatoes, collard greens and cornbread. That's who I am.
That's what I grew up with. And I like to be at a table with that
cuisine,'' said Ferris. His favorite restaurant in the world is
Smitty's, on the town square in Oxford, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of his first tasks upon moving to Washington was to
plant a backyard garden of field peas, okra, squash, bell peppers,
cucumbers and tomatoes. But Ferris said the state of Southern
cooking ``is in pretty good condition'' in his new home.
</P>
<P>
   With a considerable portion of its populace made up of African
Americans with roots in the South, the District of Columbia has a
culinary heritage of ``soul food.'' Heavy on fried pork chops, fish
and chicken and well-cooked, pork-flavored vegetables, these
comforting meals have graced the tables of both black and white
Southerners for generations.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional dishes of Virginia, located just across the
Potomac River, have also historically been a savory part of the
District diet.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's cuisine ``used to be more Southern,'' said Phyllis
C. Richman, who grew up in the District and has been food critic of
the Washington Post for the past 22 years. ``Now Southern food is
like foreign food _ trendy food _ rather than indigenous food. But
there is still a Southern influence. Even the Washington Post
cafeteria offers grits for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than half a century, the Florida Avenue Grill has been
the epicurean epicenter for authentic Southern cooking in the
capital city. The walls are covered with pictures of celebrities
who have eaten the cornbread, fried chicken, and red beans and rice
over the decades. There are testimonials from Strom Thurmond,
Denzel Washington, the Four Tops, Clarence Thomas, Janet Reno, Lena
Horne, Kris Kross, a dozen or so Washington Redskins and scores of
other distinguished diners.
</P>
<P>
   The homey restaurant is a must-stop for District politicians.
Former Mayor Marion Barry smiles down from the gallery of pictures.
New Mayor Anthony A. Williams ate a breakfast of fried eggs, grits,
sausage and biscuits at the Florida Avenue Grill on the morning
after his election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who like this kind of food if you
season it right, but it's not for the dietitian,'' said owner Lacey
Wilson, who bought the business from his father in 1969. ``My
father was originally from North Carolina. He opened the restaurant
in 1944. The menu is from the South.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the menu at Georgia Brown's _ albeit vaguely. One of
several upscale, nouvelle Southern restaurants to open in the
District in the past decade, Georgia Brown's features the
low-country dishes from the coastal region between Savannah, Ga.,
and Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a twist on some of the old classic dishes,'' said Neal
Langermann, the executive chef and a partner in the six-year-old
venture. Black-eyed peas are mashed into a cake, for instance, and
grits are loaded with shrimp, shallots, sausage and scallions.
</P>
<P>
   However, the innovation of crisp, undercooked collards met with
patron resistance. Tradition prevailed after Washington superlawyer
Vernon Jordan, a son of the South who knows his greens, advised the
chefs to cook the collards longer.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Brown's food is prepared in an open kitchen as diners
sit beneath a ceiling sculpture of flowing metal strips that is
reminiscent of the spreading limbs of a live oak.
</P>
<P>
   Some purists chafe at the versions of down-home food served at
Georgia Brown's and the similarly upscale Vidalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's somebody's take on Southern cuisine, but it's not the
food I grew up on,'' said Jody Powell, a native of Vienna, Ga., who
came to town more than 20 years ago as President Carter's press
secretary and is now chairman of the Powell Tate public relations
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can pretty much find that kind of food, but it takes a
little effort,'' he said. ``Fresh vegetables. Greens. Butter beans.
Field peas. It's hard to find butter beans at the right stage.
People up here are used to eating limas that are hard and big. Good
butter beans need to be cooked when they're small and tender. The
same thing is true with boiled peanuts. The peanuts need to be
pulled up when still young. I've given up trying to find them. When
I go home, I get some and bring them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said he bought a place on the Eastern Shore of the
Chesapeake Bay to be in farm country ``when the vegetables start
coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do miss homemade jellies and preserves. That hot pepper
sauce you put on greens. Pear relish,'' he said. ``You'd think with
all this tasteless Yankee food, I would have lost some weight, but
I haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Another uprooted Southerner who cooks his own roots food is Rep.
Billy Tauzin, R-La. His craving is for crawfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get them fresh on the waterfront marina,'' he said.
``RT's, (with restaurants) both in Alexandria and Arlington (Va.),
has the most authentic Cajun cooking in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tauzin, who is writing a book on Cajun recipes and history,
regularly has a cousin bring up staples from the bayou so he can
cook gumbo, jambalaya, milk-fed pig and other traditional Louisiana
dishes for political fund-raisers and other gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always keep some in the freezer for when I want something
good to eat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a couple of Washington-area restaurant chains
that cater to Southern tastes. Red, Hot and Blue _ whose founders
include the late political strategist Lee Atwater, a South Carolina
native _ features barbecue, including dry-cooked Memphis-style
ribs. The Black-Eyed Pea provides Washington's version of ``meat
and three'' vegetables, plus cornbread and biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Young staffers for members of Congress from Southern states
swell the clientele of the Music City Roadhouse, said manager Steve
Briggs. Located beside the C&AMP;O Canal in Georgetown, the roomy,
rollicking restaurant features a bar and pool tables downstairs and
several rooms of tables upstairs. Meals are served family style _
serving dishes set on the table so diners can help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The menu is Southern standard: fried chicken, fried catfish,
country fried steak, barbecued spare ribs, pot roast, greens, sweet
potatoes, sliced cucumbers in vinegar. Cornbread is hot from the
skillet.
</P>
<P>
   The walls are covered with pictures of country music stars and
Elvis posters. There's live gospel music during brunch every
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Richman, the restaurant critic, said her home town could
probably use some more places that feature the tastes of the South.
With an Arkansan occupying the White House and the next
presidential election shaping as a contest between a Tennesseean
and a Texan, it doesn't seem there will be a shortage of hungry
Southerners any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, I like that kind of food,'' said Richman.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
