<HEADER>
A7061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-CO     04-21 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A gift of adventure in volumes
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   (A photo of Harley Johnson is available from Cox News Service by
calling 404-526-5456.)
</P>
<P>
   By Harley Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sam Jones was a widow lady so long as I knew her.
</P>
<P>
   She owned the farm that my father worked and the little
four-room house in which we lived at the time at Mooreville, a
community of farmers in central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Her house, a beautiful English-style home with big trees in the
yard, was just up the gravel road from our little house and at the
top of the hill where the creek road intersected the main road
through town.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones was the epitome of a lady of class and distinction,
very much respected and considered to be refined and well-educated.
</P>
<P>
   I sometimes thought of her as a queen or some sort of royalty,
the way she conducted herself, dressed and spoke.
</P>
<P>
   One particular day my mother sent me to Mrs. Jones's house on an
errand, and Mrs. Jones invited me in.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself in a beautiful room, very nicely furnished and
with a shelf full of books.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at the books and felt a magical attraction to them.
</P>
<P>
   We had no books in our house, except for the Bible. I had no
comprehension of the adventures within the pages of those books.
</P>
<P>
   My mother and father had not had the opportunity to achieve a
high degree of formal education.
</P>
<P>
   They were teens when the Great Depression ravaged the nation,
and they both had to help put food on the table for their families.
</P>
<P>
   They had no choice but to quit school. My father said he cried
at times because he could not go to school.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Jones saw me looking at the books, she said, ``Do you
like to read?''
</P>
<P>
   I said, ``Yes'm, I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   And then she did something that to her was a simple act of
kindness, but to me was something that was so wonderful that I
could hardly believe it.
</P>
<P>
   She took a book from the shelf and said, ``Take this and read
it. My children loved the book, and I'll bet you do as well.''
</P>
<P>
   I took that book and cared for it as if it were worth a million
dollars. I read every word of ``The Swiss Family Robinson'' from
cover to cover, experiencing the adventures and all the beauty of
the island and the sea.
</P>
<P>
   It opened a new world for me. I have been reading ever since,
and I still take great care to preserve good books as valued
commodities.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones probably had no idea of the impact of what she did.
Then, again, maybe she did.
</P>
<P>
   She may have seen a fertile spot to plant a little seed that
would grow and grow.
</P>
<P>
   I hope she knew how she enriched my life with her one simple act
of kindness.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   (Harley Johnson is a former school superintendent living in
Hillsboro, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
