<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, April 21, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for the
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VICTIM (Littleton, Colo.) _ Don Jugert was on the tail
end of a three-week business trip in Vancouver, Ore., when the
store manager said: ``You're from Denver? Did you her what
happened?'' Jugert, a 44-year-old division manager for Napa Auto
Parts, rushed to a radio and listened with horror as the announcers
detailed the carnage at Columbine High School in this upscale
Denver suburb. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   ATHEIST-DIARY (Austin, Texas) _ After a brief but spirited
auction outside a federal bankruptcy court, the diaries and
personal papers of missing atheist leader Madalyn Murray O'Hair are
sold to an Austin lawyer for $12,000. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENTAL-TRAVELS (San Francisco) _ Mark Hertsgaard, the
hard-headed writer and environmentalist, provides a valuable
perspective on global ecological problems and the potential
solutions in a new book that chronicles his travels around the
world. By JANE KAY.
</P>
