<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CERABINO-COLUMN22-COX     04-21 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scooper maker gets the drop on posh pups
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I had really big news for Frank
DeLoncker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not kidding,'' I said, after dialing his business in
Elgin, Ill. ``Your product is the official pooper scooper of Palm
Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh boy!'' said DeLoncker, the sales manager of Dualle
Products.
</P>
<P>
   (Now I know the vicarious thrill those sweepstakes notification
people must feel.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It elates me that we're the pick of the aristocrats,''
DeLoncker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you should be very proud,'' I said. ``They looked at 20
pooper scoopers before they picked your Doggie Bag-Grr.''
</P>
<P>
   To be able to fully appreciate the enormity of the moment,
DeLoncker wanted to know something about Palm Beach. So I told him
that when it came to excretal protocol, you couldn't find a pickier
podunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even put fragrances in the sewers there,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach's waste fixation _ did I mention daily garbage
service? _ has turned its upturned nose to dogs lately. An outfit
called the Palm Beach Civic Association's Citizens' Concerns
Committee has been on a jihad over dog droppings.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen to the group's chairwoman, Etonella Christlieb,
you'd think that people slide, rather than walk, through the
streets of Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially tough on the landscapers and UPS drivers who
walk across lawns,'' Christlieb said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, curbing after your dog poses a style problem in
Palm Beach. When the Citizens' Concerns Committee gave away a
thousand disposable bags last year, it didn't have much of an
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The basic middle-class method _ the less-than-elegant inside-out
maneuver with a Publix bag _ lacks the proper panache one is
expected to display on the gilded isle.
</P>
<P>
   So the island's dog do-gooders decided to make pooper scooping
the latest fashion rage. Here's what made the Doggie Bag-Grr so
appealing in Palm Beach: 1. The scooper is long enough so that no
bending is required. This is very important, seeing as how some
residents gave up bending after their first million, and the rest
either can't bend or don't want to bend for fear of spilling the
cocktail in their other hand.
</P>
<P>
   2. The disposable bags mean that the scooper doesn't require
washing or lawn wiping after each use. This is a cost savings,
because just about any sort of cleaning in Palm Beach requires the
hiring of additional help.
</P>
<P>
   3. The plastic handle is an ideal surface for decoration.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. This was a real consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paint them gold,'' Christlieb said. ``You can put
rhinestones on them. Gator fans can paint theirs orange and blue. .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Christlieb gave scoopers to each of the town's
council members. And hundreds of Doggie Bag-Grrs will be going on
sale in six locations in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they really got behind this thing and pushed,''
DeLoncker said from Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't know the half of it. The town's dog-poop lobby has
also leaned on the police department to start writing $66 tickets
to pooch owners who are caught leaving something behind.
</P>
<P>
   The first Palm Beacher was cited Monday. Christlieb called to
tell me about it. After hanging up, I thought, that's how Clinton's
going to sound when we finally get Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   I'd look for the island's smear campaign to get only worse.
Christlieb said what her group really wants is to change the law so
that police could cite dog owners if they are caught walking
without ``a device'' to pick up after their pet.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket would be written even if the act doesn't occur.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like more Palm Beach fodder for the American Civil
Liberties Union: A violation of do-do process.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
