NYT-04-21-99 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7120 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN22-COX     04-21 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stretch in 7th brought to you by Jane Fonda
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It beats me why folks get worked up about the
prospect of major-league baseball players wearing advertisements on
their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the people in this country are walking billboards
anyway. If you're an American, and you're not naked, there's a good
chance that right this minute you have on an article of clothing
that plugs a running shoe, cigarette, beer, software company, radio
station, tourist attraction or barbecue joint.
</P>
<P>
   So why should ballplayers be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Still, you hear people crab about the proposal to put 1- to 1
1/2-inch square patches that advertise, say, Burger King, Pizza Hut
or Popeyes on the sleeves of major-league players.
</P>
<P>
   Why are y'all worked up about this? Don't tell me about the
sanctity of the game. I think we're being a little two-faced here,
sports fans. Everybody's wearing ads on their ballcaps and T-shirts
out there. Trust me, folks. We're a nation of meandering marquees.
About the only available living advertising space left in this
country is my Disney dog, Harry. And for the right price, I'll let
you hang a sign on him.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think it would be a good idea to hang an Ex-Lax sign on,
say, Roger Clemens just because he works fast. But under most
circumstances, I can't understand why anyone would worry about ads
on uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, on Friday I went downtown _ dressed in my
purple jacket with ``Roy's Taxi'' on the back _ to ask folks what
they thought of advertising on baseball uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody I spoke to was wearing a piece of clothing that
shilled for something. I saw everything from a Jim Beam ballcap to
a shirt plugging Advantage Properties. And, to be truthful, most of
the people I talked to didn't seem to care if Sammy Sosa had
Budweiser tattooed on his butt in enormous red letters.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some folks who are at least a little bent out of
shape about the concept of major-leaguers pushing products on their
sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I think it just cheapens the game,'' said Tim Yandell
of Abilene. He was standing on a Sixth Street sidewalk, dressed in
a stylish green ballcap advertising Bass. I'm not sure if Bass
referred to the shoe company, but I know it had nothing to do with
the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Gonzales, a truck driver whom I ran across at Sixth and
Congress, said it's OK for baseball players to wear advertising on
their uniforms, so long as they're paid for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't advertise for anybody unless I was getting paid,''
said Gonzales, from underneath his gimme hat that plugged Quality
Auto Repair. I asked Gonzales if he was being paid by Quality Auto
Repair to wear the hat. He said he wasn't. I don't think he saw the
irony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's not a very good idea,'' said Jesse Felan, 19,
resplendent in a green T-shirt with white lettering advertising
Casino Parties Unlimited in Houston. ``They're already doing it on
everything else. It would be really stupid _ you know what I
mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I know what you mean. But I'm just not going to lose a lot
of sleep over it. In fact, I'll sell some prime space on my
midsection _ maybe a painted sign from a barbecue joint _ and go
stand out on the corner of South Congress and Oltorf for $200 a
day.
</P>
<P>
   Where else are you gonna get a billboard that big for that
cheap?
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7121 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN22-COX     04-21 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Janeites of the world, Unite!
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Martha Caprarotta loves to think of the delicious
mincemeat Jane Austen would make of Martha Stewart: ``Jane Austen
would have a marvelous time satirizing Martha Stewart, with her
perfect little parties _ and being more interested in the veneer
than in whether everyone is having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   As a loyal ``Janeite,'' (as Austen aficionados are called) and a
very modern woman, these are the kinds of questions _ common
threads between the two very different skeins of 19th-and
20th-century women _ that Caprarotta enjoys dissecting with her
friends in the Dayton chapter of the Jane Austen Society of North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's Janeites are inviting all of us to join the
conversation with a May 1 gala: ``Jane Austen: The Accomplished
Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Life was completely different for women in the 19th century, of
course, with just this one little exception: They were expected to
be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following from the ``The Mirror of Graces,'' the
1811 etiquette/conduct book written by ``a Lady of Distinction'':
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing, however minute in manners, however
insignificant in appearance, that does not demand some portion of
attention from a well-bred and highly polished young woman. The
choice of a gown, or even the folding and sealing of a letter, will
bespeak the shrew and the scold, the careless and the negligent.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the 19th-century woman wasn't expected to be the perfect
mother, breadwinner and public citizen while landscaping her own
water garden. She was merely expected to be the perfect
needlewoman, pianist, watercolorist _ and most of all, the perfect
catch for some eligible bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, women today have it far worse,'' said
Caprarotta, better known locally as Martha Dunsky, a veteran
television reporter and producer who now works as a consultant for
NCR's Interactive Television Network. ``Martha Stewart tells them
they have to have a perfect house. Magazines and TV are saying you
have to look perfect. And, unlike the genteel woman of Austen's
time, you have no maids, and you raise your own children.'' (The
indignity of it all.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Economically, we're better off today,'' said fellow Jane-ite
Lisa Tyler, an associate professor of English at Sinclair Community
College. ``Back then, if you weren't married, you could starve.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, if you weren't married, you were considered a failure
_ never mind if you happened to rank among the greatest novelists
of all time. Austen's gravestone extols a ``beloved daughter and
sister.'' The word ``writer'' is conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   Austen sealed her destiny as a failure in her society by
refusing the marriage proposal of one Mr. Bigg-Withers (the name
says it all) in 1814. As she wrote her niece, Fanny Knight,
``Anything is to be preferred or endured rather than marrying
without affection.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an irony that this great genius was by society's
standards a failure,'' Caprarotta said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``accomplished woman'' of the early 19th century is the
theme of this year's Jane Austen gala on May 1, sponsored by JASNA
and the University of Dayton. Festivities will include lectures,
art, music, dramatic readings, charades and a Regency Fashion show,
with costumes designed by Caprarotta. For information call
836-2408.
</P>
<P>
   Did Austen qualify as an ``accomplished woman'' by the standards
of her own time? She played the piano, and was certainly a lively
conversationalist, ``but the fact that she died a spinster, means
she was not accomplished enough,'' Tyler said.
</P>
<P>
   History avenged her brilliantly _ a cosmic strike for truly
accomplished women everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
