A7123 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINOR-COLUMN22-COX     04-21 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Show 'em you love 'em: No TV for a week!
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's say you are normal, which of
course you are not _ otherwise you'd be checking your stock
dividends and yelling at your 2.5 kids.
</P>
<P>
   But let's pretend, and let's do it rather quickly because the
Today show is on right now and they're doing a segment on slimming
bathing suits and I want so see it. I need all the help I can get.
</P>
<P>
   So, you are. Normal, that is, which means that according to
Nielsen Media Research in New York City your family of three
watched 78 hours of television this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Rugrats. Doug. Ally McBeal. The Drew Carey Show. It's all
mandatory in your house. Every second of it.
</P>
<P>
   Your kid eats his chicken nuggets on a TV tray in front of the
tube. You eat your grilled cheese and tomato soup with one eye on
Dan Rather. Your husband watches Baseball Tonight when he's
supposed to be cuddling up to you and thinking about ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, you get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   If this is your life _ Wait. How could it be? It's mine! _ then
Henry Labalme has a deal for you.
</P>
<P>
   He wants you to give up television for seven days. And he'd
prefer that you do it without drugs. Otherwise, what would be the
point?
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Labalme started an organization in Washington, D.C.,
called TV-Free America. He and a lawyer friend were just a couple
of years out of college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would sit around and talk about how to save the world, and
we kept coming back to television as the root cause,'' Labalme
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them tried to get money through a grant. When that
didn't work, they wrote to about 400 family members and friends.
Together they raised $8,000 _ proof, I guess, that in our hearts we
all might really hate that stupid T.V. set.
</P>
<P>
   The first year they had National TV-Turnoff week was in 1995,
and Labalme figures about 1 million people joined in. This year, he
is expecting about 6 million. National TV-Turnoff Week starts
Thursday and runs through April 28.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be that bad. I mean, our family did it a couple of
years ago and we survived. Sort of. You can listen to baseball on
the radio. You can take a walk while you're taping The Guiding
Light. You can actually talk to your kid and your husband at
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Drastic, I know. But our nation's television habits demand
toughness.
</P>
<P>
   According to Labalme, whose 7 1/2-month-old daughter Eve has yet
to watch a single Teletubbies episode, or anything else for that
matter, here is how sick we've become:
</P>
<P>
   --The average American watches TV for three hours and 43 minutes
every day.
</P>
<P>
   --Sixty-six percent of American households eat dinner while
watching television.
</P>
<P>
   --The average kid watches 1,680 minutes of television each week.
That's 28 hours a week, more than a part-time job.
</P>
<P>
   --That same kid has 38 1/2 minutes of meaningful conversation
with a parent each week.
</P>
<P>
   That last part is what scares me.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've found is that most kids who watch TV would really
rather be doing something else,'' Labalme says.
</P>
<P>
   Like flying a kite or reading a book or playing Scrabble.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe, just talking.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
