<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even on powerful cycles, bikers no match for Mother Earth
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAINGERFIELD, Texas _ The driver of the 18-wheeler didn't have
to blow his horn.
</P>
<P>
   I was fully aware of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted me to move over. So did I.
</P>
<P>
   My motorcycle was squirming wickedly in a muddy tire rut. If I
tried to steer out of the rut away from the oncoming semi, I felt
sure that the bike would fall, possible under the truck's wheels.
</P>
<P>
   During dinner the night before, four of us discussed how this
year's Ozark motorcycle tour was not going as planned.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the fifth member of our group was stretched out
in bed with a fever not far from where we were grilling his steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone fully expected him to ride in the morning even if it
meant crawling out of his deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can ride tomorrow,'' observed one wit, ``at least he
won't have to worry about it being cold and rainy.'' That was a
lie.
</P>
<P>
   The remark elicited loud laughter from everyone except the
bedridden man's wife. She said we were sicker than her husband.
</P>
<P>
   That was the other thing not going as planned. The weather
forecast called for cold and rain. An unexpected spring cold front
with rain and thunderstorms was coming our way.
</P>
<P>
   A 4 a.m. call alerted everyone that our fevered companion was
indeed prepared to ride. The 6 a.m. departure was pushed back three
hours, however, to give the storm front a chance to pass.
</P>
<P>
   We felt that we had outsmarted Mother Nature when we turned
north off the last of a series of small paved backroads onto U.S.
259 in northeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Our plan was to take this main highway up to the ridge-line road
on the Winding Stair Mountain Range in eastern Oklahoma and western
Arkansas. This scenic road is called Skyline Drive or the Talimena
Trail. It's a beautiful road that winds for 60 miles between
Talihina, Okla., and Mena, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Loose Gravel'' sign got our attention. Loose gravel on a
paved road is an irritant to car drivers. But gravel can cause an
unsuspecting street-riding motorcycle pilot to crash and burn.
</P>
<P>
   But the sign lied. The highway department evidently didn't have
a sign that said ``Hog Wallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Before we knew it, we were in an adrenaline-pumping red mud hole
that stretched from ditch to ditch. The pavement and the road bed
were gone. All that was left was a dirt, clay and sand pig sty.
</P>
<P>
   I was pant-breathing as though I was about to give birth. I slid
to the left of the red wallow. The tractor-trailer truck appeared
in the distance. I tried to move to the right but got trapped in a
deep tire rut that pitched the bike from side to side.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver blew his horn in case I was daydreaming. Or
perhaps he thought the five of us took the day off so we could
slide our street bikes around in this mud hole.
</P>
<P>
   My left shoulder brushed one of the trailer's tires as we
passed.
</P>
<P>
   It felt like forever before we wriggled out of the mud back onto
the paved highway. All the bikes emerged muddy. One bike and rider
was muddier. He had dumped his bike.
</P>
<P>
   When he went over, the drivers in the cars coming up behind him
were nice enough to not use him or his bike for traction. But they
were not inclined to get out of their cars to help.
</P>
<P>
   Another rider witnessed the dismount in his rear-view mirrors
and slogged back to help pry the downed motorcycle out of the mud.
</P>
<P>
   As we recounted our experiences during the three-mile writhing
traverse of Texas' version of a Third World jungle passage, one
rider remarked that he had not been more frightened than at any
time since he began riding motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, inching along a 60-mile stretch of mountain
ridge in a cold impenetrable fog, he would re-evaluate this
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Never brag about outsmarting Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco,
Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
