<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yard sale brings out the best in people
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Having a yard sale is like taking medicine:
you don't really want to do it, but afterwards, you're glad you
did.
</P>
<P>
   You meet the nicest people whose names you'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   My 17-year-old daughter declared that last Saturday we would
have such a sale. She and her friend are raising money to go on a
mission trip to help build a school in Belize this summer. This was
their first fund-raising
</P>
<P>
   project.
</P>
<P>
   I had successfully been putting them off for several weeks,
dreading foraging through cramped closets and venturing into our
garage/jungle. But Kathryn finally prevailed and she and Lauren and
Lauren's mom Mary and I spent Friday evening sticking prices on
everything from shoes to household appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow the moms' motives of getting rid of unneeded items and
the daughters' mission of making lots of money managed to mesh.
Saturday, we rose before dawn so the girls could post signs around
the neighborhood. My favorite was the one on lime green poster
board which said ``Cool Stuff'', followed by our address and an
arrow.
</P>
<P>
   I came away from the sale with several distinct impressions.
</P>
<P>
   First, if you're worried about our children not reading enough,
worry no more. Children of all ages and colors dug through our
selection of books, some looking for specific items like ``The
Babysitters Club'' and some looking for anything they hadn't
already read. One very serious elementary school child wanted books
she could read to her younger sister. Those of you who roll your
eyes at the number of principals who spend time on rooftops trying
to get children to read, scoff no more. It's working.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Longview is a really terrific place. Our yard sale
coincided with the T.O.P.S. convention hosted by the city. T.O.P.S.
stands for Take Off Pounds Sensibly. Several groups of
conventioneers stopped by. One lady
</P>
<P>
   informed us that T.O.P.S. folks are avid garage-salers. They
were also some of the most cheerful people I've ever come across
and they loved Longview.
</P>
<P>
   They raved about the pine trees, the azaleas, the dogwoods and
just the lushness of the entire area. Particularly enthusiastic
about the beauty were the folks from Austin and San Antonio, places
many East Texans love to
</P>
<P>
   visit.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to see your home through the eyes of others. Makes you
feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Third, God works in wondrous ways. A very quiet gentleman came
to the sale and gave everything a thorough inspection. He made his
selections carefully and methodically: all of my husband's old
shirts, some other clothing and a few toys. He didn't say much as
he was paying for the items and it finally occurred to me he might
not speak English very well. I spoke to him in Spanish. He
responded by telling us he travels to Mexico often and takes
clothing and other items to street people. He said he is helping to
build a school for the street children he works with.
</P>
<P>
   He was thrilled when we told him the reason for our sale.
</P>
<P>
   So were we.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, Longview, Texas . E-mail: awalker(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
