</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Attachments Link PC To Mac  
 By David Einstein   
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I live in San Francisco and am committed to my
Microsoft Windows 95 system. My daughter lives in Hawaii and is
committed to her Macintosh, because she is a teacher and they use
Macs at her school. Is it possible to exchange floppies so I can do
some typing work for her, or do we need special equipment?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  If you're using the same software _ i.e., Microsoft
Word on both platforms _ you can ``sneaker-net'' files on floppies.
Use disks formatted for a PC, because Macs can read them thanks to
a nifty bit of software called PC Exchange that comes with the Mac.
PCs can't read disks formatted for a Mac.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to try having your daughter simply e-mail the
documents to you as attachments. If you're both using Microsoft
Word, you should be able to open the documents, work on them and
send them back to her. If you're using different word processors,
have her save the documents in RTF format before e-mailing them.
That will preserve much of the formatting while guaranteeing that
you can open the files.
</P>
<P>
   You've Got Mail, Sort Of
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a question regarding the e-mail function in America
Online. I would like to be able to use Microsoft Outlook to send
and receive e-mail instead of the default e-mail client that comes
with AOL. Is that possible?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unfortunately not. Although most Internet service providers
let you use any e-mail program, including Microsoft Outlook,
America Online subscribers are stuck with AOL's proprietary Mail
system. There used to be a program called Claris Emailer, which
worked with AOL on Macintosh computers, but it's no longer being
made.
</P>
<P>
   That having been said, there is a way that AOL users can send
and receive mail even when they're away from a computer that has
AOL's software. It's called AOL NetMail, and it lets you access
your messages from any computer with an Internet connection and a
browser. All you do is go to www.aol.com /netmail/ and sign onto
your account as you normally would. A Web-based version of your AOL
mailbox is displayed that provides most of the features you'd
normally get. You can write a new message, delete an old one and
check messages you've sent.
</P>
<P>
   Tidying Up the Desktop
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have had a problem removing icons from my desktop that
involve applications I have downloaded from the Internet. Whenever
I try to remove these icons, I get a message saying that if I
delete the icon, I will not be able to run the application. My
desktop is cluttered with these icons. Please help.
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of the icons are probably the installation files that
you downloaded (you double-clicked these files to install the
programs, right?) If that's the case, you can safely delete the
icons. The only reason you might want to save one is if it's a huge
file and you think you might have to reinstall it. By keeping it,
you wouldn't have to go through a long download again.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that an icon could represent the actual working
program, in which case deleting it would disable the program. But
that's highly unlikely. I don't know of any program that installs
itself right on the Windows Desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Some of your icons also probably are shortcuts _ tiny links that
let you start programs from the desktop. If you go to delete one of
these icons, you won't get a warning message. By right-clicking an
icon and choosing Properties, you'll see right away whether you're
dealing with a shortcut or a program file of some sort.
</P>
<P>
   No Warm Welcome AtHome
</P>
<P>
   Q: I subscribed to AtHome two months ago and have experienced
outages and lethargic connections. Customer service is as close to
nonexistent as possible with this company. When calling by phone,
one is greeted with a standard message about unusually high call
volume and a wait of a minimum of 30 minutes. I have sent six
e-mails concerning service and have never received a reply. Is
there any recourse when an Internet service provider does not
respond? I've invested a couple hundred dollars in startup costs.
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no excuse for AtHome not responding to your queries.
Who do they think they are, anyway, the phone company? Why don't
you call one of their PR people and leave a complaint on the voice
mail: Try Matt Wolfrom at (650) 569-5195 or Molly Lynch at (650)
569-5555. Don't expect them to call back _ heck, they don't even
call me back sometimes. But at least they'll know they've got a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you turn off your PC without going through the proper
procedure to shut down Windows, you may be treated to a delay the
next time you start it as Windows goes through a screening process
to make the system's all right. That takes only a minute or so, but
it's irritating. So here's what you do: As soon as the blue screen
appears and the screening process starts, hit the Enter key. That
will abort the process and immediately launch Windows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-14-99 2156EDT &QL;
</P>
