u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-ONLINE-VOLUNTEERS     04-21 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ONLINE-VOLUNTEERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE A PASSION FOR THE NET, MANY ONLINE VOLUNTEERS WANT PAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Mann has played piano and written arrangements for Frank
Sinatra, serenaded President Truman on his yacht and written
popular music like the song ``In the Wee Small Hours of the
Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, from his home in Kinnelon, N.J., he sits at a
different keyboard, talking about classical music with the members
of a chat room on America Online. By his estimate, he puts in at
least five hours a week as a volunteer, moderating a weekly chat
session, answering e-mail and filling out an online report about
his duties.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, he and more than 10,000 other people who perform
similar tasks for the online service get a free account and the
designation ``community leader.'' What they do not get is a
paycheck, which is fine with Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not too concerned with being remunerated, since my
purpose was to fulfill an obligation to my art _ my Muse, as it
were. I merely believe that I owe it to the cause of good music to
steer less knowledgeable people in the right direction,'' said
Mann, 82, in an e-mail interview. ``I deem it not only an
obligation for me to do so, but a privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mann considers his role a privilege, some former
volunteers for America Online view it as work and have filed
complaints with the Labor Department. They say volunteers at the
company are treated like employees and perform functions that are
integral to the online service's mission and should be paid.
</P>
<P>
   In asking the Labor Department to investigate their claims, they
have raised two decidedly Internet-age questions: When does taking
part in and enjoying a community transcend hobby status and become
work? And what does an Internet company owe to the people who give
it life, not to mention high valuations on the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   While the Labor Department will not comment on the complaints
against America Online or any action it is taking, the industry and
the volunteers themselves are looking on with interest. If the
department does find America Online in violation of laws like the
Federal Fair Labor Standards Act, it could change the online
landscape, since America Online is not the only company that relies
on the passions and goodwill of people like Mann.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other Internet businesses, including Prodigy
Communications, iVillage and Geocities, are built on the foundation
of a virtual community, where volunteer participants establish,
lead and police discussion areas. In turn, the businesses proudly
boast about the number of members who take part in their
communities, and trade on those numbers to attract advertisers and
make multimillion-dollar business deals. Without their
contributions, company executives acknowledge that their services
would be virtual ghost towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the core foundation of our business,'' said Bruce
Zanca, a spokesman for Geocities, a Web community where he says 4
million people have built free home pages. Zanca said 1,800
volunteers contributed their time to the management of the online
community, hosting chat rooms and enforcing community standards,
among other tasks. In exchange, they get Geo-Points they can use to
buy products and services on Geocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monetary exchange probably wouldn't be an inducement,''
Zanca said. ``These people are the cyber equivalent of scout
leaders and PTA members and the Rotary and Kiwanis Clubs. Why do
people participate in these programs? It's the same reason I coach
Little League on Saturday mornings. It's something people do for
their own personal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The local Little League is a different proposition, however,
than Geocities, a publicly traded company with 300 paid employees
that was bought in January by Yahoo in a stock deal worth about
$3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of volunteering for a for-profit corporation is an
unusual one, so there is little precedent by which to judge these
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   But one question the Labor Department might be asking as it
looks into the complaints about America Online is whether the
volunteer force is providing a service that the company would have
to pay for if volunteers did not exist, said Jeffrey Chamberlain,
an employment lawyer based in Albany, N.Y..
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between volunteering at IBM to assemble
computers and volunteering at the IBM soup kitchen,'' Chamberlain
said. ``The difference between doing good and making computers is
relatively conceptually easy to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   In the digital age, the lines between volunteering and working
without pay are less clear. Many of the people who volunteer online
say they do the work for personal reasons _ not for the
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Bass spends, by her estimation, 20 to 30 hours a week in
her home in Middleton, Wis., as a supervisor in the pet care forum
on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   She says she loves her virtual, unpaid job: hosting chat
sessions, checking bulletin boards for inappropriate comments,
responding to e-mail from those who visit the area. Sure, she said,
she would like to be paid. ``Who wouldn't love that?'' she said.
But even without financial compensation, she derives great
satisfaction from her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a close-knit family here,'' she said. ``Most of my best
friends are here.''
</P>
<P>
   It may seem peculiar to the uninitiated that so many people
would give so much time, without financial compensation, to a
company with $2.6 billion in revenue last year and a stock market
valuation of $130 billion. Perhaps even more peculiar is the notion
that volunteers would be so personally invested in the work they
do. But it is a phenomenon that is part of an online tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like sex, it looks funny from the outside,'' said Howard
Rheingold, author of the book ``The Virtual Community''
(Addison-Wesley, 1993). ``Any virtual community that works, works
because people put in some time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But in exchange, he said, what the members of virtual
communities need and want is respect. Many Internet businesses, in
the frenzied rush to capitalize on industry buzzwords, have used
the word ``community'' in their marketing, but not necessarily in
deed.
</P>
<P>
   Rheingold said he suspected this was the case with the
management at America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Kurnit, founder of Mining Company, a guide to the
Internet, chose a different strategy to compensate the people who
manage various topics within the company's directory, like
``pregnancy'' or ``Southern food.'' Kurnit said he knew when he
started the company that he would need a large group of guides to
fulfill his promise of a ``human-powered'' search engine, but that
the economics of hiring a large staff were unrealistic for a
start-up operation. Instead, he pays the guides a combination of a
monthly stipend and a cut of the net revenues generated by
advertising on their sections. Kurnit says the guides, who now
number 692, earn between $500 and $11,000 a month, depending on the
popularity of the section.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, he issued 200,000 shares of stock to the
guides, which is now worth a total of about $10 million. (The
company went public last month, making Kurnit, on paper, worth more
than $50 million.)
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the guides sign over the rights to the sites they
create, and agree not to work for other online services in a
similar capacity.
</P>
<P>
   While for guides who have less trafficked sites, the
compensation might not equal a living wage, Kurnit feels his
program offers a fair reward, and that the company benefits more
than it would if he relied on volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is entrepreneurs are the best workers _ they work
tirelessly,'' Kurnit said. ``Volunteers are unreliable, and have an
expectation that you owe them something.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Zanca of Geocities disagrees that the quality of work
he gets from his volunteers is less than if he were to pay them. He
also said he was not concerned that the Labor Department inquiry
might affect the way his company is structured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Net has a new dynamic,'' he said, ``and in new
dynamics, laws and regulations need to be re-evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-18-99 1817EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
