<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I had really big news
for Frank DeLoncker. ``I'm not kidding,'' I said, after dialing his
business in Elgin, Ill. ``Your product is the official pooper
scooper of Palm Beach.'' ``Oh boy!'' said DeLoncker, the sales
manager of Dualle Products. (Now I know the vicarious thrill those
sweepstakes notification people must feel.) (Cerabino, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's say you are normal,
which of course you are not _ otherwise you'd be checking your
stock dividends and yelling at your 2.5 kids. But let's pretend.
So, you are. Normal, that is, which means that according to Nielsen
Media Research in New York City your family of three watched 78
hours of television this past week. (Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WALKER-COLUMN _ Having a yard sale is like taking medicine: you
don't really want to do it, but afterwards, you're glad you did.
You meet the nicest people whose names you'll never know. (Walker,
Longview News Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Martha Caprarotta loves to think
of the delicious mincemeat Jane Austen would make of Martha
Stewart: ``Jane Austen would have a marvelous time satirizing
Martha Stewart, with her perfect little parties _ and being more
interested in the veneer than in whether everyone is having a good
time.'' As a loyal ``Janeite,'' (as Austen aficionados are called)
and a very modern woman, these are the kinds of questions _ common
threads between the two very different skeins of 19th-and
20th-century women _ that Caprarotta enjoys dissecting with her
friends in the Dayton chapter of the Jane Austen Society of North
America. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ DAINGERFIELD, Texas _ The driver of the
18-wheeler didn't have to blow his horn. I was fully aware of the
problem. He wanted me to move over. So did I. My motorcycle was
squirming wickedly in a muddy tire rut. If I tried to steer out of
the rut away from the oncoming semi, I felt sure that the bike
would fall, possible under the truck's wheels. During dinner the
night before, four of us discussed how this year's Ozark motorcycle
tour was not going as planned. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ It beats me why folks get worked
up about the prospect of major-league baseball players wearing
advertisements on their uniforms. The rest of the people in this
country are walking billboards anyway. If you're an American, and
you're not naked, there's a good chance that right this minute you
have on an article of clothing that plugs a running shoe,
cigarette, beer, software company, radio station, tourist
attraction or barbecue joint. So why should ballplayers be any
different? (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Dispatches from Dreamsville: Mrs. Jones the
widow probably had no idea of the impact she had when she loaned me
my first book. Then, again, maybe she did. She may have seen a
fertile spot to plant a little seed that would grow and grow.
(Johnson, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
