<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMDEX-0421-COX &LR;      04-21 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMDEX-0421-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMDEX FEATURES OPERATING SYSTEM WARS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By ANDREW J. GLASS  
c.1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- When it comes to our corporate customers, we say,
`Hey, whatever floats your boat.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So says Richard Sullivan, an IBM software marketing executive.
His is a widely held view at the spring Comdex computer conference
in Chicago, where much of the talk Tuesday was of rivalries,
alliances and marketing deals.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the multi-flavored approach more evident than with
operating systems, the underlying software that powers such
applications as word processors and Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   While Windows, the operating system sold by giant Microsoft,
dominates personal computer desktops, the overall market remains
more fluid. Computer professionals who deal with such hardware as
network
</P>
<P>
   servers and hand-held devices have come to recognize that they
have plenty of choices in operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft takes up the single largest chunk of floor space at
the huge Comdex trade show for its Windows 2000 system. But the
densest crowds have flocked to a cluster of booths that feature
Linux, an
</P>
<P>
   operating system that some industry watchers have hailed as a
serious competitor to Windows -- and not only because it can be
downloaded for free on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in the operating system game, you're competing with
Microsoft,'' said Robert Young, the chairman and chief executive
officer of Red Hat Software, which offers Linux at no cost on its
Web site and for $50 on a CD. ``If you compete with a monopolist,''
he said, ``you can't play by their (CQ) rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Linux users has risen from 100,000 in 1993 to more
than 15 million today, and Young estimates Linux holds 17 per cent
of the operating system market.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Windows, Linux can run on machines powered by other
</P>
<P>
   than Intel processors, including Alpha and Sun Sparcmachines
processors.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in Linux users prompted Dell Computer earlier this
month to offer Linux installations on its network servers and on
its popular Optiplex workstations.
</P>
<P>
   Also, several large computer and software firms _ including IBM,
Compaq Computer, Novell and Oracle _ have invested in Durham,
N.C.-based Red Hat Software, which makes its money by packaging
Linux software and services.
</P>
<P>
   But Linux isn't the only competition for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite Linux's momentum, sales of rival operating systems
continue to chug along at a healthy rate,'' said Joseph Panettieri,
executive editor of
</P>
<P>
   Smart Reseller, a trade publication. ``Simply put,'' he added,
``savvy resellers and network administrators know that they can't
bet their
</P>
<P>
   businesses on a single operating system. Instead, astute
technology managers are keeping one eye on established operating
systems while keeping the other on the fledgling Linux industry.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which has five times the revenue of Microsoft, illustrates
this trend. The company has named separate full-time system
managers to work in
</P>
<P>
   with Microsoft and with the Linux community.
</P>
<P>
   Said Linus Torvalds, who created Linux eight years ago and who
has emerged as a big celebrity at Comdex: ``I want to see when
people go into a computer store, that they have to think about what
operating system to use, that there isn't one default choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
