<P>
   COXNET FOOD 0420 _ When Southerners celebrate with a birthday
party, holiday dinner, shower, wedding reception or graduation
gathering, what is the cake of choice? Chances are, it's Italian
cream cake. Little is known about its origin _ except that it isn't
Italian, it contains no cream other than cheese and few outside the
South have ever heard of it. Doesn't matter. This blond, moist,
three-layer cake is the pride of both home and commercial bakers,
from Texas to Georgia. (Crider, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes one 4-column photo of cake and one 1-column photo of
chocolate cake.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES _ Chocolate Italian Cream Cake, Original Italian Cream
Cake.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPICE _ To explore the origins of the food we eat is never
to look at a salad bar quite the same way again. Tracing the
history of everyday foods _ those we may take for granted _ can
lead to something as lofty as the unfolding of civilization. Head
to food sites on the Web to learn of geography, history,
anthropology, science, culture, art and even religions of the
world. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE _ Rotelle With Asparagus and Mushroom Sauce
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOOD page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-EXOTIC _FDethnic0422a: In the mood for something
exotic-tasting tonight, but not for going out to a restaurant?
Supermarkets and farmers markets are making it easier than ever to
get those tastes at home by offering convenience products that
provide tastes of Thai, Indian, Chinese, Mexican, Jamaican. We
taste-test dozens of these products and offer simple recipes and
tips for using them. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
COLOR PHOTO .
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-EXOTIC-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with Exotic story
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Salad with uncooked Ramen Noodles. (Langhenry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ Michael Skube's beer column is not
available this week. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-COOKBOOK _ Erica McVicker's online breast cancer support
group has a physical gathering, resulting in instant friendships
and a surprising dose of humor, hope, curiosity about their
condition, and hearty interests in food. Their energies were
funneled into a cookbook that's just been published with more than
450 of their best recipes, plus 35 of their breast cancer stories
of hope _ all to raise money for the Susan G. Komen Foundation,
which funds breast cancer research and awareness programs.
(Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-EATINGHABITS _ WACO, Texas _ Jacob Koehler, 2 1/2, will eat
just about any fruit or vegetable his dad puts in front of him.
It's a good thing, too, considering his dad, David Koehler, is a
produce manager. ``Eating fruits and vegetables is very important,
especially in the early years for growing and building bones and
muscles,'' Koehler said. ``They're good for getting the vitamin A's
and C's you need for a good start in life.'' Getting children
accustomed to eating a variety of fruits and veggies early on in
life is a key to setting them on the right track to good, lifelong
eating habits, nutrition experts say. (Mays, Waco Herald-Tribune)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-BUGSLIFE _ A multi-legged wonder. This computer-animated
feature from the makers of ``Toy Story'' is the eye-popping, witty
tale of an ant named Flik (voice of Dave Foley), who recruits a
bunch of circus bugs to battle evil grasshoppers (the chief villain
is voiced by Kevin Spacey). Grade: A-. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-MINIS _ Video reviews of ``The Siege'' (Grade: B-); ``A
Night at the Roxbury'' (Grade: B); ``Monument Avenue'' (Grade: B+);
``Belly'' (Grade: C+); and ``Simon Burch'' (Grade: D+). (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
