<P>
   COXNET FOOD PAGE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET FOOD 0420 _ When Southerners celebrate with a birthday
party, holiday dinner, shower, wedding reception or graduation
gathering, what is the cake of choice? Chances are, it's Italian
cream cake. Little is known about its origin _ except that it isn't
Italian, it contains no cream other than cheese and few outside the
South have ever heard of it. Doesn't matter. This blond, moist,
three-layer cake is the pride of both home and commercial bakers,
from Texas to Georgia. (Crider, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes one 4-column photo of cake and one 1-column photo of
chocolate cake.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES _ Chocolate Italian Cream Cake, Original Italian Cream
Cake.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPICE _ To explore the origins of the food we eat is never
to look at a salad bar quite the same way again. Tracing the
history of everyday foods _ those we may take for granted _ can
lead to something as lofty as the unfolding of civilization. Head
to food sites on the Web to learn of geography, history,
anthropology, science, culture, art and even religions of the
world. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE _ Rotelle With Asparagus and Mushroom Sauce
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOOD page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-EXOTIC _FDethnic0422a: In the mood for something
exotic-tasting tonight, but not for going out to a restaurant?
Supermarkets and farmers markets are making it easier than ever to
get those tastes at home by offering convenience products that
provide tastes of Thai, Indian, Chinese, Mexican, Jamaican. We
taste-test dozens of these products and offer simple recipes and
tips for using them. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
COLOR PHOTO .
</P>
<P>
