<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7195 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS22-TAKE     04-21 1841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS22-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I wanted to see Julie Andrews in ``Victor/Victoria'' in
Houston, but that performance was canceled because of her throat
surgery. Since then I've heard she will never sing again. What's
the story?
</P>
<P>
   A: Andrews underwent throat surgery in 1997 to remove
non-cancerous nodules in her throat. She says it was described to
her as a routine procedure. Now, two years later, she remains
unable to sing and is contemplating a lawsuit. ``It is in the hands
of lawyers and we will make some decisions,'' she told London's
Daily Telegraph in February. Her husband, director Blake Edwards,
said last year he didn't think she would ever sing again. ``If you
heard her voice, you would weep,'' he said. ``It's an absolute
tragedy.'' Andrews, who was said at the time to be angered by
Edwards' comments, remains hopeful that her condition can be
reversed. ``I have to be optimistic,'' she told the Telegraph. ``I
think to some degree I'm in a form of denial about it. If I could
not sing with an orchestra . . . I think I would be devastated. . .
. Right now I simply can't contemplate it. I don't want to say that
I never can.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I bought my first Big Game lottery ticket recently. The odds
of winning the least amount ($1) by getting only the Big Money Ball
is given as 1:62. Since there are 36 numbers from which to choose
one number, shouldn't it be 1:36?
</P>
<P>
   A: When calculating the odds for the $1 prize in the Big Game,
the formula is determined by the odds of getting one gold ``Big
Money'' ball correct within a field of 36, multiplied by the odds
of getting the five white balls in a field of 50 incorrect. So the
odds indeed are 1:62.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Organic gardening often utilizes cow, sheep and/or other
animal manure as fertilizers. Does this make the risk of E. coli or
other viral or bacterial exposure a possibility on the vegetables
harvested from that soil?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's possible. Organic production does in fact increase some
risks, said Paul Guillebeau, entomologist with the University of
Georgia Extension Service. In many cases, ``organic'' means that
the foods were grown with animal manures instead of chemical
fertilizers. So the risks from pesticides may be reduced, but the
possibility of contamination with fungal toxins, such as aflatoxin,
may be increased, Guillebeau said, citing research by the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration. Animal manure is the primary reservoir for
a virulent strain of E. coli. In 1996, the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta confirmed nearly 2,500 cases of
this virulent strain, along with 250 deaths. Although organic foods
made up only 1 percent of the U.S. food supply during that time,
organics were implicated in 8 percent of the confirmed cases.
</P>
<P>
   While Guillebeau said he was not condemning organic foods, he
added that organic producers may exacerbate the problems because
they typically don't use chlorinated water or other disinfectants
before their products are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are dogs trained to sniff out drugs?
</P>
<P>
   A: A dog's sense of smell is said to be 50,000 times greater
than a human's, which enables it to detect microscopic scent
particles. Trainers and handlers of ``dedicated drugs dogs,'' as
such sniffers are called, introduce them to the scent of a
particular controlled drug _ even small amounts of cocaine,
marijuana, heroin _ early in their training. The trainers and
handlers use play, praise and patience to encourage the dog's
natural foraging instincts. When the dog detects the drug's scent,
it alerts its handler, and usually is rewarded with praise or its
favorite toy.
</P>
<P>
   Commonly used sniffer breeds include Labrador retrievers,
English springer spaniels and German shepherds. Several companies,
including the Vonderhaus Gill German Shepherd Training School in
Wapakoneta, Ohio, and Kontraband Interdiction &AMP; Detection Services
of Modesto, Calif., train the dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A federal judge has fined the American Airlines pilots' union
more than $45 million for refusing his back-to-work order during
the February ``sickout.'' Where does that money go?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Allied Pilots Union fine must be paid directly to AMR
Group, the parent of American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before the days of cordless and cell phones, people were
advised to avoid talking on their telephones during thunder and
lightning storms. Is there a similar danger if using cordless
equipment?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not if the person using the wireless phone is indoors and
protected, according to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association in Washington. It's not recommended when outdoors,
however. A CTIA spokesman said you shouldn't have any piece of
metal touching or near your body when outdoors in a thunder or
lightning storm. A mobile phone contains pieces of metal, and if
you're talking on it, you're holding the metal-containing device
next to your head. That's not a good idea, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did Samuel R. Berger do before he became the national
security adviser for the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: During President Clinton's first term in office, Sandy
Berger's title was deputy assistant to the president for national
security affairs. In that position, he served as chairman of the
Deputies Committee of the National Security Council, the
sub-Cabinet interagency group charged with coordination of foreign
policy. Before that, he was Clinton's senior foreign policy adviser
during the 1992 presidential campaign and assistant transition
director for national security of the 1992 Clinton-Al Gore
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Berger's prior experience in government includes having served
as special assistant to former New York Mayor John Lindsay;
legislative assistant for former Sen. Harold Hughes (D-Iowa) and
Rep. Joseph Resnick (D-N.Y.); and deputy director of the State
Department's policy planning staff.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked in the State Department during the administration
of President Jimmy Carter, and was a speechwriter in 1972 for
George McGovern's presidential campaign. Additionally, Berger
practiced law with the Washington law firm of Hogan &AMP; Hartson
(1973-77 and 1981-92). He received his BA degree from Cornell
University in 1967 and his J.D. degree from Harvard Law School in
1971.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw that detectives in Texas were searching in a field for
the body of renowned atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair. Do you have any
information?
</P>
<P>
   A: On Easter weekend, federal authorities _ acting on
information from seven-time felon Gary P. Karr, suspected as an
accessory in the 1995 disappearance of O'Hair and her family _ dug
up portions of a 5,000-acre ranch west of San Antonio. As last
report they were refusing to say what, if anything, they found.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin Statesman-American reported that on March 24, Karr
had spent 13 hours voluntarily talking to investigators at his
apartment in Novi, Mich. While the newspaper said he didn't confess
to the killings of O'Hair; her son, Jon Garth Murray; and the
granddaughter she adopted as her own daughter, Robin Murray-O'Hair,
he did admit to concealing bodies, hiding victims' property,
acquiring vehicles and playing a key role in transferring $600,000
to a San Antonio gold dealer. The San Antonio Express-News,
meanwhile, has quoted FBI agent William O'Leary as testifying that
Karr has admitted an ``extensive role'' in the three deaths as well
as that of one other person, and has told the FBI the city where
the victoms' bodies were buried.
</P>
<P>
   Many questions in the case remain unanswered. David Roland
Waters, a former O'Hair employee convicted in 1995 of stealing
$54,000 from O'Hair's American Atheists organization, also is being
questioned. He is in jail in Austin after being arrested on weapons
charges and Karr, also arrested on weapons charges, is in jail in
Detroit. Waters' Austin attorney, Patrick Ganne, said he believes
authorities are ``waiting for one to break,'' but he insisted that
his client has nothing to tell authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read a lot about NATO's military intervention in
Yugoslavia, but I haven't seen any explanation about its stated
motive or where it derives its authority. Can you elaborate?
</P>
<P>
   A: The stated motive is safeguarding international peace and
security, as permitted under the U.N. Charter. Just before NATO
began its bombardment campaign, A. Peter Burleigh, acting U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, said the U.N. Security Council
gave NATO that authority in October when it called for a cease-fire
in Kosovo under the council's Chapter VII, or war-making,
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China have voiced strong opposition, saying NATO's
claim to be safeguarding international peace and security is
forbidden to regional alliances without specific authority from the
Security Council. But 13 of NATO's 19 members are participating in
the attacks on Yugoslav military forces, and three of the five
Security Council members with veto power over resolutions _ the
United States, Britain and France _ are participants in the NATO
bombing campaign. So Russia and China are making little headway.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Andrea Koppel of CNN related to Ted Koppel? It's not a
common name.
</P>
<P>
   A: She's Ted's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Equifax recently ran a full-page newspaper ad saying it has a
history of ``100 years in business changing the shape of global
commerce.'' I've seen its headquarters building in Atlanta, but I
have no idea what the company does. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: Its global operations involve the financial services, retail,
credit card, telecommunications/utilities, transportation,
information technology and healthcare industries, as well as
government. Hoover's Handbook of American Business says Equifax,
the nation's largest consumer credit reporter, approves check
purchases, processes credit card applications and transactions,
provides database marketing consulting services, and develops
credit-scoring software. Its customers run the gamut from banks and
other financial institutions to hotels and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The company traces its roots to 1899, when brothers Cator and
Guy Woolford started Retail Credit Co. in Atlanta. They compiled
credit records of local residences into their Merchants Guide,
which they sold to retailers for $25 a year. The brothers extended
their services to the insurance industry in 1901, investigating the
backgrounds of insurance applicants. After several decades, Retail
Credit branched into other information sectors, and in 1976 changed
its name to Equifax (short for ``equitability in the gathering and
presentation of facts'').
</P>
<P>
   There are two other large personal credit reporting bureaus are
TransUnion and Experian, formerly known as TRW.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
