<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7197 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS22-TAKE     04-21 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS22-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My Girl Scout troop wants to send mail to U.S. service
personnel involved in the Kosovo operation. What is the address?
</P>
<P>
   A: For Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps land forces: Any
Service Member, Operation Joint Forge, APO AE 09397-000.
</P>
<P>
   For Navy and Marine Corps personnel aboard ships: Any Service
Member, Operation Joint Forge, FPO AE 09398-0001.
</P>
<P>
   For families of service members: Any Family Member, Operation
Joint Forge, APO AE 09399-0001
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department says no packages can be sent for security
reasons. Only first-class mail, with a maximum weight of 13 ounces,
is acceptable. Mail transit time from the continental United States
to the Balkans averages 8-10 days. Information: 1-800- 841-0937
(press 2).
</P>
<P>
   Q: America's consumption of chicken _ fingers, wings, nuggets,
strips, breasts, thighs, legs _ is unbelievable. Just how many
chickens are raised in the United States to feed this insatiable
appetite?
</P>
<P>
   A: The numbers are astonishing, and growing steadily. Eight
billion chickens are raised in the United States each year, says
Richard Lobb of the National Chicken Council in Washington. About
83 percent of that total is for U.S. consumption, with the
remainder exported. Americans consume about 75 pounds of chicken
per person, per year, Lobb said, with the U.S. Department of
Agriculture predicting that number may rise to 78-79 pounds per
person in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife, three children and I were at Atlanta Stadium that
cool April night in 1974 when Henry Aaron broke Babe Ruth's career
home run record. I don't remember seeing the number of games it
took for each player. Did Hank do it in fewer or more games than
Ruth?
</P>
<P>
   A: It took Aaron 467 more games than Ruth to reach 714 home
runs. Ruth did it in 2,498 games; Aaron in 2,965, said Frank Vito
of the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y. Aaron broke
Ruth's record by hitting his 715th home run on April 8, 1974. In
his career, Aaron played in 3,298 games over 23 years; Ruth played
in 2,503 games over 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can we write the judge in the Jack Kevorkian case to
express our opinion on his sentencing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Judge Jessica Cooper of the Oakland County (Mich.) Circuit
Court is not soliciting or encouraging comments, said a spokeswoman
in Cooper's chambers. ``This is a court of law, not a court of
public opinion,'' the spokeswoman added. Nevertheless, she said
letters can be addressed to: Judge Jessica Cooper, Oakland County
Courthouse, Pontiac, MI 48341.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can contributions for Kosovo relief be made to the
organization that Billy Graham's son heads?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're referring to Franklin Graham's Samaritan's Purse,
which has worked in the Balkans since the region erupted in ethnic
conflict in 1991. During that time, it has provided more than $12
million in aid to Bosnia and other Balkan countries, the
organization says. Contributions can be sent to: Samaritan's Purse,
P.O. Box 3000, Boone, NC 28607. For more information, call its
Kosovo crisis hotline: 1-800-665-2843. Online information:
http://www.samaritan.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently saw a silly movie on TV called ``Biosphere.'' It
made me wonder: What happened to the biodome or biosphere that
several scientists lived in some years ago? It seems to have
dropped out of the news.
</P>
<P>
   A: The attempt to build an enclosed, self-sustaining
``mini-Earth'' ecosystem did indeed drop out of the news because,
in the end, the $150 million dream of Texas billionaire Edward P.
Bass was a flop. Four men and four women sealed themselves into
Biosphere II on Sept. 26, 1991, planning to live there without
leaving for two years. The airtight Biosphere II named after what
the researchers called Biosphere I, which is Earth _ covered 3
acres in Oracle, Ariz., with seven different climate zones in a
glass and steel greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The inhabitants intended to grow their own food and recycle
their waste, receiving nothing from the outside world except
sunlight and electricity. Their hope was to study the interlocking
dynamics of Earth's ecology, with the data they obtained perhaps
applicable to colonizing space or gauging the feasibility of
building similar refuges on Earth to preserve life in the event of
a catastrophe such as nuclear war. Critics were skeptical from the
start, calling it a ``scientific crapshoot'' and a ``Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems weren't long in coming. On Dec. 9, 1991, operators of
Biosphere II acknowledged that outside air had been pumped into the
facilityto compensate for leakage. They denied that the move was
taken to deal with a rising carbon dioxide level, or that it
invalidated the experiment. And one member brought supplies back
from the outside after leaving the facility for surgery on a
wounded finger.
</P>
<P>
   The eight researchers emerged on Sept. 26, 1993. The team had
produced about 80 percent of its food, but suffered several crop
failures due to swarms of mites and other insects. In 1994, two
original crew members were accused of sabotaging the project, and
Bass, citing mismanagement of funds, fired several top officers and
ordered private police to seize the project. Q: Recent talk about
the downed Stealth fighter makes me wonder if our armed forces
considered trying to destroy the remains of the fallen aircraft,
once the pilot was rescued. Would such a thing be considered to
prevent sensitive technology from falling into the wrong hands?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's standard U.S. military procedure, when a plane of such
technological value crashes, either to recover the pieces or to
bomb them, for the very reason you suggest. Recovery attempts seem
to be more likely, with no information available to suggest past
use of the bombing option. Such was the case in 1997, when an F-117
crashed during an air show near Baltimore. Air Force officials
sealed off the residential crash site and scoured the area for even
tiny pieces of debris. Mechanical reasons were blamed for that
crash.
</P>
<P>
   In the March 27 incident in Yugoslavia, a large number of pieces
of the F-117 Nighthawk fighter-bomber remained intact, and Serbs
reportedly gave some of the pieces to the Russians, who reportedly
haven't yet developed their own stealth technology.
</P>
<P>
   Although Air Force and other analysts said the technologies
employed in creating the Nighthawk are outmoded, and what little
could be discerned from the pieces wouldn't be significant, other
analysts aren't so sure. They contend that enemy scientists could
glean enough clues from the debris to develop their own
radar-evading technology. In any case, the Pentagon has publicly
played down concerns about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you provide more details about golfer Jose Maria
Olazabal, winner of this year's Masters? An article mentioned that
as recently as three years ago, he couldn't walk without severe
pain, much less play golf, because of arthritis. How did he make
such a dramatic recovery?
</P>
<P>
   A: Olazabal was out of golf for 18 months because of foot
problems initially _ and mistakenly _ diagnosed as rheumatoid
arthritis. The pain was apparent when he won his first Masters in
1994, and it became unbearable near the end of 1995. He watched the
1996 Masters on TV. ``It was not very pleasant, watching the rest
of the players playing the Masters, knowing you have a right to be
here and not being able to play,'' he told The Associated Press.
``That made it really hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, while he was in Germany to be fitted for a special shoe,
Olazabal was treated by Dr. Hans-Wilhelm Muller-Wohlfahrt, who gave
the golfer injections for his lower back and prescribed an exercise
program. The problem was caused by two faulty vertebrae, which were
pinching nerves affecting Olazabal's feet.
</P>
<P>
   As the AP reported, Olazabal publicly thanked the doctor Sunday
after he won the Masters. ``Without him, I wouldn't be standing
here,'' the golfer said. ``I think I won this tournament because of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   End of two takes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
