<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-COOKBOOK22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cancer support group channels energy into cookbook
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Erica McVicker's co-workers liked her better bald than
wearing the wig that gave her a big headache.
</P>
<P>
   And her sister was kind enough to listen to all the medical
jargon when McVicker was too overwhelmed to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after a diagnosis of breast cancer three years ago, the
Atlanta resident needed a way to listen and vent to women who could
understand her feelings.
</P>
<P>
   But a support group?
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought of going and sitting in a room with other women
with breast cancer was just too heart-wrenching for me,'' McVicker,
45, said.
</P>
<P>
   What she found instead is electronic communication with women
from Alabama to Australia who've found many other common interests,
including food, and have just published a fund-raising cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   McVicker's sister, Susan Antinori, also of Atlanta, found
Sapient Health Network, a Web site (now www.webmd.com) that offers
information on many chronic medical conditions and online chatting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's a stranger when you go on the board there. You can go
in, or you don't have to. You can stay away for three weeks. People
ask about you but they know you need the downtime,'' McVicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of treatment for more than two years, the systems
administrator for the Bondurant, Mixson &AMP; Elmore law firm continues
to check in with her online friends, many of whom she has met in
person.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring the chat group had its second face-to-face meeting.
When McVicker told friends and family of her plans to go to
Memphis, Tenn., she said some wondered about the safety of
in-person meetings with people met online. Others wondered aloud:
``Are you going to sit around and be morose and show your scars?''
</P>
<P>
   What she found, instead, were instant friendships and a
surprising dose of humor, hope and curiosity about the women's
condition. Food, too, seemed to be a constant topic _ perhaps
because they are women, many with families to nourish, McVicker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Their energies were funneled into a cookbook, ``Hope, Laughter &AMP;
Delicious Dishes.'' The just-published book has more than 450 of
their best recipes, plus 35 of their breast cancer stories of hope.
Profits from the book will raise money for the Susan G. Komen
Breast Cancer Foundation, which funds research and awareness
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to talking about it and wanted to do a little
something, maybe, to say we're doing our part to get rid of this
nasty disease,'' Sue Biley said.
</P>
<P>
   Members worldwide sent recipes and stories to Biley in Iowa, who
added many of her own and sent them along to Sharon Ann Basile in
New Jersey, who got them ready for publication.
</P>
<P>
   For McVicker and others whose stories are included in the book,
the support has been invaluable. The only negative, she says, is
watching as more and more women are diagnosed and come to the Web
site looking for information and conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day new people are asking for help to deal with this
aspect of chemo or radiation, to ask, `Are my eyelashes going to
go, too?' Or, `Is there anybody out there like me?'''
</P>
<P>
   There is, she assures.
</P>
<P>
   TO GET A COPY
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope, Laughter &AMP; Delicious Dishes'' ($12 plus $3 shipping and
handling):
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mcvicker1(AT)mindspring.com
</P>
<P>
   Postal mail: Sue Biley, P.O. Box 133, Corning, IA 50841-0133.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
