<SLUG> BC-CPT-PRIVACY-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. URGES NEW RULES TO GUARD PRIVACY OF CHILDREN ON INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government proposed new rules Tuesday
to protect the privacy interests of children on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, prepared by the Federal Trade Commission, would
require commercial Web sites to obtain parental consent before
seeking information from children under 13. They would also require
the sites to post notifications about what they do with any
information they obtain from children.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal comes after a new law expanding the agency's
authority on privacy issues. That legislation moved through
Congress quickly last fall after studies by the government and
experts showed that the vast majority of Web sites collect personal
information from consumers and children, and that very few
companies provide notice about what they do with such information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are a particularly vulnerable audience,'' said Robert
Pitofsky, chairman of the FTC. ``You mix the invasions of privacy
with kids and you have a particularly combustible mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites that ask children to provide personal information
about themselves and their families have proliferated in recent
years. Sometimes the sites offer prizes in exchange for
information.
</P>
<P>
   Children who want to win a Nintendo Game Boy from the Blue Bunny
ice cream trucks can register at Bombpop.com by supplying their
name, address, age, e-mail address and favorite kind of ice cream.
The Web site does not say what it does with the information.
</P>
<P>
   At another site, run by the Liberty Fund, a large asset manager
in Boston, children are asked questions about their family's
finances, including whether their parents use mutual funds or
brokers, whether the children have received bonds or stocks as
gifts, and what the family does with its money. The site,
www.younginvestor.com, says that the surveys are ``completely
anonymous'' but that the Web site also uses cookies _ information
that Web sites record on a computer's hard drive to track the
user's comings and goings.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the FTC last June concluded that 89 percent of
children's sites surveyed collected personal information from
children and that few of the sites tried to provide for meaningful
parental involvement in the process. The study found that only 23
percent of the sites even tell children to seek parental permission
before providing personal information, 7 percent say they will
notify parents of their information practices, and less than 10
percent provide for parental control over either the collection or
use of the information gleaned from their children.
</P>
<P>
   After that study, Congress passed a law last October proposed by
the FTC that gave the agency wide authority to adopt new rules that
would protect the privacy interests of children and their families.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, the proposed rules are approved this year by
the commission's four members, compliance would provide a ``safe
harbor'' from government lawsuits for improper trade practices.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal applies to any commercial Web sites directed to, or
that knowingly collect information from, children under 13 years of
age. It would require companies to obtain ``verifiable parental
consent'' through various means. Web sites can provide a consent
form that would be signed by the parents and returned by postal
mail or facsimile, take credit card numbers from parents, offer a
toll-free number that parents could call, or accept e-mail
accompanied by a unique ``digital signature'' that demonstrates
that the e-mail was not sent by the child.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy experts have warned that standard e-mail is not
sufficient because children can easily send what appears to be
their parents' consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the proposal looks pretty good,'' said Katharina
Kopp, a senior policy analyst at the Center for Media Education, a
Washington research and advocacy group that has pushed for the
rules. ``But the FTC could have given stricter guidance that
e-mail, by itself, does not work to provide verifiable parental
consent.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry lobbyists, however, have argued in favor of a wide
latitude in developing mechanisms to get parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there should be broad flexibility,'' said Jerry
Cerasale, a leading lobbyist for the Direct Marketing Association,
which represents 4,600 companies that use the Internet, telephones
and mail to sell their products.
</P>
<P>
   Some privacy experts said the rules would be hollow without a
vigorous enforcement program in which the FTC would audit a sample
of companies to assure that they are getting adequate consent and
following their own privacy guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important piece of this policy will be whether the
FTC verifies what the companies are actually doing,'' said Jason
Catlett, president of Junkbusters Corp., which promotes consumer
protection on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky suggested that the agency would be vigorous in
enforcing any rules that are ultimately adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there's a monitoring mechanism to see what people do
when they say they are abiding by the rules, the rules are an empty
gesture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-20-99 2331EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
