r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-TRAVELS     04-21 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-TRAVELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR EXPOSES THE DANGERS OF GLOBAL WARMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the United States approaches the millennium
burdened with worry over the ailing planet, a new book by
environmentalist Mark Hertsgaard provides a valuable perspective on
global environmental problems and the potential solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Hertsgaard sharpened his hard-headed progressive politics and
writing style at Mother Jones, Vanity Fair and the New Yorker and
he's written books on the press' pliable relationship with Ronald
Reagan and the vast corporate power behind the nuclear industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth Odyssey: Around the World in Search of Our Environmental
Future'' highlights ecological challenges the author discovered in
his travels.
</P>
<P>
   Hertsgaard said that on the Ethiopian-Sudanese border he found
farmers suffering from drought sweeping the Horn of Africa, perhaps
an early consequence of global warming. Fleeing starvation and
political violence, these Dinka people know they can't take nature
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Americans and Europeans, especially those living in
cities, have grown so distanced from the natural world that they
seem to think they could live without it,'' Hertsgaard writes.
``But let thunderstorms knock out the electricity for their
computers and televisions, or let political turbulence shut off the
supply of gasoline to their cars, and those same individuals would
soon be as helpless as bugs in a jar.''
</P>
<P>
   One in six people in the world lives the life of the Dinkas,
famished and probably ill. And that, writes Hertsgaard, is at the
heart of the ecological predicament of the human species.
</P>
<P>
   He began his intermittent travels for the book _ suggested by
former New Yorker editor William Shawn _ at the Earth Summit in
1992 wondering whether humans would last 100 years. By the
journey's end, he had met many people who may not live 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   Hertsgaard is reminded that when dealing with their
environmental problems, Asia, Africa and South America must also
confront issues of poverty and development as well as distribution
and fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the planet's atmosphere has space for only a certain level
of greenhouse gases, then humans must work out a means of sharing
that space. If the Earth's fisheries, forests and farmland can
supply only a certain amount of resources without collapsing, then
humans must agree on how those resources should be divided,''
Hertsgaard writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the bulk of the Earth's environmental space is
being claimed by the United States and the other wealthy nations of
the North. But this cannot last.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that even if alternative energies are developed and used
by developing nations, they ``will still generate substantial
amounts of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``China and India, with their gigantic populations and ambitious
development plans, could by themselves all but doom the rest of the
world to severe global warming if they chose.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of extraordinary economic growth fueled by the World
Bank, factories belch pollutants. Forests and wetlands are cleared,
and canals paved over. People newly able to buy cars complain about
losing 44 days a year stuck in traffic jams, yet don't reduce
driving. Mass transit is inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The internal combustion engine is a prime culprit behind global
climate change. Cars consume one-third of the world's oil output,
Hertsgaard writes. The car driving 100,000 miles at 27.5 miles per
gallon emits nearly 35 tons of carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   The world's 500 million cars are responsible for between 20 and
25 percent of current greenhouse gas emissions. Only electric power
plants with 25 percent and deforestation with 25 percent are as
damaging.
</P>
<P>
   With motor traffic expected to increase by 60 percent over the
next 20 years, the United Nations Population Fund has projected
that by 2025, developing countries could be emitting four times as
much carbon dioxide as the industrialized countries do today.
</P>
<P>
   Motor vehicles are the world's single largest source of air
pollution. Emissions of carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxide and
volatile organic compounds cause an estimated $93 billion worth of
damage to health and the environment every year in the United
States, according to the Worldwatch Institute in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As Hertsgaard travels the world, he compiles information on U.S.
energy consumption, evolutionary time lines and global
deforestation, extinction of species and population growth.
</P>
<P>
   The world's environmental future is more at stake in China than
any other place on Earth, according to Hertsgaard.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to China, his guide was He Bochuan, the author of
``China on the Edge,'' the first book written by a Chinese native
about China' environmental challenges.
</P>
<P>
   He, out of favor in China, took Hertsgaard to a neighborhood
where canals were literally black with garbage and feces. Pedaling
on bicycles on ground littered with plastic bags and food cartons,
He pointed to new concrete houses lining the canals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're four and five stories tall, they have television,
carpeting, air-conditioning, refrigerator: The indoor environment
is quite nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``These houses belong to the richest migrant, peasants who
became wealthy after selling their farmland. That farmland is now
gone forever, and the peasants are living in these filthy
surroundings and causing environmental problems for the entire
society. So is this progress? Or is it something else?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hertsgaard sees an opportunity for China _ a nation of more
than 1 billion people _ to install clean, efficient technologies.
</P>
<P>
   It's simply not true, Hertsgaard said, that replacing polluting
activities means crushing the economy. In Germany and other
countries, he sees that repairing the environment can become one of
the biggest businesses of the coming century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hertsgaard has written a New Deal-like Global Green Deal in
which governments would eliminate built-in, unwise subsidies to
fossil fuels, such as highway funding that doesn't measure the
economic cost of the resulting air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the United States won the race to the moon, it could
commit to a new mission: Relying on market mechanisms, while
zealously supporting alternative fuels for cars, mass transit and
solar energy; renovating buildings with advanced energy efficiency
methods so air-conditioning is unnecessary; and requiring farmers
to install super-efficient drip irrigations systems.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of Hertsgaard's story on this last Earth Day of the
millennium?
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook is uncertain, the hour late, the Earth a place of
both beauty and despair. The fight for what's right is never
ending, but the rewards are immense. Humans may or may not be able
to stop the drift toward ecological disaster, but we will find out
only if we rouse ourselves and take common and determined action. I
wish us godspeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
