<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: The outsider strikes back
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As this is written the day after the Littleton tragedy, the dead
have finally been counted. Themes have emerged: Outsiders. Revenge.
Murder. Suicide. Hitler. Nazism. Medievalism. Racism. Black coats.
Ski masks. Bombs. Guns. A proud and prosperous technocracy's
burdens stirred into an occult brew, eye of toad, tail of rat.
</P>
<P>
   Mass murder in the U.S. is the crime of the outsider. The
killers, usually white and male, take revenge for the lousy things
that have happened in life. They could probably pass the classic
test for legal insanity. Barbarity makes sense. Revenge becomes
virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this now the Internet and the Global Village. Peculiar
isolates of all flavors think they are cogs in great movements. A
board game, Dungeons and Dragons, becomes a way of life, a
philosophy, a path.
</P>
<P>
   The peculiar thing about Columbine High was more than its naked
horror. It was its sense of closeness, the story we can all fear.
Littleton, however far away and in all its aspects, felt like a
local story.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
