A7285 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHEIST-DIARY-HNS &LR;      04-21 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHEIST-DIARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAN BUYS RENOWNED ATHEIST'S DIARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The diaries and personal papers of missing
atheist leader Madalyn Murray O'Hair sold for $12,000 after a brief
but spirited auction outside a federal bankruptcy courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an investment. I'm not so much an admirer as an
entrepreneur,'' said Jimmy Nassour, 43, an Austin lawyer who made
the high bid Tuesday. In January, Nassour bid $2,000 for an
inscribed Bible that belonged to O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the diaries will provide a real insight into the real
Madalyn Murray O'Hair. You have someone who probably did incredible
things for the First Amendment, yet was deemed the most hated woman
in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the auction, Bankruptcy Court Judge Frank Monroe
approved the sale of what was the last asset in the liquidation of
the O'Hair estate.
</P>
<P>
   Court-appointed trustee Ron Ingalls said more than $240,000 in
unpaid claims against the O'Hair estate remain, most owed to the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Ingalls had received approval from Monroe to auction the diaries
in hopes of raising more money. Going into the auction, a pending
high bid of $8,888.88 had been received from an Austin man who
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   A third man, Stanley Main of Austin, who weeks ago had the
highest pending offer at $6,500, remained a mute bystander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed the whole process. I was only in it as a lark,''
Main said.
</P>
<P>
   For his money, Nassour got the personal diaries of the woman who
was America's most famous atheist, from 1953 _ six years before she
filed her landmark lawsuit against prayer in public schools _ to
August 1995 _ weeks before she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   There are two significant gaps in the handwritten diaries: One
covering the 1960s and the second covering all but a few weeks of
the final five years. It is unknown if those volumes exist, or if
they were ever written.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Nassour now owns a collection of O'Hair's personal
papers and family photographs, several books and video tapes, and
various personal documents, including her military records.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray, and daughter Robin Murray
O'Hair have been missing since late September 1995, when they
vanished from San Antonio along with $500,000 in gold.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe they were kidnapped and murdered, and two
men who are suspects in the case are currently being held on
unrelated charges. One has reportedly implicated himself and the
second man in the O'Hair disappearances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The diaries present a different side to the blustering,
belligerent O'Hair, one in which she speaks tenderly of her
children, anxiously about her waistline and wearily of the burdens
of the atheist cause.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical entry, on Jan. 6, 1973, O'Hair recorded her hopes
for the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You, dear diary, are the only one who listens to me, so I'll
tell you what I want to do. File at least a couple of suits and win
one of them, get a building, get a Bible Chair at the University of
Texas, get a mink coat and a Cadillac, humiliate Billy Graham for
money and move into a bigger and better home,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nassour, who said he bought the diaries with an eye toward their
value for a book or movie, doubts their author will reappear to
claim them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been given any indication that she's anything but
deceased,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
