<HEADER>
A7302 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-GREENMEN-AZR &LR;      04-21 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GREENMEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATIRE INVADES ALIEN WORLDS OF WASHINGTON POLITICS, UFO BELIEVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Little Green Men 
Christopher Buckley (Random House, $24.95) 
 
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paranoid. Rumormongers. Fanatical believers.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how the words that apply to UFO enthusiasts also paint a
knowing picture of Washington political insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Especially funny in the hands of Christopher Buckley, who, along
with Ian Frazier, sits atop the list of truly hilarious
contemporary satirists (a list of two). Buckley's ``Little Green
Men'' pokes knowing fun at the worlds inside the Beltway and
outside the Milky Way.
</P>
<P>
   John Oliver Banion, all stuffed shirt, bad haircut and owlish
glasses, is a hugely successful talk-show host; any resemblance to
George Will is doubtless intentional. Banion lives the good life,
Washington-style. The book begins with him humiliating the
president in front of millions, then zipping off to a chichi brunch
stuffed to the gills with socialites and politicos, all of whom pay
homage to the man with the chutzpah and the pull to ridicule the
most powerful man in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not (begin itals) the (end itals) most powerful.
That title belongs to the leader of Majestic Twelve, or MJ-12, a
supersecret group that originally existed to make the Russians
think the United States had UFO technology (thus the infamous
Roswell, N.M., ``crash'').
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided that as long as they were at it,'' Buckley
writes, ``MJ-12 could serve another, even higher purpose: keeping
the taxpaying U.S. citizenry alarmed about the possibility of
invasion from outer space and therefore happy to fund expansion of
the military-aerospace complex. A country convinced that little
green men were hovering over the rooftops was inclined to vote yea
for big weapons and space programs.''
</P>
<P>
   That means staged sightings and then abductions, which means men
in alien suits probing people in uncomfortable places. The
abductions complicated things. (``For one thing, it meant finding
dwarfs with security clearances. For this reason, aliens have
gotten considerably bigger over the years.'')
</P>
<P>
   Of course, someone must decide who gets abducted. MJ-12 relies
on a ``credibility algorithm'' that tends toward overweight
Midwestern women.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Nathan Scrubbs, who works in Abductions. A few too many
Bloody Marys after his promotion is denied leads to the abduction
of one John O. Banion. Actually, it takes a couple of tries, but
Banion eventually is a true believer, one who turns his talk show
into a forum for fellow abductees, conspiracy theorists and mixed
nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Banion and Scrubbs eventually wind up working together after a
fashion to keep themselves out of trouble. The plot moves along
nicely enough, but the real beauty is in Buckley's skewering of
Washington and of UFO believers.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington crowd is filled with familiar faces. There is
Burt Galilee, for instance, in the role of Vernon Jordan.
``Everyone trusted Burton Galilee. Presidents, Supreme Court
justices trusted him. The notoriously tight-lipped chairman of the
Federal Reserve was even said to confide his lurid fears of
inflation to Burton Galilee. . . . He had a great talent: He made
White people feel good about themselves. They could honestly say,
`Me, prejudiced? Hell, one of my best friends is Burt Galilee.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pop culture is represented by, among others, Tom Clancy. Buckley
and Clancy had a real-life feud a few years back. Perhaps that
accounts for Banion's retort when the technowriter goes off on a
military rant: ``Oh, don't play soldier with me. The only uniform
you ever wore was a Cub Scout outfit, with a merit badge for
pulling the legs off insects.''
</P>
<P>
   The UFO nuts don't come off much better. There is Bart Hupkin,
for instance, author of ``Plucked,'' who practices hypnotic
regression of abductees. ``True, some of the questions he put to
abductees once they were under might be considered leading, such as
`Were you abducted by four speckled, tentacled creatures from the
Planet Farble? Yes or maybe?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Green Men'' doesn't have the bite of ``Thank You for
Smoking,'' Buckley's fabulous sendup of Big Tobacco. It's more
good-natured in its pillories. Moreover, in government conspiracies
and UFOs, Buckley has chosen a couple of targets that ridicule
themselves so well it's sometimes hard for a satirist to outdo
them.
</P>
<P>
   But it's still funny, and the takedowns of self-important
Washington figures and customs are a laugh-out-loud riot. Unless
you don't think the idea of aliens probing George Will humorous. In
that case, maybe you've been abducted too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1251EDT &QL; 
