<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7304 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      04-21 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE NORTON BOOK OF AMERICAN AUTOBIOGRAPHY &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Jay Parini (Norton, $32.50)
</P>
<P>
   You have to chuckle over a book that implies a direct line
between Benjamin Franklin and Mary Karr, but here it is: Parini
includes an excerpt from Franklin's autobiography (a classic in the
genre) in which Franklin discusses the moral virtues, and another
from Karr's ``The Liar's Club,'' the splendid but raucous tale of
her upbringing in eastern Texas, in which the moral virtues played
almost no role at all. Also here, chronologically, are selections
from Thoreau's ``Walden,'' Frederick Douglass' ``My Bondage and My
Freedom,'' Walt Whitman's ``Specimen Days in America,'' Mark
Twain's ``Life on the Mississippi,'' Henry James' ``Notes of a Son
and Brother,'' Booker T. Washington's ``Up from Slavery,'' Hellen
Keller's ``The Story of My Life,'' Eudora Welty's ``One Writer's
Beginnings, ''Wallace Stegner's ``Wolf Willow,'' Gay Talese's
``Unto the Sons,'' Harry Crews' ``A Childhood: The Biography of a
Place,'' Frank Conroy's ``Stop-Time,'' Maxine Hong Kingston's ``The
Woman Warrior,'' Paul Monette's ``Borrowed Time: An AIDS Memoir,''
Annie Dillard's ``An American Childhood,'' Luis Rodriguez's
``Always Running,'' Terry Tempest Williams' ``Refuge,'' Sherman
Alexie's ``First Indian on the Moon'' and many more. Parini calls
autobiography ``the essential American genre, a form of writing
closely allied to our national self-consciousness.'' He has done a
superb job of choosing his material, although he admits that the
original manuscript of this book was three times its current size,
and that the cutting seemed arbitrary. There is a short preface by
Gore Vidal, who reminds us of the words of French writer Jules
Renard: ``I find that when I do not think of myself, I do not think
at all.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WIT &QL; 
 &UR; Margaret Edson (Faber and Faber, $12)
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Bearing is 50, a tough, demanding professor of
17th-century poetry specializing in the Holy Sonnets of John Donne,
which, she reminds us, ``explore mortality in greater depth than
any other body of work in the English language.'' Her specialty,
then, is well-chosen, because Vivian is also a woman with cancer _
advanced metastatic ovarian cancer _ and she is about to embark on
a brutal form of experimental drug treatment that will wreak havoc
with her body. But her wit _ what of that? For Vivian's
intelligence is formidable, inquisitive, indeed nearly invincible.
Could this cancer be a match for it? Of course not, but be advised:
This is no warm and fuzzy play, any more than Vivian is a
sentimental heroine. She is challenging, thought-provoking and,
ultimately, living proof that Death shall be no more. Margaret
Edson is an Atlanta kindergarten teacher who won a Pulitzer Prize
for this, her first play, earlier this week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WATER, EARTH AND SKY: THE COLORADO RIVER BASIN &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Collier (University of Utah, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   Collier, a writer, geologist and physician who practices in
Flagstaff, is also a flier _ he takes photographs from the air in
his 1955 Cessna, which offers views of the landscape that are both
otherworldly and delightfully familiar. There is a serenity to the
airborne images, in their patterns and colors, and in the implied
silence that seems to surround them. Here Collier follows the
features of the Colorado River system, top to bottom, Wyoming to
Mexico, as viewed from the sky. We see its lazy meanderings through
a lush, green valley in Colorado (but only because of upstream
diversions _ left full strength, the river would have kept its
channel scoured), its course through rocky canyonlands in Utah, the
dams that control and divert it, its muddy journey through the
Grand Canyon and, eventually, its dry bed as it enters Mexico.
Collier's photographs are loyal to their subject (unlike books for
the tourist trade, this one does not imply that every rock and
canyon is fluorescent orange), and they are not blown into
poster-size extravagance. They are supported instead by essays from
Collier and six other naturalists, researchers and ecologists who
explore the natural and human history of the Colorado River. The
result is an elegant lesson on how natural processes and human
impact have affected one of the most beautiful rivers in the
world. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ON THE BUS WITH ROSA PARKS &QL; 
 &UR; Rita Dove (Norton, $21)
</P>
<P>
   ``How she sat there,/ the time right inside a place/ so wrong it
was ready./ That trim name with/ its dream of a bench/ to rest on.
Her sensible coat./ Doing nothing was the doing:/ the clean flame
of her gaze/ carved by a camera flash./ How she stood up/ when they
bent down to retrieve/ her purse. That courtesy.'' This, in its
entirety is ``Rosa,'' from the new collection of poetry by the
nation's former poet laureate and winner of a Pulitzer Prize. Read
``The Camel Comes to Us from the Barbarians'' (inspired by an Aesop
fable) about an ugly, difficult animal that will not bow to its
keepers _ ``A rare commodity, these beasts _/ who cannot know/ what
beauty wreaks, what mountains/ pity moves.'' Or ``There Came a
Soul,'' inspired by Chicago artist Ivan Albright's 1929 painting of
20-year-old Ida Rogers, in which he portrayed her as a lonely old
woman. Or ``Claudette Colvin Goes to Work,'' inspired by a
15-year-old Black high school student who refused to yield her bus
seat to White students a full nine months before Rosa Parks was
arrested in 1955. Dove's poems are thick with sensual details, the
hint of broader stories, the gravity of history. She is a member of
the faculty at the University of Virginia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(You can reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson &LR; worldnet.att.net.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
