A7316 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-ANNIE22-COX     04-21 0229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ANNIE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beloved `Annie' misses mark but provides pleasures
 &HT;    By Kathy Janich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how you twist it, turn it or shuffle its parts, Irving
Berlin's score for ``Annie Get Your Gun'' is a classic. Still,
there's no bull's-eye here. Like the gun sight Annie skews to win
Frank's heart, this ``rebirthing'' of the '46 chestnut just misses
its mark. So, like Annie Oakley and Frank Butler aiming at clay
pigeons, let's tally the hits and misses:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Star Bernadette Peters (anything she can do, no one does
better) as Annie. Hit! The manly Tom Wopat as Frank. Hit!
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Opening with ``There's No Business Like Show Business.'' Miss!
Tomahawking two numbers to do s2nP,Ugh.) Miss!
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nineteen tracks. Hit! Six reprises. Miss!
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A de-emphasized chorus. A tuneful ``Old-Fashioned Wedding.'' A
slow and ghastly ``I Got the Sun in the Morning.'' Miss! Hit! Miss!
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A truncated ``You Can't Get a Man With a Gun.'' Miss!
</P>
<P>
   You get the idea. This is certainly a disc that show music fans
and Peters' fans will want. Unfortunately, it's more wooden Indian
than the genuine article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Get Your Gun''
</P>
<P>
   1999 original cast. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Janich writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7317 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS22-COX     04-21 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Doug Hamilton and Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight''
</P>
<P>
   Silk. Elektra. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like the sales drop between Silk's first and second
album has made the group revert to its sensual beginnings on its
third. The Atlanta quintet hit the multimillion mark when it
released the single ``Freak Me'' from its 1992 debut and its 1995
follow-up _ an underappreciated topical and vocal stretch _ sold a
respectable 500,000 copies, but was perceived as a disappointment.
So ``Tonight'' is almost singularly focused on the bedroom again:
``Let's Make Love,'' ``Meeting in My Bedroom,'' ``Sexcellent'' _
all varied ways of suggesting the same thing. The bad thing is when
the lushly-produced suggestions come wrapped in worn cliches like
``be there or be square'' and ``you're jiggy.'' These incredibly
gifted singers could have a difficult time luring patient
listeners, much less sexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Unauthorized Biography of Reinhold Messner''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Folds Five. Sony/550 Music. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Fans of North Carolina piano man Ben Folds' heretofore wacky pop
ditties, including the 1995 hit ``Underground,'' are going to be
flummoxed by this arty, downbeat release. Ostensibly a concept
album, ``Messner's'' 11 loosely-connected tracks paint a portrait
of a weary soul trying to come to terms with a life gone awry. The
twice-divorced Folds wraps laments on the loss of love and faith in
grandiose arrangements _ the epic ballad ``Narcolepsy'' sounds like
Styx crossed with ``Night and Day''-era Joe Jackson. Not until the
sixth track, ``Army,'' does Folds indulge his wise-cracking side,
riffing on the universal adolescent dilemma of choosing a career.
It's a welcome change-up in this relentlessly sad, often beautiful
work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Anima Animus''
</P>
<P>
   The Creatures. Instinct. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Former Siouxsie and the Banshees linchpins Siouxsie Sioux and
Budgie are the Creatures. They've been exploring edgier realms of
music in this guise since their days in their former band. Sioux's
voice has matured into an impressive instrument over the course of
her 20-plus year career, and her partner has always been a great
percussionist. In fact, the Creatures' work is Budgie's chance to
display his considerable skill on a battery of instruments.
Sequenced synthesizers, marimbas and Sioux's voice dominate the
mix, as the drums lay down an often danceable beat. It's a pretty
dark ride, though, because just like the Banshees, the Creatures'
music always sounds vaguely sinister.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Doug Hamilton and Shane Harrison write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
