<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insect insurrection full of visual effects
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Bug's Life'' (G)
</P>
<P>
   A multi-legged wonder. This computer-animated feature from the
makers of ``Toy Story'' is the eye-popping, witty tale of an ant
named Flik (voice of Dave Foley), who recruits a bunch of circus
bugs to battle evil grasshoppers (the chief villain is voiced by
Kevin Spacey).
</P>
<P>
   The catch is, the big-top critters think they've been hired to
perform, not fight, which leads to a ton of amusing show biz jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's also bursting with extraordinary visual grace notes:
Forests of clover. A dandelion tuft used as a parachute. A rowdy
grasshopper cantina hidden under a sombrero. The flea circus alone
is an eye-filling accumulation of found objects, including a dog
collar used as the main performance ring and a Chinese takeout
carton filling in as a magician's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   There's enough going on here to keep every adult, child or
arachnid vastly entertained. Priced to buy: $26.99 for the VHS
tape, or $34.99 on DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
