</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video mini reviews
 &HT;    By Steve Murray, Jill Vejnoska and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Siege'' (R) _ Which would be worse, a series of
terrorist bombings of New York or the martial-law takeover by the
Army as a response? Denzel Washington, Annette Bening and Bruce
Willis star in a fast-moving, well-made paranoia thriller that
ultimately reduces a hot-button topic to a standard Hollywood
action cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Night at the Roxbury'' (PG-13) _ Those head-bopping,
nightclubbing brothers from ``Saturday Night Live'' (Chris Kattan,
far left, and Will Farrell) are out in a full-fledged story. Well,
as full-fledged as you can get when your central characters are a
couple of clueless, would-be coolsters whose dream is getting into,
and then owning, the hottest club in town. Lots of groaningly funny
lines and a surprisingly coherent story line make this a fun,
thankfully concise viewing experience. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Vejnoska
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Monument Avenue'' (unrated) _ An Irish variation on ``Mean
Streets,'' this is a bleak, gritty look at some pals in a
blue-collar section of Boston whose ties to each other and to the
old neighborhood are strangling them. They spend their time
drinking, snorting coke, stealing cars and adhering to false
notions of honor and loyalty. Colm Meaney and Denis Leary provide
standout performances. Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Simon Birch'' (PG) _ A little movie with big problems. In
the early 1960s, a preadolescent dwarf named Simon Birch (Ian
Michael Smith) is convinced he will one day be a hero, while his
best pal (Joseph Mazzello) tries to solve the mystery of his real
father (Ashley Judd is Mazzello's closemouthed mother). The movie
is clearly a labor of love; alas, it's also a labor to sit through.
Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   Notable videos now on sale
</P>
<P>
   Documentary: ``Intimate Universe: The Human Body,'' as seen on
the Learning Channel, a four-tape set, $59.98.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage romance: ``Portrait of Jennie,'' ``Intermezzo,'' ``The
Farmer's Daughter,'' ``Made for Each Other,'' $14.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray, Jill Vejnoska and Eleanor Ringel Gillespie write
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
