<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7320 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-RINGEL22-COX     04-21 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Other opportunities to love the Bard
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   His labors were never lost.
</P>
<P>
   William Shakespeare would've been 435 years old Friday. The
renewed interest in his work, sparked by ``Shakespeare in Love's''
Oscarthon, must feel like a fitting and long-overdue birthday
present. Geoffrey Rush recalls that while they were filming
``Shakespeare,'' the cast used to come up with other titles (``The
Full Monologue,'' ``You've Got Mercutio'') to make it sound more
audience friendly.
</P>
<P>
   But lately the S-word has been a box-office boon. He's been
teened in movies like ``10 Things I Hate About You'' and given the
Big Star treatment in the more traditional ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Calista Flockhart (it opens
in early May). Still to come are a high-tech ``Titus Andronicus''
with Jessica Lange and Anthony Hopkins and a musical ``Love's
Labour's Lost,'' directed by Kenneth Branagh and starring Alicia
Silverstone and Nathan Lane.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to good Will hunting on video, most of us know to
go to the sections labeled Olivier, Branagh or Welles. However,
you'd be surprised who's tackled iambic pentameter. Mel Gibson
(``Hamlet''), Leonardo DiCaprio (``William Shakespeare's Romeo +
Juliet''), Richard Burton and Elizabeth Taylor (``The Taming of the
Shrew.'')
</P>
<P>
   But let's get really obscure. Here are some Shakespeares on film
from some pretty unexpected sources.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Macbeth'' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   Roman Polanski _ yes, that Polanski, of ``Rosemary's Baby,''
``Chinatown'' and the Charles Manson murders _ directed his version
of Shakespeare's cursed play (superstitious actors always call it
``the Scottish play'') as a tale of ambition, cruelty, pagan ritual
and more slaughter than poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Macbeth is played by Jon Finch; his Lady is Francesca Annis, who
does the sleepwalking scene in the nude (Hugh Hefner produced).
Polanski had hoped that the Shakespeare imprimatur would keep the
critics from making links to the horrors of the Manson massacre
(Polanski's pregant wife, Sharon Tate, was among the victims). Of
course, if that was the idea, why didn't he direct something like
``As You Like It'' or ``Much Ado About Nothing?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``King Lear'' (1970).
</P>
<P>
   Stage director Peter Brook filmed this intensely bleak and
chilly ``Lear'' on location in Denmark. Essentially, it's a
cinematic adaptation of a highly acclaimed stage version he'd done
with the same cast a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It is definitely not for those who barely made it through the
Olivier TV version. It is difficult and opaque and, in its attempt
to link ``Lear'' to the emptiness of Samuel Beckett's work, a
stunning and challenging piece. What any viewer will savor,
however, is the superb British cast, led by Paul Scofield in the
title role. A few years earlier Scofield had won an Oscar playing
Sir Thomas More in the popular historical morality movie ``A Man
for All Seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Richard III'' (1995).
</P>
<P>
   You probably know him now from ``Gods and Monsters,'' but Ian
McKellen gave his first Oscar-worthy performance of the decade
(though he was not nominated) as humpbacked Richard of Gloucestor.
</P>
<P>
   Manipulating his way through a throng of throne-hungry, unruly
royals, he murders friend, foe and family alike in order to get his
hands on the crown. The setting has been changed to England in the
1930s and McKellen makes a magnificently media-savy monster, as
unctuous as he is unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   The impeccable supporting cast ranges from some stalwart Brits
to Hollywood faces like Annette Bening and Robert Downey Jr., both
of whom more than hold their own in such distinguished company.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' (1935).
</P>
<P>
   German theatre director Max Reinhardt (assisted by William
Dieterle) pulled out all the stops for this sumptuous studio
production of Shakespeare's comedy. Dick Powell, Joe E. Brown,
Olivia de Havilland and Anita Louise are among the name players,
but top-billed is James Cagney as Bottom, the weaver who ends up
with an ass's head.
</P>
<P>
   Cagney later recalled that Reinhardt cast him after seeing him
in something called ``Lady Killer'' (go figure). Mickey Rooney is
unexpectedly wonderful as Puck.
</P>
<P>
   Behind-the-scenes note: Halfway through production Rooney broke
his leg skiing and the rest of his scenes were shot from the waist
up (with a double for the long shots).
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
