A7329 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VICTIM-HNS &LR;      04-21 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VICTIM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FATHER, A FRIGHTFUL FLIGHT TO COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Don Jugert was on the tail end of a
three-week business trip in Oregon when the store manager said:
``You're from Denver? Did you hear what happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Jugert rushed to a radio and listened with horror as the
announcers detailed the carnage at suburban Columbine High School _
the school his daughters attend.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five dead, according to the early reports Tuesday. (The
police said Wednesday that 15 children and adults died in the
Tuesday shooting.) Did that grim figure include Angela, 16, a
junior, or Valerie, 15, a freshman?
</P>
<P>
   Jugert, a 44-year-old division manager for Napa Auto Parts, took
a plane to San Francisco to catch a connecting flight to Denver. On
his way to San Francisco, Jugert had no way of knowing what had
happened to his daughters. ``I tried calling my wife, but all the
lines were busy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the flight, Jugert entertained what he later called
``weird thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled a Saturday, two weeks ago, when he drove Valerie to
the school to see if her name was on the freshly posted list of new
cheerleaders. She had tried out before and failed to make the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Jugert sat in the car and shot video of his daughter as she
walked hesitantly to the posting and then shrieked with delight at
what she saw. He remembered how, as they drove home that day, she
said, ``Dad, this is the best weekend of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flight, he thought about Charlton Heston, his former
big-screen idol, now head of the National Rifle Association and a
spokesman for the right to bear arms. Jugert was an NRA member at
one time. He turned in his membership card several years ago
because he didn't like the organization's politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to love Charlton Heston,'' he said. ``But I'm always
going to have that sick feeling now when I watch him. `The Ten
Commandments' used to be one of my favorite movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jugert landed at San Francisco International Airport and rushed
to a phone kiosk. He called his father in Denver. He called his
wife, Char, in Littleton. Finally, he got the words he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Both daughters were alive and unharmed. He wanted to hug them.
</P>
<P>
   He boarded United Flight 1286, departing at 9:15 p.m. for
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad Valerie didn't have her cheerleader uniform
on,'' he said after takeoff. ``I know they would have targeted the
cheerleaders.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Valerie knew the group of students the suspected gunmen belonged
to _ the so-called Trench Coat Mafia. She ``just hated those
people,'' Jugert said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Valerie had been on the school's commons when the shots
rang out from nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all thought it was a senior prank,'' Jugert said. Like
last week, when the seniors glued all the school doors shut. Or the
time they threw water balloons at the freshmen during assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a teacher told her to get down,'' Jugert said. That
teacher was shot twice in the back, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Angela ran from the school library. It was there that
the gunman continued their rampage minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Char Jugert received a call from a friend in Atlanta
who had learned about the shooting on the news. That was Char's
first word of it. She tried to drive to the school, but couldn't
get close.
</P>
<P>
   It would be four hours before she learned that her daughters
were unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughters . . . were looking for each other,'' Don Jugert
said. At first, though, each girl fled from the school and took
refuge in separate houses in the neighborhood, as instructed by the
authorities at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   When Valerie and her mother finally were reunited, the freshman
kept insisting that the FBI let her return to the school to get her
backpack ``because she was going to ballet,'' Don Jugert said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she got home, her dad said, Valerie wasn't in the
mood to dance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
