<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7335 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      04-21 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
April 22, 1999. If you have any questions, please call The Star's
News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   TWA (Kansas City, Mo.) _ TWA reports a lower net loss for the
first quarter and improved operating results. By Randolph Heaster
(Story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NATO (Washington D.C.) _ The city braces for NATO's 50th
anniversary celebration, which begins Friday and will virtually
shut down the entire city for the weekend. It will be the largest
gathering ever of world leaders in Washington. 30 inches. By David
Goldstein. (Story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Live coverage from city, with an
emphasis on the victims, their families, the school and the
community. Who are the kids who were shot, and where were they when
the rampage caught them? We know from reports that some were
minorities, some were athletes and some seemed to be random. By
Scott Canon. 35 inches. (Story will move in the ``a'' category )
</P>
<P>
   MAFIA (Littleton, Colo.) _ Profile of the Trenchcoat Mafia,
exploring how it developed, how large it had become and anything
else that develops or is discovered about the perpetrators, their
home lives and the surviving students who associated with them. By
Rick Montgomery. (Story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUT _ In Racine, Wis., last year, police arrested five boys who
allegedly had threatened to take over the school and kill a bunch
of students and teachers. As it turned out, the boys had no
weapons, and some people criticized authorities for going
overboard. A day after the Colorado shootings, though, it looks
like the folks in Wisconsin were on to something. We'll look at
aggressive intervention and whether it works. How far can
authorities go in intervening before they start treading on
students' civil rights? Can you predict what teen-agers will do? At
least one expert says many young people act weird and make threats
but just a tiny percentage actually will carry them out. Is it
worth trying to identify outcasts? We talk with law enforcement
folks, scholars, teachers, counselors, administrators and others in
public and private schools to see what they think about all of
this. By Jean Buchanan, Kate Beem, Oscar Avila. (Story will move in
the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SECURE _ A roundup of what area schools have added in the way of
policies and equipment to keep students safe. Blue Valley recently
added security cameras. What's the status of metal detectors,
security cameras and guards at area schools? What does that
equipment cost? What would any of that equipment do to increase
parent confidence or prevent an incident such as the one outside
Denver? What types of crimes or activities do these investments
reduce? (Story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ For years, people thought nothing could be done about
drunken driving, but then a bunch of mothers got mad and changed
society's perceptions. Some people wonder when Americans will get
fed up with gun violence and say `We're mad as hell, and we're not
going to take it any more?' 15 inches (Story will move in the ``a''
category)
</P>
<P>
   COPE _ Are local schools doing anything special to help students
cope with the deaths in Littleton? Are their special discussion
groups, teachers talking one to one with students or counselors
offering their assistance? Will school districts makes changes in
their anti-violence programs? Olathe school officials are meeting
this morning to discuss its anti-violence policies. We check with
school districts throughout the metro area. 25. TBA with feeds from
school reporters in Indy and the Northland. (Story will move in the
``a'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
