<HEADLINE>
THE RAP ON BOW WOW; SPIN GOES   ON A BENDER; IT'S THE MONEY,
HONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes writers don't have healthy boundaries. And sometimes
they start taking on the attributes of their subjects. So let's
just be thankful that Tom Junod was not writing a piece on Roberto
Benigni for the May issue of Esquire, whose cover features a
close-up of David Duchovny looking rather stuck. With his trademark
adventurousness, Junod composes a full-length profile of
11-year-old rapper Bow Wow and his producer, Jermaine Dupri, in rap
style _ rhyming couplets, if you prefer. ``Now for all y'all who
don't know who Jermaine is _ / well, you ain't dead yet, just on
intravenous, / and we'll call the doctor, and instead of sutures, /
we'll ask him to give you a glimpse of the future. / 'Cause just
like his rival, Sean Combs (aka `Puffy'), / Jermaine's shaping the
mind of your sweet daughter, Muffy.'' The ambitious rap narrative
couldn't have been easy to write, but it's hard to take for six
pages, and too self-conscious to capture the drama of Jermaine's
play for the puppy soul of Bow Wow, whose real name _ Shad Moss _
was changed by Snoop Dogg. It's an invention that goes to lengths
too dire to bring the rap world to the men of Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   The Duchovny piece is a classic meta-interview, with the
monotoned ``X-Files'' actor sharing plenty about why he doesn't
like sharing his personal life with strangers. His feelings on
public revelation range from the vague _ ``I always find it
objectionable'' _ to the insecure, as he explains that doing
promotion means his work is not strong enough to attract viewers on
its own. His theories about America's love-hate relationship with
fame range from the simplistic _ ``I always feel, when somebody
calls you a star, it's like they're saying fag'' _ to the
elaborate, including his notion that people have controling and
envious feelings toward celebrities because they think of them as
children: ``For hundreds of years . . . the grownups sat around and
watched the kids play. Now they sit around and watch television.''
The talking-about-not-talking approach is a fitting one for
Duchovny, whose ``X-Files'' acting often depends on trust-no-one
reticence.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Duchovny has also inspired loose couplets, but the
rhyming lines about the much-drooled-over star are Internet odes to
the bathing suit he wore in an ``X-Files'' episode. One goes,
``Little red Speedo, so privileged is it / Upon those fine buns, it
proudly does sit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year it was Courtney Love and Billy Corgan and Marilyn
Manson, and this year it's Bender, the robot who's got issues. For
some reason, rock magazine Spin for May gives a giant plug to
``Simpsons'' creator Matt Groening's new animated series,
``Futurama,'' by featuring the show on its cover. I guess
``Futurama'' has some hidden alternative credibility, but the
hoo-ha does seem a bit premature, as the month-old show, set in the
year 3000, is still very much in the ``promising'' phase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fat New Yorker for April 26 and May 3 is ``The Money
Issue,'' featuring a surprisingly confessional piece by Daphne
Merkin about how growing up wealthy has affected her. Merkin also
talks about the taboo that keeps the subject of money ``in the
closet,'' and how ``you are more likely to get a woman to confess
that she has committed incest with her father than to disclose what
her father earns, or whether she's being subsidized by any of his
money.'' Another confessional piece, by Arthur Krystal, looks at
laziness, which ``just is. It's like being freckled or
color-blind.'' He admits that ``I liked everything about money
except the prospect of buckling down and making it. . . . The
thought of being bound and defined by work that didn't interest me
sent shivers down my spine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
