<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEER WORK AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a tight labor market forcing large and small companies to
find new ways to attract and keep good employees, volunteering is
fast becoming a corporate trend and recruiting tool.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning behind the push: Volunteerism not only promotes a
company's image, but also attracts skilled people in a competitive
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best and the brightest are often those who are involved in
community service,'' says Edmund Burke, founder of Boston College's
Center for Corporate Community Relations and a believer.
</P>
<P>
   At Fleet Bank, 3,000 employees will roll up their sleeves for
National Volunteer Week and spruce up a gym, read to children,
landscape a shelter's grounds, sort clothes, or serve meals at a
Boston shelter for women.
</P>
<P>
   At Warner Bros. in Burbank, Calif., employees routinely scan a
menu of volunteer projects before registering their choices with
the company's volunteer coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   At Time Warner in New York, workers receive a monthly bulletin
of volunteer opportunities. One popular offering: Time To Read, an
on-going program that pairs 4,200 tutors with more than 16,000 kids
at 300 company sites.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the nonprofit New York Cares. It designs volunteer
opportunities for busy professionals who long for ``the flexibility
to volunteer without the long-term commitment,'' says spokeswoman
Susan Schnall. ``A lot of young professionals travel, work long
hours, and really can't give more than a few hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   But should charity really begin at work?
</P>
<P>
   The California-based Ayn Rand Institute says it shouldn't. The
group has launched a campaign against corporate volunteerism and,
specifically, the reasoning behind it. Named after writer Ayn Rand,
author of ``The Fountainhead,'' the institute maintains that all
relationships are based on whether there are mutual benefits to the
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with (corporate) volunteerism . . . is managers
are now being encouraged to volunteer,'' said spokesman Chris
Wolski. ``In some cases, it is part of upper management's goals . .
. We're against that. It means people are being seen as part of a
collective greater good rather than individuals. It also means they
may be asked to do things they might not do otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, volunteerism appears to have struck a chord in the
nation's executive suites. The Points of Light Foundation reports
that 1,500 companies are now members of volunteer councils, up from
just 600 in 1985. Meanwhile, workplace specialists are attributing
the surge to the labor shortage, increased competition, and a more
critical, and discerning, consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It promotes a company's image,'' says Michael Stevenson, a
spokesman for the BC center. ``A company like Timberland, for
example, becomes recognized for community involvement, and it may
even gain sales that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke, author of ``Corporate Community Relations: The Principle
of the Neighbor of Choice,'' says public expectations have forced
companies to take a closer look at their relationship with their
``neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer enough for a company to produce a decent
product,'' he says. ``A company must also demonstrate its concern
for the environment, and to the communities where it is based.
People expect them to be more responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many working people barely have enough time for
community service, employees say they are attracted to a menu of
volunteer choices many big employers offer. It allows them to
select an activity without worrying about finding the time.
</P>
<P>
   At Fleet, some 3,000 members of its companywide volunteer army
known as TeamFleet will don blue T-shirts with the program's
insignia before volunteering at 110 different nonprofit agencies in
New England, New York, Milwaukee, Pennsylvania, Colorado, and South
Carolina _ wherever the bank has operations or affiliates, says
Melissa MacDonnell, a Fleet vice president who launched the program
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Other employee volunteers may opt to take two paid days off
during the year to assist the needy.
</P>
<P>
   One year, Lisa Joyner, a 33-year-old community development
officer at the bank, painted a barn at Boston's Franklin Park Zoo.
Another year she worked at a day-care center. And although they
were mostly one-time projects, Joyner insists that her contribution
was priceless to her; her impact, considerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone to elderly socials, assisted the homeless,
participated in clothing drives, and tutored children,'' says
Joyner, who involves her children in her volunteer activities.
``They were all wonderful experiences, a chance to give back.''
</P>
<P>
   After donating her time over two years to the Horizons
Initiative, a Dorchester day-care center for the children of
homeless women, executive assistant Diane McKinley was commended
for spending more hours on volunteer activities than any other
TeamFleet member. The company also contributed $10,000 to Horizons
in her name.
</P>
<P>
   While supporters hail corporate volunteerism, some workplace
advocates worry that employees who do not volunteer may be viewed
as having little or no management potential, or could miss out on
lucrative bonuses and perks.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 survey by the BC center found that 85 percent of 227
corporate relations professionals had encouraged managers at their
companies to volunteer. Twenty-three percent required that managers
volunteer, and 17 percent said community involvement was an
important criteria in evaluating overall performance.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, for example, has included community involvement and
volunteerism among its objectives or goals for a select group of
senior executives. Among the goals: serving on nonprofit boards,
encouraging employees to volunteer, and participating in the
company's employee charitable campaign. Community involvement also
is part of the executives' bonus structure.
</P>
<P>
   What happens if a senior executive chooses not to volunteer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, community service is not the only measure of
evaluating a person's performance,'' said Stanley S. Litow, vice
president of corporate community relations at IBM in Armonk, N.Y.
He says IBM last year contributed $22 million through its employee
charitable campaign. IBM also contributes $1,500 to the charity of
the employee's choice for any volunteer who contributes more than
100 hours of time to a school of community agency. Said Litow:
``These are incentives at the employee and management level that
support strong corporate citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com, or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
