<HEADLINE>
DERBY TO BE TWICE THE FUN FOR LUKAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Derby contenders text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDIRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trainer D. Wayne Lukas will go to the Kentucky Derby with both
barrels loaded.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Lukas would have just one horse, Cat Thief, in the
Run for the Roses. Cat Thief is a hard-trying sort, but he has been
unable to win in four starts this year. That changed Sunday, when
Lukas saddled Charismatic to victory in the $378,700 Lexington
Stakes at Keeneland. The next stop for Charismatic, a son of Summer
Squall owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, owners of Silver Charm, will
be the Derby May 1. Normally, a horse with a career record of
14-3-2-3 would be dismissed from Derby consideration, but not this
year, with the race the most wide open in memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps getting better and better,'' said Lukas. ``I've
trained him harder than I have any other horse coming up to the
Derby. The Derby was next whether it was win, lose, or draw in the
Lexington.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Charismatic dominated the field under Jerry
Bailey, winning by 2 1/2 lengths in 1:41, a new stakes record, for
the mile and one-16th. Charismatic was off at 12-1 ($26.20 to win),
surprisingly high odds considering he had run a decent fourth in
the $1 million Santa Anita Derby April 3, a test considered the
best of the Derby preps this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going real easy down the backside,'' said Bailey. ``I
was just sitting there waiting for my spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert will have at least two Derby entrants, Prime
Timber and General Challenge; Nick Zito also will have two, Adonis
and Stephen Got Even; and now Lukas will have a duo as well. Once
again, the trainer with the highest profile in America, whose
election to the Hall of Fame will be announced during Derby week,
refuses to be outdone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A strong hand
</P>
<P>
   Baffert unquestionably holds the strongest hand. General
Challenge and Prime Timber finished 1-2 in the Santa Anita Derby,
respectively, and both worked very well in their first trip over
the Churchill Downs strip. Also, Sillverbulletday, the fine filly
trained by Baffert and owned by Mike Pegram, owner of Real Quiet,
last year's Derby winner, is training sensationally under the Twin
Spires. However, Baffert continues to insist he is leaning toward
starting Silverbulletday in the Kentucky Oaks April 30, instead of
the Derby. On Saturday, General Challenge worked 5 furlongs in 1:00
1/5, out 6 furlongs in 1:12 1/5; while Prime Timber went 1:00 3/5,
out in 1:13 2/5. ``He's amazing,'' said exercise rider Dana Barnes
of General Challenge. ``Sometimes, when Bob gives me the fractions
(via walkie-talkie), I think, `There's no way, he's not going that
fast, I don't believe you.' I look around and see if he's watching
the wrong horse or something.'' ``He has really improved,'' said
Barnes of Prime Timber. ``He's grown up so much. Before, he would
hang with a horse while training; now, he just opens up.''
Silverbulletday sizzled five panels in 59 seconds Sunday, more than
two seconds faster than any other drill at that distance on that
day's Churchill work tab. ``She's quick and she loves this track,
but I'm still thinking Oaks,'' said Baffert. ``I know what it takes
for the Derby, and maybe something could change, but the field
would have to change a lot. It's a large field and she's a little
filly, she's light.'' . . . Exploit, who also was trained by
Baffert and was the winter-book favorite for the Derby until he was
injured finishing second in the San Felipe March 13, his only
defeat, will stand at stud at Taylor Made Farm in Nicholasville,
Ky. No stud fee has bee set. The son of Storm Cat won five of his
six starts and earned nearly $400,000 in his brief career . . .
Desert Hero, third in the Santa Anita Derby in only the third start
of his career, worked 7 furlongs in 1:23 4/5 at Santa Anita
Saturday. ``This was a good tightener for him,'' said trainer
Richard Mandella.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Quiet year
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet has run only twice this year and has lost both races.
After running second in the New Orleans Handicap at Fair Grounds
March 7, his first start since losing the Belmont Stakes, and
Triple Crown, by a nose to Victory Gallop last June, Real Quiet was
beaten again Sunday in the $250,000 Texas Mile at Lone Star. This
time, Real Quiet ran into a tiger as he was outfinished by
defending champion Littlebitlively. A 5-year-old son of Lively One,
Littlebitlively is tough at a mile, and he and Carlos Gonzalez held
off Real Quiet and Gary Stevens to prevail by a neck.
Littlebitlively, who was 5-2 ($7.40 to win), covered the distance
in 1:35 3/5. Real Quiet, who was 1-2, ran well and stuck his head
in front turning for home, but Littlebitlively came back along the
rail to gain the edge. ``I was surprised that they let me make the
lead so easily,'' said Gonzalez. ``He really wanted to go early,
but I got him to relax. He was running easy. I just waited for
someone to come to me.'' Next for both horses will be the Pimlico
Special, at 1 1/8 miles, May 8 . . . Suffolk Downs plans to begin
grass racing May 1 and 2-year-old racing May 2. Management believes
the infield course will be in top shape because dry weather has
prevailed during March and April, keeping the turf firm. The first
juvenile contest will be for fillies at 4 furlongs, followed the
next day by a like contest for colts . . . Suffolk will accept
advance wagering on the Derby, starting Friday, April 30. On Derby
Day, gates will open at 10:30 a.m., and Suffolk will offer a
souvenir Derby glass and a pass for the month of May with paid
admission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DERBY CONTENDERS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Here's a look at six of the top Kentucky Derby contenders:
</P>
<P>
   -- General Challenge. Sire: General Meeting. Jockey: Gary
Stevens. Trainer: Bob Baffert. Last race: Won Santa Anita Derby
April 3. Next race: Kentucky Derby at Churchill Downs May 1. &QL; 
-- Menifee. Sire: Harlan. Jockey: Pat Day. Trainer: Elliott Walden.
Last race: Won Blue Grass at Keeneland April 10. Next race:
Kentucky Derby. &QL; 
-- Stephen Got Even. Sire: A.P. Indy. Jockey: Chris McCarron.
Trainer: Nick Zito. Last race: Won Gallery Furniture at Turfway
Park March 27. Next race: Kentucky Derby. &QL; 
-- Worldy Manner. Sire: Riverman. Jockey: Jerry Bailey. Trainer:
Saeed bin Suroor. Last race: Won Dubai Derby Trial 1 at Nad al
Sheba Racecourse March 21. Next race: Kentucky Derby. &QL; 
-- Prime Timber. Sire: Sultry Song. Jockey: David Flores. Trainer:
Baffert. Last race: Second in Santa Anita Derby. Next race:
Kentucky Derby. &QL; 
-- Charismatic. Sire: Summer Squall. Jockey: Bailey. Trainer: D.
Wayne Lukas. Last race: Won Lexington at Keeneland April 18. Next
race: Kentucky Derby. &QL; 
COMPILED BY RON INDRISANO
</P>
</TEXT>
