<HEADLINE>
THE LOVE SONGS OF THORSTEIN VEBLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just the other day someone asked me what I did during my recent
fellowship at Stanford University. I responded with the usual
noises about studying psychology and going to the opera. But the
truthful answer would have been: I was researching Thorstein
Veblen's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   Not every distinguished man's sex life is worth researching, as
I learned while reading Evan Thomas's biography of superlawyer
Edward Bennett Williams. The extramarital dalliances (in the
company of the sainted Joe DiMaggio) of a repressed Catholic who
attended Mass every morning make for dull fare. But Veblen, the
enfant terrible of the turn-of-the-century economics profession,
enjoyed not just an interesting sex life; as his latest biographers
Elizabeth and Henry Jorgensen make clear, he enjoyed a life in
full.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Veblen's name is more likely to pop up on ``Jeopardy''
(April 11, 1997; category ``The Midwest'') than in a college
classroom. Too rusty for economics courses, his landmark ``Theory
of the Leisure Class'' occasionally appears in American Studies
courses. In their biography, ``Thorstein Veblen: Victorian
Firebrand,'' the Jorgensens complain, with some justification, that
Veblen is a ``lost man''; ``for a century, America has been in
denial about Veblen's ideas,'' which have been ``buried underneath
a sanitary landfill of lies and half-truths.''
</P>
<P>
   (I recall a conversation with Ms. Jorgensen, during which she
suggested that my article on Veblen's Stanford entanglements
(www.stanfordmag.org/sepoct97/articles/veblen.html) belonged to
said landfill.)
</P>
<P>
   So let the excavations begin!
</P>
<P>
   There can be no such thing as a dull biography of Veblen, and
this one does not disappoint. Born, yes, in a log cabin, the man
who would later anathematize the titans of capital was a cradle
contrarian. ``He is queer and always has been queer,'' his brother
Ed complained, using the word in the old-fashioned sense. While
Sioux marauders were killing fellow Norwegian homesteaders in
Minnesota during the 1860s, the boy Thorstein sided with the
Indians. ``Shortly after the close of the Civil War,'' his brother
noted, ``he took the side of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   A-religious _ ``If there is a difference between religion and
magic I have never seen it,'' he once said _ Veblen disdained his
family's prairie Lutheranism and mocked the pieties of America's
Golden Age. He was at heart an anthropologist. ``The Theory of the
Leisure Class'' represents fieldwork among the grandees who sent
their children to the universities where he taught, and among his
censorious in-laws. That he likened ``conspicuous consumption'' of
unneeded luxuries to the ceremonial face painting of African
chieftains made him few friends. His trenchant analysis of what
came to be called male chauvinism in his essay ``The Barbarian
Status of Women'' made him even more unpopular. Except, perhaps,
among women.
</P>
<P>
   Veblen attracted intelligent women, who shared his contempt for
male ritual. Even for the serious-minded Jorgensens, it seems
impossible to separate Veblen's life story from his love stories.
His first wife, Ellen Rolfe, destroyed his academic career by
tattling about her husband's affairs to the presidents of Stanford
and the University of Chicago. After trudging all night through a
blizzard to visit his second wife in Nowhere, Idaho, Veblen
contracted a double pneumonia that crippled him for life.
</P>
<P>
   Veblen wasn't all sweetness and light. The Jorgensens correctly
note that even his most famous writings seem thick and turgid to
the modern taste. But he was that rarest of birds in 20th century
America: a dangerous thinker. It's delicious to imagine what Veblen
would have made of Tina Brown's New Yorker _ a magazine so full of
gibberish that you had to read it _ or of ``Seinfeld''-mania, the
fetishistic worship of . . . nothing.
</P>
<P>
   That Veblen should have lived so long to read sympathetic
biographies of the robber barons Rockefeller and Morgan . . . Maybe
he's better off where he is, chuckling at our frailties from the
great beyond.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
