<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY, BORED, CONFUSED? THIS BOOK'S FOR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some books aim to go deep, and some go for being broad. ``Angry,
Bored, Confused'' is one of the broad ones.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh survey of the current political scene by Bridgewater
(Mass.) State College professor Michael J. Kryzanek lives up to its
subtitle: ``A Citizen Handbook of American Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   First the good news: There are only two fleeting references to
Monica Lewinsky, and the Starr Report is mentioned (``tawdry'')
only in connection with a disapproving explanation of shock
journalism. But the role of scandal in American political history
is thoroughly aired in the context of explaining the periodic waves
of apathy and anger sparked by the usual suspects (Watergate,
Teapot Dome, etc.) as well as the hazy ones _ I am still a little
shaky on the Tilden-Hayes imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
   A short and ideologically neutral epilogue alludes to the Senate
impeachment debate, but the author is more interested in linking
the impeachment to the deeply rooted irritation Americans feel
toward politicians and journalists for forcing that squalid
business under their noses.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news? Cynicism is rampant, for all the obvious reasons.
Voter participation is charted ominously. The media peddle scandal
and conspiracy at every turn. Kryzanek describes ``the X-Filing of
America'' by conspiracy theorists who feed off the gamy fare
offered by ``the dark side of the evening news.'' Into a broad
national context he weaves the threads of the Murrah Federal
Building bombing in Oklahoma City, the mishandling federal agents
of the Waco debacle, the demoralizing impact of unquenchable
campaign finance outrages.
</P>
<P>
   What's particularly useful about ``Angry, Bored, Confused'' is
the way the 292 pages are broken up into bite-size chunks of
readily accessible charts, quote boxes, polling breakdowns,
demographic entrailing, and reading lists at the end of each
chapter. The presentation is straight down the middle, no
recognizable bias to either right or left.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone interested in contemporary politics, whether it's the
debate about how large a defense budget is big enough or the
skeletal innards of NAFTA and the foreign trade debate, this is a
helpful jumping-off point. It would take the student _ anyone from
high school to grad school would find this a handy compendium for
papers or exams _ easily into the next level of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Kryzanek's aim was to make a user-friendly text for his college
students, and the publisher casts the result as a guide for the
``anxious consumer'' of political news. Unless you are a daily
communicant with a first-class newspaper, a lot of the serious work
of the journalism world skates right past you.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fact, much lamented by newspaper proprietors and
believers in the American system of government, that young people
today are seduced away from reading serious newspaper fare by
television and shock-jock radio. If it is true that the students of
the '90s are far less politically aware than their parents of the
'60s, then a compendium such as ``Angry, Bored, Confused'' is a
useful how-to manual for understanding the political game and the
stakes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, 58 percent of incoming college freshmen said keeping up
with political affairs is ``very important.'' Last year, only 27
percent agreed. When you cut the level of political interest among
your educated young by half in three decades, something is rotten
in the state of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the country's history, George Washington wrote
that the people of the 13 colonies had to do their part as well,
``and if their citizens should not be completely free and happy,
the fault will be entirely their own.'' That is not the case today.
Complaining about the government is as ingrained as complaining
about taxes and as close as the nearest radio dial.
</P>
<P>
   After his lengthy survey of the American political scene, the
author begins his epilogue with a Groucho Marx line: ``Politics is
the art of looking for trouble, finding it everywhere, diagnosing
it incorrectly, and applying the wrong remedies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kryzanek even gives you a short quiz to see if you're a liberal
or a conservative. It's simplest version: If your hero was Franklin
Roosevelt (government is the solution to what ailed America in the
Depression), then you're a liberal. If your hero is Ronald Reagan
(government is the problem), then you're a conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of your answer, if you read this book, you're a lot
better informed about politics and government than you were
beforehand, and you have a better grip on what must be done to
improve things.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
