<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKESPEARE IN `ECOTOPIA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA JOLLA, Calif. _ Celebrants have saluted one since 1970 and
the other since 1564. Earth Day and William Shakespeare's birthday
honor similar ideals: a sense of order, balance, and the ``placing
of man in the traditional cosmic setting between the angels and the
beasts.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the judgment of ``The Elizabethan World Picture,''
written more than 50 years ago by a Cambridge don with the hefty
handle of Eustace Mandeville Wetenhall Tillyard. Environmentalists,
who rely on hard science, could consider Tillyard's scholarship in
the humanities as green as a rainforest when he explains what
Shakespeare's audiences took for granted.
</P>
<P>
   What Alexander Pope called ``a vast chain of being'' included
the four elements of earth, water, fire, and air. ``When Cleopatra
said she was all air and fire, the educated part of the audience at
least would understand without the slightest effort of memory. The
property of air and fire was to go upwards in a straight line, as
was that of earth and water to go down,'' Tillyard explains in a
slim, 109-page book.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabethans would have understood modern ecological disasters.
Smog over Los Angeles? Too much fire in the air. Chernobyl and
Three Mile Island? Too much fire in the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare was born on ``the uncertain glory of an April day,''
as spring is described by Proteus, one of ``The Two Gentlemen of
Verona,'' the Beach Boys of their time. On the beaches of La Jolla,
this April's glory is certain. Surfers and snorkelers, bikers and
strollers savor the beaches of this town, ``jewel'' in Spanish. La
Jolla is a capital of what the bard of American geography, Joel
Garreau, calls ``Ecotopia,'' one of his nine nations of North
America. The Pacific coast is the hub of outdoor life, from here to
Big Sur to Santa Cruz up to Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The four elements survive today mostly in the astrological
columns, but in Shakespeare's time they commanded the center of
political debate between the medieval and the modern, rather like a
typical Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of Copernicus and a wide knowledge of his theories
through popular handbooks, the ordinary educated Elizabethan
thought of the universe as geocentric,'' Tillyard writes.
Shakespeare's villains are in the Copernican camp, sneering
satirically at the influence of the zodiac. ``The fault, dear
Brutus, is not in the stars but in ourselves,'' says Cassius in
``Julius Caesar.'' In ``King Lear,'' Edmund mocks ``the excellent
foppery of the world,'' that ``we make guilty of our disasters the
sun, the moon, and the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabethans were open to learning, and even Marlowe's
Tamburlaine would have approved of the Scripps Institution of
Oceanography here:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nature, that fram'd us of four elements
</P>
<P>
   Warring within our breasts for regiment
</P>
<P>
   Doth teach us all to have aspiring minds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Order encompassed more than four elements, and its most stirring
summations are in Shakespeare's later plays. ``The Tempest'' takes
place in the Bermuda Triangle, what he called ``the vexed
Bermoothes,'' where Miranda welcomes a ``brave, new world.'' In
``Troilus and Cressida,'' Ulysses says that when the planets
``observe degree, priority, and place,'' all is well, yet ``Take
but degree away, untune that string, and hark, what discord
follows.''
</P>
<P>
   On the shores of Ecotopia, on the edge of the mighty Pacific, a
few winter storms away from destruction, they still issue building
permits on the bluffs of Encinitas for expensive houses. In his
64th sonnet, Shakespeare warns of the day:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When I have seen the hungry ocean gain
</P>
<P>
   Advantage on the kingdom of the shore
</P>
<P>
   And the firm soil win of the watery main,
</P>
<P>
   Increasing store with loss and loss with store.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The soundest environmental impact statement ever filed was
Puck's, who proclaimed in ``A Midsummer's Night Dream'': ``Lord,
what fools these mortals be!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
