<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7356 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENS-MESSAGING-BOS &LR;      04-21 1733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-MESSAGING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GABBY TEENS, IT'S, LIKE, INSTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 11:15 p.m. and all is quiet at Ariel Klemmer's house. The
homework's done. The folks are in bed. Even Chip, the pet
chinchilla, is down for the night.
</P>
<P>
   But Ariel, 17, is in the family room, hunkered down in front of
the computer, where things are just starting to heat up. In their
respective homes, the same is true for Eric Hou, Nisha Hirani,
Brian Hemond, Casey Sukeforth, and Erica Holland, to name just a
few friends Ariel will be ``i.m.-ing'' tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instant messaging,'' an Internet tool that lets computer users
have live conversations, is to teenagers of the cyber-generation
what the princess phone was to baby boomers _ stupefying parents
who can't understand what their kids could be saying to each other
for so long, and effectively denying phone or computer access to
anyone else in the household.
</P>
<P>
   It's not e-mail, since conversations are held in real time. It's
not a chat room, since conversations take place between two people
(although several can be held simultaneously, in different
windows), and messages can only be sent to and from people on the
user's own predetermined ``buddy list'' if they happen to be on
line at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging is more like a written telephone conversation.
Or the script of a play, one with lots of characters, assorted
sound effects, but no obvious final act. It's real life, for better
or worse.
</P>
<P>
   An actual conversation:
</P>
<P>
   Brian to Ariel (who is also talking to Casey): What's up :).
</P>
<P>
   Ariel to Brian: Not much.
</P>
<P>
   (Sound of a door squeaking, an America Online gimmick to
indicate that someone who is on line is getting off.)
</P>
<P>
   Ariel to Eric: Why did Erica leave?
</P>
<P>
   Eric: I dunno, she's done that, like, five times.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel to Eric: Freaky.
</P>
<P>
   Eric to Ariel: Yeah, weird. (He steers the conversation to his
plans to get a passport.) My dad says it'll take like 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel to Eric: Can you pay to get it done right away?
</P>
<P>
   Eric to Ariel: It's $35. That's 3 1/2 Presidential Breakfasts
(at Bickford's) with 3 1/2 sides of toast. I'm too cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for American Online, which popularized
the use of instant messaging, some 432 million instant messages
travel across AOL each day, but there are no figures on the age of
the senders. (A number of other services, such as ICQ and Yahoo,
offer the feature, too.)
</P>
<P>
   But it's a good guess, based on interviews with area teens, that
a large percentage of the users are high school and middle school
students, along with a smaller number of their copycat siblings in
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   In the household of the Joyce family, 12-year-old Caitlin has 89
i.m. buddies on her list, while her younger sister Kristin, 9, has
(at last count) 82.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a little party every night,'' observes Dan Klemmer,
Ariel's father. `I find it very interesting that there is this
thing called phones and they see each other during the day, and yet
(instant messaging) is a religious event.''
</P>
<P>
   From a teen's point of view, the advantages are numerous. It
doesn't make the phone ring and wake up parents. It makes gossip
instantaneous. You can talk to several people at once _ and surf
the Web for a homework project, on a different screen, at the same
time. (You can also listen to music, eat a bowl of cereal, and talk
on the phone _ if you happen to have a second line.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very fun,'' giggles Erica Holland, 16, a junior at
Lexington (Mass.) High School, and one of Ariel Klemmer's regular
i.m. partners. ``You get to talk to a whole bunch of people. If
they're people I don't see a lot during the day, I feel like I am
in contact with them.'' She considers i.m.-ing either ``relaxing''
or ``hectic'' _ depending on how many people she is talking to at
once. (Unlike her friend Ariel, who has been known to manage six
i.m. converations at the same time, Erica says she only juggles
three comfortably.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually get a lot of work done while I'm on line,''
contends Erica's friend and frequent i.m. partner Eric Hou, 18, a
senior at Lexington High. ``It's not like substantial 10-page
essays, but if I have some busywork, I'll do that, like 10 problems
in math.''
</P>
<P>
   Bopping from conversation to conversation, from screen to
screen, isn't much of an exertion to him. ``It doesn't seem to bug
me that much,'' he says. ``I've grown up around computers. It's
just been, like, this big thing in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Did someone mention a generation gap? ``I am usually stunned
when someone sends me (an i.m.),'' says Sue Cohen, a lawyer and
mother of two i.m-literate daughters. ``It's not like when you go
to your mailbox, and you take a letter out and look at the return
address and open it up. Someone knows you're on line. That blows me
away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, a network of subtle rules and etiquette has
evolved around teenage i.m. use. For example:
</P>
<P>
   --No thought or observation is too trivial or mundane (for
example: ``I'm hungry'' or ``my foot fell asleep.'')
</P>
<P>
   --Abbreviations and shorthand are encouraged. As in: lol
(``laughing out loud''); brb (``be right back''); jk (``just
kidding.'') Likewise, code language is desirable. Consider this
exchange between Ariel Klemmer and Erica Holland:
</P>
<P>
   Erica: How's your running?
</P>
<P>
   Ariel: Great.
</P>
<P>
   Erica: Bread?
</P>
<P>
   Ariel: Extended forest.
</P>
<P>
   Erica: Was Eric mad?
</P>
<P>
   Ariel: When I run I don't get hungry. And he was like, where
were u?
</P>
<P>
   Erica: :)
</P>
<P>
   (Translation: Ariel and Eric and another girl started out
running together. Erica asks if they did the ``bread run''
referring to the route past a bakery that offers free bread slices.
No, responds Ariel, they left Eric and ran down Forest Street, and
a little farther. Eric, meanwhile, spent 20 minutes waiting for
them at the bread store.)
</P>
<P>
   --Speed is favored over precision; proper spelling and
punctuation may be disregarded.
</P>
<P>
   --It is important to be considerate of others. Always answer
promptly, for fear of being labeled ``boring'' or of being
``canceled,'' whereby one user chooses not to get another's
messages. Don't overdo visual devices (``I've been said to abuse
smiley faces,'' confesses Erica Holland.)
</P>
<P>
   --It is considered very rude to fall asleep. ``When that
happens, I give up and turn the whole thing off,'' says Nisha
Hirani, 17.
</P>
<P>
   --Changing your screen names frequently is cool, especially
among younger i.m.-ers. ``I just, like, get sick of one,'' says
Caitlin Joyce, 12, whose recent screen names have included
shamrock23, joycer27, and fitchlax1 (a composite of her combined
interests in Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch and lacrosse.)
</P>
<P>
   --If you're desperate and no one else is on line, you can always
talk to yourself, suggests Caitlin. ``It's really fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is an adult to make of this rapid-fire, minimalist form of
socializing? Of these ``virtuosos . . . (in the) layering of
communication modes,'' says MIT's Sherry Turkle, who teaches the
sociology of science.
</P>
<P>
   Parents seem to either love it or hate it. They worry that it's
keeping their kids up at night and preventing them from getting
their homework done. On the other hand, they always know where
their kids are. And it improves their typing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of cute on a lot of levels,'' says Dan Klemmer, a
sixth-grade teacher in Cambridge, Mass. ``Friendships meant
everything to me in high school.'' Adds Ariel's mother, Toby
Kaplin, ``Kids are under a lot of pressure now. It's a nice
release.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the experts, the verdict's still out. Some say that
beyond the novelty factor of instant messaging, there are some
actual developmental advantages to this form of socializing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids really want to have a group identity and connect with
kids as part of separating from parents without really
separating,'' says John Suler, a professor at Rider University in
New Jersey who specializes in the psychology of cyberspace. ``The
computer is a nifty solution to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Weston, a teen expert and columnist for Girls' Life
magazine, believes instant messaging is a ``less intimidating''
form of communication for some teens, eliminating the need for
scary eye contact and ``talking to kids you might otherwise not
have that much in common with.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, instant messaging makes it ``easy to feel
excluded,'' says Steve Bennett, who has written extensively about
computers and kids, including the book ``Plugged-in Parent''
(Random House, 1998). ``The sad thing is there are kids who just
kind of sit there and wait for someone'' to answer their i.m.
</P>
<P>
   And the ``emotionless' aspect of instant messaging may not, he
fears, be entirely benign. ``It does not encourage thoughtful
reflection,'' he says. And smiley faces aside, ``it's an
emotionless form of communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that today's teens will evolve into a generation
of fast-fingered, socially inept grown-ups?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is helping,'' Bennett says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TEEN-FRIENDLY FEATURES OF THREE INSTANT MESSAGING SERVICES &QL; 
 &QL; 
America Online instant messenger &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Lets users create a ``buddy'' list of friends to talk to
online.
</P>
<P>
   --Gives you a list of specific friends who are online.
</P>
<P>
   --Makes sounds of door squeaking when a buddy comes online and
door slamming when buddies leave. Enables you to customize sounds,
too, as in ``your friends are here'' (in your own voice) and
`goodbye sucker.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Yahoo! Pager
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Lets users create a list of ``friends'' online, and customize
the categories of friends (as in ``People I Hate;'' ``People I
Like;'' ``Freshmen;'' or ``Hotties.'')
</P>
<P>
   --Makes such sounds as door chiming, cowbell, or a ``yahoo''
yodel when friends are online or leave.
</P>
<P>
   -- Provides instant sport scores, news headlines, or stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ICQ (as in, ``I seek you'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Lets users create a list of ``members'' to talk to online.
</P>
<P>
   --Lets you leave voice messages with other users who have
appropriate sound equipment.
</P>
<P>
   --Makes such sounds as a foghorn noise when you start up ICQ and
``uh-oh'' you get a message. Plays a Jimi Hendrix-style ``Happy
Birthday'' tune when friends message you on their birthdays. (Also,
a birthday cake icon appears next to their name.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
