<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7359 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWEATSHOP-STUDENTS-BO     04-21 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWEATSHOP-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 CAMPUS MOVEMENTS AIM TO IMPROVE OVERSEAS FACTORY CONDITIONS
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   In the campus protest movement of the 1990s, students are taking
on big business _ and starting to win.
</P>
<P>
   In an echo of activism by preceding generations who fought for
civil rights and divestment from South Africa, students now are
taking aim at companies like Nike, Reebok, Starter and Champion.
Their goal: Improving conditions at the overseas factories used by
makers of athletic shoes and licensed clothing. With help from
unions and human rights groups, the students are employing familiar
tactics like sit-ins, teach-ins and demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   And they are beginning to change the practices and policies of
the companies and the universities who are partners in the $2.5
billion-a-year licensed apparel industry.
</P>
<P>
   The students are redoubling their efforts this spring _
including a series of conferences at Harvard, Kent and Stanford
universities this month _ to work toward a new goal of derailing a
Clinton administration effort to reform the apparel industry. The
students say the Department of Labor's attempts have been
ineffective and probusiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The student involvement got this on the agenda of the
universities, and that is starting to drive some significant
change,'' says US Representative George Miller (D-Calif.), an
advocate for reform. ``The students made the universities take it
as a serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   With pressure rising on campuses, and university administrators
acknowledging they understand the students' point, the companies
have been forced to respond.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, both Nike and Reebok have issued dueling news
releases trumpeting wage increases at their plants in Indonesia.
Industry observers, like Bob McGee, editor of Sporting Goods
Intelligence, say that the pay increases and the companys' concern
about public relations are a direct response to the students'
actions and their impact on campus.
</P>
<P>
   And Nike recently announced a willingness to disclose the
location of all of its plants overseas, satisfying one of the
students' major proposals for independent monitoring of conditions
at shoe and apparel factories outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students have always played a traditional role in helping to
foment change,'' says Vada Manager, the director of global issues
management for Nike, one of the students' major targets. ``And
they're citing some reasonable issues that we've responded to, and
we'll continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleges and universities have long engaged the manufacturers of
T-shirts, sweatshirts, jackets, caps and other clothing in
agreements to use the schools' official names, colors and
insignias. The manufacturers pay a lucrative licensing fee, which
the schools use as revenue for their general fund, scholarships or
athletic departments.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, the licensing fee yields about $500,000 to $700,000
per year that is applied to undergraduate financial aid, officials
say. At Boston College, the sale of licensed apparel generated $2.6
million last year.
</P>
<P>
   And at the major, national athletic powers with huge alumni
bodies, like the University of Michigan and the University of Notre
Dame, the revenue is much higher. At Michigan, $5.7 million was
raised in 1998 when the football and hockey teams both won national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue that's really close to us,'' says Rachel
Salomon, one of the student activists at Boston University. ``We
buy this stuff, and it helps pay for things that we do at BU. It's
our responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Students have targeted work conditions at apparel and shoe
plants in Latin America, the Caribbean and Asia in which workers in
plants owned by American companies, or contracted by them, often
pay wages that are well below what governments in those countries
say is sufficient to support a family.
</P>
<P>
   Activists also assert that many young women's decisions about
childbirth and child care are dictated by employers, and that
workers are prevented from any union organizing.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas sweatshops burst into the limelight in 1996, when
Kathie Lee Gifford attracted negative publicity for working
conditions at plants making her brand of clothing. Labor unions and
human rights groups had been targeting Nike and other companies for
several years. But no one seemed to be listening.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1997, the AFL-CIO and other unions tapped dozens of
students for internships. ``It was called Union Summer and it had a
similar impact as Freedom Summer for college students during the
civil rights movement,'' recalls Ginny Coughlin, of the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees.
</P>
<P>
   Critics claim that much of the student activism has been
provoked and underwritten by organized labor. But the students
reject the assertions.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means are we puppets of big labor,'' says Peter
Romer-Friedman, a student leader in the antisweatshop efforts at
Michigan. ``It's no different from (student) civil rights activists
using the NAACP in the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   What has followed Union Summer is a series of demonstrations on
campus. Students launched sit-ins at Duke University, Georgetown
University, Michigan and the University of Wisconsin in recent
months. At more than 50 other campuses, from Massachusetts to
California, students circulated petitions, launched Web sites and
picketed.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the universities have responded. Thirty-three have
joined the Fair Labor Association, a White House-backed group of
schools, companies, unions and human rights organizations that aims
to set and enforce codes of conduct for the overseas factories.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan and Wisconsin now insist they will not make any
licensing agreements with companies that do not disclose the
location of overseas plants. Michigan also has pledged to study the
issue of ``a living wage,'' to test what pay levels are appropriate
in which countries.
</P>
<P>
   Moves toward reform have been particularly swift and sweeping at
Catholic universities like Boston College. According to a BC
spokesman, Angela Borzon, a senior, approached the Rev. Joseph
Appleyard, the vice president of ministry and mission, and told him
of the students' concerns. The next day, at Appleyard's behest,
vice presidents of BC voted unanimously to accept the students'
challenge to establish a code of conduct for BC's licensed
companies.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the schools are meeting the students' demands, the
companies are showing different degrees of flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Reebok officials assert they have actually been ahead of some of
the student leaders and unions. Reebok says its factories pay
workers in Indonesia 43 percent more than the established minimum
wage and now keeps the plants free of toxic glues. Reebok even
helped bring a pilot program on union organizing from an arm of the
AFL-CIO to five factories in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But other companies, like Champion, a division of Sara Lee, and
Pro Player, the sports and licensing division of Fruit of the Loom,
seem less aware of the sweatshop issue.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Carter, vice president of corporate affairs at Champion,
says the company will never accede to the students' demand for full
disclosure of manufacturing sites overseas. ``We have no interest
in our competition learning where we are located and taking
advantage of what has taken us years to build,'' Carter says.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Pro Player said the company was not even aware
of the Fair Labor Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been working to organize the
group for two years. The intention is to bind the companies,
unions, human rights groups and universities to a single code of
conduct for overseas apparel manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   The companies will pay dues ranging from $5,000 to $100,000
each, based on their annual sales. Universities will pay 1 percent
of their annual licensing revenues, up to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   But students say the association is fatally flawed because it
has not called for full disclosure of the overseas manufacturing
sites or for the payment of a living wage.
</P>
<P>
   Some labor unions have walked out on the FLA process, and
administrators at some of schools say they will either not join the
association, or join it while holding their own licensees to a
higher standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to join the Fair Labor Association, but we also
realize there are a lot of question marks with the FLA,'' says
Allan Ryan Jr., Harvard's general counsel. ``It may or may not
prove to be an effective way of improving situations in the
sweatshops.''
</P>
<P>
   And if not enough companies join FLA, ``it's a dead letter,''
says Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard may soon have a new statement of general policies and
practices that will govern its licensing partners, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would any of this be happening if the students and the trade
unions supporting them were not involved?'' Ryan asks. ``The answer
is no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
