<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS` COMP COMPANIES SWEAT IN SUNNY MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to find a happier story in Massachusetts than the
story of workers' compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four years, the rates employers pay to insure
employees against the cost of injury have dropped 48 percent. The
number of on-the-job injuries has dropped, injured workers are
getting back to work faster, and the system for handling disputes
has been streamlined.
</P>
<P>
   So why aren't the insurance companies that write workers'
compensation cheering? It could be because they aren't making any
money. Liberty Mutual, the nation's biggest workers' comp insurer,
last week issued its annual report. The Boston company's profits
from all its domestic insurance business were down 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In workers' comp, Liberty lost money for the second year in a
row, according to president Edmund Kelly. The company looks for no
more than a break-even year in 1999. ``Wars of attrition are not
good wars to be in,'' says Kelly, explaining the grim numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance business always goes through cycles and in
workers' comp the swings have been wild ones. In the '80s, insurers
bailed out of the market because they were losing so much money.
After many states, including Massachusetts, passed major comp
reform laws in the early '90s, conditions and profits improved.
</P>
<P>
   Those profits, however, attracted new competitors the way nectar
attracts bees, To gain a foothold in the market, the new players
cut prices, setting off a war that is still being waged. ``There
are too many companies writing business and a lot of them are
losing money,'' says James Walter, president of ManagedComp, an
insurer based in Waltham. Both Walter and Kelly say the new
competitors don't really understand the comp business and may not
fully appreciate how badly they are doing.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where many insurance rates are set by the
state, insurers are offering discounts _ sometimes as much as 30
percent _ on top of the official 48 percent rate cut. As in auto
insurance, the discounts typically are offered only to companies
with the best safety records. The comp insurers all say they would
love to end the discounts, but as the auto insurers have found,
once customers get used to a bargain they don't like to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   The workers' comp insurers are not asking for the moon. In the
rate case they filed recently with the Division of Insurance, the
insurers requested a modest 2.6 percent rate hike. ``We are hoping
for some stability,'' says Roy Stewart, head of the group that
represents the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the insurers, stability may be too much to
hope for. At a recent hearing, virtually everyone testifying called
for more rate cuts. ``Employers have paid and are currently paying
more than they should for workers' compensation insurance,'' argued
Carolyn Boviard, director of economic development for the Cellucci
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Boviard said that the industry's past projections of losses have
failed to materialize so there is no reason to worry. The
Associated Industries of Massachusetts, a trade group, also urged a
rate cut. And Stephen D'Amato, a former state insurance official,
called for a ``massive double-digit rate decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   His proof that insurers could afford it? Because so many of them
are offering big discounts today. Gotcha.
</P>
<P>
   The final decision on rates will be made by Insurance
Commissioner Linda Ruthardt. Based on her track record, the
industry should be nervous. Last year the auto insurers asked for a
15 percent rate hike. Ruthardt granted them a raise of less than 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the national level, Liberty's Kelly is not expecting a quick
fix. He thinks the industry may be approaching a turning point but
he foresees a slow and gradual turn. ``Appropriate prices are still
a couple of years away,'' he predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, employers can look forward to a few more years
of bargain-basement rates for workers' comp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago we trumpeted the birth of a new era.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years as the Massachusetts company with the greatest
market value, Gillette relinquished the title to EMC, the
Hopkinton, Mass. technology firm.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a short era. Last Friday, Gillette moved
back in to the number-one slot; its market value stood at $55.2
billion as of the end of the day Tuesday. Gillette's stock hasn't
done particularly well, but EMC's shares have been hammered, part
of a general technology sell-off. EMC closed at 102 3/16 Tuesday,
giving it a total market valuation of $51.4 billion; two weeks ago,
with the stock at 134, the company's market valuation was $67.2
billion. On the bright side, EMC Tuesday reported a 51 percent
increase in earnings and predicted smooth sailing for the rest of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
