<SLUG> BC-FOOD-WELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULINARY SLEUTH KEEPS HER EYE ON PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes ``Food-lover's day'' text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The stylish proprietor tips a little hazelnut oil onto a
plate. Patricia Wells has been stepping aside in the narrow shop as
visitors sample almond oil, pistachio oil, and walnut oil. But when
Anne Leblanc opens the slender bottle of hazelnut, and that
unmistakable smell perfumes the air, Wells smiles and reaches for a
crust of baguette. The taste is earthy, toasty, and irresistibly
warm.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Wells does: She hunts down unusual food sources all
over this city and then introduces them to the world. It all began
15 years ago with her first list of great food finds, which she
published as ``The Food Lover's Guide to Paris'' (Workman). In the
book's fourth edition, out this month, Wells takes her fans to
Huilerie J. Leblanc oils and 23 other new spots.
</P>
<P>
   Leblanc was easy to find. It's near a landmark from her original
guide: the famous tea salon Mariage Freres, where $8 gets you a
brew selected by one of Europe's premier buyers. And it's not too
far from another spot in the new guide: Bistrots d'Autrefois, where
you can buy Ricard pitchers and other vintage bistro paraphernalia.
But Wells almost couldn't miss the oil shop: It's next door to her
newly acquired studio on Rue Jacob, one of the most fashionable
streets in the charming 6th arrondissement.
</P>
<P>
   After years of writing at home on the other side of the Seine,
she now works and cooks in her compact Left Bank studio _ though
she still goes home at night to Walter Wells, news editor of the
International Herald Tribune. Patricia Wells has worked at the
paper for almost 20 years, as its restaurant critic, so she's
hardly a tourist anymore. But she still discovers corners of Paris
in a wide-eyed way _ especially in her new neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   A former jogger, Wells walks all over the city, which isn't
common here. Indeed, Parisians are so used to doing their marketing
close to home, she says, that sometimes she's asked: ``Vous etes du
quartier?'' (Do you belong here?)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in Paris who have never left their
neighborhood,'' she says. ``I get to 14 arrondissements every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wells as tour guide, we set out recently to spend a day in
the life of a zealous Francophile foodie. Umbrella in one hand, the
Parisian's classic red book of maps in the other, we trail behind
her to Leblanc, as well as to a food market, a cookware shop, a
wine bar near the Sorbonne for lunch, and a boulangerie (just to
look at the beautiful breads and pastries). At day's end, we eat in
a homespun restaurant where the decor has hardly changed for two
decades, the husband cooks, and the wife greets guests.
</P>
<P>
   A typical Wells day invariably includes a stop at the closest
covered food market. In this neighborhood, one of the best is the
market that runs along Boulevard Raspail. Like all the others, this
is a roving market; on Sundays, it's the only organic market open
in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these people grow their own food and make their own
cheese,'' Wells explains. She stops in front of an elderly,
heavy-set woman whose display consists mostly of root vegetables.
They're beautiful, like everything here, but somehow nicer _ even
fresher _ than the others. Later, Wells speculates that the woman
isn't just the seller but the grower. ``You can tell by her
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells knows these vendors. ``If you sell potatoes with the
dirt,'' she says, moving briskly past a stall piled with expensive
spuds, ``you can charge more.'' Parisians, like Americans, are
interested in boutique-quality food and in the organic movement _
``biologique'' in French _ so dirt sells.
</P>
<P>
   Wells knows the growers' quirks, too. Passing a mound of beets,
she explains: ``These are always sold cooked. During the war, fuel
was so expensive that no one would buy them. So beet growers cooked
them in their fields over wood. That never changed.''
</P>
<P>
   We stop at a cookware shop to see if it has a french-fry cutter.
Wells is investigating how restaurateurs make fries for ``Paris
Cookbook,'' a book she's working on.
</P>
<P>
   She had wonderful fries at a restaurant and called the chef. ``I
said, `I want this recipe and this recipe.' I made an
appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived at the restaurant, he wouldn't divulge the
formula. ``These are my secrets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't give up. ``The French say no twice, then they say
yes. I knew he had a coal-fired stove. `Can I see your stove?' I
asked, figuring I'll get closer to the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the kitchen, she asked what kind of potato he used.
Then:
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you saute them?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' he answered, like an outwitted fox. ``You don't
saute. You fry them in oil.'' And he began to demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Madame walked in, and the cooking lesson came to an abrupt
halt.
</P>
<P>
   Researching the guidebooks has changed the pace of Wells's days;
though the life of a restaurant critic in Paris may sound like the
epitome of glamour, it wasn't. ``I used to work in my pajamas until
8 p.m., when I would go out for dinner,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even after 20 years in Paris, and even in Parisian black with a
quilted suede Chanel bag and patent-leather boots, the
Milwaukee-born Wells remains down to earth and decidedly un-French.
When she and her husband moved here, they planned to stay for only
two years. Walter Wells still has the Herald Tribune job he came
for: No. 2 on the editorial masthead. ``I'm the permanent
undersecretary,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When he took that job, Patricia Wells had to leave a job she had
coveted for a long time, as a food writer for The New York Times
(where they met). And they had to leave a co-op apartment they had
just renovated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was being a good wife and going with my husband,'' she says.
Months later, back visiting friends who lived in their old
building, she saw a heartbreaking sign in the laundry room:
``Garland stove for sale. Formerly owned by Patricia Wells.'' Her
renovation was being ripped apart. But there would be other
professional ranges _ and other writing opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Wells became the unofficial French food correspondent
for a number of American publications, the Times included. Her
byline has appeared in all major food magazines, and after the
first ``Food Lover's Guide to Paris,'' she continued to write
books. Her ``Food Lover's Guide to France'' came out in 1987, and
``Patricia Wells at Home in Provence'' (Scribner), set in her
ocher-walled farmhouse kitchen, was published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That kitchen is in Chanteduc (``song of the owl''), an
18th-century stone house on 10 acres in Vaison-la-Romaine, in the
south of France. The Wellses bought the house 15 years ago; now,
they bottle their own wine, and she teaches cooking classes there
several times a year (at a fee of $3,000 for 5 1/2 days).
</P>
<P>
   It is a life to dream of, but Wells started dreaming of
something else. ``I wanted a change,'' she says. ``I didn't want to
change husbands. I didn't want to change professions. And I didn't
want to leave Paris. But I wanted to stop working in the spare
bedroom.''
</P>
<P>
   So she bought the studio. To get to work now, she takes the
metro across the river, then walks.
</P>
<P>
   She remodeled her new little place so that it, too, can be used
for classes. It bears the crisp quality of a new renovation, though
much of it has been fashioned from old pieces worked into the new.
She searched for this place and waited two years for the work on it
to be finished. It's small, like most living spaces in Paris _ and
expensive. ``I could afford 500 square feet,'' she says. ``I think
this is 498.''
</P>
<P>
   It's quite bright, lit by a row of frosted glass windows and a
vaulted glass ceiling. The kitchen has a huge white-tiled center
island whose drawers, from a defunct market, have such labels as
moutarde (mustard), girofles (cloves), and navets (turnips). A La
Cornue range sits along one wall, and two marble sinks, several
yards apart, are along another. There are no overhead cabinets and
only a small refrigerator. (A big ``American'' refrigerator, as
Wells calls it, is hidden in the flat, as are a washer and dryer.)
</P>
<P>
   Besides the kitchen, there is a small dining room with built-in
cabinetry, made from old cafe doors, and an office with a
butter-yellow leather couch that doubles as a bed. To turn the
office into a bedroom, large shutter doors, purchased at a flea
market, pull out of the walls and seal off all the computer
equipment and books. Eventually, says Wells, the apartment could
become a pied-a-terre, with the house in Provence the couple's main
residence.
</P>
<P>
   From here, they'll be able to slip across the Seine for an
espresso at Cafe Marly, which overlooks the I. M. Pei glass pyramid
in the Louvre courtyard (new guide); get buttery kugelhopf at
Boulangerie Alsacienne in the neighboring 5th arrondissement (old
guide); stop for a quick lunch at Le Mauzac wine bar, also in the
5th (new guide); hop on the metro to the 11th for a visit to one of
their favorite bistros, Auberge Pyrenees-Cevennes (new guide). Or
simply spend another day walking the streets to see what they find.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a memorable madeleine or an old cafe table looking
for a home. You never know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A food-lover's day in Paris
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Raspail Market is located on Boulevard Raspail, between Rue du
Cherche-Midi and Rue de Rennes. It's open on Tuesday, Friday, and
Sunday (when it's organic). Metro: Rennes or Sevres-Babylone.
</P>
<P>
   --Huilerie J. Leblanc handmade oils are located at 6 Rue Jacob,
Paris 6. Metro: St. Germain des Pres.
</P>
<P>
   --Le Mauzac wine bar is located at 7 Rue de l'Abbe-de-l'Epee,
Paris 5. Metro: Luxembourg. Patricia Wells loves the hanger steak
(called onglet), which is delicious. So are the fries, the
unfiltered Beaujolais, and the runny St. Marcellin cheese.
</P>
<P>
   --Kayser is located at 8 and 14 Rue Monge, Paris 5. Metro:
Maubert-Mutualite. Wells likes the open-faced sandwiches here,
including goat cheese and pear. ``If you have time for just one or
two bakery visits,'' she writes in the newest ``Food Lover's
Guide,'' ``make sure that Eric Kayser's shop is on your route.''
The shop at No. 14 offers all organic products. Flours for both
shops are stone-ground, the salt is sel de Guerande from Brittany,
and everything is rustic and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   --Auberge Pyrenees-Cevennes is located at 106 Rue de la
Folie-Mericourt, Paris 11. Metro: Republique. When Lyon native
Francoise Petit married Daniel Constantin, they bought this classic
bistro and continued to make some of the former owner's
southwestern specialties. They also added Lyonnais dishes. So all
the food is hearty and quite wonderful. Hams and sausages hang from
the ceiling, and the place hasn't been given a face lift, which
makes it charming. Francoise, who greets you, is a ball of fire.
Daniel, hidden in the kitchen until the end of the night, is a
terrific cook. Order cassoulet, platters of sausages, and salad
with bacon, and roll yourself back to your hotel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
