<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-EXPANSION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMON CARTER 2001: FORT WORTH ART MUSEUM TO CLOSE FOR EXPANSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Amon Carter Museum, a cornerstone of
Fort Worth cultural life and tourism, will close Aug. 1 for more
than two years so that an addition can be built that more than
triples its exhibition space, museum officials have announced.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Philip Johnson, architect of the Carter's core 1961
building, the roughly 85,000-square-foot addition requires
demolition of all but the original building, with its commanding
view of downtown Fort Worth. The museum will re-open in fall 2001 _
a year before the new Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth opens two
blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, museum staff, archives, library and educational
services will be housed in a temporary facility in west Fort Worth.
Many key artworks from the collection will be placed on loan to the
National Gallery of Art in Washington, the Museum of Fine Arts in
Boston and the Sid Richardson Collection in Fort Worth, among
others, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Carter will rent space downtown for gallery
displays and a small museum shop.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the project is estimated at $36 million _ including
demolition, construction and operation of the new facility, and
temporary off-site facilities. Museum trustees are developing a
capital fund-raising campaign that will include support by the Amon
G. Carter Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   With partner Alan Ritchie, the 93-year-old Johnson ``has
designed a remarkable expansion of the original building ... a
labor of love,'' said museum President Ruth Carter Stevenson who,
with her late brother, Amon G. Carter Jr., commissioned Johnson to
design the original memorial to their newspaper-publisher father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once and for all, in the fall of 2001, we can open our doors
and say, `Here is a collection of American art, second to none,
housed in a beautiful building, in exciting spaces, in Fort Worth,
Texas,''' Stevenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inauguration as the Amon Carter Museum of Western Art,
the Carter's collection has expanded in numbers and purview _ from
400 works by Frederic Remington and Charles Russell to about
300,000 works reflecting a panoramic view of American culture and
history from the early 19th century through the present.
</P>
<P>
   The need for additional space to exhibit the collection, as well
as special loan exhibitions, has been critical for several years.
Many works from the permanent collection have never been shown, and
the museum's staff has declined to host a number of touring
exhibitions because there wasn't room to present them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say we will be able to show four times the art,''
said Robert Workman, the Carter's assistant director.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior of the new building will be clad in brown granite
slabs that will contrast with the cream-colored shellstone of the
1961 structure and its portico entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Its flat roof will feature what Johnson calls a ``vaulted
lantern,'' a broad, low-profile skylight covered by bronze-finished
metal, with windows on all four sides. The lantern caps a two-story
atrium, walled with shellstone, that becomes a major junction for
traffic inside the museum.
</P>
<P>
   On the main level, the new entrance will be on the museum's
south side, facing the Fort Worth Museum of Science and History.
The museum store and auditorium will be located there. Visitors
will be able to walk through the atrium to the main floor of the
Carter's original building where the downstairs galleries will
display Amon G. Carter's collection.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors also will have access to the atrium stairs or nearby
elevators to get to the second floor and its new galleries, and to
reach the mezzanine galleries of the original building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expansion is about the Carter, but it's also about the
Carter in light of developments at the other museums,'' said Doug
Harman, president of the Fort Worth Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
``It's all part of making Fort Worth one of the most important and
dramatic museum cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two-year wait will be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call her at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
