<HEADLINE>
NHL PLAYOFFS IN THE FROZEN . . SOUTH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   Greensboro?
</P>
<P>
   This is hockey? This is the Stanley Cup playoffs? We should be
talking about one of those long-lost rinks like Montreal Forum,
Maple Leaf Gardens, the Aud, or Chicago Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are going to North Carolina for their first round of
the 1999 playoffs. Thursday night _ in a gym made famous by David
Thompson, Len Elmore, Tom Burleson, and John Lucas _ the B's and
Carolina Hurricanes will begin a best-of-seven joust.
</P>
<P>
   The Greensboro Coliseum was just about perfect when it served as
permanent site of the Atlantic Coast Conference basketball tourney,
but it's been a hideous hideout for the Artists Formerly Known as
Hartford Whalers.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, folks. These Hurricanes had the wisdom to do what
Robert K. Kraft certainly will do very soon: bolt from Hartford.
Until two years ago, the 'Canes were the Forever .500 Whalers,
skating endlessly toward mediocrity in the cold heart of America's
File Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   They moved to Carolina in 1997-98 and have just completed their
second season in their temporary home in Greensboro. When the
1999-2000 season opens, the 'Canes are scheduled to be playing in
their shiny new rink in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   Greensboro is less than an hour's drive from ACC kingpins North
Carolina, Wake Forest, Duke, and North Carolina State. This is
great for college basketball, but useless when trying to sell
tickets for NHL games. (The inside of Greensboro Coliseum is
adorned with a giant black curtain that hides the empty seats in
the highest level.) Hurricanes owner Peter Karmanos is expecting
things to change when he moves into the spanking-new Raleigh
Entertainment and Sports Arena next fall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 'Canes are in the playoffs, and Greensboro is the
site. Wonder what they're saying about this in Mount Pilot?
</P>
<P>
   Shazam! Can we expect to see Gomer, Goober, Aunt Bea, and Ernest
T. Bass in the cheap seats at Greensboro? Do any of these folks
even know that the Bruins are part of the NHL's Original Six?
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, hockey in North Carolina is no dumber than
hockey in Anaheim, Tampa, Dallas, Nashville, San Jose, Phoenix, or
Los Angeles. The National Hockey League was not adequately
supported in Minneapolis, Winnipeg, or Quebec City, where mucking
in the corners is part of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   In this spirit, league officials are mining American cities with
bustling incomes. Raleigh (``Best Place to Live'' _ Money Magazine)
was chosen, and it was determined that two years in Greensboro, 80
miles from Raleigh, would be better than two more seasons in
Hartford while the new arena was built.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina-Boston. This is quite a matchup. James Taylor should
drop the ceremonial first puck. Sweet Baby James spent considerable
time in both regions. He sang about snow on the Massachusetts
Turnpike ``from Stockbridge to Boston,'' and going to ``Carolina in
my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Carolina is tobacco road. Boston is the home of
smoke-free restaurants and workplaces. They gave us Cedric Maxwell
and Trot Nixon. We gave them Dave Cowens _ for a while. They gave
us draft picks that yielded Sergei Samsonov and Kyle McLaren. We
gave them Glen Wesley. They had Sam Ervin. We had Sam Adams. They
have George Shinn. We have John Harrington. And remember that the
estimable Peter Gammons went from Groton School to the University
of North Carolina (Chapel Hill) to the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   They gave the world Michael Jordan. We gave the world John F.
Kennedy. They have Outer Banks. We have Georges Bank. They had the
Wright Brothers. We had the Bulger Brothers. They have TV sheriff
Andy Taylor. We have TV barkeep Sam Malone. They have Cape
Hatteras. We have Cape Cod. They have Winston-Salem. We have Salem.
They have Wilmington. We have Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   We share the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it won't be about any of this. This is the NHL
postseason tournament and the team with the hot goalie will win.
Still, those datelines are going to look funny. The Bruins are in
the playoffs and they are going to Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
