<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BURNS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD-DEGREE BURNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Pat Burns has three moods at the rink. Grumpy,
grumpier, grumpiest.
</P>
<P>
   Away from hockey, the Bruins coach is charming, funny, colorful,
and a gifted storyteller, covering subjects such as the Hell's
Angels, his love of Harley Davidsons, and his days as a former beat
cop in his native Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   When he is in a hockey environment, though, Burns narrows his
dark eyes, wears a perpetual frown, and, in looks and manner, is
utterly in charge.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Bruins are playing well, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this _ he's at his grumpiest after we win,'' said
president/general manager Harry Sinden, chuckling. ``He's able to
dismiss a loss, analyze it and go on. When we win, I think he's
worried we'll lose it between now and the next game. I don't go
down (to the dressing room) when we win.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, some of Burns's grouchy demeanor is a mask, donned for
effect. There are times when he'll snap at one person, then wink at
the next one he sees. His mood is very much a tool in a large and
deep toolbox.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden, whose team opens its first-round Eastern Conference
playoff series against the Hurricanes in Carolina Thursday night,
enjoys his conversations with the coach, who like most pro bench
bosses has dual personalities. The two have discussed every
possible subject, outside of hockey and in.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real game-face, game-day guy,'' said Sinden. ``He's a
very interesting person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Burns about anything from politics to fishing to the
internet to travel, and he will tell you a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had lots of nights like that with him and he's good
company in those times,'' said Sinden. ``Then, there are other
times, I keep my distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the lot of the professional coach. The pressure can be
suffocating, the hours long, the tenure short, the blame plentiful,
and the credit sparse. When the Bruins were struggling in late
January into early February, Burns told his wife, Line, to take a
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go have fun,'' Burns told her, because at that time, with the
team in an 0-6-2 skid, no one around the club was enjoying much of
anything. Holdouts and injuries had prevented Burns from having a
full lineup until that point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston finished the 82-game schedule with the exact same record
as last year _ 39-30-13. But Burns has had to work harder at it
this season. Much harder.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997-98, there were plenty of unknowns on the young, unproven
club. Few had heard of Hal Gill or P.J. Axelsson. No one knew how
good Sergei Samsonov was going to be or that Jason Allison was
going to have a breakout year. No one knew that Byron Dafoe was
capable of joining the elite class of netminders. What was known
was that Burns was a good coach.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's had to be even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year went very smoothly,'' Burns said. ``We didn't have
too many problems. It was harder this year. It changes your life
around a little bit because you're taking it more home than you are
usually. Often you'll sit there and people are talking to you and
you don't hear them. My wife will be talking to me and she'll say,
`You're not listening to me.' And I'll say, `You're right, I'm
not.' It's because your mind is churning all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Sinden, too, didn't consider Burns a very
good listener. He would talk to the coach about the games, about
players' performances, about this line or that line.When he
received no response, he thought his analysis was falling on deaf
ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry O'Reilly was a bit like that in that I could talk to him
about different subjects and he'd be listening without
responding,'' said Sinden. ``But you never know. Now that I know
Pat, I might have had some of those doubts, not doubts so much, but
wonderings on whether he was hearing me or not when I first met
him. There are so many things later on that he comes back and said,
`Do you see this now that we talked about?' And I said, `Yeah.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So he was listening and didn't do it or he was listening and
did do it. I talk to him quite often and he doesn't comment on a
lot of subjects but he's listening. He sorts it out, throws it out,
keeps it or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he is like Detroit coach Scotty Bowman in that he's
open to the opinions of concessionaires, ticket takers, janitors,
reporters, fans, and yes, even his boss. He processes all the
information and then uses what in his judgment will most help the
team succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he feels I'm not listening but I am listening,''
said Burns. ``He has a way of saying it that's maybe different than
anybody else but what he says is constructive. I maybe don't always
react to it. I'll think about it and churn about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do certainly listen because I know he's been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said the ultimate responsibility rests with him because he
makes the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to get to know me,'' said Burns. ``I'm not a
one-man show. I listen to everybody but I'll take what I feel is
important because I feel I'm on the firing line. I have the
decisions to make. I have a fraction of a second to make a
decision. That's what I like about Harry. Harry has been there. He
knows. He's had to make those decisions. Maybe he didn't make the
right one that time or made a good one. I'm not saying I make all
the right decisions. He's the best GM I've ever had for that
because he's been there. (Former Montreal GM Serge Savard) was
never there, (former Toronto GM Cliff Fletcher) was never there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns has been compared to Bill Parcells, and there are
similarities. Both are whip smart, know how to play the media like
a violin, and are among the very best at what they do. The hallmark
of both is instant credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of respect from a lot of people,'' said right
wing Rob DiMaio. ``He's hard, he's tough, he's a very smart hockey
man. He has passion for the game, and wanting to win is probably
the biggest thing. He's never satisfied with what we're doing. We
can always do more, and for a young hockey team, those are the
right ingredients for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to get the most out of his players. He's got a
great system that fits this team real well. He's definitely been
the biggest influence in changing the feeling of the Boston Bruins
and making us a contender again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the final say in how this team is run and I think that's
a big step to get the respect of the players, knowing that what he
says is actually going to happen. Whether that's fear or I'm not
sure what it is, upper management knows that and I think they lay
off him and let him do his thing.''
</P>
<P>
   His thing involves being part pop psychologist, part father
figure, part taskmaster, part tactician. If anything has changed
from his first year to this one, Burns said, it has to do with his
players getting a tad too comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's human nature,'' he said. ``They're going to try
something. You always try something. The first year, you don't try
nothing because you're scared of him, thinking, `Is this guy crazy?
The second year, they'll try to get around something to see.
Anybody who works in any kind of business, when there's a new boss,
everybody's got their ears propped up. The second year, they say,
`Let's see what happens if I try this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the strongest part of Burns's repertoire is his
ability to convince all the players to stay on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen too many stray dogs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he couldn't change now even if he wanted to, and he
doesn't want to. Experience has taught him the best way to evaluate
his personnel, and his years on the police force taught him to
trust his instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have guys who want to be better, there are other players
who will not be better no matter what they do,'' he said. ``You see
more things in practice than you do in a game. You see the
character of the player, you see how his habits are, on the ice and
off, his working habits, if he's liked by the team. That part is
trying to identify who's still on board and who maybe you're
wasting your time with.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro coaching is a lonely job with a short shelf life. It's
fraught with headaches, literal as well as metaphorical. It's the
quickest route to high blood pressure. Relaxing is not an option
and Burns doesn't even try.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never satisfied as a coach,'' said Burns. ``You're
never, never happy. If you're ever content, your team will be
content. If your team is content, you're done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won nothing up to now. Don't get me wrong. I want
them to feel good. I want to be happy and to like each other. I
want them to feel proud but I don't want them to feel like they've
accomplished anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real fine line. Coaching is where you have to keep 24
guys happy. It's impossible. That's the toughest, to keep 24 guys
on board and happy.''
</P>
<P>
   He's earned his grumpiness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
