<HEADLINE>
MANCHESTER UNITED BOSS MISLEADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Rupert Murdoch can afford to purchase
Manchester United Football Club, at any price. But his offer of
more than $1.06 billion was recently blocked by Trade and Industry
Secretary Stephen Byers, leaving the club to scrape through.
</P>
<P>
   The news was embraced by fans who had set up opposition to
Murdoch, fearing the soul of the club would be diluted by such a
massive sale. So Manchester United remains quite profitable and
supporters still have a voice in the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a time of potential turning points for the rich
clubs. The goals of quality soccer combined with fan involvement
and maximizing profits are clashing at higher levels.
</P>
<P>
   In England and Scotland, supporters' attachment to clubs remains
strong enough to overwhelm even the greatest of profiteers. And
since every city has at least one viable club, team directors and
owners cannot use the US-style blackmailing threat to move teams.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Martin Edwards, the Manchester United director
who would profit most from a Murdoch takeover, is painting a gloomy
future for the team. He expects only one reinforcement, a
replacement for Danish goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought with the backing of one of the world's most able
media companies we could have underpinned our domestic position and
increased our ability to do more than just challenge for European
honors,'' Edwards wrote in Sunday's match program for United's 3-0
win over Sheffield Wednesday. ``We believe the `silent majority' of
United fans were supportive of the bid _ we certainly know that
supporters of other clubs were delighted that our plans were
thwarted.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards's statement seems petulant. Manchester United has a
chance for ``The Triple'' _ Premiership, FA Cup, and European
Champions League titles. It is difficult to feel sorry for him.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Manchester United collapses on the field in the next
month, the club will have had a glorious season.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Giggs, who scored a dramatic tying goal in the 92d minute
of the first leg, then made the difference against Arsenal in the
FA Cup semifinal replay, watched Saturday's game on crutches. Then,
the News of the World tabloid reported that his brother, Rhodri
Giggs, 21, has been selling cocaine and prostitutes through an
apartment rental agency in London, using Ryan as an unwitting
accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some heavy promotion by a US-based apparel company, Ryan
Giggs has not attained the stature he might deserve on the global
stage. He will not likely ever play in the World Cup, since Wales
has not qualified for the finals since 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Juventus has been rejuvenated by the arrival of coach
Carlo Ancelotti and a classic left wing of its own, Frenchman
Thierry Henry. During a 3-1 victory over first-place Lazio, Henry
scored his first two goals of the Serie A season.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Giggs, Henry arrived with little publicity. Henry scored
three goals in the 1998 World Cup finals, but he kept a low profile
compared with his veteran teammates.
</P>
<P>
   And with Juventus, he has been unsettling defenses with his
exceptional speed and now seems to be developing the finishing
instinct.
</P>
<P>
   The son of immigrants from the Caribbean island of Guadaloupe,
Henry, 21, grew up in Les Ulis, in the western banlieues of Paris,
a symbol of the changing face of French society _ half of the World
Cup champion team were first-generation immigrants from Africa, the
Caribbean, and Polynesia _ a dignified riposte to the National
Front xenophobes.
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich is favored to advance in the other semifinal after
tying Dynamo Kyiv, 3-3, in the Ukraine capital in the first leg.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Ukrainians left their mark on the competition.
Crowds of 100,000-plus filled their Olympiyskyi Stadium for the
quarterfinal elimination of defending champion Real Madrid and the
Bayern Munich game. The team was selected by entering data for
prospective players into a computer, which matched players to
positions, determining optimum characteristics. Though a colder
basis for choosing a team could not be conceived, the Kyiv club has
produced a joyful, skillful, risk-taking style that belies its
microchip origins.
</P>
<P>
   Striker Andriy Shevchenko, 22, will join Milan next year, and
will likely return to the Champions League since Milan has pulled
within a point of Serie A leader Lazio. And Dynamo Kyiv is likely
not finished since only two of its players are as old as 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
