<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      04-21 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PARTY TRANSFORMS INTO A WAR COUNCIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's 50th birthday party has a lot of people
singing the blues.
</P>
<P>
   Starting at the top, Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright
and national security adviser Samuel Berger in somber tones Tuesday
recast the celebration scheduled long ago for this weekend in
Washington as a nothing-but-work war summit over NATO's deepening
crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Further down the White House command chain, Richard Socarites,
the official in charge of three days of luncheons, dinners,
meetings, press conferences, and making the motorcades of no fewer
than 44 world leaders run on time, laments that ``as a social
event, this summit is turning out as a bust.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two law enforcement agencies in the Washington area face
an unprecendented security assignment that was stressful to begin
with and only got worse when NATO started bombing Yugoslavia.
``We're prepared for anything,'' said Kenneth Piernick, an FBI
counterterrorism specialist, ``from simple assaults to weapons of
mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for Washington tourists, here by the tens of thousands at
the height of the spring-vacation season, the red carpet rolling
out for NATO VIPs means a long weekend of frustration: airport
delays, traffic gridlock, closed museums, no White House tours, and
six square blocks of the capital cordoned off from anybody without
a special pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to hate me,'' said Karina Ferguson, a tour guide
anticipating the reaction of visitors when she tells them, come
Friday, it's Mount Vernon, George Washington's home in northern
Virginia, or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is underestimating the significance of this NATO summit.
What could have been a predictable weekend of windy speeches,
self-congratulation, splendid parties, and an effusive welcome to
NATO's three newest members, Hungary, Poland, and the Czech
Republic, has suddenly switched to a strategic war council on
Kosovo that will test the alliance's mettle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had planned a summit that focused a bit on the past and a
great deal on the future . . . but now it is necessary to have it
and to focus intensely on the present as well,'' Berger said at a
White House briefing Tuesday. ``Now this is going to be a working
meeting of a military alliance in the middle of a conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of the summit were already daunting: How to greet,
move, protect, lodge, and entertain the heads of state, prime
ministers, and hundreds of other foreign dignitaries from 19 NATO
countries and as many as 25 NATO-affiliated nations. Consider, for
example, that diplomatic protocol demands the NATO leaders arrive
in alphabetical order (by country, English spelling) at a White
House dinner for 800 on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the last minute, NATO officials have ripped up the
program and are improvising. The opening ceremony Friday morning
has been replaced by a three-hour meeting on Kosovo. A military
parade has been canceled, and an emergency session on humanitarian
aid may be held Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A commemoration will take place Friday in the same Constitution
Avenue auditorium where the North Atlantic Treaty was signed 50
years ago, but NATO has nixed a warplane flyover as inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   With images of bleak, Balkan refugee camps fresh on TV screens,
NATO also scratched black-tie events and anything not fitting a
theme of ``simple, serious, and dignified,'' said Socarides, a
special assistant to President Clinton and the summit's chief
operating officer. ``More work, less pomp and circumstance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say socializing has been eliminated entirely. In
addition to the White House dinner in a tent on the South Lawn, the
president and Mrs. Clinton will greet guests at a more exclusive
party Friday evening, and Mrs. Clinton will host two luncheons for
VIP spouses. The cost of the summit, shared by the US government
and corporate sponsors, will be about $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   As Washington events go, the size of this summit is small with
about 5,000 attendees, including 3,000 journalists. (The Federation
of American Societies for Experimental Biology brought more than
11,000 conventioneers to the capital this week.) But in scale _ in
catering and floral arrangements, in fleets of limousines required,
in mobile phones in use, and certainly in security _ this is the
mother of all Washington weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service is in charge of security, and it is leaving
no manhole or mailbox unsealed, no rooftop unguarded, no airspace
unpatrolled, no biological threat unchecked. To control the summit
area, the Secret Service is restricting the six square blocks
around Federal Triangle to NATO traffic only, and it has required
nine of the Smithsonian museums to close Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia will shut down its government and
public schools Friday, and 90,000 federal bureaucrats will get that
day off too, with pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to assume there is a very high threat level,'' said
Chuck Vance, a Secret Service veteran who now runs a private
security firm in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lived here 19 years, through some huge events on the
Mall and several presidential inaugurations, but I don't recall
anything like this,'' said Marie Tibor, vice president of the
Washington Convention and Visitor Association. ``If a rolling
motorcade excites you, this is the time to be here. For anyone
else, it presents a true challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
