<SLUG> BC-TILBERIS-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIZ TILBERIS, EDITOR OF HARPER'S BAZAAR, DIES AT AGE 51 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Elizabeth Tilberis, 51, editor-in-chief of Harper's
BAZAAR since 1992, died Wednesday after a long fight with ovarian
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A well-respected and powerful force in the fashion community,
Tilberis helped raise public awareness of the disease and worked to
raise funds for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis was diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 1993, during the
height of her magazine career, while she worked in the center of
the glamorous world of international fashion. A year after she was
hired by Hearst Magazines to revitalize one of the world's fashion
bibles, Tilberis underwent major surgery and chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision Liz had for Harper's BAZAAR was to set the agenda
for modern elegance,'' said Frank A. Bennack, Jr., president and
CEO of The Hearst Corporation. ``She not only achieved her vision,
but her optimism and passion for living every day to the fullest
were admired by all who knew her. We will miss this force in
fashion and this remarkable woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen P. Black, president of Hearst Magazines, said that
Tilberis' ``instincts and eye for fashion, fashion photography, and
style were unparalleled. She will be remembered as one of the
magazine industry's greatest 20th century talents. And for those of
us who were lucky enough to work with her, her passion and love for
life were inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from her role as editor, Tilberis served as president of
the Ovarian Cancer Research Fund, Inc., a position she held since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis is being awarded the annual Humanitarian Award by the
Council of Fashion Designers of America (CFDA) for her memoir, ``No
Time to Die,'' published by Little, Brown &AMP; Company in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When she began her career at British Vogue as fashion editor in
1974, Tilberis exhibited a forward-thinking style and a gift for
working with photographers. She later served as executive fashion
editor (1984), editor-in-chief (1987) and director of Conde Nast
Publications (1991).
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Tilberis was named editor-in-chief of Harper's BAZAAR,
the year which marked the magazine's 125th anniversary. Her
editorial debut with the September issue, featuring Linda
Evangelista on the cover, brought Tilberis a new level of
international recognition. Fashion and beauty photography was at
the core of BAZAAR.
</P>
<P>
   She introduced more art features and high-quality fashion
journalism. Her impressive editorial team included Creative
Director Fabien Baron and Fashion Director Tonne Goodman.
Internationally renowned fashion photographers Patrick DeMarchelier
and Peter Lindbergh also joined her staff.
</P>
<P>
   Tilberis is survived by her husband of 28 years, Andrew, and
their two sons Christopher, 14 and Robert, 17; her mother, Mrs.
Thomas (Jane) Kelly; sister, Lois Stuart-Black; and her brother,
Dr. Grant Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ---------- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following are key dates in the life of Elizabeth (Liz) Tilberis:
</P>
<P>
   1947 -- Born in Shirehampton, England, Sept. 7, 1947.
</P>
<P>
   1969 -- Won a Vogue talent contest and secured a summer
internship with British Vogue, as well as edited her own weekly
fashion page on the Bath &AMP; Wiltshire Evening Chronicle. Began her
fashion career while still in college at Leicester Polytechnic.
</P>
<P>
   1970 -- Graduated with honors from Leicester Polytechnic. Joined
the British Vogue staff as a fashion assistant.
</P>
<P>
   1974 -- Served as fashion editor at British Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   1984 -- Served as executive fashion editor at British Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   December 1990 -- Secured H.R.H. The Princess of Wales as cover
subject for the cover of British Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   1991 -- Served as director of Conde Nast Publications.
</P>
<P>
   February 1992 -- Named editor-in-chief of Harper's BAZAAR.
</P>
<P>
   September 1992 -- Relaunched first official relaunched issue of
Harper's BAZAAR.
</P>
<P>
   April 1993 -- Accepted two National Magazine Awards, the
industry's most prestigious honor, in the Design and Photography
categories respectively, garnered on behalf of the first four
issues following the relaunch (September - December 1992) of
BAZAAR. Accepted the Society of Publication Designers 28th annual
competition, including the Gold Medal for overall redesign.
</P>
<P>
   1994 -- Received Special Award from the Council of Fashion
Designers of America, which was presented to her by the Princess of
Wales. Served as co-chair of the Pediatric Aids Kids for Kids
Carnival, for which First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton served as
honorary chair, and which raised over one million dollars for
pediatric AIDS research.
</P>
<P>
   1994 -- Selected as Advertising Age's Editor of the Year, and
Adweek named BAZAAR one of the ten best magazines of the year.
</P>
<P>
   1994 -- Nominated, on behalf of BAZAAR, for the National
Magazine Award for excellence in photography.
</P>
<P>
   1995 -- Nominated, on behalf of BAZAAR, for the National
Magazine Award for both design and photography.
</P>
<P>
   1995 -- Served as co-chair for the 1995 Kids for Kids Carnival.
Received of the 1995 Matrix Award in the magazine category.
</P>
<P>
   1996 -- Served as co-chair of the Metropolitan Museum's Costume
Institute Gala.
</P>
<P>
   1998 -- Wrote ``No Time to Die,'' published by Little, Brown and
Co.
</P>
<P>
   1999 -- Scheduled to receive the Annual Humanitarian Award from
the Council of Fashion Designers of America (CFDA).
</P>
</TEXT>
