<P>
   And a related story
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ECON-RUBIN (Washington) _ In a speech about reforming the
international financing system, Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin
is critical of calls for ``dollarization'' throughout the
hemisphere. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NAMES (Washington) _ The new Internet governance
committee announces the five companies that will be the first to
compete with Network Solutions in the domain name registration
business. America Online is one. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column: Why economists
have a difficult time explaining an economy with both low
unemployment and low inflation. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2:10 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 52 points, Nasdaq was up 50. Elsewhere, stocks in
London were little changed, while stocks in Frankfurt were up 1.5
percent. In Tokyo, the Nikkei fell 1.2 percent, and the Hong Kong's
Hang Seng was up 1 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-EARNINGS (Undated) _ IBM posts results after the close of
trading. The forecast is for $1.41 a share. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Compaq reports first-quarter
earnings of $281 million, meeting the diminished expectations of
Wall Street. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Coca-Cola announces earnings. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Sunbeam posts a huge loss, but says
it has no plans to sell any units. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BEEF (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The European Union threatens
to ban imports of hormone-free beef from the United States in a
broadening of a trade dispute. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-BOOKS (Undated) _ Borders, the nation's second-largest
bookstore chain, says chief executive has resigned and that it will
take a charge for the quarter. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert's ``In America'' and William Safire's ``Essay.''
</P>
