<P>
   COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTING FOLLOW-UP
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-LEDE _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ News lead on today's
developments in the aftermath of Tuesday's school shooting in which
at least 18 were killed in the nation's deadliest school rampage.
The bodies are scheduled to be removed from the school at 1 p.m.
(MDT) today. (Barker, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-MAIN _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ Main news developments of the
day after the shooting. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-GUNMEN _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ A profile of the two gunmen.
(Cleary/Barker, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-HARRIS _ Who was Eric Harris, one of the suspects in the
shootings? (ABrice/Marlon Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-KLEBOLD _ Who was Dylan Klebold, the other suspect in the
shootings? (Burritt/Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-REACT _ LITTLETON, Colo. _ Talking to teens in the malls
and at a prayer service in the aftermath of Tuesday's tragic school
shooting. (Sauer, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-GUNBILLS _ DENVER _ Gun legislation, including a bill on
concealed weapons, is scheduled for discussion today in the
Colorado Legislature. (Cleary, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SAFETY _ WASHINGTON _ Reaction to the Colorado school
massacre by federal education officials, members of Congress and
others. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-ALIEN _ What makes affluent kids choose alienation, even
deadly alienation, as an identity? And what pushes passive
alienation into violence? Why are those feelings expressed at
school rather than malls and airports? (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-POPCULTURE _ A list, with a brief description, of movies,
books and video games and music popular with teens that romanticize
alienation.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PARENT _ A guide for parents: How do you help kids who
feel different. How do you tell if behaviors are just quirky or a
sign of real trouble? Where can you or your child go for
counseling? What role should schools play? (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-PARENT-SIDE _ What to do if your child is afraid to go to
school. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SOLACE _ How do you get your head around this tragedy.
Comments from the clergy and secular folks who've counseled people
after tragic events. (Hendrick,
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CNN _ CNN has spent a lot of money covering the war in
Kosovo. The network's best investment, though, may be the
wide-ranging associations with its affiliates around the country.
(Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-CON-EDITORIAL _ Lead editorial on the Littleton tragedy.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-JNL-EDITORIAL _ It's no excuse for violence, but you have
to wonder whether ``in crowd'' cruelty in their earlier lives
helped push Colorado teens down the path to savagery. (Matthews,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-SHELLING _ KRUME, ALBANIA _ Accelerated shellings and
explosions the Serbian Yugoslav military are aiming at this craggy
border region are raising fears for the safety of Kosovo refugees,
aid workers and local Albanians. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). 20.
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHES _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ The first of the
long-awaited Apache attack helicopters finally land here. What is
their mission? When will the others arrive? How soon will they go
into action? What is their capability? Developing. (Albright, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen
and Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen. Henry Shelton testify at 2
p.m. EDT before a House Appropriations subcommittee on President
Clinton's $6 billion emergency request for Kosovo. (Malone, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ Aid officials scrambled today
to care for thousands of newly arrived refugees from Kosovo crammed
into a remote village inside the Macedonian border. In nearby
Macedonia, President Kiro Gligorov warned that the influx of
130,000 Kosovo Albanian refugees and the presence of thousands of
NATO troops was destabilizing his country, like Croatia a former
Yugoslav republic. Developing. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BALKAN-BABY _ Following the story of the Bosnian baby diverted
to Atlanta for emergency heart surgery. Developing. (Guthrie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABILITIES _ The U.S. Supreme Court hears arguments
Wednesday on a Georgia case in which two mentally disabled women
contend the Americans with Disabilities Act requires the state of
Georgia to pay for their treatment outside a state institution.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20-25
</P>
<P>
   TAX-UPS _ WASHINGTON _ United Parcel Service of Atlanta has
filed a 222-page petition appealing an IRS order that it pay more
than $209 million in back taxes plus $10.7 million in penalties.
(Moskal, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RUSSIANS _ ASHKELON, Israel _ Will the election for the
leadership of the Jewish state be decided over plates of pork chops
by people who don't even know Hebrew? The 900,000 Russians who
immigrated since 1990 are considered a key voting block in the May
17 elections for prime minister and parliament. The Russians a re a
complex group, highly educated, cultured, and secular. In Ashkelon,
they have several Russian newspapers, their own political
leadership and butchers who flout kosher laws against pork
products. Coming from the largest country in the world, they are
apprehensive about turning over any of tiny Israel to the Arabs and
that's why, in 1996, two-thirds voted for Benjamin Netanyahu. But
they are said to be unpredictable and looking for alternatives.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CHOICE _ The 40,000 tuition grants being given nationally
to poor kids to opt out of public schools is a lot like an
initiative in Atlanta begun in 1992. We'll focus on a mother and
two daughters who received these scholarships and talk about that
parents in this program, while they appreciate it, didn't use it to
get a vastly better education, used it instead to get a very
religious education at unaccredited schools. So if this scholarship
program is to show that we should have tax-funded vouchers, the
move to religious school raises constitutional problems with mixing
church and state and changes the very nature of public education
from a public good to a private commodity. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EARTHDAY _ Study from Use Less Stuff/Michigan State/National
Consumers League shows one easy way people can save money and help
the Earth: Buy 10 common things, like soft drinks, cereal and
pasta, in the least massive containers (i.e. cereal in bags instead
of boxes). Waste reduction promises to hit home even harder, as
cities go to various pay-as-you-throw schemes, which charge
homeowners based on the amount of garbage they produce. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
