<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-BEST-SERMON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 JOHN WINTHROP and `THE CITY ON A HILL'  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece and Millennium
Plus partnership clients. To publish as a one shot _ and for
millennium rates and packages _ please contact one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By PETER J. GOMES  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 For release: April 18 or thereafter  
 Editors: See THE LOCAL ANGLE box below  
 &HT;    __  The Bible as civic blueprint ... John Winthrop and the `City
on a Hill'  __
 &HT;    
 &HT;    To consider the most influential sermon of the second Christian
millennium is, for most of us, to think of those larger-than-life
preachers who enjoy a modest immortality in the anthologies and
surveys of American history, literature and religion.
 &HT;    Chief among them is probably Jonathan Edwards, whose sermon
``Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God'' was imposed upon
generations of high school students as an example of Puritan
preaching. Unfortunately, with a single stroke, that sermon has
perhaps managed more than any other to ruin the reputations both of
Puritanism and God.
 &HT;    Today's students of America's ongoing culture wars might point
to Harry Emerson Fosdick's 1923 sermon, ``Shall the Fundamentalists
Win?'' as the defining word in the conflict between liberals and
conservatives for America's soul. And there is not a person alive
today who has not heard, at least in part, Martin Luther King's
1963 elegy on the American dream uttered at the foot of the statue
of Abraham Lincoln.
 &HT;    These three all have their claims upon the American imagination,
but in naming the best sermon of the last 1,000 years, my vote is
for none of them.
 &HT;    Instead, when I think of a definitive sermon I turn to that
formative moment in 1630, when the layman Robert Winthrop, governor
of the Massachusetts Bay Colony, preached to his fellow immigrants,
while still at sea aboard the ship Arbella.
 &HT;    ``Christian Charity: A Model Hereof,'' is what Winthrop called
his sermon, and it would have languished in obscurity, known only
to an elite class of Puritan scholars, were it not for its
felicitous use of a biblical image _ that of the ``city set on a
hill'' _ to describe the moral purpose of the Pilgrims' adventure
into the unknown.
 &HT;    That image, familiar to generations of Christians from Jesus'
``Sermon on the Mount'' in Matthew's gospel, is what gave
Winthrop's sermon life, while also giving a new context to
Matthew's text.
 &HT;    And it provided perhaps the most enduring metaphor of the
American experience, that of the exemplary nation _ the ``city on a
hill'' _ called not to prosperity and private gain but to virtue
and mutual support.
 &HT;    Indeed, when in 1961 John Fitzgerald Kennedy addressed the
Massachusetts legislature as its favorite son and president-elect,
he, son of a different collection of immigrants to the New World,
cited Winthrop's sermon as the text for his new administration.
Ronald Reagan, as Garry Wills reminds us, adopted Winthrop's vision
as his own, with a little help, of course, from speechwriter Peggy
Noonan.
 &HT;    Both Gandhi and Abe Lincoln have been claimed as the moral
tutors for Martin Luther King's ``I Have A Dream,'' his ringing
ideal of the American experience. But I would argue that it was
Winthrop's sermon that was the rhetorical ancestor of King's finest
oration.
 &HT;    True, by standards of contemporary preaching, Winthrop's sermon
is long, argumentative and complex, qualities that give preaching a
reputation for tediousness. It does not read like an inspirational
tract, and there is no appeal to cheap emotion or sensation.
 &HT;    It reads like a lawyer's brief, actually; Winthrop was a lawyer
trying to make the best possible case for the legitimacy of the
Puritan enterprise. He did this on the basis of a new Christian
conscience upon which would be founded a new social contract, the
likes of which the world had not yet seen.
 &HT;    Winthrop's idea of civic virtue was derived not from secular
models of political economy but from the biblical principles of
justice and mercy: ``There are two rules whereby we are to walk one
towards another: justice and mercy.'' These were not abstract
virtues, but social necessities if, in fact, the mixed society of
poor and rich over which he presided was not to fracture into
self-interest groups.
 &HT;    In a less than ideal society, one which Winthrop and his
co-religionists would have understood as fallen, these virtues were
essential to mutual survival and prosperity. And if Massachusetts
was to be an improvement upon experience, the whole of society and
not just the church must be animated by them.
 &HT;    Some have argued that the Puritan ideals of Winthrop were naive
and utopian, suited only for a religious fantasy world of the weak
and like-minded. But what runs through his sermon is a painfully
honest realization of the powerful seductions of self-interest and
ambition.
 &HT;    It is Winthrop's sense of sin that animates his plea for civic
virtue. He understood that a rampant individualism was as dangerous
to the common good as the familiar threats of peril, famine and
pestilence.
 &HT;    When he asks, ``What rule must we observe and walk by in cause
of community peril?'' he answers his own question, ``The same as
before (justice and mercy) but with more enlargement towards others
and less respect toward ourselves.'' And he cites examples of the
primitive church which sold all and held everything in common:
``Neither did any man say that which he possessed was his own.''
 &HT;    Mutuality was the cohesive principle: ``This sensibleness and
sympathy of each other's condition will necessarily infuse into
each party a native desire and endeavor to strengthen, defend,
preserve and comfort the other.''
 &HT;    Having established mutual love as the model of Christian
charity, he summarizes the object of the enterprise: ``The end is
to improve our lives, to do more service to the Lord, the comfort
and increase of the body of Christ whereof we are members, that
ourselves and posterity may be the better preserved from the common
corruptions of this evil world to serve the Lord and work out our
salvation under the power and purity of his holy ordinances.''
 &HT;    Any other course would cause the shipwreck of the new society.
The only way to prevent such a disaster was to ``Follow the counsel
of Micah, to do justly, to love mercy, and to walk humbly with our
God.
 &HT;    ``For this end we must be knit together in this work as one man,
we must entertain each other in brotherly affection, we must be
willing to abridge ourselves of our superfluities. For the supply
of others' necessities we must uphold a familiar commerce together
in all meekness, gentleness, patience and liberality; we must
delight in each other, make others' conditions our own, rejoice
together, mourn together, labor and suffer together, always having
before our eyes our commission and community in the work ...''
 &HT;    This seems an impossible task for mere human beings. It had not
worked before, and the eyes of the world would look with cynical
interest for the failure of such a noble ambition: ``We shall be as
a city set on a hill, the eyes of all people upon us.''
 &HT;    But failure would be failure for all time, Winthrop intoned, and
so success was the only moral option. The choice was between new
life and old death, and the choice was obvious.
 &HT;    Ending his sermon with the appeal of Joshua to the Israelites as
they stood on the brink of the promised land, Winthrop concludes:
``Therefore, let us choose life, that we and our seed may live by
obeying his voice and cleaving to him, for he is our life and our
prosperity.''
 &HT;    Winthrop's is a layman's vision for a new civil body politic.
Even today, that vision still lives and awaits its fulfillment. A
sermon that is as powerfully relevant to the future as it was at
the moment of its utterance, nearly four centuries ago, and whose
impact can be measured across the nation-states of the world,
deserves not only to be remembered but to be regarded as the
prophetic utterance that it was, and is.
 &HT;     c.1999 Peter J. Gomes  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Peter J. Gomes is Plummer Professor of Christian Morals and
Pusey Minister in The Memorial Church at Harvard University.) &LR; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; THE LOCAL ANGLE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1) Check your local library for offerings on subjects such as
civic virtue, the American Dream and `the city on a hill' image as
an inspiration in the famous speeches of our era. Here are a few
specifics to request:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I Have A Dream: Twenty-four Writings and Speeches That
Changed the World,'' M. James, ed., Harper, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Let the Word Go Forth: The Speeches, Statements, and
Writings of John F. Kennedy, 1947 to 1963,'' Theodore C. Sorensen,
ed., Dell, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The City on a Hill: Fulfilling Ronald Reagan's Vision for
America,'' by Michael Reagan with Jim Denney, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   2) Click to the following Websites which are themed to the
development of civic virtue and the values of the American Dream:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Paul &AMP; Daisy Soros Fellowship Program for New Americans
(http://www.pdsoros.org).
</P>
<P>
   -- The Character Education Partnership lists organizations and
seminars in various states whose goal is to ``develop civic virtue
and moral character in our youth for a more compassionate and
responsible society.'' For the programs nearest you, consult the
website (http://www.character.org.); write, 918 16th St., N.W.,
Suite 501, Washington, D.C. 20006; or phone, 1-800-988-8081.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Alliance for Justice, a national association of civil
rights and consumer advocacy organizations (http://www.afj.org).
