u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEETH-ART-2NDTAKE-HNS     04-21 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEETH-ART-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
with anesthesia, letting him back on the ice.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``These guys don't want to quit,'' said Henckel, who has a small
room inside the Compaq Center equipped with a table, light and
medical kit for dental emergencies. ``They're absolutely infatuated
with the game. It doesn't matter what the injury is; they just want
you to stitch 'em, numb 'em and get 'em back out there. You
wouldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the time former Aeros player Bill Bowler got his face
smashed into the boards by an opponent after a play had ended. A
guy came up and _ bam! _ checked him right into the wall, knocking
out two front teeth. After controlling the ``bleeding situation,''
as Henckel diplomatically put it, he gave Bowler a shot of Novocain
and sent him back out. Right away, Bowler slammed his stick hard
into the guy's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``That threw him out of the game, but he didn't care at that
point,'' Henckel said. ``All he wanted was retaliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the inevitability of dental injuries in ice
hockey, intentional and otherwise. It's like ham and eggs. If
you're going to play, you're going to lose a tooth, probably
several, said the good dentist. All those sticks, all those pucks,
all those big, hyperventilating men. ...
</P>
<P>
   Henckel said he tries and tries to get his players to use their
mouth guards, but some of them _ around 40 percent _ just won't do
it. It interferes with their breathing, they tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm called in about every third or fourth game,'' said
Henckel, whose wife carries a pair of binoculars to games to alert
him of dental events before he's even paged on the intercom.
``Actually, I'm amazed at how infrequent the injuries are, with all
those sticks being slung around.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken McRay, assistant coach for the Aeros, said there's not one
player on the current team who has retained all his original teeth
(except for goalies, who wear wire mesh masks).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just part of the game,'' said McRay, who lost his four
front teeth during a game against the Quebec Nordiques in the
big-time National Hockey League. On the upside, he said, his caps
``look better than my real teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Henckel became the team's dentist when the Houston Aeros,
currently Southwest Division champs and part of the International
Hockey League, formed five years ago. (An earlier Houston Aeros
team played in the '70s under the auspices of the now-defunct World
Hockey Association.) He happened to be the dentist of Dr. Charles
Baker, head doctor of the Aeros medical team. But he was also
well-suited for the complexities of the job, he said, having
rotated through a variety of specialities during the Army _ oral
surgery, periodontal work, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   A low-key sort who hasn't tried to bank off his status as a
celebrity sports-dentist, Henckel has seen his already-flourishing
practice grow from his association with the Aeros, mostly through
routine dental care he provides to the players' wives and kids.
When he treats the team's sports-related injuries, he gets paid
(though not much, he mentions) through players' workers'
compensation insurance.
</P>
<P>
   He's not the only medical person on staff at ice hockey games. A
veritable battalion of doctors _ internist, orthopedist,
ophthalmologist _ stand by to treat the inevitable injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Which on occasion can involve spectators zonked by high-flying
pucks. Henckel has never ministered to a downed spectator (Compaq
Center has its own paradmedics for that, he said), although he did
once see a lady get bonked between the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked, and there wasn't anything wrong with her mouth,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
