<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEETH-ART-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      04-21 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEETH-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PUCK STOPS HERE: DENTIST TAKES A BITE OUT OF HOCKEY INJURIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Sore gums? Toothache? Broken fillings?
</P>
<P>
   You think you've got problems. Try taking a hockey puck at 90
mph on those bright-and-shinies.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened two years ago, when a puck intended for the
Houston Aeros' goal inadvertently wound up in former player Carl
Valmont's mouth instead.
</P>
<P>
   Then-goalie Troy Gamble witnessed the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really gross,'' he said. ``He basically ate the puck.
He fell right away. ... Then he got up and skated off with a
towel.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers wondering why trainer Jerry Meins was on his hands
and knees on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I realized: he was looking for teeth. And he found them.
Two big front ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble saw the teeth again the following week, when Valmont had
them proudly displayed in a glass jar at his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize teeth were so long,'' Gamble mused. ``There's
so much tooth up inside the gum.''
</P>
<P>
   Aeros left wing Jeff Christian has his own toothsome tales. As a
rookie in Canada, he lost two front teeth to a puck. A dentist
installed a permanent bridge. Next season, the bridge got knocked
out by a stick. Now he wears a removable bridge, making him a hit
at watermelon seed spitting contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's like getting whacked in the mouth with a
hammer,'' Christian said of his close encounters of the puckish
kind.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to contact sports, ice hockey is as gnarly as it
gets. Bloody and aggressive, the action is fast, furious and in
your face. Tempers frequently fly, as do fists, sticks and pucks.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's not tennis.
</P>
<P>
   So when the guys on the ice take a hit to their pearly whites,
they rely on Houston Aeros team dentist Don Henckel to stand in the
gap. Handy with a cap or crown, always up for a root canal, Henckel
attends all the Aeros home games, where he's ready to rescue
free-floating choppers and return them to the tender gums of
thankful hockey players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so fortunate to have him,'' said Gamble, now retired
and a color commentator for the team. ``Even if it's loose, Doc
Henck's philosophy is always to try and save the tooth.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Aeros enter the playoffs, one of the busiest men in
dentistry said that overall the team's dental health is ``pretty
good, except for a few cavities here and there.''
</P>
<P>
   In private practice since 1968, Henckel is a polite, serious,
quietly cordial man. Handsome, with snowy-white hair and a ruddy
complexion, he looks like one of those grandfatherly doctors in an
HMO pamphlet. Sitting in his multiroom dental complex, he's full of
tooth (make that toothless) stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really devastating,'' said Henckel, recalling
Valmont's unorthodox oral-handling of a hockey puck. ``There wasn't
any possibility of ever re-implanting those teeth. They were gone.
All the bone around them was gone as well.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Henckel _ who has bushy eyebrows, one of which
lowers when he talks, giving him an earnest, Lloyd Bridges look _
had to rebuild Valmont's ``arch.'' That's the bony ridge where the
teeth go in. Henckel reconstructed it with synthetic materials so
the subsequent bridge would sit right in Valmont's face, and he
wouldn't scare people in bus stations.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was that Long Beach player who took a puck to the
jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It knocked out one of his lower teeth; the other four were
just waving there,'' said Henckel, who provides dental care to
opposing teams when they're on Houston turf. ``You could move them
very easily. We re-implanted the one that came out and wired the
other ones back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, though, injuries are more minor _ a chipped
tooth here, the occasional exposed nerve or broken molar there _
leaving Henckel and wife Patricia to enjoy the game and their hot
pretzels in the stands. His most common procedure is injecting a
tooth-challenged player with anesthesia, letting him back on the
ice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
