<HEADER>
A7497 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-EXOTIC-RECIPES1S     04-21 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EXOTIC-RECIPES1STTAKE22-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A world of flavors waits on kitchen shelf
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ W e've come a long way from the days when a taco kit
was considered the most exotic ``ethnic'' cuisine we could buy at
our local grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   I worked with recipe tester Margaret Ann Surber to comb the
aisles of a few area grocery stores, and we came up with literally
dozens of products to bring some global flavor into the home
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   And the good news is, all the products are indeed easy to use
and less than $5 a pop _ unlike many found at gourmet markets that
sell for twice that price. Do you love the pad Thai noodles at your
favorite Thai restaurant? Then you can have similar noodles within
minutes at home.
</P>
<P>
   Does Indian curry seem intimidating? There are plenty in jars
and cans to give you a quick fix without all the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for something different for lunch? Make a chicken salad
with some mango chutney or toss some noodles with peanut sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you hit the soy sauce and salsa aisle, linger
awhile. Read the labels. They often have good recipes and
suggestions for use. Some products require more effort than others.
And some deliver more authentic flavor than others. Read on for our
opinions _ but then get busy with your own taste tests.
</P>
<P>
   the Bombay way
</P>
<P>
   Indian is the latest explosion on the packaged ethnic foods
scene, with a wide array of products available, from curries to
condiments. Much of it has bold, spicy flavors with some heat.
Here's what we tasted:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sharwood's Indian puppodums ($3.29 at Kroger): Puppodums are
crackers made of black gram bean flour _ sounds gross, but they are
really crispy and delicious. Usually you have to find these at
Indian markets and fry them up. Sharwood's can be popped in the
microwave _ no mess, no fat. A fine accompaniment for an Indian
meal or a great anytime snack.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Patak's Major Grey mango chutney ($3.89 at Harry's Farmers
Markets): This is the quintessential Indian condiment of pickled
fruit, often spooned on top of curries. This variety is
particularly chunky; but we didn't find a great deal of difference
between brands, so go with what you find. If you don't see it with
other ethnic foods, look for it on the condiment aisle. Great to
mix into cream cheese for a dip.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Patak's dopiaza cooking sauce (mild) ($3.49 at Harry's Farmers
Markets): This is a mild, tomatoey sauce in a jar that's easy to
use. It's a nice introduction to Indian flavors. You simply brown
meat, pour in the sauce and heat. It is a bit thick and tends to
scorch if you don't add water.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Patak's hot chili and cumin sauce ($2.49 at Harry's Farmers
Markets): Much hotter and more intense than the dopiaza; this one
comes in a can. It's more authentic and for the more initiated.
Good for meat or vegetables. A real experience.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Curry King curry sauce ($2.99 at Harry's Farmers Markets):
Strong tomato and cinnamon flavors make this one special; it's
recommended as dip, but you need to heat it to really coax out all
the flavors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rajah Kashmiri masala paste ($4.38 at Kroger): Here, the
emphasis is on vinegar and chilis. This paste is hot, hot, hot. You
blend it with yogurt to make a sauce for meat or vegetables. You
may have to experiment to find the best ratio of paste to yogurt
for your hot/spice tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Chutney Chicken Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A great way to give an American classic _ chicken salad _ an
exotic twist. The next time you have leftover chicken, give this a
try. It's as simple as opening a jar of chutney. For even more
Indian flavor, add a pinch or two of curry powder.
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup mango chutney, chopped if pieces are very large
</P>
<P>
   4green onions, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2ribs celery, sliced
</P>
<P>
   3or 4 boneless, skinless chicken breasts (about 1 pound), cooked
and diced
</P>
<P>
   4lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon almonds, toasted and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon coconut, shredded and toasted
</P>
<P>
   In a medium mixing bowl, combine mayonnaise, sour cream,
chutney, green onions and celery. Stir in chicken, mix to coat
well. Serve on lettuce leaves and garnish with almonds and coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 304 calories, 32 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 47), 7 grams carbohydrates, 95
milligrams cholesterol, 153 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican mania
</P>
<P>
   The availabilty of Mexican food items is phenomenal, in part
because of the growing Hispanic population in Atlanta and the
ever-popular appeal of food at your local Tex-Mex joint. I always
keep tortillas and cheese on hand for a quick quesadilla. But there
are many other great products to try. Here's the lowdown on some we
sampled:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Goya guava jelly ($2.49 at Kroger): This tangy jelly isn't bad
on the morning toast, but I like to combine it with rum and lime
juice and then heat it up for a glaze _ especially good on grilled
pork chops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Knorr refried beans ($1.29 at Kroger): In all honesty, you're
better off making these from scratch _ a great way to use up
leftover beans. Many canned versions of refried beans aren't black;
so if frijoles negros are your choice, this packet variety will do
for a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  La Costena chipotles in adobo sauce ($1.19 at Publix): It's so
easy to add a touch of smoky, peppery flavor to your favorite
enchiladas, burritos, tacos and even rice and beans. Just pop open
a can of these smoked, ripe jalapenos. I like to toss a few on a
flour tortilla with shredded cheese for a quick quesadilla. Great
to mix with sour cream for the side, too. Be forewarned, though:
They're smokin' hot; a little goes a long way.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Goya Mexican-style rice (chicken flavor) ($1.79 at Harry's):
This earns points for being a mix but not tasting like one. Good
chicken flavor, with corn and bell peppers, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dona Maria mole sauce ($2.19 at Kroger): Once you've had an
authentic mole ground in a mortar and pestle, you'll probably find
packaged versions like this terribly inferior. Then again, if you
haven't had that opportunity, you may like this mixture of ground
chiles, sesame seeds, cocoa and other spices. Try adding brown
sugar to offset the slightly bitter taste. Nice with turkey
cutlets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  World Harbors Guadalupe Mountain Mexican-style fajita sauce
($2.29 at Kroger): Better than a dry, packaged mix. Loaded with
flavor and a must for the spring grilling season. You can stir-fry
with it, too.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chipotle Chicken Enchiladas
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   With so many prepared items on the market, making enchiladas is
a snap. The tortillas and sauce come ready to use. You can buy
shredded cheese, and if you don't have time to cook the chicken
yourself, pick up some pre-roasted. The chipotles add a whole new
dimension to this favorite dish.
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1small to medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   3/4pound boneless cooked chicken, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2(10-ounce) cans mild enchilada sauce, divided (we used Old El
Paso)
</P>
<P>
   3to 4 chipotle peppers in adobo sauce, from a can
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2cups shredded cheddar cheese, divided
</P>
<P>
   1(12-count) package medium flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Lightly grease a 13-by-9-inch
baking dish and set aside. Place oil in a large skillet over
medium-high heat, add onion and cook, stirring constantly, until
onion is soft, about 5 minutes. Add chicken and cook until heated
through. Stir in 1 can enchilada sauce, chipotle peppers, sour
cream and 1 1/2 cups of the cheese. Combine well and spoon fillings
onto tortillas and roll. Place, seam side down, in prepared baking
dish and pour remaining enchilada sauce over the top. Sprinkle with
remaining cheese and bake 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 296 calories, 17 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 25 grams carbohydrates, 46
milligrams cholesterol, 566 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   peanut sauce passion
</P>
<P>
   My theory is that the proliferation of Thai restaurants in
Atlanta is due to a flavor near and dear to Georgians' hearts _
peanuts. Many of us were introduced to peanut sauce as a condiment
for dipping grilled satay, or small skewers of meat. But then we
found it's good on other things too, like spring rolls and noodles.
I love to splash some in my homemade chili. There are numerous
brands available now. We sampled several and found big differences
in flavor and texture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dynasty ($1.69 at Harry's): Very tangy and vinegary, with an
afterburn that comes on strong. The hottest of those we tried.
Thin, less sweet than others, with no additions like coconut milk.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thai Kitchen ($3.89 at Publix): Coconut is the predominant
flavor, and this one also had the most chunks of peanuts. Very
sweet, perfumey and thick. Good for dipping; dilute for dressing;
too much sugar for grilling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  House of Tsang ($3.89 at Publix): Our favorite. Smooth _ it
uses peanut butter. Not too hot, not too thin. Has a touch of
sherry. Balanced, good for all purposes. Even worth pouring on a
cracker.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Annie Chun's ($4.59 at Harry's): Thin, with lots of sesame
seeds and _ balsamic vinegar? Seems and tastes a little
incongruous. This was more soy/sesame than peanut and would be best
used as a marinade.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Taste of Thai ($2.49 at Kroger): This one comes in a packet,
not a bottle, and frankly, we don't think it's worth the trouble.
Your work is rewarded with weak flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
