<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7498 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-EXOTIC-RECIPES2N     04-21 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EXOTIC-RECIPES2NDTAKE22-C </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: with weak flavor.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Noodle Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes/Chilling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a recipe found on the House of Tsang Bangkok Padang
Peanut Sauce bottle. It's so quick and easy, it's become one of my
favorite lunches. For a heartier version, add some chicken. I've
found the Kame brand Chinese egg noodles near the soy sauce and
stir-fry sauces at Kroger. If you can't find them, angel-hair pasta
will work, too.
</P>
<P>
   8ounces of Chinese egg noodles, or angel-hair pasta, cooked
according to package directions, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   6ounces cooked shredded chicken (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup shredded carrot (about 1 large)
</P>
<P>
   1cup cucumber, matchstick cut
</P>
<P>
   1cup broccoli florets, blanched
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup peanut sauce
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the noodles, chicken if using, carrot,
cucumber, broccoli and peanut sauce. Toss to mix well; serve cold.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without chicken): 384 calories, 14 grams protein,
13 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 30), 55 grams
carbohydrates, 54 milligrams cholesterol, 27 milligrams sodium, 3
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Thai _ beyond peanut sauce
</P>
<P>
   There is more to Thai food than peanut sauce _ principally,
fantastic curry sauces. There are two main brands available _ Thai
Kitchen and Taste of Thai. A couple of tips: Some of the recipes on
the labels call for fish sauce or ``seasoning'' sauce, also sold in
groceries. In Southeast Asia, it's as important a condiment as soy
sauce is in China and Japan. Don't be put off _ used sparingly, it
adds an appealing dash of salty, anchovylike flavor. Secondly, when
cooking with coconut milk (the unsweetened kind), remove the entire
top of the can to pour in order to get all the thick, creamy stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thai Kitchen red or green curry simmer sauces ($3.99 at
Publix): It doesn't get any easier than this, and perhaps these
pour-and-heat sauces are the best place to start. The difference in
the color simply has to do with the difference in the chiles.
Typically, the green chile would be a bit hotter, but there wasn't
much difference here. Good for any of your favorite meats,
vegetables and tofu.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thai Kitchen red or green curry paste ($2.79 at Publix): For a
little more work, you'll get a lot more flavor. These pastes are
power-packed. You combine them with coconut milk so you have
control over the heat and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Taste of Thai red curry base ($2.49 at Kroger): This comes
from a packet and has quite a kick. It's a bit paler than the other
curries, with more perfume and sweetness. You use 1 tablespoon with
a can of coconut.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Taste of Thai coconut ginger rice ($2.29 at Harry's): If you
are a fan of packaged rice mixes, you'll love this one. I can eat a
bowl of this as is and be satisfied, but the flavors aren't too
strong to serve as a base for curries, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Taste of Thai coconut ginger soup mix ($2.69 at Harry's):
Are you picking up on a theme here? Ginger and coconut are popular
flavors _ but I would skip this. It doesn't look like the colorful
soup on the package, and it is considerably blander than that
lovely soup at your favorite Thai restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thai Kitchen pad Thai noodles ($2.79 at Publix): This kit
provides the noodles and the sauce _ you add the egg and anything
else, like sprouts or chicken or shrimp. Good for a quick fix, but
the sauce is much sweeter than what most restaurants serve.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Taste of Thai sweet green chile sauce ($2.29 at Harry's):
Keep this with your other hot sauces for adding a dash of sweet-hot
spice to almost anything, from greens to stews.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Quick Green Curry
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   I once made a Thai red curry paste by hand. I drove to three
different markets to get all the ingredients, and then it took
eight hours with a partner to cut, grind and make the paste. It was
great, but with that kind of labor, I've only done it once. Enter
prepared curry pastes and sauces. They aren't as fresh and complex,
but they sure do satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   1/2to 1 tablespoon green curry paste
</P>
<P>
   1(14-ounce) can coconut milk (lite or regular)
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup canned sliced bamboo shoots
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1small onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2green bell pepper, cored, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   8ounces scallops or peeled and deveined shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Cilantro for garnish, if desired
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, combine curry paste and coconut milk.
Bring to a simmer over medium heat. Simmer 5 minutes and add basil,
bamboo shoots, fish sauce, brown sugar, chicken stock, onion and
bell pepper. Bring to a boil, reduce heat to simmer, cook for 10
minutes, add scallops or shrimp and cook until just done, 3 or 4
minutes. Garnish with cilantro if desired. Serve over cooked rice.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 399 calories, 18 grams protein, 29 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 66), 21 grams carbohydrates, 26
milligrams cholesterol, 752 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   stir-frying a cinch
</P>
<P>
   First, get a couple of bags of the frozen stir-fry vegetables.
Even if you love fresh, you know you don't always feel like going
home and chopping. Just discard the sauce provided _ it's way too
salty. Instead, peruse the bottled stir-fry sauces _ you'll be
amazed by the choices.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lindy's Kung Pao Szechuan sauce ($3.69 at Harry's): A fairly
generic sauce that's good if you are new to these flavors. Though
often Szechuan means spicy, this sauce isn't. Kids would like it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  House of Tsang Saigon Sizzle stir-fry sauce ($3.89 at Publix):
This one has a very nice heat that gets hotter when cooked. Similar
to a Szechuan sauce but hotter and more complex than Lindy's.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Annie Chun's hot and spicy shiitake mushroom sauce ($4.59 at
Harry's): This one delivers the earthy flavor you'd expect from a
mushroom sauce. It's slightly bitter, but loses that flavor when
cooked. Has an afterburn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  House of Tsang Imperial citrus stir-fry sauce ($3.49 at
Harry's): Sweet-and-sour fans, this one is for you. Very unusual
and made with natural ingredients like grape juice and orange
puree. It's sweet, so a little different for stir-fry. It would
also make a nice salad dressing, especially for fruit salads. Kids
would probably eat their veggies with a little of this on top.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lawry's Stir Fry Seasonings (sesame ginger) ($2.99 at Publix):
This is a good starter sauce, but it has more artificial
ingredients than the others. Pretty basic ingredients like soy and
tomato paste make it rather dull.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp and
</P>
<P>
   Broccoli Stir-Fry
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 -20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here is but one suggestion for a stir-fry. The fact is you can
substitute your favorite vegetables or your favorite meats. This
goes nicely with white or brown rice and canned pineapple chunks or
mandarin orange slices.
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon plus 2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon minced fresh garlic (about 3 cloves)
</P>
<P>
   1pound medium shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1red bell pepper, seeded and cut in 1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   1bunch fresh broccoli, cut in florets
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup bottled stir-fry sauce
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet or wok, heat 1 tablespoon of the oil over
medium-high heat. Add garlic and shrimp. Cook 4 minutes, or until
shrimp turn pink, stirring constantly. Transfer the shrimp to a
plate. In the same skillet, heat remaining 2 teaspoons oil over
medium-high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add red pepper and cook 2 minutes, stirring constantly. Stir in
broccoli and water. Cover and cook 4 to 5 minutes, or until
broccoli is crisp-tender. Uncover and stir in stir-fry sauce and
the shrimp. Cook until the shrimp are heated through and the sauce
forms a glaze. _ Source: Registered dietitian Michele Peters
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 248 calories, 28 grams protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 29), 16 grams carbohydrates, 172
milligrams cholesterol, 1,260 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Regean Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
