<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-EXOTIC22-COX     04-21 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-EXOTIC22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American palates expand well beyond meat and
potatoes,supermarkets are sticking up on everithing form curry
paste to chipotles
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A tall, lanky waitress in a North Carolina diner
walked over to a table to take a drink order, and informed the
customer of the daily special: spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   The customer ordered sweet tea, but declined on the special. ``I
just don't eat any of those strange things, he told her, turning
his attention back to the tired meat-and-potatoes menu. ``I like to
stick to American foods.''
</P>
<P>
   To which the waitress replied: ``You're right. I don't eat no
foreign food either.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pillsbury, a geography professor at Georgia State
University, likes to relate that conversation he overheard a few
years back. Its irony, in fact, prompted him to title his latest
book ``No Foreign Food'' (Westview Press, $19.95.) It traces the
astounding speed with which our culture assimilates new and often
``foreign'' culinary concepts.
</P>
<P>
   A few old-timers may remain suspicious of the spaghetti that was
confined to Italian neighborhoods in the first part of this
century. But for the rest of us, ``Italian'' has been dropped from
the description and it's a mainstay of weeknight family meals and
school fundraising suppers.
</P>
<P>
   And all signs are that we will only continue to stir ethnic
cuisines into our daily eating habits. No place bears witness to
this trend better than the local supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Where once a small corner of a shelf was devoted to such
``exotic'' items as taco kits and soy sauce, there are now entire
aisles crammed withcans, jars, envelopes and boxes containing
flavors from around the world _ peanut sauces, Chinese egg noodles,
Thai curry pastes, Indian pappadoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing intense growth in ethnic foods at the retail
level, specifically convenient items at the corner supermarkets,''
said Brian Sansoni, spokesman for Grocery Manufacturers of America,
which represents major brand name food makers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, ethnic foods accounted for $208 million in the food
product market. By 1996, that figure was $272 million and market
analysts estimate ethnic food products may reach $383 million by
2001, Sansoni said.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury calls the trend ``an extension of trying to reduce
prep and cooking time to fit into our busy schedules combined with
the restlessness which is characteristic of the upper middle
class.''
</P>
<P>
   The days of having the same menu week after week _ roast chicken
on Monday, fish on Friday _ are gone. ``We are tired of eating the
same old thing,'' said Pillsbury. ``We are always looking for
something new over the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   That something new is often the dish sampled last week at the
latest ethnic restaurant. Some ambitious cooks go so far as to
scout specialty markets, research cookbooks and enroll in cooking
classes to try to duplicate those tastes from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't take a marketing genius to conclude that more
would just as soon cut to the chase and buy their mole sauce or
curry paste ready-made. There is a reason lots of cooks don't own a
mortar and pestle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are working and they have families and they just don't
have two hours to prepare a meal anymore,'' said Sansoni. Nor do
they have the time or inclination to clean up, Pillsbury added.
</P>
<P>
   Sansori predicts that in years to come, ethnic food products
will not only be more prevalent, but more cleverly marketed _
making shopping for them easier. ``You'll see stores group
everything needed to make an entire meal together on one aisle,''
he said, even if it means dropping in a small refrigerated case in
the middle of a dry goods aisle. That concept already is in play in
some Atlanta area stores, like Harris Teeter, where you can find
refrigerated pasta sauces next to the dry pasta noodles. The goal,
again, is to save time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really amazing how the Atlanta market has changed over
the last decade,'' says Pillsbury. ``It used to be that you could
only find certain products at Harry's or at international markets.
Now, most of that stuff you can find at the larger Kroger and
Publix stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows. Stir-fry night and curry dinners may be the school
fundraisers of the future.
</P>
<P>
   In 20-minutes you can have an Asian-inspired noodle salad using
bottled peanut sauce and quick-cook Chinese egg noodles _ items now
found at your local grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   We toured the aisles of a few local and national chain grocery
stores to see what other convenient ethnic items we could find for
a well-stocked global pantry. Here are our favorites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Anything from The House of Tsang line of products, beginning
with the Bangkok Padang Peanut Sauce and including any of their
innovative stir-fry sauces.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thai Kitchen curry paste (red or green) and a can of coconut
milk. To make a paste by hands takes hours. In minutes, you can
have exciting Thai flavors with your favorite meats or veggies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sharwood's Indian Puppodums _ crispy crackers spiked with
whole spices like black pepper. Better than potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Patak's Hot Chili and Cumin Sauce. Just pour a can of this
thin, spicy sauce over your favorite meats and veggies and heat for
an intense, authentic-tasting Indian experience.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  La Costena chipotles in adobo sauce. Pop the can open, chop
and toss some smoky flavor into your favorite enchiladas,
quesadillas, burritos and tacos.
</P>
<P>
   We found literally dozens of cans, jars and envelopes of quick
ethnic fare in local groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
