<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7514 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-21 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INITIALLY UNWILLING ROLE MODEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julie Krone never asked to be a role model for little girls. She
never volunteered to be a pioneer for women's equality in the world
of sports _ or anywhere else, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   When others set out to impose such burdens on her, in fact, she
resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I didn't want to participate in that,''
Krone said the other day.
</P>
<P>
   And who could have blamed her? In the early years of her career
as a jockey in the sport of thoroughbred horse racing, she was
plenty busy just trying to get established. Just trying to make a
living.
</P>
<P>
   Who had time to lead a crusade against sexism?
</P>
<P>
   That was then. This is now.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Krone began to notice that women in and out of
sports saw her as an icon in the battle for equality. She began to
notice that young girls looked to her for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I got older, I realized there was a contribution to make,
being a female in a sport that was mostly in the past dominated by
males.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone decided to accept the ``gender emphasis'' that she
initially rejected even as she went about the business of
diminishing gender emphasis in her chosen field of endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily because of Julie Krone, female jockeys are no longer a
curiosity at thoroughbred race tracks. Many horse trainers who once
wanted nothing to do with female jockeys now hire them to ride the
best horses in the barn.
</P>
<P>
   There is still sexism in horse racing, but thanks to Krone,
there's a lot less of it than there used to be.
</P>
<P>
   So when Krone retired Sunday after winning three races at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie, no one was saying that she'd had a
wonderful career ``for a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   No, experts and nonexperts alike praised her as one of the
finest practitioners of one of the most challenging jobs in all of
sport. Gary Stevens, arguably one of the two or three best jockeys
on the planet, also rode some horses in Grand Prairie over the
weekend _ and he left no doubt regarding Krone's standing among her
peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not just a great woman jockey,'' Stevens said. ``She's a
great jockey, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Her victories in the second, third and fifth races on Sunday's
Lone Star card gave Krone a total of 3,546 first-place finishes in
her 18-year career. Her mounts won more than $81 million in purse
money; as of Sunday, only 15 jockeys had racked up higher lifetime
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   I first saw Krone ride in 1985, at Monmouth Park in New Jersey.
I worked at a newspaper just a few minutes away from Monmouth, and
I would occasionally go to the track at lunchtime to have a hot dog
and watch _ OK, bet _ the Daily Double.
</P>
<P>
   One day, Julie came storming down the stretch aboard some
forgettable nag that most bettors had overlooked, lighting up the
tote board with a juicy payoff and lighting up the faces of what
was by that time a growing coterie of Krone fans. As Krone posed
for pictures in the winner's circle, a grinning railbird smugly
waved his winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best horse, best jockey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The horse wasn't the best, wasn't even close to the best. But
the jockey was the best _ in that race and in thousands of races to
come.
</P>
<P>
   I've followed Krone's career ever since, cheering her through
countless triumphs on the racetrack, laughing with her through her
appearances on David Letterman's TV show, commiserating with her
through the excruciating injuries that finally persuaded her to
give up riding at the age of 35.
</P>
<P>
   She reminisced about the good times and the bad during a news
conference after her final ride _ a second-place finish in the Lone
Star Derby _ and she talked about the ``gender emphasis'' that she
used to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that all the years I ignored it and maybe
purposely pushed it aside, that maybe I've made up for it and
contributed enough to make a substantial difference in a lot of
little girls' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take that role very seriously,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's an important role. But she's not just a great role model
for girls.
</P>
<P>
   She's a great role model, period.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
