A7517 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUENSTER-GERMANFEST-T     04-21 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUENSTER-GERMANFEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPLE THE BEST AND THE `WURST' FROM MUENSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Muenster is one of those great Texas communities that have
developed their own personalities over the years. It is not a
``boutique'' town that grew overnight for the sake of tourists and
antique dealers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the farmers who tow their livestock to market daily
would laugh at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   Muenster likes tourists OK, even summons them each spring with
an annual Germanfest. This year's event begins Friday and runs
through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But when the festival closes, there will still be some of the
best German sausage available at Fischer's Meat Market. When all
the tourists are gone, you can still go down to Bayer's
Kolonialwaren and Backerei where Cherilyn Pollard will serve an
apple strudel.
</P>
<P>
   At the Center Restaurant &AMP; Tavern, you can get the Altenmuenster
sausage plate, and several places in town serve really good
schnitzel.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing phony or temporary about Muenster, or
Germanfest for that matter. An appreciation of German food and fun
is a constant thread running through the community's life.
</P>
<P>
   Muenster, on U.S. 82 about 14 miles west of Gainesville, was
established in 1889. Three brothers from Westphalia, than a
province of Prussia, surveyed the area as a possible site for a
German Catholic settlement. Within months of their first visit, a
train stopped on the North Texas prairie and discharged a small
group of settlers.
</P>
<P>
   All they found was a piece of paper with the name ``Muenster''
written on it. It was tacked to a nearby telegraph pole.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny group considered Dec. 8 the birthday of the town,
although they arrived a month earlier. It was on Dec. 8 that the
first Mass was celebrated on a makeshift altar constructed in the
land office. Town records indicate that 25 men, seven women and six
children were present at the Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture remains the life's blood in Muenster, now a town of
1,500, but Germanfest does give that life a little extra punch.
</P>
<P>
   Where else can you go to a cook-off that features ``schweine
rippen, gerauchertes fleisch,'' and ``wurst?'' For those of us who
can't tell the front from the back on our lederhosen, that means
pork ribs, barbecue brisket and sausage.
</P>
<P>
   Muenster is in Texas _ even though it is dangerously close to
the Oklahoma line _ therefore it must have a chili contest, and it
does.
</P>
<P>
   All those foods are available during Germanfest, as well as
assorted homemade cheeses, breads, pies and cakes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the prize food items that can be purchased at Germanfest
is strudel. There is no strudel contest because strudel is very
hard to make, and no one wants other folks looking over their
shoulder while guarded family recipes are applied.
</P>
<P>
   And, there is always that chance that someone might sneak in
with a strudel that's made from phyllo dough. That, by the way, is
nearly a hanging offense.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make strudel, make it the right way. Make it the
way Elizabeth Knabe made it. Knabe was one of the six children
present at the first Mass in 1889. Her recipe has been passed down
through the family and is now in the keeping of her granddaughter,
Margie Starke.
</P>
<P>
   Starke warns that it is time-consuming, but worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   APFELSTRUDEL (Apple Strudel)
</P>
<P>
   Yields 10-12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Pastry:
</P>
<P>
   3 1/4 cup sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons shortening
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Lukewarm water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   6 sliced apples
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   Glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk, beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Pastry: Mix flour, salt and shortening; combine eggs, sour cream
and lemon juice and add enough lukewarm water to make a soft but
firm dough. Knead for 15-20 minutes or until dough is elastic and
bubbles on surface. Cover and set in warm place for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Filling: Combine sliced apples, raisins, pecans, sugar,
cinnamon, flour. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Glaze: Beat egg yolk, and add sour cream and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Place a large clean cloth over a large table; sprinkle with
additional flour and place dough in center. Roll dough; lift, pull
and stretch carefully until dough is as thin as paper. Trim edges.
Brush with butter, and sprinkle and spread apple filling over
surface to within 1 1/2 inches of the ends. Roll up into a long
thin roll. Place carefully on a well-greased baking sheet. Brush
with glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Place strudel in oven and bake 20
to 25 minutes or until golden brown. Sprinkle with powdered sugar;
cut into thick slices and serve with a scoop of ice cream, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 286 calories, 8 grams fat, 51
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 55 milligrams cholesterol, 34
milligrams sodium, 24 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
