<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV29-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND-ME-DOWNS HOLD MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Thursday, April 29)  
(mk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I sit on the carpet surrounded by piles of my children's
outgrown clothes.
</P>
<P>
   My task this lazy afternoon is to sort and pack and ship. Out
with the old, make closet space for the new.
</P>
<P>
   The pink toddler sundresses and purple leggings with pink hearts
are all in one stack. My daughter's hand-me-down chain is simple. I
have just one close friend who has a daughter younger than Sarah,
and she lives a few streets away.
</P>
<P>
   I lug a paper bag over when it gets full, and Amy and I share a
pot of tea and watch the girls play in her den. What 1 1/2-year-old
Sally Ann doesn't need, Amy passes on to relatives or church thrift
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, I'll see Sally Ann at day care in one of Sarah's
little neon-striped sunsuits or Dalmatian puppy pullover, and I'll
get a time-warp jolt. It's amazing how your children's old clothing
can trigger flashbulb memories, as if past experiences had been
woven into the worn threads.
</P>
<P>
   The disbursement of my son's clothes is a bit more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   I have three close friends with young sons: Tammy, in West
Virginia, with 5-year-old Zachary and 3-year-old Jake; Kristin, in
California, with 4-year-old Max and 2-year-old Cole; and Terri, in
central Florida, with 4-year-old Zachary and 3-year-old Kelley.
</P>
<P>
   And so, every six months or so, I make three piles.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't random stacks by any means. No, they are carefully
selected with the recipients, and their moms, in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The tie-dyed shorts and Greenpeace/endangered wildlife T-shirts
go to Kristin, who once traveled across the country with her
husband and dog in their VW van. I send her the light blue sweater,
too, to match Max and Cole's eyes, and the tan corduroy pants for
cool evenings on the Monterey pier.
</P>
<P>
   Terri gets the Power Ranger pajamas, the Batman T's, and the
preppy blue and green sweater with a collegiate crest. Her son, who
is going to a private Catholic preschool next year, is as enamored
of superheroes as Adam once was. She also gets the swimming trunks,
since the wading pool is filled practically year-round in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy, who lives with her family in my grandmother's two-story
farmhouse in West Virginia, gets all the play clothes, since her
boys still spend much of their days climbing apple trees, sliding
across the wet pasture on their knees and making mud pies in the
gravel drive. She also gets the heavier coats and sweaters, since
she's the farthest north and gets the most snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   I try to stick a few discarded toys and books in each box, so
the kids won't think I'm that boring mommy who just sends boxes of
clothes all the time. These treats have become so popular with Max
that he calls Adam, whom he has met only once in real life,
``Adam-from-the-box.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin sends pictures of the boys in Adam's clothes, which he's
happy to see are enjoying a fresh lease on life while
snow-sledding, seal-watching and trail-hiking.
</P>
<P>
   And so, as my babies sprout up and out, I pause in midstream to
send my friends these secret messages.
</P>
<P>
   Because, of course, that is what the clothing boxes really are.
They say: Watch out. Pay close attention. See how fast they grow?
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland, Fla., Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
