<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7525 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT &LR;      04-21 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PREPARATIONS NEEDED TO BUILD A STAIRCASE 
</HEADLINE>
  ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building a staircase is a job for a master carpenter, but an
experienced do-it-yourselfer can usually construct a simple set of
stairs for a backyard deck. Cutting the pieces and assembling them
are relatively simple. The hard part is measuring the rise,
calculating the number of steps needed and marking the layout on
the boards. This part may take some trial and error, in adjusting
the dimensions of the steps, to get the number of steps to come out
even.
</P>
<P>
   The main components of stairs are the tread, riser and
carriages. The tread is the flat horizontal board that you step on
as you walk up or down the stairs. The riser is the vertical board
that extends up from the back of one tread to the nose of the one
above. Together the tread and riser join to make a step.
</P>
<P>
   Carriage boards, or stringers, are the long slanting boards that
rise from the ground to the top of the deck. The steps are mounted
in a series of notches, resembling a sawtooth pattern, that must be
cut into the carriage boards. Stairs with steps less than 32 inches
wide (from side to side) need only two carriage boards, provided
the tread is at least 1 1/2-inches thick. Thinner treads, made of
3/4-inch stock, need a carriage centered between the others if they
span more than 24 inches.
</P>
<P>
   An ideal riser height is 7 or 8 inches. The optimal tread width
(from front to back) is 10 inches. Treads should never be less than
9 inches, nor more than 11 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Begin by measuring the total rise of the stairs, that is the
distance from the ground to the top of the deck. It is easy to take
this measurement at the foot of the deck, but this may not be good
idea if the ground around the deck is uneven. The steps will meet
the ground a few feet from the deck. If this area is significantly
higher or lower than the ground around the deck base, it could
affect the pitch of the steps, so it's a good idea to take a second
measurement away from the deck, approximately four feet for stairs
with only four or five steps, and compare the two figures.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the total rise by seven (the ideal riser height in
inches) to get the number of risers. A whole number indicates that
each riser will be exactly seven inches high. If the number has a
remainder, ignore the remainder and divide the whole number into
the total rise to determine the dimensions of the risers. For
example, suppose the total rise is 45 inches. Dividing 7 into 45
inches yields 6.43. This means that there will be 6 risers in this
pattern. Dividing 6 into 45 inches yields 7.5 inches, the height
for each riser.
</P>
<P>
   Next, calculate the total run, the length of the stairs from the
first step to the deck. Select a tread width -- it's best to start
with 10 inches so you can add or subtract an inch if necessary --
and multiply by the number of treads to find the total run.
Remember that there is always one less tread than riser.
</P>
<P>
   Using the previous example, there are 6 risers, but there will
only be 5 treads, because the top riser will mate with the deck
surface. Multiplying 5 by 10 inches yields a total of 50 inches,
the total run of the stairs. You can modify this distance somewhat
by adding or subtracting one inch from the tread width.
</P>
<P>
   When you know the number of risers and treads, you can calculate
the amount of lumber needed. Multiply the number of treads and
risers by their width (side to side) in inches. Calculating the
length of the carriages requires a bit more thinking. Since the
carriage forms the hypotenuse in a right triangle, you can use the
Pythagorean Theorem to find its length. Square the measurement of
the total rise and add it to the squared figure of the total run.
The square root of the sum is the length of the carriage. Using the
previous example: 45 inches squared plus 50 inches squared is 4,525
inches. The square root of 4,525 is 67 inches.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds too complicated, you can simply run a tape
measure from the floor of the deck to the point where the stairs
will start. Double this figure because there are two carriages,
then add about 24 inches. The extra length will allow some leeway
in case you have adjust the layout around any defects in the
boards.
</P>
<P>
   At this point you have determined the dimensions of the stairs
and you have obtained the lumber for the project. You are now ready
to lay out the steps, cut the pieces and assemble them together.
This will be covered next week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
