<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH, RECORD, REPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday marks the beginning of National TV-Turnoff Week, an
annual event in which several million people vow to leave their
television sets dark for seven days no matter how many tantrums
their children throw.
</P>
<P>
   TV-Free America (www.tvfa.org), the group that sponsors
TV-Turnoff Week, wants people to spend the time they would usually
spend watching TV _ an average of 3 hours 46 minutes per day per
person, according to the A.C. Nielsen Company, a market research
firm _ in pursuit of more creative pastimes, including ``healthy
physical activity, civic engagement, reading, thinking and doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are laudable goals, of course. To prepare for this week, I
got some healthy exercise installing an intriguing new device
called ReplayTV (www.replaytv.com), which some day _ not any time
soon, but some day is destined to be the successor to the
not-so-trusty video cassette recorder.
</P>
<P>
   As for reading, I spent about an hour studying the ReplayTV
manual, learning about its many features. And as for thinking, here
it is: Because the ReplayTV video recorder is so smart, so much
easier to use and so much more talented than my old-fashioned VCR,
it will very likely change the way I watch television. I'll
probably end up watching more TV than before.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, TV-Free America.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV is the first of several new tapeless VCR devices to
arrive this year, not as replacements for the VCR _ at least not
immediately _ but rather as smart companions. Unlike a VCR,
ReplayTV lets you watch a ``real-time recording'' of a live
program, put it on pause, then return to pick up your viewing where
you left, even as the recording continues. It also makes recording
programs easier. (ReplayTV's main rival, Tivo Inc., whose Personal
Television Service is made by Philips Electronics, declined to make
a review unit available for a comparative review. More information
is at the www.tivo.com site.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the VCR, which records programs on inexpensive magnetic
tape and plays back prerecorded tapes, ReplayTV records video
programs on a hard disk drive like the one in a personal computer.
It does so by compressing and decompressing the video and audio
signals almost instantaneously, and as a result it appears that
what is running is live TV, when what the viewer is actually
monitoring is a real-time recording _ the recording is being made
as the show is being broadcast or sent over cable.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is a real-time recording, the ReplayTV device has
capabilities that go far beyond a VCR. One can sit down to watch a
program, then pause it for a few minutes to answer a phone call or
to nuke some popcorn in the microwave. When you return, you resume
watching the show without missing anything. The show is still being
recorded, but you are watching it now with a time delay, in other
words, your are actually watching something that was recorded a few
minutes earlier.
</P>
<P>
   You can continue to watch a few minutes behind for the rest of
the evening, or you can catch up during commercials by using the
quick-skip button on ReplayTV's remote control, a button that
advances the show precisely 30 seconds, which just happens to be
the length of the average television commercial.
</P>
<P>
   The hard drive allows a quick reverse, too, unlike tape, which
has to be rewound. Viewers can hit an instant-replay button for any
scene, whether a close play at the plate or a line of dialogue lost
when the kids were fighting over who could use the ReplayTV system
next. There are also VCR-like controls for fast forward and
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Recording a single program or movie is easier than it is on a
standard VCR, once the user goes through an inescapable hour to set
up the system and read the manual. Part of the set-up entails
connecting the ReplayTV's built-in modem to a standard phone line.
The box then calls _ toll free _ a database each night in the wee
hours to update the latest program schedules for any television
services the user has, including broadcast, cable and satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Using the remote control wand that comes with the system, the
user then calls up the on-screen TV listings guide, highlights the
program to be recorded, and pokes the record button on a remote
control. There is no need to enter channels or start and stop
times, as ReplayTV keeps track of all that. Pressing the button
twice instructs ReplayTV to record not just this one episode, but
all future shows in the series, as long as there is room on the
drive.
</P>
<P>
   This idea of persistent, intelligent recording is the most
intriguing feature of ReplayTV. It enables couch potatoes to create
their own television channels based on favorite themes _ not just
series names like ``Star Trek'' or ``ER,'' but also ``Yankees'' or
``fishing'' or ``Michelle Pfeiffer.'' It can track actors,
directors, hobbies, obsessions and key words.
</P>
<P>
   Typing in the themes using ReplayTV's clunky virtual keyboard is
a temporary annoyance but a long-term benefit. (Searching the
program guide on screen is also slow and clunky.) Once programmed,
the ReplayTV system will automatically search through each week's
available program listings to find anything that matches those key
words. The system works even if the show changes times from week to
week.
</P>
<P>
   If the theme is Michelle Pfeiffer, for example, ReplayTV can
find her in a movie on one channel, on a talk show the next week on
another channel and so on. ReplayTV will seek out and record any
program where her name appears in the program listing, as long as
there is space on the hard drive. The viewer can watch the shows at
a convenient time, and then either erase them or transfer them
through a VCR to videotape for archiving or portability, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its cleverness, ReplayTV is not going to send the VCR to
the junk pile any time soon. A decent VCR can be had for less than
$200, and six hours of programs can be recorded on a tape that
costs $2. An entire season's worth of ``Ally McBeal'' can be stored
on $10 worth of videocassettes and treasured for years.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, ReplayTV has limited recording space. The ReplayTV
model 2001 ($699) can record a maximum of about 10 hours of
programming at the lowest of three levels of recording quality, and
after that the machine will start recording over previously
recorded shows, unless the shows are protected. The Model 2003 has
a maximum capacity of 14 hours and costs $899. The Model 2004 has
up to 28 hours of storage and costs $1,499.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with videotapes, hard drive recording space is
expensive. The ReplayTV system uses one gigabyte of hard drive
space to record one hour of video using its standard
(lowest-quality) MPEG-2 compression ratio. The image is slightly
inferior to that on a VHS tape, especially for sports or action
movies, because of weaknesses of the MPEG-2 system. To get better
picture quality, the user must choose medium compression, which
cuts the recording capacity in half. To get an image equal to that
of the original signal, including cable and satellite signals, the
ReplayTV recording should be set on high, which reduces the
available recording time even further.
</P>
<P>
   ReplayTV will become more attractive when hard drives become
cheaper or when improved mathematical formulas for compression
increase recording capacities by squeezing more data onto the
drive. ReplayTV comes with an IEEE-1394 (Firewire) data port, which
means that ReplayTV is planning to support future Firewire-based
storage attachments that could record onto, or play back from, some
type of removable medium like a recordable DVD disk.
</P>
<P>
   My wife discovered, much to her annoyance, that the ReplayTV box
made noise all night long, even when it was not recording, because
the hard disk is always spinning, so the device was banished from
the bedroom TV to my office TV.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Tivo system, which relays a ``personal profile'' of
the owner's viewing habits back to Tivo and then to advertisers,
the ReplayTV phone call each night gathers program listing
information but does not report on what the owner has been
watching. For privacy reasons alone, I would choose it over the
Tivo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I have some sympathy for the TV-Free America folks.
They note that some six million videocassette movies are rented
each day, compared with three million items checked out of public
libraries, and that the average American youth watches 1,500 hours
of television a year, compared with 900 hours spent in school.
</P>
<P>
   If ReplayTV makes it easier to track down quality programming in
the vast wasteland of television, that is really doing something.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
