<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7528 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-EXODDUS-GAME-NYT &LR;      04-21 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EXODDUS-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HERO WHO, ODDLY, DOESN'T LOOK THE PART 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The eponymous hero of Abe's Exoddus doesn't fit the description
of a video game superman. He's not a lantern-jawed commando armed
with assault weapons, inexhaustible ammunition and a rippling
physique.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a schlub,'' said Lorne Lanning, who directed Abe's
Exoddus, the second title in the Oddworld quintology that began
with Abe's Oddysee. In the first title, Abe frees his fellow
Mudokons from Rupture Farms, a meat-packing plant whose ruthless
corporate overseers, the Glukkons, were butchering its workers to
increase short-term profits. Once an ignorant, happy floor waxer,
Abe becomes a hero to his people.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of his hero's reception, however, a clumsy fall
knocks him unconscious, and a vision reveals his next destination:
Soul Storm Brewery, where the Glukkons grind Mudokon bones into a
tasty narcotic beverage. Soul Storm Brew is highly profitable (and
it keeps the workers in line), but the bone shortage created by the
shutdown of Rupture Farms has put a damper on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Being very practical and profit-minded, the Glukkons have found
another source of raw materials _ the ancient Mudokon burial
grounds _ commenced mining and accelerated factory production to
meet quarterly earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were inspired by the corporate raiders of the world,''
Lanning said. ``The guys that find profit in destruction. They have
a very practical, legal way that they can make a good next quarter.
And their market will support that, and everyone's all hunky-dory,
except the guys that work there.''
</P>
<P>
   So Abe rounds up five friends and sets out across the desert to
shut down Soul Storm Brewery. Thus begins Abe's Exoddus, another
hero's ordeal for our scrawny-shouldered floor-waxer-cum-messiah.
What follows is in some ways a typical action-adventure game filled
with platforms, trap doors, armed assailants and dangerous
industrial equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But the game is atypical in other ways: Abe doesn't carry a gun.
He has to solve his problems by thinking them out, using his brain,
being clever. And he needs help, which means managing a group of
ragtag Mudokons who are unskilled, miserable, tired and
uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   But the game is atypical in other ways: Abe doesn't carry a gun.
He has to solve his problems by thinking them out, using his brain,
being clever. And he needs help, which means managing a group of
ragtag Mudokons who are unskilled, miserable, tired and
uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   It also has suggestive, and disturbing, resonances. A game named
Exoddus with a group of creatures who are slave laborers in a
nightmare factory that grinds them up for profit cannot help but
invite thoughts of the Holocaust and raise questions of taste. But
the designers say there was no intention to tie the game to the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are other cultural references in the game _
American Indian masks and Australian aboriginal music. And the look
of the game suggests newts in trouble rather than crimes against
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Lanning said the Exodus reference was Biblical and meant to
suggest the triumph of the downtrodden, any downtrodden. He said
the Mudokons could easily stand in for American Indians or
aboriginal Australians or wage-slaves in Southeast Asia, and that,
above all, they are heroes. ``It's what happens when cultures are
oppressed and individuals rise to the occasion to make change,''
Lanning said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's a game, not a treatise. And one of the
challenges and pleasures is that the Mudokons are not oppressed
humans, they're some kind of really dumb, but cute, green trolls,
which poses problems for Abe.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to lead the ``Mission: Impossible'' team. It's
another to undertake a heroic enterprise with a bunch of losers who
need constant supervision. Half of the game controls in Abe's
Exoddus have to do with communication. Some words are simple
commands (``Work,'' ``Wait,'' ``Follow me,'' and ``Stop it.'').
``Hello'' initiates a conversation. ``All ya!'' alerts all the
Mudokons at once.
</P>
<P>
   But part of Abe's vocabulary is gestures, or postures,
indicating feelings like anger and sympathy. And you need this
emotional vocabulary because the Mudokons are a moody lot. If
they're angry, they won't listen to you unless you say you're
sorry. If they get ahold of laughing gas, you have to slap some
sense into them.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they get depressed; they're so upset about living in
slavery that they'll scarcely acknowledge Abe. If you yell at them,
they'll commit suicide. If you want to be General Patton, you're in
the wrong game.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, that might be disappointing or frustrating. A
lot of games are sold on the promise of omnipotence. They put you
in a world where you embody strength and aggression and a sort of
cartoon arrogance that is appealing, particularly to adolescent
boys.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's refreshing to play a video game whose
emotional range extends beyond rage and fear and whose protagonist
is not an amalgamation of Arnold Schwartzenneger, Bruce Willis and
Sylvester Stallone. Abe is more like a combination of Roberto
Benigni, Michael Moore and E.T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to design our characters as archetypal forms that
represent certain states of mind,'' Lanning said. ``In Abe's case,
he's certainly not the most intelligent guy in the world, but he
has an intuitive understanding of the difference between right and
wrong. He's not able to intellectualize it. In fact, if he was
arguing with someone halfway intelligent, he'd probably lose the
debate. But still, in his heart, he knows the difference. And so to
us, he embodies a sense of pure conscience undiluted by logic.''
</P>
<P>
   Abe is an archetype, no less than the cowboys and commandos in
Duke Nukem and Quake. But he's a different archetype _ the little
guy _ so he inhabits a different kind of story, which is a story
about losing your innocence and becoming a hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's allegorical to the way things work in today's world,''
Lanning said. ``In many ways, it's a story like `The China
Syndrome' or `Silkwood.' Very ordinary people find themselves in
extraordinary circumstances where their own conscience is what's
tearing them apart. They think everything's fine, they witness
something, and it blows apart their whole perception of reality.
</P>
<P>
   So for Abe, he was working in the meat-processing plant. He was
employee of the year. And then he found out the place was not what
it was cracked up to be. The retirement plan was a lie, and he was
going to wind up a Tasty Treat. And it just shattered his whole
perception of reality, and he had to do something. For us, those
are inspiring stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Abe's Exoddus, developed by Oddworld Inhabitants, published by
GT Interactive; for Playstation and Windows 95 and 98; CD-ROM,
$44.95; all ages.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
