<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE RACE COULD BE BED OF THORNS FOR HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 25)   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c. 1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``I love New York, I always have,'' purred Hillary
Rodham Clinton, delivering what could be the opening line in a
fascinating political drama.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady campaigned last week through the state that next
year will elect a successor to the eminent Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, a Democrat who is retiring after four terms. Her hope,
presumably, is that she will be that successor.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to excite the residents of a state that is
satiated with celebrities from the worlds of sports, theater, high
finance, literature and politics. But Hillary is trying to and
appears to be succeeding, at least with Democrats who want her to
seek Moynihan's seat.
</P>
<P>
   With charm and intelligence, she is paving her own way to a
possible announcement that she will take up residence in New York
and enter the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   But she is enough of a realist to understand that what could
await her is a bed of thorns rather than a bed of roses.
</P>
<P>
   Having campaigned many times with her husband, she should be
ready for blistering assaults on her character, her credibility,
her role as mother and wife and her part in the many controversial
activities that have gotten her attention.
</P>
<P>
   If she decides to run for the Senate, and if her Republican
opponent is New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Hillary would be
entering the ring against a tough, determined political pugilist
who would not be awed by her status as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Critics will be scanning a new book, ``The First Partner:
Hillary Rodham Clinton,'' by Joyce Milton and other books for dirt
about the president's wife. Publishers's Weekly describes Milton's
book as ``a revealing and withering portrait.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, Milton probes Hillary's role in questionable political
fund-raising activities as well as her relationship with a
philandering husband who is an adept prevaricator. Milton suggests
a romantic link between Hillary and Vincent W. Foster Jr., her
onetime law partner who became a White House aide and took his own
life. She also claims that Hillary declared the White House
off-limits to Barbra Streisand because the president and the
chanteuse allegedly were involved in a bit of hanky-panky.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary has no role model for this adventure because no previous
first lady has sought public office after her husband's White House
tenure came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   The idol with whose spirit Hillary sometimes communes, Eleanor
Roosevelt, made a career of demolishing barriers erected to control
the activities and ambitions of women. Yet she didn't seek elective
office.
</P>
<P>
   After the death of President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1945,
there were some suggestions that Mrs. Roosevelt might run for
office in her home state of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing came of the idea. Mrs. Roosevelt did play a
prominent role, however, in Democratic Party activities, starting
in 1940 when she flew to the national convention in Chicago to
quell a rebellion against her husband's selection of liberal
Agriculture Secretary Henry A. Wallace as his third-term running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, she was a strong supporter of Adlai Stevenson for
president. At the 1960 convention, she again urged Stevenson's
nomination, but the prize went to John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Roosevelt's most enduring commitment, following 12 years in
the White House, was to the United Nations. President Harry Truman
appointed her a delegate to the world organization in 1945 and she
served until 1953. Kennedy reappointed her in 1961, but she died
the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Other former first ladies have been active in their post-White
House years, without venturing into political battle as Hillary may
do.
</P>
<P>
   After her second husband, Aristotle Onassis, died, Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis became a highly-regarded book editor at Doubleday.
Lady Bird Johnson, who made beautification of America a major theme
of her activities as first lady, established, in her post-White
House years, the National Wildlife Research Center in Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Ford, who struggled with alcoholism and drug abuse,
established the Betty Ford Clinic to help others overcome their
chemical dependency. Rosalynn Carter has continued since the end of
her husband's presidency to support efforts to help the mentally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reagan and Barbara Bush have made a few public
appearances, but have not taken on major projects.
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary Rodham Clinton accepts the challenge to run for
office in New York, she will be a trailblazer, a pioneer slashing
her way through the Empire State's tangled political thicket.
</P>
<P>
   She told reporters in New York last week that ``right now I am
very focused on the situation in Kosovo.'' She is ready to visit
the area at the invitation of the U.S. Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady added: ``I think it is very important for me to
go to Kosovo eventually, but I want to go when my going does not
interfere with the work and in any way displace resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a journey could add to her prestige and strengthen her
political credentials. That other female political pathfinder,
Elizabeth Dole, must have seen similar advantage in such a journey
when she visited the Balkans and returned recently to proclaim that
the war must be won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
