<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7543 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SESAME-STREET-ART     04-21 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SESAME-STREET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SESAME STREET' SITE: SERIOUS CHILD'S PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The office of Children's Television Workshop Online in Manhattan
is a preschooler's decorating dream, with a wall-size blackboard,
armchairs that fairly beg for someone to curl up and tell a story
and a mesmerizing carpet of crayon-bright red, blue and orange that
could have been designed by a Romper Room Martha Stewart. The only
thing missing is ... children.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not. Most of the staff members who designed and
created the new Web site (www.ctw.org) for the Children's
Television Workshop, the creator of ``Sesame Street,'' look too
young to even have children themselves. But they have valuable
firsthand experience: they are, after all, members of the first
generation of children who grew up with Muppets.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Sharkey, the group's vice president and general manager,
certainly fits that description, and she was described by her
former boss, Candice Carpenter, a founder of the Internet company
iVillage, as ``more like a kid than any other adult I know.'' Ms.
Sharkey, who is 34, said the ``Sesame Street'' show ``invented one
of the most important movements of the 20th century, empowering
families to get involved with their kids' learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sharkey admits that she still watches ``Sesame Street.'' ``I
was on the treadmill one morning last season, watching an episode
about Slimey the Worm, who wanted to go into outer space,'' she
said. ``There was Tony Bennett, standing on a rooftop singing,
`Slimey to the Moon,' and all of a sudden, I started sobbing. It
was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The task that faced Ms. Sharkey and her team of 30 producers,
designers and marketers at Children's Television Workshop Online in
1997 was to recreate on the Web the enormously familiar and
comforting blend of education and entertainment that ``Sesame
Street'' pioneered on television nearly three decades earlier. ``We
had to take what we as a company understand about a 6-year-old's
mind-set and then apply it to the Web,'' Ms. Sharkey said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Sesame Street's status as a pop-culture icon, as
the veritable gold standard of children's programming, made the
online team's job more complicated. They had to compete with a
legend. The producers of Sesame Street understood kids and they
understood television. But did they understand the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Web site for the company, which is nonprofit,
had to define itself in relation to such well-entrenched commercial
destinations as Disney Online's www.disney.com and the www.nick.com
site of the Nickelodeon cable network.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Nickelodeon announced its plan to create a free
online service for kids, tentatively named Project Nozzle.
Scheduled to begin on Sept. 1 and backed by on-air promotions from
Nickelodeon worth $100 million, the project is widely viewed as the
network's attempt to ``basically own the children's TV space on
line,'' said Patrick Keane, a senior analyst at Jupiter
Communications, a Web research firm.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Sharkey arrived at Children's Television Workshop's
online division in July 1997, the Web site consisted of some
material recycled from a previous online venture and a television
schedule. ``Essentially, when I got there, I found nothing,'' she
said. ``They did a business plan before I got there. There were a
few staffers. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step was to appeal to the Children's Television
Workshop's core audience: families. One of the insights of the
original designers of ``Sesame Street'' was that children would
watch educational programs more readily if their parents watched,
too, which is one reason the television series has always featured
pop cultural references and celebrities and sophisticated humor.
</P>
<P>
   Web site staff members knew that a receptive family audience was
already on line. A recent study from the Find/SVP and Grunwald
Associates research firms showed that 67 percent of parents who own
computers log on with their children. ``We needed to build on the
idea that we are the only company in the world who has this
rite-of-passage relationship with kids and parents,'' Ms. Sharkey
said. That meant creating a site that encouraged a preschooler to
sit on a parent's lap and engage in collaborative mouse-clicking
adventures _ what the producers began to call ``lapware.''
</P>
<P>
   In designing the site's home page, ``we had to think about the
way kids play, how they like to have everything spread out all
around them and then they want to choose one thing to do,'' said
Paul Marcum, the online group's executive producer. The result was
a menu that is as brightly colored as the office carpet and that
offers users numerous options with names like Sesame Street
Central, Preschool Playground and Activity Time.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that children like to master tasks, the team designed
interactive games that reward children for right answers. In a
counting game that features the popular Muppet called Grover as a
farmer, children who match numbers hidden in his harvested
vegetables are rewarded with a Tinkerbell-like jingling sound. A
mismatch prompts the computer to emit a noise more reminiscent of a
Bronx cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Another Children's Television Workshop staple has been
storytelling. ``When you're reading a book, the interaction might
consist of turning a page,'' said Karen Kane, the team's director
of programming. ``But we created branching stories on line so
children can control the plot, depending on what they click on.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in a story about Telly the Muppet going into outer
space, a child can drag objects into the story to change the
action. Dragging a moon into the story screen sets the scene at
night; if a sun is dragged instead, the story's action occurs
during the day. The activity is especially compelling for small
children, who love repetition, because they can return to the story
to change its plot numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   The redesigned site, called the CTW Family Workshop, went on
line in September 1998, aimed squarely at families with
preschoolers. True to the Sesame Street formula, the site also
offers material for parents, including Internet technical advice
explained in plain English and an easily downloadable program that
lets a user tickle Elmo by clicking on a mouse. The flavor is
unmistakably Sesame Street. And Elmo is adorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the craft activities they have on the site _ I print
them out, and we do them later,'' said Sandy Homan, a mother of two
in Mount Laurel, N.J. Her 6-year-old son, Spencer, is a big fan of
the ``Sesame Street'' television show and visits the Web site every
day. ``I think what he likes about going to the site on line is
that he feels like he's a part of it,'' she added. ``He can
actively do things there, instead of just passively sitting,
watching television.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The designers have taken pains to make the site distinct from
its commercial counterparts. For instance, the Muppet characters
star in interactive games, but they are not promoted directly as
products, the way commercial sites market their popular characters.
</P>
<P>
   The site has a store created by eToys that sells more than 250
products licensed by Sesame Street, but the merchandise offers are
not as prominent or intrusive as those on commercial sites.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the television program, the Web site does carry
advertising. There are no advertisements on content aimed directly
at preschoolers, however, and advertisements aimed at older
children are clearly labeled.
</P>
<P>
   Some people concerned with children's media issues say the
limits are not enough. ``I don't think children are a proper target
for commercial speech,'' said Peggy Charren, a visiting scholar at
Harvard University's Graduate School of Education and a leading
lobbyist on such issues. ``Ads tell children they need something
they may not be able to afford when in reality, they probably don't
need it. Children learn best when they feel satisfied with
themselves. And when they want something they can't have, they feel
unsatisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary E. Knell, executive vice president for operations at the
Children's Television Workshop, responded that the Web site
followed the same guidelines the organization had always followed
on not interrupting content aimed at preschoolers with advertising.
``We need something to be self-supporting,'' he said. ``We don't
want the online site to bleed the whole organization into oblivion.
As with every not-for-profit venture, this one has to raise the
money to support its content.''
</P>
<P>
   The Family Workshop site took a bigger risk in January, adding
content aimed at an elementary-school audience, older than the
Sesame Street crowd. The site's new Kid City lets children 6 to 12
years old create their own home pages and collect and trade online
stickers. ``It's original content, based on the idea that we can do
non-Sesame Street content,'' Ms. Sharkey said. ``It's a big step
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Family Workshop draws considerably fewer visitors than
commercial sites. Certainly, the number of unique visitors to
Disney Online's sites (4.6 million in February) and Nickelodeon
Online's sites (nearly 1.5 million in February) continues to dwarf
the number of visitors to the Children's Television Workshop's
online venture (in February, 300,000), according to Media Metrix, a
company that measures Web traffic.
</P>
<P>
   To broaden its online audience, Children's Television Workshop
has struck a deal that allows it to distribute its content through
the Excite search engine, in its Lifestyle category, and through
Excite's Web Crawler search engine, under its Kids and Family
heading.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, a special version of the Children's Television
Workshop's Family Workshop with exclusive interactive storytelling
content has been available on America Online's proprietary service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was enormously important to us to get their content, not
only because 53 percent of AOL households have children but because
kids are coming on line at younger and younger ages,'' said Regina
Lewis, an America Online spokeswoman. ``We did a poll of 10,000
parents last month, and 25 percent of them said their kids were
using the computer at age 2. You have to give them quality
programming right from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the site will probably be gently tweaked, rather
than redesigned, to accommodate what is learned from research about
how families use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent research project, Sholly Fisch, the vice president
for program research at Children's Television Workshop and a former
writer for Marvel Comics, went into a handful of homes of computer
users to observe firsthand how families navigate the www.ctw.org
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out it's not a linear experience for them at all, it's
a family thing, with kids getting up from the computer to get
snacks, an older brother coming in in the middle of a session, the
phone ringing,'' Fisch said. ``Now we have to go back and think
about how to use that information to make the site work even
better.''
</P>
<P>
   All the tinkering in the world will probably not vault the site
past larger commercial sites. But there are few sites on the Web
that offer as much of a refuge from commercial pressure as the
Children's Television Workshop site, much as ``Sesame Street'' on
public television has offered a refuge from commercialism. And
that's fine with Ms. Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never going to be as big,'' she said, ``and we're never
going to have the reach or the resources. But you know what? We
have something special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
