<HEADER>
A7559 &Cx1f; tab-z
r c &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     04-21 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV09-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., MAY 9, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I am building a small office in my previously unfinished
basement and am framing out the walls with regular 2x4 studs. I
want to include a door in the center of one wall, but am not
certain as to how I should frame out the opening for this doorway.
Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   A: The usual method is to nail a header across the top of the
door opening consisting of doubled 2x4's as shown here. For a
standard 30-inch door the headers should be 35 1/2 inches long. You
first nail the two jack studs (the shorter vertical studs under
each end of the header) to the inner surface of the regular wall
studs on each side of the opening. The jack studs should be 1 3/4
inches longer than the height of the door. The header of doubled
2x4's rests on top of these jack studs. Short lengths of 2x4
(called cripple studs) are then nailed vertically to the inner
surface of the studs above the header on each side.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some polyurethane varnish was spilled on my kitchen ceramic
tile floor. This dried for several days before I knew about it, so
it was never wiped up. How can I remove this hardened varnish
without damaging the tile?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your best bet would be to use an industrial grade semi-paste
paint and varnish remover. This will soften the varnish enough so
that it can be easily washed away with a detergent or scraped off
with a plastic scraper. Be sure you buy a brand remover that says
on the label that it will work on polyurethane finishes. Then
carefully follow the directions on the can.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The living room floor in our old house seems to be sagging
slightly along one wall. We've been told that this is probably due
to the installation of a large entertainment center and bookcase
that we had built in along that wall, while others say it is due to
warping and settling of the floor beams. What do you think we
should do?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is most likely due to a combination of both _ the extra
weight caused the beams or joists to sag. You should be able to
correct both problems by installing two or more adjustable jack
posts or lolly columns in the basement under that sagging floor.
These posts consist of lengths of heavy steel tubing that telescope
inside each other with an adjustable jack on top. The base of the
post must rest on a concrete footing at least six to 12 inches
thick, which usually means chopping a hole in the basement floor.
This is a job that may require the services of a professional _
unless you are quite handy and familiar with concrete work. Also,
remember that the jack must be raised VERY slowly (no more than
about half a turn every three or four days). Otherwise you can do
severe damage to the house if you're not careful.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We had new storm windows installed on our 32-year-old house a
couple of years ago, but we still have some problems with
condensation on these windows during very cold weather. What can we
do to eliminate this problem?
</P>
<P>
   A. Make certain the storm windows fit properly and are properly
caulked so that cold air is not seeping in around them. Also, take
steps to lower the humidity inside the house. If you have a
humidifier on the furnace try turning it down, or even turning it
off completely for awhile. Make certain your clothes dryer is
vented directly to the outside and that there are exhaust fans in
the kitchen and in each bathroom that also vent directly to the
outside. If the problem persists you can also install plastic storm
window kits on the inside of each window (kits for this purpose are
sold in most home centers and hardware stores).
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``HEADER FOR DOORWAY OPENING'' goes with
this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Doubled 2x4's serve as header across top of doorway
opening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
