<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLAS BURPED, OR `WHY CAN'T WE ALL JUST GET ALONG?'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the best beer in the world?
</P>
<P>
   There's a question guaranteed to start a brawl. When it comes to
beer, mutual-assurance pacts between sovereign nations go right out
the window. We're talkin' WAR here, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Think I'm kidding? I invited two friends, Dieter from Munich and
Richard from Sheffield (don't call him Dick), over to Melton Manor
one night to sample their country's respective brews. Aiming for
cultural harmony, I provided an internationally diverse menu of
appetizers: English Stilton, chubby smoked Deutsche knackwurst and
San Francisco sourdough.
</P>
<P>
   Dieter won the coin toss, and we enjoyed a lively Bitburger
pilsner from Germany. The convivial conversation proved
encouraging. But then, perhaps unfairly, considering the
Bitburger's lightness, we poured a Guinness Extra Stout from
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muddy water,'' Dieter opined dismissively. Richard bristled
and said, ``I think you mean full-bodied.''
</P>
<P>
   Dieter stiffened. ``I think I mean vulgar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy howdy, this cheese sure goes well with the sausage,'' I
offered brightly.
</P>
<P>
   Dieter ignored me. ``British beers are assaults to the taste
buds. German beers are uniformly subtle and graceful.''
</P>
<P>
   Popping a chunk of Stilton, Richard replied, ``German beers are
overengineered. British beers are individualistic and expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How 'bout them Cowboys?'' I asked pathetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Dieter reflected, ``we engineer things to be their
best. Take our Messerschmidt 109s. They outperformed your Spitfires
over the channel during the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Omigod.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be,'' Richard replied. ``But as you'll notice, we
won. Chalk it up to British spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Or British conceit,'' Dieter countered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pipe down, both of you,'' I interjected. ``Us Yanks kicked you
Brits in 1776 and 1812, then wiped Deutschland all uber the place
in 1918 and 1945. Let's forget this nonsense and enjoy a nice
Miller High Life, whattaya say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``American beer?'' they chimed in unison. ``Bah, humbug,'' said
Dieter. ``Machts nichts,'' said Richard. They beamed at each other,
new-found allies against a common enemy.
</P>
<P>
   I threw them both out, popped a Miller and watched a ``World at
War'' rerun. Sure enough, we won big-time. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Miller High Life may not be individualistic or engineered, but
it's light, refreshing and even has the beginnings of complexity.
Best of all, it's cheap. And American.
</P>
<P>
   The best beer in the world? As Patton might have said, ``The one
in your hand, moron.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
