<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FROGDESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNING IN THE SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Texas, Germany, Sweden) (js) 
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It came as a disappointment to the executives of Lufthansa when
marketing surveys showed that the German airline was respected for
its fine record of safety and punctuality, but not liked.
Specifically, customers noted that the airline's flight attendants
rarely smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching smiles out of the staff proved frustrating; an
alternative remedy was more successful. Lufthansa went to
Frogdesign, a company founded in Germany with offices in New York,
California and Texas, dedicated to what it calls ``integrated
strategic design and communications.'' Airlines have always
resorted to designers; Henry Dreyfuss and Raymond Loewy did full
redesigns for several airlines, right down to the forks and sugar
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing competition among airlines has led many of them to
call the designers back in. This time, however, designers are being
asked not just to redo seats or dishes, but to reshape the
experience of flying, from check-in to luggage retrieval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal must be to design the whole journey,'' Frogdesign's
chief executive, Hartmut Esslinger, wrote of the Lufthansa project
for the German magazine Form. Recent redesigns by Scandinavian
Airlines, Cathay Pacific and others also show a new experiential,
almost New Age impulse.
</P>
<P>
   Designing the journey is a form of soothing the traveler. Many
airlines, including Lufthansa, offer showers in business and
first-class lounges. John Pawson's lounge in Hong Kong for Cathay
Pacific goes further. It includes a stream running through its
granite floor _ what a mall developer would call a ``water
feature.''
</P>
<P>
   Lufthansa's new look, which had its premiere last fall in
Frankfurt, will be showing up later this year at airports around
the world, including Kennedy International in New York. It aims to
evoke the romance of the early days of aviation. ``We call it
`retro futurist,''' said Sonja Schiefer of Frogdesign's New York
office.
</P>
<P>
   The design theme takes its keynote from the corrugated metal of
the Junkers Ju-52 airliners that Lufthansa flew in the early 1930s.
The metal covers the walls at check-in counters and lends its shape
to new seats. It appears as background on the Web page where
customers can make reservations. Frogdesign used the Junkers'
curves in the walls of the lounges, along with Josef Hoffmann-style
chairs appropriate to a waiting room of the Weimar Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The same curve, Ms. Schiefer said, was used at the check-in
counters, once as rigidly rectilinear as a timetable. Designers
scooped out curves in the counters, physically drawing the customer
and agent closer.
</P>
<P>
   To rework a tunnel connecting terminals in Frankfurt, Frogdesign
hired Michael McDonough, a New York architect, who is a champion of
recyclable materials. He combined the corrugated metal and the
conceit of going back in time to produce a ``time tunnel,'' where
lights, sounds and even odors, wafted through ventilators, vary as
pedestrians pass.
</P>
<P>
   Like Lufthansa, SAS has introduced a ``rebranding'' aimed at
warming its public image. The job went to the Stockholm Design Lab,
which refined the logo, changed colors _ the dominant blue has been
brightened and made ``happier,'' the designers say _ and created
new lounges in softened Scandinavian style. They used Kaj Frank
glassware and Bang &AMP; Olufsen television sets but otherwise tried to
convey ``the character of a generous Scandinavian home.'' For the
airplane toilets they deployed Swedish birch _ and added windows.
</P>
<P>
   The physical redesigns at both airlines coincide with more
customized service. Customers choose when they want to eat, for
instance, so the meal no longer arrives just as they begin to doze.
But the overall ambition seems to be projecting, by physical and
social ambiance, some enveloping version of a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, the motto was, `Let us show you,''' Esslinger said.
``Today, the slogan is `We like you, and together we will have a
really great experience.'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, design aims at not just body and mind but spirit. On the
pods that hold the jet engines and beside the doors, the SAS
designers added lines of poetry. Where it usually says, ``Push here
for emergency slide release,'' the traveler may read lines such as,
``Some travel in their minds, some travel in their heart.'' It
might make even a flight attendant smile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
