<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-RESTAURATEUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN GETS A PIZZA THE ACTION WITH HIS OWN EATERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Mike Salerno was 5 years old, he asked
his mother to take him to McDonald's so he could apply for a job.
Mom was busy making dinner, so, in the dark, Mike took off down
Beach Street to speak to the manager. Halfway there, his father
caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His dad took him on down there,'' says Mike's mom, Aurora
Jackson, ``and the manager said he was exactly the kind of employee
he looks for, but he was just a little too young.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9 years old, Mike applied for an American Express card,
listing his $2-a-week allowance as his income. American Express
politely declined his application, stating that his current income
was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   At 12, he started busing tables at Italy Pasta &AMP; Pizza, a
restaurant owned by his uncle. That led to kitchen work and
whatever he could learn in between making pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   Now 18, with more than five years of restaurant experience
(''that might not sound like a lot to you, but it's a big part of
my life''), Salerno decided to strike out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled together money from relatives, friends and savings.
With ``enough to buy a new car,'' he bought a pizza oven, beverage
machines, plates, flatware, banquettes and tablecloths, and signed
a lease with the partners who own the Western Hills Motel and
coffee shop on Camp Bowie Boulevard in Fort Worth. This year, he
opened Mike Salerno's Italian Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   He supervises the staff, buys supplies, tosses pizzas and does
the books.
</P>
<P>
   Salerno says he gets a lot of help from his mother and his
father, Victor Salerno. That doesn't mean he isn't at the
restaurant most days from 11 a.m. to 11 p.m., trying to study in
between busy spells. He's hoping to make enough money to continue
at Texas Wesleyan University in Fort Worth, where he is a freshman
majoring in economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just the pizza guy,'' Salerno says. ``The executive chef
is Ernie Tortofelli'' (whom Salerno took with him, in the best
tradition of restaurants, from Italy Pasta &AMP; Pizza).
</P>
<P>
   But as the pizza guy, Salerno also jumps in when the cash
register clogs up, cooks when the chef is out and delivers food
when the wait staff is stretched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love his entrepreneurial spirit,'' says Fort Worth
Theater actor and regular customer Steve Garrett. ``I think it's
great that here is a young man without an attitude who is taking
this on.''
</P>
<P>
   With a menu that ranges from baked ziti ($4.95) to veal
parmigiana ($7.95) to calamari salad ($4.95), it might take Salerno
a while to make his mark.
</P>
<P>
   But if American Express is smart, the next time this boy comes
knocking, he'll get a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes from Chef Ernie Tortofelli of Mike Salerno's
Italian Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   POLLO ALLA VENECIA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce chicken breast cut in half, tenderized and floured
</P>
<P>
   1 cup green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup green peppers, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tomato
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup of red wine
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 ounces pasta of choice, dry weight, cooked according to
package instructions
</P>
<P>
   Add enough olive oil to cover the bottom of the pan. Once the
oil is hot (almost to the point of smoking), add the tenderized
chicken to the oil. Once it has changed from pink to white, flip
and saute, then drain the oil from the chicken. Add the vegetables
and butter. Place the chicken on top of the vegetables to prevent
it from burning. Saute the vegetables until they have become soft.
Add the red wine, let the wine flame (if using a gas stove) and
come to a boil, then add the chicken stock to the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Let it come to a boil again. Remove the chicken and put it on
the serving plate. Remove the vegetables and place them on top of
the chicken. Pour half the sauce on the top of the vegetables and
chicken. Place the pan back on the stove and bring remaining sauce
to a boil. Add hot pasta to the sauce, mix, and place the pasta on
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 587 calories, 25 grams fat, 54
grams carbohydrates, 36 grams protein, 77 milligrams cholesterol,
118 milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   TORTELLINI MICHELANGELO
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 cup green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 ounce Parmesan or Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces tortellini, dry weight, cooked according to package
instructions
</P>
<P>
   Place the butter, garlic, green onions and mushrooms in the pan.
Saute until the mushrooms become soft. Add the heavy cream; let it
rise to a boil. Add the Parmesan cheese, letting the sauce thicken,
then add the tortellini. Mix until the tortellini is covered in
sauce. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 905 calories, 50 grams fat, 96
grams carbohydrates, 21 grams protein, 175 milligrams cholesterol,
192 milligrams sodium, 50 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   CALAMARI SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces cleaned calamari, uncooked
</P>
<P>
   1/4 head of lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sliced black olives
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups shredded mozzarella cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon each basil, oregano, black pepper, parsley and
granulated garlic
</P>
<P>
   Juice from 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Pull apart or cut the calamari into strips. Combine calamari
with lettuce, sliced black olives, mushrooms, garlic and mozzarella
cheese. Combine spices with lemon juice, balsamic vinegar and
cheese, and pour over salad. Serve cold.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 489 calories, 34 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 36 grams protein, 272 milligrams cholesterol,
1,319 milligrams sodium, 62 percent of calories from fat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
