<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VERSAILLES-CONSERVE-A     04-21 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERSAILLES-CONSERVE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN PENNIES IN FRENCH FOUNTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Catherine Hamilton, president of the American Friends
of Versailles, has spent 18 months losing sleep in her penthouse, a
10,000-square-foot duplex designed around a collection of
18th-century paneled rooms imported from France.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for her insomnia is Le Bal de Versailles, a six-day
extravaganza of Sun King proportions she is organizing in France to
raise $4.5 million to restore the Bosquet des Trois Fontaines, the
derelict garden masterpiece at the palace.
</P>
<P>
   You'd lose sleep, too, if you had to figure out how to make
$25,000 contributors feel more important than $5,000 ones and
$500,000 donors feel superior to the $125,000 ones, not to mention
the $1 million donor who must be made to feel as omnipotent as
Louis XIV surveying his beloved gardens from the wheelchair to
which he was confined by gout.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Mrs. Hamilton, who doesn't speak much French but
spends a good deal of time at Chateau St.-Georges Motel, the
17th-century mansion she and her husband, David, a Chicago
businessman, also own outside Paris:
</P>
<P>
   ``For $5,000 they get five events, four tax-deductible,'' she
said, sitting in the carved and gilded Louis XV dining room of her
apartment on Lake Shore Drive, puffing on a Virginia Slim, lit with
a tasseled lighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get champagne in the bosquet and barbecue at my house,
but they don't get a fabulous cocktail party at Sandy's,'' she
said, referring to the grand Paris socialite Jean de Yturbe and her
important 16th-century home, Chateau d'Anet. ``For $75,000, I think
they get their name on a plaque, but if they spend $500,000, they
can have one of the three fountains named after them. They get
invited to Ambassador Rohatyn's for a seated lunch for $10,000. But
they do not get the state dinner at Trianon Palace with drinks
where Louis XV used to have strawberries and cream.''
</P>
<P>
   The fete begins June 23 in Paris with dinner at Baron Guy de
Rothschild's. (Yours for $50,000 and up.) Until then, Mrs. Hamilton
_ a warm, down-to-earth Texan who isn't the sort to turn to you and
sigh, ``tres amusant, n'est-ce pas?'' _ has been making the grand
tour among Francophile friends in places like Greenwich, Conn., and
West Palm Beach, Fla., a retinue of moneyed Mrs.-es _ Mrs. Winston
Guest, Mrs. Christopher Getty _ she calls ``the most extraordinary
people, generally quiet people, people of substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Over champagne, and often accompanied by Olivier, the Vicomte de
Rohan, who is president of Les Amis de Versailles, she'll talk
about the American connection to Versailles: of Benjamin Franklin
raising money to support the American Revolution, the 2 million
American visitors a year, the fact that, unlike Americans, the
French don't get tax credits for charity.
</P>
<P>
   The French government contributes about $47 million a year to
maintain the palace. Between 1975 and 1985, it spent $50 million to
restore the ground-floor rooms and paneling, bringing them back to
their 1789 appearance. But according to the Vicomte de Rohan, there
are no funds for reconstruction or ``anything that is a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The rescue was begun by a young American doughboy named John D.
Rockefeller Jr., who gave $130 million between 1923 and 1936 to
restore and stabilize what was then an abandoned chateau. Since
then, Versailles has been a magnet for American philanthropists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have nothing to lose and everything to gain,'' said
Mireille Johnston, a French writer and broadcaster on cultural
affairs. ``Versailles is a way for them to celebrate elegance and
power through objects, which is truly what they themselves are all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipient of rich Americans' current affection is the
Bosquet des Trois Fontaines _ the Grove of the Three Fountains _
which is considered a triumph of design and hydraulics, though it
is now an overgrown ruin neglected for 200 years. It epitomized
``La Gloire'' and the undiluted genius of its designer, Andre Le
Notre, who defined the French formal garden and, along with a
legion of ruinously expensive craftsmen, imposed geometric order on
nature's most fluid creations: water and trees.
</P>
<P>
   There were 15 bosquets tucked into Versailles' expansive gardens
_ hidden groves with concealed pools surrounded by thick woods.
They were created to please the senses, with clever water tricks
designed to amuse the king's courtiers. Here, writes Versailles'
chief architect today, Pierre-Andre Lablaude, in ``The Gardens of
Versailles'' (Editions Scala, 1998), Louis XIV sought to ``imprint
the image of himself as a demigod in a garden where all was his.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bosquet des Trois Fontaines, visible from the newly restored
portrait galleries in the north wing, is notable for its simplicity
and lack of architectural and sculptural decoration. It featured
three successive descending terraces with three pools, each a
different shape. Within each pool gushed a water jet in the form of
a spear, vault or spray. It is the only bosquet in whose design Le
Roi himself is believed to have had a hand. ``Was it the pencil or
the intention?'' Lablaude mused in a telephone interview. ``Nobody
knows. But it's the one bosquet where the King was very involved in
the conception.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The delivery of water to 2,000 fountains was a megalomaniac
effort that at one point involved a scheme (a failure) to reroute a
tributary of the Seine. In the end, Lablaude writes, water had to
be parsimoniously meted out by fountain controllers, who turned the
valves on when the king approached and off when he left, ``only to
be thrown into a panic when he sometimes took an unforeseen route,
either out of malice or by mistake.'' Today at Versailles a system
of small lakes and 175 miles of canals carry 8.3 million gallons of
water by gravity over 28,600 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other bosquets, the Trois Fontaines escaped zealous
redesign in the late 17th century by Francois Mansart, Le Notre's
nemesis, who, Lablaude said, wanted to see gardens eclipsed by
marble.
</P>
<P>
   When it was built, Versailles cost about 1 percent of the French
national budget. The restoration of the bosquet is a less expensive
affair. In 1990, a storm destroyed more than 1,500 trees, bringing
to public attention the deterioration of many parts of the garden
and prompting an ambitious 20-year program to restore the park. In
the late 1980's, with $6 million in public and private money, the
French government recreated the Bosquet d'Encelade (1675), a riot
of trellises, foliage benches and fountains decorated with gilded
shells.
</P>
<P>
   The bosquet, Lablaude said, will be restored ``using ancient
soldering techniques few artisans know today,'' including bronze
faucets and copper nozzles. Preliminary excavations have revealed
vestiges of original elements from the two upper pools as well as
the marble ramps built for Louis XIV's wheelchair. Suburban
development near the palace in the 1970's and 1980's resulted in
the destruction of the original hydraulics, which must now be
reconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The king never had enough water to exhaust his wishes,''
Lablaude said. ``And our biggest problem today is that there is not
enough water.''
</P>
<P>
   To Mrs. Hamilton, Versailles is a monument that, in spite of (or
perhaps because of) its excesses, belongs to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty inspires people,'' she said, wending her way down her
apartment's grand marble staircase, made by four French
stonemasons, leading to pedestaled marble figures depicting the
four seasons. ``It's about keeping up a level of the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hamilton, who is flirting with the idea of going into the
boiserie business and who started Sotheby's Midwest office in
Chicago, first visited France as a young woman on a grand tour.
</P>
<P>
   She has been personally inspired by Versailles: after living for
12 years in an apartment once owned by P.K. Wrigley, she and her
husband, who made his fortune in the food service and trucking
businesses, gutted the dark Tudor interiors evocative of Vincent
Price and completely redid the apartment to fit their collection of
18th-century French paneled rooms, down to the last centimeter,
finishing them off with parquet de Versailles on the floors. Their
dishwasher is paneled. The dining room was modeled on Mme. du
Barry's low-ceiling apartments on the top floor of the palace.
``She gave us the courage to do a room with low ceilings,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, neither Madame nor the king had computerized climate
controls, especially for paneling, that can be set to vacation
mode.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment, dressed in ancien regime silks, contains numerous
objects once owned by Consuelo Vanderbilt. She also once owned the
Hamiltons' chateau, which Winston Churchill frequently visited. (He
loved painting the tall pink-brick manse, its two towers surrounded
by a double moat.) At Versailles, she continued, ``the arts reached
its absolute height.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've enjoyed a lot of the French culture,'' she added, citing
wine, couture, pastry, perfumes and Impressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hamilton, 51, said she was prompted to crusade for the
bosquet, which is now consuming every waking moment, ``because
everyone always thinks `they' will do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you get to a certain age,'' she said, ``you realize
the `they' is you.''
</P>
<P>
   She is particularly excited about the black-tie state dinner in
the gallery of the Grand Trianon, where French horners will
announce dinner. ``It's going to be perfection,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The affair will recall the grand fetes of Louis XIV, who served
56-course dinners culminating in huge explosions of fireworks and
rockets outlining his monogram in the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   Like the king's pruners, Mrs. Hamilton's must now apply the
social shears. ``Darlin','' she said, turning to an assistant, ``we
need to get rid of the Z list.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
