<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
 
My loyalty can't be bought, but the lease is up for renewal 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One might assume that writing a beer column is just about the
greatest job in the galaxy; one would assume correctly. However,
it's not without its downside. For example, several people have
already voiced their concern about calories: ``Aren't you worried
about gaining weight?''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. I'm already a fat slob, so I don't care. What's
another 10 or 20 pounds?
</P>
<P>
   No, what really concerns me is this: Every week, I sample new
brews, and every week, I find new favorites. My former fierce
loyalty to two or three stalwarts has been shaken to its core, and
I wonder: Am I becoming a fickle foam fanatic?
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: A couple of weeks back, I sang the praises of
Paulaner, a longtime favorite, even going so far as to call it
Germany's finest, in my opinion. Darn good thing I added that
little caveat, because my fickleness is in full bloom.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of my treachery? A delightful little pilsner called
Warsteiner.
</P>
<P>
   Brewed by the Cramer family since 1753 in Warstein, Germany, it
bills itself as the top-selling beer in Germany, and from the first
sip, its distinctiveness seems to bear out its boast. Washing over
the tongue with a clean, refreshing and delicate balance of hops
and malt, Warsteiner finishes smoothly, with the perfect trace of
bitterness. As an aperitif, it stands boldly, but without the
overpowering rudeness of some better-known import lagers. As an
accompaniment to meals, Warsteiner's crystal-golden character
assumes complexity without sacrificing body or crispness.
</P>
<P>
   To my mind, this flexibility and all-around ease of use makes
Warsteiner the perfect brew for springtime backyard barbecues or
just loafing around (my personal favorite). I hereby give
Warsteiner the ``good sport'' award for beers and announce to all
that it's my New Best Friend.
</P>
<P>
   For this week, at least. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
