<HEADLINE>
NO FREE LUNCH, NOW NO FREE PARKING? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Va., N.Y., Pa., Ark.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The former New Yorkers were tanned and rested, but in revolt.
The city of Miami Beach was testing 20 new parking meters. ``Smart
meters,'' the city called them, proudly deploying them on busy
Washington Avenue. The former New Yorkers called them something
unprintable.
</P>
<P>
   That was because the meters had infrared eyes that let them
``see'' when a car pulled out of the space and reset the time on
the meter to zero, denying the next customer the beat-the-system
thrill of finding a few free minutes on the dial. To try to make up
for it, the city set the machines to allow a five-minute grace
period before a vehicle became, in the euphemistic jargon of the
meter readers, ``ticket eligible.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice try. John A. Todaro, who once lived in New York but is now
a parking superintendent in Miami Beach, was charged with fielding
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We explained that they were getting five minutes free,''
Todaro said, ``but they wanted somebody else's half-hour.''
</P>
<P>
   In part because of the uproar, the city removed the meters, but
the extra money they could generate is tempting for Miami Beach and
other municipalities. Just as the formerly indignant now find
themselves meekly following voice-mail directions, people may find
themselves dealing with such meters in cities across the country
within three to four years, authorities on parking say.
</P>
<P>
   Cities may prove willing to swallow a few months of criticism in
return for the windfall that would be produced by the meters that
taketh away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling people the only free parking will be on a Monopoly
board,'' said Kim E. Jackson, a director at the International
Parking Institute, a trade association in Fredericksburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   When the intelligent parking meters were tested at 50 spaces in
the Bronx and Queens about a year ago, they became notorious for
their unforgiving souls, or at least for their unforgiving
microchips.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City test, on Morris Park Avenue in the Bronx and
Steinway Street in Queens, lasted just three months before the
meters were pulled out in February 1998 as too unreliable. Still,
Richard Matarangelo, a former supervisor at the city's Department
of Transportation who helped coordinate the test, said the meters
were promising.
</P>
<P>
   The man to blame for this new nuisance is Vincent G. Yost, 46,
an inventor who said he had come up with the idea for smart meters
in 1994 when he was selling electronic cash registers and failed to
talk his way out of a ticket after a sales call in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the meter reader that it had just expired, and she said
she had no way of knowing that,'' Yost said. ``I thought, `Geez,
she's right. There must be a better way.'''
</P>
<P>
   So Yost, the president of Intelligent Devices of Harleysville,
Pa., came up with a meter that does not lie and does tattle. It
uses heat sensors, motion detectors and an infrared eye to sense
when a car moves, how long it has been parked and how many minutes
have ticked away after the metered time has expired.
</P>
<P>
   His ``better way'' has taken awhile. Yost's smart meter is in
its third version, and he admits that the first two prototypes did
not work very well. ``With the first generation,'' he said, ``you
could fool it by someone simply walking by.''
</P>
<P>
   Yost said he had solved the early mechanical problems and now
used ``slot-machine-quality'' parts. A smart meter costs about
$200, compared with about $150 for a regular meter. The company
says its studies show that the smart meter can increase parking
revenue by about 25 percent if the meter resets to zero when the
car leaves the parking space. That would create a large boon for
New York City, which has 71,872 meters that collected $70.9 million
in the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incarnation is so smart that it might be called the
Mensa meter. The window can display 10 symbols to convey
information about the vehicle that is parked there and the
condition of the meter itself. Maintenance workers would carry
hand-held computers that would allow local officials to chart
occupancy rates, the average parking time and other information
that used to be compiled by hired consultants. Eventually,
Intelligent Devices hopes to make meters that will send data
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1641EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7604 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PARKING-METERS-AR     04-21 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PARKING-METERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: data electronically.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several other meter makers are testing similar models, industry
officials say. POM Inc. of Russellville, Ark., built a prototype of
what it calls a ``self-zeroing meter,'' a model that sits in the
office of the company's president, Skeeter Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Bobra L. Wilbanks, POM's technical sales manager, said in a
telephone interview that cities were worried about complaints from
the public and about how to answer the challenges that might result
from tickets based on an electronic, rather than a human, eye.
</P>
<P>
   To make its technology seem friendlier, Intelligent Devices is
offering another feature. Because the meter knows when a car parks
or leaves, it can dispense free minutes _ typically five _ when the
car pulls in, giving the driver enough time to find change or get a
cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Doylestown, Pa., is using that feature for the 325 meters it
plans to begin installing this spring at a cost of $125,000, which
includes a year of service.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Eynon, who at 61 is the dean of the Doylestown
parking-meter enforcers, hears as many indignant excuses from
delinquent parkers as a state trooper hears from speeders. Whether
it is the woman who said she had forgotten the meter because she
had been in labor (that excuse worked), or the folks who said they
had been held up in court or had become caught up in a conversation
(those excuses did not), almost all the violators have one thing in
common: their emphatic assertion that the meter expired just
seconds ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must've just popped,'' they say over and over all day long,
and Mrs. Eynon has to play Carnac, trying to figure out just how
old the red ``Time Expired'' flag is. She hopes that the smart
meters will reduce the number of daily confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the potential public-relations drawbacks to the smart
meter, some cities _ including Doylestown _ are planning to disable
the return-to-zero time feature, allowing residents to continue
savoring the quiet thrill of the freeloader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's your right as an American,'' said John H. Davis,
the Doylestown borough manager. ``If you can scarf someone else's
meter time, God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   These cities say that they are willing to forgo added revenue
from the smart meter and that it is still useful to them. The smart
meter can be programmed to require that a car leave the parking
space before more money is accepted. Municipal officials say that
encourages people to shop in struggling downtowns because it forces
turnover at the meters instead of allowing one shopper _ or even a
store employee _ to hoard a parking space.
</P>
<P>
   For the determined scofflaw, the smart meters present less
violent possibilities than Paul Newman found in his 1967 role as
Lucas Jackson in ``Cool Hand Luke,'' when he went on a spree with a
pipe cutter, lopping off the heads of parking meters with the
succinct explanation, ``Small town, not much to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When several of Doylestown's meters stopped working during a
recent test, a trip to the street revealed the culprit _ gum in the
motion sensor. An Intelligent Devices technician applied an equally
low-tech solution: He scraped it off.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea being tested in several places is a meter that uses
a ``smart card'' sold at hotels and grocery stores. Some of POM's
smart-card meters have a feature called ``Refund-a-Card,'' which
allows parkers to put extra time back on their cards before pulling
away.
</P>
<P>
   With other meters, early departers are out of luck _ leaving a
few free minutes for any driver who might happen along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
