<SLUG> BC-ZIMERMAN-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIANIST KRYSTIAN ZIMERMAN PLAYS BY HIS OWN RULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Krystian Zimerman avoids plane travel, and he wouldn't dream of
playing the 100 or so concerts that other pianists perform each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never play more than 50 in one season,'' he says. ``And
that's on the edge for me. I should play more, but I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fort Worth has become one of the five or so essential
places on the continent where any touring pianist must appear,
Zimerman, 42, had never performed there. That changed this week,
when he performed on the Cliburn series at Bass Performance Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor has it that Zimerman happened to hear a Cliburn
Competition medalist refer to him in a TV interview as one of the
great pianists of our time, which made him amenable to being booked
on the Cliburn series.
</P>
<P>
   Zimerman, however, says that he worked Fort Worth into his
current North American tour _ in spite of travel difficulties _
because of his immense respect for Cliburn Foundation Executive
Director Richard Rodzinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Rodzinski is one of the most important people in
American concert life,'' Zimerman says. ``He's one of 30 or so
people who make American concert life what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimerman is traveling by car, accompanied by his personal piano
technician _ and his personal piano. Although most pianists play
whatever instrument is available, Zimerman insists that traveling
with one's own piano is sensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always take my own toothbrush when I travel, too,'' he says.
``It's not a question of whether the local pianos are good or bad,
but how much time you have to get used to one. A violinist takes
three months to get used to a new instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few top-echelon pianists _ such as Van Cliburn _ insist
on transporting a familiar piano to all concerts, even to the point
of shipping an instrument overseas by air. Although his technician
also travels with him, Zimerman does the final regulating and
voicing of the piano, using fluids and needles to fine-tune the
density of the felt hammers.
</P>
<P>
   Zimerman calls the Steinway grand that travels with him ``an old
friend,'' and says that it is particularly suited in tone and touch
for the music of Chopin and Schumann.
</P>
<P>
   The Chopin half of his Fort Worth program included the grand,
largely cheerful Scherzo No. 2, the Impromptu in F, the Fantaisie
in F minor and three Mazurkas. Polish-born Zimerman won
international fame when, as the youngest of 118 competitors, he
took first prize in the 1975 Chopin Competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling about Chopin is that he didn't write any bad
music,'' Zimerman says. ``He didn't destroy his bad music, like
some composers, because he didn't write any.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimerman admits that the current view of Schumann is somewhat
different _ and that the Sonata No. 1 is not always placed on the
list of that composer's undisputed masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played this piece about 15 years ago. I was never really
very happy about it, and had a feeling of not getting all I could
out of it. Now, I have 15 more years of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Those 15 years include the births of two children, who live with
him on his estate in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in keeping with his unusual, personalized view of what
a pianist's career should be, he has taken on piano students in a
special program at the Basle Academy. His dislike of travel
encouraged him to accept that job close to home, even though his
classes include pupils not of the top rank.
</P>
<P>
   The half-dozen pupils he accepts study an unusual curriculum
including acoustics, electronics and piano technology. They
recently assembled, from ready-made parts, three Steinway
keyboards, the better to learn the mechanics of the instrument.
Zimerman expects even the potential artists in the group to learn
how to tune a piano.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
