<HEADER>
A7639 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-APPLE-LOVE-ART-NY     04-21 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-APPLE-LOVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PC VS. IMAC: THE GRASS IS ALWAYS GREENER ACROSS THE DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm conflicted. The iMac is a sensation, with more than a
million units sold since its release last August. And like a lot of
former Mac users who had made the switch to a Windows 98 PC, I have
found myself drawn, even taunted by the iMac's cool esthetic.
</P>
<P>
   It has conjured up that old Apple magic for me, that
self-righteous promise of a better-built mousetrap that not only
compelled me to use Apple computers once but also prompted me to
move west and go to work for the company.
</P>
<P>
   I bought an iMac the day it went on sale and yet, as I revise
this article on a Windows 98 personal computer, I wonder if that
magic is enough to pull me back for good.
</P>
<P>
   I was bitten by the Apple bug early. I picked strawberries on a
farm as a 16-year-old to bankroll my first Apple, a IIe. But the
Macintosh was different. I decided after seeing the famous ``1984''
Macintosh commercial during the Super Bowl that I wanted a Mac, but
I couldn't afford one.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I was 20 and working as a computer trainer for the
Harrah's casino in Atlantic City. The Mac was a foreign language in
the casino business. I had read somewhere that Apple had given a
Mac to every new employee so I called the company and asked for a
job. I was invited to drop by if I was ever in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   I called my boss at the casino and asked if he wanted to buy my
new Compaq PC. He said yes, and that he would pay me on Monday.
Floating myself the cash, I wrote a technically bad check and took
the first flight out on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, I had landed a job in the information
services department at Apple. A few months later, I was introduced
to John Sculley, then the chairman of Apple. He had heard about my
enthusiasm for the Mac and my flight west. He was looking for a
technical assistant to teach him how to use the Mac and keep him
tuned in to exciting developments in the Mac world. My job was to
eat, sleep and breathe Macintosh. It was a dream job, and I stayed
with it for nearly four years.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere in there, I had got it into my head that I wanted
to be a novelist. So I quit Apple, and after a few false starts, I
followed the advice many successful novelists give to aspiring
authors: write what you know about. I started writing about Silicon
Valley. And I started going broke.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time Windows was really taking off. Tons of games
were being written for the PC, but not so many for the Mac. I faced
a difficult decision: PC or Mac? The PC won out, for purely
economic reasons. I reviewed PC games to pay the rent. I wrote PC
and video game strategy guides. At the same time, I wrote and
rewrote my novel.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a decade since I left Apple. My novel was published
recently and is getting fair reviews. I bought myself a new Sony
Vaio PC that ran Windows 98 and was decked out with the fastest
processor, tons of memory and a powerful 3-D card that makes the
latest games look great and run smoothly. This should be the
happiest time of my life.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not, and I blame the iMac. My attraction to the ``VW
Bug of computers'' is rooted in feelings of sensuality and
sentiment. As a computer, it could be frustrating, at least when it
first came out. With no floppy drive or Zip drive connection, I
couldn't easily transfer my few novels and other writings.
</P>
<P>
   With no viable all-in-one personal information manager, like
Microsoft's Outlook 98 for Windows, I couldn't easily move over my
e-mail, contacts, schedule and task and notes information that
Outlook handles so skillfully on my PC.
</P>
<P>
   Still, my new iMac looked great, and I was enormously pleased
with how Apple's operating system upgrade, System 8.5, smoothed the
appearance of the type on the screen. The Mac's windows are
prettier than Windows' windows.
</P>
<P>
   So I went ahead and laboriously sent myself all my files via
e-mail, figuring that I would survive with my Palm Pilot as my
personal information manager until the iMac could handle that
function (which took months). Furthermore, I couldn't use my
Hewlett-Packard Laserjet 6 printer; the only choices for iMac were
ink-jet printers, which are not ideal for printing 300-page
manuscripts. I mentioned to my friends that despite these
inconveniences, I was switching back to Mac. They called me crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Then something happened. Software and hardware makers started to
become excited about providing products for the iMac. Imation began
selling a Superdisk floppy drive that also doubles as back-up
storage because it handles both regular and high-density disks.
Iomega came out with a Zip drive that works with both PCs and
iMacs.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Computing began giving away a clever contact manager that
runs on Macs. Logitech released the Quickcam Pro, a digital video
camera that works with PCs and iMacs. Infowave started selling an
adapter that makes almost any PC printer work with the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Connectix's Virtual PC can, in a pinch, run Windows 98 on the
iMac so I can connect my Hewlett-Packard Jornada handheld computer,
which I use for writing and the Internet when I visit my family for
the weekend. But I missed my PCs wheel mouse: the iMac's mouse
turns into a slippery puck during pointing and clicking. Yet that
complaint was only a temporary one: Logitech has just started
offering a Universal Serial Bus wheel mouse for iMacs. All should
have been right in my iMac world.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't. I began to miss my PC. I missed the nearly
perfect Outlook 98; I even begged Microsoft to create a Mac
version. I missed being able to play the hottest games. I missed
the quicker response the PC with Windows always seems to have (my
Mac friends actually complain that ``it's too fast'').
</P>
<P>
   I especially missed the always handy right mouse button that
speeds up everyday tasks. And there is more for me to write about
in the PC world than the Mac world, and writing pays my rent.
</P>
<P>
   After 5 or 10 bouts of swapping the PC and iMac on my desk, I
finally settled on the PC. To resist the temptation of the iMac, I
gave it to a financially challenged friend who has been threatening
to write a novel of his own. It made perfect sense. He is new to
computers and carries none of the baggage _ emotional and practical
_ that I do. The iMac is perfect for him.
</P>
<P>
   I have moved past Macintosh in some very specific ways. (I read
recently that my former boss, Sculley, has himself become a PC
user.) Still, choice is good, and it's nice to see Apple making a
comeback, headed by the iMac's bright alternative to the accustomed
Windows view of the world. I should be at peace with my decision,
and I am. For now, anyway. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hutsko is a writer and computer consultant in New York. His
novel, ``The Deal'' (Forge, 1999), is available for Palm Pilot at
www.peanutpress.com. Macintosh users may scold him at
jhutsko(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
