<HEADER>
A7640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NC-FURNITURE-420&AMP;ADD-     04-21 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-FURNITURE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TREND'S A NONTREND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LIZ SEYMOUR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ If furniture follows fashion, then the
International Home Furnishings Market, which opened here last
Thursday and ends Friday, is a cashmere twin set: luxurious,
understated, pretty and comfortingly familiar.
</P>
<P>
   With some 75,000 visitors temporarily doubling the population of
this small Southern city, home to the world's largest furniture
market, there was plenty of excitement but not many surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``The furniture industry had its best year ever in 1998, and
shipments are still strong,'' said Jerry Epperson, an industry
analyst. ``Factories are running full out, hiring is a problem,
fabric mills are having trouble keeping up with orders, and lumber
supplies are tight. Everybody's getting better at making fewer new
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the market's 8 million square feet of showroom space,
exhibitors struggled to put labels on their wares but could only
come up with oxymorons to describe the nontrend trends. Bernhardt
Furniture Co. unveiled a line of popularly priced upholstered
furniture it called New Vintages. Other exhibitors touted ``casual
elegance,'' ``simple luxury'' and ``retro modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Eclecticism was in the air. Baker Furniture interposed new
pieces of Michael Vanderbyl's elegantly retro designs with
reproductions from the Historic Charleston Foundation. ``We're
embracing tradition and the historical without being traditional
and historic,'' said John Black, Baker's vice president of product
development. Similarly, Hickory Chair Co., which added everything
from bureaus to garden benches from Winterthur to its repertory of
reproductions, deliberately spanned ages and continents in room
settings that borrowed from all of its collections. Larry Laslo,
one of the first and best proponents of 1950s cocktail-culture
modern, redesigned the John Widdicomb showroom, covering furniture
from its Victoria &AMP; Albert Museum collection in leather and animal
patterns. Upstairs, his own designs were low and sleek and dressed
in basket-weave chenille.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a single trend that everyone could agree on, it was
toward luxury. Mitchell Gold added to his mid-priced Platinum
furniture collection, featuring goose-down cushions. Baker
showcased sofas upholstered in silk velvet, and elsewhere, mohair
(or, at Mitchell Gold, ``mohairesque'' acrylic), suede and wool
were much in evidence. After several years of blond wood, dark rich
finishes made a strong return. ``People are buying high-performance
cars,'' Gold said. ``Now they want high-performance furniture.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The most ubiquitous luxury was leather. Down a corridor
upholstered in cowhide, Lane Action showed off 17,000 square feet
of new sofas and chairs covered in everything from the cowhide to
embossed nubuck. Vanguard Furniture, a new licensee of Stetson,
showed boot-stitched embossed and quilted leather. MGM licensed
Classic Leather to make a Hollywood-inspired collection of Art Deco
sofas and chairs, and Baker showed its new Coach line of leather
furniture. Mulholland Brothers, a first-time exhibitor known for
its high-end luggage and accessories, offered a small collection of
handsome furniture upholstered in saddle leather.
</P>
<P>
   It was really a red meat kind of market _ from the 150-pound
bureau carved from solid Spam at Stanley Furniture's
75th-anniversary party to a triumvirate of buffed beefcake angels
in fluffy white wings who mingled with guests at Mitchell Gold's
10th-anniversary party. Lackawanna Leather, one of the industry's
major suppliers, celebrated its success with a charity auction of
celebrity-designed quilts, including a surprisingly kinky black
leather number from Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture buyers' appetites also seemed to include bigger
helpings. The trend toward gigantism in new suburban homes,
especially in master bedrooms, was reflected in Brobdingnagian
furniture: an 86-inch-tall armoire at Stanley, a 90-inch-tall
Victorian-style headboard at Hooker. Other manufacturers banked on
furniture that was unabashedly pretty. Mining popular European
country looks for inspiration, many new collections _ Lexington
Furniture's Southern Living Collection, Shermag's Orleans
Collection, Rue de Provence at Highland House, Coeur de France at
Century _ spoke a kind of Esperanto that combined elements of
French, English, Spanish and American design. Lexington headed
farther north to Sweden for Solgarden, an all-white collection that
was one of the prettiest of the market's introductions.
</P>
<P>
   With the baby-boom generation comfortably in its hip pocket, the
furniture industry began eyeing the next group of spenders, the
puzzling and notoriously hard-to-corral members of 19-to
33-year-old Generation X, just coming into their nesting years.
Broyhill introduced a cheap and cheerful line unambiguously named
GX, priced so that a bed, chest, dresser and mirror combination can
retail for under $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fast-food furniture,'' said Boyd Barnhardt, the director
of marketing. ``Everything is designed with efficiency and price in
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Catnapper, a mid-priced recliner company, was not quite
ready to let the baby boomers go. Demonstrating a $699 Naugahyde
chair that not only reclines but also gently lifts a sitter to his
or her feet, Don Hunter, Catnapper's vice president of
merchandising, saw a limitless future. ``With the graying of
America, we're looking ahead,'' he said. ``We think we've found a
market just waiting to be tapped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
