<P>
   CALIFORNIA-AD-BIAS. (For the Hollywood Reporter.) In an effort
to increase the advertising in media outlets that serve minorities,
FCC Chairman William Kennard and ad industry executives announced
voluntary guidelines to boost ad placements in minority media (300
words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-KOSOVO-DELEGATION. NATO's air war in Yugoslavia has not
brought the alliance closer to achieving its goals and the future
looks grim, according to Colorado's GOP congressmen, who have
access to top-secret intelligence from the Clinton administration.
(500 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT-KOSOVO-GEJDENSON. The leading Democrat on the House
International Relations Committee, Rep. Sam Gejdenson of
Connecticut, said he thought two Kosovo-related resolutions -- one
to formally declare war on Yugoslavia and another to pull out of
the NATO operations -- would be rejected. (400 to 500 words.) By
Laura Maggi
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-VISCLOSKY-CRIME. Rep. Pete Visclosky today asked
Congress for nearly $3 million to continue operation of the Lake
County High Intensity Drug Trafficking Area. (400 words.) By C.J.
Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-TAUZIN-DUKE. Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-Chackbay, is
expected to endorse former Louisiana Gov. David Treen for the
congressional seat vacated by House-Speaker designate Bob
Livingston. Tauzin, who has led the state delegation's efforts to
defeat candidate and ex-Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke, will detail
how he hopes to derail the Duke candidacy. (300 words.) By Mark
Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SNOWE-KOSOVO. President Clinton asked Congress for $6
billion to fight the war in the Balkans on Monday, but failed to
provide a blueprint for ending the conflict, an apparent violation
of a law written last year by U.S. Sen. Olympia J. Snowe. (500
words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-CONYERS-GAO. Rep. John Conyers and other members of
Congress today called on the General Accounting Office to examine
federal health data to see if low-income communities and
communities of color are suffering disproportionately from
environmental hazards. (400 words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-MENDOZA. Rep. Steve Rothman hosts a meeting of
Ecuador's deputy chief of consulate and the family of Mickey
Mendoza, the 14-year-old from Saddle Brook who was killed under
confusing circumstances April 11 in Ecuador. By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-AUDIT. Pennsylvanians are more likely to be audited
by the IRS than any other state in the region, based on last year's
audit rates. Experts talk about why. (650 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-BANKRUPTCY-BALDWIN. Madison Democrat Tammy Baldwin
passed two amendments through the House Judiciary Committee
Wednesday that will protect employees from losing their benefits
from 401(k) plans and similar saving plans if their employer goes
bankrupt. The amendments were created in response to a court battle
that resulted when several employees from former Louis Allis Co. in
Milwaukee lost their benefits when the company went bankrupt last
year. (400 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
