<HEADER>
A7674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLOWS-GARDEN-NYT &LR;      04-21 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLOWS-GARDEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DOCTORS REVIVE A DESERT GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By JIM ROBBINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM SPRINGS, Calif. _ A Mediterranean-style mansion called the
Willows, tucked into the flank of Mount San Jacinto here, was best
known in the 1950s as the home of Marion Davies, an actress famous
as the mistress of newspaper magnate William Randolph Hearst.
Before that it was known as the place where Clark Gable and Carole
Lombard stayed on their honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the best reason to know the Willows is that it was
bought shortly after it was built in 1927 by Samuel Untermeyer, a
New York civil rights lawyer and passionate horticulturist.
(Untermeyer gave the Untermeyer Fountain with three maidens to
Central Park's Conservatory Garden.)
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer, who died in 1940, had sought the California desert
for his respiratory health. At the Willows, two hours from Los
Angeles, he doted on his massive multilevel garden, decked with the
willow trees that gave his home its name. Untermeyer's guests here
included Gable and Lombard; New York City Mayor Jimmy Walker and
Albert Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   Former Palm Springs Mayor Frank Bogert remembers chatting with
Einstein. ``He was a wonderful little guy,'' said Bogert, 89. ``He
could explain his theory of relativity to a dummy like me, in a
language I could understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Between its glamorous past and the 1970s, the home fell into a
bizarre state of disrepair. Its mahogany trim was painted pink and
blue. There was shag carpeting on the floors. A Budweiser sign hung
in the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was devastated,'' said Dr. Tracy Conrad, 36, an
emergency room doctor from Los Angeles who, with her business
partner, Dr. Paul Marut, another emergency room doctor, bought the
house in 1994, restored it and turned it into the Willows Bed and
Breakfast. ``We wanted to save it. Thank God there are people who
don't know what they're getting into, or these projects would never
get done.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost was $1 million, and by 1996, enough restoration was
completed to begin receiving guests. At the end of last year, a
$50,000 garden restoration was completed. This will be the first
spring for the new old garden, designed to flourish in the intense
summer heat on the flank of the mountain behind the Willows.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer amassed a fortune early in life. He also owned
Greystone Manor, a sprawling mansion in Yonkers, N.Y., where he had
60 greenhouses and 12 gardeners and grew 3,000 varieties of
orchids. When Untermeyer was staying at the Willows, he had orchids
sent to him from Yonkers once a week. Dr. Conrad honors that legacy
with an orchid in a small pot next to the beds.
</P>
<P>
   Untermeyer was responsible for terracing the garden into the
mountain, with a series of paths and steps made from granite. The
steps weave through groves of palm trees, sharp-spined cactus, and
lemon, orange and tangelo trees heavy with fruit. Most important to
Dr. Conrad was restoring the willow groves around the house with
native species, like curly willow. She sought advice from an expert
in London, who responded with a three-page, hand-written letter.
</P>
<P>
   This month, with the garden in bloom, hummingbirds hover around
the deep red bougainvillea, the lavender verbena, the yellow
flowers of the brittle brush and wild pink sweet peas. Benches and
tables offer breathtaking views of the Coachella Valley beyond. The
garden centerpiece is a 50-foot artificial waterfall, made from
tons of rock. Water is pumped to a pool at the top of the garden
and spills to a another pool 50 feet below, on the patio next to
the dining room. The cascade functions as a cooler as it mists the
home during blast-furnace summers.
</P>
<P>
   The house itself was built to withstand the heat. ``It's a house
within a house,'' Dr. Conrad said. Cement walls more than three
feet thick have a space inside that acts as insulation. The front
porch has been fitted with towering canvas curtains that can be
closed against the desert sun.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight guest rooms, which cost from $250 to $500 a
night. All have been tastefully redone, and some, like the Einstein
Garden Room, are named after former guests or owners. In the '50s,
Marion Davies owned not just the Willows but also the nearby Desert
Inn. Legend has it that she tore the kitchen out of the Willows,
put in a bar and had all her meals sent over from the inn. Today,
the Marion Davies Room has a balcony with a view of a Chinese
orchid tree. ``I picture her walking around in a pink satin gown
with a martini,'' Dr. Conrad said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock Room, downstairs, has a bathroom that includes a large
chunk of gray and white granite protruding from the mountain. (It
once was Untermeyer's two-room wine cellar.) The Library Room, with
its carved cherry wood fireplace, was where Lombard and Gable
stayed.
</P>
<P>
   The red oak floor in the living room, a public area, has been
refinished along with the sandstone fireplace. The wrought-iron
chandelier is original. The home, listed by the State of California
as a historic site, is one of the 10 oldest in Palm Springs, built
long before the city became a testing ground for Modernist
architecture. The Willows once sat on four acres of ground, which
included a grove of citrus trees. In 1967, much of the land was
sold to create the Desert Museum, which now has a Rodin exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The restored garden, Dr. Conrad said, is pleasing her during its
first spring. Samuel Untermeyer's great-granddaughter, Pamela
Street, remembers the Willows from childhood visits from
Connecticut in the 1960s. She revisited the home in the late '70s,
after it had been sold and carpeted in shag. She returned recently,
after the Conrad-Marut renovation, and burst into tears. ``It was
just like it had been,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
