<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBERATOR-VILLAGE-TEX     04-21 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERATOR-VILLAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IN LIBERATOR VILLAGE UNITED BOMBER-PLANT WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE SETTLEMENT, Texas _ The aircraft from Lockheed Martin
ascend abruptly now, but in 1943, lumbering B-24 Liberators
struggled low over the rooftops of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The strain of the engines was a common sound to the thousands of
people who lived directly below. They were the people who built the
planes, the people of Liberator Village, a community of 6,000
housed in 1,500 government-built apartments named for the famed
World War II bomber.
</P>
<P>
   Liberator Village was never an official township, never
incorporated, never a part of Fort Worth. It was simply a
collection of working families bound by the common causes of making
a living and supporting the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   The village was governed by a ``community council,'' and there
was an energetic spirit of patriotism. It was nearly idyllic for
the older residents who had suffered through Depression years _ a
job and a home, closely connected. For the children, it was bliss:
an endless supply of playmates on a giant neighborhood playground
that seemingly never closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 12 when we moved here and my parents went to work at the
defense plant,'' said Rex Scott, a former mayor of White
Settlement. ``It was like a large extended family. We all had
almost the same things in common, and that was to make things as
good for people in the military service as possible. ... No one was
rich, no one was real poor. We were all the same, blue-collar sort
of families.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberator Village is nearly gone now. There is one remaining
building, tucked inconspicuously off Cherry Lane at Wyatt. The
white tile structure was once a residence for several families; now
it houses the offices of a suburban newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might have been 100 people living around here prior to
the Village, a few farmhouses,'' Scott said. ``White Settlement
would never have developed the way it did without Liberator
Village. It increased the growth of White Settlement and of Fort
Worth dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The intersection of Cherry Lane and White Settlement Road was
the epicenter of Liberator Village when it opened in February 1943.
The Village was hailed as a great improvement for workers at
Consolidated Aircraft Corp., better known as ``the bomber plant.''
</P>
<P>
   The plant opened in April 1942. It was an enormous magnet for
workers who had struggled through pre-war hard times and were now
encouraged with Consolidated's comparatively lucrative pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   The work force was abundant, but not the housing. As the
government helped finance the building of the plant, it financed
the living accommodations as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three sections, 500 units each,'' said Jim Weaver,
who moved to Liberator Village in 1944. ``The first section was
built with white asbestos siding and pier-and-beam foundations. The
second section was the same only on slab foundations. They were
called `The Whites.' The third addition was built with red tiles
and called `The Bricks.'''
</P>
<P>
   They were four-plexes, small, but not unusually tiny for the
times. Rent was $34 for a one-bedroom, $38 for two bedrooms, $42
for three bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved to Liberator Village from Itasca,'' Weaver said.
``Dad was working for the cotton mills for 35 cents an hour. He
came to Consolidated and doubled his pay to 70 cents an hour. Our
apartment at the Village was the first indoor plumbing I had ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the families moving to the Village were like the
Weavers. West Texans, hungry for jobs, came to the Village in large
numbers. Some already worked at the bomber plant but were driving
several miles in the darkness of early morning and late night. Time
away from their families.
</P>
<P>
   The ``town hall'' of the Village was actually the recreation
center, a long, gray, 1-story building that housed nearly all the
clubs and associations within the complex. It was there that church
services were held, as well as ping-pong matches and airplane club
meetings, home nursing classes, sewing classes, dance classes and
Bible studies.
</P>
<P>
   Life revolved around work at the bomber plant. While one shift
was working, the other two were sleeping or at play.
</P>
<P>
   There were few problems, at least during the war years. In 1948,
the Snack Shack burned to the ground when the Liberator Village
Fire Department refused to answer the call. It turned out the Fire
Department could not legally respond to any call ``not involving or
threatening the $4 million government housing facility.'' The Snack
Shack was privately owned and just off government property.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of 1949 lapped at the streets of Liberator Village but
didn't damage the community. A nearby trailer park, however, was
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, federal authorities decided that they would begin
selling off the Village. The ``Whites,'' the frame structures, were
demolished, and the 500 tile buildings were the only ones left. In
1956, a developer bought the land to build brick homes. Those homes
remain, but recollections of the village are nearly exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   By 1963, Liberator Village was completely gone, save the one
remaining building.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated became Convair, then General Dynamics and
eventually Lockheed. The B-24 Liberator gave way to the B-36, the
F-111 and the F-16. With each transition, the community was
altered. Transportation improved; people moved away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of fond memories surrounding Liberator
Village,'' Scott said. ``You couldn't do anything like that today.
Everybody knows so much more about one another now. They don't take
people at face value anymore. Times have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CAPSULES-ART-2NDT     04-21 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CAPSULES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: apple peeler.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been attempts throughout time capsule history to
think through the problem of the unintelligible message, like one
included on a medium that requires an obsolete device to ``read''
it (a book displays itself, but a CD-ROM must be ``opened'' with a
separate device).
</P>
<P>
   The International Time Capsule Society maintains the Crypt of
Civilization, a swimming-pool-size vault sealed in 1940 that has
been described as ``a kind of Noah's Ark of Depression-era
knowledge and technology''; it will not be opened until 8113. That
year was chosen because the people who created the crypt decided
that 1940 was the midpoint between the start of time and 8113,
although now it is not at all clear whether their calculations hold
up.
</P>
<P>
   The crypt includes, among many other things, 640,000 pages of
microfilmed material and, crucially, a film reader with a
wind-powered generator. The crypt's planners left little to chance:
the first item encountered upon entering the crypt is a device
designed to teach English to its finders.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Voyager spacecraft contained a kind of time
capsule intended for extraterrestrials: a 12-inch gold-plated
phonograph record carrying sounds and images selected to portray
the diversity of life and culture on Earth. Each record is encased
in a protective aluminum jacket along with a cartridge and a
needle. Instructions, in symbolic language, indicate how the record
is to be played.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is making plans for a Times Capsule to
complement a 1999 series of six special Times Magazine issues
inspired by the millennium change. Jack Rosenthal, editor in chief
of the Times Magazine, said the paper was considering a method of
including data in its capsule (to be deposited for 1,000 years at a
still undecided spot in Manhattan) that uses a new technology known
as HD-Rosetta. It can etch data microscopically, using a
charged-particle beam, on a nickel disk that can be read with a
microscope. More than 90,000 8-by-11-inch text pages can be stored
on one 2-inch disk.
</P>
<P>
   Children's University, a private elementary school in Arlington,
Texas, is planning a time capsule to include a school scrapbook and
items selected by the children. Lynn Kenner, the school's director,
said that when it came to messages, the students insisted that
their words be put on computer diskettes. ``We suggested paper, but
the kids wanted the space to really say a lot,'' she said, ``and
they also appear to feel that computers are the way to communicate
with the future.'' The school's capsule will be buried for just 12
years.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term capsules do appear to be growing in popularity. Chris
Chance, managing director of Future Archaeology
(www.futurearchaeology.com), a capsule manufacturer that has sold
nearly 4,000 capsules this year _ up fourfold from last year _ said
many of his customers were planning to open their capsules in a
mere 10 to 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Benford did not approve. ``Where is the sense of awe in that?''
he said. ``You might as well just send it to yourself through the
mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff McCarty argues that burial is passe. He is founder and
president of Original Time Capsule Co., in Greenfield, Ind., which
plans to sell $20 ``personal capsules'' in card stores. It offers
capsule kits to commemorate personal events like graduations and
births.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't relate to anything longer than a human
lifetime,'' McCarty said. ``The trend is that people want to open
up their own capsules. That's what I'm planning for a capsule I
created last year for my wedding. I'm going to open it in 10
years.'' He included a cellular phone in his capsule because ``it's
something I use a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The new preference for shallow time capsules may in itself
reflect our technological obsessions, said Alexander Rose,
executive director of the Long Now Foundation (www.longnow.org), a
group in San Francisco that among other things is trying to spur
opinion-makers to embrace longer-term perspectives by building a
10,000-year clock. ``Short-term capsules are a reaction to
technology,'' Rose said. ``They're saying you can't look beyond 5
to 30 years because that's our technological cycle, the life cycle
of our devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Shallow time capsules do sidestep a basic conundrum: It has been
estimated that for every thousand or so capsules that are buried,
only one is found. The International Time Capsule Society even
maintains a list of Most Wanted capsules, prominent examples that
have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   McCarty said there might be a happy medium between the shallow
and the deep that also solved the problem of technological
obsolescence: ``perpetual'' capsules that are opened at regular
intervals. He is involved in an effort to create what he calls
``the first fully electronic capsule'' as part of the Times Square
2000 event. It will include messages from high school students
throughout the nation and other information using digital
videodisks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're considering a plan to open it every 25 years and migrate
the information inside to new technology,'' he said. ``Think about
it: we all put our 8-millimeter home movies on VHS, and it was no
big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   To think in short windows, some people say, undercuts the value
of time capsules. Messages left unintentionally, like the remains
of Pompeii, tend to have far more import than those handpicked by
people, Benford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the truths about capsules,'' added Ms. O'Connell, the
documentary filmmaker, ``is that they are as much for the here and
now as they are for the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
