<HEADER>
A7735 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SPIDERS-WEB-NYT &LR;      04-21 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SPIDERS-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE BETTER TO FIND OUT ABOUT SPIDERS THAN ON THE WEB? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spiders belong on the Web, and not just to make a bad pun. They
are interesting, colorful and far more useful than harmful to
humans. Unfortunately, Internet menus are cluttered with listings
for ``Web spiders,'' a term for wide-ranging search programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the American Museum of Natural History in New
York has greatly expanded its online offerings, especially in
conjunction with its new Hall of Biodiversity. In cooperation with
Discovery Channel Online, the museum has created a spider page that
focuses on a recent expedition to Western Australia
(www.discovery.com/exp/spiders/spiders.html).
</P>
<P>
   In Spider Fact of the Day, one can find tidbits like E.B.
White's inspiration for his immortal Charlotte _ Araneus cavaticus,
the orb-weaving barn spider. The site mentions an estimate by
William Bristowe, a British arachnologist, that the total weight of
insects devoured each year by British spiders is greater than the
weight of all British subjects. (The site does not say whether
British cooking reduces the human biomass.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In Your Own Backyard'' describes and illustrates spider
families. ``Name That Spider'' prints some of the 4,000 contest
letters children wrote about spiders. The winner, Jeremy Falling of
Manchester, N.H., is having a spider named after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up Close'' lets viewers identify magnified spider parts. There
are comments on what the world would be like without spiders
(overrun with insects and disease, and devoid of most plants we
eat).
</P>
<P>
   For students wishing harder science, the museum details the
Australian mission at http://research.amnh.org/entomology/spiders.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kefyn M. Catley, a native of Wales who helped create the
online spider pages, is a former professional flutist who changed
his career to zoology. In a recent interview at the museum, he
recalled the boyhood bug stage he never outgrew, looking under the
eaves long ago and wondering how a spider could build her web at
night, and why she did not get stuck herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not a hard sell,'' Catley said of spiders. ``Everybody
on this planet has at least one story to tell.'' They do get a bad
press, he admitted. ``People have this vision about how spiders
went out to wreak havoc on mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he said, you are 11 times more likely to be killed by
a bee or wasp, and 20 times more likely to die from lightning.
Spiders are at least 360 million years old, and are the dominant
predators on Earth, he said. ``People should think of them not just
as allies, but as absolutely necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Tarantula Society (http://torgo.cnchost.com/ats/),
in Carlsbad, N.M., calls itself the largest arachnid society in the
world, and it offers one-stop surfing for students, teachers,
breeders, collectors and lovers of T-shirts with larger-than-life
tarantulas on them.
</P>
<P>
   The society holds an annual conference in June, and publishes an
arachnid magazine, Forum, six times a year. (Forum's letters page
is called the Eggsac.) On-line articles include ``How Bad
Information Invades Kids' Books,'' in which the author laments the
``icky spider mindset'' in children's literature.
</P>
<P>
   Through the society, one can buy Texas tan and other tarantulas.
The online shop sells books including ``The Tarantula Keeper's
Guide.'' The conditions needed to keep one species alive often will
kill another species, the experts warn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that the Internet has been responsible for a flurry of
interest in tarantulas as pets,'' Doug Martin, Webmaster of the
society's page, wrote by e-mail. ``People from across the world are
able to sell, breed and trade spiders as never before. This has
resulted in a vast number of species being available to the public
as opposed to one or two when I started out in the hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's own site, Doug's Tarantula Page
(http://www.geocities.com/Petsburgh/Farm/3173) is oriented toward
the novice keeper. One link is to a bulletin board for buyers and
sellers, a kind of arachnid stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But before even thinking about it, Martin cautions, buy a book
on responsible pet-keeping, check with an experienced owner and
learn about state and postal regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
