A7746 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSA     04-21 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TEENSTALK-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT GUYS, SUICIDE 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I'm having a hard time with this guy I like. He
claims to like me a lot, and we used to have fun hanging together.
But recently he says he doesn't have time for me. I have paged and
called him and he never calls me back. He plays football, and it is
very time-consuming. Should I move on? _ Football.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Football: You have tried in every way to get messages to
him and let him know that you are still interested. He has not
returned the messages, so it's time for you to move on. You can try
to talk to him, but the signs are clear that he is moving on. You
deserve to have a guy who has an interest in you and time for you.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: My best friend recently committed suicide. No
one ever expected it. He was very religious and always happy. He
had a girlfriend and their relationship was going great. One
morning, his parents found him _ he hanged himself. Everyone was
confused as to why he did it. His parents are torn up and the kids
at school don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   The school has called in counselors, and they are talking to
students. I just can't seem to stop thinking about him. I really
wish he had talked to me or someone else about his problems, or
left a note. I feel hollow. I don't want to go to his funeral. I
really don't know what to say to his family. Help.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Help: There are not always going to be signs that someone
close to you is upset or thinking of suicide. Like your friend,
some people decide that their problems are too large to handle and
their only solution is suicide.
</P>
<P>
   They often give no warning. There are no direct signs that
indicate that a person is contemplating suicide. Indirect signs may
be hopelessness, talking about death, no planning for the future,
not eating, not sleeping, inability to complete daily functions and
tasks, and no interest in family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like your friend left no clues to his depression. You
are feeling left out of his thoughts and want answers to his
depression. You are hurt and upset that your friend did not write a
note or talk to you. Your friend chose not to disclose his
depression. You cannot feel guilty; you need to grieve your friend
and accept his choice. You should try to attend the funeral and
talk to his family to share your grief and to get closure to his
death.
</P>
<P>
   You need to talk to a counselor. Later, you can talk to your
friend's parents. Presently, though, you need to work on your
feelings. Your grief is a natural process. You could attend group
counseling _ a group of people who share the same grief. Cherish
the times and memories you had with your friend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts Teenstalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior college _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: Teenstalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
