<SLUG> BC-KIDS:TRENDS:WEIRD-STUFF-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENDS: WEIRD, FUN STUFF TO COLLECT 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By KELLY DEGARMO 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONEY, I SHRANK THE SKATEBOARD!
</P>
<P>
   Ya don't have to be an awesome skater to perform a 360 with one
of these boards.
</P>
<P>
   Developed by a 12-year-old California youth, Tech Deck
fingerboards rock like real skateboards. They contain grip tape,
metal axles, adjustable trucks, removable axle nuts, replaceable
wheels and tiny skate tools.
</P>
<P>
   But the coolest part about them is the graphics. They come in
rowdy color schemes, licensed by the top makers of full-size
boards.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the company expects to sell 12 million of them in
1999. Priced at under $9 each, they slip right into the pocket,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Tech Deck fingerboards are hot sellers at Gadzooks, Fast
Forward, Miller's Outpost and other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   A FASHION MYSTERY REVEALED
</P>
<P>
   FUBU stands for ``For us, by us!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers see our pictures and can relate, whereas they
couldn't relate to some 45-year-old man living in Italy,'' said
FUBU co-founder Daymond John. ``We are just like them. We are the
consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   FUBU and its designers are being recognized for their fashion
success by ``Essence'' magazine. The company's founders are Daymond
John, Carl Brown, Keith Perrin and J. Alexander Martin, all guys
from Queens, N.Y., reports the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   They will receive their awards on April 30. The ceremony will be
taped and televised by the Fox network in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   For more scoop, check out www.Fubu.com.
</P>
<P>
   SATCHEL SAVVY
</P>
<P>
   The latest backpack resembles something the letter carrier might
wear. Yes, the ``messenger'' bag wins the title for the coolest
carry-all on the fashionable east and west coasts. With a sturdy,
wide strap, the unisex bag is designed to wear over one shoulder
and across the chest. Look for canvas, leather and plastic styles
by Gap, Dickies, Old Navy and other manufacturers ($16 and up).
</P>
<P>
   BOXERS 2000
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder about the future of underwear? Joe Boxer does. Check
out the ``E-Mail Zipper Boxer,'' one of several millennium
underwear predictions from Joe Boxer founder Nicholas Graham.
</P>
<P>
   James Bond, look out!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
