<HEADER>
A7749 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS:COVER:EARTH-DAY-     04-21 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS:COVER:EARTH-DAY-art-CLASSACTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVER: TAKING CARE OF MOTHER EARTH 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Includes one color slide of Brooke Gunnels (center), holding a
butterfly as her classmates look on. (Credit: Photo by Ron T Ennis.
Courtesy of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.) 
 By JESSAMY BROWN 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earth Day is officially celebrated on April 22, this Thursday.
But that doesn't mean students limit themselves protecting the
Earth to just one day.
</P>
<P>
   Conserving the environment is an ongoing project that requires
effort and action. At one elementary school, prekindergarten
students are learning that taking care of the Earth means taking
care of their own rooms, homes, playgrounds and schools. Tomorrow,
the 4-year-olds will join fourth-graders in planting begonia
flowers outside the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody does a little bit, then it makes a big
difference. If people didn't care about the Earth now, 30 years
from now we'll have trash everywhere,'' said teacher Kristin Hood.
``It just helps the students become aware of their surroundings.
They will want to take care of their surroundings if they're taught
early enough. It's an important concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ways students are working to help the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Earth Alert group at one junior high has been monitoring the
health of two local streams since 1992. Students inspect the water,
conduct tests and take temperature readings and report results to
the Trinity River Authority, a government agency.
</P>
<P>
   On one trip, students noticed an oil slick on the stream water.
They reported the problem, which was traced to a resident who was
later fined for harming the environment, group co-sponsor Cynthia
Gladden said.
</P>
<P>
   At another elementary school, students are glad that trees on
the campus lawn will be planted again this spring, said
fifth-grader Miranda Langlet. Last summer, five trees that students
planted were pulled up by vandals. The trees died in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, school organizations raised money for
landscaping the school's front and to provide badly needed shade in
back. After the vandalism, local companies offered to replace the
trees.
</P>
<P>
   One school's third-graders are using _ and preserving _ their
16-acre campus for ecological activities. They've planted a garden,
trees, and built wood boxes to attract birds (30 species live on
campus). Kids even hopped into a canoe to collect trash out of a
pond, says admissions director Martha Vandeveerdonk.
</P>
<P>
   A group of sixth-graders will be weeding flower beds, replacing
blooms and scrubbing outdoor walls and picnic tables to remove
graffiti in an effort to help students take pride in their campus,
said science teacher Penny Suazo.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Earth Day activities around the world,
check out these Web sites:
</P>
<P>
   For a wide range of Earth Day information, try The Wilderness
Society's site at www.earthday.wilderness.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Heartland All Species Project site offers ideas on how to
celebrate Earth Day in your neighborhood. Site:
www.allspecies.org//block.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
