<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     04-21 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING A WAKE-UP CALL ON THE ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ So I'm headed toward that city to the east
of here and all of a sudden God speaks to me from a black
billboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What part of `Thou Shalt Not' didn't you understand?'' he
wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 70 miles per hour, it's the sort of to-the-point query
you grasp right away. But not believing my eyes, I slow to around
50 and turn in the direction of my heart.
</P>
<P>
   I think of the Ten Commandments: Thou shalt not bear false
witness; thou shalt not kill; thou shalt not covet anything that is
thy neighbor's. I wonder which of them I've kept, which of them I
haven't.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the highway, closer to Dallas, God speaks to me
again: ``You think it's hot here?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm thinking I'm either dead or the end is near and
he's warning me. Just for reassurance, I ask my daughters, Jamila
and Asha, if they see the sign. Does it say something about making
rush hour longer if we use his name in vain?
</P>
<P>
   They say it does. I breathe a little easier, thinking this is
some sort of sick joke.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I found a news story that explains my highway
experience. It seems those billboards have been springing up for a
month in more than 100 places in Dallas and Tarrant counties,
compliments of a wealthy individual who believes that Americans
have lost their moral bearings.
</P>
<P>
   The financier has insisted on anonymity. But Andy Smith, the man
behind the advertising agency that created the ``God Speaks''
signs, was quoted as saying: ``Our society these days is a mess of
murder, rape and adultery. God gave us rules, and it is his rules
we need to live by.''
</P>
<P>
   The story went on to say that response to the black-and-white
signs _ meant to get people thinking about God during the day _ has
been so positive that billboard companies nationwide have agreed to
donate millions of dollars' worth of space.
</P>
<P>
   And because Americans are considered the most devout population
in the industrialized world, according to a Gallup poll, it's only
natural that they'd want to spread this good news around.
</P>
<P>
   But I was struck by the rest of the Gallup findings. The poll
found that more than 70 percent of Americans are members of a
church or synagogue, and 40 percent attend regularly. Sixty percent
believe that religion can solve the vast majority of today's social
problems.
</P>
<P>
   So why do we need billboards to get us thinking about God?
Better yet, why is society in such a mess if we love the church so
much?
</P>
<P>
   Because attending church won't change society. It won't even
change us. Read those numbers again and consider our moral state.
</P>
<P>
   In the book of Luke, Christ said, ``No one can become my
disciple unless he first sits down and counts his blessings _ and
then renounces them all for me.''
</P>
<P>
   That tells me that I've got to be willing to give up something
to draw nearer to a holy God. I have to give up lying and cheating
and backbiting and hatred. It means I've got to be willing to give
up something big for something good.
</P>
<P>
   It ought to be said here that the organizers of the ``God
Speaks'' campaign are offering nondenominational messages. They
believe these messages should have meaning to anyone who believes
in a Supreme Being.
</P>
<P>
   I was certainly moved when I saw them. Ask my daughters. But
God's word is more than a string of stark white letters to get us
thinking about him. Allowed to penetrate our hearts, they change
who we are, and so how we treat one another.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
