<P>
   COMPAQ-EARNINGS _ AUSTIN _ Compaq Computer Corp. reported a $281
million first-quarter profit today that met its own recently
diminished forecast, hurt by stiff price competition and slow sales
of its most profitable business computers. (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS _ Coca-Cola, which is holding its annual
shareholders meeting in Delaware today, reported a 13 percent drop
in first-quarter earnings as the soft drink maker continued to
suffer from a slowdown in some of its key markets. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MEAD-EARNINGS _ Mead Corporation said Wednesday it earned $22.9
million, or 22 cents per share, in the first quarter, down from
$30.6 million or 29 cents per share in the same period in 1998. Net
sales for the first quarter of 1999 were $863.2 million, up 3
percent from $839.0 million in 1998, primarily due to unit growth.
(Dillon, Dayton Daily News). 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   NCR-EARNINGS _ NCR Corp. said Wednesday it earned $3.3 million,
or $0.03 per diluted share, for the first quarter ended March 31,
compared with breakeven in the year ago period. Operating income
improved $26 million from a loss of $34 million a year ago. The
results exceeded consensus analyst expectations. (Townsend, Dayton
Daily News). 9.
</P>
<P>
   REYNOLDS-EARNINGS _ Reynolds and Reynolds expected to release
solid second-quarter earnings. Might announce some sort of
acquisition, too. (Bischoff, Dayton Daily News). 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   PBP-SUNBEAM _ Sunbeam finally gets around to releasing its
fourth quarter and 1998 numbers. The reason for the delay: all the
digits they had to write in to show the losses, $897,000,000 for
the year. The company blamed the loss on ``unusual'' costs such as
lawsuits, Y2K preparedness and payments to fired executives.
(Sedore, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ Sex is bad for business. So says Fortune (May 10) in a
cover story on the variety of problems U.S. corporations are
dealing with from sexual harassment to cybersex on company time to
expense account abuse. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
