<HEADER>
A7777 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX     04-21 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``People Behind the Peace''
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald A. Wells
</P>
<P>
   Eerdmans, $13
</P>
<P>
   When looking at ``The Troubles'' of Northern Ireland at one
point, writes Ronald A. Wells, ``it seemed like nonsense (to some)
to say, `Religion has failed; give us more religion.' Christians,
for their part, agreed, or should have done so. Indeed, many
Christians should have said something more like `Religion has
failed; give us Christianity.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``People Behind the Peace'' is Wells' sketch of three
residential communities seeking to embody the Christian idea of
``Blessed are the peacemakers'' in a region struggling with a
year-old peace plan. The Calvin College history professor also
provides an overview of Ireland's history and a discussion of the
concept of forgiveness in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Wells does not see forgiveness and reconciliation as easy (or as
the same thing), and although he is probably more ecumenically
minded than many readers, he is aware of the problems there, too.
Still, ``People Behind the Peace'' provides an encouraging glimpse
of people truly seeking to bring about accord in a region that
needs it badly. _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Revival
</P>
<P>
   Various artists
</P>
<P>
   Vineyard Music
</P>
<P>
   Revival is subtitled ``10 Songs From England, Brownsville,
Toronto and the World.'' It just as easily could have been called
``the soundtrack of the charismatic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   A resurgence of revivals in Toronto, the Brownsville Assembly of
God in Pensacola, Fla., and at other churches has given birth to
some wonderful praise and worship tunes. These songs are in common
usage in contemporary music churches that might even disagree with
the nature of true revival.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the best are included in this compilation album from
Vineyard Music.
</P>
<P>
   The songs, featuring worship leaders Andy Park, Brian Doerksen,
David Ruis, Lindell Cooley and Danny Daniels, were recorded live,
and the passion that was present in those worship services is
evident.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights include the prayerful plea for revival on ``Light the
Fire Again,'' the call for unity on ``Break Dividing Walls'' and
the raw joy of ``We Will Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessary to be charismatic or Pentecostal to enjoy
these songs, but they should come with a warning label. If you're
not careful, they might make you get up and dance and raise your
hands in praise.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
