<HEADER>
A7785 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-CENTER-2NDTAKE-K     04-21 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-CENTER-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANTRELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   seating approximately 400.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's existing downtown theaters are all at least 60
years old. And their stages, far smaller than current standards,
cannot accommodate some touring shows _ even some ballet repertory.
The Music Hall has bad sightlines, and both it and the Lyric
Theatre have cramped seats and problematic acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have done our best to adapt to the facilities in the
city,'' said William Whitener, artistic director of State Ballet of
Missouri, which is based in the Lyric Theatre. ``But it's time for
Kansas City to join the many other cities in the nation that have
made commitments to state-of-the-art performance facilities.''
 &LR; brk:Design consideration  &LR; tx:Early on, there was concern that the
slope of the Perot property could be a problem. But a site proposal
by architect Charles Young concluded that the slope would actually
be an advantage, requiring less excavation for raked seating if the
two halls were positioned at right angles.
</P>
<P>
   The location also has the advantage of matchless freeway access
from all corners of the metropolitan area. And, although located
just outside the inner freeway loop, it's adjacent to Bartle Hall
and within four blocks of the other downtown performance halls,
hotels and the proposed Power &AMP; Light District.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has talked with the city about building parking
garages on the north side of 16th street, to be shared between the
convention and performing arts centers.
</P>
<P>
   The Perot site also could connect the downtown loop to the
revitalization of the Crossroads and Freight House districts
immediately to the south, and from there to Union Station and Crown
Center. And there's been discussion of creating a parklike setting,
even a pond, on the southeast corner of the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a part of downtown we feel will really pick up,''
Kauffman said. ``I'm really excited about the site, personally.''
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge will be picking an architect for what will be
a very large complex on a dramatically exposed site. And Kauffman
has said all along she'd like the building to be designed by an
architect of international significance.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Nelson-Atkins Museum, which has picked six
architecture firms for a sketch competition to design an addition
and renovations, the Kauffman Foundation hasn't favored a
competition. But Dworak mentioned several architects the foundation
plans to consider: Charles Young, David Schwarz, Cesar Pelli, Moshe
Safdie, Frank Gehry, Rem Koolhaas and Rafael Vinoly.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman earlier announced that the foundation had picked Artec
Consultants Inc. to design acoustics for the new facility. Founded
by Russell Johnson, the New York-based firm has been acclaimed for
its designs for, among others, the Morton Meyerson Symphony Center
in Dallas and Birmingham Symphony Hall in England. It also has
planned acoustics for facilities under construction in Philadelphia
and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've just created one superlative hall after another,''
said conductor Manson, who has been emphatic about the Kansas City
Symphony's need for a better concert hall. ``I think that this is
by far the best acoustical engineering firm in the world for
concert halls. They haven't had a single failure, and their recent
halls, in particular, have been exquisite.''
</P>
<P>
   Still to be determined is the future of the Lyric Theatre, now
home to Lyric Opera of Kansas City (which owns the building) and
the Kansas City Symphony, as well as the State Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, for the next four of five years all the organizations
are going to continue to be housed there,'' said Evan Luskin, Lyric
Opera's general director. ``So I think it was a very good thing
that we were able to purchase the Lyric, in 1991. We will have been
here 13 or 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have not been thinking about the implications (of a
new performing arts center) for the theater, and I think we're
going to have to do that. I don't have any answers for what will
happen five years out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
