<SLUG> BC-TAX-UPS-0422-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CONTESTS $333 MILLION TAX BILL
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By JERRY MOSKAL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- United Parcel Service has found itself with a
</P>
<P>
   package it would rather not accept -- a $333.3 million tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much the Internal Revenue Service is demanding the
Atlanta-based package-delivery company and its subsidiaries pay for
</P>
<P>
   the 1985-87 tax years. The bill includes $209 million in
additional taxes, $17.26 million in penalties and $107 million in
interest.
</P>
<P>
   UPS has filed a petition with the U.S. Tax Court in Washington,
seeking to
</P>
<P>
   overturn the IRS decision.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS claim for $209 million in additional taxes includes at
least $105 million in dispute in a still-undecided Tax Court case
covering 1983 and 1984, UPS spokesman Norman Black said. The rest
involves normal, year-end tax disagreements, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An IRS spokesman said the agency does not comment on pending tax
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the alleged tax deficiency in the 1985-87 case stems
from the IRS denial of deductions for aircraft operation,
depreciation and repairs expended by United Parcel Service Company
Inc., the subsidiary that operates the company's air fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year there are disagreements on various aviation tax
issues,'' said Black. ``They are always worked out, and we're
confident we can work this out with the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   UPS claims the IRS ``erroneously determined that (the)
petitioner is not entitled to deductions...for costs incurred by
UPSCO (the air fleet subsidiary) for the inspection and maintenance
of certain of UPSCO's aircraft rotable (CQ) parts,'' such as
engines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the petition complained, the IRS erred when it
found that UPSCO changed its method of accounting for aircraft and
inspection of those parts without ``requesting and receiving
permission'' from the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those decisions, the petition said, the IRS ruled
</P>
<P>
   that the company had $42.3 million in additional taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   The petition added that the IRS erroneously found that $422.5
</P>
<P>
   million in ``excess value charges'' for the three-year period
</P>
<P>
   after $144.7 million in deductions should have been reported as
</P>
<P>
   taxable income.
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The 222-page petition by UPS not only asks the court to find
that
</P>
<P>
   there is no tax deficiency for 1985-87, but that the company
</P>
<P>
   overpaid its 1986-87 taxes by an unspecified amount.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   According to the petition, the IRS also erred when it:
</P>
<P>
   Denied $89.28 million in deductions paid to Liberty Mutual Fire
Insurance Co. for worker's compensation coverage during the three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Failed to allow $4.86 million in depreciation deductions on
UPS's 15 package delivery centers.
</P>
<P>
   Would not allow UPS to take a $4.3 million deduction for
depreciation of the customer lists it acquired when it bought Hill
Truck Rentals Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Did not allow a $10 million deduction for a cancellation fee
paid in 1987 to Interstate Airlines and Air Traffic Service Corp.
for voiding an aircraft leasing agreement when the air fleet
subsidiary took over the operation of company-owned planes.
</P>
<P>
   Did not allow a deduction of more than $2.5 million spent on
loan
</P>
<P>
   fees.
</P>
<P>
   Decided that UPS should have capitalized and expensed over
</P>
<P>
   a number of years $32.8 million in interest, increasing the
</P>
<P>
   firm's taxable income by that amount for 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Disallowed a $5.2 million deductions for payments made for
</P>
<P>
   industrial relations service in 1985-87.
</P>
<P>
   Ruled that $6.18 million spent on research and development in
</P>
<P>
   1987 could not by written off.
</P>
<P>
   Denied $6.5 million in investment tax credits for the purchase
of new aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Determined that almost $115 million spent on four new jet
</P>
<P>
   planes purchased in 1985 was not eligible for investment tax
</P>
<P>
   credits as new property.
</P>
<P>
   Would not allow investment tax credits for expenditures on
``used parts incorporated in the manufacture of the new aircraft''
</P>
<P>
   bought in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The petition also maintains the IRS erred when it ruled that
</P>
<P>
   UPS could only capitalize $1.6 million for depreciation purposes
</P>
<P>
   instead of $4.55 million that was claimed in investment tax
</P>
<P>
   credits on its former headquarters in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The IRS issued its notice of deficiency Jan. 14, and has 60
</P>
<P>
   days to respond to UPS' April 14 petition. If the company and
</P>
<P>
   agency fail to negotiate a settlement, the case could go to
</P>
<P>
   trial before a tax court judge.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
