<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MEETING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT MEETING OFFERS GOOD NEWS, LABOR STRIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shareholders at Sprint Corp.'s annual meeting Tuesday got more
than the usual coffee, cookies and corporate pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, earnings were up in the first quarter. The company had a
big year. And shareholders will get a 2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P>
   But before they could enter Sprint's headquarters on Shawnee
Mission Parkway, shareholders had to run a gantlet of
placard-waving union members calling for a kinder, gentler
workplace and protesting the generous pay package of Chairman and
Chief Executive William T. Esrey.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 members of the Communication Workers of America and
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers lined Shawnee
Mission Parkway before the meeting, shouting their message to
passing traffic: ``Hey, hey, ho, ho, corporate greed has got to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Esrey received about $24 million in direct compensation in 1998
and has amassed stock options in the last two years worth about
$240 million, as of the close of business Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company has frozen base pay for about 3,000
employees in the company's local telephone division, introduced
incentive-pay plans and imposed mandatory sales quotas.
</P>
<P>
   The unions contend those plans are unfair to many workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to let share owners know that the exorbitant
salary of Bill Esrey is a parasitic act off the backs of workers,''
said Jim Brimer, a spokesman for the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers. ``Sprint's refusal to bargain with us over
clearly negotiable items has got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says the plans are necessary for the company to
remain competitive in a rapidly changing industry and have actually
resulted in increased pay for 77 percent of the affected employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't sell our customers those products and services,
some competitors will sell them, and our business will diminish and
jobs will go away,'' Esrey told union workers in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Sprint's headquarters Tuesday, the audience was
considerably calmer. Some shareholders offered effusive praise for
management, and even union members acknowledged the ``financial
wizardry'' that led to a 65 percent total return on Sprint's stock
in 1998 and an additional 37 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   There was more good news on that front, as the company reported
another solid quarter of earnings growth in its core businesses and
announced a 2-for-1 stock split of the company's FON stock,
effective June 4 for shareholders of record May 13.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter profit at Sprint's FON Group, which includes all
operations except its Sprint PCS wireless phone business, rose 16
percent to $406.2 million, or 93 cents a share, from $351.2
million, or 80 cents, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The results surpass the 90-cent average estimate of analysts
surveyed by First Call Corp. Sprint's stock Tuesday rose 3, to 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no surprises here,'' said Tony Ferrugia, an analyst
with A.G. Edwards in St. Louis. ``The results were strong, as
expected. It was a solid quarter for Sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales in Sprint's FON group rose 7 percent to $4.17 billion. The
company rang up record sales in its long-distance division as more
residential customers signed up for its dime-a-minute calling plans
and businesses used more data and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from Internet and other data services surged 50 percent
during the quarter. And overall calling volume, or minutes of
traffic on Sprint's network, rose 24 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sales also were strong in the company's local division as it
boosted its number of local phone lines 5.2 percent, to 7.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   The increases helped Sprint boost FON group operating income 8
percent to $737 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FON Group's first-quarter performance reflected
exceptional execution across the board,'' Esrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Not including losses from Sprint's new businesses, Sprint said
the FON Group earned $1.10 a share, up from 96 cents a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Losses at its Global One joint venture with France Telecom and
Deutsche Telekom narrowed to 10 cents a share from 13 cents a year
ago. The international venture has been troubled since its
inception and is the subject of speculation as the partners decide
whether to reorganize or dissolve the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said the company should begin to make meaningful progress
toward profitability this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is upgrading its phone network to offer high-speed voice,
data and video services. Continued construction of that network,
known as ION or Integrated On-Demand Network, cost the company an
additional 7 cents a share in the first quarter, wider than 2 cents
a share in the first quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is beta-testing ION at seven large businesses and a total
of 29 sites across the country. It plans to begin testing consumer
and small-business versions this summer and release them in
selected markets at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects to spend up to an additional $700 million to
construct the network, which combines voice and data on one
platform.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the company's Sprint PCS wireless operation is
still in the red. Its net loss for the quarter widened to $625.6
million, or $1.46 a share, from $145.2 million, or 97 cents, a year
earlier. The loss includes a charge of 5 cents a share related to
the prepayment of debt.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue at Sprint PCS almost tripled from a year earlier, to
$604 million. The company turned on service in 50 markets during
the quarter, including Atlanta and Chicago, and added 763,000
customers _ a record for any U.S. wireless company in the
traditionally slack first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company ended the quarter with 3.35 million customers and
expects a total subscriber growth of more than 3 million this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
