<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIELDS-COOKIES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDER OF MRS. FIELDS COOKIES SHARES RECIPE FOR SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Debbi Fields had a dream. She wanted to
open a store that sold fresh-baked cookies.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seemed outrageous in 1977, especially when it was
suggested by a 20-year-old who didn't have a college degree or any
business experience.
</P>
<P>
   Even her own family thought it was ludicrous. But Fields spent
eight months trying to get a loan, always arriving at the bank with
a fresh batch of her cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have money, but I had a dream, and I had a recipe,''
said Fields, who founded Mrs. Fields Cookies and currently consults
for the $250 million company. ``I figured my greatest failure was
not to try.''
</P>
<P>
   A banker who liked her passion, conviction and cookies finally
lent her the $25,000 she used to launch the cookie empire.
</P>
<P>
   Fields, who sold the company in 1993 but remains on its
executive board, was in Kansas City on Tuesday for Sweet Ambitions.
The event is sponsored by the Mid-Continent Council of Girl Scouts
as part of activities for Take Our Daughters to Work Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Ms. Foundation established Take Our Daughters to Work Day in
1993 in response to studies that found that girls often lost
self-confidence and self-esteem as they reached adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of girls are expected to head to the workplace
Thursday to learn about their parents' jobs. One-third of American
companies participated last year, according to a Roper Starch
Worldwide poll.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 girls and adults Tuesday attended the sold-out Sweet
Ambitions event at the Westin Crown Center.
</P>
<P>
   Fields, a former Girl Scout and the mother of five girls, said
her recipe for success was one-third passion, one-third perfection
and one-third perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may not have been talented, but I was willing to work
hard,'' she said. ``I believe that whatever you do, you have to
give it your all.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields doesn't think failure is bad. It just means that you have
to stop what you're doing and try something else.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled the day she opened her first store in 1977. She had
designed the store to look like her kitchen so customers could
watch her bake.
</P>
<P>
   When no one came that first day, she brought the cookies to
them. Sales that first year reached $250,000, far greater than
anyone dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   Fields credits Girl Scouting and her father, who was a welder,
with teaching important lessons to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad said you always have to love what you do,'' she said.
``He always said you are wealthy if you have true friends, family
and love what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Scouting taught her skills she didn't have _ and taught
her about s'mores.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she spends about eight days a month away from home but is
constantly in touch with her daughters, who range in age from 7 to
19.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, she still loves baking cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookies, to me, is the universal gift of friendship,'' she
said. ``When you share cookies, you're sharing part of your
heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7789 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PHONE-HOLD-NYT &LR;      04-21 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PHONE-HOLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE CUSTOMERS FRET ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Ill., Wash.)   (af)  
 By BRUCE HEADLAM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's 11:30 p.m., your hard drive has crashed and you have been
on hold to the manufacturer's support line so long you would swear
you had heard that Bob Seger song three times already. Your
computer may be irreparable. But would some different music help?
</P>
<P>
   James Kellaris, an associate professor of marketing at the
University of Cincinnati, recently compared four kinds of music
used by companies for customers who are on hold: classical, light
jazz, old rock and alternative rock. As part of the study, 71
clients of a technology company listened to six-minute time blocks
in each of the styles. Then they estimated how long they had waited
and recorded their reactions to the music.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, the subjects overestimated the amount of
time they spent on hold. ``Of course, we already knew that,''
Kellaris said.
</P>
<P>
   What did surprise him was that women and men had very different
reactions to the music. Men reacted most favorably to classical
music and estimated the wait as the shortest (6.8 minutes). In
contrast, women perceived the classical music wait to be the
longest (7.6 minutes). Women preferred light jazz, estimating that
wait as the shortest (6.6 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The issue may be more than simply a matter of taste. ``A lot of
customers in this product category are baby boomers so we expected
that the rock oldies format would produce a good response,''
Kellaris said. ``But it produced the least favorable reaction
across the two groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Familiarity, he said, may breed contempt. ``The women may have
been more familiar with the classical music,'' he suggested. ``When
people hear part of a piece of music they know, they infer the
whole piece. So they think that they were on hold longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The results also surprised Gordon Bruner, associate professor at
Southern Illinois University and a leader in the field of consumer
time perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stereotypically,'' he said, ``men like hard rock and women
like soft rock. But with music, the question I'd ask is: do we want
people to say `they play music we like' or to say `so what?' if
they liked it. They stayed on the line. That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Muzak Corp., where music is the bottom line, one
executive expressed skepticism that music choice really affected
perceived waiting time. Reached at the Muzak headquarters in
Seattle (after two long minutes on hold with Billy Joel's ``River
of Dreams''), Kenneth Kahn, vice president for marketing, said that
``almost all our concerns have to do with the message, not the
music.'' Muzak designs on-hold messages for many technology
companies, including Cisco Systems and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Can Muzak learn anything from the study? Kellaris did joke that
companies might offer an option: ``If you are male, please press 1.
If you are female, please press 2.'' In the meantime, the less
offensive compromise appears to be alternative rock (7.18 minutes).
As for old-style elevator music, he did not even bother with a
test. ``Too many associations with root canals,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
