<HEADLINE>
KAUFFMAN FOUNDATION PICKS SITE FOR NEW PERFORMING ARTS CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANTRELL  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long-vacant hillside south of Bartle Hall will be the site
of a performing arts center likely to cost $225 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Muriel McBrien Kauffman Foundation, which has been
researching and planning for a new performing arts center for the
last four years, has signed a purchase agreement for the 18-acre
site roughly bounded by 16th Street on the north, 17th Street on
the south, Broadway on the west and Wyandotte Street on the east.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day ``due diligence'' agreement gives the buyer time to
check environmental facets, title and other issues. But Julia Irene
Kauffman, the foundation's CEO, said, ``I don't see any reason why
this won't be the site for the performing arts center.''
</P>
<P>
   In the best of circumstances, between design and construction
phases, a new facility won't open its doors for five or six years.
But the site represents a tangible commitment to the long-discussed
performing arts center.
</P>
<P>
   With its pronounced slope toward the southeast, the site is by
far the most dramatic _ and the largest _ of seven alternatives,
all downtown, that were considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wonderful location,'' said Anne Manson, music
director designate of the Kansas City Symphony. ``For one thing,
the view is beautiful. For another, there's a lot of land there to
be developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a great setting for the new concert hall,
especially if there were a lot of landscaping and maybe some
restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman declined to disclose the cost of the property, which is
owned by the family of Texas entrepreneur Ross Perot, other than to
say, ``It was reasonable...a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Kauffman disclose how much the $250 million foundation
established by her late mother would contribute toward the new
complex. But she said a figure probably will be announced soon
after the 90-day investigation period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say it will be substantial,'' she said, ``more than
substantial.''
SUB HED--Two halls-SUB HEAD  &LR; tx:Kauffman did say the plan calls for
two halls: a non-proscenium symphony hall and a proscenium theater
for opera, ballet and stage productions. The $225 million figure
includes a substantial endowment to support ongoing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of major fund drives for Science City at
Union Station and the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, and with a drive
for Liberty Memorial in the works, this could be a challenge for
area funding sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most of the other drives are winding down,'' said Ken
Dworak, the foundation's project manager for the performing arts
center. ``And this will be six years before opening, so we've got
some time.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-hall configuration was the virtually unanimous
recommendation of area arts leaders and leading theater and
acoustical consultants brought in to study local needs.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the different art forms have very different
physical and acoustical needs. For another, a single multipurpose
facility would be a scheduling nightmare for organizations at the
mercy of touring artists' schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion has centered on seating capacities of 1,800 to 1,900
for each hall. (By contrast, the Folly Theater seats approximately
1,100; the Lyric Theatre 1,600; the Music Hall 2,400; and the
Midland Theatre 2,700.)
</P>
<P>
   But Kauffman said the opera-ballet theater might be made
slightly larger to accommodate touring Broadway shows. The center
also might include a third theater seating approximately 400. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
