<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV23-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FETCH, SIT UP AND FILE
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday, April 23)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALIC)I've seen a look in dog's eyes, a quickly
vanishing look of amazed contempt, and I am convinced that
basically dogs think humans are nuts.(END ITALIC) _ John Steinbeck
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Humane Society or PETA intervenes soon, the first
ever Take-Your-Dog-to-Work Day will take place on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Pet Sitters International, Take-Your-Dog-to-Work
Day is intended _ and I quote _ to ``demonstrate that dogs aren't
just good pets, they make good co-workers, too!''
</P>
<P>
   I am staring right now at Buster, who is a pug and therefore
technically a dog, and I am failing to see any good co-worker
potential unless your definition of a good co-worker is someone who
sleeps 18 hours a day, rousing himself only as long as it takes to
pee on the kitchen floor and/or bark at random oxygen molecules
that threaten to break into the house.
</P>
<P>
   (I have seen office workers who, after attending one too many
meetings, behave in a similar fashion, but that has little or
nothing to do with the issue at hand, so let us move on.)
</P>
<P>
   Dogs are skilled in many areas (shedding, digging, chewing), but
I have yet to meet one that can file, set up a conference call or
steal change from the coffee fund without anyone noticing.
</P>
<P>
   You could not count on a dog to bring in a dozen doughnuts
(intact) every Wednesday, nor could you depend on it to think up
something pithy and original every time a birthday or get-well card
was passed around.
</P>
<P>
   While a dog is probably just as capable of mastering computers
as most people, it would not experience the same feelings of anger,
frustration and futility that make the machines so fascinating to
humans. I may be proved wrong, but I cannot see a dog taking a
sledgehammer to a recalcitrant PC or tying a stout chain to a balky
modem and using it as a boat anchor. Fear and loathing of computers
are integral ingredients of the thin glue that bond office
employees to one another. A dog may drool on the keyboard or issue
a low growl when the words ``system error'' appear on the screen,
but beyond that it finds the whole subject rather boring.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may worry about dogs bringing fleas into the work
place, but if anything, it's the dogs that should be concerned
about the multitude of poxes and plagues that waft through the
office like the odor of scorched microwave popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   A bright-eyed dog that at home is always up for a brisk game of
Frisbee or slobber-on-the-tennis-ball would see its health
deteriorate quickly in the office environment. Aside from the
occasional desultory shuffle to the office vending machine for some
stale pretzels, there are few opportunities for vigorous exercise
in the average office. Indeed, employees who sit up on their
haunches with a gleam in the their eye and a stick in their mouth
are not only seldom rewarded with a game of fetch but are often
overlooked, or worse, when raise time rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   Miners used to take canaries into the shafts as a primitive form
of pollution alert. When the canary keeled over, the miners knew
the air had become too poisonous to breathe and it was time to get
out.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot help but wonder if there is some of the same sort of
thinking behind the idea of bringing dogs into the work place.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to put it another way, as Edward Abbey once said, ``When a
man's best friend is his dog, that dog has a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, my advice to dogs is, come June 25, you might want
to hide under the bed.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
