<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BADFINGER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUITARIST JOEY MOLLAND KEEPS BADFINGER ALIVE AND ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL DeYOUNG   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, the British-Welsh band Badfinger turned out
a half-dozen stunning records. The band foreshadowed the ``power
pop'' sound with a combination of hard-rocking guitars, big beats
and luscious harmony vocals.
</P>
<P>
   It all came to a tragic end with the 1975 suicide of guitarist
Pete Ham, who'd composed and sung some of the band's biggest hits:
``No Matter What,'' ``Day After Day'' and ``Baby Blue.'' Eight
years later, bassist Tom Evans killed himself, too, after trying _
and failing _ to re-light the Badfinger flame.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Joey Molland, the band's lead guitarist and a
contributing songwriter, tours the country under the Badfinger
name, backed by a bassist and drummer and playing the songs that
took him from his native Liverpool so many years ago and made him
part of a rock 'n' roll legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the same thing as we've always done, a bunch of
Badfinger songs from the different records, and some of my songs
from the solo records, and one or two new songs,'' said Molland,
50, in a telephone interview from his home in Minnesota.
``Depending on what the crowd is like. I've been doing a solo
version of `Name of the Game' onstage, things like that. Try and
play a couple of Pete's songs, tell people about him a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Badfinger is warmly regarded as a pioneering group. Their
albums _ originally issued on the Beatles' Apple Records label _
are top catalog sellers on CD.
</P>
<P>
   Molland says VH1 has prepared a segment of its top-rated
``Behind the Music'' series on Badfinger's rise and fall. ``I guess
it's all ready to go,'' he said. ``It's been put back until
September because of some type of Beatle involvement, maybe. They'd
like to get those guys involved if they could. I mean, I doubt if
that's going to happen, myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After several prolonged legal battles over Badfinger issues,
Molland has fallen out with drummer Mike Gibbins, the other
surviving member, who lives in Orlando, Fla. ``There's a dispute
going on in the courts now, and frankly I doubt if I'll ever talk
to the guy again, after what he's said about me,'' Molland said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the guitarist happy with ``Without You: The Tragic Story
of Badfinger,'' a hefty biography published two years ago. Author
Dan Matovina painted Molland and his American-born wife _ both of
whom declined to be interviewed for the book _ as self-obsessed and
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing about it is how people believe it,'' says
Molland, who said he hasn't read the book. ``People just swallow it
hook, line and sinker. I've had people arguing with me about what
happened with the band, because this guy said that's what happened.
It's outrageous, and I'm doing my best to stay away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Molland prefers ``Badfinger,'' filmmaker Gary Katz' video
biography, released almost simultaneously with the book. ``The
video turned out good,'' he says. ``And we've had a lot of
compliments on it, just because it doesn't bull---- around. It just
tells the story.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bill DeYoung is arts &AMP; entertainment editor of The Gainesville
Sun.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
