<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-FURNITURE-845(2     04-21 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FURNITURE-845(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT FORMS EASE WINDS OF WORRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NC-FURNITURE) 
(js) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Wriggling derrieres replaced chattering into cell
phones as the signature gesture at the Milan furniture fair, the
world's premier showcase of forward-thinking design.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors did wriggle as fast as they could in the deflatable
Memo chair by Ron Arad of England while it transformed from squishy
beanbag to body-molded nest as the air was sucked out.
</P>
<P>
   They gyrated with hula-hooping ease in a tubular steel chair
with a hammock-sling seat by Achille Castiglioni, the octogenarian
modernist, and his collaborator, Ferruccio Laviani.
</P>
<P>
   And at B&AMP; B Italia, a jump-suited engineer was on hand to help
weaklings crank Antonio Citterio's Freetime chaise _ a recliner as
only a Milanese would interpret it, in swank wool cashmere.
</P>
<P>
   In a year with no big-bang design movements, with minimalism
still dominating 5 million square feet of exhibition space, with
some furniture factories only a dozen miles from the border with
the former Yugoslavia, and war on everyone's mind, unease pervaded
the 38th annual fair, which ended April 18. Furniture seemed to be
slouching toward the millennium. The search for relief was on.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers and manufacturers from 140 countries, along with magazine
editors in search of hip trends, were looking for high style and
technological wonder, to be sure, but also for balm for the urban
soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is so fast, people can't compete with it,'' said
Sven-Anwar Bibi, 27, a Cologne designer in a trio called Kombinat.
The team christened its first installation _ or was it a manifesto?
_ ``Homesick.'' It was an elegantly monastic refuge of three
compartments: paneled walnut walls, with a single bed, desk and
bench as built-ins. ``The wood of our childhood,'' Bibi explained,
``to remind us of a time which is much slower than now. We need
that.'' Designed for a populace yearning for permanence _ furniture
without wheels is a good place to start _ the assertive immobility
of this modern cloister seemed to touch a nerve in the Satellite
pavilion, the fair's showcase for young innovators.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 162,555 attendees, a relatively sober mood prevailed
in spite of buoyant business. In Italy, new furniture sales
increased from $16.8 billion in 1997 to $18 billion in 1998 with
exports to the United States up by 3.3 percent to $972 million in
1998. (The United States is still the second largest customer,
after Germany.)
</P>
<P>
   The mild shock of seeing the young and avant-garde developing
high-concept furniture for slowing down was reinforced by Philips,
the mainstream Dutch electronics company, which displayed a House
of the Future with a distinctly nostalgic bent. ``Emotion
containers'' _ stainless steel cones that digitally capture the
image, voice and scent of beloved family members _ may soothe a
homesick 21st-century Willy Loman _ but why not simply give the
kids a good-night kiss?
</P>
<P>
   More useful, perhaps, was the Interactive Tablecloth made of
washable linen and woven with power circuits. It promised to supply
current for lights, appliances and warming plates without singeing
a fingertip. A Philips spokesman said the tablecloth could be
available within five years _ that is, unless it joins the ranks of
other obsolescence-bound improvements from yesterday's Houses of
Tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   A testy appreciation for the past rippled through the fair, even
among the most technologically daring. ``The first day of the next
millennium is going to look a lot like the last day of this
millennium,'' Arad said. ``Televisions get slimmer and slimmer and
computers get more sophisticated, but tables and chairs and sofas
have stayed more or less the same. The modern chair peaked in the
1950s with Charles and Ray Eames, George Nelson, Arne Jacobsen, and
after that there was very little revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Arad promptly overturned his own theory by supplying the fair
with some of its most challenging entries. A pair of vases made of
plastic resin and polymer wire were created with the latest design
technology, called rapid prototyping: ``I put my idea into a
computer, it's translated over the phone to Holland and delivered
here in finished form the next day,'' Arad explained.
</P>
<P>
   His Memo chair for Inflate Design Studio of London suggested
that if the times are not relaxing, people have at least relaxed
their idea of what a piece of furniture should look like. He spoke
of Memo, which is high-performance vinyl filled with polystyrene
balls, as ``infinitely adjustable.'' And it is _ so long as there's
a pump or vacuum cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stay quite rigidly in place for it to work,'' said
Matty J. Veldkamp, a visitor, as she tried to carve out room for
her elbows as the chair hardened around her. ``It's really quite an
effort.'' Ms. Veldkamp, a senior adviser at the Dutch Ministry of
Education, Culture and Science, also questioned whether a vacuum
cleaner was the right accessory for a stylish living room. (Decide
for yourself: the chair will be at Totem, the New York store, in
May, starting at $350.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Comical or innovative, trend-setting or eyebrow-raising, here
are some of the furnishings that provoked the most impassioned
comment over the morning caffe lattes and the midnight grappas.
</P>
<P>
   Sole of Wit
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Morrison, the London designer, looked inside his
girlfriend's Prada shoes for inspiration. His Low-Pad and High-Pad
chairs for Cappellini display a clipboard-thin profile with
cushions in bas-relief. The lightness and model-thin silhouette
clearly delighted this 39-year-old minimalist, but he quickly
added: ``You've got quite a lot of padding. I have a very bad back,
so it's become a major issue with me that the chair really has to
support in the right way.'' The chairs could well take airport
furniture to a higher level and will be sold through Cappellini and
Modern Age in New York, starting in May, at $554.
</P>
<P>
   The Mad Max Award
</P>
<P>
   A study in tactile dissonance, Hi Square, a sofa by Massimo
Morozzi for Edra, is ``the furniture equivalent of the Sex
Pistols,'' said Paola Antonelli, a design curator at the Museum of
Modern Art in New York. In a nod to trendy straw-bale houses _ or
to a nostalgic hayride? _ its milky translucent polyurethane
cushions are stuffed with a straw lookalike (actually, a flax
fiber). In high-fashion counterpoint, the padded neoprene frame is
a gleaming lacquer red. Buyers beware: Cushions may be sticky when
hot, so this may not be ideal for a miniskirt. The Dr. Scholl Award
</P>
<P>
   For its luminous blue-and-green transparency and squishability,
nothing beat Werner Aisslinger's Soft Cell gel-furniture,
upholstered with polyurethane used to pad bicycle saddles and
wheelchairs. No bed sores.
</P>
<P>
   The Techno-Hut Award
</P>
<P>
   New materials don't have to result in new forms. Hella
Jongerius, a Dutch designer who is now working on Donna Karan's
home collection, based her Kasese chair on one made of sticks she
found in a church in Uganda. ``It was poetry,'' she said, ``and it
made me think, ``Well, what is our poetry?' Can I translate this
for the '90s, in high-tech materials, into something you can
love?'' (It folds up, too.)
</P>
<P>
   She remade it in lightweight carbon, knitted and woven to look
like animal skin, and covered the seat in neoprene or a
dramatically folksy felt that looks like shaggy goat hide. Murray
Moss, the owner of the New York store Moss, saw it and said, ``It's
primitive yet highly informed, it's jarring, and yet you have to
smile.''
</P>
<P>
   The Great Reveal
</P>
<P>
   Cassina and Flexform were among the many companies
reinterpreting the ingenious tubular-steel experiments of the early
modern masters Le Corbusier, Charlotte Perriand and Marcel Breuer.
A graceful arc of tubing joins chunky leather back and low-slung
seat cushions in a new Flexform chair by Citterio. The seat slides
and the back tilts without shedding any James Bond cool. And the
Nest sofa by Piero Lissoni for Cassina exposes its frame, as pliant
at its corners as a line of ballerinas bending at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   The Not-Afraid-to-Flirt Award
</P>
<P>
   Emmemobili, an Italian furniture manufacturer, threw minimalism
a few welcome curves with an elegant wall shelf made of
crescent-shaped bent plywood buoyed by a divider in a sine-wave
pattern. A gleaming giant toadstool of a table by Ferruccio Laviani
was made entirely of wood _ its base painted a '70s-era lacquer
white and the top waxed wenge wood. It will be carried by Salon
Moderne in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Hummel Award
</P>
<P>
   Part cute figurine, part Jeff Koons sculpture, Philippe Starck's
new small table was literally based on the iconic garden gnome. It
outraged some, flabbergasted others and had Claudio Luti, the
managing director of the Italian manufacturer Kartell, shaking his
head in disbelief that so many customers wanted to buy it
(including a new hotel in London).
</P>
<P>
   Starck, explained: ``Minimalism has become a retro '70s
fashion,'' he said. ``There's no life in it. Why not a little bomb?
We need humor and tenderness more than we need beautiful lines.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gummi Bear Award
</P>
<P>
   Gaetano Pesce brought a collection of lamps, tables and
children's chairs to Milan from his studio in Manhattan. Made of
resin, in jujube colors, they are shipped flat to be snapped
together. In typical Pesce style, each seat is etched with a jaunty
profile or cut-out clown's face. They will be available for under
$200 at Moss in New York in May. At 60, long an innovator of the
domestic landscape and Milan fairs, Pesce seemed the right choice
to predict the shape of things to come: ``Cheap and unique,'' he
said promptly, ``that's the future.''
</P>
