<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV29-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY WITHOUT GAS? WHY NOT A WEEK?
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, April 29)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A commuter to San Francisco declared she'd sooner run out of gas
on the Golden Gate Bridge than stop at the gas station in Marin
that was charging over $2 a gallon last week. We snorted in
agreement. It's a self-immolating notion, but understandable in
these times.
</P>
<P>
   Tell Americans they're going to pay more for gasoline and they
go off faster than a Lexus. It's one of the few consumer protests
we can get behind. They can't get away with hiking prices like
that, no matter what the reason. Here we are spending more on car
payments than our parents paid for their houses. We can't be
expected to go another 43 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks the Internet has been hopping with e-mail exhortations
to join an April 30 protest, a day no one buys gas and we make a
collective face at the oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, will we show them. Of course, we'll be hurting a lot of
people whose jobs have been reduced to selling cigarettes and
passing out bathroom keys, who have to pay the same price for gas
to drive to work that the rest of us do, but who are they?
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite gas station is permanently closed, because
of environmental regulations having to do with underground tanks. I
would have had a hard time snubbing those guys because they took
care of all the cars in our family. You could drive in and say ``Do
these tires look soft?'' and someone would wipe his hands on his
dark blue pants, pull out his tire checker and reassure you they
were fine. No charge. On stormy days they'd sometimes wave you back
in your car even if you were at the self-serve pump. Since they're
gone I go to places where you pump it yourself, pay for it outside
and worry about your own oil. The people who work there are
faceless.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I could boycott them and not feel guilty but I doubt
they have any more influence on OPEC than I do.
</P>
<P>
   I hate the idea of any business upping their prices just because
they can get away with it, although that seems to be the way with
everything from blue jeans to airline tickets, but I'm not a
student of pump prices. Until this latest hike hit the frenzy mark
I didn't really notice what I paid. I also didn't realize, until I
just read it, that last December gasoline was a deal at $1.16 in
Northern California _ less than we'd paid for five years. I don't
remember the celebrations back then.
</P>
<P>
   It depends on your priority. Some of us will drive extra miles
to save a bit on white meat canned tuna but when it comes to gas
it's who's closest when you're empty.
</P>
<P>
   If we're going to get agitated about the cost of gasoline, why
not resent how much it costs to drive, period? What about the price
of new tires and car insurance? How about the cost of parking and
parking tickets? The price of a car phone, infant seat, sun roof,
security system and real leather seats.
</P>
<P>
   Driving a car is no bargain. It's a luxury, yet when it comes to
gasoline we act as if it's a public utility, like heating fuel and
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather protest the sorry lack of good food along the freeway
than gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about the car addiction we pass on to high school kids so
that most teen-agers now depend on a car to get to work for the job
they need to pay for a car?
</P>
<P>
   We Americans are said to have a love affair with our cars, but
they sure make us grumpy. It's no surprise that people are foaming
at the mouth over gas prices. We're at our most ferocious when
we're in our cars. And we're always in our cars.
</P>
<P>
   We've accepted road rage as a cultural trait, rather than as
something we might want to control. Reasonable people become
maniacs behind the wheel, cursing at strangers, muttering to
themselves, shutting the world out with loud music and flipping off
those who don't like it. We are annoyed by red lights, stop signs
and drivers who don't turn into oncoming traffic when we think they
should.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us are snobs about public transportation. We'll visit a
new city and master its metro but refuse to even try to take the
bus in our own town.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the protest. What is a single day going to achieve? The
protest organizers predict that if no one buys gas on April 30, the
prices will drop drastically. I don't believe that.
</P>
<P>
   Big Oil could handle one day without us, because they know we'll
be thirsty the day after.
</P>
<P>
   How about if we went a week without gassing up?
</P>
<P>
   If we had to make a tank of gas last a week, or even longer, we
would have to get smart and budget our car use. We'd have to share,
plan, car pool, walk, try out the bus. We might even start to think
how nice it would be to have a train as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that would show them.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
