<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7806 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES     04-21 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUSE WITH A CAMERA SEES RATHER THAN FEELS  
 LINUX'S POPULAR CREATOR STEALS THE SHOW FROM GATES  
 NEXT-GENERATION GAME PLAYER IS ON THE WAY FROM SEGA  
 PALM PILOT MAY BE POWERFUL, BUT THAT SCREEN IS FRAGILE  
 A PROGRAM THAT CAN REMOVE ADVERTISING ON INTERNET PAGES  
 GREAT ART FOR YOUR PAGE? YOU CAN GET IT FROM GATES  
 ROBOT OLYMPICS? LIVE ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its sleek silver back and glowing red underbelly and
taillight, the Microsoft Intellimouse Explorer, which will become
available in September, is the most visually striking computer
mouse yet.
</P>
<P>
   But the most impressive feature about the mouse, which is
expected to cost $74.95, is that Microsoft removed almost all the
interior moving parts, including the mouse ball. Instead, the new
mouse, which is about the same size as other such devices, uses an
optical sensor and a digital signal processing (DSP) chip to track
minute movements over virtually any surface except glass.
</P>
<P>
   The camera snaps some 1,500 tiny images each second; the chip,
using a process called image correlation processing, compares
images to see what has changed, then translates the changes into
coordinates that show how the mouse has moved.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse is more fluid and precise than with an old-fashioned
``ball'' mouse and better even than the earlier optical mice that
required a special optical mouse pad. And because there is no mouse
ball to roll lint, dust or cookie crumbs into the device's belly
button, it is fastidiously clean.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two new buttons, controlled by the thumb,
designed specifically for clicking forward and backward through
pages of a Web sites and a scroll wheel for Net applications.
</P>
<P>
   The new Microsoft mouse is designed for right-handers, and it
works only with computers with Windows, so it's hard cheese for
left-handed Macintosh or Linux users who have glass-topped desks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter H. Lewis &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Linux's Popular Creator Steals the Show From Gates  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the annual Comdex-Windows World conference this week, William
Gates, the Microsoft chairman, standing with an eight-foot high
model of the new optical mouse, attracted the usual overflow crowd
for his opening day keynote speech. But the real star of the
conference was not the head of Microsoft, but a lone programmer who
gives away his work: Linus Torvalds.
</P>
<P>
   Torvalds, the creator of the Linux operating system and current
darling of the technologically hip, was scheduled to give the
keynote address for a conference-within-a-conference called the
Linux Pavilion. The original venue was a small conference room that
would hold about 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   When a line started forming two hours early, the event was moved
to a larger room that would hold about 500 people. Even that wasn't
big enough. The crowd, estimated at about 1,500, filled the room
and spilled out into the halls.
</P>
<P>
   While Torvalds didn't disappoint them, he did seem a little
stunned by the enthusiasm, including a standing ovation at the end.
Someone asked if he had nightmares about security issues
surrounding Linux.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but I think that users should have nightmares about
trusting their software security to the control of a single
vendor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Torvalds is convinced that Linux will continue to grow in
popularity, but he warned the faithful, ``Don't get caught up in
the hype.'' Judging from the reaction to his appearance, it may
already be too late for that. &QL; 
_ Stephen C. Miller &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Next-Generation Game Player Is on the Way From Sega
</P>
<P>
   In the video-game universe, most of the hottest action has
migrated from consoles to CD-ROMs in recent years. No more,
promises Sega of America, an arm of Sega Enterprises, based in
Tokyo. On Sept. 9 the company will release in &QL; 
the United States the Sega Dreamcast machine, one of the most
highly anticipated home video game players in years, Dave Karraker,
a Sega spokesman, said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamcast will have 128-bit architecture and will be 15 times as
powerful as Sony Playstation and 10 times as powerful as Nintendo
64; it will &QL; 
have four times the graphics-processing power of even the fastest
Pentium II chip, Karraker said. And it will cost only $199, well
below what next-generation game machines usually cost when they are
introduced. But don't look to play your old Sega games on it; a
whole new generation of games are in the works for it.
</P>
<P>
   But its pre-eminence in the highly competitive video game domain
is not assured for long. Sony is expected to release its own
next-generation machine, an even faster and more powerful machine
(at least on paper) than Dreamcast, early next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michel Marriott &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Palm Pilot May Be Powerful, But That Screen Is Fragile
</P>
<P>
   Unlike your PC, when Palm Pilots crash, they really crash.
According to a representative in Palm Computing's repair
information department, the most common complaint _ an estimated 90
percent of the calls _ are from users with cracked or broken glass
screens that have rendered the units inoperable.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens when your Pilot takes a swan dive onto the
unforgiving floor? You call up Palm Computing to report it. If the
problem is obviously screen damage, they will _ for $100 _ send
right out to you, via Airborne Express, a reconditioned Pilot of
the same model.
</P>
<P>
   The screen on your old Pilot is then replaced and sent to the
next person on the broken-glass repair list. While you don't get
your original unit back, you can restore your personal data by
synching the handheld device to the Palm data port on your desktop
computer.
</P>
<P>
   For more information or to report a broken screen, call (888)
956-7256. Please write this number down, but not in your Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Biersdorfer &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A Program That Can Remove Advertising on Internet Pages  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A German electronics company is tackling those banner
advertisements with a product that strips most advertising off Web
pages. Web Washer was developed by engineers at Siemens AG who
wanted to get rid of advertising they thought was obtrusive. During
testing on the company's intranet, they discovered that it also
reduced the time pages took to load in a browser. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The software sits on a user's computer and waits for a user to
click on a link. Web Washer looks at all the pieces of what is
being requested and if anything looks as if it might be an ad, the
program will toss out that part of the request. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roland Cuny, the Siemens engineer who came up with the idea for
Web Washer, said the program could filter out ``any kind of
undesired information, like over-designed background images on
Internet-intranet pages, ad banners, graphics, frames, Java
scripts, Java applets and pop-up windows'' and could be tuned by
the user to be more _ or less _ restrictive.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The program is free for personal use and is available at the
www.siemens.de/servers/wwash/wwashus/buy.htm site. Current versions
run only on Windows 95 and 98 and NT, though Cuny said Macintosh
and Linux versions were in the works.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steven E. Brier &QR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Great Art for Your Page? You Can Get It From Gates
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, Bill Gates' other company, the Corbis Corp.
in Seattle (www.corbis.com), has been quietly acquiring the
electronic reproduction rights to 25 million images, including some
of the world's great art and historical photographs, like Monet's
``Poplars,'' Ansel Adams' ``Moonrise Over Hernandez,'' John F.
Kennedy Jr.'s salute at his father's funeral and the Challenger
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Corbis, a privately held company that is
wholly owned by Gates, announced that it was now selling nearly
400,000 of its images to individuals for one-time personal use.
Corbis, which already sells its images for commercial use, has
dubbed the new service the Corbis Picture Experience. The company
will let customers choose from 500,000 images to send free
electronic postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Each image will cost $3, which could change, depending on how
that price is accepted by consumers, said Steve Davis, president of
Corbis. The purchase of the images works through Qpass, a service
for online purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey conducted by Corbis, 61 percent of personal Web site
builders said they planned to use Corbis images in their Web sites
in the next two years. The images may also be used for personal
newsletters, classroom reports, computer wallpaper and screen
savers.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said Corbis' move to sell images to consumers was in
keeping with what he describes as Gates' initial vision for Corbis:
putting great images on individual desktop computers. ``That was
part of his vision, to make historical images available for
personal use,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Katie Hafner &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Robot Olympics? Live on the Net
</P>
<P>
   Will robots one day rule the world? Probably not, but they may
have taken over recess for a day. On Friday and Saturday, NASA will
broadcast this year's finals of the National Robotics Competition
live over the Internet (quest.arc.nasa.gov/firstrobots). The event
pits robots built by high-school students against one another in
tests of strength and skill. .  &QL;
</P>
