<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, April 22, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Flooding rains and severe thunderstorms will menace parts of the
Middle West Thursday as a major spring storm system continues to
evolve Thursday and throughout the evening. Rather than striking
with a single offensive of stormy weather, the system will mount
several assaults as a series of potent jet stream disturbances
eject eastward from the main upper-level low pressure area hovering
over the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, a cluster of showers and thunderstorms will
produce heavy rains from northeast Kansas and northwest Missouri.
Storms will then move east-northeast into Iowa, northern Illinois
and southern Wisconsin. Rainfalls will likely exceed an inch.
</P>
<P>
   Another batch of showers and thunderstorms will erupt Thursday
afternoon over parts of eastern Kansas, eastern Oklahoma and
northeast Texas along a boundary that separates dry air from the
plateaus of Old Mexico and humid air from the Gulf of Mexico. A few
of these storms will approach severe levels, with isolated
tornadoes probable. Very warm air at 5,000 feet over southeast
Texas will act as a lid, likely prohibiting the development of
strong thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   A snowstorm will likely occur along the Front Range of the
Colorado and Wyoming Rockies as moist winds from the east are
forced to ascend the sloping terrain. Though the two jet stream
disturbances to the east and south of the region will likely
intercept a large portion of the moist plume of humid air flowing
north from the Gulf of Mexico, there will still be sufficient
moisture to produce 6 to 12 inches of snow in some spots.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Dry Florida
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning the mercury stood at 50 degrees, a record
minimum, in Orlando, Florida. Less than a week ago, the middle of
the state had record maximums between 95 and 100 degrees. The usual
maritime climate of Florida has become more continental after a
serious winter drought. In fact, the relative humidity on Wednesday
afternoon was at desert levels, near 25 percent, in northeast
Florida. This shift to arid weather has led to numerous brush fires
that have burned more than 155,000 acres in the Everglades so far
this season. A few showers may dampen the southeast sections
Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast Text for Thursday, April 22 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sunday: Warmer, sunny weather will prevail across much
of the West as high pressure dominates the region. A low pressure
system in the southern Rockies will create mountain snows and
valley rain showers. Milder air will surge ahead of a cold front
moving into the Upper Middle West. The Northeast will be cool and
damp to start. Meanwhile, thunderstorms may erupt in the Southeast
as much of the South stays warm and humid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday: A potent storm will cause wet and very cool
weather across much of the Great Lakes and Northeast. A cold front
extending from the low pressure will press across the Southeast
leaving all but Florida with cooler weather. Meanwhile, quieter
conditions will prevail in the Plains as a large high pressure area
settles in the region. Unseasonably warm and sunny weather will
spread northward through the Rocky Mountains. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
