<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SEATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON CAR SEATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are we a nation of stupid, uncaring parents?
</P>
<P>
   It seems that way when you consider these statistics:
</P>
<P>
   The National Traffic Safety Administration estimates that 70
percent to 80 percent of child-restraint systems are incorrectly
installed or improperly used.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us let our children roam the back seat unrestrained
while the car is moving.
</P>
<P>
   Car accidents are the No. 1 killer of children ages 5 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   If all child restraints were installed and used properly and
consistently, 71 percent of children killed in motor-vehicle
crashes could be saved, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riding in a car is the most dangerous thing we do with our
kids on a daily basis,'' says Ann Athey, former director of
advocacy for Cook Children's Medical Center in Fort Worth and the
Safe Kids Coalition of Tarrant County. Seventy-five percent of
motor vehicle crashes occur within 25 miles of home; 60 percent
occur on roads with speed limits of 40 mph or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I see is what to do with the older
child,'' Athey says. ``The prevailing attitude is, the child can
come out of a car seat once he outgrows his forward-facing
convertible seat, at about the age of 4.''
</P>
<P>
   But most kids at 40 pounds won't fit correctly into seat belts
without a booster (the shoulder belt should fit across the
collarbone, not the neck or face). Putting the shoulder belt behind
the child or under the arm is NOT a good solution; it could cause
serious internal injury during a crash. A booster for older
children won't boost their ``cool'' quotient, but it could save
their lives. Now, that seems more than worth a little whining.
</P>
<P>
   REVAMPING VEHICLES
</P>
<P>
   All new motor vehicles must be equipped with standardized
child-restraint anchorage systems, effective Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Under the government regulation, all new cars and trucks will
have standard anchors built into their back seats, and all new
child-safety seats will have three standard attachments, one on top
and two at the base, that link directly into the anchors.
</P>
<P>
   The new anchorage system is designed to be easy to use and
independent of vehicle seat belts. It is in accord with European,
Canadian and Australian regulations, which assure that all
child-restraint seats can be properly hooked up in all motor
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S THE LAW
</P>
<P>
   Texas law requires that a child younger than 2 be restrained in
a federally approved safety seat when riding in a motor vehicle.
Children 2 to 4 must wear a seat belt or be strapped in a safety
seat.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone older than 4, seat belts are required only in the
front seat. However, safety advocates say that everyone in the car
should be properly restrained in a car seat, booster seat or seat
belt.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mike Moncrief of Fort Worth has a bill before the
Texas Legislature that would require all children under 15 to
buckle up, no matter where they are riding (front or back).
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation's panel to improve
child-passenger safety says all states should require children
younger than 4 to be in a child-safety seat, and older children up
to age 16 be in either a properly adjusted seat belt or a booster
seat.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
