   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-CHOICE _ The 40,000 tuition grants being given nationally
to poor kids to opt out of public schools is a lot like an
initiative in Atlanta begun in 1992. We'll focus on a mother and
two daughters who received these scholarships and talk about that
parents in this program, while they appreciate it, didn't use it to
get a vastly better education, used it instead to get a very
religious education at unaccredited schools. So if this scholarship
program is to show that we should have tax-funded vouchers, the
move to religious school raises constitutional problems with mixing
church and state and changes the very nature of public education
from a public good to a private commodity. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
