<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SAFETY22-2NDLE     04-21 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SAFETY22-2NDLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OFFICIALS PRAY, PONDER HOW TO CUT SCHOOL VIOLENCE
 &HT;    Eds: Updates in 7th graf with Reno visit planned.
 &HT;    480&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the White House to Congress, federal officials
struggled Wednesday to express national sorrow for the mass
violence in Littleton, Colo., and to start yet another search for
ways to increase safety in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Moments of silent prayer, meditation and condolences to the
families of the victims were led in the White House by President
Clinton and on the House floor by Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deep desire to comfort the grieving and counsel
with children,''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, a former high school teacher and wrestling coach, had a
message for the parents of students at Columbine High School: ``As
a parent of two boys, I can only imagine the grief you are feeling
today as you try to make sense of yesterday's tragic events.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said, ``It is very important to explain to children all
over America what has happened and to reassure our own children
that they are safe (and) to hammer home to all the children of
America that violence is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said agents from the Federal Bureau of Investigation and
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms were already assisting
local law enforcement authorities. School and community leaders
were offered help from grief counselors and other post-crisis
consultants at a federally supported center in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   He also cleared his schedule for Thursday, in case state and
local officials request a visit by him. A visit was planned by
Attorney General Janet Reno, who along with Education Secretary
Richard Riley last August mailed a security manual to every one of
the nation's more than 100,000 public and private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said the decision not to visit Littleton on Wednesday was
reached during late-night consultations between officials of
several departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a mistake for people like me to go soaring in
while the local people are trying to sort out the tragedy,'' Riley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to requests from ``many'' senators, Chairman Jim
Jeffords, R-Vt., announced that his Senate Committee on Health,
Education, Labor and Pensions would hold hearings on school
violence in May.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., said the ``terrible tragedy in the
heart of the nation'' might lead to new gun control and gun safety
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 14 children die every single day from gun violence''
outside schools, Kennedy said. ``But none of us here is coming up
with a silver bullet to solve all of those problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., said Congress and society should find
a way to counter ``a culture of violence'' that includes
literature, gangsta rap and video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't things government can have much to do with,'' he
said. But he said that parents should realize that ``disrespect for
life'' can grow out of video games in which a child ``may punch out
an opponent on a machine _ kill, kill, kill _ just by punching a
button on a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., said the Littleton violence might
increase the chances of approval of his bill requiring the Justice
Department to spend $2 million setting up a new School Security
Center at Sandia National Laboratories in his home state and giving
schools $30 million over three years to buy technology recommended
by the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, by installing cameras, schools could be
forewarned of problems, and law enforcement can use those cameras
in situations like the hostage situation that occurred in
Colorado,'' Bingaman said.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, Wednesday was the day on which the House and
Senate overwhelmingly approved a compromise version of this year's
first education bill, which Clinton has agreed to sign.
</P>
<P>
   One short clause in the Educational Flexibility bill, which
gives schools more flexibility in spending federal funds, will make
it easier for school officials to expel a student who possesses a
gun on school property.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, some students wiggled out of expulsion by arguing
that mere possession of a gun that they might have discovered
inside a school did not prove that they had violated the federal
ban on bringing a gun onto school property.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
