<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     04-21 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MORGAN': THE FACTS DON'T SUPPORT THE IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the introduction to her authoritative new biography of John
Pierpont Morgan (1837-1913), Jean Strouse makes a startling
confession about her experience in writing ``Morgan: American
Financier,'' her first book since ``Alice James: A Biography'' was
published in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent years availing herself of a virtually untouched
trove of uncatalogued biographical documents in the Pierpont Morgan
Library in New York, as well as additional material in private
hands, at the Morgan Grenfell archives in London and other
repositories on both sides of the Atlantic, she eventually began to
write and got about halfway through a draft when she saw that it
wasn't working.
</P>
<P>
   She explains: ``Months later I realized why. From the outset I
had found Morgan's detractors more convincing than his champions:
they were better writers, they reflected popular American
assumptions (including my own) about the `robber baron' chapter of
our history, and their bracing hostility gave the story force. The
advocates, by comparison, seemed defensive and fawning. As a
result, I had been looking for a modified, human-scale version of
the `boss croupier' of Wall Street _ the cynical tycoon who
subjected the entire U.S. economy'' to what E.L. Doctorow, writing
about Morgan in his novel ``Ragtime,'' referred to as ``the
psychopathology of his will.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``this was not what I had found,'' she writes. ``The
evidence didn't support the picture I had pre-emptively drawn, and
I hadn't been noticing what it did suggest.''
</P>
<P>
   What adjustments did Ms. Strouse then make that have permitted
her to write a book that does indeed work in offering a coherent
portrait of Morgan? One set of revelations has to do with his
personality. Popular iconography has given us an image of Morgan
that is brusque, arrogant, unapproachable, imperious and
overwhelming in its force. While Ms. Strouse confirms this side of
him, she also shows us a man who was mercurial; given to depression
and nervous exhaustion; possessed of what one friend called ``a
very feminine streak in his nature''; flirtatious; vulnerable to
flattery, and occasionally so sensitive to criticism that some felt
that his appearance in 1912 before a House Banking and Currency
subcommittee trying to establish the existence of a ruling ``money
trust'' helped bring on his terminal illness.
</P>
<P>
   Another dimension of Ms. Strouse's portrait reveals more about
Morgan as a great collector of art. His image here, too, has not
always been flattering. The connoisseur Bernard Berenson once
remarked of Morgan's London house, ``It looks like a pawnbroker's
shop for Croesuses.'' The critic Roger Fry delivered a summary
judgment that, in the author's words, ``has defined Morgan as
collector for generations of scholars and readers: `A crude
historical imagination,' the critic wrote, `was the only flaw in
his otherwise perfect insensibility (to art).'''
</P>
<P>
   As a corrective to these remarks, Ms. Strouse reveals a man
whose sensuous nature was deeply attracted to art, who put himself
in the hands of experts and whose ``larger project'' was ``to
harvest `the best' of the world's cultural past for the American
future.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is of Morgan as a financier that Ms. Strouse offers the
most profound revision. His eloquent detractors have portrayed him
as a ``great financial Gorgon'' set on squeezing to death the
farmer and the working man for the sake of his own profit. But
while conceding he was ``tone-deaf to the sensitivities of people
whose interests did not coincide with his own,'' she argues that in
his own mind at least, his interests were always identical to
whatever would benefit the public.
</P>
<P>
   His motive for organizing trusts was not to monopolize products
but to organize markets more efficiently for the sake of everyone's
profit. His bank's manipulations during panics were consistently
meant to stabilize the market, no matter how profitable they might
prove (and often enough they didn't). His defense of the gold
standard was as much to sustain the flow of European capital into
America as it was to protect his own interests.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, Ms. Strouse writes: ``When Pierpont Morgan died in 1913,
at 75, he was the most powerful banker in the world. He had
organized giant railroad systems and corporate `trusts,' presided
over a massive transfer of wealth from Europe to the United States,
and, at a time when America had no central bank, acted as a monitor
of its capital markets and lender of last resort. In the process he
helped transform a largely agrarian society into a modern
industrial state _ and entered into a struggle over the nature of
the country's identity that dates back to Jefferson and Hamilton.''
</P>
<P>
   Woven together, Ms. Strouse's revelations tell a story whose
interest is only limited by the inherent dryness of banking as an
activity. After all, what Morgan essentially did when he wasn't
abroad buying art and seducing women was simply to judge financial
opportunities, raise money and issue bonds. Even his philanthropy,
while heroic, was straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   As authoritative as her text is, her footnotes extend her reach
in fascinating directions. In one, she quotes Theodore Roosevelt in
his autobiography on why trust-busting was NOT the way to control
corporate concentration; government regulation was. In another she
reveals that British diplomat Cecil Spring-Rice ``wrote the lyrics
to `I Vow to Thee My Country,' which became the favorite hymn of
Diana, Princess of Wales, and was played at her wedding and
funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   And in yet another she reveals that Morgan did, after all, have
one admirer on the left. ``In speaking of the capitalists who
strive only for profit, only to get rich,'' Stalin, of all people,
told H.G. Wells in an interview, ``I do not want to say that these
are the most worthless people capable of nothing else. . . . We
Soviet people learn a great deal from the capitalists. And Morgan,
whom you characterize so unfavorably, was undoubtedly a good,
capable organizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is an understated way of putting what Ms. Strouse has
argued with such force here.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MORGAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American Financier' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Jean Strouse  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 796 pages. Random House. $34.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
