<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0422-     04-21 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0422-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVARS STYMIED FROM FLIGHT IN ALL DIRECTIONS, AS BALKAN
CONFLICT WIDENS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-APACHES-0422; ALBANIA-SHELLING-0422.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Trouble intensified Wednesday at all three
borders where Kosovar Albanian refugees are trying to flee, as the
Balkans conflict widened with new Serbian aggression against
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   All the exits from Kosovo posed problems for ethnic Albanians
trying to escape the Serbian ethnic cleansing campaign there.
</P>
<P>
   With border tensions rising, relief efforts will concentrate on
moving refugees to where they are welcome as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the Clinton administration decided Wednesday to
allow Kosovo refugees to come to the United States for shelter
rather than sending them to the U.S. military base in Guantanamo,
Cuba, as originally anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, announced by Vice President Al Gore in a speech at
Ellis Island in New York, the U.S. gateway for millions of
immigrants, was in part an effort to relieve pressures on
neighboring Macedonia, a top U.N. refugee official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the American ideals highlighted by Ellis Island
hold the key to peace, tolerance and diversity throughout the
world,'' Gore said. ``We are determined to see a free and peaceful
Kosovo, and one day see democracy throughout the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   Serb assaults on villages in Montenegro Wednesday were blocking
or diverting the flight of refugees heading west into that
autonomous province of Yugoslavia, according to Nicholas Morris,
the special envoy to the Balkans region for the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
   The Serb attacks apparently were directed at bases in Montenegro
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA, and they were forcing
refugees to look for ways out of the province they had thought
would afford safety.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here Wednesday Morris said the border
between Montenegro and Croatia had been closed by Serb forces,
cutting off that escape route. Some refugees were trying to find
safe haven by crossing further northwest into Bosnia. At least
20,000 had left Montenegro to the south, coming into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Morris expressed concern over destabilization of Montenegro, as
Serb forces continued their effort to take control of the
Montenegrin police that have remained largely independent and
neutral in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   People apparently were being diverted from crossing into Albania
at the main border point just north of here. Only a handful have
crossed since Yugoslavia cut diplomatic relations with Albania on
Sunday, despite earlier reports that thousands were headed to this
border and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   And more shooting across Albania's northern border was reported
Tuesday and Wednesday, during which two Albanian soldiers were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The deteriorating security situation in northern Albania has
prompted humanitarian aid organizations to redouble efforts to
remove as many as possible of the estimated 130,000 refugees from
this region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time a shell, God forbid, drops in a refugee camp
here, this question of relocating refugees will be academic,''
Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, where thousands of refugees were being prevented
from entering the country, authorities emptied a desolate frontier
no man's land of refugees in darkness Wednesday, ending a two-day
ordeal of rain, filth and captivity on the heels of the refugees'
expulsions from homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said Macedonia's government needed guarantees that
further refugees it accepts would be moved out quickly to avoid
upsetting the country's ethnic balance, estimated to be 25 percent
ethnic Albanian before the refugee exodus began.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia came under sharp criticism from international aid
agencies earlier this month after it kept up to 80,000 Kosovar
Albanian refugees penned up for more than a week in a squalid,
shelterless no man's land at Blace, a few miles from the capital,
Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   This time, at the Lojane crossing, Macedonian officials moved a
bit faster. But aid agencies were again critical, saying they were
prevented from bringing in supplies to the 3,000 trapped refugees,
or from quickly moving them to established camps where they would
at least have food and shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Albania the border remained eerily quiet, after a rush
of about 35,000 refugees between last Friday and the sudden halt of
people midday on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The respite caused anxious concern for the fate of those still
inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea how many, but there are tens or hundreds of
thousands of people who want to leave,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of new refugees to shelter and feed has given relief
agencies a grace period to prepare new tent camps and try to coax
refugees from the border area.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon the first NATO helicopter evacuations
took place, and about 116 refugees were ferried to Peskopje, about
60 miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is carrying out refugees who are ``vulnerable'' and
would have difficulty making a road trip out due to age or illness.
However, the refugees waiting for the choppers said they simply had
volunteered to leave and didn't have any particular problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather delayed these first experimental flights by more
than three hours. Had the Italian military trucks that carried the
refugees out to the airfield simply driven them off to Peskopje,
they probably would have arrived sooner than they did by awaiting
the helicopters' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour wait in the trucks, in cloudy, cold and damp
weather, the refugees did receive a food ration package courtesy of
the U.N. World Food Programme.
</P>
<P>
   British Lt. Gen. John Reith, commander of NATO's new
humanitarian effort, came for the first flights but didn't stick
around long enough to see them happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we don't want them (refugees) within range of
artillery fire,'' he said. ``We don't want them to be targets.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
