<HEADER>
A7832 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ADVANCE-HNS &LR;      04-21 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALKAN FIGHT CAST SHADOW ON NATO SUMMIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A little war can just ruin a birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a gala celebration this weekend to mark NATO's 50th
anniversary have become a victim of the fight in the Balkans _ a
conflict that tests the alliance's resolve and relevance.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day summit, beginning Friday, will be a far different
event than was being planned a month ago when NATO, in its first
attack ever on a sovereign nation, began the air campaign against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the glitz of tuxedoes and black ties. Gone is the
military flyover. Gone is any hint of triumphalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a party. It's a commemoration of 50 years of what we
believe is the most important alliance we have: NATO,'' said White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining ceremonies have been trimmed to allow a session of
at least two hours in which leaders of the 19 member nations can,
for the first time since the Yugoslav campaign began, have a
face-to-face discussion of the air assault, its prospects and what
it means for the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents and prime ministers, who set the parameters for
NATO's military action, may consider new economic sanctions against
Yugoslavia, a blockade of its ports and possibly whether an
invasion by ground troops should be considered.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana predicted only a more solid
allied front will emerge from the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of determination is total,'' Solana said. ``This is
not a conflict over territory or raw materials or strategic routes.
Only values are at stake here.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has responded snappishly to questions about how
the Yugoslav operation has altered once rosy plans for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have adjusted the schedule to reflect the fact that there
is a military conflict ongoing in Kosovo,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   But more than scheduling is at stake. For some analysts, the
NATO fight with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic threatens the
alliance's existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many are predicting this will be the funeral of NATO,'' said
Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   It is, at least, a time of testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think NATO is on the line now,'' said retired Air Force Gen.
Brent Scowcroft, who was national security adviser to Presidents
Ford and Bush. ``If we do not succeed here, NATO will be severely
strained, if not fractured.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joe Biden of Delaware, ranking Democrat on the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee and a supporter of Clinton policy, said
Wednesday that if NATO had not moved against Milosevic and, now, if
he is not defeated, the alliance ``would have been finished.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very delicate point in NATO's maturation process,''
Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   The North Atlantic Treaty Organization is generally acknowledged
as the most successful military alliance in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the recent chaos, it is important to remind ourselves
that in its earlier respects, NATO worked,'' editorialized the
Spectator, a British establishment weekly. ``It brought Europe the
longest period of peace in its history. ... Confronted, the Soviet
Union eventually crumbled.''
</P>
<P>
   The birthday summit was planned, in fact, to show off NATO's
growing ties with former Soviet satellites, especially the new
alliance membership of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Even Russia, as a participant in Partnership for Peace, the
so-called ``NATO Light,'' was invited. But the Kremlin's strong
opposition to NATO's air campaign against fellow Slavs has raised
doubts that Russia will even be represented.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the presence of the leaders of at least 43 member nations
of the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council will make the summit the
biggest international gathering _ and security headache _ ever in
the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   To clear out the summit area in downtown Washington, and make
room for dozens of intricately choreographed motorcades, 90,000
federal employees are being given a day off from work Friday. Much
of the area will be closed to any but official traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The opening ceremony will still mark the half century since
NATO's founding and be held in the neoclassical Mellon Auditorium,
where the alliance-founding Treaty of Washington was signed on
April 4, 1949, under the watchful gaze of President Truman.
</P>
<P>
   The new focus on the the Yugoslav campaign has prompted
postponement of an expected debate on when new members might be
added and a long-planned discussion and possible decision on when
NATO would go into combat outside the territory of one of its 19
members.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the agenda shifts, Solana has tried to make a virtue
of what the alliance leaders believe is a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the age of 50, NATO has left the passive, reactive approach
of the Cold War and today NATO is setting the security agenda in
ways we could only dream about decades ago,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
