<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7835 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BUDGET-SURPLUS     04-21 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BUDGET-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO COSTS COMING OUT OF FEDERAL BUDGET SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even if the United States were to enter into a
full-scale war, complete with ground troops, against Yugoslavia,
the cost would not eat up the government's huge budget surplus,
although it could take a bite out of it, an expert said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might lop $20 billion to $30 billion off of it,'' said
Robert Reischauer, a former Congressional Budget Office (CBO)
director who is a scholar at the Brookings Institution here. ``But
when we are dealing with a surplus of $110 billion, we've got some
leeway here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reischauer explained, however, that his estimate would be
reached only if the United States deploys ground troops, tanks and
other equipment in the next few months to secure Kosovo, the
southern province of Serbia, which is the dominant republic of
Yugoslavia. The $110 billion surplus is projected for the fiscal
1999 budget year, which ends Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The bite out of the surplus is more likely to be between the $6
billion that President Clinton requested this week to continue the
anti-Yugoslavia bombing campaign through September and around $10
billion, which some Republicans have said is needed.
</P>
<P>
   For this fiscal year, congressional leaders have said they
intend to pay for any Kosovo-related costs out of the surplus
rather than offset them with cuts to other programs, and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he wants to keep the
total cost in the ``single-digit range.''
</P>
<P>
   For the future, however, some Republicans want to boost defense
spending even at the expense of the party's cherished plans to cut
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president sent us a request which I believe to be
deficient to our needs,'' said House Majority Leader Richard Armey,
R-Texas. He declined to say how much higher the Kosovo spending
should be, but said Congress in next year's budget may have to cut
domestic spending and the Republicans may have to scale back their
proposed $800 billion tax cut over 10 years to finance broader
defense needs beyond Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo spending is exacerbating the larger debate over what to
do with the surplus after sequestering most of it to bolster Social
Security. The nation's retirement system will have enough money to
pay full benefits until 2034. At that point, unless the system is
changed, benefits will have to be cut or payroll taxes raised.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the surplus, most Democrats want to use it to
shore up Medicare, the health insurance program for the elderly and
disabled, and to increase funding for domestic programs. Most
Republicans want to use it for defense and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In the budget plan that Congress approved last week, lawmakers
from both parties agreed to set aside $1.8 trillion of the
projected $2.3 trillion surplus over the next 10 years for Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   In figuring the surplus, the government includes the Social
Security trust fund's surplus. If that number is excluded, the
government would actually have a deficit this year of $16 billion,
according to the CBO, or $42 billion, according to the White House
budget office. And over the next decade, the surplus would total
$600 billion, not $2.3 trillion, if Social Security is excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's costs in future years would depend on whether ground
troops are deployed, how many are dispatched, how much humanitarian
aid for refugees is needed and how much the United States will
spend on rebuilding Kosovo. President Clinton has said he thinks
the figure should be 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Budget experts say the air war over Yugoslavia is now costing
the United States about $1 billion a month. The CBO estimates that
ground troops might cost about $300 million a month while other
analysts put the figure closer to $1 billion a month.
</P>
<P>
   As for refugee aid, the CBO says it cannot estimate the exact
amount, but it noted that the United States spent $254 million in
humanitarian aid and $306 million in reconstruction aid for Bosnia
in 1996. The United States has been paying an additional $200
million a year since them.
</P>
<P>
   Once the fighting ends, CBO estimates it would cost about $600
million a year to keep U.S. troops in Kosovo as part of a NATO
peacekeeping force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1816EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
