<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7839 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-DISABLED-HNS &LR;      04-21 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-DISABLED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT WEIGHS STATE'S RIGHT TO CHOOSE CARE FOR MENTALLY DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a case that could produce the decade's most
important ruling on treatment for mental patients, the U.S. Supreme
Court on Wednesday heard Georgia state officials argue that they
should be allowed to choose where the patients receive care.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials want the authority to decide whether a mental
patient should stay in a state mental hospital or be moved to a
less restrictive facility, such as community care centers.
</P>
<P>
   Mental health advocates disagreed, arguing that mental patients
who receive approval from a doctor to move from a mental hospital
to a care center have the right under the 1990 Americans with
Disabilities Act (ADA) to be transferred and that the move should
be done within a few weeks of the approval.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA requires increased access to public and private
facilities and programs for disabled individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Disability rights groups prefer community care centers, as
opposed to state mental institutions. The advocates for the
disabled say the community centers allow patients to lead more
productive lives and to interact with society because the centers
are generally group houses in residential communities with medical
support staff.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is Title II of the ADA, which applies to public
services offered by state and local governments. It provides that
``no qualified individual with a disability shall, by reason of
such disability, be excluded from participation in'' or ``be
subjected to discrimination'' by a government program or service.
</P>
<P>
   The court must also consider ADA regulations that require the
services to be administered in the ``most integrated setting
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of the phrase ``most integrated setting'' quickly
became the focus of the arguments before the justices.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Senior Assistant Attorney General Patricia Downing told
the court that states should be free to choose between community
settings and large state hospitals so long as each institution
provides proper care for the patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot be assumed that because one option is appropriate,
another is inappropriate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gottesman, a Georgetown University law professor
representing two mentally disabled women, argued that the most
integrated setting for his clients was with ``everyday people and
not in an institution.''
</P>
<P>
   He said forcing the two women to wait for assignment to a
community center amounted to ``isolation and segregation from the
societal mainstream of American life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Antonin Scalia, who appeared sympathetic to the
state, immediately shot back: ``This isn't isolation. They're not
being locked in rooms against their will.''
</P>
<P>
   The two women, Lois Curtis and Elaine Wilson, were free to leave
the state hospital at any time, although leaving would have meant
an end to state medical aid.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyer Irving Gornstein, representing the
Clinton administration, joined Gottesman in calling for the ADA to
require states to place qualified mental patients in community
centers.
</P>
<P>
   But Justices Stephen G. Breyer and John Paul Stevens voiced
concerns that adding such a requirement might end up harming the
people whom the law seeks to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me is writing something which, as it works out in
the real world, leaves many who need to be in institutions, out _
abandoned on the streets,'' Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said state institutions could feel pressured to transfer
nearly all of their mentally disabled patients to community care
centers, including those who were unable to cope with society, to
avoid violating the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that states will have a motive and incentive to
push people out on the streets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that some states may stop offering community care
services to avoid the costs of transferring patients from state
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Both a district court in 1997 and the 11th Circuit Court of
Appeals in 1998 ruled in favor of the two women, saying that
placing mental patients in community care centers is required
unless it would fundamentally change a state's services to the
patients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Supreme Court, disability rights organizations, such
as ADAPT and representatives of the Bazelon Center for Mental
Health Law, demonstrated in support of Curtis and Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Anthony, spokeswoman for ADAPT, said the lawsuit was a
symbolic civil rights case that follows decades of government
segregation of disabled people in mental health institutions.
</P>
<P>
   She said that if Curtis and Wilson lose their case, it could
mean a return to the institutionalization of the mentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must destroy this shameful wall of exclusion separating
people with disabilities from other Americans,'' she said before a
crowd of people in wheelchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, about 70,000 mental patients are in state hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The importance placed on this case by advocacy groups could be
seen over the past few months as they organized demonstrations and
mass mailings in many of the 26 states that had formed a coalition
in support of Georgia's appeal by signing a brief as friends of the
court.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the lobbying efforts, 19 of the states backed out
of the coalition by the time Georgia filed its final brief.
</P>
<P>
   The states remaining in Georgia's camp are Indiana, Tennessee,
Mississippi, Hawaii, South Carolina, Montana, Nevada, Wyoming,
Washington, Texas and Colorado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
