<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUL-LEWITT-MURAL-ART-     04-21 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUL-LEWITT-MURAL-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIE'S BRINGS A NEW MURAL TO ROCKEFELLER CENTER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Soaring three stories inside the entrance to 20
Rockefeller Plaza is a mural by the Conceptual artist Sol LeWitt,
its colors so intense and its surface so glossy that it still looks
wet.
</P>
<P>
   While the wet look may suggest fast work, the mural, which
envelops the entrance to Christie's new American headquarters, took
weeks of painstaking sanding to achieve its smooth surface. Then a
team of four painters spent three weeks, working six days a week,
painting, sanding and varnishing to complete the job for Christie's
opening on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month ago nobody except the artist and his team
believed the project _ the first mural to be installed in the
original complex of buildings that make up Rockefeller Center since
1946 _ would be completed as planned. To begin with, the walls had
to be properly prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is always the hardest part of the job and takes a lot of
work,'' said LeWitt, who arrived one morning in late March from his
Connecticut home to survey the work. ``These new walls should not
have a blemish. They should be as smooth as a car's surface, or a
mirror.'' If not, he cautioned, every imperfection becomes a
glaring eyesore when the paint is applied.
</P>
<P>
   That morning the walls were still not as smooth as LeWitt
wanted. The construction crew was instructed to keep sanding and
re-sanding until the walls were glasslike to the touch, and this
was more of an ordeal than anyone had anticipated. It delayed the
project by a week.
</P>
<P>
   Then LeWitt's crew was told that its eight members could not
pick up their paintbrushes until they joined the local painter's
union, a demand he had not encountered on previous projects. His
painters duly joined the union.
</P>
<P>
   Projects of this size are often fraught with problems no matter
how careful the planning. It was over a year ago that officials at
Christie's first contacted Pace Wildenstein, LeWitt's gallery,
about designing a mural for the auction house's new offices. ``It
was a natural to commission a mural because of the space and
because of the history of Rockefeller Center,'' Christopher Burge,
chairman of Christie's in America, said.
</P>
<P>
   The original buildings that make up Rockefeller Center, designed
and constructed through the 1930s by a consortium of architects led
by Raymond Hood, were part of a coherent plan combining several
skyscrapers, outdoor spaces and public art.
</P>
<P>
   Such artists as Isamu Noguchi, Josef Albers, Paul Manship,
Gaston Lachaise, Jose Maria Sert and Stuart Davis were commissioned
to design sculptures, panels and murals for both indoor and outdoor
spaces. (Diego Rivera designed a mural for the lobby of the RCA
Building, but it was removed when the artist refused to alter a
panel glorifying Lenin.)
</P>
<P>
   Because Rockefeller Center is a landmark, the only alteration
the New York City Landmarks Commission allowed Christie's to make
to the building's exterior was to enlarge the windows at the
entrance. ``Our landlords were keen that we do something to animate
the street,'' said Burge. Six windows, three stories high, give
passers-by a peek into the auction house and a view of the mural,
titled ``Wall Drawing No. 896, Colors/Curves.''
</P>
<P>
   The design _ giant curves and undulations of red, yellow, blue,
lavender, green, orange and black _ is by far the boldest and the
brightest by the artist. ``They chose the one I'd hoped they'd
pick,'' said LeWitt, who had offered four designs, including two in
black and white. ``It just seemed best for the space.''
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt, now 70, has designed many murals for public buildings,
including one in the Equitable Building in which bands of lines in
four directions soar six stories, and one under way for the lobby
of a new hotel in Battery Park City. In each of these projects
LeWitt conceived the design and his assistants have carried it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out doing everything myself, but then the projects
got too big,'' he said when asked why he does not paint such murals
himself. ``They do it much better than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   LeWitt began his career working with pencil and paper in the
1950s. He first drew attention for geometric sculptures of white
three-dimensional grids that earned him a temporary place among the
Minimalists.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1960s he was one of the leaders of the movement that
became known as Conceptual Art, and was transferring his gridded
structures into two dimensions by drawing them on walls. He often
reduced his work to a series of instructions that others would
execute.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1980s he had moved from austere linear designs to
geometric shapes in rich primary colors. Last year he created a
mural for Pace Wildenstein's SoHo gallery with dense patterns
similar to those of two of the designs he offered to Christie's.
This latest work, with its bold colors and more free-hand
undulations, seems a logical progression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from pencil to crayon to ink to acrylic,'' LeWitt said.
The design, which is executed in acrylic paints, recalls late
Matisse collages like ``Jazz,'' and some of the stained glass
designs Matisse executed toward the end of his life for a chapel in
Vence in the South of France.
</P>
<P>
   When LeWitt began working on the Christie's designs, he said, it
wasn't Rockefeller Center he had in mind so much as the space.
``Rockefeller Center is a work of art in itself,'' he said. ``It
resonates with history.''
</P>
<P>
   The space _ a rectangular, boxlike entrance 29.6 feet high and
17.6 feet wide _ leads into the heart of the auction house. LeWitt
said he conceived of the work as a giant panel, like a 15th-century
gesso painting. ``I thought of it as the world's largest
miniature,'' he said. ``It's like a big box in which I had to
figure out how to visually enter the space and move around it. It
had to be bright, shiny, intense, because the area is so
compressed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   John Hogan, who has been part of LeWitt's team for about 20
years and jokingly calls himself a mixologist, prepares every
bucket of paint. The colors, which come from a Swiss manufacturer,
don't change, but his ``recipe'' calls for other ingredients like
retarders to slow the drying process, distilled water and a binder.
As he stirs on and on he says the paint is ``still cooking.'' As
with a seasoned chef, only he knows when the consistency feels
right.
</P>
<P>
   Sachiko Cho, who leads the artist's crew, works out the design
directly on the wall, at a scale 15 times larger than the maquette.
Once the walls are sanded, she measures and tapes the design in
place, marking each area with numbers, like in a paint-by-numbers
set, to indicate where each color should go. After each coat of
paint the surface is sanded smooth, covered with varnish and sanded
again, a total of seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sol doesn't mind a bit of handiwork showing,'' said Ms. Cho.
``That way it doesn't look as if the paint has been sprayed.'' What
makes the colors so rich and saturated, she said, is the layering
technique. The varnish in particular makes the whole design seem to
pop out from the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Is LeWitt worried that the mural will fade over time, no longer
appearing as if he has just put down his brush? ``Come back in 100
years,'' the artist said. ``That's the only way to tell.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
