<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ ANNOUNCES ITS `DISAPPOINTING' FIRST QUARTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas) (rk) 
 By   SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confirming the bad news that led to the ouster of its chief
executive this week, the Compaq Computer Corp. announced Wednesday
that it earned $281 million in the first quarter, or 16 cents a
share, half of what analysts had expected only two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall results were disappointing, and they were
unacceptable,'' Benjamin M. Rosen, the company's chairman and
acting chief executive, said in a conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosen declined to provide much new information to illuminate
the sources of Compaq's problems or to outline its path back to
financial health.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McCarthy, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
said, ``We want to know what went wrong and what their action plan
is to fix it, and the details are still murky on both.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 9, Compaq warned that its sales and earnings would be
below expectations because of price pressure and weaker demand in
the market for business computers. Then last Sunday, Compaq's board
called for the resignation of Eckhard Pfeiffer, the chief executive
since late 1991, and Earl L. Mason, the chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sales were $7.8 billion in the quarter, up 40
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, based in Houston, attributed its disappointing profit to
weak demand from businesses for both personal computers and the
larger systems sold by two recent acquisitions, the Digital
Equipment Corp. and Tandem Computers.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq said its services business _ the sale of programming,
consulting and other advice _ met its own targets, as did the
consumer unit.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it sold 3.5 million computers in the first
quarter, about what industry analysts had expected. But a greater
percentage of those were low-margin machines, including home PCs
selling for $600. Moreover, it has had to cut prices on business
PCs to match competitors.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company's gross profit margin _ sales minus the
cost of goods _ was 24.7 percent. That is up from 18 percent a year
ago but down from 26.4 percent in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the biggest problems appeared to be the slow and
difficult integration of Digital and Tandem and the complexities of
finding a way to match the efficiencies of Dell Computer _ which
sells directly to customers _ without offending the dealers who
provide the bulk of Compaq's current sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to blame industry conditions rather than their own
decisions more than I would,'' said Steven Milunovich, an analyst
at Merrill Lynch. ``My guess is they are losing share in the
corporate market to Dell and that DEC and Tandem are weak.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's shares closed Wednesday at $24.25, up 25 cents, less
than half the 52-week high of $51.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
