r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING:-ATEEN-REACT     04-21 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING:-A </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCEPTANCE MAY BE KEY TO HEALING CAMPUSES
</HEADLINE>
 TEEN-REACTS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW S. COLGLAZIER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why? Why? Why? Why? Why?
</P>
<P>
   That was the only word that ran through my mind as I watched the
news programs' pictures of students and parents trying to piece
together the tragedy unfolding before them.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to scream.
</P>
<P>
   What horror had occurred in Littleton, Colo.?
</P>
<P>
   Why did two students kill 13 people?
</P>
<P>
   Why had people been arbitrarily executed by these students full
of fear, hatred and hurt?
</P>
<P>
   On television, I saw boys my own age crying and hugging
classmates, and parents running to look at lists of the students
who made it out safely. All were so upset by their personal loss.
</P>
<P>
   But those of us who don't go to that high school must feel
something else. Dejection _ and disgust for the hate that caused
this tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of differences that end up in tragic shootouts. Tired of
looking over our shoulders every time another high school gets shot
up.
</P>
<P>
   But now we cannot see.
</P>
<P>
   Our eyes are clouded with tears for those lost, both the killers
and the victims.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to move forward. The healing of American high schools
is long overdue. The same anger that caused these shootings must
not interfere with the process that MUST take place.
</P>
<P>
   Students must pay more attention to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Look for signs that might seem dangerous or threatening.
Confront friends who use racial slurs, even jokingly. Break the
code of silence that surrounds kids who might be involved in
activities dangerous to themselves and others.
</P>
<P>
   Compassion is an exercise in both tolerance and patience.
</P>
<P>
   We as high school students must have tolerance of others'
opinions and appearance and skin color, and the patience to deal
with differences instead of seeking revenge.
</P>
<P>
   We must accept.
</P>
<P>
   For parents, the compassion that must be shown at school must be
shown at home. Communication skills are taught by example from the
earliest age.
</P>
<P>
   And the guns must be put away. Students who have the direct
resources to further their fanaticism WILL do so.
</P>
<P>
   This is the last time we can let this happen.
</P>
<P>
   All high school communities must move forward, weary of the past
but hopeful for the future; careful not to censure or militarize
but to nurture and communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Change can come only through a shift in student attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Our generation must be called to stand for something, and the
word ``acceptance'' is crying out.
</P>
<P>
   Boys who did not feel accepted in Colorado decided not to accept
others, and the pain they caused is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to heal our high schools and move toward the promise
of acceptance and real communication.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matthew S. Colglazier is a senior at Paschal High School in Fort
Worth. He wrote this commentary for the Star-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
