<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE LEAD OUT OF PEWTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Does modern British pewter contain lead? I have a pewter
tankard and would like to drink out of it. _ U.C., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Although early pewter contained as much as 40 percent lead,
Britannia pewter was introduced by metalsmiths in the 18th century
with 90 percent to 95 percent tin, 5 percent to 10 percent antimony
and ``virtually no lead,'' according to a 1994 ``Country Living''
article.
</P>
<P>
   American pewter manufacturers agreed in 1972 to restrict lead
content to 1/2000th of a product's total weight, but some products
are still being sold with unsafe lead levels. Shirley Pewter Co.
recalled pewter baby cups in 1992 because of their lead content,
according to the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Because lead can leach into food and beverages, the FDA
recommended in 1993 that consumers ``limit the use of antique or
collectible housewares for food or beverages to special
occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Lead Information Center offers an information
package for consumers about the health concerns associated with
lead-based paint and other products. To request it, call (800)
532-3394.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did the cartoon featuring Fearless Fly air in the '60s?
_ R.P.T., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Fearless Fly appeared on ``The Milton the Monster Show,'' an
animated series originally broadcast on ABC from 1965 to 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Hiram the Fly puts on a pair of super glasses, he becomes
the assertive superhero Fearless Fly,'' series fan Dave Mackey
writes. ``Fearless adversaries include Dr. Goo Fee and Professor
Weirdo.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackey publishes a World Wide Web site devoted to ``Milton'' and
its producer, Hal Seeger.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
