<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7875 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-HOUSING-HNS &LR;      04-21 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUOMO CALLS PUBLIC HOUSING A `SUCCESS STORY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to counteract a long-standing negative
image of public housing, Andrew Cuomo, the secretary for housing
and urban development (HUD), on Wednesday called the federally
subsidized program a ``miraculous success story.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo cited a new survey showing 75 percent of public housing
residents are satisfied with their dwellings and he presided over a
ceremony here recognizing 630 public housing authorities as either
``high performers'' or ``successful performers.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary also unveiled a new HUD analysis of about 750
housing authorities, 22 percent of the nation's 3,400 such agencies
that manage the subsidized units. The survey showed that 87 percent
of the authorities were well managed and on sound financial ground.
</P>
<P>
   Physical inspections of the housing units operated by these
authorities showed 23 percent in excellent condition, 64 percent in
good condition and 13 percent needing improvement, Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, for decades, this nation has had a false
impression of public housing,'' Cuomo said, noting that many people
associate all public housing with Chicago's notorious,
drug-and-crime-plagued Cabrini Green housing project. But he added
that ``public housing is a miraculous, miraculous success story''
and insisted that the ``vast majority'' of the nation's 3,400
housing authorities are functioning well.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of residents and analysis of the 750 public housing
authorities did not include any major city such as New York,
Chicago, San Francisco or Los Angeles. Stan Vosper, HUD's chief
spokesman, said HUD would turn its attention to the larger cities
by October.
</P>
<P>
   Vosper also said HUD had not skewed the results of the survey
and analysis by omitting big cities. ``I'd expect some changes in
percentages as we complete our review of the entire stock (of
public housing), but our statisticians are telling us they believe
the final numbers will be quite close to what we're seeing today,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the housing authorities that Cuomo recognized were those
in San Beunaventura, Calif.; Cohoes, Mechanicville and Watervliet
in New York, and New Braunfels, Poteet, Bastrop, Cotulla, Odessa
and Seguin in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, HUD oversees 14,000 developments that house 1.3 million
low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Big cities are where the vast majority of public housing
residents reside, and they are the places where local housing
authorities have been in the most trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, the Department of Housing and Urban Development has
kept a list of ``troubled'' housing authorities. Typically, the
authorities on the list have a history of financial mismanagement
and an inability to keep their housing units safe and in good
repair.
</P>
<P>
   Housing authorities in San Francisco, Chicago, New Orleans and
Detroit have been on and off the list over the last two decades. Of
the four, only San Francisco's authority is still on the list,
although Chicago's is now under direct HUD control.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993 when President Clinton was sworn in, HUD has made a
concerted effort to demolish big, dysfunctional housing units. With
large concentrations of the nation's poorest families, these
projects had become breeding grounds for crime, drug abuse and teen
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, HUD has knocked down 45,000 units and plans to
increase that total to 100,000 by 2002, Vosper said.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo called on the assembled public housing officials to help
rekindle the spirit of the 1930s, when public housing was started
under President Franklin D. Roosevelt. ``We can do it,'' he said.
``We have the capacity. We have the knowledge. (In the 1930s) we
had the right dream, the right aspiration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
