<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Thursday, April 22. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Ned Kilkelly. The final FRONTPAGE will move later in
the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Ledeall; The death
toll in the shooting at a suburban high school is at 15, with
several students in critical condition. Officers painstakingly
checked the sprawling school; close to 30 explosive devices were
found. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SUSPECTS (Littleton) _ The two 18-year-old suspects
were from affluent areas; one's father was a retired military man,
the other maybe a geologist. They dressed in black trench coats.
They had rich lives on Internet. Other students described them as
outsiders who were smart but did not get along with their peers. By
Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-COLUMBINE (Littleton) _ Columbine High School is
like a lot of suburban high schools, proud of its high SAT scores,
its winning sports teams. Last Friday the school had a giant sports
rally, followed Saturday night by a senior prom for which parents
had raised $50,000 for a no-alcohol after-prom party. It is the
kind of school where a teacher last year assigned her students to
read about the school shooting in Jonesboro, Ark., to help them
understand the real world. By Sarah Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ Amid talk of ground troops, British
are trying to force the issue because of the great lag time. The
U.S., wary of politics, is divided. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SUMMIT (Washington) _ As heads of NATO states began
arriving for the 50th anniversary of the alliance, they were
embarking on a summit transformed from a celebration of triumph to
a war council on the Balkans. Leaders say the future shape of the
alliance, which successfully stood up to Communism, is at stake. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PARKINSONS-FETAL (Washington) _ A team of government-funded
scientists announced today that they have relieved the symptoms of
Parkinson's Disease with transplants of tissue from aborted
fetuses, a discovery that establishes for the first time that the
damaged brain can actually be repaired. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
