<SLUG> BC-INS-OVERHAUL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD GRANT RESIDENCE TO SOME FOREIGN-BORN CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The head of a House immigration panel said he would
introduce legislation Thursday that would grant permanent residence
to foreign-born children of American citizens who face deportation
because of delays in handling their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children of many U.S. citizens are being unnecessarily
punished by the Immigration and Naturalization Service through
bureaucratic processing delays when they apply for legal
residence,'' Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by Smith, who is chairman of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on immigration, would ease some restrictions contained
in a 1996 law that tightened immigration rules. Smith also
sponsored that legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He cited the case of Montserrat Rodriguez of San Antonio as he
prepared the bill that would grant legal residence to immigrants
who turn 21 and have a U.S. citizen as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, a native of Mexico, is the step-daughter of an
American citizen and applied for legal residence when she was 19.
She turned 21 three weeks ago before the INS acted on her request
for permanent residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frustrated,'' said Rodriguez, an honor student at San
Antonio College. ``I wish I never would have turned 21.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of eligibility for legal residence means deportation
for many young immigrants living in families with a U.S. citizen as
a parent.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rodriguez has received permission to stay in the
country, she will be considered a foreign student and be required
to pay increased tuition. She will be ineligible for student loans
or federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez ``is in kind of a bureaucratic nightmare, a
Catch-22,'' said her lawyer, Bernard Fischman of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has really put her in a heck of a fix,'' Fischman said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's bill, the Child Status Protection Act of 1999, would
grant permanent residence status immediately to children of
American citizens if their applications are not processed by the
INS by their 21st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the bill could provide permanent residence to some
3,000 young people each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous that the INS has allowed the backlog for cases
such as this one to climb to more than a million, causing anxiety
for so many immigrant families,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Cardona, an INS spokeswoman, said the agency recognized
there are problems and has been seeking remedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is widespread support for changing the (current)
statute,'' Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has received support of the National Council of La
Raza, the nation's largest Hispanic rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Najar, an NCLR immigration policy analyst, said the bill
would soften strict legislation sponsored by Smith and passed in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a welcomed admission that people are getting caught up in
a black hole of INS bureaucracy and a nasty provision in the 1996
law,'' Najar said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was pleased Smith ``recognizes the bill he drafted in
1996 has its problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a shame, if every time these things pop up, we have
to have a small bill to take care of it,'' said Najar, who would
like to see Congress re-examine major potions of the 1996 overhaul
bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
