<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLSHOOT-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES PARENTS TO TEACH KIDS HOW TO RESOLVE CONFLICTS
PEACEFULLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER DAY 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As investigators in Littleton, Colo., struggled to
understand what provoked two young men to storm their school and
murder classmates, President Clinton said parents must reassure
children that they are safe and remind them that violence is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who canceled a Wednesday trip to Houston and Austin,
made the remarks during a speech to White House volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should take this moment to ask what else they can do
to shield our children from violent images and experiences that
warp young perceptions and obscure the consequences of violence, to
show our children, by the power of our own example, how to resolve
conflict peacefully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the president in conjunction with the departments of
education and justice announced a plan to prevent school violence
that included distribution of an ``Early Warning Guide.''
</P>
<P>
   The education department already had begun to revise the warning
handbook before Tuesday's shooting, said spokeswoman Melinda
Malico, but no details have been released as to what changes will
be made or when the new guide will be finished.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, said Education Secretary Richard Riley, $300
million has been earmarked for a school violence prevention
initiative and a proposal is pending in Congress to provide $12
million to help schools hit by incidents such as the one in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Education has helped coordinate counseling
efforts and has linked Columbine High School officials with
security experts and others who can help with long-term recovery,
said Joe Lockhart, White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Although local officials are handling the investigation, agents
from the Federal Bureau of Investigation and the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearm have provided technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The news of yet another schoolhouse shooting not only prompted
congressmen, presidential candidates and special interest groups
throughout the nation's capital to express their condolences to
those touched by the Littleton massacre, but started another debate
over what can be done to head off another such tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado shooting was at least the seventh school shooting
in the past 18 months in which a student has opened fire on
classmates and teachers. The other shootings combined killed 14
people and wounded more than 40.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the problem has to be done with a mix of
legislation and a ``bully pulpit function,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president has a unique role in bringing Americans
together and in raising issues, and I think this is an issue that
has consumed a significant amount of his time as far as trying to
raise the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The day started in Congress on Wednesday with a moment of
silence for those killed in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no easy answers to these questions, but some things
I do know,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. ``We must do
our best to make our schools safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The crime subcommittee of the House Judiciary Committee will
begin its day Friday by considering a bill to provide mental
counseling for youths who enter the juvenile justice system, said
Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas and chairwoman of the
Congressional Children's Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   However, unless youths such as the two gunmen in Littleton have
contact with the justice system, either through an arrest, truancy
or some other form of misbehavior, they may never get the help they
need.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
