<HEADER>
A7892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN22-COX     04-21 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debates over Kosovo, domestic harmony define chances for
presidency
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two very different debates are emerging as the two
parties begin the speeded-up process of picking presidential
candidates for next year. The outcome of the next election could
rest on which debate seems more vital in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The debate about Kosovo is being carried on almost entirely on
the Republican side. By the time Vice President Al Gore made his
first major speech on the subject Wednesday, the field of GOP
contenders had already defined a wide diversity of opinion on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona has emerged as the most hawkish
advocate of a wider war in the Balkans, with Elizabeth Dole not far
behind. Soon, they'll be taking their place in candidate forums
with Pat Buchanan, who has denounced the action against Serbia as
``an illegal, presidential war''; Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire,
who has introduced a resolution to cut off funding of the war; and
Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, who this week called for a negotiated
settlement with Yugoslav leader Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Unmentioned so far is the GOP frontrunner, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush _ which may be the most significant political development of
all.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may still have an overwhelming advantage, but barring
better news from the Balkans than anyone expects, he will be forced
to articulate a clear position on the war in the months ahead.
Whoever wins the Republican nomination will have their candidacy
forged in the debate over the war.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on the Democratic side _ and former Sen. Bill
Bradley's encouraging New Hampshire poll numbers insure there will
be one _ is much different.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has expressed some reservation about the
administration's strategy, and Gore, unsurprisingly, strongly
defended it in his speech Wednesday on Ellis Island. What
disagreement there is between the Democratic rivals on this subject
is largely unformed, however.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democratic activists, the speech more likely to stir
interest was the one Bradley gave in New York, only hours before
the shooting began in Colorado, about the need for racial healing
in America.
</P>
<P>
   There is the potential, at least, that the dialogue on the
Democratic side may evolve beyond civil rights homilies into a more
searching discussion of the nation's domestic insecurities, which
as Tuesday's tragedy demonstrated, can be every bit as baffling as
the the Balkan entanglement.
</P>
<P>
   Call this the debate over the Trench Coat Mafia. The Republican
candidates responded to the shootings, but in a manner that
promised no more formed a discussion of what happened in Littleton
than what the Democrats have said about the Balkan war. It's a
matter once again of articulation: Bradley seemed to address the
Littleton murders more directly before they happened than most of
the other candidates did in their aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush on the Balkans, Gore can't avoid this domestic debate.
It even sounded an eerie echo in the signature line of his Kosovo
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we really allow the 21st century to be shaped by men in
black ski masks with weapons in their hands and hatred in their
hearts?'' the vice president asked.
</P>
<P>
   Good question. But with only minor adjustments, it could be
asked about Colorado as well as about Kosovo
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
