<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT HEARS ARGUMENTS ON EXTENT OF STATES' OBLIGATION TO THE
DISABLED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hearing arguments in an important disability rights
case Wednesday, Supreme Court justices wrestled with what they
appeared to see as a pair of unpalatable alternatives: permit
states to continue confining people with severe disabilities in big
institutions, when such settings are not medically necessary, or
prompt the mass discharge of people who actually need close
supervision and care.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Justice Stephen G. Breyer told the lawyer for
two Georgia women with mental disabilities, who won the right to
care outside the big state hospital where they had lived for years:
``What worries me about your position is writing something that,
the way it works in the world, leads people to be thrown out and
abandoned on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy challenged a
Georgia state lawyer, who argued that federal law does not require
states to provide alternatives to institutionalization: ``You're
saying if hospitalization is excessive, so be it; the state can
make that judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   As presented to the court, this case _ the first of four
disability cases to be heard over the next week _ presents a
relatively narrow legal issue. The question is whether the Justice
Department is properly interpreting the Americans With Disabilities
Act to require that once a state offers treatment to people with
disabilities, the treatment must take place in a ``community
setting'' if that is medically appropriate and not unreasonably
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But in context, as part of the ongoing struggle over the meaning
of the sweeping yet vague disability law, no one regards this as a
narrow case: not Georgia, which describes the Justice Department
regulation as an unwelcome and unauthorized federal intrusion into
state prerogatives; not people with disabilities and their
advocates, who have described this case as the Brown vs. Board of
Education of the disability rights movement; and, it was evident
Wednesday, not the justices, who were unusually engaged by the
policy implications of the contrasting interpretations that were
put before them.
</P>
<P>
   The provision of the 1990 law at issue prohibits any public
agency from discriminating against a person with a disability ``by
reason of such disability.'' Georgia takes the view that while this
provision requires ``even-handed treatment'' of people who have
disabilities and those who do not, it imposes no requirements for
the actual treatment of those with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter, addressing Patricia Downing, Georgia's
senior assistant attorney general, objected that the state's
interpretation seemed to assume that all people with disabilities
are alike.
</P>
<P>
   But all disabilities are not the same, Souter went on. He asked
Ms. Downing to consider two groups of people, one group ``simply
unsuited'' to live outside an institution, and another group ``who
can live perfectly well'' on the outside despite their
disabilities. If the state keeps all members of both groups
hospitalized on the ground that all have disabilities, isn't that
discrimination on the basis of disability, Souter asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Downing replied that it would not be discrimination as long
as the people in the second group require some level of treatment
and can benefit from being in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if they can benefit, that renders irrelevant the fact that
they can get appropriate treatment outside?'' Souter asked with
evident skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mere fact that someone can be treated in the community
does not constitute discrimination,'' Ms. Downing replied.
</P>
<P>
   The state is appealing a ruling last year by the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in Atlanta, which held that if treatment
in a group home or other noninstitutional environment can be
provided, it generally must be provided.
</P>
<P>
   Although as many as 26 other states told the court at one point
that they supported Georgia's appeal, that number has dwindled to
seven as governors and state attorneys general responded to the
anger their positions evoked in constituents with disabilities. The
states still supporting a friend-of-the-court brief for Georgia are
Colorado, Hawaii, Montana, Nevada, Tennessee, Texas, and Wyoming.
The most recent states to withdraw were Indiana, Mississippi,
Washington, and South Carolina.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Justice Department regulation, which the department calls an
``integration mandate,'' requires states to provide services ``in
the most integrated setting appropriate to the needs of qualified
individuals with disabilities.'' That means, to the extent
possible, that people should be able to live in neighborhoods and
to have the chance to interact with those who are not disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Irving L. Gornstein, an assistant solicitor general, told the
court that in passing the Americans With Disabilities Act, Congress
``understood that the unjustified segregation of people with
disabilities is a form of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael H. Gottesman, a law professor at Georgetown University
who represented the two women who brought the lawsuit, tried to
allay the justices' worries that ``states in order to avoid the
risk of liability will have the motive and incentive to push people
out into the community who really shouldn't be there,'' as Justice
John Paul Stevens expressed the concern.
</P>
<P>
   Gottesman said the judgment on the best type of care would in
any event be up to the state's doctors, who had found that his
clients, Lois Curtis and Elaine Wilson, who have both mental
illness and mild retardation, could be treated in the home-like
settings where both now live.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
