<HEADLINE>
TEXAS 10-GRADERS' TEST SCORES SET RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ High school sophomores set a record passing rate
this semester on the state test required for high school
graduation, state Education Commissioner Mike Moses announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At least 90 percent of 10th-graders who are not in special
education passed the reading and writing sections of the exit-level
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills test for the first time in the
exam's nine-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a red-letter day for Texas students,'' Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, chairman of the Senate Education
Committee, said the results were the ``best scores we've ever seen
in the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Kauffman, an attorney for the Mexican American Legal Defense
and Education Fund, which has sued the state over the exit-level
test, said he also was pleased that the TAAS scores are improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think it necessarily shows an increase in
knowledge,'' Kauffman said.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he added, the improved scores show that schools and
students are more successful at giving and taking the tests.
</P>
<P>
   In its suit, scheduled to go to trial this summer in federal
district court in San Antonio, the Mexican American Legal Defense
and Education Fund contends the exit-level test discriminates
against minority students, partly because of differences in
learning opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Although test scores for minorities continue to lag behind the
marks for white students, Hispanic and black students continued a
five-year trend of narrowing the performance gap, the Texas
Education Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Houston school district officials said they would not release
local figures until their report is formally prepared, although
several other districts released statistics on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Students take the exit-level TAAS for the first time in the
spring semester of the 10th grade. Those who fail any section of it
have several chances to retake those parts of the test during their
junior and senior years.
</P>
<P>
   Only 8,146 of the state's 212,773 high school seniors _ less
than 4 percent _ have not yet passed the test and will have one
more chance to do so next week in order to receive diplomas this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Students can continue to take the exam, if necessary, after they
leave school.
</P>
<P>
   Among non-special education sophomores taking the exit-level
test for the first time in February, 90 percent statewide passed
the reading test, 92 percent passed the writing test and 83 percent
passed the mathematics test.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide passing rates by ethnicity on each exam were:
</P>
<P>
   Reading _ white, 97 percent; Hispanic, 82 percent; black, 85
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Writing _ white, 97 percent; Hispanic, 86 percent; black, 88
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Math _ white, 91 percent; Hispanic, 75 percent; black, 69
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight percent of the 10th-graders passed all sections of
the exam. By ethnic breakdown, that included 89 percent of white
students, 66 percent of Hispanics and 63 percent of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five percent of low-income sophomores of all races passed
all the sections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moses said more work still needed to be done, particularly in
preparing minority and low-income students for the exam.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, minority students' gains in scores on all three
test sections have significantly outpaced those of white students
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He said improvement by minority students on the math section of
the exit test have been particularly impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, there was a 37-point gap between
African-American students and white students and a 29-point gap
between Hispanic and white students on the exit-level math test.
That gap has shrunk considerably and is now down to 22 points for
African-American students and 16 points for Hispanic students,''
Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15,318 high school students in special education classes
were exempted by their school districts from the TAAS test,
compared to 11,885 last year. The TEA will use the performance of
special education students for the first time later this year when
it rates school districts and campuses under the state's school
accountability system.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight percent of special-education sophomores who took
the TAAS test passed all sections. Sixty-four percent passed the
reading section, 47 percent passed the math section and 63 percent
passed the writing test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
