<HEADLINE>
NATION LOOKING FOR FAITH IN THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA VALDEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Is the face of America changing from John Wayne to
Willie Loman? From can-do toughness to has-been lethargy?
</P>
<P>
   The questions grew out of one of those slick magazines that come
uninvited into my mailbox. This one, called ``Arizona Blue,'' was
from the friendly folks at BlueCross BlueShield of Arizona. The
story on Page 6 says one out of every 10 people suffers from
depression at one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   It's an incredible statistic. And the Mental Health Association
of Arizona says it's just the beginning of a growing trend.
</P>
<P>
   How can this be? We live in a country that's the envy of the
world. Our optimism is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Way back when Jimmy Carter talked about a national malaise,
people thought it was something to spread on their sandwich. The
very idea that Americans were anything but giddy with delight over
their bounty was an outrage.
</P>
<P>
   We looked at the long gas lines, the high interest rates, the
tight job market and scoffed at President Carter's dire assessment.
We considered it less than patriotic.
</P>
<P>
   Now we live in a country where the stock market is up,
unemployment is down, food is plentiful, life is long _ and one in
10 suffers from depression.
</P>
<P>
   America looks like the stereotypical 1950s housewife. She had
enough labor-saving appliances to run a kingdom, all shiny and new.
She had smiling kids and an attentive husband. Yet more than the
house was empty when everybody left for the day. She cried all
alone.
</P>
<P>
   They used to call it the blues. But these days the diagnosis is
depression. Mental health experts say it is a change in brain
chemistry. The cause can be genetic. Or it can come from a lack of
emotional support coupled with a barrage of negative environmental
stresses.
</P>
<P>
   It could apply to any one of those leaden-eyed people who ride
up the elevator with you at the office.
</P>
<P>
   It could also apply to America, the sad-eyed matron in a nation
full of conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   America gets little emotional support. Republican politicians
harp on our loss of morality, traditional values and fear of God. A
Democratic president provides evidence for their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers are full of stories about failure. The school system.
The health care system. The family. We don't question the message.
Instead, we wrap ourselves in the weight of our shortcomings and
wail. We become the downtrodden salesman holding a sample case full
of yesterday's accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   And there are the negative environmental stressors. Plenty of
them. Littleton, Colo. Laramie, Wyo. Jasper, Texas. Oklahoma City.
A travelogue of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The BlueCross article is entitled ``Seeking Help for
Depression,'' but where does a nation go to get back its faith in
the future?
</P>
<P>
   We can't take a slugload of Prozac and hope the feeling goes
away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet attention must be paid to America's misery. Attention must
be paid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Valdez can be reached at linda.valdez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
