<SLUG> BC-MA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STUDY SHOWS SHIFT IN MASSACHUSETTS ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Software, telecommunications and other high-tech
industries have been the source of one-fourth of Massachusetts' job
gains since 1995 and have laid a sturdy foundation for the economy,
according to a study published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Massachusetts report examining technology's
impact on the economy found that in the years following the demise
of the minicomputer industry, the state has rebounded smartly.
Unemployment in Massachusetts hit 2.8 percent last month, its
lowest level since the economic peak in the late 1980s, when makers
of minicomputers were booming.
</P>
<P>
   But sharp job losses among high-tech manufacturers caused
economic shifts, which opened the way for growth in
non-manufacturing industries experiencing a boom, including
software, telecommunications, networking and other high-tech
sectors.
</P>
<P>
   A report says the fact that high-tech has taken off would not
surprise anyone who has seen the stock prices of Internet companies
soar. But the report pinpointed the sources of the state's growth
in specific technology sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Using employment data, Craig Moore, a UMass professor of
political economy who prepared the study, said it was an attempt to
provide a more refined breakdown of the technology sector than is
available in state jobs reports.
</P>
<P>
   The study documents ``the most significant shift in our economy
and growth that's taken place in decades,'' Moore said.
Massachusetts, he added, is ``moving from a product-based economy
to an information-based economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Between June 1995 and June 1998, the state had a net job gain of
116,817, Moore's study found.
</P>
<P>
   Of those jobs, 28,783 _ or 24.6 percent of the total _ were
added by the ``information technology sector,'' which now employs
nearly 169,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Growth among high-tech companies is only part of the story, said
Nicholas Perna, chief economist for Fleet Financial Group. ``A lot
of the other signs of prosperity we see in the Commonwealth _ an
ebullient housing market and the fact you can't get a parking space
downtown,'' Perna said, ``are the consequences of the high-tech
boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Software accounted for much of the explosive growth in services
_ 61,000 service jobs were added in the three years studied.
Services include many of the state's software firms as well as
consulting firms that sell technology services to business
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts still ranks after California in software
employment (134,419) and has fallen behind Texas (56,778), where a
booming software industry has sprouted around the University of
Texas in Austin. Massachusetts, a much smaller state, employed
36,640 in software.
</P>
<P>
   Although job growth in Massachusetts software grew by 43 percent
during the three years studied, it slightly lagged nationwide
growth of 52 percent in software.
</P>
<P>
   But, gains in computer networks and telecommunications in
Massachusetts outpaced the nation, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the growth can be seen around routes 128 and 495, the
two big eastern Massachusetts beltways. Big companies such as Cisco
Systems are growing, and small, start-up companies creating new
hardware and software for telecommunications and the Internet are
flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   That industry, tagged ``systems integration'' _ hardware and
software linking computer systems as well as telecommunications and
services _ is growing faster than any other sector, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harrison, executive director of the Massachusetts
Telecommunications Council, said 1996 deregulation has led to
fierce competition _ and growth _ among internet service providers
and telephone, cable and other carriers, fueling demand for new
types of software, as well hardware such as switches and routers.
``The reason it's growing is the technologies are growing so
rapidly,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The systems industry added 11,386 jobs in Massachusetts, growing
174 percent from 1995 to 1998. That compared with US growth of 52
percent, according to report.
</P>
</TEXT>
