<SLUG> BC-POLAROID-UHRICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER SENIOR OFFICIAL LEAVING POLAROID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polaroid Corp. says another top executive would be leaving the
financially struggling Cambridge company.
</P>
<P>
   Carole J. Uhrich, executive vice president and assistant chief
operating officer, said Wednesday she will be leaving after 33
years at the instant photography company to ``pursue other
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Uhrich is the second high-level executive to leave Polaroid in
recent months. In December, Serafino ``Sandy'' Sosa, the company's
senior vice president for worldwide marketing and new product
development, resigned for ``personal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid observers say the departures leave a new triad of key
leadership consisting of Gary DiCamillo, chairman and chief
executive; Jerry Noonan who replaced Sosa as top marketing
executive; and Judith Boynton, chief financial officer. All three
have joined Polaroid in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Uhrich's move did not surprise Wall Street analysts, and her
announcement barely registered on the company's stock, which crept
up 1/16 to close at 20 1/4 Wednesday on the New York Stock
Exchange. For months, speculation whirled that Uhrich, 55, aspired
to be chief executive of Polaroid, a hope that may have been dashed
when DiCamillo, 48, joined the company in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to run a company, and she didn't see any likelihood
of that at Polaroid with Gary being seven years younger than she,''
said Pete Enderlin, analyst at FAC-Equities in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Uhrich said she is weighing several job options, both locally
and nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``My future plans are hopefully to run a company, and I'm
talking to several people right now about that possibility,''
Uhrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid has already launched a search for Uhrich's successor,
said DiCamillo, who predicted that the company would make a
selection within ``a couple of months.'' In the meantime, Uhrich's
duties will be shared by DiCamillo and Boynton.
</P>
<P>
   Enderlin predicts that the job will be filled internally.
``Chances are they will stay within the company,'' he said. ``They
already have enough management depth to be able to do that and it
will send the right message to management.''
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid is struggling to make a comeback and reverse a
four-year financial slide. Polaroid is betting that three new
products _ called PopShots, JoyCam and PocketCam _ aimed at younger
consumers will pull the company from its doldrums. The strategy is
showing early signs of success. The company lost $15.1 million in
the first three months this year on revenues of $379 million, far
less than in previous quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``New products are going to be key to Polaroid's survival,''
said Ben Reitzes, vice president of PaineWebber in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
