<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-APACHES-0422-C     04-21 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-APACHES-0422-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BASE APPROACHES WAR FOOTING AFTER APACHES' ARRIVAL
 &HT;    650&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0422; ALBANIA-SHELLING-0422.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ This mud-slicked tarmac moved toward
a war footing Wednesday after the first formation of U.S. Army's
most lethal tank-busting helicopters touched down here and prepared
to battle Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of U.S. troops lined up along the runway to gawk as the
six wasp-shaped Apaches skimmed in to land at Albania's only
functioning civilian and military airfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were going to play 'The Flight of the
Valkyries,' like in 'Apocalypse Now,''' said one impressed
onlooker, U.S. Army Sgt. Matt Fredrickson, 24, of Cedar Rapids,
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But as ``Task Force Hawk'' progressed to a new level at this
airfield, the White House said it would support revising NATO's
six-month study on sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO Supreme Commander Gen. Wesley Clark and
Secretary-General Javier Solana ``believe it's prudent to update
the assessment, based on the changing circumstances on the ground,
we would support that,'' spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 assessment concluded that as many as 75,000 ground
troops would be needed in Kosovo alone and that fighting through to
Belgrade and the rest of Serbia could require 200,000 soldiers or
more.
</P>
<P>
   The first Apache missions are being kept a secret, and will come
with no advance warning, according to military officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one to know when we are going to go will be Slobodan
Milosevic,'' said U.S. Army spokesman Capt. Mark Arden, 29, an
Apache pilot now serving as a staff officer.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has been frustrated in its efforts to degrade Milosevic's
Serb infantry and armored units in southern Kosovo province, which
can melt into mountain terrain and pick times to attack when most
fighter aircraft are ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Taking no chances at having the mission fail, NATO's Clark
assigned one of his top deputies, Army 5th Corps commander Lt. Gen.
John W. Hendrix, to run Task Force Hawk, as the Apache attack
brigade has been designated.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Serbian forces) have been successful so far against women and
children that are unarmed,'' Arden said, ``but I think the table is
about to turn when we enter the conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not difficult to understand where this confidence comes
from.
</P>
<P>
   Flying in from a base in Brindsi, Italy, the six Apaches -- the
first of 24 to be deployed throughout the area -- that flew in
through a slate-gray sky from the direction of the Adriatic Sea and
touched down an hour before sunset looked sleek and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The scene seemed like an aerial procession of matadors before a
very deadly bullfight.
</P>
<P>
   They were as part of a deafening convoy of 15 helicopters that
also included five troop-carrying Blackhawks, two Chinook
heavy-lifters and two Blackhawk medivac choppers. The stately
procession hovered in a low-level loop over the airfield before
they alighted.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has earmarked another 18 Apaches to intensify the air war
against Serbian tanks, heavy guns and troop formations. There was
no word on when the other 18 would arrive, or whether they all are
needed here before the first Apaches can start strikes into Kosovo
and Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the Apaches comes several days later than
originally estimated by the Pentagon when it was announced in late
March they would be part of the air war against Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   As late as Tuesday, the U.S. military struggled to adjust to a
decision that the originally chosen site for the Apaches -- well
removed from the hard airstrip here, in a remote field cordoned off
from the rest of the base, wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   And incessant rains had turned the open plain to a near marsh,
delaying deployment of the Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   But now that they're here, Arden said the Apache pilots ``are
all fired up -- they know that they are the tip of the spear in the
entire United States military.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the Apaches ``highly lethal'' and said that ``we
expect that those (Serbian) forces will suffer heavily under our
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   During the Gulf War, the AH-64 Apaches were credited with
destroying more than 500 Iraqi tanks, plus scores of artillery
pieces and armored personnel carriers -- all without the loss of a
single Apache.
</P>
<P>
   Correspondents viewed long lines of Iraqi tanks, each with a
blackened hole the size of a grapefruit at the base of the turret.
cut???
</P>
<P>
   But an Apache pilot was also responsible for one of the worst
``friendly fire'' episodes in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of combat, the pilot -- an experienced Apache
veteran who was a lieutenant colonel -- accidentally transposed two
map coordinates and launched several laser-guided Hellfire
missiles. They scorched two American Bradley fighting vehicles,
killing two Americans and wounding six.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches that arrived Wednesday in Albania were part of the
11th Attack Aviation Regiment based in Hildesheim, Germany. The
Gulf War ``friendly fire'' episode'' also involved a pilot from the
11th Attack Aviation Regiment, who left the service almost
immediately after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Some American commanders in the Gulf were so distrustful of the
Apaches' inability to distinguish ``friendly'' targets at night
that they ordered the advancing American tank columns to move only
by daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday whether the Apaches will be able to avoid
striking columns of refugees in Kosovo by accident, Arden said,
``We are aware that there are civilians on the battlefield . . . We
believe every measure has been taken to reduce the possibility of
collateral damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Arden said that since the Gulf War, the Apaches have been fitted
out with advanced computerized targeting equipment to allow the
pilot and his co-pilot/gunner to identify targets more precisely.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
