<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC SIGNS STARTING BC GUARD COLLINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Boston College center and the Patriots' first draft
pick, Damien Woody, may have familiar company to his right on the
offensive line in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Collins, the starting right guard at BC last fall, was one
of the 10 undrafted free agents the Patriots announced they had
signed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Collins and Woody and the rest of the team's recent
signees and rookies are due in for a weekend rookie orientation.
Collins, who played at 6 feet 5 inches and about 285 pounds last
season, is up to 300 now. He and Woody, 6-3 and 319, were two of
the very big reasons the Eagles put up 4,527 yards in total offense
last year, with Mike Cloud running for 1,726.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good line last year,'' said BC coach Tom O'Brien.
``We had a guy taken in the first round, a guy in the third (guard
Doug Brzezinski by Philadelphia) and one who signed as a free
agent. That's not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, incidentally, said the Patriots did not contact him to
talk about Woody before taking him with their first draft pick. He
said he didn't know whether it was common for NFL teams to check in
with college head coaches on high draft picks before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not for the Patriots,'' O'Brien said. ``I've had
other kids who were first-round draft choices and someone would
come in and talk with me, but maybe that not where the Patriots
are.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Patriots, he said, might have talked with Jeff
Jagodzinski, the former BC offensive line coach who is now with the
Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would presume they did,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose after the weekend when O'Brien commented
candidly to reporters about Woody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told the truth,'' O'Brien said. ``He didn't play as
well last year as he did in our first year. They asked me a
question and I gave an honest answer. He was much better as a
sophomore than as a junior. But he has tremendous potential and
great upside. I think he came in too heavy last year and lost some
quickness. But he can be an All-Pro as far as I'm concerned; he's
got that much talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins credits Jagodzinski and Woody, who passed up his senior
year of eligibility, with helping him switch from the defensive to
offensive side of the ball. He was moved during the spring before
his junior year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I made the move, I knew that was where I
belonged,'' Collins said. ``I felt a lot more comfortable from Day
One. Damien helped me a lot through the transition. He knows his
stuff and he'd always pull me aside if he noticed I needed help and
help me through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins became a starter as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job for us last year,'' O'Brien said. ``He
seemed to solidify the line for us. He's a very physical player.
He's a tough kid. I wish for his sake he had played offense a
little longer, he'd probably be further along in technique. But
he'll work and play for them and if they have patience and give him
an opportunity, he'll do a good job for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the yards for the team and Cloud, Collins said the line
took great pride in the fact that it led the Big East in fewest
sacks allowed with 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy with the year we had,'' Collins said. ``The big
thing was the least amount of sacks in the league. It wasn't that
hard to block for Cloud. He made plays on his own. It was a gift to
block for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time Collins toured Foxborough Stadium he was perhaps
6 and lived in Ohio and his uncle, Matt Cavanaugh _ then a Patriot
and now the Chicago Bears offensive coordinator _ flew him out for
a visit and a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been going to games as long as I remember,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After starring at BC, he is excited about the next step, about
20 minutes down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in the NFL is what you dream of,'' Collins said. ``And
playing for the hometown team is just gravy. It doesn't get any
better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins is under no illusions about where he stands with the
team. The Patriots had called before the seventh round to say they
had two picks in the round and weren't sure what they were going to
do, but were very interested either way. He was not picked, but
within 15 minutes of the end of the draft, his agent had a deal
with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what to think as far as making the team,''
Collins said. ``I'm going into this hoping to at least get on the
practice squad. I feel I have a lot of room for improvement. I
think I have a lot of upside and I can learn and get better. I
haven't plateaued. I want to get in and develop with a good line
coach and turn into a player eventually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
