<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GIVEN AN EDGE OVER HURRICANES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They're the sixth seed and they're the favorites.
Figure that one out.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, when the Bruins open their best-of-seven
first-round Eastern Conference series against the third-seeded
Carolina Hurricanes Thursday, they will be slightly favored by
virtue of finishing the regular season with a better record.
</P>
<P>
   So, what does that mean? Not much, really. The Hurricanes,
formerly the Hartford Whalers, are making their first postseason
appearance in seven years. That, too, is misleading since many of
their players have had plenty of playoff success with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   How do you evaluate this matchup? All in all, it's pretty even.
The season series finished at 2-2-1. Bruins coach Pat Burns, who
ran a spirited workout at the team's practice rink in Wilmington,
told the media and his players that everything that has brought
them to this point no longer has a great deal of meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new season; you've got to be ready,'' said Burns, who
will be without No. 2 center Joe Thornton for at least Game 1
because of a bruised sternum. ``I think we're ready. We're the
favorites and that's the difference this year and we have to live
with that. We've got more points than them, it doesn't mean
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you're the favorites, they feel like they're the
underdogs. We have to go in there and make sure we're ready. It's
game by game. You lose one, you win one, nothing is won until it's
all done. We have to get our head on straight, understand our
responsibilities, be accountable for what you have to do, and
everything should be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Bruins were the fifth seed, matched up against
Washington. The Capitals beat the Bruins and made it to the Stanley
Cup finals before being swept by Detroit. Ray Bourque said this
team, which is more seasoned than the rookie-heavy club of 1997-98,
won't be happy just to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, it ended with a sour taste, knowing that we played
pretty well and didn't have anything to show for it,'' said
Bourque, entering his 19th postseason. ``I think we were excited to
come into the year and picking up where we left off. We never
really got to that point until a month and a half ago, when
everybody got healthy and we started playing the type of hockey we
thought we were going to play all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're just excited about the opportunity of being back
in the playoffs and competing and going out and winning. We don't
just want to compete, we want to win the series and go from there.
It would be huge for this team. It isn't going to be easy but we
feel we have enough in this room to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Hurricanes have an edge, it's in the size department.
They're aggressive, well-coached, and big. Boston has better
goaltending, talented forwards, and excellent skaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ever now, the experience factor counts,'' said
Burns. ``Even more at this time of year because players know what
it takes to get by a round, they know what it takes to play a game.
They know not to get excited or down if you lose one. I don't have
a lot of guys who have been by too many one-rounders. You get Ray
to talk in a meeting. He's got knowledge. This first round is the
toughest one, and then things seem to pick up a little more and you
start feeling good about yourself. These first rounds are always
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque is one of the few Bruins left who even remember the
Hartford Whalers, who moved to Carolina after the 1996-97 season.
From Keith Primeau to Sami Kapanen to Gary Roberts to Arturs Irbe,
the Hurricanes have plenty of talent to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very good team,'' said Bourque. ``They're very
solid, a lot of experience, good size, good speed. They don't have
any major weaknesses on their team. They're the type of team that
you look at their lineup and say why aren't they doing any better.
They're a dangerous team.''
</P>
<P>
   And center Tim Taylor and the rest of his teammates feel the
Hurricanes' regular-season record should not affect the Bruins'
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many times a team underachieves during the season and then
all of a sudden they come alive in the playoffs and they're the
money players,'' said Taylor. ``Hopefully, that's what we are in
here. We know they have a lot there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
