<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SUMMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHADOW OF KOSOVO LOOMS OVER NATO ON EVE OF SUMMIT
</HEADLINE>
   (mb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the leaders of NATO countries began arriving
here Wednesday for the 50th anniversary of the alliance, they were
embarking on a summit transformed from a celebration of triumph to
a war council on the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the alliance _ which successfully stood up to the
Soviet Union and its Communist allies in the Warsaw pact, but which
has been grappling for a new role since the collapse of the Soviet
bloc _ has unexpectedly come to hinge, NATO leaders say, on the
outcome of the conflict with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, said Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., in remarks at
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee this week: ``If we do not
achieve our goals in Kosovo, NATO is finished as an alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials and the NATO leaders are hoping
that the summit will illustrate the utility of NATO and that the
alliance, rather than being an obsolete ornament striving for a new
mission, is actually functioning as it should.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message is that the NATO of the future is as good as the
NATO of the past,'' said Ronald Asmus, deputy assistant secretary
of state for european affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Asmus said that NATO had to be able to deal with crises outside
its member states, and Kosovo, he said, underscored that NATO had
come together in such a way.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the war against Milosevic is the first instance in the
history of NATO in which the alliance is acting as a regional
policeman rather than the way it went along for its first 40 years
as a partnership bound by a mutual defense treaty, without firing a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   After its enemy evaporated with the end of communism, NATO
methodically expanded by selecting three former satellites of the
Soviet Union for membership in the alliance _ Hungary, the Czech
Republic and Poland. NATO also extended its mission to include
peacekeeping operations in areas outside its own membership, such
as Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   There were other initiatives planned in the last year that were
intended to bring the alliance forward.
</P>
<P>
   Before the conflict in Kosovo appeared on the horizon, the
Clinton administration pushed NATO to deal with the next century by
embracing a new initiative on the spread of chemical, biological
and nuclear weapons. This was a way the administration argued for
NATO to become a modernized post-Soviet organization.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen said that, as planned, a
center for these weapons of mass destruction would be unveiled this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But these plans will pale at the summit compared with the
immediacy of preventing a possible debacle in Kosovo and a
humiliation for the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Clinton administration wants to emerge from
this weekend is the notion that a Balkans dictator can stand up to
NATO air power and wreak havoc with the alliance, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be difficult to avoid the fact that Milosevic has
drawn the alliance into turbulent waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo has brought NATO into the never-never land,'' said
David Gompert, vice president of Rand who was on the National
Security Council in the Bush administration. ``It has brought us
into a situation where a regime that slaughters its own people is
no longer sovereign and where the United Nations Security Council
is no longer a requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are so high over Kosovo that Gompert outlined two
stark outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming NATO doesn't shatter, something positive will emerge
from this tragedy,'' he said, adding that the most important result
could be a stronger relationship between the United States and its
European allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If NATO cracks and as a consequence fails in Kosovo,'' there
would be a new realignment of the Western allies. In essence, he
said, an ``unprepared'' Europe would be left to take care of the
defense of Europe and the United States would turn almost
exclusively to the defense of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kosovo, the centerpiece of the summit was to have been
the adoption of a new ``strategic concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, as the NATO leaders confront what amounts to the fourth
Balkan war of this century and discuss the scope of the atrocities
against ethnic Albanians by Milosevic, they will also be
fine-tuning the wording of the strategic concept.
</P>
<P>
   The new concept talks of ``crisis management and partnership''
with non-NATO countries. This is an idea that can be broadly
interpreted to cover the war in Kosovo, officials said. But even
so, they added, it stops short of asserting that NATO should go to
war over an ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most telling is what will not be stated in the new
strategic concept.
</P>
<P>
   One of NATO's most cherished descriptions of itself will be
dropped. Thus, these lines that were at the heart of NATO's last
strategic concept, written in 1991 when the Soviet Union was still
alive, will disappear: ``The Alliance is purely defensive in
purpose: None of its weapons will ever be used except in
self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with new responsibilities outside the territory of its
members, NATO created several institutions under the alliance's
umbrella. One will be prominently on display at the summit, another
will be conspicuously absent. The Permanent Joint Council,
established as the place where Russia would be informed on NATO
matters, is now suspended after the Russians walked out in protest
against the Kosovo air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly more important is the Euro-Atlantic Partnership
Council, founded in 1997 for the 25 countries that belong to the
Partnership for Peace program _ such as Romania, Bulgaria, Croatia,
and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its search for a new mission in the early 1990s, NATO
invited countries to join the Partnership for Peace. The program,
conceived at the time by Secretary of Defense Les Aspin, was
intended to encourage non-NATO members to develop civilian control
of defense ministries and to start joint planning and joint
military exercises with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   By broadening its principals and methods across Europe to such
former communist states as Ukraine, Slovakia, Georgia and as far
afield as Tajikistan, NATO found new participants for peacekeeping
and humanitarian operations. For example, Ukraine, which joined the
Partnership for Peace program, is part of the peacekeeping force in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the partner countries, most notably Albania and
Macedonia, have become what the Clinton administration calls
``front-line'' states in the Kosovo war, the places where Milosevic
is attempting to create turmoil by expelling hundreds of thousands
refugees onto their territory.
</P>
<P>
   These countries now need as much help as they can get from NATO.
In recognition of this, a special session of ``front-line'' states
was hastily added to the summit schedule, yet another reminder that
the once-formal ceremonial meeting has been transformed by
Milosevic to deliberations about war.
</P>
</TEXT>
