<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7927 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-EUROPE-BOS &LR;      04-21 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-EUROPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DIVERSITY A WEAKNESS IN EFFORT AGAINST MILOSEVICH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As he boarded a flight Wednesday for NATO's 50th
anniversary celebration in Washington, British Prime Minister Tony
Blair was said to be carrying, in his head at least, a plan to
persuade President Clinton of the need to send ground forces into
Kosovo sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's lobbying mission, which he was to begin Wednesday night
at a White House meeting, could be one of many as leaders of NATO's
19 countries converge to brainstorm on how to prevail in the
alliance's biggest challenge since winning the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering, and the temporary shift of NATO's headquarters
from Brussels to Washington for nearly a week, reflects both the
strength and the weakness of the alliance as its battle against the
regime of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic enters its 30th
day.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of NATO and its formidable power is contained in
Article 5 of the North Atlantic Treaty, which notes that ``an
attack against one or more of them in Europe or North America shall
be considered an attack against them all.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there is strength and security in numbers, there is also
the difficulty of reaching consensus. Everything NATO does, from
deciding to target Milosevic's regime in the first place to what
sort of military tactics to employ, must be approved by each of the
19 members.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO has stuck exclusively to an air war because there is
little political stomach for sustaining casualties on the ground in
Kosovo, Blair's idea to make the threat of ground forces more
credible is likely to get a good airing. A senior administration
official in Washington Wednesday said the weekend summit will
address the issue of ground troops, even though no decision is
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible for leaders not to discuss ground
troops. But will there be decision making on ground troops? I don't
see that,'' said the official.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the American who is NATO's supreme commander,
has reportedly complained about trying to wage a war with two hands
and one leg tied behind his back. For example, while the NATO
countries have signed off on air strikes against oil refineries in
Serbia, one of the two republics that make up the Yugoslav
Federation, some have balked at the idea of a naval blockade of
Montenegro, the other Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and his advisers believe a blockade is needed to cut off
refined oil arriving by tanker. France is the most outspoken of
NATO nations that believe it would take a United Nations Security
Council resolution to authorize a blockade.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, NATO commanders complain that their job is much
harder because their political masters on the North Atlantic
Council, NATO'S poitical arm, must reach consensus on decisions
about military tactics. Publicly, however, that accountability is
held up as evidence of NATO's moral superiority.
</P>
<P>
   At the Supreme Headquarters Allied Powers Europe (SHAPE), one of
Clark's aides, Major Rick Jones, acknowledged, ``General Clark
doesn't do anything unilaterally.'' But Jones insisted that such
accountability is not a liability but ``an excellent example of
what democracy can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Major Jan Joosten, a NATO officer in Macedonia, where some
12,000 NATO forces are waiting to go into Kosovo to implement the
peace plan Milosevic rejects as a violation of Serbian sovereignty,
said Milosevic has it easier in prosecuting a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come from 19 different democracies with 19 different points
of view,'' said Joosten, a Dutch officer. ``We are accountable to
our political masters, and they are accountable to 19 different
leaders, who are accountable to 19 different electorates.
Everything we do has to be debated by 19 countries. When Milosevic
wants to do something, he just does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Williams of the North Atlantic Assembly, which advises
NATO in an unofficial capacity, said in theory there must be
unanimity among NATO members before the commanders can act, but in
practice countries that oppose certain tactics often abstain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countries will not oppose, they'll let it go by. It's rather
subtle,'' said Williams. ``Technically, if Italy or Greece were to
oppose the bombing, it would cease to be a NATO operation.''
</P>
<P>
   As in any coalition or political alliance, there is
scorekeeping. The Greeks, for example, are expected to seek some
form of payback for acquiescing to the attacks on their fellow
Orthodox Christians in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians have also expressed reservations about the air
strikes, which are launched by mostly American pilots using Italian
airbases. Some think it is no coincidence that an Italian officer,
Gen. Giuseppe Marani, has emerged as the chief NATO military
spokesman at daily briefings in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, NATO's gathering was to have been a celebration. But
the war in Yugoslavia has dramatically reshaped the Washington
conference into more of a strategy session. For example, Friday's
commemorative ceremony was scheduled to last four to five hours. It
has been trimmed back to just over an hour. Instead, there will be
more strategic meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Washington Wednesday, Alastair Campbell,
Blair's press secretary, agreed the summit had been transformed
from celebration to strategy session _ with all the difficulties of
reaching consensus among 19 very different countries.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, however, refused to be drawn into suggestions that
Blair will try to persuade Clinton that the threat of ground forces
has to be built up quickly, and used if Milosevic doesn't back down
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the advantages that Milosevic has is that he doesn't
have to discuss any of this publicly,'' Campbell said. ``What you
will see at the Washington summit is the leaders of the NATO
alliance gathering to discuss all of these questions, us being very
open about those discussions and explaining the background to them.
But I think it is probably sensible that we let them do that
first.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe staff writer Fred Kaplan contributed to this report from
Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
