A7937 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-OIL-BOS &LR;      04-21 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-OIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO IMMEDIATE EFFECT SEEN IN BOMBING OF YUGOSLAV OIL   RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To hear US and NATO officials talk in recent days,
the crucial element in the air war against Serb leader Slobodan
Milosevic is the attempt to destroy his oil.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie P. Shea, noting Napoleon's dictum that an
army marches on its stomach, said this week that the motorized army
of today ``marches on its oil reserves.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 oil sites have been bombed, in some cases
repeatedly, since the war began a month ago. NATO briefers say
Serbia's oil refineries have been virtually wiped out, and a
quarter of its oil storage tanks have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   However, several analysts argue that this aspect of the bombing
has had no visible effect on Milosevic _ and isn't likely to for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's grasping at straws,'' said Eliot A. Cohen, professor of
strategic studies at Johns Hopkins University's School for Advanced
International Studies and the director of the US Air Force's
official, five-volume study of the 1991 air war against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attacking oil targets has worked only when the other guy has
to consume a lot of oil to do what he's doing,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Serbian troops are not moving very much, they do not
require much fuel. Much of what they do need can be diverted from
the civilian economy. Oil has also been obtained from tankers
offloading on the Adriatic ports of sister republic Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days, US officials have been urging the NATO
allies to approve some kind of blockade against these ships, but to
no avail thus far. It is a topic that will be discussed at the NATO
meeting this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Even if tankers can be cut off, one senior administration
official said, the Serb military currently has on hand ``several
weeks'' of fuel if they move around a fair amount _ ``a few months'
'' worth if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of attacking oil facilities has been a central feature
of US Air Force doctrine since World War II, when Allied bombers
staged thousands of air raids on Nazi oil fields and refineries. At
the end of the war, 1,200 Nazi panzer tanks, which had massed to
push back a Russian offensive, rolled to a halt because they ran
out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   However, the US Strategic Bombing Survey, an official Allied
study conducted after the war, concluded that the bombing was
effective because it was combined with pressure from ground troops.
A major source of fuel, the Ploesti oil fields in Romania, was
bombed ferociously for a year _ but with ``only limited effects,''
the survey concluded, because the Nazis were able to repair much of
the damage. The turning point did not come until the Soviet Army
overran and occupied the fields.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon and NATO briefers have said this week that the attacks
on oil in this war have started to strain the movements of Serbian
forces.
</P>
<P>
   However, these same briefers say that Serbian troops continue to
move in and out of Kosovo, and that their number, inside and around
its borders, has grown from 35,000 to 43,000.
</P>
<P>
   Paramilitary troops, who do not require much fuel, also continue
to raid Kosovar villages. Army troops have even managed a couple of
incursions across the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   To some NATO officials, however, the real purpose of bombing oil
is to disrupt not the Serbian military but rather the system that
keeps Milosevic in power.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the US Air Force has adopted a doctrine of
``parallel warfare,'' which sees an enemy's society as an
interlocking set of ``rings.'' The center and most vital ring is
the leadership. The second ring is the infrastructure _ roads,
bridges, rail lines. Then comes civilian industries, and, finally,
the troops in the field.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of parallel warfare is to destroy the key points that
link these rings together, with the ultimate aim of shattering the
center ring. Oil is one of those links.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cohen does not see the current bombing as a good
example of parallel warfare. ``It's not massive enough,'' he said.
``You have to knock out Serbian television, their electrical power,
all kinds of things, the first night. What they've done here is a
fraction of the Gulf War. It hasn't been a very ferocious air
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Some NATO officials have a more indirect view of how to pressure
Milosevic. They note that Serbia's oil refineries _ as well as
various factories that have been bombed _ are owned by Milosevic's
friends and relatives, who, angered at seeing their assets blown
up, might push Milosevic to give up his aims in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, this theory goes, airstrikes on Serbian
military headquarters will drive a wedge between Milosevic and his
general staff.
</P>
<P>
   British defense secretary George Robertson said Wednesday,
``There are clear indications that military commanders, and some
high in the civil world, are not happy about what is happening and
see only defeat on the horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Cohen is skeptical of this notion. ``NATO's doing the
bombing,'' he said. ``Why should Milosevic's cronies get mad at
him?''
</P>
</TEXT>
