<HEADER>
A7941 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-21 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAY: CELEBRATING DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Manhole covers are being sealed and sharpshooters
are preparing to patrol rooftops as this capital braces for the
biggest turnout of world leaders since the Kennedy funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 nations of the Atlantic alliance had planned to celebrate
the 50th anniversary of the military organization that stopped the
Russians. Instead, they will be marking their failure to stop
Serbia from expelling unwanted Albanians from its province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody at NATO will concede defeat. Beribboned briefers use
laser pointers to show bridges destroyed, oil refineries destroyed
and empty barracks blown up _ as if bombing from a safe distance
had anything to do with NATO's military mission.
</P>
<P>
   That was not to ``degrade'' anything but to stop the Serbs from
emptying Kosovo. Threats of bombing failed; actual bombing failed;
no matter what pictures of devastation are shown on television
screens, nobody can credibly deny that NATO is failing in its
primary mission. The Serbs have almost finished doing the bloody
work they set out to do.
</P>
<P>
   That is military defeat. If unreversed, it means the end of NATO
and a new century of ethnic war. Punishment from the air,
calibrated to hurt but not too much, is not enough to win the war.
The way to free Kosovo is to send in men with guns to force out the
men with guns now doing the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Why are we not even preparing to do that? Diplomats can blame a
miscalculation of Slobodan Milosevic's willingness to gamble all;
buck-passers can find an excuse in the difficulty of getting
consensus from every nation in the alliance on the need to send in
troops; our embarrassed generals can explain that taking the threat
of invasion ``off the table'' emboldened the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, NATO's inability to stop the slaughter and mass
expulsion was caused by the failure of nerve of the president of
the United States. He saw the unfolding carnage, eloquently
articulated the stakes in stopping war criminality, made much of
the need for ``staying the course,'' but then _ when ethnic
cleansing made it starkly plain that he would have to lead the
alliance into a battle costing casualties _ choked.
</P>
<P>
   He is afraid it will be labeled ``Clinton's war.'' Public
opinion, now supporting ground action to stop rapine and mass
murder, could turn against him at the first sight of body bags. And
so he waits for others to push him into taking the military steps
to save refugee lives that NATO credibility and international
morality urgently require. The banner he wants to carry into battle
reads ``60 percent support.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Congress has done nothing to get our commander in
chief to do his duty to lead. Too many Republicans like the notion
of ``Clinton's war,'' anticipating public disapproval of
ignominious defeat or of costly victory. Too many Democrats with
memories of Vietnam and no recollection of World War II are still
mired in quags.
</P>
<P>
   Not all in Congress are shrouding themselves in ambiguity on
Topic A. This week Sen. John McCain, credentialed by suffering in
war and joined by three Democrats and three Republicans, offered a
resolution spelling out the mission _ Serbian withdrawal and the
return of refugees under NATO-led long-term protection _ and
authorizing ``all necessary force'' to accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' said McCain, getting to the heart of the cause of
Clinton's vacillation, ``as should anyone who votes for this
resolution, that if Americans die in a land war with Serbia, we
will bear a considerable share of the blame for their loss. We are
as accountable to their families as the president must be.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a tough vote, but one necessary to strengthen a president
loath to assume ``the awful burden'' by himself. The key NATO
leaders assembling here know that with Clinton's hands frozen on
the wheel in this storm, McCain has for weeks been the de facto
president of the United States, providing leadership, accepting
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate should not flinch from debating and passing the
McCain Seven's ``all necessary force'' resolution. The alliance
should use a powerful infantry presence on Serbia's borders to
threaten invasion on more than one front. If no Kosovo withdrawal
ensues, let NATO be NATO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
