<SLUG> BC-Y2K-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WILL BE SET FOR Y2K BUT LOCALITIES MAY NOT BE, OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly all the federal government's computers will
be ready for the year 2000, and so will those of most states, but
those of some local governments and small businesses will not be,
the official supervising computer preparation for 2000 said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, John Koskinen, chairman of the President's Council
on Year 2000 Conversion, also predicted that some hospitals and
other health care providers could run into financial trouble that
could force them to close because their billing and reimbursement
systems will not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of those institutions are going to in fact run out of
money and shut down if they can't get their financial systems and
patient-care records fixed,'' Koskinen predicted, in a briefing
summarizing progress.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, few medical devices that use computers would fail,
because their operation does not depend on the date.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen added that he was still considering whether to
recommend paying in December some federal benefits that normally
would be due in January. This would have income tax consequences
that some recipients would not like, he said, and the billions of
dollars of payments could disrupt the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Many computer systems were programmed to record years in only
two digits, and will assume that the year after 1999 is 1900, with
many unhappy consequences. Koskinen announced last month that 92
percent of the federal government's most important computers were
ready for 2000. Wednesday's briefing included predictions of what
would be accomplished by the end of the year and assessments of the
economy sector by sector.
</P>
<P>
   The government has gathered a lot of data about the preparedness
of the private sector, but mostly on the condition that it not
identify individual companies. It will begin issuing advisories
about foreign countries in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   While the national electric grids, major telephone networks and
other big systems will continue to function, Koskinen said, small
systems may not. He advised mayors and other local leaders to meet
with heads of local utilities, including water and sewer systems,
to determine their state of preparedness. Some leaders of local
governments and companies, he said, plan to wait for January to see
what goes wrong and then fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a high-risk roll of the dice,'' he said, adding
that some small governments might assume that others will come to
their aid. ``Those communities ought not to assume the state is
going to show up everywhere, and certainly shouldn't assume the
federal government is going to show up everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, ``there are probably going to be half a
dozen to eight states that are moving too slowly'' and will not be
ready.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that emergency services, including 911 systems,
showed a wide disparity in readiness, and that some smaller
airports were lagging behind in checking computer-operated systems,
including those for security and landing lights.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts have recommended declaring Monday, Jan. 3, Monday,
a federal holiday to give businesses and governments an extra day
to make sure systems work. But Koskinen said that move would
require banks and other financial institutions, most of which have
just finished preparing for 2000, to reprogram again to observe the
holiday. Koskinen said he would advise President Clinton that the
New Year's holiday observed by the federal government should remain
Jan. 1, a Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
