<HEADLINE>
SUNBEAM REPORTS $898 MILLION LOSS FOR YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunbeam Corp., still struggling with the effects of excessive
inventories and heavy debt, turned in another round of dismal
financial results Wednesday, including an $898 million loss for
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam, the beleaguered small-appliance maker, has been trying
for nearly a year to unload warehouses full of unsold electric
blankets and barbecue grills as current management tries to clean
up the mess left by Albert Dunlap, whom the board ousted last June
as chairman and chief executive when the company virtually imploded
and its stock collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The results released Wednesday confirmed that the housecleaning
continues.
</P>
<P>
   In its fourth quarter, Sunbeam lost $311 million, or $3.09 a
diluted share, compared with net income of $9.5 million, or 11
cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier. Revenue rose to $515
million from $262 million, but excluding sales generated by
businesses that Sunbeam bought last year, sales declined to $223
million.
</P>
<P>
   For the full year, Sunbeam lost $898 million, or $9.25 a diluted
share, compared with net income of $38 million in 1997, or 44 cents
a share. Revenue for the year increased to $1.8 billion from $1.1
billion. Excluding sales from the acquired businesses, however,
sales declined to $828 million.
</P>
<P>
   Results for the quarter and year were dragged down by numerous
one-time charges, including some related to the inventory problem,
which the company said would linger into 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the company incurred large losses for the quarter and
full year, they included substantial non-recurring and unusual
items, as well as the continuing effects of working down excess
inventories,'' said Jerry Levin, who replaced Dunlap as chairman
and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sunbeam fell 18.75 cents Wednesday, to $5.375. They
traded as high as $31 last April.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the effect of the bloated inventory, Sunbeam was also
hit by vastly higher interest expenses. They soared to $131 million
from just $11 million in the previous year primarily because of
higher borrowing levels in 1998 to finance acquisitions and to
increase working capital.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that while current management seemed to have
adequately assessed Sunbeam's problems and was working through
them, it was still too early to say whether the company would fully
recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way at this early stage to issue a report card,''
said David Leibowitz, an analyst with Burnham Securities. ``Let's
revisit the issue three or four quarters from now when we at least
have the turnaround of '99 already reported and the outlook for
2000 better clarified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
