<HEADLINE>
BEDECK YOUR BACK YARD WITH A CUSTOM BRICK PATIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laying a brick patio without mortar easy. Sort of. The skill
level needed is fairly basic, but the amount of sweat expressed is
enormous. Still, adding a brick patio to your home can enhance its
value and give you a beautiful surface that will last for decades.
</P>
<P>
   TOOLS NEEDED:
</P>
<P>
   Flat shovel
</P>
<P>
   Wheelbarrow
</P>
<P>
   Garden hose with fine spray nozzle
</P>
<P>
   Hard garden rake
</P>
<P>
   Broad-blade chisel, brick splitter or masonry saw for cutting
and fitting the brick (both are available for rent at local rental
stores or brick distributors)
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter's level
</P>
<P>
   Wood screed strip _ a 2-by-4, at least 3 feet long, raised on
side rails to a height of 1 inch (used to create a uniform sand-bed
depth)
</P>
<P>
   Electric drill and appropriate-size bit (for wood edge only)
</P>
<P>
   Trowel
</P>
<P>
   Broom
</P>
<P>
   Plate compactor
</P>
<P>
   MATERIALS NEEDED:
</P>
<P>
   Bricks. To determine the number needed, calculate the square
footage of your planned patio by multiplying the length by the
width.
</P>
<P>
   Pavers come in three standard sizes: 4-by-8-inch pavers (you'll
need 4.5 per square foot); 3 5/8-by-7 5/8-inch pavers (you'll need
5.2 per square foot); and 3 3/4-by-7 1/2-inch pavers (you'll need
5.1 per square foot). Add 5 percent extra for chipping or breakage,
and 1 1/2 bricks per linear foot for cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Example: For a 10-by-20-foot patio, 200 square feet x 4.5 pavers
900 pavers. An additional 5 percent would be 45 pavers, and 60
linear feet (10 \+ 10 \+ 20 \+ 20) x 1.5 90 pavers. The total
number needed: 900 \+ 45 \+ 90 1,035 pavers.
</P>
<P>
   Sand and crushed stone. These are measured in cubic yards (1
cubic yard equals 27 cubic feet). You'll need to lay 1 inch of
sand. To determine the number of cubic yards of sand, multiply the
square footage by 0.00309. Example: For a 200-square-foot patio,
200 x 0.00309 0.62 cubic yards of sand.
</P>
<P>
   For the base of your patio, you'll need 4 inches of crushed
stone. Multiply the square footage by 0.01235. Example: For a
200-square-foot patio, 200 x 0.01235 2.47 cubic yards of crushed
stone.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER OR EDGING MATERIALS
</P>
<P>
   1. Brick
</P>
<P>
   2. Rigid plastic or metal specifically intended as edging
material
</P>
<P>
   3. Wood 2-by-4 or 4-by-4, pressure-treated or natural redwood
(for wood, metal or rigid plastic, you will need metal spikes that
are at least 8 inches long)
</P>
<P>
   String and wooden stakes (for aligning brickwork)
</P>
<P>
   PREPARING THE AREA
</P>
<P>
   1. Check with your local utility companies to determine the
location of underground lines. You don't want the gas company
digging up your patio at some later date.
</P>
<P>
   2. Check for proper drainage. There should be a
1/4-inch-per-foot slope away from foundations or other permanent
structures.
</P>
<P>
   3. Outline the area with stakes and string, making sure to
include the width of your edging material.
</P>
<P>
   4. Use a flat shovel to remove only enough sod or dirt to
provide a flat, level surface upon which to place the crushed-stone
base. Excess soil that is reinstalled must be firmly settled with a
plate compactor for an even, solid base.
</P>
<P>
   INSTALLING THE BASE
</P>
<P>
   1. Once the sod has been removed and any additional soil has
been compacted, place the crushed stone into the excavation. Using
the plate compactor, tamp down 4 inches of crushed rock. If this is
not done carefully and thoroughly, at an even depth, the bricks
will move over time.
</P>
<P>
   2. The base material should be slightly damp when compacting.
</P>
<P>
   FRAMING THE BORDERS
</P>
<P>
   1. The border, or edging system, is necessary to ensure that the
bricks remain firmly in place. Begin by installing, but not
anchoring, your edging.
</P>
<P>
   2. Once you are satisfied with the placement, anchor the edging
by driving spikes at least 8 inches into the base every 2 to 3
feet. For wood edging, drill holes and drive the spikes through the
middle of the wood. For brick edging, dig a trench deep enough so
that the top edge will be flush with the patio surface.
</P>
<P>
   3. One border can remain unanchored until final brick
installation to ensure a tight fit.
</P>
<P>
   INSTALLING THE SAND BED
</P>
<P>
   1. Dampen the sand with a fine mist of water to remove any
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place screed over crushed rock. Fill area between screed
rails with sand. Pull the screed over the sand to ensure a uniform
1-inch depth. Be careful not to walk on or disturb the leveled
sand. Move screed and repeat process.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove the screed rails and fill the indentations with loose
sand. Level with a broom or trowel.
</P>
<P>
   LAYING BRICK PAVERS
</P>
<P>
   1. Start at a corner _ if possible, one that includes an edge,
such as a house, sidewalk or curb. Lay one run of bricks from the
corner along the two intersecting edges (Figure B). Simply set the
bricks on the sand; don't press or hammer them into place. They
should fit snugly, with a gap of 1//16 inch to 1//8 inch between
each brick. Work from the laid bricks, not from the sand side. If
you disturb the sand, relevel it with a broom or trowel before
laying more bricks.
</P>
<P>
   2. Continue to lay bricks, working from your starting corner to
the unanchored edge (Figure C). With the first run of bricks as a
reference, put a string line across the front of your laying edge
(every 2-3 feet) to maintain alignment (Figure D). If the pattern
wanders somewhat, a trowel, screwdriver, or wide-blade putty knife
can be used to make small adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   3. Check the level and alignment of the brickwork frequently
during installation.
</P>
<P>
   4. Once all the whole bricks have been installed up to the final
unanchored edge, cut or saw the remaining bricks to complete the
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   5. Anchor the final border.
</P>
<P>
   FINISHING UP
</P>
<P>
   1. Inspect your work, making final adjustments in brick height
and joint alignment. Sweep dry sand into all the joints to lock the
brick into place.
</P>
<P>
   2. To further set the bricks, you may want to use the plate
compactor to tamp them down gently. If a compactor is used, spread
a layer of sand over your pavers to prevent contact between the
bricks and the compactor.
</P>
<P>
   3. The sand you sweep into the joints will gradually settle. You
should sweep additional sand into the joints as necessary after the
next few rainstorms until the bricks are fully stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   This information was provided by the Brick Industry Association.
For a more detailed brochure with a variety of brick patterns, send
$1 and a stamped, self-addressed envelope to Brick Industries of
America, 11490 Commerce Park Drive, Reston, VA 20191.
</P>
<P>
   If you read the instructions and decide the math and the digging
are WAY too much trouble, check the Yellow Pages under ``Masons''
to locate professionals.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
