r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DALLAS-ZOO-TEX     04-21 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-ZOO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A NEW TIGER HABITAT, THE DALLAS ZOO HOPES TO RIVAL FORT WORTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Rich Buickerood is pumped.
</P>
<P>
   One moment he touts the Dallas Zoo's recent growth spurt, the
next he pounds his chest like Tarzan.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the director's finger as he peers through a window of one
of two buildings that make up the zoo's new Thai Village. There
before him is more than an acre of lush rain forest with heated
rocks, shrubs, exotic grasses and pools of water. This is the Exxon
Endangered Tiger Habitat, where Sasha and Paul, Sumatran tigers
from the Belle Isle Zoo in Detroit, will make their home next
month.
</P>
<P>
   It is also one of two new showplaces _ the other is the new
Children's Zoo, scheduled to open in 2000 _ that the Dallas Zoo is
counting on to help propel it into the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   After years in the shadow of its counterpart in Fort Worth _ and
after nearly closing seven years ago _ the Dallas park may be on
its way to becoming one of the finest zoos in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Metroplex has two major cities, and there is no reason in
the world why we can't have two major zoos,'' said Buickerood, who
joined the zoo in 1992. ``There's no reason why we both can't be
successful. We think we're at the stage where we are a very good
zoo, and we've got plans to make us even better.''
</P>
<P>
   The tiger habitat, scheduled to open May 8, is the first major
animal exhibit in the Dallas Zoo's ZooNorth section in 25 years. It
also means that, for the first time in its 111-year history, the
zoo can breed the endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   The habitat, Buickerood said, is a nationally sanctioned
facility designed to bring new hope for the tigers through careful
breeding and public education. Because of habitat loss and
poaching, only 5,000 tigers remain in the wild. Officials estimate
that only about 20 zoos in the country have tiger breeding
programs; of those, six have Sumatran tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great exhibit,'' Buickerood said. ``We can breed the
tigers, and I've got all sorts of room to breed other tigers.''
</P>
<P>
   VIEW AT THE ZOO
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Zoo spreads over 110 acres. About 95 have been
developed, and signs of growth and expansion are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The tiger habitat, for instance, is just across from Primate
Place, the first component of the $4.5 million Exxon exhibit, which
opened in August. The year before that, the $1.9 million,
19,000-square-foot Kimberly Clark Chimpanzee Forest in the Wilds of
Africa opened. And the year before that, officials unveiled the
Lemur Lookout, the featured attraction at the grand opening of the
$4 million entry complex, which includes a new entrance directly
off Interstate 35, parking areas, an entry plaza and a 67
1/2-foot-tall giraffe sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dealing with 200,000 cars a day on I-35 going by us
and people not knowing we were here,'' Buickerood said. ``I knew we
needed an icon, and we came up the giraffe everyone knows now.
Everybody talks about it, takes pictures of it. We knew we couldn't
move the zoo, so we moved the entrance.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of entering the complex on the north at Clarendon Drive,
patrons can access the zoo at Marsalis Avenue right off the
interstate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dallas Area Rapid Transit opened a light-rail
station just across the street, which makes it easier for patrons
to find the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are under way for an indoor restaurant that will overlook
the tiger exhibit and a 4-acre, $7 million children's zoo. It will
feature a bubbling fountain called Raccoon Springs, where children
can wash their hands; an outdoor amphitheater for live wildlife
presentations; a wandering stream where children can get wet as
they play; and a farm where children can interact with goats,
guinea pigs, ducks and chickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you discount the horrible summer we had last year,'' said
Buickerood, ``we really blossomed when access was better. Seventeen
to 18 percent of visitors are coming by train, and the number of
people by car has increased 40 percent over the last four years.
We're thrilled by the public's response to all the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   GROUNDS FOR PRAISE
</P>
<P>
   Charlie King is certainly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   As schoolchildren, parents, grandparents and toddlers in
strollers milled about, the zoo visitor from Richmond, Va., offered
this cursory impression:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's phenomenal. I just came through the African
exhibit. If I were an animal, I wouldn't mind living here. The
habitats are very natural. I'm real impressed with this.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Lanita Roomiani, who was with a group of fifth-graders
from Dover Elementary in Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she hadn't been to the zoo in years, but that ``it
looks nicer.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Maki and Sprina Liu, animal keepers at Zoo Atlanta, were
making special note of the park's lush grounds. Because the
vegetation at Zoo Atlanta is beginning to wear down from overeating
and browsing, Maki and Liu were in Dallas to talk to zoo
horticulturists for restoration tips.
</P>
<P>
   Even Buickerood will admit that seven years ago, Dallas' zoo was
in pretty bad shape. It couldn't add any exhibits or market itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place was stinko,'' he said. ``We really thought we were
in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   With the city in an economic drought, Buickerood suggested
closing the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we got everybody's attention,'' he said. ``The zoo
society stepped up support, as did the Parks Department. There was
also an outpouring of support from the public and, quite frankly,
it was good for us that the Fort Worth Zoo was enjoying such good
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Before management of the Fort Worth Zoo was turned over to the
Fort Worth Zoological Association in 1991, Dallas was considered
the better of the two parks. Dallas had opened its much-touted
Wilds of Africa exhibit, which included a monorail ride, and for a
time was drawing good crowds.
</P>
<P>
   But support from the Fort Worth association and some of its
wealthy members quickly moved the Fort Worth zoo into major-league
status. Since then, individuals, foundations and corporations have
contributed more than $25 million to upgrade exhibits and add the
kind of polish that most city-run zoos cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
   With Dallas recommitted to its zoo, the park's budget has grown
from $6 million to $9 million over the past five years. The
zoological society has also increased its support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty contented cows right now,'' Buickerood said. ``We
started to see a turnaround in 1994, and it's just been straight
uphill ever since. There's been nothing but positive things
happening out here for the last several years, and I see nonstop
construction for another decade.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
