<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7955 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      04-21 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S PARTIES GROPE FOR WAY TO FORM NEW GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ A diverse, bickering collection of parties
united for long enough in Parliament on Saturday to bring down the
Hindu-nationalist-led government by a single vote. But they are
having a lot more trouble figuring out how to form a new
government.
</P>
<P>
   With great assurance, Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born heir to
India's political dynasty, declared Wednesday that the Congress
Party, which she leads, would form a government with the
parliamentary support of more than a dozen other parties.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday evening the Samajwadi, or Socialist, Party, whose
backing is essential if Congress is to attain its goal, said that
in exchange for its support, it wanted to be part of the new
government. And it suggested that Jyoti Basu, the aging Communist
leader who is considered one of the country's elder statesmen,
should be prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot do without Congress and Congress cannot do without
us,'' said Amar Singh, a leader of the Samajwadi Party, which has
20 votes in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The coming days will tell whether the party's position is a
bargaining tactic or a serious threat. After she emerged from a
half-hour meeting with President K.R. Narayanan earlier in the day,
Mrs. Gandhi said she was confident that Congress would win the
Samajwadi Party over.
</P>
<P>
   She said Congress now had the support of 272 members of
Parliament, enough for a bare one-vote majority, and promised that
she would give the president letters from allies to prove it within
two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 272 and we hope to get more,'' she said. ``We are
confident we will get more.''
</P>
<P>
   As the battle for power inches along, the tone of criticism from
members of the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, which
headed the year-old coalition government that collapsed Saturday,
is growing more shrill and bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the 1999-2000 budget, scheduled for adoption
Wednesday by consensus of all political parties, was delayed
because of disruptive, angry exchanges in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament was adjourned four times after irate members of the
Hindu nationalist coalition stormed to the well and shouted that
the Congress Party was trying to lure away the votes of members of
their alliance with unfair ``horse trading.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi replied, ``It is the habit of the BJP to accuse
others of what they have been indulging in.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress Party leaders want Mrs. Gandhi, the widow of one prime
minister, Rajiv Gandhi, and the daughter-in-law of another, Indira
Gandhi, to continue the dynastic reign. But she said Wednesday that
any such decision was premature. ``When the time comes, then we
will see,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi, who entered politics only a year ago to head the
foundering Congress Party, has had little experience in the
wheeling and dealing that will be required to hold together a new
government. Nor, party officials say, does this very private woman
have a strong appetite for politicking.
</P>
<P>
   But if she makes the leap now, she can expect the Hindu
nationalists to use her foreign birth against her. A Catholic from
Italy, she married Rajiv Gandhi in 1968 and became an Indian
citizen in 1986. Her husband was defeated as prime minister in 1989
and assassinated as he campaigned to regain the position in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday she got a taste of the hardball strategy. About a
dozen lawmakers from Bharatiya Janata and its allies noisily
gathered outside Parliament chanting: ``Sonia, go back. Rome raj
will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Gandhi can deliver the votes to form the government of
her choice _ and that is still far from certain _ the once dominant
Congress Party, in ruinous decline in the last decade, would
reclaim power from its main national rival. The new government
would be India's sixth since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts say that such a government, dependent for survival
on a set of regional, leftist and caste-based parties, would be
likely to topple in short order, with the probable result of new
national elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalists led a fractious coalition that came
undone last week and lost a confidence vote on Saturday by a
breathtakingly slim margin of 270- 269. There are 545 seats in the
lower house of Parliament, but with two vacant, 272 is for now the
magic number for a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The ousted government shocked the world last May by conducting
underground nuclear tests, which were then matched by Pakistan. In
recent months it has defined itself with steps to try to further
open India's economy to foreign investors, notably in the
government-run insurance industry, and to lower trade barriers, cut
food subsidies to people above the poverty line and start a
dialogue between Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and Nawaz
Sharif, the prime minister of archrival Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of a Congress-led government, heavily dependent on
support from parties on the left, would probably slow down
pro-market economic policies, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. diplomats say a Congress-led government would be much
less likely to sign the nuclear test ban treaty by the September
deadline set more than two years ago by a U.N. conference. Congress
has previously taken the position that India should not sign the
treaty until the major nuclear powers agree to take definite steps
to disarm their own nuclear stockpiles.
</P>
<P>
   Since India conducted its nuclear tests, Foreign Minister
Jaswant Singh and Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott have had
eight rounds of talks that only recently seemed to be heading
towards a successful conclusion, which in U.S. eyes would include
India's signing the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Singh and Talbott have developed a close rapport in what the
Americans describe as the most sustained high-level talks between
the United States and India since India gained its independence in
1947.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to start all over again, or at least give the new
government a while to sort itself out,'' said one frustrated U.S.
diplomat. ``In the best case it will take several months before we
can get moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mrs. Gandhi's confident statements Wednesday, it is not
clear who is providing the 272 votes she said she had. The
opposition had only 270 votes Saturday, and two small leftist
parties with 7 of those votes have vowed that they will never
support a Congress-led alliance.
</P>
<P>
   And now the 20 votes of the Samajwadi Party, based in the state
of Uttar Pradesh, are in question. The party sees Congress as a
potential threat to its own vote base among Muslims and Yadavs, the
politically influential cow herders' caste.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party may well be counting on defections from the
coalition led by the Hindu nationalists. By Wednesday, two members
of Parliament had switched sides, and a small party from the state
of Kashmir with two votes was hinting that it might support a new
government.
</P>
<P>
   Congress Party spokesman Arjun Singh said Tuesday that the
``migratory birds'' would begin to roost in their new home only
when the voting season arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi's confident remarks Wednesday may have been intended
to convince wavering members of Parliament who had been allied with
the Hindu nationalists that they should hitch themselves to a new
winning side. But the Samajwadi Party's defiance of Congress' game
plan exposed the fault lines that may yet crack apart any new
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
