<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: BHUTTO FACES PARLIAMENT OUSTER
</P>
<P>
   The chief election commissioner issued a notice for former Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto and her husband, Asif Ali Zardari, to
appear on Saturday before the commission, which is expected to take
steps to disqualify them from their seats in Parliament. The two
were convicted on corruption charges and barred from public office,
but Ms. Bhutto, who is in London, has said she will not return to
Pakistan until the Supreme Court decides on an appeal of her
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: POLICE ACCUSED
</P>
<P>
   Allegations of police brutality have more than doubled in the
last 12 months compared with the year before, according to a new
agency investigating police misconduct. The figures came to light
as the Independent Complaints Directorate took over the
investigation of six officers videotaped abusing suspects when they
took a television documentary crew out with them one night. The
officers were seen kicking, punching and setting their dogs on
handcuffed suspects.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: LINKED TO ALGERIAN ARMS
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor asked for prison terms of three to eight years for
11 men charged with smuggling arms to Islamic rebels in Algeria.
The network was said to have operated from Paris and to have
smuggled out weapons via Marseilles. The trial began in January and
a verdict is expected soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
