<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOSTFOUND-REVIEW-LADN     04-21 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSTFOUND-REVIEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S SOMETHING TO BE SAID FOR LOW-BROW COMEDY
</HEADLINE>
 -LADN (For use Friday, April 23 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ David Spade's new comedy, the sporadically funny
``Lost and Found,'' contains what may be the best dog poop visual
gag in recent film history. Whether you think this sounds appealing
or repulsive has everything to do with your decision to see this
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing its tone (and its cute little dog) from ``There's
Something About Mary,'' ``Lost and Found'' keeps its vulgarity
sweet and sassy, although the jokes are not nearly as inventive as
the Farrelly brothers' brand of warped humor. There are more laughs
than expected in the midst of a predictable plot that has Spade
pursuing French actress Sophie Marceau. If you can buy the
Spade-Marceau pairing, then you're halfway home to liking this
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Spade plays Dylan, co-owner of a failing restaurant and
possessor of some secret magic that makes him irresistible to
women. In the opening scenes, we see his breakup with a cowgirl
stripper. Dylan mourns the relationship for about five minutes
until he bumps into Lila DuBois (Marceau), his new next-door
neighbor. She's from Paris, plays the cello and owns an adorable
terrier that likes to roam away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan is instantly smitten and tries to charm Lila, but can't
get her alone. So he kidnaps her dog, figuring it's a good excuse
to spend some quality time together searching for the pooch. Mix in
a lost diamond ring that the dog may have swallowed, a handsome and
meddlesome ex-boyfriend (Patrick Bruel) determined to take Lila
back to France, and a rousing stage tribute to Neil Diamond, and
you've got the makings for a low-brow comedy that will easily amuse
the undiscriminating.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jeff Pollack (``Booty Call''), working from a script by
Spade, B.B. Cook and Marc Meeks, keeps things moving briskly. Jon
Lovitz shows up in a funny cameo as a ``dog whisperer'' and there
are brief, enjoyable appearances from Estelle Harris, Rose Marie,
Marla Gibbs and Carol Cook as a flatulent group of women who like a
good game of strip poker. Also on hand: ``Mad TV's'' Artie Shaw,
funny as a Chris Farley-like sidekick. (Lovitz: ``I see large and
small. Where's the medium?''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the romantic plot, Spade smirks less than usual,
which makes the prospect of spending an hour and a half with him
much more palatable. The script isn't smart enough to give Marceau
much to do besides smile and look great, but she doesn't seem to
mind being here. Neither will you if you're looking for something
lame-brained and light. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAUER-POLITICS-620&AMP;AD     04-21 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAUER-POLITICS-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAUER INVOKES COLORADO MASSACRE IN ANNOUNCING RUN FOR PRESIDENCY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Colo., Ohio, Ind., Okla.)  (rk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, Ky. _ Invoking the deadly shootings at a school in
Colorado as the agonizing measure of a country that had lost its
moral bearings, Gary L. Bauer announced his candidacy for the
Republican presidential nomination Wednesday and pledged to put
America back on a righteous track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture glorifies death in a thousand different ways,''
Bauer told an audience of about 900 people, including hundreds of
students, at the high school he once attended in this dowdy
working-class suburb of Cincinnati. ``We've got movies and music
and television shows that show people dying as if it were something
that was as simple as the sun coming up in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the America I want,'' he continued, his voice rising in
pitch and fervor, ``those Hollywood producers and directors _ they
wouldn't be able to show their faces in public, because you and
every other American would point to them and say, `Shame! Shame!
Shame!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a religious conservative on leave from his post as
president of the Family Research Council, had prepared a speech
that gave moral and social issues little more attention than tax
cutting and foreign policy. But he said the deaths in Littleton,
Colo., on Tuesday compelled a narrower focus and a more urgent
tone.
</P>
<P>
   His almost single-minded emphasis on morality in Wednesday's
speech underscored questions about whether Bauer, a long shot for
the Republican nomination by any pollster's calculations, joined a
crowded field as a truly viable contender with ideas on diverse
subjects or a protest candidate trying to hold other Republicans'
feet to a conservative fire.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, for example, made it clear that he could brook no
equivocation on the matter of abortion, legalized more than a
quarter century ago by a Supreme Court decision that he said
``really boils down to one simple and profoundly evil idea. They
said that our unborn children have no rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the polls say,'' Bauer said. ``I will never
sacrifice one American child, born or unborn. You can count on
it.'' At that, his listeners rose to their feet, as they did
several times during his impassioned remarks, with a roar of
approval and a sustained round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   Although other candidates for the Republican nomination like Dan
Quayle and Pat Buchanan have also put themselves forward as social
conservatives, Bauer Wednesday cast himself as the true standard
bearer.
</P>
<P>
   But he comes to presidential politics without any experience in
elective office. Bauer served as domestic policy adviser to
President Reagan in the 1980s and subsequently built the Family
Research Council, an advocacy group on the front lines of the
opposition to abortion and gay rights, into a rich, potent
political organization whose officers are widely quoted.
</P>
<P>
   The group's large mailing list has given Bauer a built-in base
of supporters and donors. Indeed, many of the people at his
announcement Wednesday said they had become familiar with Bauer
through their involvement with the council.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Green, a political scientist at the University of Akron
who studies religious conservatives, said that the council's base
could yield enough volunteers and small contributions to give
Bauer's candidacy some zest in the early primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of resources,'' Green said. ``In a crowded field,
he could finish second or third.''
</P>
<P>
   But Green said that Bauer's appeal was ultimately limited even
among religious conservatives, many of whom care most about picking
a Republican who can go the distance to the White House. ``I think
many of these pragmatists are convinced that if Pat Robertson
couldn't win the nomination, Gary Bauer can't,'' Green said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bauer did not get any break in the timing of Wednesday's
announcement, eclipsed by news of both the military operations in
Kosovo and the Colorado shootings. His situation called to mind the
misfortune four years ago of Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., who
announced his candidacy on the day that a bomb ripped apart the
federal building in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer sought to tailor his speech to this newly altered context
and found more verve in these spontaneous comments than in the
prepared remarks his aides had distributed a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He complained that America's robustness was too often gauged by
the size of its military or the dizzying heights of the stock
market. ``But you can also measure a nation by how many of its
families are broken, how big its virtue deficit is, how many of its
children cry themselves to sleep at night,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a gymnasium where the campaign placards and bunting
were no more conspicuous than two giant electronic scoreboards,
Bauer set himself apart from the moneyed, glitzy cliques who he
said often held sway over politics and popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many people in the elites of America _ in
Hollywood and on Wall Street and in Washington, D.C. _ too many
people that have forgotten that our liberty comes from God, not
from any man,'' Bauer told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, he tried to clarify for reporters the precise
connection between that observation and the bloodshed in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a society where you're no longer telling many of
your kids that they're created by God,'' he said, ``that their
liberty comes from him, that virtue matters and death is never an
option, whether it's an unborn baby or settling a fight, I don't
think we can be surprised when we get the kind of horrible pictures
and scenes that we increasingly see.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his opposition to more stringent gun control laws had
been shaken, he said it had not, because the problem is not the
availability of weapons but the hearts of those who use them.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's speech touched only briefly on other parts of his
agenda. He advocates a flat tax of 16 percent with more tax credits
for families with children. He also supports a stronger national
defense, though he has expressed opposition to the American
military involvement in Kosovo, which he said was not certain to
solve the region's endemic conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   In ways direct and indirect, he invoked Reagan, borrowing one of
his campaign anthems and the ``shining city on a hill'' reference
so beloved by the former president.
</P>
<P>
   But at least some of his listeners seemed less interested in
Gary Bauer the Reagan follower or Gary Bauer the tax cutter than in
Gary Bauer the moral crusader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's been called by God,'' said Donald Ochs, 52, the
owner of a company that makes computer parts.
</P>
<P>
   Geri Koch, 72, who described herself as an evangelical
Christian, said that Bauer was the candidate who best articulated
her values. Then she urged her interviewer to take Jesus Christ as
a personal savior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus is the only way to heaven,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
