<SLUG> BC-ELECT-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTILE TONE MAKES `ELECTION' A DOWNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Friday, April 23 by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A brutal satire about the impact of a hard-fought
student government contest, ``Election'' is smart, often funny and
nearly impossible to like. Writer-director Alexander Payne has
fashioned a complex, knowing look at the vile impulses that lurk
beneath the surface of seemingly nice people, but his movie is so
mean-spirited and full of contempt for humanity that it largely
becomes an exercise in hostility.
</P>
<P>
   The self-defeating movie opens with snarky voice-overs from its
two main characters. Jim McAllister (Matthew Broderick) is a
well-liked student government teacher who has been with Omaha's
George Washington Carver High for 12 years. He drives a beat-up
Ford Fiesta, wears short-sleeve shirts with outdated ties and has a
cold, dispassionate marriage with his wife (``my best friend''),
Diane (Molly Hagan).
</P>
<P>
   Jim's nemesis is Tracy Flick (Reese Witherspoon), a
preternaturally perky overachiever who views high school as the
first step toward world domination. Tracy is running _ unopposed _
for student body president until Mr. McAllister recruits his own
candidate, Paul Metzler (Chris Klein), a popular football hero.
Tracy does not take this development lightly. ``The weak always try
to sabotage the strong,'' she intones ominously.
</P>
<P>
   Is good-natured Jim McAllister weak? Initially, his animosity
toward Tracy seems to stem from his knowledge of her affair with
his best friend and former colleague, Dave Novotny (Mark Harelik).
Knowing she's not quite the ingenue that her image suggests, Jim
sets out to thwart her.
</P>
<P>
   But as ``Election'' moves along and Jim's behavior becomes more
and more erratic, it becomes clear that there's something deeper at
work here. Although he insists everything is fine (the man is in
deep denial, Jim clearly isn't fulfilled by either his wife (he has
a trunk full of porn in the basement and fantasizes about Novotny's
estranged wife) or his job. Thus, when he looks at the industrious
Tracy, he sees his own stagnant life with a new-found clarity.
</P>
<P>
   This is all well and good, but Payne (who, with Jim Taylor,
adapted the screenplay from Tom Perrotta's novel) lets his
stridency get the best of him. Payne grew up in the film's Omaha
and set his other movie, the abortion comedy ``Citizen Ruth,'' here
as well. Judging from the hateful manner in which he portrays every
person in this story and the godawful way he films the
surroundings, the experience must have been a painful one.
</P>
<P>
   If the film was half as insightful as it believes, the shrill
tone would go down a little easier. But too many of the broadsides
here are obvious, including a Monica Lewinsky moment that concludes
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they are playing complete caricatures, Broderick and
Witherspoon come across fairly well, with Broderick nicely playing
off his ``Ferris Bueller'' high school past. The film's other teen
roles went mostly to unknowns _ Klein's dim-witted Paul; Jessica
Campbell as Paul's angry lesbian sister, Tammy; and Frankie
Ingrassia playing the bisexual Lisa, the object of the siblings'
affections. The newcomers acquit themselves nicely even if their
efforts are ultimately overwhelmed by all the sneering. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
