<HEADLINE>
REGGIE LEWIS JURORS TO HEAR SOME DRUG EVIDENCE, JUDGE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A judge has ruled that allegations of illegal drug use
by the late Boston Celtics star Reggie Lewis may be considered as
evidence at an upcoming malpractice trial resulting from his death.
</P>
<P>
   But Superior Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith said Wednesday
that jurors will only be able to hear specific allegations if
lawyers for the four doctors Lewis's widow is suing can prove a
connection between Lewis's alleged cocaine use and the doctors'
failure to diagnose the heart condition that killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Lewis's widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, had asked that
any evidence of illicit drug use be barred from the trial,
scheduled to begin next week, arguing that the issue had been
raised ``for the sole purpose of trashing'' Lewis's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   After a hearing Wednesday in Suffolk Superior Court,
Fremont-Smith ruled that evidence of drug use would be relevant
``if it can be proven.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., the cardiologist who treated Lewis,
said he could not accurately diagnose Lewis's condition because
Lewis withheld information on his cocaine use until two weeks
before he collapsed and died on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Fremont-Smith said he would decide what, if any, evidence of
drug use would be admissible on a case-by-case basis during the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis, who denies her husband used cocaine, has sued
Mudge and three other doctors, Peter L. Friedman, Mark A. Creager,
and John D. Rutherford, for failing to diagnose Lewis with a
life-threatening heart condition. Lewis died in 1993 shortly after
collapsing on a basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom Wednesday, Harris-Lewis declined to
comment on the judge's ruling, saying only that she was ``anxious
for the truth to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to restoring Reggie's good name for his
children, his family, the community, his fans, and for me,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
