<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-TILBERIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIZ TILBERIS, 51; EDITOR OF HARPER'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harper's Bazaar editor Liz Tilberis, renowned for raising public
awareness of ovarian cancer, died of the disease Wednesday in New
York at age 51.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tilberis, whose career included a stint as editor in chief
of British Vogue, was diagnosed with cancer in 1993. She described
her struggle with it, and her rise in the fashion industry, in her
1998 memoir, ``No Time to Die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Liz's instincts and eye for fashion, fashion photography, and
style were unparalleled,'' said Cathleen P. Black, president of
Hearst Magazines, Harper's publisher. ``She will be remembered as
one of the magazine industry's greatest 20th-century talents. And
for those of us who were lucky enough to work with her, her passion
and love for life were inspirational.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tilberis, born in Shirehampton, England, was a true student
of fashion who, in her early years, eagerly studied fabrics and
designs. She got her foot in the door at British Vogue in 1969 _
not through high-level connections, but by winning an essay
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Although office culture dictated that she wear the most
up-to-the-moment designer clothes, Ms. Tilberis in those days
humbly shopped at Woolworth's and flea markets. She dyed her shoes
different colors every night to match the next day's outfit, and
even repaired the broken zippers of her colleagues' pants to
supplement her $1,500-a-year starting salary.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview in July in Boston, she said, ``I never had
good taste. Even today, I don't feel I have great taste. I trained
to become a designer, and I was a very bad one. When I became a
junior fashion editor, I was very observant. I watched very
carefully women with great taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Her studies paid off and she ascended the ranks at British Vogue
(from intern to fashion assistant to fashion editor to executive
fashion editor to editor in chief) with a reputation for forward
thinking. Under her direction, for example, the late Princess of
Wales graced the cover in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   She was named editor of Harper's in 1992, the 125th anniversary
of the magazine, and she became a fashion force in New York. When
Ms. Tilberis hosted a Christmas party at her home a few years ago,
Calvin Klein was the first one there, followed by Ralph Lauren, and
Donna Karan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tilberis introduced to Harper's a higher quality of
journalism by hiring such staffers as internationally renowned
fashion photographers Patrick DeMarchelier and Peter Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   The editor tackled her cancer with the same zeal she used to
steer her career. She was convinced that she developed ovarian
cancer from the fertility treatment she underwent years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the president of the nonprofit Ovarian Cancer Research Fund
Inc., Ms. Tilberis traveled the country speaking about her
experiences and encouraging others. Last summer she told the Globe,
``All I care about is for a woman (with symptons) to make an
appointment'' with her gynecologist.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tilberis leaves her husband, Andrew; and two sons,
Christopher and Robert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STACY-ENGLISH-HORN-AR     04-21 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STACY-ENGLISH-HORN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING A MYSTIQUE OF THE ENGLISH HORN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Thomas Stacy was a 14-year-old in rural
Arkansas, he made a decision that must have struck his friends as
odd. Having already studied the piano, violin, clarinet and oboe _
moving from one to another as he became captivated by their sound
on recordings _ he resolved to take up the English horn, the
instrument he now plays in the New York Philharmonic, and sold his
motorcycle in order to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a Harley or anything, just a small, lightweight
motorcycle,'' Stacy, who is now 60, said in defense of the trade.
Still, one had to ask, why the English horn? ``I think it can be
played like Renata Tebaldi sang, or the way a great cellist plays a
solo,'' he said. ``It innately has a many-hued tonal palette, and a
wide emotional menu, and it offers the possibility and potential of
inflecting each note, to give it forward motion, or make it
something special. People love the sound of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviews of the Philharmonic's concerts support that assertion:
in works with prominent English horn lines _ Sibelius' ``Swan of
Tuonela,'' the Largo of Dvorak's ``New World'' Symphony, the
Shostakovich Eighth Symphony, the Tchaikovsky Fourth and Copland's
``Quiet City'' are examples _ his contributions are regularly
singled out for their graceful phrasing and rich tone.
</P>
<P>
   He also made several appearances as a concerto soloist with the
Philharmonic, and at the orchestra's concert Thursday night, with
Sir Colin Davis conducting, he is to give the U.S. premiere of
``The World's Ransoming,'' a concerto by Scottish composer James
MacMillan. (The program is to be repeated Friday morning and
Saturday evening.)
</P>
<P>
   Several of the concertos that Stacy has performed with the
Philharmonic were composed for him, the most recent being Ned
Rorem's 1994 Concerto for English Horn and Orchestra. MacMillan's
work was not. It is the first part of an orchestral triptych called
``Triduum,'' composed for the London Symphony in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he uses the various registers of the English horn to
their expressive advantage throughout the piece,'' Stacy said of
MacMillan. ``It is scored for a very large orchestra, and there are
some technical considerations, as there are in most concerti. But
he also creates moments, architecturally, where the English horn
can float out its sound. The greatest difficulty, I think, is to
make sure it expresses something of oneself, and has the right
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   MacMillan, 39, is part of a growing group of composers around
the world _ others include Arvo Paert, Somei Satoh and Osvaldo
Golijov _ who find inspiration in religious mysticism. In his case,
the source of the inspiration is Roman Catholicism, and the three
sections of ``Triduum'' are meant to evoke the days leading to
Easter. ``The World's Ransoming'' suggests Maundy Thursday and uses
references to the liturgy for that day, including the chant
melodies ``Pange lingua'' and ``Ubi caritas.'' The second part of
``Triduum,'' a Cello Concerto, is for Good Friday, and ``The
Vigil'' is for the night before Easter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first, shall we say, religious concerto that I've
ever played,'' Stacy said, ``and knowing that, I suppose I do
approach it differently from the way I would approach a work
without those associations. But I think of it as contemplative
rather than descriptive, and I tend to bring my own meaning to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Stacy was born in Augusta, Ark., a town with a population of
about 3,000. After piano lessons with his mother, he had brief
flirtations with the violin and the clarinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I heard an oboe on a record in my mother's collection,''
he said, ``and that sound intoxicated me.''
</P>
<P>
   From the oboe it was a short leap to the English horn, the
tenor-voiced member of the same family of double-reed instruments,
and which uses similar fingerings. Stacy also plays the alto of the
oboe group, called the oboe d'amore. In his recitals, he sometimes
plays Gardner Read's ``Phantasmagoria,'' a work in which he is
required to switch between oboe, oboe d'amore and English horn.
</P>
<P>
   Having apparently exhausted Augusta's supply of music teachers,
Stacy taught himself to play the oboe and the English horn with the
help of a book that showed the fingerings. When he was 17, and
still a high school junior, the Eastman School of Music in
Rochester gave him a full scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a little crazy to teach yourself the oboe,'' he
said, ``but I just wanted to do it, and I did it. I had to start
over when I got to Eastman, because my technique was all wrong. On
the other hand, I think I was a fast learner because, having taught
myself, I was very aware of what I was doing physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out on oboe at Eastman,'' he added, ``but I also
played English horn in some of the performing groups. It was
already my preference. It fits my musical persona like a glove.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes it an odd preference, though, is that opportunities
for English hornists are comparatively few. It does not have a vast
solo repertory. It offers no life whatsoever in jazz or popular
music, and its best prospect in the classical music world is the
possibility of an orchestral position. Even those are few and far
between: orchestras have only a single English hornist, compared
with more than 30 violinists, and three or more flutists, oboists,
clarinetists and trumpeters.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Stacy found a job with the New Orleans
Philharmonic soon after his graduation from Eastman in 1960. A year
later he moved to the San Antonio Symphony, and in 1962 he joined
the Minnesota Orchestra, where he remained until he joined the
Philharmonic in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   During his 27 years with the Philharmonic, Stacy has worked with
notable success at creating a solo life for his instrument. He has
given the premieres of 25 works, including concertos and solo
pieces by Stanislaw Skrowaczewski, Gunther Schuller, Vincent
Persichetti, Petris Vasks, Sydney Hodkinson and Calvin Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   He teaches at the Juilliard School and for the last 20 years has
led an annual English horn summer seminar. The seminar began in
Ithaca and has traveled around the country. It is now held in
Carmel Valley, Calif., and attracts, Stacy says, players from 15 to
76. When his commitments to the Philharmonic allow, he tours as a
recitalist, chamber player and orchestral soloist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arranging the appearances is a different sell for me than it
would be for, say, a violinist,'' he said. ``An orchestra might
decide to program the Beethoven or Brahms violin concerto, and then
decide which soloist to hire. With me, we have to sell both the
repertory and my being the soloist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic gives Stacy ample spotlight time as well: he
has given 60 performances as a concerto soloist with the orchestra,
which is unusual among American orchestras for the frequency with
which it presents its first chair players (and sometimes others) in
concertos. Besides Stacy's performances, the coming weeks include
concerto performances by Cynthia Phelps, the principal violist, and
Rebecca Young, the associate principal, in a new double viola
concerto by Sofia Gubaidulina; Christopher Lamb, the principal
percussionist, in a new concerto by Tan Dun; Joseph Robinson the
principal oboist, in the Strauss Oboe Concerto, and Joseph Alessi,
the principal trombonist, in William Grant Still's ``Romance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This MacMillan piece really is a tour de force,'' Stacy said,
``and several people have remarked on the endurance required to get
through it. But I don't know _ I never think about that. And now I
kind of wish no-one had mentioned it to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
