<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHALE-AUTOPSY-BOS &LR;      04-21 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALE-AUTOPSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY INSPECTION RULES OUT EXTERNAL CAUSE FOR WHALE'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLFLEET, Mass. _ In life, Staccato was a rare ray of hope for
the world's dwindling band of Northern right whales, a strong
female who bore at least six calves over the last 25 years, making
her the mother of perhaps 2 percent of the whole species.
</P>
<P>
   In death, turned awkwardly on her side on a sandy beach as an
autopsy team methodically stripped the blubber from her body,
Staccato became another symbol of man's inability to protect the
most endangered large whale species in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Despite extraordinary measures to save the creatures such as
planes assigned to keep an eye on them, Staccato died from causes
that have not yet been determined, bringing the right whales one
step closer to extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know every one of them that washes up on the beach. I hate
going to these things,'' said Scott Kraus, director of the Doc
Edgerton Lab at the New England Aquarium who estimates he has seen
Staccato two dozen times. ``You keep rooting for them to have
babies, but the population keeps going downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy, conducted under sunny skies before a crowd of
onlookers on a stretch of the Cape Cod National Seashore, resembled
a demolition project more than a medical procedure, as a back hoe
attempted to pull the head away and workers carved the carcass with
scythe-like tools called flensing knives.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grim task and the powerful odor, however, the
45-foot-long whale will be a bonanza for researchers looking to
better understand the whales' plight. Almost every part of the
animal, from the blubber to the eyeballs to her skeleton, was
promised to a researcher or an educational institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we get our hands on a right whale, we pull out all
the stops'' for the autopsy, said Douglas Beach, in charge of right
whale protection efforts at the National Marine Fisheries Service.
He said researchers want to know everything from Staccato's age to
any chronic diseases she might have had.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that researchers are still debating, the Northern
right whale population has not recovered more than 60 years after
the last of the whalers put away their harpoons. While other whale
species, such as the humpbacks, have shown strong population growth
in recent years, the right whale population has remained stuck at
around 300 members.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, researchers at Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution and
the University of Massachusetts at Boston recently concluded that
the slow, steady loss of whales like Staccato have put the species
on a course for extinction if current trends continue.
</P>
<P>
   When Staccato's carcass was reported floating off Wellfleet's
Great Island on Wednesday, speculation centered on whether she had
been struck by a boat, the leading cause of human-induced death.
Officials at the state Division of Marine Fisheries had been
worried that an unusually large number of right whales had gathered
in the bay, making them vulnerable to boat strike.
</P>
<P>
   But the autopsy team, led by David St. Aubin of the Mystic
Aquarium in Connecticut, could find no signs of external injuries
from a boat strike, nor any signs that the whale had become fatally
entangled in fishing nets. However, the team could not rule out a
ship strike until members examined internal organs for damage.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, St. Aubin's team found ulcers on her big gray
tongue that could indicate a viral infection, as well as unusual
lesions near her fluke. Still, St. Aubin said he could not say
whether disease played a role in Staccato's death until he examined
her internal organs _ and perhaps not even then.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we have no diagnosis,'' said St Aubin, whose
work was hindered by an advancing afternoon tide that pooled around
Staccato's carcass.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the questions surrounding Staccato's death matched the
</P>
<P>
   questions about what should be done to save the species.
Officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service, which is
drafting a new 10-year protection plan, say the sheer size and
range of the whales makes them hard to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have a right whale hatchery'' to increase the
population, Beach said, because 60-ton whales need far too much
space to live, ranging from Florida to the Bay of Fundy in the
wild.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, state and federal regulators have tried to prevent more
whale deaths, but that has proven difficult, requiring widespread
controls of fishing gear and shipping traffic on the Eastern
seaboard to prevent whale strikes and entanglements that occur just
a few times a year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kraus of the New England Aquarium said the federal
government needs to make a bold investment in the whales, much as
they have other high profile rare animals. He noted that the
Clinton Administration wants to spend $127 million to protect
salmon in the Pacific Northwest, but the National Marine Fisheries
Service spends just $1 million a year on right whales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
