<HEADER>
A7976 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPA-ATHOME22-COX     04-21 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPA-ATHOME22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Liquid refreshment: A relaxing `spa' bath with all the trimmings
restores a sane outlook
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling tired, overworked and stressed? Relax and put your feet
up.
</P>
<P>
   For some women, that means a day or weekend at a full-service
spa. But if you don't have the time or the money, you can create a
similar experience at home using spa products designed to
rejuvenate the body and soul.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is one hour and a hot bath.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Kinzer Trettel of Atlanta makes a ``spa'' bath part of
her weekly ritual. The 32-year-old special events planner says her
health problems and stress level have improved as a result of the
pampering and relaxation therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can't live without it,'' she says. ``I try to do it more
than once a week, but sometimes it doesn't always happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Health and beauty experts say prioritizing is key.
</P>
<P>
   You have to put yourself at the top of your to-do list, put down
the cell phone, turn off the beeper and lock the bathroom door.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we think about an hour and how much time we spend and waste
in an evening, we can take that time to do something nice for
ourselves. It helps your head. It helps you feel like you're worth
it,'' said Sydell Harris, owner of Spa Sydell, which has five
locations in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   To create the mood, start with scented candles, soft music and
aromatherapy, the art of using essential oils to treat the body and
mind therapeutically.
</P>
<P>
   Clean your body and face with an exfoilating scrub. Rinse off in
the shower and towel dry. Now it's time for a luxurious bath. To
begin, fill the tub and put a few drops of an essential oil into
the water. Harris recommends lavender or rosemary for relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   While the bath water is running, apply a facial mask. Soak for
at least 15 to 20 minutes. While you are there, massage your feet.
Place camomile tea bags on the eyes to reduce puffiness. Then rinse
off. After towel drying, apply a massage oil to the body, a foot
cream on the feet and lotion on the hands.
</P>
<P>
   It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to do too much, you'll start working too hard.
Choose one or two things and make it a very comfortable, relaxing
experience,'' says Patti Beggs, owner of Natural Body Day Spa,
which has four locations in the metro area.
</P>
<P>
   For example, instead of trying to polish your nails and toes and
color your hair after the bath, leave it for another night. A long
bath is more important.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Ragsdale, director of Jolie the Day Spa in Atlanta,
recommends muscle soaks for women who exercise a lot.
</P>
<P>
   And if you can get a massage _ whether at home or at a spa later
_ go for it, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massaging the body is becoming a must, not a luxury,''
Ragsdale adds. ``It's a necessity to relieve the stress and tension
the body endures.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding aromatic products to enhance the spa experience is easy.
The industry has grown so much that consumers can purchase them at
full-service spas, bath shops, department stores and discount
chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, the aromatherapy business had grown from a
nonbusiness to a $230 million business,'' said Aubin Wilson, show
manager of Ex.Tracts for George Little, a New York trade show
management firm. ``Since then, a host of people, like Coty for
example, have gotten into the market. Coty is now doing the whole
Healing Garden line.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend is being driven by baby boomers who are trying to slow
down their hectic lifestyle _ and the aging process _ by turning
their homes into oases of peace and tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   Target recognized the trend with its own line of products last
year called Inner Spirit. The line, which includes a muscle soak,
polishing body scrub and moisturizing body lotion, is made with
lemon grass and ginger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really call it aromatherapy, because we don't
necessarily have all essential oils in our products. We call it
wellness,'' said Sherry Day, buyer of bath and fragrance products
for Target.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
