<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-KILLERS-BOS &LR;      04-21 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-KILLERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEGED KILLERS FIT A DANGEROUS PATTERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The black BMW was a fixture outside the Reed
Street home where Eric Harris lived, an almost daily sign of
another visit by the car's owner, Dylan Klebold, a loner in
fatigues and a black trench coat who didn't want to be alone.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, the day before the two young men allegedly
massacred 12 fellow high school students and one teacher before
killing themselves, the visits to Reed Street seemed as
unremarkable as Klebold and Harris themselves. The two invariably
stayed inside, avoiding the sunshine to retain a ghoulish pallor,
working on computers, and commiserating about their shared plight
as teenage misfits, according to friends, neighbors, and
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   But at about 9:30 a.m. Monday, when they should have been at
school, Harris and Klebold arrived together in the BMW, seeming
agitated and hurried, acting as if something had gone wrong, said
Bill Konen, a human resources consultant who lives next door on the
quiet cul-de-sac of modern $200,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard one say, `I need a metal baseball bat,''' recalled
Konen, who was painting the back of his house, unnoticed by the
pair. ``They left the garage door open, like they didn't care who
saw them. And then all you could hear was breaking glass, like they
were smashing the place all up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from the polite young man whose mother had
introduced him to Konen as a ``computer nut'' who would be happy to
help set up an Internet web site. In retrospect, according to Konen
and more than two dozen others interviewed Wednesday, Monday's
outburst was the most outward sign of what was brewing. Before they
allegedly brought guns and pipe bombs to school on Tuesday, causing
the deadliest rampage inside an American school, Harris, 18, and
Klebold, 17, seemed not terribly different from thousands of
teenagers who gravitate toward each other at least in part because
they don't fit anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   They were neither athletic nor particularly studious, lacking
social skills and the grace and self-confidence that popular
teenagers often possess or project. But unlike Harris and Klebold,
the overwhelming majority of youths in such situations never
respond with violence.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever set the Columbine High School killers into deadly
action is not known, authorities said Wednesday, acknowledging that
with the two suspects dead, they may never have more than troubling
pieces of an incomplete puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, a picture can be drawn of Harris and Klebold
that fits a disturbing pattern among young men who erupt in deadly
rage in the places they see as the locus of their torment: their
schools.
</P>
<P>
   They were members of a self-styled ``Trench Coat Mafia,'' fellow
students said, describing the group of anywhere from 15 to 30
students as outcasts who often dressed in black or in military
fatigues, covered by long black trench coats or Australian-style
duster coats. At times, some also wore red or green berets,
students said.
</P>
<P>
   Several students said Harris, Klebold and their friends spoke of
mutilating animals, and were interested in the occult, androgynous
rock star Marilyn Manson, and World War II, especially Nazism and
Adolph Hitler, whose birthday was Tuesday. Harris, in particular,
was interested in German culture and often spoke German, said Matt
Good, 16, a sophomore who lived two houses away from Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quiet, but he wasn't mean or anything,'' Good said.
``He just hung around with that group, and pretty much all of them
were strange.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Good said, Klebold ``seemed really mean. He glared
at people all the time.'' Several other students commented on
Klebold's temper.
</P>
<P>
   Good said he heard Klebold make comments about blacks and Jews,
who together make up only a small minority in the school of 1,800
students.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold also seemed particularly angry about the
perceived popularity and power of student athletes. ``You'd always
hear them say, `Jocks think they can run the school,' and stuff
like that,'' Good said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at the same time, they also reportedly were enrolled in a
morning bowling class, built web sites for fun, and Klebold _ a
lanky six-foot-three _ was an active member of a fantasy baseball
league. They also reportedly had made a video about how to cope
with teenage life, though some students who said they saw it
claimed it contained hints about the violence that was to come.
Authorities said they had obtained a copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boy next door has a silent crisis: He's desperate, lonely
and confused about his self-esteem,'' said William Pollack, a
clinical psychologist at Harvard Medical School and author of the
book ``Real Boys: Rescuing Our Sons From the Myth of Boyhood.''
``The line between the normal, healthy boy and the ones who pick up
a gun is much thinner than we would like to think. My question is,
`How come more don't do it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   School officials said they were unfamiliar with the Trench Coat
Mafia, saying they considered it part of the ``goth'' crowd of
teenagers who wear black lipstick and white face powder, and who
claim to follow satanic rituals. But students scoffed at the
suggestion that the group was unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every student in the school knows about them,'' said Josh
Nielsen, 17, a junior. ``If the teachers didn't, they sure should
have.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a group of so-called Trench Coat Mafia members posed
for a photo in Columbine's 1998 yearbook; neither Harris nor
Klebold appears in the photo, under which a caption reads: ``Who
says we're different? Insanity's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Klebold's picture in on a separate page, with the statement:
``After going through many experiences in their lives, oftentimes
students have regrets of past actions.''
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, the ``mafia'' included an 18-year-old named
Robert Craig, who in 1997 killed his stepfather and then fatally
shot himself, according to police. It was not immediately clear if
Craig was a friend of Harris or Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Harris and Klebold's only previous run-in with
the law was a 1998 criminal trespass case in which they attempted
to break into a car intending to steal its contents.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the only sign of activity at Klebold's house
was a sheriff's deputy parked in the driveway, shooing away
reporters who hoped for a glimpse of his parents. The house _
located on the fringe of a national park _ was magnificent, two
wood-and-glass structures framed by massive sandstone formations.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris family moved to Reed Street, about 10 miles from
Klebold's house, about two years ago, neighbors said. Keith Huff, a
sales representative who lives across the street, said Harris's
father, Wayne, was a retired military man; he did not know whether
Harris's mother, Cathy, worked outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're good people. They were always nice and
friendly,'' Huff said. ``You didn't see them a lot, but they were
good neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor, Steve Cohn, recalled that there was a robbery
at a nearby home last year in which several guns and a rifle were
stolen. Cohn said a member of the Trench Coat Mafia, though not
Harris or Klebold, was implicated in the robbery. ``My friend who
was robbed called . . . and just kept saying, `Was it my guns, what
if it was my guns?' '' Cohn said.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered the door Wednesday at Harris's well-tended home;
a black Toyota pickup truck sat in the driveway. Behind a back tire
was the morning newspaper, detailing what the boy who once lived
inside had allegedly done.
</P>
</TEXT>
