<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-STUDENTS-COX     04-21 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-STUDENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students in other parts of Colorado stunned by school shooting
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ The nervousness Grand Junction High
School freshman Trisha Hunt felt
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday should have been reserved for getting a test back or
cheerleading tryouts. But less than 24 hours after the deadliest
school shooting in U.S. history, Hunt said she was actually scared
to go to class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous,'' said the 15-year-old, referring to Tuesday's
massacre in Littleton. ``If it could happen in Denver, it could
happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt sat in a circle with four friends eating lunch Wednesday
with the thoughts of what happened just 250 miles away still fresh
in her mind, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire and explosions riddled the Columbine High School commons
area Tuesday at lunchtime as two students attacked classmates with
guns and homemade bombs. The siege ended with 15 students and
teachers dead. More than 20 additional victims were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Later, authorities discovered 30 explosive devices in the school
and parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt's feeling of nervousness may have been unique, but a somber
and heavy-hearted atmosphere Wednesday engulfed high schools
normally bustling with spring fever this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids were a little quieter,'' said Fruita Monument
Principal Mark Zipse. ``But if there's a good side, I'm seeing a
lot more hugs in the halls and hearing friends telling each other
that they appreciate them a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Edmonds, principal at Grand Junction High School, observed
the same thing in the halls of her school. ``It was a little more
of a sober feeling today. People caring more about each other,''
she said. ``I feel like everyone realizes that we're all in this
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Edmonds said, she saw students talk to classmates
they didn't even know or had never spoken to before.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Irvine, a 15-year-old sophomore at Palisade High School,
said teachers were encouraging students to create a better
environment by being more accepting of all students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were saying that it could happen anywhere and that we
need to give everyone respect at our schools,'' Irvine said.
</P>
<P>
   All the schools have cliques of students that keep to
themselves, Hunt said, and there is even a group at her school who
wear trench coats.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're involved in things and really nice,'' she said,
adding that they certainly didn't fit the description of suspected
gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, members of a group of
outcasts called the ``Trench Coat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout school districts, principals met with their staffs
before classes began to review emergency procedures and talk about
the situation in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kasper, principal at Pomona Elementary School, said he asked
teachers to be listeners Wednesday. As he went around the building
this morning, Kasper said, he heard discussions about what children
had heard and seen on television the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some classes it was being discussed and in others, students
were talking to teachers individually,'' Kasper said. ``It seemed
to be a successful day.''
</P>
<P>
   John Vail, principal at Bookcliff Middle School in Grand
Junction, said first-period teachers were instructed to ask
students if they had questions or comments. After about 15 minutes
to a half hour of discussion, it was business as usual at the
school, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the high school, Hunt said, teachers actually practiced the
lockdown procedure that helped save the lives of many Columbine
High School students Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There was also an additional police officer at the school to
offer any assistance he could, Hunt said. ``Some people don't seem
to understand why there's more cops,'' Hunt said. ``But I'm glad we
have more police officers here today.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials would not allow counselors to speak with
reporters, but Zipse and Edmonds said that there have been no
students overwhelmed with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The counselors are not as busy as we thought they'd be,''
Edmonds said. ``They've talked to some students. Some have been
touched more than others and they needed to talk about it a little
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Miller, a 14-year-old high school freshman, said she
couldn't even imagine going through what her friends who attended
Columbine were forced to go through. ``To have to look at a list to
find out if you're friends are OK?,'' she said shaking her head.
``I couldn't even go back to that school.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
