<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAIN-KIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUSES OF DEATH DETERMINED FOR TODDLERS FOUND SLAIN NEAR AUSTIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUTTO, Texas _ A blunt blow to the head killed the little boy
while the girl, also still in diapers, was suffocated, authorities
said Wednesday of two toddlers' bodies found dumped in a shallow
creek outside this small farming town near Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question at this point that it is a homicide,''
Williamson County Sheriff Ed Richards said at the rural crime scene
in Central Texas where the bodies, still unnamed and unclaimed,
were found on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe the boy is between 1 and 3 years old while the
girl is likely older, between 2 and 4. DNA tests will soon be
conducted to determine whether the children, who strongly resemble
each other, are perhaps siblings.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said he was comfortable releasing no more than basic
shreds of findings from the autopsies, performed by the Tarrant
County medical examiner's office in Fort Worth. Information has
been a highly guarded commodity in a confounding case that
authorities say has yielded few concrete pieces of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Law officers, however, said media focus on the mysterious case
has produced several good leads and they remain hopeful for a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most horrifying thing about this is no one seems to know
who these children are,'' said Texas Department of Public Safety
spokeswoman Tela Mange. ``These babies have a name, and somebody
knows them and somebody loves them.''
</P>
<P>
   An evidence search of nearby fields has yet to turn up
``anything of any significance,'' the sheriff said. The search
expanded Wednesday to deeper holes in the mostly shallow Brushy
Creek where a couple discovered the small bodies nearly 48 hours
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A team of five DPS divers unloaded equipment at the scene where
they battled with water moccasins and rugged terrain, said
department spokesman Mike Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've shot several snakes down there. It's real rugged and
real snaky territory that they're going through,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just checking to make sure they haven't missed
anything in the search. There are some pockets there that are
fairly deep, so that's why they'll be wearing wet suits,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Cox and others conceded it was unusual not to have identified
the two corpses 48 hours after their discovery. They noted,
however, that children so young don't carry identification or have
dental records that could be checked.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two Texas Rangers have determined that the
victims &UR;  &LR; don't fit the descriptions of most of the 74 missing
children listed by the DPS Missing Persons Clearinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they've exhausted every name yet but they're
moving pretty far down the list,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
