<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-REORG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGED FLEET-BANKBOSTON WILL HAVE NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Barely one month after sealing an agreement to combine
into the nation's eighth-largest bank, Fleet Financial Group Inc.
and BankBoston Corp. have hunkered down over the drawing boards to
design a new company out of two dissimilar institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Though regulators won't approve the merger until later this
year, dozens of staffers from both sides are already drafting
blueprints to meld the two companies and select an A-list of
executives who will run the combined bank's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The planning, a delicate and contentious process that will
eventually result in people and chunks of Fleet and BankBoston
being moved around like building blocks, must be done carefully.
Any missteps could shake investor confidence or scare away
customers, which in turn could hurt earnings and even attract
bidders for the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Executives must figure out how Fleet _ hard-nosed, aggressive,
and diverse in its business lines _ will absorb the smaller and
more consumer-oriented BankBoston, a Brahmin institution with an
international presence that Fleet lacks.
</P>
<P>
   There is social engineering, too.
</P>
<P>
   Redesigning the corporate structure means creating a new
hierarchy _ a sticky winnowing in which some senior BankBoston
executives will find themselves working under Fleet peers. Despite
efforts by both banks to describe their $15 billion merger as one
of equals, Fleet, which held its annual shareholders' meeting
Wednesday, has moved quickly to take the reins of the planning
process.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month Fleet's mergers and acquisitions strategist,
H. Jay Sarles, and his counterpart at BankBoston, Peter J. Manning,
separately drew up charts showing what each thought the new bank
should look like. While the two men are jointly in charge of
melding the two companies, most of the work and decisions are being
made by Fleet's head of corporate strategy and development, Brian
T. Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   With a staff of 12 people, mostly from Fleet, Moynihan is
designing a new organizational structure, drafting cost-savings and
revenue-boosting plans, overseeing plans to divest $13 billion in
deposits and $5 billion in assets, and plotting how to win both
regulatory and shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fleet chief executive Terrence Murray and his
BankBoston counterpart, Charles K. ``Chad'' Gifford, have discussed
four times in recent weeks which 50 executives will be in charge of
the new company's 20 main business lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to resolve issues of both turf and people,''
explained one BankBoston source. ``What might be under one function
at BankBoston is under another one at Fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   Six of the nine top executive positions at the combined bank
have already been filled by Fleet people. So when the original list
of next-level executives proposed by Murray was full of Fleet
names, it raised Gifford's hackles. Murray, in the mood for
compromise, has since sought ways to include more BankBoston
executives, but the two men are still wrangling. The list is to be
unveiled early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the list, Thomas F. Theurkauf, a banking analyst at
Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods Inc., said, ``the next organizational
charts are critical. You have to establish clear lines of authority
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined bank plans to keep intact BankBoston's inner-city
branches, known as First Community Bank. But it is has not been
decided whether Gail Snowden, who now heads the network, will
continue to do so at the combined company, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest squabbles are over how to organize corporate, or
wholesale, banking. With a large, sophisticated lending practice
steeped in tradition _ it financed McDonald's Corp. founder Ray
Kroc and the classic Hollywood film ``Casablanca'' _ BankBoston
caters to the nation's top companies and has a national reputation.
BankBoston groups San Francisco investment bank Robertson Stephens
Inc. into its wholesale banking unit.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, by contrast, is much more modest, and primarily focused
on midsize New England companies. Combined, the two banks, with
$178 billion in assets, will be the nation's top commercial finance
provider and number three commercial lender.
</P>
<P>
   To help him decide who and what go where, Moynihan has two dozen
people _ half from Fleet, half from BankBoston _ who will soon
begin gathering data on core business lines, from retail banking to
an on-line brokerage. The idea is not just to glue the two banks
together but to figure out, for example, which structure will help
the combined bank sell Fleet-run mutual funds in Latin America,
where BankBoston has a major toehold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fleet is very good at doing these types of things, and they're
going to take the best of both institutions,'' said Charles Wendel,
president of Financial Institutions Consulting in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Murray told Fleet shareholders at the annual meeting that the
combined company would have earnings per share growth of 10 percent
a year from 2002, after 6 percent in 2001 and 1 percent next year,
and return on equity _ a measure of profitability _ of 18 to 20
percent from 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the new bank's projected $600 million in cost savings
will come from job cuts of up to 5,000 positions, or 8.3 percent,
of the combined bank's work force. Sixty percent of the savings
will be achieved in 2000, the first year of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Over the first two years, the combined bank will have
incremental earnings, or earnings in excess of what the two banks
would have made separately, of $400 million. That extra capital
could be reinvested or used to buy back stocks or make
acquisitions, Fleet's chief financial officer, Eugene M. McQuade,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray brushed off shareholder questions about Fleet's stock
price, which is down 1.3 percent so far this year despite strong
first-quarter earnings and a booming stock market. Fleet shares
slipped nearly 12 percent after the merger was announced on March
14 but have since rebounded. Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Anthony Inc.
said the decline came from shorting of the stock and worries about
how the two banks would integrate, among other factors. Fleet rose
1/2 to close at 44 15/16 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, McQuade said Fleet was deciding whether to sell
shares in its booming on-line brokerage, Suretrade, to the public.
A decision is to be taken in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   Around 5 percent _ an average rate _ of the combined bank's 8
million household customers are expected to feel inconvenienced
enough by the new merger to switch to a new bank.
</P>
<P>
   Integration planning, according to executives at both banks, is
supposed to be collaborative and help create a unified culture out
of Fleet and BankBoston. The banks expect to close their deal in
the fourth quarter immediately after receiving regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   But while merger integration staffers gathered recently to
attempt to bond over pizza, the two sides are not yet feeling like
one happy family.
</P>
<P>
   Said one Fleet staffer: ``It's too early for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
