<HEADLINE>
BURNS PLAYING CAUTIOUS WITH THORNTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Emphatically, unequivocally, Pat Burns said Joe
Thornton will not play Thursday when the Bruins open up Round 1 of
the playoffs against the Carolina Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   OK, coach, we'll see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I've been down this road before,'' Burns harrumphed,
once informed that his star pupil, the gangly and talented
second-year center, said he was feeling pretty good after
Wednesday's workout and thought he probably (itals)could(unitals)
suit up tonight. ``Too many times. I've seen it . . . heard it. Too
many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Players. Their heart can be in the right place, their head in
the clouds well-intentioned self-deception. Thornton has been
nursing a strained something-or-other in his chest since the
weekend, and Wednesday, once more, Jumbo Joe didn't practice with
the rest of the black-and-gold gang.
</P>
<P>
   In Thornton's spot, smack dab between Dmitri Khristich and
Sergei Samsonov, Burns had Randy Robitaille playing the pivot.
Thornton, following a lengthy physical therapy session (he's been
having two-a-days on the table) in the trainer's room, skated
briefly on his own.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:06 p.m., the lights turned low inside the Ristuccia rink
in suburban Wilmington, Thornton planted feet and hands on the ice,
near the door that leads to the club's dressing room, and snapped
off an impressive round of pushups. He didn't wince. He popped back
up on his feet, smiled the ever-present Thornton smile and clomped
off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels unbelievable, a big improvement, really,'' said
Thornton, the former No. 1 draft pick who is the key factor in the
Bruins holding together a two-line offensive attack. ``It felt
good, shooting. I wound up and it felt good. You know, I think I
might be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Only some 30 minutes before, Burns declared Thornton a scratch.
He went on to say that Thornton could be back for Game 2 Saturday
or Game 3 Monday at the Vault. By missing Thursday, said the coach,
Thornton would have three days of rest leading up to Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get (Keith) Primeau in your face,'' said Burns, referring
to the Canes' behemoth center and the physical toll he can exact,
``it's a different game.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton will be back on the ice Thursday morning when the
Bruins go through the paces of their pregame skate in Greensboro,
N.C. Chances are, he'll feel even better than Wednesday, making
chances even better that he'll tell Burns that all systems, sternum
and all, are ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put me in coach,'' he'll say. ``I'm ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   And then it will be up to Burns to decide between head and
clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants you to be 95 percent (ready) rather than 80
percent,'' said Thornton, figuring how a bargaining session with
Burns might play out. ``I think I'm, oh, 85 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten percentage points and the deal gets closed. If Burns were
working the floor of a car dealership, he'd drop his pen on the
desk, gently rake his fingers through his hair, and tell Thornton
to stay seated while he consulted with his sales manager. He'd
wander off to a desk in the corner, strum his fingers across the
boss's three-ring binders, and come back with an offer so good it
would jeopardize the future of the dealership.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns is too wise, too savvy for these negotiations. An
ex-cop, he prides himself on an innate ability to outthink the
other guy, be he street thug, opposing coach, or millionaire kid
with a realistic dream of superstardom. He likes Thornton, and he
is smart enough to know that ultimately there could be a very high
reward for being one part foster father, one part demanding coach.
</P>
<P>
   Burns would love to be able to put Thornton in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's how that goes,'' said Burns, as if reciting from some
TV movie he's seen a thousand times. ``The player's hurt and he
tells you he can play, `Oh, I'm OK coach . . . please, please let
me play.' He gets out there and, boom, first shift he gets hurt
again and he's all done. Then what do you do? You dressed him, now
he can't play, and you're behind the bench with one finger up your
nose and the other one . . .''
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't stand the suspense, the other finger goes in
a place it also doesn't belong. If the coach feels Thornton doesn't
belong in a sweater, he'll point him in the direction of the press
box. From there, maybe Robitaille will get his chance to light it
up in the big time, or perhaps Burns will wring more out of fewer
forwards, double shift Jason Allison, ask Khristich to work the
slot.
</P>
<P>
   This much clearly changed over the course of 30 minutes
Wednesday, prior to the Bruins breaking camp here and heading to
Hanscom Field in Bedford to catch that charter flight: Burns's
emphatic, unequivocal decision to give Thornton the night off had
been tempered ever-so-slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, first game of a series,'' said Burns, working the equation
of risk and reward in his head. ``Maybe if it's Game 5, 6, 7 . . .
he's in there for sure if it's that kinda game.''
</P>
<P>
   From deep in Burns's thought process, you almost could here the
plea: ``Oh, I'm OK coach. . . . please, please let me play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Burns. ``We'll see how it is after the
morning skate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
