<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXISTENZ-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWEAKING THE GAMES THAT PEOPLE PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Friday, April 23 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; David Cronenberg's latest ickfest, ``eXistenZ,''
is probably his most erotic movie. There isn't really much sex in
it, but if virtual reality games are your thing, it's a nonstop
orgy.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, after failing to convince us that auto wrecks were sexy
in his last film, ``Crash,'' anything the brilliant but, um,
uniquely fixated director tries to do is bound to seem sensual by
comparison. Even when it inevitably turns your stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The film is set in a near-future when interactive games can be
plugged directly into people's central nervous systems and played
in a kind of hyper-realistic dream state. It revels in such
fun-sounding biotech diversions as surgical body penetrations,
MetaFlesh game-pods and the cool-to-say, ooky-to-see umbycords that
connect the other items together.
</P>
<P>
   There are also gristle guns made out of human flotsam, mutated
creatures that provide assembly line parts for those game-pods, and
yucky, venereal-like diseases that the pink, fondle-ready little
playthings can catch.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still reading, this movie is probably for you.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``eXistenZ'' (pronounced like the first three
syllables of existential, which it kind of, sort of is) registers
on the benign end of the Cronenberg gross-out scale. There are no
exploding heads (``Scanners''), no giant talking bugs (``The Fly,''
``Naked Lunch''), and the bioport spinal jacks that people plug
their umbycords _ love that word! _ into are not nearly as
nauseating as the gut cassette slits in ``Videodrome,'' the
Cronenberg film ``eXistenZ'' most resembles.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Jason Leigh plays Allegra Geller, a brilliant virtual
game designer who is attacked _ with a gristle gun, of course _
during the first public demonstration of her new masterpiece, also
called eXistenZ. It seems the Realist Underground considers her the
antichrist, responsible for seducing millions into the vivid but
imaginary worlds of her games, and they've offered a fortune for
her assassination (Cronenberg has said that the film's story, the
first original he's written since the 1983 ``Videodrome,'' was
inspired by the Salman Rushdie situation).
</P>
<P>
   Geller escapes into the countryside with an inexperienced
bodyguard, Ted Pikul (English actor Jude Law), and her wounded
master game pod. After an unnerving encounter with a grubby
mechanic/bioport installer (Willem Dafoe in high creep mode), she
and Pikul go into the game in search of permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, every aspect of their reality is called into
question. But then, where did that two-headed mutant amphibian they
encountered while on the lam come from?
</P>
<P>
   The game's virtual world boasts geek-filled electronics stores
and the ultimate disgusting Chinese restaurant. But except for a
few surreal details, it all looks like rural Canada. Oftentimes,
``eXistenZ'' comes off like ``The Matrix'' without the budget; its
what-is-reality? mind games are showcased in a way that emphasizes
their intellectual underpinnings rather than their potential for
action-adventure spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that the more philosophical ``eXistenZ''
is all that smarter than ``The Matrix.'' It sometimes hits on
brilliant ideas _ I especially liked the bits when Geller and
Pikul, not fully in control of their game-world behavior, felt like
actors trapped in a movie they knew was bad.
</P>
<P>
   But there are pat notions aplenty here as well. Although modern
computer technology has refreshened the concept of
worlds-within-worlds-of-illusion for the movies, it's a decades-old
standby in science fiction literature, and sharp new insights on
the subject are hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its weaknesses and transgressions, though, ``eXistenZ''
can be pleasurable in a weird, sometimes mystifying way, which is
more than can be said for most recent Cronenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Must be the umbycord. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
