<HEADER>
A7987 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-GOTHIC-COX     04-21 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-GOTHIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teens' fascination with dark culture could be a sign of trouble
 &HT;    Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ The two Columbine High School students
who went on a bloody rampage Tuesday in Littleton were typical of
many high school students around the state, said Grand Valley youth
pastors.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Trench Coat Mafia,'' as the Littleton students dubbed
themselves, were like many teens on the cusp of adulthood who turn,
for various reasons, to rebellious, dark-themed music, dark
clothing and a dark view of the world.
</P>
<P>
   They tend, said Wayne Hanson, youth pastor at Fellowship Church,
to be intelligent and in search of direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Littleton is pretty much the epitome of where these kids are
coming from,'' Hanson said, with families that have plenty of
disposable income. And because because both parents work in many
cases, the children have a great deal of free time. ``They don't
want to be labeled as nerds, but we're talking the same kids, only
they've gravitated to a darker side to find strength in each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock singer Marilyn Manson and the band Nine Inch Nails are
favorites, but so are German philosophers Friedrich Wilhelm
Nietzsche and Martin Hiedegger, he said. And, he said, ``They love
to quote the Bible passage, 'Judge not lest ye be judged.' That
gives them a whole lot of freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Goths, as they are called, are given to shocking dress and
music, he said, because it gives them attention that they don't get
any other way, ``and they don't care if it's good or bad
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Such worries about Goths are a ``big generalization,'' said
another youth pastor, Matt Rissell of New Life Church, and Brian
Roush of First Assembly of God Church agreed. ``Kids who do the
Goth thing aren't necessarily destructive,'' Roush said. ``Just
because they dress that way doesn't necessarily mean they're
destructive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have quite a few Goths groups and they dress with the whole
Marilyn Manson look of black lipstick, black fingernail polish.
Some of these kids are great kids and this is just their way of
finding out who they are, '' he said. ``Some, though, use it to
mask any issues they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Other students also have problems, sometimes just as disturbing
as the images the Goths seek to present, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of angry kids out there,'' he said. ``Some are
kids you'd think would never be angry. There are several kids out
there who are just as much as a threat as those two kids were in
Littleton.''
</P>
<P>
   Rissell estimated that each high school campus has three or so
groups of Goths with five to seven members each.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McGill, youth pastor at St. Joseph's Catholic Church, said
Goths are as much a product of teen cliquishness as of their
problems and fears. ``I think a lot of these kids get into this
stuff without realizing what they're getting into''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
