<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-HARRIS22-COX     04-21 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-HARRIS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Tormented' teens outwardly nonthreatening
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel and Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Teen-agers Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold twirled dough
and cooked for Blackjack Pizza in Littleton, Colo. They sometimes
arrived together in Klebold's black BMW.
</P>
<P>
   ``As employees, they were good to excellent,'' said Chris Lau,
who bought the Littleton pizza delivery outlet six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The two high school seniors already were on the payroll. They
last worked Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Their boss, neighbors and classmates at Columbine High School
said there was little warning about the carnage Harris and Klebold
would deliver four days later.
</P>
<P>
   There was no hint that the two members of the so-called ``Trench
Coat Mafia'' _ a gang of downtrodden high school outcasts _ would
turn into a killing machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Lau said in a telephone interview. ``I had
no familiarity with that group at all. They were normal high school
kids, had the normal high school camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Columbine High School students said Harris and
Klebold wielded firearms and explosives in a rampage that killed at
least 15 people at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officials said it was a suicide mission: The bodies of
Harris and Klebold were among 12 found in or near the school
library, the bloodiest and most gruesome site on Columbine's
sprawling campus.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged killers died of self-inflicted gunshots, the sheriff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' father _ who did not return repeated telephone calls
Wednesday _ is a retired military man, according to neighbors and
news accounts.
</P>
<P>
   As late as December 1991, Wayne N. Harris received mail at
Wurtsmith Air Force Base in Michigan _ which served as headquarters
for a B-52 squadron that carried nuclear weapons before it was
closed in 1993 _ according to a review of public and private
records.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, the family said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to express our heartfelt sympathy to the families of
all the victims and to all the community for this senseless
tragedy. Please say prayers by everyone touched by these terrible
events. The Harris family is devastated by the deaths of the
Columbine High students and is mourning the death of their youngest
son, Eric.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cul-de-sac neighborhood off South Reed Street in
Littleton, there are 10 houses, most two-stories tall and worth
$100,000 to $200,000. Neighbor Brent Wilde, 47, said the Harrises
moved into their gray-blue house with a brick front about two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   From what Wilde could tell, Eric Harris wasn't a troublemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a lot of noise,'' said Wilde, a financial
planner. ``He was a serious-looking kid. I never saw him smiling.
Last weekend was the last time I saw him. He looked just like the
kid next door.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilde said he noticed that one of Eric's friends came by in an
older-model, flat-black BMW. Wilde said Harris was ``tall and
slender,'' about 6-feet but no more than 160 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a normal-looking kid,'' Wilde said. ``He had short
hair. There was nothing unusual about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Classmates said Harris came to school in steel-toed combat boots
and wore a German cross.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' America Online Web site included instructions for making
pipebombs, The Associated Press reported. While the information
can't be verified as authored by Harris, any information considered
relevant to the investigation was copied for the FBI, AOL
spokeswoman Kim McCreery said.
</P>
<P>
   As a Cub Scout, Klebold worked hard for his badges.
</P>
<P>
   He rooted for the Boston Red Sox. He was quiet and smart,
friends said. But he changed around Harris, whom he met four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Baumgart, 17, a senior who met Klebold in grade school,
said, ``Dylan was a follower who was constantly looking for someone
to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers linked their home computers and played video
games, including ``Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had death matches with violent computer games, matching
computer to computer,'' Baumgart said. ``I don't believe violent
video games lead to violence, but this was different. They'd play
these games for hours and hours and hours.''
</P>
<P>
   John House, 17, a senior, said he refused to associate with
Klebold after he joined the Trench Coat Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went bowling with him, and when he would do something good,
he would shout `Heil Hitler' and throw up his hand,'' House said.
``It just made everyone mad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trench Coats are fans of Adolph Hitler, speak German to each
other and listen to German techno music, the Denver Rocky Mountain
News reported. Tuesday's massacre took place on Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The group was no secret. They posed for a yearbook portrait.
They had a running feud with the school's athletes. Carrying swords
and brassknukcles, the Trench Coats showed up for a fight with some
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The showdown never happened because the Trench Coats went to the
wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were capable of violence, but I just didn't know
they would do it,'' Columbine junior Pauline Colby told the Rocky
Mountain News. ``They were just very angry, but they didn't know
how to release their anger. They were angry about people not
accepting them and no one knowing how smart they were.''
</P>
<P>
   The only previous run-in with the law for Harris and Klebold was
a 1998 criminal trespass case in which they attempted to break into
a car intending to steal its contents, according to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shrader, a lieutenant with the Jefferson County Sheriff's
Department, said the Trench Coat Mafia is limited to Columbine High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we've heard the term,'' Shrader said.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home Wednesday, senior Julie Duran said Harris and
Klebold were constantly made fun of at school _ to their faces and
behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids were tormented throughout their high school
years,'' Duran said. ``That's one of the problems at Columbine.
It's easy to make fun of people who are different.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
