<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE ME OUT TO THE LIBRARY FOR A BASEBALL BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHY FRISINGER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All right, so the Rangers are off to a shaky start.
</P>
<P>
   But the weather is breezy and warm, daylight lingers into the
evenings, and it's hard for a sports-minded child not to be excited
about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, children can't play baseball all the time. They have
to leave some time for watching baseball _ and some time for
reading about baseball. Here's a lineup of baseball books that
should score well with young sluggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball Bob,'' by William Joyce (HarperFestival, $6.95). This
board book for toddlers mixes baseball with another kid favorite,
dinosaurs, in a somewhat strange little story. The book concludes
with a song, The Ballad of Dinosaur Bob. ``He's Mesozoic and
heroic, and he's really green.'' Best for toddlers who like to
think out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leagues Apart, The Men and Times of the Negro Baseball
Leagues,'' by Lawrence S. Ritter, illustrations by Richard Merkin
(Mulberry Books, $5.95). This excellent book begins with a
discussion of two of the greatest Major Leaguers of all time, Hank
Aaron and Willie Mays. Many fans don't know the two began their
careers in the Negro Leagues. From there, the book segues into bios
of greats such as Satchel Paige, Josh Gibson, Bullet Joe and, of
course, Jackie Robinson. Best for age 8 and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Striking Out,'' by Will Weaver (HarperTrophy, $4.95). Billy
Baggs is 13 years old, but he doesn't have a very childlike life.
Poverty and the memories of a terrible accident five years earlier
make for a rather joyless family. But change is on the horizon _ in
the form of baseball. An ALA Best Book for Young Adults. Best for
age 11-teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farm Team,'' by Will Weaver (HarperTrophy, $4.95). The story
of Billy Baggs continues. When Billy's father lands in jail, the
responsibility for running the farm lands on Billy's shoulders _
which doesn't leave time for baseball. But then Billy's mother
comes up with a way for Billy to continue to play the game he
loves. An ALA Best Book for Young Adults. Best for age 11-teens.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
