<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELTER HELPS MOMS, GIVES BABIES A GOOD START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Summer is when the faces at the Arlington
Night Shelter always change.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do they become predominantly female, most of them are
young mothers with small children. And more and more of them are
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The shelter is the last place they thought they'd end up, but
the only place they can go to escape the poverty and violence that
characterize their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still think that all we do is serve winos on the back
porch,'' said Beverly Wright, coordinator of Each Baby Counts, a
program that the shelter has launched to help lower the infant
mortality rate among these women. ``There are about 2,000 homeless
people in Arlington. Of those, 75 percent are moms and kids.''
</P>
<P>
   On this morning, the shelter is quiet. Those who spent the night
have gone on to God knows where. But as sure as the sun goes down,
they will be back, and, come summer, their numbers will swell. They
always do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lull now, but as it starts to warm up and school is
out, the numbers will increase,'' Wright said. ``We'll be full of
young mothers and pregnant women who have not had prenatal care.''
</P>
<P>
   It has happened this way for years, she said. As temperatures
rise, tempers begin to flare, and the women have no other choice
but to leave. For years, the only things the shelter could offer
were empathy or, in some cases, a referral to another agency.
</P>
<P>
   This summer promises to be different.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a $40,000 grant from the March of Dimes, the shelter
can provide an estimated 25 women with prenatal counseling, a
registered nurse, well-birth and parenting classes, and badly
needed life skills.
</P>
<P>
   Under Each Baby Counts, women will receive help for nine weeks.
After that, two case managers will monitor them and their babies'
progress for up to one year.
</P>
<P>
   Each Baby Counts, not unlike the Birthing Project, aims to help
lower the infant mortality rate, which according to preliminary
1997 statistics from the national Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention is 7.1 infant deaths per 1,000 births. But the black
infant mortality rate is almost double that, at 13.7.
</P>
<P>
   At the night shelter, the majority of clients are white. Half of
them, Wright said, either don't know who the father is or expect a
biracial child. Their babies will generally have chronic health
problems because of low birth weight and a lack of prenatal care.
</P>
<P>
   This is why I'd been invited to talk with Wright. The Birthing
Project was established in 1989, primarily to help African-American
women before their babies were born and ultimately to lower the
mortality rate among this population. Today, it serves women of all
ages and ethnicities And has some 50 chapters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   I started the Fort Worth chapter in 1998, and since then we have
helped shepherd nearly 20 infants safely into this world. The
chapter is run by volunteers, called ``Sister-Friends,'' who help
young women through the last four months of their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   We offer moral and other support, making sure that they get
proper prenatal care and parenting classes through the first year
of their babies' lives.
</P>
<P>
   The women who have sought our help range from 14 to 23 years of
age. They are single and usually have been in broken relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said that with Each Baby Counts in place, the Arlington
Night Shelter hopes ``to make sure the babies are born healthy and
stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the Birthing Project's goal also. We do it 10 babies at
a time, but we need your help. If you'd like to be a big sister to
someone, call me or a coordinator in your area.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is coming. That's a promise. But it doesn't have to be
like summers past. Let's work to change things.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
