<SLUG> BC-FINGERBOARDS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Teen boys are flipping for fingerboards 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Alex Collins is eager to demonstrate his dexterity
on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is called a pop shove-it, where it goes like this,''
explains the regular at Eisenbergs Skatepark in Plano, Texas, a
haven for skate boarders and in-line skaters. ``And you can grind
like this, which means you slide on, like, metal rails. And you can
do a back flip like this ...''
</P>
<P>
   Alex's mom, Bobbie, stands by smiling while Alex performs the
daring skateboard maneuvers _ on a glass counter top at Eisenbergs,
no less.
</P>
<P>
   A risky stunt? Not when the skateboard is 3 inches long and Alex
is riding it with his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Fingerboards are it, dude. Among the 10- to 14-year-old set _
mostly boys _ the miniskateboards have begun to generate a buzz
comparable with the Pog craze of several years back.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Escondido, Calif.-based X-Concepts mailed its first
shipment of Tech Decks mainly to regional toy, hobby and clothing
retailers in the West. One sporting-goods store in California sold
4,000 in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cool,'' Bobbie Collins says. ``You're actually
skateboarding with your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Miniboards have been around for more than a decade, but
X-Concepts is apparently the first to use designs from actual
high-end skateboards, company co-owner Tom Davidson says. ``We made
it real, and we made it cool by putting the (licensed) graphics on
it,'' Davidson says.
</P>
<P>
   The company has rights for the designs on 15 brands of boards
used by pros such as Ethan Fowler, Enrique Lorenzo and soon Tony
Hawk, whom Davidson describes as ``the Michael Jackson of
skateboarding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tech Decks ($8.99 at Eisenbergs) are wood boards with tiny
working parts, unlike the all-plastic models that have been out for
a while. They come with extra wheels and tools to remove teeny
screws and bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Plus Tech Decks are covered with the same kind of fine-grain
sandpaper _ called grip tape, for you old fogeys _ that lets
boarders ``grind,'' ``ollie'' and ``quarter pipe'' over concrete
surfaces everywhere. Grip tape gives the skateboards a nailfilelike
surface that grips the boarder's shoes _ or in this case,
fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   It's waaay harder than it looks. Try, for instance, landing a
180-kick flip, which 16-year-old Ryan Dawes recently mastered in
less than an hour: Place an index finger on the center edge of the
board and middle finger on the back end and press down, forcing the
board to rotate in the air and change direction.
</P>
<P>
   Even Davidson can't pull that off. ``I can make it jump from my
desk top up to a folder, like I'm going up a curb,'' he says, ``but
I'm 52 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson's partner, Peter Asher, brought the idea to X-Concepts
via his son, Steven. Last year, the 12-year-old and his friends
started making fingerboards out of cardboard. They copied graphics
out of skateboard magazines and drew them on their imitation
boards. A light bulb blinked on in Peter Asher's head.
</P>
<P>
   X-Concepts has sold more than 2 million Tech Decks in five
months. Mall stores such as Gadzooks and Fast Forward sell the
line, which includes 208 board designs. New and improved
fingerboards are due out this summer, Davidson says, along with
accessories such as an entire miniature Tony Hawk skate park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sixth-graders had them at school this fall, and they
wouldn't tell any of the fourth-graders where they got them,''
Bobbie Collins says. ``And it was a big mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenbergs has its Tech Decks in a glass display case next to
the miniskateboard key chains. The skatepark has sold out of the
ramps, but Alex, a Dallas fourth-grader, is undeterred. Balancing
on his in-line skates, he continues to demonstrate his fingerboard
mastery.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an ollie,'' he says after rolling the Tech Deck eight
inches into the air and back down without his fingers ever leaving
the grip tape.
</P>
<P>
   Alex plays with his fingerboards for hours while watching TV or
goofing with his cats, his mom says. His typical route takes him
through the game room and into his bedroom next door.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my house, I have a couple of ramps I built out of paper,''
Alex says, ``and then I get on, uh, kind of a pool table and I
ollie and then I jump maybe 10 feet and then I slide sideways on my
door and then I come down on my bed about five feet away.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jeremy Blakemore, ``real'' skateboarders aren't all
that into fingerboards; the toys are for wannabes, says the
18-year-old manager at Eisenbergs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're mad because they can't really skateboard,'' Blakemore
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that ain't it,'' insists 12-year-old in-line skater Robert
Hood, who admits skateboarding ``is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' Blakemore adds. ``See. You can't do it with your
feet, so you do it with your fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
