<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-DUMPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OILMAN CHARGES FOREIGN PRODUCERS DUMPING CRUDE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Crude prices had already dropped to desperately low
levels. But the talk in Oklahoma was that prices in the oil fields
might fall even further, to a staggering $6 or even $5 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   At those prices, reasoned Harold Hamm, an independent oilman
from Enid, Okla., even the oil-rich OPEC producers couldn't cover
their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with the depressed prices, foreign crude was flooding
into the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Certain the low prices were all part of a foreign scheme to
drive American producers out of business, Hamm _ inspired by the
success of U.S. steel producers _ launched an effort to file a
federal dumping complaint against four of the world's largest oil
producers, Venezuela, Mexico, Kuwait and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to get this market,'' contends Hamm, president of
Continental Resources. ``We're already down to nothing, and they
want that too?''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm's grass roots campaign is highly unusual and probably
quixotic.
</P>
<P>
   No official interviewed could recall a dumping complaint
involving crude. At least one target _ Venezuela _ has officially
denied the charge, while some of the major oil companies are
vehemently opposed to the measure.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the dumping complaint could push up the price of
imported oil by something approaching 45 percent, not a
particularly popular prospect in much of auto-adoring America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much of a win it would be for the American
public if a substantial amount of the oil imported into this
country would cost several dollars more,'' said one Energy
Department source, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Oil Patch, Hamm's movement has spread like a brush
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Some 22 state and regional trade organizations have voiced
support for the dumping complaint, including the Texas Independent
Producers &AMP; Royalty Owners Association, which signed off on the
proposal late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based Independent Petroleum Association of
America's board of governors is expected to vote on the measure
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters include Raymond Plank, head of one of the nation's
largest independent producers, Houston-based Apache Corp., and
Denise Bode, former head of the Independent Petroleum Association
and now a member of the Oklahoma Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela is the nation's largest foreign supplier of petroleum
products. And together, the four target producers account for more
than a third of the oil imported to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   To back up his claims, Hamm points to a Dec. 3, 1997, report
from Caracas in the trade publication Oil Daily.
</P>
<P>
   The story said officials at Venezuela's state-owned oil company
_ Petroleos de Venezuela _ were advocating a strategy to bring down
oil prices in a bid to gain some market share. That strategy
``would result in some marginal production being shut in and force
some high-cost producers, particularly in the United States, out of
business,'' the story said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm believes Venezuela hoped to push oil prices down a couple
of dollars by overproducing but overshot and helped send prices in
a free fall.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent visit to Washington, Venezuelan oil minister Ali
Rodiguez called the allegations ``absurd and untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Perera, deputy chief of the Venezuelan embassy assured
Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., in a recent letter: ``Be assured that
there is no such strategy. ... Far from benefiting Venezuela, low
oil prices have only wreaked havoc with Venezuela's overall
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela, Perera wrote, ``has more in common with independent
and small producers of oil in the United States than differences.
Our primary goal is maintaining world prices at sufficient levels
to permit appropriate returns for producers in the United States as
well as Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers declined to say why the other nations were
targeted for the dumping action.
</P>
<P>
   Independent producers have been vocal about their opposition to
the United Nations-supervised oil-for-food program for Iraq, which
permits Baghdad to export about $5.2 billion worth of crude every
six months, much of it coming to the United States. They have
lobbied _ so far unsuccessfully _ to persuade the Clinton
administration to try to block the program.
</P>
<P>
   If the dumping action were successful, many large oil companies,
which purchase crude directly from the four producing nations,
could be forced to pay substantially higher prices. The American
Petroleum Institute, the Washington-based trade organization for
Big Oil, has remained neutral on the issue, but some companies are
not hesitating to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Conoco, in a written statement, said it does not
support ``the efforts of any coalition making allegations that
producing countries have dumped oil in the U.S. market,'' noting
``the cost to produce any given barrel of oil may vary widely
within a given country and is almost never known with complete
certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevron Corp., meanwhile, notified the Independent Petroleum
Association that it would not support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also has caused much friction among the members of the
Independent Petroleum Association. George Yates of Roswell, N.M.,
head of the trade group, came under bitter fire from Hamm and other
independents for agreeing to travel to Venezuela. (Yates' trip,
scheduled for this week, was canceled because of the death of
Yates' father).
</P>
<P>
   If all proceeds as planned, Hamm and his allies will file their
dumping complaint with the U.S. Commerce Department and the federal
International Trade Commission within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators will then look back at market conditions in the past
year, when oil prices were at their lowest. But the fact that oil
prices have risen substantially since that time and are now at far
more comfortable levels _ crude futures for June delivery closed at
$17.92 on the New York Mercantile Exchange Wednesday _ could well
affect any kind of ruling, trade experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department will decide whether the alleged dumping
actually occurred, while the International Trade Commission will
determine if at least 25 percent of the domestic industry was
harmed or faced the threat of damage as a result of the alleged
dumping.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
