<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-TIMOR-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL FACTIONS IN THE VIOLENCE IN EAST TIMOR SIGN A PEACE ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ The warring factions in the former Portuguese
colony of East Timor took a tentative step toward reconciliation
Wednesday with the signing of a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The six-point agreement, signed in the lush tropical garden at
the residence of the Nobel Peace laureate Bishop Carlos Belo,
commits the militias supporting the Indonesian government and the
separatists to ``stop violence, killing, intimidation and terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia annexed East Timor in 1976 and the province has been
plagued with violence ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of the Indonesian armed forces, Gen. Wiranto, an
architect of the accord, warned the signers that the document would
be useless unless it is backed up by deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a signed document,'' he said. ``It has no meaning
at all if people don't stick to it. This problem is bigger than
just East Timor and Indonesia; it is an international issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had asked the armed forces and the police ``to stop
the violence, to be neutral and treat everyone without
discrimination.'' The Indonesian military has been accused of
fomenting militia violence against the separatists.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's best known independence leader, Xanana Gusmao, who
is under house arrest in Jakarta, signed the accord earlier
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another signer for the pro-independence faction, Leandro Isaac,
said: ``Peace is dependent on both sides. If both sides keep their
word there will be peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Basilio Araujo, a spokesman for the groups that want East Timor
to remain part of Indonesia, said that while the agreement did not
specifically mention disarmament, it was implied. ``Once we've
agreed to sign the document, from that day on we won't be able to
carry guns,'' he said. ``The main context of the document is to
stop the violence. The implication is the laying down of weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the deal is important. Prime Minister John Howard
of Australia is to hold talks on Tuesday with President B.J.
Habibie on the future of East Timor. Ana Gomes, the senior
Portuguese diplomat in Jakarta, is to visit Dili this week, and an
announcement on a U.N. proposal for the territory is expected this
week.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 27, Habibie surprised the international community by
reversing Indonesia's policy with an offer of self-determination
for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   A provincial referendum supervised by the United Nations,
scheduled for July, has been thrown in doubt by rising violence. If
voters reject the offer of wide-ranging autonomy, Habibie says,
East Timor could be given independence, subject to approval by
Indonesia's parliament.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last weekend 2,000 supporters of East Timor autonomy within
Indonesia, armed with assault rifles, muskets, bows and arrows,
spears and machetes rampaged through Dili, the provincial capital,
attacking homes and offices of known and suspected supporters of
independence. The toll is unlikely to be known, though accounts of
up to 30 people killed are regarded as credible.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing persecution, scores of people have fled into the
mountains, a common refuge since the days of the Indonesian
military invasion in 1975. The violence has driven many
independence supporters and their leaders underground.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, the streets of Dili's commercial area, normally
bustling with shoppers, remained quiet, with many shops still
shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   The peace agreement may have been signed but confidence about
its success remains elusive. Reports from outside the capital
indicate that pro-Indonesian militias are still manning road
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Belo's fenced compound, which was ringed by military
police, a handful of ordinary East Timorese watched the signing
ceremony with mixed feelings, tinged with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the problem in Yugoslavia,'' said one woman. ``The
same thing is happening in East Timor. Goodness! I can't believe
what has been happening here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
