<HEADER>
A8006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROUGHT-ART-500&AMP;ADD-N     04-21 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT CUTS INTO LIVESTOCK IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ariz., Fla., Neb.)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ On the J.E. White &AMP; Sons Brite Ranch in far West
Texas, the breeding stock is typically considered sacred, their
future secure long after other parts of the herd have been sent to
market.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, another plagued by drought, is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cut into our young productive cows because there is nothing
for them to eat,'' said Kathleen Hartnett White, who lives on the
trans-Pecos ranch that has been in her husband's family for 114
years.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Neeb, district director for the Texas Agricultural
Extension Service in far West Texas, estimated that there had been
a 50-to 80-percent reduction of livestock in that region, with some
ranchers liquidating everything.
</P>
<P>
   As many parts of Texas and portions of the southern United
States brace for a second consecutive year of drought, the
situation in the trans-Pecos may be a sign of things to come.
Ranchers there are confronting tough decisions after drought
conditions that have consumed the area for more than six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have borrowed enormous amounts to stay in
business,'' Ms. White said, noting that her family had coped by
relying on savings. ``I don't know whether it's worse to spend
everything you ever saved or to borrow.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are concerns that loans may also dry up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing from bankers that in the year 2000 they might not
be able to continue loans,'' said Susan Combs, the state's
commissioner of agriculture. ``It's too many bad years, too close
together. That is a serious long-term problem for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Combs has predicted that the prolonged drought could drive
some 10 percent of the state's agricultural producers out of
business this year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Ms. Combs established a ``hay hot line'' to connect
people who need to buy hay with those who want to sell it. If the
drought continues, the hot line can also be used to solicit
donations of hay. In addition, Ms. Combs appointed a drought
coordinator to assist farmers and ranchers who need the help of the
Texas Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state has not experienced the fires that Florida
has as a result of the drought, Gov. George W. Bush also declared a
potential wildfire emergency in 167 of the state's 254 counties.
Outdoor burning has been banned in 13 counties.
</P>
<P>
   The drought is being traced to La Nina, a weather system that
operates the opposite of its better-known counterpart, El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   While El Nino is related to warmer-than-normal surface water
temperatures in the Pacific Ocean of South America, La Nina results
when water surface temperatures are colder than normal, said Don
Wilhite, director of the National Drought Mitigation Center at the
University of Nebraska in Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino causes above normal precipitation in the southern United
States and California in the winter and above normal temperatures
in the Pacific Northwest, Wilhite said. La Nina, which has not been
studied as extensively, seems to be more associated with drought.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The center says the drought extends from Arizona east through
Texas and into Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the drought in Texas led to a $2.4 billion drop in
farm and ranch production with $8 billion lost in business that
depends on farming.
</P>
<P>
   As ranchers last year sold off stock to avoid the additional
costs of feeding herds, the average price a pound for cattle
dropped to 59 cents in November 1998 from 65 cents in November
1997.
</P>
<P>
   While the drought was not directly related to a drop in crop
prices that occurred last year, officials said, falling prices did
significantly add to problems farmers already hit by production
losses related to the drought. Corn fell to $2.35 a bushel in 1998
from an average of $2.74 a bushel in 1997 (that was down from $3.19
a bushel in 1996).
</P>
<P>
   With drought-like conditions setting in about three months
earlier than last year, there are some concerns about the impact on
planting. Complicating matters, federal crop disaster money
promised for January _ money that could have been used for buying
seeds _ will not arrive until June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
