<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-WALKER-LADN     04-21 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-WALKER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANCHERS, BIOLOGISTS WORK TO IMPROVE WEST WALKER FISHERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB WHEAT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Calif. _ Cowboy boots and wading shoes. Often they
wind up on either side of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers frequently are at odds with anglers and
conservationists who claim their livestock ruin the land by
damaging plants and streams and, ultimately, deplete fishing
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But Department of Fish and Game fishery biologist Steve
Parmenter offers one success story. He hopes his West Water River
project will be a national model for how cattlemen and ecologists
can put their differences aside and work together toward a common
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's news to see cowboys and fishery biologists working
together,'' said Parmenter, who specializes in habitat issues that
take years, or even decades to come to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   Under Parmenter's direction, the DFG has hammered out a plan
with local cattlemen to protect a 9-mile section of the West Walker
River, known for the rainbow, brown and, more recently, cutthroat
trout that swim in these waters along Highway 108, northwest west
of Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Alternating the areas where cattle graze, replanting lost native
plants and trees along the stream and creating protective fish
screens are among the ways the river has been rejuvenated.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have been done without the ranchers, stressed
Parmenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we had to do was establish trust, that we were
on the same side,'' Parmenter said. ``Once I proved to them that
they could still make the same beef, or possibly more (through
improved land management), it helped a lot. Now it's actually
worked out the best for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although one of the pastures in question has been eliminated
from grazing permanently, seven areas are rotated for the ranchers
to use; each meadow gets a reprieve from cow's hooves two out of
every three years to regrow vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Fish screens were introduced to keep the smaller, juvenile trout
from slipping into offshoot irrigation channels from the main
streambed.
</P>
<P>
   About 4\ miles of new fencing was stretched, some which
connected existing fence sections. Natural barriers keep cattle out
of the water where fencing isn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   Many Southern California anglers from the Federation of
Flyfishers have been have instrumental in replanting Cottonwood
trees and other plants native to the area, which, on maps, appears
as a hodgepodge of private holdings, U.S. Forest Service property
and DFG land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was the stream was widening and becoming more
shallow, with the fish having less room to go deep and grow,''
Parmenter said. ``Now we're starting to intensely study this plan.
For example, if rotating the (grazing) areas really works well,
then we can open up the permanently closed site. If not, then we'll
have to look at other solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Settelmeyer, whose family has been working cattle since
the 1890s and in this Mono County area since 1918, is glad the
ranchers and biologists could reach consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like herding sheep now; (the cattle) stay
together on the rotating pastures,'' Settelmeyer said from his
ranch in Gardnerville, Nev. ``We're only on (each of) those meadows
about 20 to 30 days a year, and there's a lot more awareness of the
willows and growth in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have other ranchers call me and ask all kinds of questions.
They're hesitant for sure, but if we can just get them out there
and show them, it really changes minds.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parmenter also had a bargaining chip _ Pickel Meadow
pasture, rich in vegetation, was one of the five disconnected
parcels of land, totaling 990 acres, that the Wildlife Conservation
Board purchased in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been hard to have cattle up there without Pickel
Meadow; it would have really hurt the ranchers,'' Parmenter said.
``But we wanted to work with them. And, so far, it's been great. It
wasn't an easy thing for them, but Arnold really cares about the
land and you can tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Now management of the next phase of the project turns to fishery
biologist Dawne Becker, who will work with agencies such as the
U.S. Forest Service and the UC Santa Cruz on monitoring and
learning from the land-management experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another important aspect of this project is the educational
one,'' said Becker, who works with Parmenter out of the DFG's
Bishop office. ``Not just what we can learn. I mean we're actually
going out to schools and teaching kids about this plan and why it
works. Are we influencing the ranchers of tomorrow? You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are future obstacles _ cattle trespassers, not enough
manpower to quickly get at fences when they fall into disrepair and
the impacts of years of overgrazing are among the largest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have this picture in mind from the movies where the
cowboys were riding with their cattle all the time,'' Becker said.
``Today they kind of check on them, so, if a fence falls, it's
usually not one cow that gets in but a few.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
IF YOU'RE GOING
</P>
<P>
   To reach Pickel Meadow and the revamped section of the West
Walker River, drive highways 14 and 395 past Bridgeport_ some 350
miles north of the San Fernando Valley _ and turn west onto Highway
108 at Sonora Junction.
</P>
<P>
   The project area is upstream from where the 108 crosses the
river, all of which is open to public fishing; access is where you
can see the river from the road.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow trout are the mainstay residents, planted in the river's
upper reaches; wild trout swim in the faster, boulder-strewn areas
around Sonora Bridge, closer to Highway 395. Browns are available,
too, and Lahontan cutthroats have been stocked the last two years.
Native mountain whitefish can be found in the long, calm pools of
the flat, green meadows.
</P>
<P>
   Five trout can be kept per day, 10 can be in possession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
