A8009 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SHOOTING-SPI &LR;      04-21 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHOOTING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER TRAGEDY IS SEARED INTO MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Reality can be exceedingly brutal, but necessarily so
for those of us who tend to be unmoved by human tragedy. Daily
newspapers deal with death and disaster all too regularly. Taking
an obituary is as routine for us as covering a baseball game. It's
alarmingly easy for journalists to seem insensitive, or at least
somewhat less than compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a news event made me cry was when the space
shuttle Challenger exploded in 1986. I chalked it up to being like
most people who grew up in the Space Age. I'd dreamed of being an
astronaut. I'd even applied for the Journalist in Space program.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, the tears came again as I watched a teenager
describe how she almost died at school. Sobbing non-stop, she
described how a boy pointed a shotgun at her head ``and asked if we
all wanted to die.'' She said she screamed and begged him to spare
her life. He did. Instead, he shot a girl and a boy who were next
to her.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt if the horror of that event will ever leave her. Heck,
I'm more than a thousand miles away and I know the image will never
leave me. Just as that crazy white cloud in the brilliant sky above
Florida is forever imprinted in my mind, that girl's face _ the
hysterical eyes, the trembling lips _ will be with me for a very
long time.
</P>
<P>
   It speaks to the immediate power of television. And to its
greatest weakness.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of a few hours Tuesday, that interview with the
horrified girl was played repeatedly because, quite simply, it was
one of the best visual images available as networks and local
affiliates scrambled to make sense of the gruesome news unfolding
at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But as we've all learned in these situations, precious few
details surface in the minutes immediately after the event. So a
handful of images are repeated again and again, to desensitizing
effect, because this is the time when wall-to-wall coverage is
considered virtually essential. Never mind that a common by-product
of such saturation is speculation, hearsay, rumor and bad judgment.
(At least one anchor in Seattle reported that authorities had
``confirmed'' 25 people were killed in the Littleton bloodbath,
even though it was widely reported that the number was an
estimate.)
</P>
<P>
   The obsession with being first rather than right is what damages
so much TV coverage during big news stories like Littleton. As I
watched coverage of Tuesday's massacre, much of it detached,
breathless and sensational, I thought back 12 years to when I was
running a small-town daily in the Midwest. On a spring day not
unlike Tuesday, an accident killed a railroad worker and it
happened right on our deadline. We pieced together a story for the
next day's paper _ still not knowing the identity of the victim _
and as the edition rolled off the press we found satisfaction in
knowing we'd beaten our competition to the story.
</P>
<P>
   The self-congratulatory reverie ended abruptly when the identity
of the victim became known. He was the father of one of our
co-workers. To say I didn't feel a twinge of guilt about our
``scoop'' would be a lie. Not that we'd gotten anything wrong. The
story was accurate, but I was troubled by the way I'd viewed it
earlier in the day. In newsroom jargon, it was a ``fatal'' on the
tracks outside of town. In reality, it was somebody's dad.
</P>
<P>
   I like to think the heightened awareness I took from that
experience made me a better journalist. But I'm sorry that the
price of my awareness was so dear, and that in the rush to report,
other journalists are still missing the big story.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for a big turnoff?
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, an estimated 12 million people have experimented
with a TV-free lifestyle by taking part in National TV-Turnoff
Week. It's not the sort of thing a TV critic should do if he wants
to keep his job, but as one who spends way too much time in front
of the tube, I can heartily endorse the idea of some time away from
it.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday begins the fifth National TV-Turnoff Week. It is
sponsored by TV-Free America, a non-profit group that thinks too
much TV turns Johnny's brain to tapioca. Some days, I could be the
poster child.
</P>
<P>
   Though the organizers would be delighted if we all took our TVs
to the landfill, they present TV-Turnoff Week as a more moderate
effort to reduce the amount of television-watching in America. The
emphasis goes beyond complaints about programming, focusing instead
on the things that TV-viewing might displace, such as creativity,
productivity, healthy physical activity, civic engagement, thinking
and doing. Some of TVFA's suggestions: Visit the library, listen to
music, plant a garden, go dancing, play the piano, go fishing,
repair a bicycle, invent something.
</P>
<P>
   To get involved, all you have to do is not watch TV between now
and April 28. Or you can consider joining TV-Free America or
becoming a local organizer of TV-Turnoff Week. For details, call
202-887-0436, e-mail tvfa &LR; essential.org, or write TV-Free America,
1611 Connecticut Ave. NW, Suite 3A, Washington, DC 20009.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping a civil tongue
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to Monday's column about coarse language on prime-time
network shows was swift, overwhelming and delightfully civil. The
consensus is summed up in this e-mail from a reader in Olalla,
Wash.: ``You'd think TV producers would catch on to the fact that
one reason people don't watch programs is because of degrading and
uncivil language. Not only is it coarse, it's boring and shows a
lack of enough brains to produce an interesting vocabulary. Also,
it's their no-brainer substitute for good plots.''
</P>
<P>
   Many readers asked for network addresses so they could vent _
politely, of course. The networks don't make it easy for viewers to
send e-mail, but some of their Web sites offer opportunities to
direct electronic correspondence to specific programs. None offers
an easy mail drop for general correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the corporate mailing addresses and Web sites of the
six broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   American Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
   77 W. 66th St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, NY 10023
</P>
<P>
   www.abc.com
</P>
<P>
   CBS Television
</P>
<P>
   51 W. 52nd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, NY 10019
</P>
<P>
   www.cbs.com
</P>
<P>
   Fox Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 900
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Hills, CA 90213
</P>
<P>
   www.fox.com
</P>
<P>
   National Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
   30 Rockefeller Plaza
</P>
<P>
   New York, NY 10112
</P>
<P>
   www.nbc.com
</P>
<P>
   United Paramount Network
</P>
<P>
   11800 Wilshire Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, CA 90025
</P>
<P>
   www.upn.com
</P>
<P>
   The WB Television Network
</P>
<P>
   4000 Warner Blvd., Bldg. 34-R
</P>
<P>
   Burbank, CA 91522
</P>
<P>
   www.thewb.com
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything. On Monday, MTV said ``Warning Signs,'' the
first in a series of programs about violence and its effect on
young people, would air on April 27 at 10 p.m. On Tuesday, after
the shootings in Littleton, Colo., MTV moved the premiere to
Thursday night.... Robert Guillaume, who suffered a stroke in
January, returns to ABC's ``Sports Night'' for the season finale
May 4. During Guillaume's absence, art has paralleled life on the
series, with Guillaume's character, Isaac Jaffee, also laid up by a
stroke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
