<HEADER>
A8011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-LEDE-COX     04-21 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-LEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials begin removing bodies from Columbine High School
 &HT;    By Chris Barker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Authorities on Wednesday afternoon began the
grim task of removing the bodies of 15 people killed at Columbine
High School, as details about the shooting and police rescue of
students emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Students Dylan Klebold, 17, and Eric Harris, 18, who authorities
believe carried out the carnage Tuesday before killing themselves
inside the suburban Denver school, may have had help, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure two could carry all those explosives in,'' said
Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone. Officials said the arsenal
used to kill 12 students and one teacher included:
</P>
<P>
   _ 30 bombs, some equipped with timing devices. The cache, found
throughout the school, was made up of two types of pipe bombs and
several homemade bombs constructed from propane gas cylinders.
Nails were used for shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   _ One 9 mm ``assault-weapon style'' semiautomatic rifle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two pistol grip shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   _ One handgun.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least 100 rounds of ammunition stored in spare clips.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the victims are still being withheld,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   First Judicial District Attorney David Thomas said he would
``pursue vigorously'' the possibility that others may have been
involved in planning the attack or at least have known it was going
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The attack began about 11:30 a.m. Tuesday, minutes after a bomb
exploded in a field about one and a half miles from Columbine,
officials said. That blast was likely meant to be a diversion for
the school attack, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire was reported inside the school until about12:30 p.m., as
nearly 2,000 students rushed to escape the melee, said Steve Davis,
spokesman for the Jefferson County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Three Jefferson County deputies, including one based inside the
school, returned fire, providing cover for fire vehicles and an
armored car to help usher injured teens to safety, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A ``makeshift SWAT team'' was inside the building within 20
minutes of the first report of shots fired, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   A surreal scene unfolded as officers walked through the halls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were kids hopping out from under desks and from out of
broom closets,'' said Sgt. George Hinkle of the Lakewood Police
Department's SWAT team.
</P>
<P>
   Students called for help on cellular phones and the Internet,
Hinkle said.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the victims had all been notified as of
Wednesday afternoon, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students visited a park near the high school on
Wednesday, putting up memorials of flowers, cards and signs,
embracing one another, crying and singing songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shocking,'' said Deborah Barnes, mother of a 15-year-old
Columbine student. ``You don't know until you actually put your
arms around your child if they're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Healing won't come quickly to the upper-middle-class community.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine will remain closed for an undetermined amount of time,
Jefferson County school administrators said Wednesday. The
districts remaining 14 schools will reopen today with increased
security and supervision, said Rick Kaufman, a spokesman for the
district.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities shed no light Wednesday on a motive for the crime,
but said there were signs the two boys could make trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a real concern with people who identify themselves with
heros like Adolph Hitler,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Several students said Klebold and Harris were part of a group
that worshiped Hitler, whose 110th birthday fell on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other investigators said generalizations about what has been
termed the ``Trench Coat Mafia'' may be inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids wear black clothes and Doc Martens,'' said
Thomas, the district attorney. ``I don't want to make more out of
this than there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Barker writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
