<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PROSECUTOR-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE YELTSIN, PROSECUTOR INVESTIGATING KREMLIN RETAINS POST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The upper house of parliament rejected both lobbying
and a personal plea from President Boris Yeltsin Wednesday and
voted lopsidedly, for the second time, to retain a prosecutor
investigating corruption at the heart of the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-61 vote was a serious setback for Yeltsin, who has been
striving to rebuild both the illusion and the reality of political
clout in order to resist impeachment and a steady erosion of his
authority.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it seemed a clear victory for the Communists
who back the prosecutor, Yuri I. Skuratov, and who are leading the
impeachment drive. It also may have lifted the fortunes of Prime
Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov, who has gained power with every ball
Yeltsin has dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin had sought to enlist Moscow's powerful mayor, Yuri M.
Luzhkov, and had dangled the prospect of expanded powers before
members of the upper house in a bid for their support in the battle
over Skuratov.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the legislators decided to retain Skuratov
as general prosecutor, the nation's top law-enforcement post. It
was the second such vote; on March 17, the same chamber rejected
Yeltsin's first effort to dismiss Skuratov by an even more
one-sided vote.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov has been embroiled since January in a bitter and
sometimes seamy war with Yeltsin and his aides over control of the
prosecutor's office _ and indirectly, of an inquiry into rake-offs
by unidentified officials in Yeltsin's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a battle that has been splayed across the nation's
newspapers and on state television, which not so long ago broadcast
a videotape of Skuratov in bed with two prostitutes, the targets of
that inquiry have never been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov did not identify them again on Wednesday. To do so
before his inquiry was finished ``would be fatal to the country,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov said later that ``the law triumphed today,'' and he
urged Yeltsin to give Skuratov time to complete his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was not clear that the law, Skuratov's inquiry or
even Skuratov's future had much to do with Wednesday's vote. The
question instead seemed to be whether Yeltsin had the power to
resist yet another encroachment on his turf: this time, his control
over the administration of justice.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears that he did not.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption inquiry may have lost a bit of its sex appeal
Wednesday when Skuratov reportedly acknowledged to legislators that
it does not involve Yeltsin or any members of his family. Skuratov
had been tracing money held in Swiss bank accounts by the Russian
elite, and speculation was widespread that Yeltsin's daughter and
confidante, Tatyana Dyachenko, was under investigation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not many analysts expect Skuratov to remain in his job for long.
Skuratov said Wednesday that he had been unable to work with other
investigative agencies in Yeltsin's government and that he would
support an independent corruption inquiry run by members of the
upper house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, his credibility has been seriously undermined by the
broadcast videotape of his liaison with the two women, which some
say was part of a blackmail scheme unrelated to his Kremlin
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he retains his job, Skuratov remains under
suspension while another agency investigates the circumstances
surrounding that liaison. One popular theory Wednesday was that
Skuratov would resign soon in favor of a replacement dictated not
by Yeltsin, but by the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, Wednesday's vote confirmed how dramatically
Yeltsin has lost influence among the regional governors who compose
the upper house of the legislature and who have been his strongest
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   That is doubly important because it is the upper house's duty to
stage a trial should Russia's lower house of parliament, which is
dominated by Communists, decide to impeach Yeltsin. The lower house
has scheduled a mid-May vote on five impeachment charges against
Yeltsin, but before Wednesday, the prospects that the Communists
could actually force a trial seemed remote.
</P>
<P>
   Now, experts are not so certain. Some saw in Wednesday's vote
the deft hand of Luzhkov, himself a presidential aspirant, who is
expected to have a strong say in whoever succeeds Skuratov. Others
saw it as a victory for Primakov, who consolidated his grip on the
government during Yeltsin's long bout of illness last winter and
seems reluctant to surrender it now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
