<HEADLINE>
RISING CRIME DEFINES PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN IN ARGENTINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Crime is emerging as a major political
issue for the first time in the big cities of Argentina, a country
where people have traditionally stayed out well past midnight to
hop from cafes to tango clubs without a fear in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is filling a vacuum in an otherwise listless campaign
to succeed President Carlos Saul Menem in which the two leading
candidates generally agree on economic and social policy. It is a
touchy issue for both candidates: Buenos Aires Mayor Fernando de la
Rua and Gov. Eduardo Duhalde, who is responsible for governing the
province surrounding the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Neither presidential candidate is blaming the other for the
crime wave, apparently for fear that such a charge could backfire.
De la Rua, the Alianza candidate, has come under fire from critics
for an increase in Buenos Aires street prostitution under his
watch. Critics of Duhalde, the front-runner for the Justicialist
Party nomination, have attributed a rise in crime around his
province to his purging of his corrupt and violent provincial
police.
</P>
<P>
   But with recent polls showing that crime is the No. 2 concern of
Argentine voters, after unemployment, advisers to the two
candidates are drawing up detailed anti-crime programs that will
include shaking up Argentina's corrupt and underpaid police
departments and court systems.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, members of Congress of the ruling Justicialist
Party and the opposition Alianza coalition have traded barbs
accusing each other of being soft on crime, but they joined
together to lengthen prison sentences for juvenile offenders and
people found concealing guns without a license.
</P>
<P>
   Menem is prohibited by the constitution from running for a third
consecutive term, but many of his backers hope he can still file a
successful legal challenge before the Supreme Court and compete in
the October balloting. Menem has been sending mixed signals about
his political intentions, but he seems to be trying to capitalize
on the growing concerns about crime to help consolidate his control
over his party, if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not willing to watch unmoved the spectacle of a country
where politicians speak while innocent people die,'' he said in a
recent interview, in which he made specific reference to the
successes the New York City police have had in bringing down New
York's crime rate. This week he transferred more than 1,500 border
police and navy military police to help patrol the streets of
Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's vice presidential candidate, Carlos ``Chacho''
Alvarez, criticized the president's move, warning that ``we should
not militarize the conflict.'' And De la Rua suggested that crime
was rising because the government was ineffective at fighting
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Menem responded in an open letter, published in the local press
on Wednesday, scolding the mayor for ``confusing the dignity of the
poor with the pathology of delinquency.''
</P>
<P>
   While preparing for his run for president, Duhalde made a
pilgrimage to New York a year ago to be photographed with Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and receive a briefing on the city's successful
anti-crime strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, Duhalde has included references in his stump
speeches to ``zero tolerance'' _ the policing theory, made popular
in New York, that a crackdown on small crimes contributes to a
decrease of more violent crimes. Meanwhile, De la Rua had a
well-publicized breakfast here in November with a former New York
City police commissioner, William Bratton, in which they discussed
crime strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I was impressed with the visibility of the
police,'' Bratton said in a telephone interview, ``but I wasn't
sure they knew what they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton noted that Argentina, like other countries emerging from
military dictatorships, was struggling to make its security forces
more responsive to community needs while coordinating their
operations more effectively with civilian prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the public has been bombarded with crime
stories in the media, including one about a serial killer on the
loose in the beach resort of Mar del Plata, and others about daily
holdups in Buenos Aires restaurants, banks and discotheques. Fear
of crime has even spread to pristine Patagonia, where, in the city
of Neuquen, police have begun searching pedestrians waiting at taxi
stands for concealed guns.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina remains one of Latin America's safer countries, and
Buenos Aires has nowhere near the crime problem of Caracas,
Venezuela; Mexico City, or Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. Still, the
Buenos Aires daily La Nacion recently published a front-page
article with statistics leaked by the government indicating that
incidents of serious reported crimes in Buenos Aires doubled
between 1995 and 1998, from 480,000 to 960,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
