<SLUG> BC-REALITY-CHECK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY 15 MINUTES, STUDENTS GET A GRIM REMINDER ABOUT DRUNKEN
DRIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROWLEY, Texas _ At precisely 9:45 a.m., the Grim Reaper came
for Hilaree Hawkins _ down the halls of Crowley High School and
right into her class. Hawkins, a 17-year-old senior, went quietly;
as she left, a Crowley police officer entered the class and read
her obituary aloud to her classmates.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, the ritual continued: The tall man in the black,
hooded robe (carrying a scythe, no less) entering a classroom, the
student getting up silently and leaving, the police officer
solemnly reading the obituary.
</P>
<P>
   The Reaper was punctual. He interrupted a class to snatch away a
student once every 15 minutes _ the frequency with which someone in
America is killed by a drunken driver.
</P>
<P>
   This was precisely the point of ``Every 15 Minutes,'' a program
involving about 35 Crowley High students _ and many of their
parents, who wrote the obituaries. Sponsored by C.R.A.S.H.
(Communities for Responsible Auto Safety Habits), ``Every 15
Minutes'' is a Tarrant County-wide, multiorganizational initiative
designed to make teens aware of the dangers involved in drinking
and driving. C.R.A.S.H. even included a simulated alcohol-related
car wreck (complete with ambulances and a helicopter ambulance
taking a victim away) in front of the school.
</P>
<P>
   The students who participated in the program were taken to a
nearby hotel, where speakers and counselors discussed the
consequences of alcohol and drugs. The second day featured an
assembly during which the ``dead'' students were returned to the
student body, and trauma-treatment and legal professionals talked
about the consequences of drinking and driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ever make it real enough for kids, but this is the
best way we can show them'' the effects of drinking and driving,
says Karen Pfleger, trauma program coordinator at Harris Methodist
Fort Worth hospital. ``I'd like to stand all of them in a trauma
room when a victim of a drunk driver comes in, but you can't do
that. You can't just tell them not to drink and drive. You have to
show them the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit to Crowley High School was the first such program put
on by C.R.A.S.H., which formed last year and is made up of
representatives from the hospital, area police and fire
departments, the Metroplex chapter of Mothers Against Drunk Driving
and the Texas Department of Transportation. The organization's goal
is to ``decrease teen motor vehicle fatality and injury in Tarrant
Country,'' said to Debbie Phillips, Harris Methodist's manager of
community health and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every 15 Minutes'' was initiated by the Chico, Calif., Police
Department in 1995. Last year, the Mansfield Police Department
staged one at Mansfield High School, which is how C.R.A.S.H. heard
about it. ``We decided it'd be a good way to reach a lot of
students,'' Phillips says. ``The Mansfield police felt it really
reached out to a lot of students; kids remembered the program three
and four months later.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, who can forget a helicopter landing in the parking
lot? About 10 a.m. on the day of the program, the students were
told there was a car crash in front of the school; they walked out
to see a car and a station wagon nose to nose, with a ``dead''
student (17-year-old junior Ben Barnett) lying in front of them,
his head in a pool of blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's cool to be part of a program that reinforces how
bad drinking and driving is,'' Barnett says. ``I hope people see
how real it can be, how it can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, police cars, two ambulances and a CareFlite
helicopter had arrived to ferry away the faux-injured, who included
one young man with a severed arm, which lay on the hood of the car.
A police officer opened the station wagon door; out spilled liquor
bottles and beer cans, and Phillips' 18-year-old daughter, Sarah,
playing the drunk who caused the wreck. She was led away in
handcuffs, just as Barnett was covered with a white sheet, which at
least momentarily cut way down on the amount of talking in the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Mooney stood nearby, watching his son, Brandon, an
18-year-old senior, lie still in the car. He wanted his son to
participate in the program because ``he needs to realize one or two
drinks does matter. This can be a good experience for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing his son's obituary, he says, was ``depressing, for lack
of a better word. It was hard to do; his mother and I probably
spent 12 to 15 hours on it. It's not something you do every day.''
He says it has led the two of them to talk about drinking and
driving. ``He's hoping it'll open some eyes,'' Mooney says. ``We've
talked about what we'd do without him. If it makes one child take
this seriously, it'll be worth the time and the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary; it makes you realize what can happen,'' says
Martha Mahanay, an 18-year-old senior. ``It was realistic. I hope
it got through to people _ to have something like this happen in
our school would be awful. I think it'll touch some people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
