u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-ROBOTS-HNS &LR;      04-21 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-ROBOTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEARING BOMBS FROM COLORADO SCHOOL DELAYS INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Before investigators were allowed into
Columbine High School to collect evidence and remove bodies
Wednesday, specialists spent hours sweeping the campus for
explosives left during a shooting and bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want anyone to go back into that building until the
bomb team felt it was safe,'' said Jefferson County sheriff's
office spokesman Steve Davis. ``That's what's been taking so much
time last night and today.''
</P>
<P>
   Technicians in bomb suits, recruited from several agencies
around Littleton, searched the facility using bomb-sniffing dogs
and remote-controlled robots.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found long rifles, semiautomatic handguns and
about 30 explosive devices _ including pipe bombs set off several
miles from the school 15 minutes before the rampage Tuesday.
Officials believe those were a diversion to distract emergency
personnel during the attack on the school. No one was injured at
that site.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives were cleared to enter the building and begin their
investigation about noon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials found ingredients they said could be used in
explosives at the homes of Columbine students Eric Harris, 18, and
Dylan Klebold, 17, whom police have identified as the gunmen. Their
bodies were found in the school, and authorities believe they shot
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold, members of an outcast group known as the
``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' stormed the school about 11:30 a.m. Tuesday
wearing masks and black clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students and faculty clambered for the exits while
others hid as the pair sprayed gunfire at lockers and hallways and
set off the bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the school's 1,870 students were eating lunch and
were trapped in the cafeteria as the armed students entered. Most
of the victims were found in the cafeteria and second-floor
library, where Harris and Klebold also were found dead.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the explosive devices were in duffel bags and on the
floors inside the school. Officials believe Harris and Klebold
brought the bombs with them.
</P>
<P>
   Although preliminary investigations suggest that the two acted
alone, Jefferson County District Attorney Dave Thomas said it is
possible others may have helped construct the bombs. If so, the
others could face criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Searchers used protective clothing and other bomb retardant
equipment, robots and dogs trained to sniff out explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The remote-controlled robots are guided into areas using video
screens to detect bombs without endangering humans.
</P>
<P>
   Only two or three bombs were detonated during the attack, but
another went off in a parking lot Tuesday night, Westminster Police
Spokeswoman Jacki Tallman said. No one was injured then.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the devices were pipe bombs, but investigators also
found what Tallman described only as a ``gas-type'' bomb and a
``propane-type'' bomb in two cars.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs could have been made using chemicals found under a
typical kitchen sink or purchased at hardware stores. Recipes for
the deadly concoctions can be found in books and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
