<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-ALIEN22-COX     04-21 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-ALIEN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intervention can help deflect violence spurred by alienation
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The American teen-ager. Yearning to stand out, and
desperate to fit in. Struggling to be a rebel, yet terrified of
losing status with the cool group. It is an age of alienation.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of being on the outside looking in is ``typical in
adolescence, from 12 to 18,'' says Dr. Michael Popkin, an Atlanta
psychologist who deals with teens. Such alienation breeds feelings
of rejection, he says, which is why movies such as ``Carrie'' _ the
fiery 1976 revenge fantasy of an outcast girl, a remake of which
was recently released _ are so popular.
</P>
<P>
   But fantasies don't kill teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday a pair of Colorado high school students described by
their peers as ``freaks'' and ``outcasts,'' kids who wore black and
fancied themselves as rebels, turned their anxiety into a
bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a troubled kid cross the line into real anger, and
real violence? And how can we intervene?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem is we haven't even looked at that question
enough,'' says Iris Bolton, executive director of The LINK
Counselling Center, a nonprofit center that focuses on suicide
prevention and children in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton suggests that many schools will respond by putting up
metal detectors to protect themselves from killer students. A more
useful approach, she says, would be to learn how youngsters are
driven to despair, and to rescue them beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   That means targeting teens prone to violence, whether against
themselves or against others. Isolated kids often gather to create
their own group, a place to belong, which can also be a hotbed for
violent action.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might get goaded by other members of the gang, or be dared
to take action,'' says Popkin. ``My hunch is when they get to the
bottom of this (Colorado) investigation, there will be other people
implicated in this, who might have been pushing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The two students accused in the Colorado shootings called
themselves the Trench Coat Mafia and dressed in black trench coats.
They were called ``goths'' by fellow students. Goths, a subculture
that grew out of the punk movement, affect black clothing, a gloomy
attitude and a fascination with Victorian poets and such champions
of the morose as Edgar Allan Poe and Anne Rice.
</P>
<P>
   But clothes don't necessarily provide a clue to the wearer, and
psychologists point out that plenty of other folks also dress all
in black
</P>
<P>
   ``Most goths do wear all black,'' but so do most art directors,
says Carissa Craig, who helps organize the goth night at the
Masquerade venue in Atlanta. ``Everyone is very offended at the
gothic term being brought up in relation to this crime,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The Trench Coat Mafia borrowed not only gothic affectations but
elements of white supremacy, which has nothing to do with goth
ethos.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the warning signs is crucial, but the problem, say
experts, is that many of us are too busy to see what's going on in
the lives of those around us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationships are superficial,'' says Dara Gocheski, 18, a
senior at Marietta High School. ``We never pay attention to see
what makes people tick.''
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Thompson, 18, is a senior on the Marietta High School
track team. ``I was wondering if any of the kids I know would flip
out like that, because I know some kids like that who get teased a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never know who at Marietta is carrying a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearances are deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Cornelius had two sons. One was a punk rocker who shaved
his head and broke his nose stage diving. The other was a Sunday
school honor student and an acolyte in the Episcopal church.
``Which one of those took his own life?'' asks Cornelius.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Ryan Cornelius, the ``good'' kid, stole his
father's pistol, found the key to a locked box of bullets, and shot
himself. Her son, it turns out, had been tormented most of his
school life by bullies and was severely depressed. And his mother
never knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Her tragedy spurred Cornelius to become involved with the
Suicide Prevention Advocacy Network, and her experiences there
convince her that a screening for depression could help many
potentially troubled high school kids.
</P>
<P>
   But much youth violence is impulsive, says Dr. Rodney Hammond,
director of the Division of Violence Prevention at the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, and difficult to predict.
</P>
<P>
   Early research indicates that there are risk factors that
increase an adolescent's chances of committing violence against
himself or others, says Hammond, including violent attitudes, a
history of threats and access to firearms.
</P>
<P>
   While youth violence in general is dropping, the incidents of
multiple homicides is actually rising, says Hammond, a figure that
worries CDC officials. Yet the attention on violence in schools
disguises the fact that less than 1 percent of violent deaths of
those 18 or younger occur in school-related settings. Most occur at
home or in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Professionals such as Hammond see prevention as the key to
dealing with youth violence. But, says Bolton, prevention begins
with discussion. Teachers and parents must acknowledge the threat
of suicide and violence. Students who are warned regularly about
drugs and alcohol need to be trained just as vigorously in dealing
with anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of focusing on what can the president say to console
us, and what can we put into the schools to protect this from
happening, lets talk about why does it happen in the first place,''
says Cornelius. ``It's a taboo subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from her own experience, Cornelius says the events in
Colorado will have one positive result. ``Once a suicide occurs,
then people learn the warning signs of depression,'' she says,
adding, ``don't ignore them. Don't think it's a joke if someone
says 'if I don't pass this test I'm going to kill myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``This community can survive this and make meaning out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
