<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-GUNBILLSQCOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado governor vows to veto bill that halts lawsuit against
gunmakers
 &HT;    By C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Gov. Bill Owens Wednesday said he will veto a bill that
would prohibit municipalities from suing gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   And two other gun-related bills still before the Legislature
will not move forward, the sponsors said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The moves come as Coloradans tried to deal with the aftermath of
the massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, a Republican, also set aside $1 million Wednesday to
assist the victims' families. The money also could also be used to
repair Columbine High School, which Jefferson County School
District officials say may not reopen this school year.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said he will veto Senate Bill 205, sponsored by state Sen.
Ron Teck, R-Grand Junction, because of constitutional questions
about the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would prohibit municipalities from suing gun
manufacturers if weapons are used in the commission of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attorney has briefed me during the last couple weeks,''
Owens said during a Wednesday afternoon press conference at the
capitol. ``There are serious constitutional questions. I will veto
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens said he also supports the decision to table the two other
bills. Senate Bill 84 would have authorized residents free of a
criminal record and who complete a training course to carry
concealed weapons. House Bill 1305 would have standardized firearms
regulations across Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   State House Speaker Russell George, R-Rifle, said he had been
trying since Tuesday to convince legislators to drop the bills.
Owens said in light of what happened in Littleton, he's not sure
what form, if ever, the bills would return.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature and governor's office have already started to
look at how other states reacted to school shootings to see what
direction to take.
</P>
<P>
   George said the issues range from school uniforms to finding
more money for security. State Rep. Matt Smith, R-Grand Junction,
said he believes the Legislature immediately will see a request for
more support for private and charter schools. Whether anything can
be accomplished during the two remaining weeks of the session is
not certain, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions of school safety are at the forefront of parents
checking their kids into school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Owens said he set aside the $1 million in assistance so the
multitude of officials involved can do as much possible to deal
with the crisis. ``We need to do whatever we can to mitigate what
is before us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cleary writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
