<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-LAWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST SHOOTINGS INFLAME GUN-CONTROL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Colorado's high school massacre stoked the nation's
already fiery gun-control debate Wednesday as lawmakers pressed
anew for strict controls on access to firearms. But, they conceded,
the rule of law is little match for random violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps the most important thing all of us can do right now is
to reach out to each other and to families and children,''
President Clinton said. ``It is very important to explain to
children all over America what has happened and to reassure our own
children that they are safe.''
</P>
<P>
   As the president pledged his administration's swift support to
help Littleton, Colo., cope with the tragedy, his spokesman
reaffirmed Clinton's commitment to measures that would hold adults
criminally liable for allowing easy access to guns, provide firearm
safety locks, and establish a lifetime gun-possession ban for those
who commit violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me emphasize that it's unclear that any of these would
relate directly to the incident that we are going through now,''
said Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Across Capitol Hill Wednesday gun-control advocates used the
shootings half a continent away to bolster their case for some of
the 50 gun-control bills now pending before Congress, while
acknowledging that legislation alone will not control the carnage
that has erupted in schools from Alaska to Arkansas, Oregon to
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough to wring our hands and pray it won't happen
again,'' said Senator Charles Schumer, a New York Democrat. ``We
need to act. Let's resolve to work together to do what is necessary
to protect our children. Let us focus on better counseling,
documentation of hate groups with the school, encouraging students
to come forward, and much better laws to prevent kids from getting
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, who has introduced legislation that would ban
unlicensed Internet sales of weapons, said, ``We must accept that
any solutions must involve a change in gun laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Patrick Kennedy, a Rhode Island Democrat, called
for education grants to pay for school violence prevention programs
and legislation that would automatically revoke licenses from
dealers who sell firearms to underage buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Rand, director of federal policy for the Violence Policy
Center, said the Colorado slayings will galvanize efforts to
oversee a gun industry that she called the nation's last
unregulated consumer-product manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's finally beginning to sink in that if we don't
really start doing something, we are going to have to learn to live
with this _ and it's going to happen every couple of months,'' said
Rand.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican National Committee chairman Jim Nicholson, who
used to live five miles from Columbine High School, said it would
be wrong to make the killings in Colorado grist for speedy new
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doubtless there will be those who will try to politicize these
tragic events, who will exploit our emotions in the furtherance of
simplistic political solutions,'' Nicholson said in a statement.
``Americans know better. We're not even able to formulate the
questions about Wednesday's tragedy, much less learn the answers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, Governor Bill Owens would not say whether he will
continue to support a bill that would make it easier to carry a
concealed weapon. ``We have tight, tough gun-control laws here in
Jefferson County in the state of Colorado right now,'' Owens said
on ``Good Morning America.'' ``They broke those laws. They broke
laws concerning the making of guns. They broke laws concerning that
we shall not kill. I'm not sure that they would have obeyed a
further law.''
</P>
<P>
   The concealed weapons bill was one of two gun proposals
withdrawn Wednesday by their sponsors in the Colorado Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress expressed frustration that six months
after a White House conference on school violence underscored the
need for intervention for troubled students, and training to
recognize early warning signs of potential violent behavior, there
is no way to legislate away senseless shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of horrors are the expression of deeply troubled
people, and they're affected by so many different factors that it's
hard to say with any confidence that we know how exactly to prevent
them,'' said Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
