<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-GUY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FOX CARTOON MOCKS TV, `THE SIMPSONS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like its animated counterpart ``The Simpsons,'' Fox's new
cartoon sitcom ``Family Guy'' isn't afraid to worship at the feet
of its maker ... the almighty idiot box.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so much of ``Family Guy'' is devoted to parodying or
lauding television, the show promises to be for the little screen
what ``The Critic'' was for the big. (The series had a sneak
preview after the Super Bowl in January, but is only now settling
in for its regular run.)
</P>
<P>
   From its ``All in the Family''-style opening theme song to the
obligatory reference to Fox's ``reality programming'' specials (in
this case, ``Fast Animals, Slow Children)'' _ ``Family Guy's''
premiere makes for a scathingly funny look at our media-obsessed
society. In fact, a recent episode revolved around, believe it or
not, television. When the town's cable dish was accidentally
knocked out, viewers were forced to come to grips with their
airwave addiction.
</P>
<P>
   But just as ``Futurama,'' the new Spage-Agey cartoon from
``Simpsons'' creator Matt Groening, struggles to escape the shadow
of TV's foremost 'toon family, ``Family Guy'' also displays a
Simpsonesque influence. The family guy himself is Peter Griffin,
the patriarch of a typically dysfunctional American household (kind
of like Homer). Wife Lois is the lovable, levelheaded one (kind of
like Marge); daughter Meg is the smart, underappreciated kid (kind
of like Lisa); and Chris is the dim-bulb slacker (kind of like
Bart). The only characters who stray from ``The Simpsons'' formula
are the toddler and the family pet. They are the show's most
endearing and interesting characters.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Maggie remains mute, content to suck on her pacifier,
baby Stewie is a precociously verbose conniver bent on taking over
the world. And although Santa's Little Helper may be the only
Simpson who's dumber than Homer, the Griffins' pooch is the
brainiest member of the household, happy to sip martinis and read
the paper while dispensing clever bons mots.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious lifts from other series, you can't deny that
some of the TV parodies the family watches are pretty dead-on _
especially an amusing send-up of William Shatner's Captain Kirk and
an update of ``Scooby-Doo.'' (Yep, that's the voice of the original
Freddy, Frank Welker.)
</P>
<P>
   Show creator Seth MacFarlane lends his voice to all the main
characters except for Lois, voiced by Alex Borstein. And if
MacFarlane can keep the TV skewers as sharp as in the premiere,
this show's got more of a future than ``Futurama.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
