<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-CHANGES-ART-2T     04-21 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-CHANGES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPHONE MERGER SIGNALS NEW ERA FOR EUROPEAN INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic on companies at a glance and top 10 cross-border
deals in Europe is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ A year ago, even a month ago, it still
seemed unthinkable. Wednesday, it began to look unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   The planned merger between Deutsche Telekom AG and Telecom
Italia, which were both government-owned telephone monopolies until
very recently, would be more than just another record-breaking
corporate deal.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its sheer scale, the pact demolishes many of the European
taboos against cross-border mergers in politically sensitive
industries. It also sets the stage for a new series of big
telecommunications takeovers, much as the regional Bell companies
jumped into each other's arms in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   What is most remarkable about the deal between Deutsche Telekom
and Telecom Italia is how little political opposition it has
ignited. Even more than big banks and car companies, European
telephone companies have been national enterprises that remain
under heavy political control by their governments.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite some last-minute angst by Italian officials about
``selling out to the German government,'' both governments were
more worried about letting their telephone companies become too
weak than about giving up national control.
</P>
<P>
   The surprisingly passive reaction reflects two big changes. The
first is the onslaught of new competition in the year since most
European governments opened their telephone markets to rivals for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom, which presides over Europe's biggest and
wealthiest telephone market, has lost 30 percent of its
long-distance market to new rivals and been forced to slash some of
its prices by 70 percent. Most of Europe's other telephone
companies are bracing for similar attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The second big change is the unrivaled new influence of
international shareholders and global capital markets. Faced with
the need to raise billions of dollars to finance expansion,
European corporations of all types are relying far more heavily on
global public stock and bond offerings than they did in the past.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the shares of DaimlerChrysler and Deutsche
Telekom trade in New York and Tokyo as well as Frankfurt, survival
depends far more on profitability than nationality.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed the rules of the game. Companies that alienate
shareholders, most of whom have no interest at all in a stock's
nationality, risk being cut off from major sources of capital. Or,
as in the case of Telecom Italia, they become vulnerable to a brash
hostile takeover attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have come at a curious historical juncture. Most
European countries, including Germany and Italy, have elected new
left-of-center governments in the last two years. Yet Europe's
corporate culture, consumed with hostile takeovers and gigantic
mergers, increasingly mirrors that of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed of the deal making is increasing as the intensity of
the competition is increasing,'' said Scott Beardsley, a
telecommunications consultant at McKinsey &AMP; Co. in Brussels. ``The
incumbents are facing wrenching changes in their markets, not only
in the sense of competitors but from investors as well.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains far from clear that shareholders will be smitten by
the proposed megamerger. Many analysts are skeptical that a
trans-Alpine telephone giant will be able to fend off competitors
any more effectively than the two companies on their own. And they
note both companies still have a lot of restructuring work in front
of them.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger would at least create a company with additional
scale, which could help it shave costs in buying equipment. And the
merged company would have a big base on which to build a
pan-European telecommunications network to compete with the likes
of the alliance between British Telecommunications and AT&AMP;T Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an industrial logic, because their purchasing power
rises substantially,'' said Juergen Roethig, head of securities
trading at Metzler Securities, a private bank in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts caution that the savings are not likely to add up
to more than 1 percent of revenues, and that the promised synergies
between the two companies will not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have very different telephone systems and
corporate cultures. They are supervised by very different
regulators. And because Germany and Italy do not share a border,
the two companies will not necessarily enjoy big advantages in
connecting their networks together.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could also be blocked or altered by competition
authorities at the European Commission in Brussels. A trade group
representing competitors to Deutsche Telekom announced Wednesday
that it would ask the regulators to intervene and warned that the
merger would ``greatly endanger the competition that is just now
getting under way in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Karel van Miert, Europe's minister of competition, had already
indicated this week that the deal would not be approved unless the
companies pared off at least some of their holdings. Deutsche
Telekom would be forced to give up its stake in Wind, a new
competitive phone company in Italy, but it might also be forced to
make other concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Even assuming the deal is approved, the two companies face big
restructurings. Analysts say Deutsche Telekom's costs are still too
high, given the price reductions it has had to swallow in response
to its new competitors. Deutsche Telekom's revenues declined nearly
7 percent in the first three months of this year, to 16.1 billion
marks ($8.75 billion), from 17.3 billion marks in the comparable
period a year earlier; profit was flat at 1.04 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia needs to cut costs as well, but it also needs to
divest marginal businesses in equipment manufacturing, real estate
and financial services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a really tough challenge,'' said Francois
Travaille, a telecommunications industry analyst at Banque
Nationale de Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural differences are mind-boggling. Under the plan,
Deutsche Telekom's tough and austere chairman, Ron Sommer, would
share power with Telecom Italia's chief, Franco Bernabe. Somehow,
the two would have to decide how best to shed tens of thousands of
additional jobs and to merge management teams that speak different
languages and will be battling each other for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The tensions have been apparent as Telecom Italia's board
agonized over the merger offer this week. Fearful of simply being
acquired by the German government, the board demanded that the
German government limit its voting power and clarify its plans to
sell off part of its stake. They also insisted &QL; 
that the job of company chairman should rotate regularly between
executives from each company.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the German government refused to limit its voting
rights or to reduce its stake more quickly than originally planned.
But it insisted that it remained committed to the full
privatization of Deutsche Telekom and had no interest in taking
over control of day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Even Wednesday night, after three days of deliberations, Telecom
Italia board members appeared nervous about the deal and hesitated
about issuing any public statements. But they were also apparently
ready to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry analysts and executives contend that Deutsche
Telekom is acting more out of opportunism than strategy. Bernabe of
Telecom Italia has been desperately looking for a white knight to
prevent his company from being taken over by Olivetti, the
electronic equipment and telecommunications company that made a
hostile takeover bid worth more than $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the German telephone company appears to be on the prowl
for other big acquisitions, which it would finance in part by
selling more than $10 billion worth of new shares this year.
</P>
<P>
   There have been numerous reports in the German media that
Deutsche Telekom would like to buy Sprint Corp., the third-largest
American long-distance carrier in which both Deutsche Telekom and
France Telecom already own 10 percent stakes. But it has been
extremely cautious about committing itself to any further
entanglement with Sprint. Deutsche Telekom has also held extensive
talks with Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC, according to German newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, industry executives say the merger frenzy in
European telecommunications still has a long way to go. Mannesmann,
one of Telekom's biggest competitors, acquired the network owned by
O.Tel.O, Germany's third-largest telephone competitor. With about
50 new rivals in Germany alone, more such deals are likely.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, analysts say smaller traditional telephone carriers,
like those in the Netherlands or Austria, may feel pressured to
look for partners. The telephone companies of Sweden and Norway are
already merging, and Tele-Denmark is now controlled by Ameritech,
regional Bell company based in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   All Europe seems already to be looking beyond this deal to the
next step. For even if the prospective marriage between the Italian
and German phone companies falls through, the mere fact that it got
this far suggests that European business has now crossed the
Rubicon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
