<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS PRESSED TO CONSIDER GROUND TROOPS FOR KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON and CRAIG WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Britain and France are pressing the United
States to seriously consider sending ground forces into Kosovo. But
as leaders of the NATO nations begin gathering here on the eve of
the alliance's 50th anniversary summit, their differences are so
pronounced that the matter has been left off the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration seems to be extremely wary about
suggestions that ground troops might have to go into Kosovo. One
senior official said he worried about a situation in which NATO
troops found themselves mired in a guerrilla war with Serb
renegades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not fighting your way in; it is what happens
after you get there,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Washington signalled some flexibility on Wednesday
night, saying it favored a broad NATO review of options developed
last summer on the use of ground troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes debate broke out into the open this week
in a coordinated series of statements by Britain's prime minister,
defense minister and foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   With four weeks of bombing attacks already behind them, they
argued that weeks, if not months, of sustained bombing might
sufficiently weaken the Serb military so that NATO ground forces
could move into Kosovo and establish order with limited
casualities. The scenario has been discussed so much in the
corridors of NATO headquarters here that it even has a name: ``a
semi-permissive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The British proposal would be a major shift from the NATO's
current plan, which is to send in a peacekeeping force of 28,000
troops, but only if President Slobodan Milosevic withdraws his
forces from Kosovo and accepts a peace settlement that allows the
1.8 million ethnic Albanians to return to their shattered homes.
</P>
<P>
   As Robin Cook, Britain's foreign minister put it Tuesday in an
address to the House of Commons, it is possible to ``conceive of
circumstances in which it may be feasible to commit ground
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The main condition would be the assurance that NATO's force were
not facing ``organized armed resistance.'' As British officials
tell it, Milosevic would not be given a ``veto'' over the
introduction of allied ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The British are not alone in pressing for the possible
introduction of ground forces. President Jacques Chirac of France
said in a televised speech Wednesday night that the alliance should
apply ``additional means'' besides escalating the air war to stop
``massacres, rapes, burned villages, families separated and thrown
onto the roads.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials said Chirac's statement was an allusion to
ground forces, and that France's plan was to seek a U.N. Security
Council resolution mandating such a force.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the entire question of ground forces going into
potential combat in Kosovo has been highly sensitive. American
officials have sought to avoid public discussion of the matter.
Defense Secretary William Cohen suggested on Wednesday that the
matter of ground troops did not need to be decided because Gen.
Wesley K. Clark, the NATO commander, had not officially requested
authority to plan a military operation using combat forces.
</P>
<P>
   Left unstated was the fact that NATO's military commander was
not about to propose a major escalation in the fighting unless the
United States, the leader of the alliance, was behind it and was
ready to use its political influence to build support for a
decision to send in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   But after saying for weeks that no such planning was necessary,
the White House said on Wednesday that it was time to study the
size and composition of the forces that would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. would certainly support as a prudent measure any
updating of the assessments of the use of ground troops in a
permissive and non-permissive environment,'' the White House
official said on Wednesday evening. ``It would be irresponsible for
us not to periodically update our plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The allies were not the only ones the Clinton administration
appeared to have in mind. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is seeking
the Republican presidential nomination, has lambasted the Clinton
dministration for starting an air campaign against Yugoslavia
without a backup plan for combat troops.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, all the allies agree the bombing needs to go on for a
long time. Clark has repeatedly argued that the bombing campaign
has to have time to do its work and that it is too early to say if
it will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the 29th day of bombing, allied planes hit
the headquarters of Milosevic's party in Belgrade, a
glass-and-steel 23-story building that also housed three local
television and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister George Robertson of Britain described the
building as ``one of the nerve centers of the machine which plans
the killing in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Western diplomats say Clark has told allied leaders
that he cannot guarantee that bombing attacks alone will compel
Milosevic to withdraw Serbian troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, NATO nations have yet to ask him to draw up a new
plan to send in combat troops, nor has he asked for the authority
to begin planning.
</P>
<P>
   The review of military options, which the Clinton administration
says it now supports, stops considerably short of that.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there was a plan, lengthy preparations would be needed
to assemble the force. Even then, no ground attack could be carried
out without the approval of the entire 19-member alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of an agreement, diplomats here initially sought
to paper over their differences. But lately, the British have
insisted that ground troops might be needed to bring the war to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Prime Minister Tony Blair met with Clinton here
Wednesday night in an apparent effort to persuade him to do more to
actively prepare in case land forces were needed.
</P>
<P>
   Blair made the case for this after meeting at NATO headquarters
with l Clark on Tuesday. He drew a distinction between sending in
ground troops against tough Serb resistance and sending them in
after punishing NATO bombing had taken the fight out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always made clear the difficulties of putting in
ground forces as a land force invasion against undegraded organized
Serb resistence,'' Blair said. ``We have also equally made it clear
that the international military force is there to allow people to
go back to their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Going in on the ground would mark a huge departure for NATO,
which has been as preoccupied with maintaining public support at
home for the military campaign as in taking the war to Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroder of Germany would probably be in
favor of sending ground troops to Kosovo, but one European official
sepculated that Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer's Greens Party
might break apart over the issue, collapsing the government.
</P>
<P>
   Canada would not oppose an alliance consensus, Prime Minister
Jean Chretien said in Montreal on Tuesday. ``If everyone is in
agreement, I will not be the only one disagreeing,'' Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
   The French position is less bold than it seems. French officials
say that France would be prepared to send in troops but only with a
mandate for such a force from the U.N. Security Council, which
would require persuading Russia not to use its veto power there.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a tall order since Moscow is adamantly opposed to
any force that does not have Milosevic's approval.
</P>
<P>
   NATO members will have ample opportunity to debate the issue at
the summit. Their foreign ministers and defense ministers will also
have separate meetings of their own on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of ground troops is not on the agenda in Washington,
but the leaders are certainly going to be talking about it, in
bilateral meetings, over dinner, informally,'' a high European
official of the alliance said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British, the French and the Turks might all be willing to
go in with ground troops,'' he added. ``Others are more reticient.
But what do the Americans want?''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has been reluctant to take the lead
in thinking about a land operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an American-led organization,'' the senior European
official said. ``If the Americans said we can't let Milosevic get
away with this, we've got to go in with ground troops, then each
country would have to consider the issue and make a decision. And
we could agree that only the countries that wanted to would
contribute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-POPCULTURE22-C     04-21 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-POPCULTURE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Icons of teen angst pose as prophets of alienation
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Teen-age alienation isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout popular culture's catalog of images and attitudes, it
has become a much more extreme proposition. Inevitably, teen-age
alienation is also part of the landscape against which events like
Tuesday's Colorado school shootings take place.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of how far the envelope has been pushed, think
back to James Dean, the sensitive, sensual ``Rebel Without a
Cause'' in the epochal 1955 drama. He looks positively quaint when
you compare the film to some of its '90s counterparts. The amoral
universe of Larry Clark's 1995 ``Kids,'' for instance, is a
latchkey generation apocalypse, in which promiscuous teens and
preteens drift through a haze of drugs and sex _ unblinkingly
clouded by the shadow of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Dean lived fast and died young, true to formula for romantic
myth. But he died in a car accident. The 1990s version is the saga
of Nirvana singer Kurt Cobain, whose wrenching howl and knack for
fusing Beatlesque melody with a barrage of feedback was a catharsis
for his own troubled youth. Cobain ended his life with a shotgun
blast in 1994 at age 27, immortalizing himself _ for many of his
younger fans _ as a prophet of alienation and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Classic American blues and country music wouldn't be the same
without these weighty themes, but then seminal Delta bluesman
Robert Johnson and Appalachian banjo wizard Dock Boggs, who often
sang about death, Satan, sex and murder, among other things, didn't
have MTV to promote them. They were just dealing with life as they
knew it, projecting a little bit, and carrying forth traditions
with links to Africa and Scotland. And it's hard to imagine how
these Smithsonian-approved folk legends would look in
buttocks-baring Spandex.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: The success of a performer such as Marilyn Manson, who
capitalizes on the same themes, substituting theatrical shock
tactics and professional cynicism for Nirvana's earnest angst. Yet,
there's a strong appeal for disenfranchised kids inherent in
Manson's concept albums. ``Antichrist Superstar,'' the 1996 album
that brought the singer into the pop mainstream, is a
semi-autobiographical fantasy in which an outcast, high school
``worm'' transforms into an avenging angel (and big-time rock
star). Last year's ``Mechanical Animals'' swaps the gothic chic
that had characterized Manson's image for the androgynous duds of
'70s glam-rock. But the sci-fi psychodrama offers consistent
touchstones: anger at the embalming grip of authority, the idea of
the singer as the faceless spawn of a meaningless society.
</P>
<P>
   Manson, ultimately, fancies himself as an ubermensch. The
current kings of teen-age rage are self-conscious losers with lots
of issues: the members of California hard-rock band Korn. ``Every
time I start to believe, something's raped and taken from me,''
rails lead vocalist Jon Davis on the new single ``Freak on a
Leash.'' Korn's latest album, ``Follow the Leader,'' is rife with
images of childhood abuse and sexual aggression, but the violence
most often seems to turn inward, and the sexuality is sometimes
ambiguous. These are songs that could have been written as therapy.
In fact, they are therapy, sung by a high school outsider who found
his way to the spotlight: ``In the past I was known as a freak, had
no friends, picked on cause I was weak/Sang my ass off got into
this band, never thought the band would become the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Music, though, seems less a focus for pundits trying to explain
the source of violent episodes than visual media. Reportedly, the
two students who launched Tuesday's assault were ardent competitors
in ultra-violent computer video games, in which animated gunmen mow
down scores of opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It was that medium that parents of three students killed Dec. 1,
1997, at Heath High School in Paducah, Ky., had in mind when they
recently filed a $130 million lawsuit. Targeted were makers of the
``Doom,'' ``Quake'' and ``Mortal Kombat'' games that the parents
contend influenced the killer. They also sued Time Warner and
Polygram Filmed Entertainment Distribution Inc., whose parent is
Seagram, for releasing ``The Basketball Diaries.'' In the 1995
film, Leonardo DiCaprio plays an adolescent heroin addict who _
during a dream sequence _ uses a pump-action shotgun to blast away
at high school students in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The high school as killing field theme has been recurrent in
recent films aimed at young audiences. In ``Disturbing Behavior,''
a school's picture-perfect teens are actually ``Stepford'' kids
drugged by their parents and a psychiatrist. But raging hormones
drive them batty, and the noninfected kids have to kill them off.
When the teachers in ``The Faculty'' turn out to be aliens, the
students have to destroy them. A pair of juvenile serial killers
replace the usual bogeyman in the tongue-in-cheek thriller
``Scream.'' Bad girls form a killer clique in ``Jawbreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   In each of these movies, though, elements of irony or the
fantastic create a sense of distance. Everyone is disposable _ even
Drew Barrymore, the big-name teen attraction who, surprise, gets
killed off in the opening sequence of ``Scream.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, kids get senselessly wiped out in real life, too.
And irony isn't bullet-proof.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Bob Longino contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
