<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR GROUND TROOPS IN KOSOVO GAINS MOMENTUM 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prospects for the commitment of ground troops in
Kosovo appeared to firm up Wednesday as allied officials suggested
they will seek authorization for an invasion plan when NATO leaders
meet Friday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing in London, British Defense Secretary George
Robertson said the planning for a ground commitment would be an
``integral part'' of deliberations at the three-day NATO summit.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart also said President
Clinton would support updating plans for a ground invasion if
NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, asks for it, as
reports have indicated he will.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of a ground invasion came as the long-awaited U.S. Army
Apache attack helicopters, accompanied by 4,000 support troops and
ground missile launchers, began arriving in Tirana, Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also announced Wednesday that it would bring
some refugees to the United States temporarily to relieve pressure
on nations such as Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The 24 helicopters along with an undisclosed number of Black
Hawk helicopters and other support aircraft are expected to launch
within a few days the first low-level attacks on Serb forces in
Kosovo since the allied bombardment of Yugoslavia began 29 days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign continued Wednesday with some of the heaviest
attacks yet on the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade. Allied missiles
struck at Milosevic's Socialist Party headquarters, which Robertson
described as ``one of the nerve centers of the machine which plans
the killing in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   At least three missiles hit the 23-story government building,
which also houses television and radio stations owned and
controlled by Milosevic's daughter Marija.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic by now can be under no illusion that we mean
serious, unrelenting business. We are now striking at the very
heart of his bloodstained regime, and we'll do so again and again
and again,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO attacks Tuesday night and Wednesday focused again on
hitting communications relay sites, oil refineries, fuel and
ammunition supply facilities and factories suspected of producing
military-related goods.
</P>
<P>
   Allied planes also destroyed the last remaining bridge over the
Danube River at Novi Sad, Yugoslavia's second largest city,
severing the country's rail connection with Hungary and the rest of
Europe. Five other bridges were damaged along military resupply
routes into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO strikes at the high-rise that houses Yugoslavia's
ruling party was aimed at taking out what alliance spokesman Jamie
Shea called Milosevic's ``propaganda machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if NATO was trying to target buildings where Milosevic
might be hiding in an effort ``to take him out,'' Shea said that
killing Milosevic is not an objective of the allied assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are certainly targeting the power structures that make
him what he is. We will go after anything which is used to plan, to
conceive, to direct what is a campaign of repression in Kosovo,''
Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, if I can take the image of the human body, we
will go for the brain as much as we'll go for the fingertips.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of an effort to intensify the air campaign, the Pentagon
awarded the Boeing Co. a $41 million contract Wednesday to convert
95 nuclear versions of air-launch cruise missiles to conventional
use. The move is designed to address a shortage of conventional
cruise missiles, which are no longer being produced because a new
generation of the weapon is being developed.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO allies also continued relief efforts aimed at feeding
and caring for over a half million Kosovar refugees driven from
their homes into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro. Thousands have
been given sanctuary in Western countries, and Vice President Al
Gore announced in a visit to Ellis Island in New York that up to
20,000 of them will be airlifted to the United States to be housed
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. plan had originally called for placing them at Guantanamo
Bay naval base in Cuba, but that was scrapped when humanitarian
workers said it would amount to putting them in a guarded detention
center.
</P>
<P>
   Once here, the refugees will be allowed to apply for political
asylum. But Gore stressed that most would likely return to Kosovo
once the hostilities there have ended.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
