<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-21 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TO WELCOME 20,000 KOSOVAR REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration opened the door
Wednesday for as many as 20,000 Kosovar refugees to seek shelter in
the United States, dumping an earlier plan to confine the displaced
victims of Serb aggression at a US naval base in Guantanamo, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees, a fraction of the 600,000 who have been driven
from their homes in Kosovo, will be moved from temporary shelters
in neighboring Balkan countries and matched with relatives or
sponsors throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy, announced by Vice President Al Gore at Ellis
Island, was developed after concerns were raised that images of the
United States confining the refugees to a military base in Cuba
would create a propaganda boon for Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic. Human rights advocates also criticized the prisonlike
conditions the refugees would endure at Guantanamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will accept, on the American mainland, up to 20,000 of the
hurting and homeless Kosovar refugees, those with close family ties
in America, and those who are particularly vulnerable,'' Gore said
in a speech marking the 50th anniversary of the NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   On the 29th day of NATO air strikes, there was increasing
discussion among NATO allies about the possibility of deploying
ground troops against the Serb forces. The prospect of a ground war
is expected to be a major topic when NATO's anniversary summit
starts Friday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But US officials said they continue to oppose the initiative, as
do leaders of several other NATO nations. And Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen warned against raising expectations of NATO troops
invading Kosovo. ``If we were to threaten ground forces and not
have the consensus for it,'' Cohen told a House Appropriations
panel, ``it would be an empty threat.''
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments Wednesday as the Balkans
remained mired in conflict:
</P>
<P>
   --Evidence mounted that Milosevic's forces are expanding their
``clean-and-sweep'' operation against ethnic Albanians beyond
Kosovo to Yugoslavia's sister republic of Montenegro. The Serb push
into Montenegro, increasing the danger of the conflict spreading,
raised red flags among NATO members. Secretary of State Madeleine
K. Albright told the House International Relations Committee that
the United States and NATO have warned Milosevic ``that incursions
into Montenegro would have serious consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   --NATO expanded the focus of allied air strikes from military
targets to centers of Milosevic's political power. In Belgrade,
missiles hammered the national headquarters of Milosevic's
Socialist Party of Serbia. Transmitters for television and radio
stations owned by Milosevic's daughter also were hit, as were other
businesses and political offices run by allies of Milosevic. ``We
are now striking at the very heart of his bloodstained regime,''
British Defense Secretary George Robertson said at a briefing in
London.
</P>
<P>
   --Milosevic and his associates expressed continued defiance of
the NATO forces. But in an interview to be broadcast Thursday night
by a Houston television station, Milosevic said the three American
soldiers who have spent three weeks as prisoners of war in
Yugoslavia are not in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very old people with a long tradition of respecting
POWs,'' Milosevic said, according to a news release from KHOU-TV in
Houston. ``Nothing will happen to them. They are being treated
well. They are healthy. The Geneva Convention will be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   --Clinton's approval rating dropped to 56 percent, its lowest in
nearly two years, as a result of the attack on Yugoslavia,
according to a poll conducted by the Pew Research Center. Although
Clinton's favorability rating remains relatively high, the figure
never dropped below 59 percent during the Monica S. Lewinsky
scandal, including the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United States prepared to expand its involvement
in the conflict by dispatching low-flying Apache helicopters to
strike Serb ground troops and armored units. Twelve Apaches arrived
Wednesday in Tirana, Albania, after a lengthy delay caused by
stormy weather. Twelve more of the attack helicopters are on the
way.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, running short on cruise missiles, Wednesday
awarded Boeing Co. a $41.3 million contract to convert 95 nuclear
versions of the air-launched missiles to carry conventional
warheads. The American stockpile of cruise missiles has dropped
below 100 after scores have been fired on Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
   At Ellis Island, Gore used the symbolic backdrop of the historic
immigration center to say the 20,000 Kosovar refugees will remain
in the United States ``until they are able to return home safely.''
The refugees are expected to enter the country through air bases on
the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   By relocating the displaced ethnic Albanians to the US mainland,
however, the Clinton administration will give the refugees the
opportunity to apply for political asylum in the United States,
which they could not have done at the naval base on the Cuban
island.
</P>
<P>
   International relief agencies expressed growing concern about
the potential exodus of an additional 850,000 ethnic Albanians from
Kosovo as Serb troops continue their campaign of alleged genocide
and ``ethnic cleansing'' in the separatist Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest worry we have,'' said J. Brian Atwood,
director of the US Agency for International Development, the
nation's top relief agency, after touring a refugee center
Wednesday in Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said Albania, which has taken in more than 370,000
refugees, lacks the infrastructure to help any more, despite its
willingness.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, which is providing temporary shelter to more than
135,000 refugees, is ``at a breaking point,'' Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Hillary Rodham Clinton appealed for private
contributions to help ease the crisis. ``We cannot let this
conflict derail the social, economic and political progress that
Macedonia and its neighbors have struggled so hard and for so long
to achieve,'' she said in a speech to humanitarian relief groups.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, tensions remained high in neighboring Montenegro,
where Yugoslav Army forces directed by Milosevic have targeted some
of the 75,000 refugees from Kosovo. The Yugoslav troops are vying
with the state police, who are loyal to the anti-Milosevic
government of Montenegro, for control of the republic, although the
conflict has yet to explode into open, armed confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is widespread fear that the crisis could erupt into
a civil war or military coup. Tensions are highest at key border
crossings between Montenegro and Croatia. ``These are sensitive and
potentially dangerous places,'' said Luigj Juncaj, the Montenegrin
minister for minority rights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report
from Tirana, Albania. Milligan reported from Montenegro; Hohler
reported from Washington. Wire service material was used in its
preparation.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2049EDT &QL; 
