<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RESTRAINT-BOS &LR;      04-21 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RESTRAINT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TV STATIONS AGREE TO CURTAIL HOSTAGE COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In an unusual move aimed at limiting the risk during
hostage situations, Boston TV stations have quietly negotiated an
agreement with Boston and State Police that will restrict live
coverage when hostages or armed suspects are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Under a draft of the arrangement obtained by The Boston Globe,
the TV stations agree that they will not ``air either critical
ground or aerial videotape until after the incident has been
resolved.'' According to Margot Hill, spokeswoman for the Boston
Police Department, that means refraining from live broadcasts of
footage that could jeopardize a rescue attempt by revealing police
movements or hostages' whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the agreement will restrict Boston's six news
stations to a single pool camera on the ground and a single
helicopter camera during what police call ``critical incidents.''
The guidelines were drafted before the shootings at a Colorado
school Tuesday again spotlighted how tricky the media's role can be
during a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Boston stations agreed not to attempt to contact
suspects ``without the guidance of the chief hostage negotiator''
or to otherwise ``interfere with the negotiation process'' during
hostage situations.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the TV stations will be granted a location ``within
the inner perimeter'' of the action for the pool camera, and will
receive ``lots of access, lots of informational updates'' from
police, according to Hill. Police will also hold informational
meetings with employees of each news station to explain how they
operate in the field during crisis situations.
</P>
<P>
   The draft of the agreement also contains a clause that will
expand access for newspaper photographers. It states that a pool
photographer for the print media ``shall also be given an
advantageous shot.'' Currently, police can keep photographers
behind designated lines during crisis situations.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Southwick, director of photography for the Globe, said
``the intention of the agreement is positive. Under ideal
conditions it will give news organizations, including our own, more
ability to cover these situations.'' He added: ``The greater issue
is that we don't want in any way to interfere with public safety
doing their jobs or endanger anyone's life.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed Wednesday by news directors at Boston
TV stations. They said they accept the agreement and itscurbs on
live coverage _ which will only apply when hostages are being held
or armed suspects have barricaded themselves _ because they believe
the restrictions will mean less danger for hostages and bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them as guidelines for safety,'' said Peter Brown, news
director at WBZ-Ch. 4. ``My issue is that no story is more
important than someone's life.'' Agreed Mark Berryhill, news
director at WHDH-Ch.7: ``It makes a lot of sense, with times
changing. There have been some situations that have arisen that we
want to prevent in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But some questioned the arrangement. Bob Steele, director of the
ethics program at the Poynter Institute for Media Studies in
Florida, said that while broadcast journalists need ``meaningful
guidelines'' for their coverage of crises, the ``danger'' of the
Boston accord is that ``journalists also have a responsibility to
cover law enforcement as an independent watchdog.''
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement is the outgrowth of a meeting between
officials of the Boston, Brookline and State Police, TV news
directors, and newspaper photography supervisors. Media executives
emphasized that the agreement is voluntary and that they are not
required to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the TV stations will agree to the curbs
underscores the degree to which, in an era of live saturation
coverage, they want to avoid the pitfalls that abound for
broadcasters every time a school explodes in violence or hostages
are seized.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are made-for-television dramas,'' said Robert Lichter,
director of the Washington-based Center on Media and Public
Affairs. ``The problem is that reporters tend to become actors in
these dramas.''
</P>
<P>
   That happened again during the Columbine High School shootings
on Tuesday. Denver TV stations drew criticism Wednesday for
televising SWAT team movements and the escape routes of terrified
students, and for broadcasting interviews of students trapped
inside the school. ``There are some lessons that can be learned
from looking at (Tuesday),'' said Candy Altman, news director at
WCVB-Ch. 5. ``We all need to take a deep breath in this business
and think about the impact of everything we put on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Last February, before Berryhill arrived at Channel 7, the
station ignited controversy during a Salem hostage situation by
reporting that the suspect was in the home of a prison guard _ a
fact police did not want publicized. Last May a radio station and
newspaper in Florida drew criticism for calling a gunman holed up
in a gas station with a hostage and interviewing him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
