<HEADER>
A8078 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-WRONGKLEBOLD-CO     04-21 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-WRONGKLEBOLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado man's name same as school shooting suspects
 &HT;    By George Orbanek
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday, April 20, dawned like any other morning for the Larry
Klebold family of Broomfield, Colo. For Larry and wife Karen, it
was another day tending to the family business, the Klebold
Consulting Group, a construction financial consulting business. For
sons Cory and Mason, another school day awaited in the Broomfield
Public School system, roughly mid-way between Boulder and the
suburbs of north Denver.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, the family?s life had been knocked askew, the
result of being caught in the intersection between the tragic
events which occurred at Littleton?s Columbine High School and the
rush of the national and international press to cover the bloodiest
act of school violence in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's authorities identified the two suspected gunmen as
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, both of whom were said to have
committed suicide after leaving 13 students and teachers dead in
Tuesday's shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   The Dylan Klebold of Littleton's Columbine High School is not
related to the Larry Klebold family of Broomfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've since learned that I'm apparently the only Klebold listed
in the Colorado telephone directory,'' Larry Klebold told areporter
Wednesday afternoon. ``My telephone hasn't stopped ringing since
this whole thing started.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Broomfield's Klebold family has since been given a
personal insight into the workings of the modern media hive.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold said he was telephoned by The New York Times twice. He
ticked off a lengthy laundry lists of other media interests
demanding to know if he was the father of one of the two suspected
gunmen. They included, among others, the New York Daily News, Fox
News Network, all of the Denver television stations and most of the
city's printed press, ``Dateline NBC,'' ``Inside Edition,''
reporters from Melbourne, Australia, and Toronto, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best one was the guy from ?Larry King Live,? `` said
Klebold. He said that the representative from King?s evening cable
talk show expressed all manner of sympathy for the family's
presumed anguish over the loss of a son and quickly added, ``We're
going to be in Denver
</P>
<P>
   tomorrow and if I were you I really wouldn?t do interviews with
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The family also has had to cope with a number of harassing phone
calls. Klebold said, ``I got a call at 3 o'clock in the morning
from someone who says, `Are you the guy who raised this bastard' ``
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday afternoon, the Larry Klebold family of Broomfield
did not know that a Dylan
</P>
<P>
   Klebold, alleged mass murderer, even existed. ``I want out of
the loop,'' Larry Klebold said.
</P>
<P>
   Orbanek is the editor and publisher of the Daily Sentinel in
Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
