<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SANCTUARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME KOSOVARS MAY BE SENT TO MASSACHUSETTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton's administration decision Wednesday to
allow 20,000 Kosovar refugees to settle temporarily in the United
States, a political about-face from a prior plan to put them at
Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, could bring a significant number of the
ethnic Albanians to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   At least 15,000 Albanian-Americans, and possibly many more, live
in the Bay State, according to Anthony Athanas, the founder of
Anthony's Pier Four restaurant, who was born in Albania and came to
the United States when he was six years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to do anything,'' said Athanas, who spoke with
President Clinton about the Kosovo situation when Clinton visited
Massachusetts last week.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also demonstrates that the administration believes
the war in the Balkans is going to last longer than originally
anticipated, analysts said. The new policy of bringing the refugees
to homes throughout the United States probably means that the
Kosovars' hope of returning to their homeland is, at best, many
months away.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official said that under the family
reunification program, ethnic Albanians in camps in Macedonia who
want to relocate to the United States will be interviewed,
connected with American relatives, undergo a medical screening, and
be processed as refugees, or persons who have been persecuted in
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   With refugee status, they will be eligible for a host of
social-welfare benefits, including food stamps, and entitled to
apply for permanent residency in the United States after one year.
</P>
<P>
   The 20,000 refugees will include some who don't have American
relatives but are deemed ``in vulnerable circumstances'' by State
Department and immigration officials, said Maria Cardona, a
spokeswoman for the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees who volunteer will come only from camps in
Macedonia, a State Department official said, ``because we want to
relieve the strain there first.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration initially opposed having the refugees come to
the US mainland, saying that might give the impression Washington
was legitimizing the ``ethnic cleansing'' policy of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of housing the refugees at Guantanamo prompted
harsh criticism from human rights advocates who said the Kosovars
should be allowed to come to the US mainland rather than a
prison-like facility on a naval base.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a welcome change in policy,'' said Sherle
Schwenninger, a senior fellow at the World Policy Institute. He had
criticized the original plan of using Guantanamo, saying images of
refugees behind barbed wire would be a public relations disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing the US is good at is opening itself up to
displaced people and refugees and immigrants,'' Schwenninger said.
</P>
<P>
   Families interested in hosting refugees will be able to call a
toll-free number that should be set up Thursday, the State
Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they were not sure where the bulk of the
relocations would be, and they expected it would take several weeks
to get the refugee airlift under way.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who has advocated bringing the
refugees to the United States, said: ``This action is certainly far
better than housing them in Guantanamo. It is important for
Americans to be at the forefront of the international effort to
meet the needs of the refugees and ease their suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Azem Tachi of Worcester, Mass., a leader of the
Albanian-American community there, said he believes as many as 300
to 500 refugees could find temporary homes there and applauded the
decision by Clinton to allow them to come to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good because these people might be able to work right
away and not be stuck in camps, and children can go to school. They
get back to life. It will be a big change for them. If things
straighten out in Kosovo, people will be elated to go back if they
want,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tachi said there are about 2,600 residents of Albanian heritage
in the Worcester area and many are willing to help. A group there,
the New England Albanian Relief Organization (NEARO), has been
shipping food and clothing to Kosovo for years, he said, but even
more in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe reporter Andy Dabilis contributed to this article from
Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
