<HEADER>
A8099 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS &LR;      04-21 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CUBS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ If Wrigley Field ever decides to succumb to the trend of
selling naming rights, the Astros might suggest Jiffy Lube or
Tune-Up Masters.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After all, nothing gets the Astros' motor going faster than a
trip to the Friendly Confines.
</P>
<P>
   To say the Astros' offense is clicking on all cylinders might be
an understatement. The crack mechanics known as the Chicago Cubs'
pitching staff may as well have installed rocket boosters on the
Astros' bats, which revved up to the tune of 13 hits in a 10-3
blowout Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell was the driving force behind Wednesday's effort,
belting three home runs and overtaking Jimmy Wynn as the Astros'
all-time long-ball king. In typical Bagwell fashion, he tried to
downplay his accomplishments, choosing instead to focus on the
team's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just up there swinging and trying to hit the ball
hard,'' said Bagwell, whose 225 career homers are two more than
Wynn had as an Astro. ``I was just trying to do something to help
the ballclub. It was a good win for our team; it's nice to see our
offense starting to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   That tends to happen here.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have won five consecutive games at Wrigley Field,
outscoring the Cubs by a combined 53-17. Bagwell, who hit three
homers in a game for the second time (he did it against the Dodgers
in 1994), also matched his career high with six RBIs and extended
his hitting streak to 10 games _ the longest for an Astro this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole thing is driving in runs,'' he said. ``That's why I
liked the second one the best.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth three-homer game in Astros history, Bagwell hit a
solo blast in the first, a three-run shot in the third and a
two-run bomb in the seventh. He struck out in the fifth and
grounded out to third in the ninth, missing a chance to tie the
major-league record of four homers in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting on Baggy after he didn't get a homer in that
last at-bat,'' shortstop Ricky Gutierrez cracked. ``He had a heck
of a day.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was hardly a one-man effort. Every Astro who had an
at-bat _ with the exception of pitcher Shane Reynolds and pinch
hitter Alex Diaz _ got at least one hit, with Gutierrez and Carl
Everett collecting two apiece.
</P>
<P>
   That was more than enough offense for Reynolds, who scattered
eight hits over seven innings and held the Cubs to two runs _ quite
an accomplishment considering the trouble he dodged over the first
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who lead the National League with a .306 team
batting average, have totaled 45 hits and 28 runs over their last
three games. Needless to say, concerns about their once-struggling
offense have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was just a matter of time before we started putting
up some runs,'' said Everett, who has hit in 13 of the Astros' 14
games. ``The only thing that has been missing is the key hit _
getting guys in from second and third. Now, we've started to do a
better job of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's three-run homer in the third came with two out. The
long blast ended up on Waveland Avenue and gave the Astros a 4-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs had runners in scoring position in each of the first
three innings against Reynolds, but they weren't able to break
through until the third. Lance Johnson and Mickey Morandini led off
the inning with doubles, the second of which scored Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   A botched rundown play and a walk put Reynolds in a bases-loaded
jam with nobody out. But unlike in his previous outing _ he allowed
the Cardinals to score five runs in the fourth inning _ Reynolds
minimized the damage, allowing just one more run on a sacrifice fly
by Glenallen Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stay away from the big inning,'' Reynolds said.
``We saw that in my last start. They had a chance to score a lot of
runs in the third inning, but I made some good pitches and got out
of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (3-1) retired 14 of the next 18 batters he faced after
walking Mark Grace in the third, effectively shutting down the
Cubs' offense until the torrid Hill (.484, five homers, 14 RBIs)
greeted reliever Doug Henry with a leadoff home run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting a pair of homers off Cubs starter Scott Sanders
(0-2), Bagwell decided to pick on reliever Rodney Myers. His
two-run homer off Myers highlighted the Astros' three-run seventh.
Derek Bell had an RBI single in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored three more runs in the eighth inning, two on
Craig Biggio's fifth double of the season and the other on an RBI
single by Tony Eusebio. By that time, Bagwell already had made sure
there would be no comeback for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the man today,'' Astros third baseman Ken Caminiti
said. ``Three home runs in a game _ that's called earning your
money. He can hit, man. He's just one of those guys who can hit in
his sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bagwell had plenty to sleep on after Wednesday's heroics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
