<SLUG> BC-NETWORK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Rivalry Comes to Online Addresses
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Internet domain names _ the cyber equivalent of real estate _ got
its first wave of new brokers yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   America Online and France Telecom were among five high-tech
companies selected to compete with Network Solutions, the U.S.
government-sanctioned company in charge of assigning such popular
Web addresses as .com, .net and .org.
</P>
<P>
   A second group of 29 companies led by AT&AMP;T Corp. is expected to
follow them and dole out popular Web addresses as early as this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The long-anticipated move is designed to give consumers and
businesses the benefits of a competitive market for online
addresses as part of the government's hands-off Net policy. They
will have more firms to choose from and mostly likely pay less for
their services.
</P>
<P>
   The decision also provides a much needed cash infusion for NSI,
which will gain revenues from rivals who will pay fees to access
NSI's computer systems and list addresses on its database.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, AOL is expected to hawk personalized Web
addresses to its 17 million subscribers as a digital vanity license
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's announcement is the initial phase in a ``major
milestone in the joint efforts of the public and private sectors to
bring Internet users the benefits of real competition in
registration services,'' said Esther Dyson, interim chairman of the
nonprofit Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers
(ICANN).
</P>
<P>
   The companies chosen to compete with NSI by ICANN, a group in
charge of privatizing the Internet, include Australia's Melbourne
IT, Register.com and the nonprofit Internet Council of Registrars.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, ICANN was formed by the U.S. government to phase out
NSI's exclusive hold on so-called top-level Web suffixes that
stretches back to 1993. Those domain names are considered prime
real estate destinations for selling goods and conducting business
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The move delighted new cyber-landlords, such as AOL. ``We're
committed to an open, competitive environment on the Internet,''
AOL spokesman Jim Whitney said. ``There is a tremendous level of
commercial interest in opening the market for domain names
services.''
</P>
<P>
   The first wave of companies selected to compete against NSI will
undergo a two-month trial, starting Monday. When the two-month
trial is completed in late June, AT&AMP;T Corp. and 28 other companies
are expected to be allowed to compete against NSI, which has been
expanding its international business in anticipation of competition
in the new market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Domain-name services are still in an early age,'' NSI
spokesman Christopher Clough said. ``There will be 100 million
top-level names registered ending in .com, .org and .net in the
next several years. We couldn't do it all and welcome the help.''
</P>
<P>
   NSI will continue to maintain a master database of addresses.
The company will receive at least $9 for each domain name its
competitors register and will charge test registrars a one-time
licensing fee of $10,000 for software. Test registrars will also
pay a $5,000 annual accreditation fee to ICANN for administrative
costs.
</P>
<P>
   NSI charges $70 for registering a Web address for the first two
years, and $35 for each additional 12 months. But those prices are
likely to fall with a raft of competitors on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Herndon, Va., company has been the only place to
go for addresses ending with .com, .org or .net. It has registered
three-fourths of the world's 5.5 million online addresses,
parlaying its government-backed monopoly on domain names into $93
million in sales last year. The company, which went public in
September 1997, has a market value of $2.84 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NSI's volatile stock soared more than 50 percent yesterday on
the news, to $92 per share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
