<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-COLUMBINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER SCHOOL HAS GOOD REPUTATION FOR SATS AND SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take to move within 30 minutes.) 
 (nk) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Columbine High School is like a lot of
suburban high schools, proud of its high SAT scores, proud of its
winning sports teams. Last Friday the school had a giant pep rally,
followed on Saturday night by a junior-senior prom for which
parents had raised $50,000 for a no-alcohol after-prom party.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of school where a teacher last year assigned her
students to read about the shooting at a high school in Jonesboro,
Ark., to help them understand the real world because nothing like
that could ever happen here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we lived in a bubble,'' said Josiah Pina, an
18-year-old senior who played on the school's championship football
team, known as the Rebels.
</P>
<P>
   And Columbine High School is like most high schools, divided
into various groups, from the jocks and preps who rule the halls to
stoners, skaters and freaks. And at Columbine there was also the
Trenchcoat Mafia, many of whom have chafed at the dominance and
arrogance of the jocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cliques all over the place,'' said Meg Hains, a
16-year-old sophomore. ``You can't go to high school without
cliques.''
</P>
<P>
   Hains and her friends Jessica Jones, 15, and Erin Brinkley, 15,
who gathered outside the high school on Wednesday with hundreds of
other students, classified themselves as their own tiny group,
``the individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the outsiders,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``individuals'' shun clothes bought at the Gap and
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, the labels favored by the jocks and preps.
``We vowed we would never wear Abercrombie,'' said Jones, adding
that she could not afford the $30 shirts and $25 hats even if she
did like them.
</P>
<P>
   While Columbine is not as affluent as some other schools in the
area, there are many students who can afford the labels, and who
drive expensive cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``One jock has a Hummer,'' said Jones, whose father owns a candy
store, and who does not have her own car. ``He totaled one Hummer,
and his dad bought him another.''
</P>
<P>
   As she complained about how the jocks and preps looked down on
her and her friends, Emily Hackett _ dressed in a pale-green Gap
shirt, Levi Silvertab jeans and American Eagle sandals _ came up
and wrapped her arms around her.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `Why do you talk to her,' '' Emily said. ``I
say, `She's cool, she's my bud.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Glancing toward Hackett, Brinkley said, ``There's some nice
preps.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Hackett said, a lot of Columbine students do own cars.
``I'm getting a purple Jeep when I turn 16 in three months,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Resentments and jealousies are as much a part of adolescence as
first dates and acne, and whatever divisions there were inside the
school before Tuesday, the members of the different groups stood
side by side on the grass Wednesday, weeping together, hugging and
exchanging survivors' stories. Individuals, preps, jocks, freaks
and skaters, they all seemed nice. They were polite to the throng
of reporters, patiently answering the same questions over and over.
Even in their shock and grief, many of the students were eager to
talk about their school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows Columbine in Colorado,'' said Amy Staley, 15,
who is on the track team and just made the cheerleading squad. ``We
always have the first or highest SAT scores in Jefferson County.
The reason so many kids were in the library yesterday is because
they care about their grades. Everyone is always going in there to
read.''
</P>
<P>
   Staley's friend, Kim Mohracher, 15, who was standing nearby,
chimed in: ``Fifty kids in our school have straight A's. Over 200
have a 3.8.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohracher happens to have straight A's, as do two of her friends
who were huddled with her and Staley on Wednesday, Brooke Allison,
15, and Nicole Bucci, who is a star on the tennis team.
</P>
<P>
   As for safety at Columbine, the students say it never occurred
to them to worry. Metal detectors? Those are for urban schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
