<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Head of High-Tech Magazine Hopes Internet Stocks
Will  Rebound 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Tony Perkins, the head of the high-tech investment magazine Red
Herring, hopes that giant hissing sound on Monday wasn't the air
going out of Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   That's funny, considering he's predicting their demise in a
book, ``The Internet Bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   But his book isn't due out until August. So when the Dow Jones
Internet index dropped nearly 19 percent on Monday, he got an
anxious call from his publisher, Harper Business Books.
</P>
<P>
   After all, who would buy a book called, ``After the Bubble: The
Internet Soap Stain Left on the Floor?''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins is keeping his fingers crossed for Net stocks to
continue swimmingly until his book comes out, at which point he
hopes that, uh, something ``hits the fan.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like potentially dangerous talk for a businessman in
Perkins' position. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _The Herring is built on providing information about the
intersection of technology and money.
</P>
<P>
   _The Herring is retooling for the Internet. It plans to triple
its online staff and add subscriptions, services and e-commerce to
its existing banner ad and sponsorship business.
</P>
<P>
   _The Herring is likely to have its own public stock offering
sometime next year, although nothing has been formally decided.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins certainly is covering his bases: His business is staked
on Internet market success, while his book is staked on Internet
market failure.
</P>
<P>
   From his corner office on the ninth floor of the renovated
Hamm's Brewery building, Perkins looks down upon San Francisco's
Multimedia Gulch _ on dozens if not hundreds of companies hoping to
cash in on Internet dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Like those entrepreneurs, he is optimistic about the Net.
</P>
<P>
   But Perkins, who was a banker before he became a journalist,
remains a contrarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ain't real,'' he says. ``Show me the money.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SELLING SALON: &LR;  Technology journalists love checking the worth
of their erstwhile brethren who have jumped to the digital world.
(Some say those snooping journalists are jealous, but I would never
hang that label on them.)
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com, the San Francisco online media company, can't talk
about its intent to sell stock to the public because it's in an SEC
mandated ``quiet period.'' So, we'll let Salon's SEC filing do the
talking.
</P>
<P>
   David Talbot, the company's chairman and editor in chief, earned
$130,312 last year and received options to buy 175,000 shares.
Talbot already holds 600,000 shares. Salon expects to sell shares
for between $10.50 and $13.50; at the low end of that range,
Talbot's existing shares are worth $6.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot is the former arts and features editor of the San
Francisco Examiner, and many of his old colleagues are with him at
Salon as vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   They include Vice President for Business Development Andrew
Ross, a former Examiner foreign and national editor, who holds
280,000 options; design director Mignon Khargie, a former Examiner
graphic artist, 260,000 options; executive editor Gary Kamiya, a
former Examiner senior editor, 240,000 options; and senior editor
for technology Scott Rosenberg, a former Examiner theater critic
and technology columnist, 100,000 options.
</P>
<P>
   At $10.50, a share, everyone with more than 100,000 shares is an
instant millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Other former Examiner staffers already scored big on Wall Street
at CBS Marketwatch.com. Marketwatch's Larry Kramer and Thom
Calandra (the Examiner's former editor and business columnist,
respectively) are paper multimillionaires thanks to their firm's
successful sale of stock earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapering never paid so well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY IN THE WELL: &LR;  Another tidbit from Salon.com's SEC filing:
Salon forked over 4.4 percent of the company to buy pioneering
Internet community the WELL two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   If Salon goes public at $10.50, that stock would be worth $4.87
million _ a premium price for a company revealed in the filing to
have lost $69,000 on revenues of $484,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHITHER WIRED DIGITAL: &LR;  Wired Digital has hit another speed
bump as it tries to become part of the Lycos Web portal. The sale
should have closed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the companies announced another delay. The deal first
announced in October will now close in June, they said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For perspective, consider that America Online announced it
would buy Netscape in November for $10 billion _ one month after
the Wired Digital-Lycos announcement _ and it consummated that
merger last month.
</P>
<P>
   The latest snag in the $83 million deal for Wired Digital was
the Securities and Exchange Commission's request for more
information. Lycos filed a new document with the SEC last week, and
Wired officials say it could take a few weeks to hear if they've
satisfied the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The filing reveals that Wired founders Louis Rossetto and Jane
Metcalfe opposed the deal when it was first brought to the board of
directors. Published reports on Salon.com and TheStreet.com
revealed that Wired Digital's original investors were fighting with
the company's current big shareholders over who would get how much
in the Lycos deal.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding matters, Lycos is battling to convince its own
shareholders to let it merge with USA Networks, in what's turned
into a messy public fight.
</P>
<P>
   At least one person, who would only agree to be identified as a
source close to the Lycos-Wired Digital deal, said the deal may not
have the votes among Wired shareholders &UR;  &LR; to go forward, that the
shareholders are continuing to squabble, and that the SEC may not
sign off on the latest filings so readily.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of dissent, which has dogged the company for months,
upset Wired Digital spokesman Andrew de Vries. ``I am so tired of
this going on,'' he said. ``Until you have a stockholder vote, it's
all hearsay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any one person can say the deal is in
jeopardy,'' de Vries said. ``Everyone is fully committed to having
this deal close.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The San Francisco Chronicle.
Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd(AT SIGN)sfgate.com,
call (415) 777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
