<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNET-SFCHRON &LR;      04-21 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Cnet Beats Forecasts in `Blowout Quarter'   By Dan Fost 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Cnet Inc., the San Francisco publisher of computer Web sites,
reported a strong quarter yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The company doubled its revenues, beat analysts' estimates for
its earnings and announced a 2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cnet had a blowout quarter,'' said Danny Rimer, an Internet
analyst with Hambrecht and Quist.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months that ended March 31, the company reported
net income of &UR;  &LR; $23 million (61 cents per share), compared to a loss
of $5.7 million in the same quarter last year. Revenues grew 101
percent, to $19.6 million from $9.8 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Income exceeded revenues because the company reaped a $19.9
million windfall when BuyDirect.com _ in which Cnet was a
significant shareholder _ was acquired by Beyond.com.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the profit from that sale, or the write-off of
$300,000 in expenses from a small Cnet acquisition, Cnet earnings
were $3.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was the company's fourth straight quarter to show a profit,
still a relative rarity among Internet firms.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet attributed its success to the growing popularity of the
company's Web sites. It writes &UR;  &LR; news and reviews about technology
products and provides a way for readers to link directly to
companies selling the products. Cnet makes money by selling
advertising and by charging companies for every business lead
generated on a Cnet site.
</P>
<P>
   Those leads have grown, from 90,000 per day in December to
104,000 per day in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become a place that a lot of technology companies feel
they have to be,'' said Halsey Minor, Cnet's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   While sales in Cnet's first quarter have typically dropped off
from the previous quarter, Minor said this year they remained
strong. This week, Cnet also announced a deal bringing more ads
from top computer-makers Dell, Compaq, Gateway and Acer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Cnet's earnings come from its online business, but
yesterday's report revealed that its cable television programs also
brought in a slight profit, even as revenue slipped to $1.7 million
from $1.8 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet announced its earnings after the close of trading
yesterday. As tech stocks continued to rally from Monday's slump,
Cnet closed the day up $14.25 at $119.75.
</P>
<P>
   The stock split, scheduled for May 28, will affect shareholders
who own Cnet stock as of May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Along with many other Internet stocks, shares in Cnet have
soared this year. Since the start of the year, the stock is up
nearly 400 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the stock rose in part on rumors that some larger
company could acquire Cnet, Minor dispelled such talk. ``There's a
lot of growth ahead for the company,'' he said. ``Our shareholders
are better suited by the company remaining independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that in the quarter, Cnet bought four smaller companies,
Minor said, ``I see us more as an `acquirer' than an `acquiree.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rimer, the analyst, agreed. ``There really is no need to be
consolidated. They will be able to enjoy being independent for a
long time,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
