A8109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-CNN22-COX     04-21 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CNN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN taps local TV to get inside scoop
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite scores of correspondents scattered throughout
the Balkans, tons of state-of-the-art equipment and hundreds of
thousands of dollars of satellite time, the most memorable images
on CNN recently have been courtesy of local TV news operations.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, it was the videos of the students fleeing the massacre
at Columbine High School and being reunited with their parents.
Last week, it was the dramatic helicopter rescue in Atlanta of
Ivers Sims from his crane above the raging fire.
</P>
<P>
   While CNN is mostly on its own covering the war in Yugoslavia,
these sudden outbursts of domestic news get instant coverage
because of Newsource, CNN's long-standing arrangement with about
600 TV stations around the country. It also allows CNN to cover a
story before its own reporters can get in place and to switch among
stations _ four, in Denver's case _ sharing footage with CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly critical,'' said Earl Casey, CNN senior vice
president of newsgathering, who coordinated the feeds from Denver
stations Tuesday that CNN aired to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   A Denver TV station called CNN when the story broke, before
anyone knew how serious it was, and Casey started watching KUSA,
the NBC affiliate in Denver, eventually putting it on the air. At
the same time, CNN was arranging with the ABC, CBS and Fox
affiliates to get their signals to Atlanta via satellite and
fiber-optic cable links.
</P>
<P>
   The four signals were eventually fed into the main control room
in CNN Center, where producers could pick and choose which station
to carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking at the monitors, and they see some coverage
they want to go to, or they see some footage that they don't want
to carry,'' Casey said.
</P>
<P>
   Although CNN is based in Atlanta, it relied on local TV for its
coverage of Sims' rescue last week, mainly because the stations
already had news helicopters in the air covering the fast-breaking
story. For a while, WXIA chopper pilot Bruce Erion became the voice
of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   CNN has had news-sharing arrangements with stations virtually
since the network was launched in 1980, but in the early days the
links were more informal. In the mid-'80s, CNN began to package its
coverage as Newsource and sell it to stations for a fee, and part
of those deals was that the stations would share their news footage
with CNN. As another part of Newsource, the stations can use CNN's
live signal or packages; the biggest usage was during the Persian
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The sharing also allows one Newsource station to use another
one's in its broadcast area, using CNN as a connection. Thus
Atlanta's WSB, an ABC affiliate, used footage Tuesday from Denver's
KUSA, an NBC affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The links were also crucial after the Oklahoma City bombing in
1995 and the crash of a Valujet airplane in Florida in 1996, when
local reporters covered the scene until CNN personnel arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing with TV stations with scores of journalists who
know the community down to the intersections,'' Casey said.
``There's an informational and community richness that comes to us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
