<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-PARENT-SIDE22-     04-21 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-PARENT-SIDE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents should reassure kids in wake of horror, experts say
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The tragedy of Littleton, Colo., is a relatively
isolated incident that will never be repeated at the overwhelming
majority of schools, crime statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   But the horror of what happened in Littleton _ and Springfield,
Ore., Jonesboro, Ark., West Paducah, Ky. and Pearl, Miss. _ does
touch kids everywhere. Parents trying to reassure their children in
the wake of Tuesday's shootings must be careful not to say, ``That
could never happen here,'' say mental health and education experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to put this in perspective,'' said Dr. Arthur
Kellerman, director of the Center for Injury Control at Emory
University. ``The chances that this will happen in your child's
school are very, very, very remote. But the chance is not zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to acknowledge that this was a real event, a real
tragedy. Kids are not stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   June Arnette, associate director of the National School Safety
Center, echoed this sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't promise your kids that harm won't come their way,
because you can't make that promise,'' Arnette said. ``But as a
parent, you can provide encouragement. Schools are the safest place
for kids to be, safer than roaming the streets or hanging out at
the mall. We can let our kids know this.''
</P>
<P>
   Massacres may be relatively rare in schools, but violent crimes
aren't, according to a 1997 study by the National Center for
Education Statistics that analyzed violence and disciplinary
problems in U.S. public schools during the 1996-97 school year.
</P>
<P>
   The study concluded that 1 in 10 public schools experienced one
or more serious violent crimes, including murder, rape, suicide,
assault or robbery, during that school term.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 survey by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
found that about 10 percent of high school students had carried
some kind of weapon, such as a gun, knife or club, on school
property within the 30 days before the survey.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8 percent of high school students in the survey said
they had been recently threatened or injured with a weapon on
school property.
</P>
<P>
   Those victimized by violent acts _ and even some who witness
them _ can experience post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Teens are no exception, said behavioral psychologist Stephen
Thomas of Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a normal response in the face of tragedy to be
traumatized,'' Thomas said. ``Those kids who were running out of
that school with their hands above their heads were traumatized.
They all had experienced conditions of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Teens who remain severely frightened or shocked by what they saw
happening in Littleton should seek counseling.
</P>
<P>
   And parents, teachers and counselors should be on lookout for
symptoms of extreme or lasting anxiety over the incident, and help
teens get help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there are kids in metro Atlanta who feel they're
scared, because it conjures up and triggers their own pain and loss
and grief,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
