<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SOLACE22-COX     04-21 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SOLACE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tragedy can teach sanctity of life, love
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They shatter our sense of well-being, our collective
delusion that life is good and fair, and force us to question the
most fundamental characteristic of humanity _ optimism.
</P>
<P>
   That's why tragedies such as the mass killings in Colorado this
week seem to strike such intense fear, confusion _ even grief _ in
nearly everyone, many experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like this, they make us question our fundamental
principles about the world, about life,'' says Dr. Ken Pargament, a
psychologist at Bowling Green State University. ``How do you square
such a tragedy with your hope and belief that the world is a place
that's improving, that people are basically good, and life is a
good thing? You can't.''
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to believe it, but bad things do happen to good
people, every day, every minute, he says. And it's the
headline-grabbing tragedies, not the daily ones, he adds, that
force us to face up to this harsh fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of thing that makes people develop a more
realistic view of the world, a world that is random and
uncertain,'' says Pargament, author of ``Psychology of Religion and
Coping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, religion has offered ways for people to deal
with the downside of life. But these terrible tragedies make even
the religious question their beliefs, their faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Nancy Oliver, minister of children and youth at
Peachtree Christian Church, said such tragedies are hard to deal
with ``because you're dealing with a good God, but at the same
time, you're dealing with the condition of humankind, and humankind
can be pretty evil at times.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she's publishing in her upcoming weekly newsletter an
article on violence prevention that suggests parents help their
children develop problem-solving skills, and model those skills at
home.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Neil Bernstein of Johns Hopkins University, the author
of several books on teen-age rebellion, said parents need to work
on skills, too _ learning to recognize warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not random occurrences,'' he said. ``The public
needs to realize this. These things are well understood, and they
do happen for a reason. We just miss the cues, the warning signs.
Every once in a blue moon, you get some crazy who runs out and does
this. But this is a behavior contagion. It's catching. Other crazy,
disturbed kids are seeing it on TV and saying, `maybe that's what I
should do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe that's why similar incidents have been
occurring for two years or more in the United States. Since Jan.
27, 1997, at least 34 students or faculty members have been killed
in their schools.
</P>
<P>
   The odds remain astronomical against it happening to you or even
someone you know, ``but unfortunately the odds are growing because
of the accessibility of firearms to minors,'' said Olaf Vancura, a
physicist in Las Vegas and expert on odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not natural disasters. People can be influenced by
prior events. There probably is a trend where, once this happens,
it may continue to grow, unlike other disasters. People who might
be inclined to do this may be biased by what they see has
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Karamo Barrow of Clark Atlanta University agreed, and said
history holds little solace for those who believe such events are
aberrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been happening always,'' he said. ``Man's cruelty to
one another is all through the pages of history. Kids are
neglected. People don't have time for life, or even for each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the situation is hopeless, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Pargament said religion offers people a way to deal with
feelings of hopelessness and that beliefs shouldn't be questioned
``because of these events that we cannot hope to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   He thinks tragedies can lead people to a deeper appreciation of
life and a need for religion and spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ted Wardlaw of Central Presbyterian Church met
Wednesday with a clergy group that gathers monthly and said he had
``taken great solace from coming together as a community.''
</P>
<P>
   He said people also can find solace in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are talking right now about the conversations
they want to have with their children, the new initiatives they
want to take as parents, and as part of the community,'' he said.
``To the extent that people who are moved by this tragedy can put
that into action, that has its own power to console.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Wimberly, a professor of Christian education at the
Interdenominational Theological Center in Atlanta, said parents
should carve out times to spend with their children to prevent them
from veering off into dangerous directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That often means turning off the TV, structuring family time
to actually sit and eat together,'' she said. ``A lot of parents
and kids don't know how to relate to one another. They have to sit
down, share with one another and learn how to listen all over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   And prayer also helps, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pargament said tragedies such as airplane crashes, fatal car
wrecks or tornadoes raise deep and profound questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most religions don't say God is a good father who will make
things turn out well for everyone,'' he said. ``It's hard to square
the idea that God really isn't there directing every event in life,
he's not a master puppeteer pulling all the strings.''
</P>
<P>
   He said people should take solace in the notion that ``we on
Earth are the ones responsible for trying to make the world a
better place. We have an obligation to try to make the world more
just, and to create God's kingdom on Earth. It's up to us. That's a
richer religious view of the world than one that just says God is
someone in heaven who ensures that good things happen to good
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of this terrible situation, it pushes some people to
develop a more intricate and richer spirituality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Atlanta's Barrow said the tragedy should alert Americans
to the idea that we need each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are taught love, you give love,'' he said. ``Society is
so highly technological, most families do not have time for each
other. We're all spread out. We ought to learn from this.'' Staff
writers Gayle White and John Blake contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
