<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shootings spark online dialogue
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't have the answers, does anyone?'' asked one participant
in a live chat on America Online focusing on the massacre at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and students from all over the country logged in in
large numbers to AOL's moderated chat area ``The Globe'' (keyword:
AOL Live) to offer observations and try to make some sense out of
the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the participants _ who numbered more than 600 at a time
by day's end _ were online searching for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are called public schools because we, the public, are in
charge,'' wrote one chat participant. ``GET INVOLVED,'' she typed
in large letters.
</P>
<P>
   As parents discussed the relative merits of teaching their
children more spiritual values at home and keeping a vigilant eye
out for loner or isolationist behavior, the teens who were taking
part in the chat spoke more passionately about more personal high
school traumas, such being unable to fit in. They talked about
``cliques'' that ridicule and ostracize perceived outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to high school is a stressful experience for anyone,''
added another member, ``not just the outcasts. And I know plenty of
kids like the Trench Coat Mafia who would bully people better than
the jocks could.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parents tried to blame the techno or heavy metal music
teens listen to, but one teen burst in saying, ``It's not the music
or anything else, it's mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Added a high school English teacher, ``Parents do not seem to
care what their kids do as long as they don't have to deal with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep shouting until someone takes this
seriously,'' said someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AOL's message boards, a popular retreat for AOL's
teen members to talk about things that matter to them were so
jammed by midday Wednesday that access was next to impossible. By
late Wednesday afternoon, more than 100,000 members had posted
comments and opinion.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's Digital City Denver (http://denver.digitalcity.com) also
offered areas for local residents to share their feelings about the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents, as well as Web users from around the country
who wanted to express their feelings to the families in Littleton
posted messages in Digital City's ``Reaction Board.'' Most
expressed their deep sorrow to their neighbors and wondered, along
with the rest of the country, how this could have happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the two killers were considered strange and openly made
threats to some of the students, how come this never came to the
attention of any of the teachers?'' asked a user named Nicky.
</P>
<P>
   Another member wrote, ``We should help the problem kids instead
of ignoring the fact and hope it will go away. Wake up everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But another user stressed the problem was not with teen-age
outcasts. ``This kind of thing did not happen in our high schools
of days past. There were plenty of outcasts then also,'' read one
post. ``There is something more insidious here.''
</P>
<P>
   But what that is remains a mystery to the thousands of members
sharing their thoughts and feelings on AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
