<HEADER>
A8117 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-ASSESS-NY     04-21 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS AND ALIENATION FUEL TEEN-AGERS TO VIOLENCE, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The fact that the worst school shooting in modern
times happened in one of those places where Americans tend to move
because they are seeking good schools _ in this case, Jefferson
County, Colo., one of the fastest-growing areas in the nation _
came as no surprise to Suzanne Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Propelled by grief, Ms. Wilson has spent the last year trying to
make sense of the recent carnage in playgrounds and libraries. She
lost her own daughter, Brittheny, to a pair of middle school
students in Jonesboro, Ark., last year.
</P>
<P>
   She has listened to all the psychiatrists, the school
counselors, the lawyers and specialists in youth violence, and what
she has concluded is that places that might seem least likely to
yield horrific violence are the very places where Americans should
look for answers.
</P>
<P>
   In these towns _ the Springfield, Ore., of new malls and big
houses on one-acre lots, the West Paducah, Ky., of horse trails and
tree forts where Tom Sawyer would be at home _ the details of
school slaughters follow a pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a mixture of heavy firepower, alienated youths whose
threats were largely ignored, and popular culture with a violent
and nihilistic message is predominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children are telling us things and we are not hearing
them,'' Ms. Wilson said. ``The other thing is that, the children in
these cases all have guns. These wouldn't be massacres if they
involved just knives or baseball bats.''
</P>
<P>
   The guns used on Tuesday _ two shotguns, a semi-automatic pistol
and a 9-mm. semi-automatic assault rifle _ would fit in the arsenal
of the culprits in other major school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Whether details about the weapons will alter the debate over gun
control, now focused on laws requiring adults who own guns to keep
them under lock and key, is hard to judge. But on Wednesday, a bill
that would have loosened controls on people who carry concealed
weapons was pulled from the Colorado Legislature, after it had
looked as if it would pass.
</P>
<P>
   The initial sketch of the teen-age shooters _ described by
friends as bright, scornful of authority, with eccentricities that
should have set off alarms _ also matched that of other children
with guns and grudges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear these youths were having significant problems,''
said Dr. Beatrix Hamburg, a New York psychiatrist who is the
co-author of ``Violence in America's Schools,'' (Cambridge
University Press, 1998). ``In most of these cases, there are lots
of symptoms. But teachers ignore them, because they are not trained
to respond to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding common symptoms and patterns to school shootings may be
the easy part. The more troubling question, perhaps, is why the
normal problems of adolescence seem to be resolved now in
extraordinary spasms of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shooters and victims in Tuesday's killings were
supposed to meet several months ago in a rumble pitting students
known as the Trenchcoat Mafia against the athletes _ Goths vs.
Jocks, as some students described it. It was going to be a
fistfight to settle a feud, and it certainly would not have made
news.
</P>
<P>
   But that fight never happened. Instead, a slaughter unfolded
over fours hours in the suburb south of Denver, going from the
parking lot to the cafeteria to the library, where most of the
bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   So, once again, what lingers is a question that begs for
clarity: why a massacre instead of slugfest? Was that lethal virus
so many experts spoke of last year loose again in the culture?
</P>
<P>
   In pure numbers, no. School violence is way down from highs of
five years ago, and, until yesterday, this school year was shaping
up as the safest one in a decade, according to the National School
Safety Center of Westlake Village, Calif., which monitors lethal
action in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993-94 academic year, for example, 52 children were
killed in school violence nationwide. Last year the toll was 42.
With barely two months to go in this school year, the tally stood
at nine.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a decade of sharp increases, homicides by
juveniles dropped substantially in 1995, and continued to fall for
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, though the police in Colorado described the shooting
as a ``suicide mission,'' youth suicide is down from the highs of
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   What remains high is the number of guns in schools. More than
6,000 students were expelled in the 1996-97 school year _ the last
full year for figures _ for bringing guns to school, according to a
study issued by the Department of Education. These numbers are
among the highest recorded.
</P>
<P>
   To the police officers who saw the bloodied bodies of students
in the Columbine High School library or the teacher who died while
cowering in a closet, the national numbers and trends provide few
answers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about a motive for the shooting, Sheriff John Stone said,
``A dysfunctional individual, several dysfunctional individuals.''
He paused. ``I don't see any motive,'' he said, then added, ``I get
a real concern with people who identify with Adolf Hitler as a
hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances of some of the youths said they were fans of
Hitler, and the shooting happened on Tuesday to commemorate the
birthday of the Nazi dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler-worship, if openly expressed, is certainly something that
would have touched off alarm among teachers. But schools today are
so focused on test scores, and not emotional train wrecks, that
they are missing the real problems, some experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that we don't have any place in our society
where we help kids systematically think through emotions,'' said
Dr. John Coie, a professor of psychiatry at Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   Coie said he feared a copycat pattern: that one school shooting
sets off another, because the action validates a fantasy of someone
who would normally not be moved to violence. As such, judging from
the body count, that pattern is escalating.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what really scares me,'' Coie said. ``Kids who are
looking at these other examples must be talking to themselves about
how they can create a bigger massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts say simply that many American youths _
particularly those enamored of violent video games and musicians
who sing of suicide and death as others once sang of love and
freedom _ do not have a strong concept of the consequences of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   In the Colorado killings, acquaintances said the shooters were
fans of Marilyn Manson, a pop artist who caters to the nihilistic
impulses of some teen-agers, and was a hero to shooters in other
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider this age developmentally, a lot of these
kids don't have a concept of death yet,'' said Dr. Richard
Lieberman, a school psychologist with the Los Angeles Unified
School District. ``They view it as magical, reversible, and
temporary.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, as the images of graphic death at a house of learning
are shown on television, many parents try to shield their children.
But Wilson, who lost her daughter to violence in Jonesboro, thinks
it is better for people to feel a taste of sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teach our children, `Thou Shalt Not Kill,' and then we let
them play hours and hours of the most violent video games,'' said
Ms. Wilson. ``I say let the children go to funerals. Let them see
what happens after the shots are fired. Let's show them the empty
bedroom. Let them know that death is final.''
</P>
</TEXT>
