<HEADER>
A8118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-CON-EDITORIAL22     04-21 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-CON-EDITORIAL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death in our schools
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's hard _ terribly hard _ to wrap your mind around
the tragedy at Columbine High School. It's like trying to wrap your
arms around the world; it's just too much. And at times like this
when the brain goes numb, other organs pick up the slack. You feel
this thing in your gut and in your heart ... fear, confusion and a
profound respect for the grief that the people of Littleton, Colo.,
must be enduring.
</P>
<P>
   But the mind is a stubborn thing. It keeps asking questions, the
same questions of how and why, even when no answers are likely to
come. We call it meaningless violence, then sift through its rubble
for meaning.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of such tragedy, we take for granted that something
important must have changed, that something's gone terribly wrong.
And the sad fact is, that may not be true. History, religion,
psychology _ every discipline for understanding the human mind
tells us that the capacity for such violence has always existed and
probably always will. We have built cultures and civilizations and
communities in an attempt to restrain the darkness, but sometimes
the restraints simply fail, as they did Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But where did the restraints fail, and how can we patch the
fabric of society so it doesn't fail again? If the capacity for
violence is a trait of our species, this particular manifestation _
the mass slaughter of children by children _ is indeed something
new.
</P>
<P>
   Guns are part of it. They are not merely physically accessible;
they are psychologically accessible as well. Our children _
particularly adolescent boys _ have seen countless examples in the
movies, on television, video games and elsewhere in which anger is
satisfied by the pulling of a trigger. It is entertainment, for
most people pleasing but not provoking of that ancient portion of
our brain where the urge to violence lingers.
</P>
<P>
   For most people ... but not all. Eyewitness accounts of the
slaughter Tuesday indicate that the two armed students took
coldblooded joy in their killing and in the terror they inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Some want to draw the line right there, indicting the mass-media
culture for violence but dismissing the easy availability of
firearms as a factor. In other words, ``Guns don't kill people;
movies kill people.'' That's foolish. The potentially deadly
emotions that drive violence _ greed, anger, hate, jealousy _
become far more deadly when expressed with a gun. Any society that
refuses to acknowledge that fact dooms itself to a repetition of
such tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   In circumstances such as these, questions about parenting are
also inevitable and probably appropriate. It is hard to believe
that mothers and fathers fully involved in the lives of their
children could have missed the signs leading up to Tuesday's
massacre. On the other hand, we've only seen the end result of the
lives of the two killers; school officials, for example, report
that the boys involved had no history of discipline problems.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the late 20th century has no monopoly on poor
parenting; in fact, parents today face unique challenges. In our
mobile society, many American parents don't have an extended family
to fall back on, as their own parents and grandparents did. And
where parents were once the major source of information and
influence over the lives of their children, they now compete with a
range of outside influences that are difficult to control.
</P>
<P>
   When first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton proposed that ``it takes
a village to raise a child,'' she took a lot of criticism for
making a statement that is true on its face. The village might be a
town, a neighborhood, a community, a school, but even in our
individualistic culture, raising children is a communal task. When
the village fails, the village pays the consequences. And when guns
are more available than counseling, we've got some rethinking to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was troubling to hear the students at Columbine High
speak so matter-of-factly about the isolation to which they had
condemned the members of the ``Trench Coat Mafia.'' The
cliquishness of high school life has long been a part of growing
up, but the massacre Tuesday exposed something particularly
aggressive and cold. Too many Columbine students apparently came to
believe that the best way to define themselves, to elevate
themselves in their own eyes and the eyes of others, was to
identify, isolate and belittle those who were different.
</P>
<P>
   Now where would they get a strange idea like that?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
