<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8124 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-JNL-EDITORIAL22     04-21 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-JNL-EDITORIAL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retracing the path to savagery
 &HT;    By Richard Matthews
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nothing written here should be considered in any way
an excuse for what happened in Littleton, Colo., Tuesday afternoon.
It's not an attempt to justify an unforgivable horror, not an
effort to ``blame the victims'' for the unconscionable violence
committed upon them.
</P>
<P>
   It is merely a suggestion that we take a closer look at the
lives our children lead, the values they hold dear among themselves
(regardless of what parents teach them) and, most important, the
resulting way they treat each other. Here, perhaps, may lie one
tiny piece of the near-impossible task of figuring out how
Columbine High School could have become a killing field.
</P>
<P>
   Start with an unfortunate but unavoidable admission: No one is
more naturally and comfortably cruel to others than children. From
the 3-year-old who snatches a toy from his little sister's hands to
the 16-year-old who calls a classmate ``fatso,'' the urge to
selfishness and meanness comes as naturally as breathing.
</P>
<P>
   For teens, that urge is compounded by the newer and more
powerful need to forge an independent identity, and to have it
accepted by others. The surest way to confirm that acceptance is to
join in the rejection of those who don't fit in. That's why a high
school is a kind of social battlefield _ and a peculiar one, on
which no victory is ever final. The winners must never cease
defeating the losers, over and over, day after day.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't new. We didn't have the word ``nerd'' when I was in
school, but we had nerds, and I was one of them. Life was rarely
fun for the bookish, the plump, the ugly and the ungainly. Phys Ed
class was a particular torture. Nearly every day the bigger guys,
especially the jocks, found an opportunity to push us down into the
sandspurs when the coach wasn't looking, just so they could laugh
about it. They proved their ``superiority'' beyond doubt, but
always seemed to need to demonstrate it time and again.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who weren't into pushing and shoving found myriad
ways to remind the undesirables that they were undesired _ omitting
them from club activities, ignoring their efforts to join a
conversation, laughing none too secretly about their appearance or
their lack of style and grace. No one who was ``out'' ever had to
wonder about his or her standing in the social order.
</P>
<P>
   None of us was happy about all that, but of course few of us
ever felt moved to do anything about it. We simply suffered in
silence, and dreamed of a day when we would find some kind of niche
where we would be accepted, or at least respected. Most kids in
that situation today no doubt do the same thing. A few, however,
take more drastic measures _ measures that we never dreamed of in
our simpler time.
</P>
<P>
   The two teens who killed and wounded dozens of their classmates
in Littleton this week were described as ``nerds, geeks and dweebs
trying to find someplace to fit in.'' Clearly they were not highly
regarded. From all accounts, they brought on much of the scorn
themselves, at least in their later teen years, but one has to
wonder if something happened earlier to help send them down that
path.
</P>
<P>
   More important, one has to wonder if there is anything we can
say to our children about their regard, or disregard, for the
feelings of those who aren't among the popular, the beautiful, the
athletic elite. If that could change, even a little, could we
lessen by the tiniest amount the likelihood that we'll be seeing
this same mind-numbing story on the news in the next months or
years?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
