<SLUG> BC-BOEING-MISSILES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING WINS CONTRACT TO CONVERT CRUISE MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With its inventory of air-launched cruise missiles
running short because of the war in Yugoslavia, the U.S. Air Force
on Wednesday The Boeing Co. a $41.3 million contract to convert 95
nuclear versions to carry conventional warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has fewer than 100 operational missiles left in
its inventory, having fired more than 60 in the NATO air war
against Yugoslavia. The missiles are launched from B-52s.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion work would be done at Boeing's cruise missile
plant in St. Charles, Mo., and the first of the converted missiles
delivered to the Air Force late this year.
</P>
<P>
   But some members of Congress are urging Defense Secretary
William Cohen to place a new cruise missile order with Boeing,
which would mean restarting the company's long-dormant production
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the dwindling cruise missile inventory is one of
our most urgent national security issues and requires the
president's and your immediate attention,'' 19 House Republicans
said in a recent letter to Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., said Wednesday in an interview
that he would support restarting production of Boeing's
air-launched cruise missile, provided it was cost effective to do
so, could be done quickly and if the Air Force agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we run out, we don't have a weapon to launch from our
B-52s,'' said Dicks, one of the more knowledgable members of
Congress on defense issues.
</P>
<P>
   The air-launched cruise missile has been one of the military's
favorite weapons in recent years. It was used extensively in Desert
Storm and more recently in Desert Fox, when the U.S. and Britain
launched sustained air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, about 250 of the converted missiles have
been launched from B-52s. Fewer than 250 nuclear ones remain that
can be converted to carry conventional warheads.
</P>
<P>
   The converted missiles carry 2,000-pound warheads and have a
range of more than 600 miles. The conversions cost about $400,000
each, compared with about $1.5 million for a new missile.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing stands to make a lot more money if it built new missiles
from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post last Saturday reported that the letter sent
to Cohen by the 19 House Republicans was circulated to House
members with a cover memo from Boeing's chief Washington, D.C.
lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extremely important issue to the Air Force, Navy
and Boeing in light of current world events and the limited number
of missiles remaining in inventory,'' the Boeing cover memo said,
according to the Post story.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers who sent the letter want the United States to
restart production of not only Boeing's air-launched cruise missile
but Raytheon's Tomahawk cruise missile.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy does not favor additional production of the
Tomahawk. Instead, it wants limited funds to go toward the newer
Tactical Tomahawk, which is now in development.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks said Wednesday he has not yet been briefed by the Air
Force on the possibility of restarting production of the Boeing
missile.
</P>
<P>
   Restarting production of the air-launched cruise missile would
only be an interim solution to the missile shortage. The Air Force
plans to replace Boeing's air-launched cruise missiles with an
advanced Joint Air-to-Surface Standoff Munition. Lockheed Martin
won the contract over Boeing last year to supply the Air Force with
2,400 of the missiles, beginning in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boeing will continue to convert the old nuclear
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing began production of the nuclear version in the 1970s at
the height of the Cold War. The first were converted to carry
conventional warheads in 1986. Boeing has subsequently received
several contracts for more conversions. The company delivered the
last batch of converted missiles to the Air Force in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
