<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-21 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES, FRIENDS WAIT FOR BODIES AS AUTHORITIES CAREFULLY SEARCH
FOR ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As parents waited in agony nearby and police
squads searched for explosive booby traps inside, authorities
carefully made their way through Columbine High School on Wednesday
where they found the bodies at least 15 people killed by gunshots
or homemade pipe bombs in a massacre Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead were the two members of the junior class who are
believed to have unleashed the carnage before turning their guns on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve of the dead, including both suspects, were found in the
school's library, said the Jefferson County sheriff, John Stone,
who added that there were so many weapons and explosive devices _
including 30 bombs, a semi-automatic rifle and pistol and two
shotguns _ that investigators were still unsure how they got it all
inside the school. They may have hidden it during several trips or
they may have had help, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   But an even more unfathomable set of questions surrounded the
motivations of the two suspects, 18-year-old Eric David Harris and
Dylan Bennett Klebold, 17, who were described by many students
Wednesday as members of a self-styled group of loners and outcasts
who called themselves the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' after the long black
coats they wore and shared a fascination with violent video games
and a antipathy toward the more popular students who they referred
to as ``jocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Harris and Klebold were arrested last year for breaking
into a car, and parents of another student at the school said that
they had complained to authorities last year about death threats
made by Harris against their son. Nonetheless, school authorities
and many students insisted Wednesday that they never seriously
considered either young man to be inclined toward the horrific
violence let loose here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident set off a national bout of soul-searching and
debates over whether the killings were spurred by easy access to
guns or by the violent images on television and in video games to
which America's children are routinely exposed.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said in Washington that ``all of us are
struggling to understand exactly what happened and why.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings also had immediate political reverberations as
well: In at least three states, including Colorado, sponsors of
legislation expanding the rights to carry guns withdrew those
measures Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were still so concerned about the possibility of
more danger that just two bodies had been removed from the school
by Wednesday evening, and others were so unrecognizable that
parents were asked to bring dental records of their missing
children to the school.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the death toll, which represents the
largest school massacre in the country's history, but was also a
downward revision from the possible 23 deaths that the authorities
had said on Tuesday, will rise again as the search inside the
school continues.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the dead are male, including at least one teacher and
one black student at whom the killers had shouted racial
obscenities before shooting him in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen people are still hospitalized, 11 of them in serious or
critical condition, according to a spokesman for the sheriff's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the school at the time of the attack Wednesday
described a series of gunshots and thunderous explosions followed
by frantic requests from some teachers that they get themselves
into classrooms and barricade the door. Within minutes, as news of
the attack spread outside, many students with pagers found them
going off incessantly, as parents, siblings and friends sought to
reach out in a frenetic bid for news of their safety.
</P>
<P>
   Other students who carry cellular phones started using them to
call outside, even as the gunshots continued down the hall,
primarily in the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid called his mother right away and he just said, `Mom, I
hope we're going to be okay, but I love you, Mom, and if anything
happens I just want you to know that I really love you, even if I
didn't always act like it,''' said 17-year-old Craig Nason, a
junior at Columbine, who was herded with 60 other students into the
glee-club room, where the boys moved two desks and a filing cabinet
to create a barricade.
</P>
<P>
   Another student in the library managed to scribble a cardboard
sign that said ``Help me _ I'm bleeding to death'' which he placed
in the window where police officers could see it, said Sgt. George
Hinkle, a leader of the Lakewood, Colo., police department's SWAT
team. That student was now believed to be among the dead, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, under sunny skies that turned slate grey with an
approaching storm Wednesday afternoon, students gathered near the
high school for any news about friends still officially listed as
missing. Many were crying or clutching flowers that they brought to
a makeshift memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even imagine walking into that school right now,''
said 17-year-old Dara Ferguson, a junior, who had three friends
whom she feared were dead. ``I don't think I ever want to set foot
in there again.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Jefferson County School District said that
the building, with hundreds of bullet holes and several inches of
water that came from sprinklers that went off after the bombs did,
would remain closed for the rest of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   As the authorities sought to identify the dead and piece
together what happened and what motivated the young men, some
educators wasted no time in tracing the incident to cultural
factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many children grow up surrounded by images and violence
and hate on video games, in music lyrics, on television and on the
Internet,'' said Sandra Feldman, president of the American
Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children don't create those images, adults do,'' she said.
``In the coming days, we need to take a good hard look at what our
culture is celebrating, and what our country must change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
