<HEADLINE>
APACHE HELICOPTERS ARRIVE IN ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ The first of the long-awaited American Apache
attack helicopters touched down here Wednesday evening in a frenzy
of media attention and Army vows to transform NATO's thus far
ineffective campaign to halt Serbian attacks against Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the helicopters, which won a reputation as tank-busters
in the Persian Gulf War, buzzed in from the west through gray
cloudy skies at 6:15 Wednesday night after a flight from allied
bases in Italy. They were accompanied by seven Black Hawk
helicopters, two of them modified for medical evacuations and
marked with red crosses, and two huge Chinook transport
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The full contingent of Apaches is expected to number 24, and
will normally operate in flights of six. The NATO commander, Gen.
Wesley K. Clark, had been seeking the Apaches since the bombing
began on March 24, and is understood to have requested more, but
their deployment has lagged for a number of reasons, including bad
weather.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches' actual engagement in combat over Kosovo _ where
they are expected to attack Serbian tanks, hidden light-artillery
positions and small troop clusters, which have proved elusive to
high-altitude bombers _ will take still more time, military
officials indicated, perhaps a week or so.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches have dropped into a logistical nightmare. Albania is
the poorest country in Europe, with unpaved roads in the center of
its capital. For years Rina Airport here was used mostly by the
hard-line Communist dictator, Enver Hoxha, to greet a steadily
dwindling number of foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The area from which the allied forces are operating relief
flights, down the runway from the main terminal, is reachable only
by a dirt road snaking around the airport's edge past tattered
snack kiosks, half-built houses and dozing sheep. The road has now
turned into mud, barely two vehicles wide and rapidly crumbling at
the edges. A big American military truck fell almost on its side
into a ditch near the gate Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the developed part. The U.S. Army camp is in
something close to a mud pit some distance from the runway.
Vehicles that have been here two days are covered in filth, with
fresh mud up to their door handles. Engineers are building a road
to the Army tents but it is difficult right now for the officers
even to make their way to the main base, where the Air Force is
coordinating about 300 flights a day.
</P>
<P>
   How _ and whether _ the Apaches will operate in this
environment, along with the hundreds of relief flights, is unclear.
The allied forces are beginning an expanded program, in cooperation
with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, to evacuate
by helicopter the sickest and weakest of the 100,000 refugees still
stuck in the remote mountainous northern border region of Kukes,
further increasing the pressure on the forces here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One possibility is that the Apaches may be moved to an old
military airport further north, but American military officials
would give no details of the deployment.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the Apaches, however, has become such a
ballyhooed event that the rustic airport swarmed with more than a
hundred journalists, mostly television crews, seeking to record the
arrival. Army public affairs officers struggled to contain the
unruly crowd within an area where they would not be hit by flying
rocks when the helicopters landed.
</P>
<P>
   The Army also brought forth a qualified Apache pilot _ a tall,
lean, 29-year-old captain, Mark Arden _ to speak to journalists,
though it turned out that Arden would not actually be flying
because he is the administrative officer of the 11th Attack
Aviation Regiment, which is based in Germany and is a main
component of the Apache group. The helicopters were not a part of
NATO's original plan and the force here has been cobbled together
from a number of units, including paratroopers from the 82nd
Airborne Division who are to guard the helicopters _ hundreds of
miles and several mountain ranges away from the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs have been successful in defeating women and children
that are unarmed,'' Arden said, hooking his black-gloved thumbs in
his ammunition belt. ``The tables are about to be turned,'' he
added, because his comrades ``are fired up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know they are at the tip of the spear of the entire
United States Army.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
