<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVARS BALK AT LEAVING THE CAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ After five mornings of chilling rain left his
children coughing and wheezing, Ilir Januzi could take no more.
Just after daybreak Wednesday, he took his wife and children _
including an 8-month-old son _ from the old car that had been their
only shelter and boarded a bus for Vlora, 220 miles south of here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to get out of here,'' Januzi said as he waited for
the bus to depart. ``This is no man's land.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, a combination of bad weather and appalling
sanitary conditions have pushed more than 16,000 Kosovar refugees
to leave this no man's land of garbage and mud, and head once more
for unknown places they hope will be better than the places they
left.
</P>
<P>
   But even so, many of the buses that are to carry refugees to
less crowded and more secure encampments elsewhere sit half empty.
Their drivers are not allowed to leave until the buses are full, so
they end up sleeping one, two, three nights in their buses, waiting
for enough refugees to make up their mind to leave.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials say the situation is turning critical, with the
chance of an epidemic rising along with the increasing danger of a
Serbian attack here _ only 10 miles from the border _ as tensions
between Albania and Yugoslavia worsen.
</P>
<P>
   There has been shelling nearby, but the greatest danger for
refugees so far has been illness. Already, 59 refugees have died in
the camps since the beginning of the crisis, according to U.N.
figures. While that rate is not considered excessive, with tens of
thousands of physically weakened refugees passing through here, it
has caused concern.
</P>
<P>
   The most crippling illnesses have been respiratory infections
caused by the dampness and the cold, said Muhammed Dualeh, senior
public health officer for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
which coordinates care for the Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially lethal problem is posed by the five cases of
bloody diarrhea recently reported in the camps here in Kukes, a
small city in northeastern Albania that has been swamped by a flood
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Dualeh said the cases have been isolated, so far. And the cold
weather has actually helped contain the danger. If temperatures
rise and the flies that carry the disease begin to hatch, an
epidemic could easily arise in the unsanitary conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Although the flow of refugees has stopped temporarily, the
numbers here still are so great that the solution to one problem
can sometimes be the cause of yet another.
</P>
<P>
   Food is available now, but garbage collection has become an
enormous concern. With fresh bread delivered every day, stale
pieces are thrown in heaps, where they mold or turn to stinking
mush. Along with empty sardine tins and used disposable diapers
that are now distributed by some agencies, the aid has added
substantially to the waste.
</P>
<P>
   It accumulates everywhere, even along the stairs to the single
mosque in Kukes, a place traditionally swept spotless every day.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Morris, special envoy to Albania for the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, said that despite the filth and the
cold, there appears to be growing reluctance to leave on the part
of a great number of the 100,000 refugees estimated to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to stay here because they don't know where their
family and relatives are,'' he said. They also are reluctant to
leave behind the tractors on which many came.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal being considered would set aside one day a week to
allow the refugees to take their slow-moving tractors on the only
road that leads from here to warmer areas in the south. Currently
refugees are not permitted to take tractors on that road.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations providing the refugees with services are
encouraging people to leave now. Pamphlets already are being
distributed urging people to go, and soon there will be daily radio
broadcasts detailing the advantages of alternative locations. Many
refugees brought their own transistor radios, and a foundation will
soon begin to give away hand-cranked radios.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has also agreed to provide helicopters that can ferry the
weakest refugees to less congested southern towns, where they will
be able to stay with willing Albanian families. The first three
helicopters transported more than 110 people Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But most refugees, if they leave, still go by bus. Every
morning, around dawn, a fleet of battered private buses from
throughout the region line up in the largest plaza. With the
destination marked on each bus, a refugee like Zenel Josha has to
decide only where he wants to go. The ride is paid for by the
Albanian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not one of us has had a bath in three weeks and we are ashamed
of how we look,'' said Josha, a window maker from Mitrovica, in the
industrialized northern part of Kosovo. He left there on a tractor
with his brother, Naim, and their families _ 10 people in all.
</P>
<P>
   Josha had decided to board the bus to Vlora after the rains
soaked the few things he still owned, and his children began to
sniffle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard they are going to find a place for us with an
Albanian family,'' Josha said, holding one of his children on his
lap to keep her warm as they waited for the bus to fill so it could
leave. ``But no matter what it is like there, it has to be better
than here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
