<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS PREDICT IMPROVED EARNINGS AT K-SWISS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. -- Athletic shoe maker K-Swiss Inc. is
expected to race far past last year's finishing line when it
releases its first-quarter results today.
</P>
<P>
   According to a First Call survey of four analysts, K-Swiss
should earn about 75 cents per share for the quarter ended March
31, more than double the 31 cents the company earned in the
comparable year-ago period. The analysts' estimates ranged from 74
cents to 77 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts also expect the company to end the year with
earnings of about $1.84 per share, or 67 percent up from last
year's $1.10 per share. Estimates ranged from $1.64 to $2.03.
</P>
<P>
   All numbers have been adjusted to take into account the
two-for-one stock split that took effect March 29, according to
Chuck Hill, director of research for First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff van Sinderen, a research analyst for B. Riley in Santa
Monica, expects K-Swiss to earn 74 cents per share, and thinks
second-quarter earnings will be strong as well.
</P>
<P>
   Come back-to-school time, however, the company could become a
victim of its own success as rival companies release knockoffs of
K-Swiss's popular all-white sneaker style.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest question I have is, are some of the retailers
going to decide to try the knockoffs because of the lower price
point?'' van Sinderen said. ``Aside from that, I think this quarter
there will be strong results, and next quarter will also be
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock went on a wild ride between Feb. 8 and March
17, nearly doubling to a split-adjusted high of $34.125 on the
strength of its year-end earnings and anticipation of its stock
split before steadily declining to the low $20s.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, K-Swiss shares closed the day at $34.875, up
$2.75.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
