<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFERING TO PLACE 20,000 REFUGEES WITH FAMILIES, GORE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The United States is offering to bring 20,000 Kosovar
refugees to the American mainland for temporary placement with
families, Vice President Al Gore announced Wednesday. The offer
represents a new policy, and formal abandonment of the
much-criticized earlier proposal to relocate thousands of the
refugees to the naval base at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will accept, on the American mainland, up to 20,000 of the
hurting and homeless Kosovar refugees _ those with close family
ties in America and those who are vulnerable,'' Gore said in a
speech to about 200 community leaders on Ellis Island in a ceremony
commemorating the 50th anniversary of NATO. ``We will bring them
here until they are able to return home safely.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees are to be screened from among the many thousands
who have fled Kosovo, and they will need to meet international
standards for refugees in order to come.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they had no idea how many refugees
might want to come to the United States, but that they were
limiting the number to those who had family in the United States or
whose health was too fragile to withstand the difficulties of the
nomadic life many have now been forced to adopt. The United States
is home to numerous pockets of Albanian-Americans, including in New
York and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the refugees would not be granted political asylum.
``We anticipate their return to Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO allies, including the United States, first announced
plans two weeks ago to provide temporary homes for the refugees who
have been streaming out of Kosovo. So far, refugees have been
placed in 11 countries; Germany has accepted about 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has indicated to the United States that it is simply
out of space for accommodating any more refugees, one U.S. official
said.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said that refugees could be
identified for placement early next week.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration's plan to send refugees to a vast
tent community at the naval station on Guantanamo Bay has fizzled,
with officials suspending a proposed airlift and offering to build
barracks in Albania instead. Many refugee agencies and Albanian
refugee families rejected the idea of being shipped so far from
their homeland, and to such an isolated spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to use Guantanamo was made when it looked like a
large group needed to be moved quickly and there was no time for
screening,'' an administration official said. The official said
that those circumstances no longer prevailed and that there would
be more time for screening and moving those who wanted to move.
</P>
<P>
   When the base was first selected as a location, administration
officials indicated it was also chosen to eliminate the possibility
that some of the refugees would claim political asylum in the
United States. Under federal immigration law, refugees can claim
asylum only once they reach American soil.
</P>
<P>
   More important, as recently as last week, President Clinton,
among others, said that moving the refugees out of the Balkan
region could appear to hand a victory to President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia and to his policy of ``ethnic cleansing,''
and that it would therefore not be in NATO's interest.
</P>
<P>
   While in the Detroit area last week, Clinton met privately with
seven Albanian-Americans who have relatives in the war-torn region.
P.J. Crowley, a spokesman for the president, said Clinton agreed
with them that for the short term, it would be better to try to
help the refugees stay in the Balkans rather than move them to
Guantanamo Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said at the time that temporarily relocating some
refugees to Guantanamo ``remains an option,'' but for the moment,
such a mass movement would look like ``a propaganda victory'' for
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about some refugees' reluctance to leave the Balkan
region, Gore said, ``It is a balance. The vast and overwhelming
majority will remain right in the region prepared to return on
short notice. These too, the ones coming to the United States, will
also be prepared to return on short notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee's immigration panel, said that ``the administration's
decision to bring 20,000 Kosovar refugees to the United States is
the largest and most compelling evidence yet of a complete
breakdown of administration policy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the goal was to halt Serb atrocities, we now have the
biggest refugee crisis in postwar history,'' Smith said. ``We are
now witnessing a stunning string of failures that continue to
multiply the miseries of the Kosovars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
