<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8144 &Cx1f; tad-z
s a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-REACT-COX     04-21 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-REACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents say teens have seen too much misery
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ They came in groups, pairs or eight at a
time, clutching bouquets of red roses or single tulips or sprays of
dandelions to leave at the bases of Clement Park trees transformed
to memorials.
</P>
<P>
   They came from all over, not just Littleton, eyes flooding and
breath hitching as they held each other in tight, desperate hugs,
as if by loosening their holds they might slip away forever.
</P>
<P>
   All day Wednesday, as flat gray clouds rolled in from the east
to settle menacingly against the stark Rocky Mountain foothills
that skirt Littleton, people came to Clement Park, a quarter mile
north of Columbine High School, to grieve and remember and ask an
overwhelming, bewildering question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers and mothers and pastors and young children began
pouring onto the park around noon, and almost invariably they
asked, Why here? Why innocent kids? Why did this happen to us?
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning about 11:25, Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold,
17, both seniors at Columbine entered the school armed with two
sawed-off shotguns, a semiautomatic handgun and many homemade
bombs. They opened fire in the hallways and library, killing 12
students, one teacher and, according to District Attorney David
Thomas, themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Because they rigged an elaborate series of booby trap bombs
around the school _ Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone said SWAT
team members found 30 bombs in and around the building _ law
enforcement officers had to do extensive sweeps of the building
before the bodies of the slain students and teacher could be
removed.
</P>
<P>
   So people stood on the trampled grass behind the police
barricades and in the parking lot, staring silently at the signs,
flowers, stuffed animals and candles surrounding two trees in a
rapidly growing expanse.
</P>
<P>
   They looked at the memorials and cried the tears they thought
they didn't have left, holding onto each other tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got two little kids at home,'' said John Williams, an
assistant manager of a Littleton movie theater. ``I keep thinking
about what I'd do if I got a call from the school saying my
children had been killed. I don't think I could handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, people had no choice but to handle it. Teenagers,
mostly unaccustomed to feeling grief, stood in tight circles for
comfort and warmth as a sad April wind sighed all around them and
made the flags at half-staff fly out straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' asked a Columbine sophomore, clutching her friend's arm
as they stood near a memorial tree. ``Oh, God. God. Why did this
have to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knew. Zondra Lapp came to the park at 5:30 a.m. Wednesday
with her son, Joshua, 16, who was in the library when the first
shots were fired. He escaped unharmed and went a friend's house,
but Zondra spent a panicked Tuesday afternoon at Leawood Elementary
School before she was reunited with Joshua at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As Joshua talked to reporters, Zondra looked at him and started
to cry. ``He saw too much. He's only 16 and he saw too much,'' she
said as she stood shivering in the predawn chill.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Woods didn't let his son, Justin, 15, out of his sight as
Justin waited to talk to reporters. Jim occasionally kissed
Justin's cheek or patted his shoulder or put his arm around him.
Justin was playing soccer when the shooting started and ran to a
house near the school to call his parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodses spent the entire evening talking and praying and
crying. ``We didn't go to bed last night,'' said Justin's mother,
Lisa. ``I just can't stop thinking about what Justin will see when
he goes in his room, turns on the light, if he'll see the bodies of
the students who were shot. He's going to have to live with that
even though we'll go to counseling as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sun rose and thin light filtered through the clouds, more
people came to the park to brave the ravenous hordes of reporters
and looked to each other for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in this town have been amazing,'' said Peggy Beck,
a registered nurse at Centura Littleton Adventist Hospital, to
which 10 injured students were taken. ``It sounds cliche, but
people have really pulled together.''
</P>
<P>
   She said a restaurant sent over pizza and many people called to
check on the welfare of the students.
</P>
<P>
   All day Wednesday, people brought food for the Jefferson County
Sheriff's Department deputies guarding the streets to prevent
people from going to the school. By afternoon, the deputy at the
intersection of Bowles and Pierce had a tidy pile that included
McDonald's cheeseburgers, a muffin, a case of bottled water and
chocolate-chip cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, people from around the metro-Denver area came to
Clement Park to stand in support of those who grieved. They brought
butterfly balloons and hopes to remind people how beauty can rise
from ugliness.
</P>
<P>
   They formed spontaneous prayer circles and sang gospels songs
with upraised arms and fervently closed eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing they could say, so they stood and sat and
kneeled _ pastors from Denver, students from Arvada, grandmothers
from Wheat Ridge - and vowed they would get through the tragedy
together and never let it happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Sauer writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
