   (NYT32) NEW YORK -- April 21, 1999 -- OBIT-TILBERIS, 4-21 -- Liz
Tilberis, left, editor in chief of Harper's Bazaar and former
editor of British Vogue, with Princess Diana at Metropolitan Museum
of Art in 1996 during the museum's annual Costume Institute gala of
which Tilberis was a chairperson. Tilberis died Wednesday, April
21, 1999 after a long bout with ovarian cancer. She was 51. (Bill
Cunningham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 21, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-8, 4-21 -- Students console each other outside
Columbine High School on Wednesday. Specially trained officers
painstakingly checked the suburban Denver high school where over 15
people were killed Tuesday in the deadliest U.S. school rampage on
record. The bodies of the victims remained inside the school as
police conducted their search. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) BERKELEY, Calif. -- April 21, 1999 -- PEOPLE'S-PARK,
4-21 -- A woman practices yoga in People's Park, owned by U.C.
Berkley, and leased to the city. People's Park received its bloody
christening in 1969 when the university decided to take back its
land in one of the most infamous domestic clashes of the Vietnam
era. Two weeks ago, the university issued a quick denial to reports
that the chancellor was considering converting the park to student
housing, the very plan for the site 30 years ago. But to many here
housing on the site is an idea whose time has come. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) TOKYO -- April 21, 1999 -- JAPAN-TOJO, 4-21 -- Yuko
Tojo, granddaughter of Japan's wartime prime minister and the man
who ordered the attack on Pearl Harbor, prays at a Buddhist temple
earlier this month. Fifty years after the Allied-backed War Crimes
Tribunal ordered Tojo's execution, his granddaughter is leading a
campaign to revise his image. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) TIRANA, Albania -- April 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MILITARY-3,
4-21 -- U.S. soldiers clear a field for debris just before the
arrival of U.S. Army Black Hawk and Apache helicopters at Rinas
airport on Wednesday. Six U.S. Apache helicopter gunships arrived
in Albania on Wednesday, increasing the firepower available to NATO
commanders in the Yugoslav conflict. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- April 21, 1999 -- SCOTUS-COX, 4-21 --
Members of ADAPT, a national grassroots group advocating rights for
disabled Americans, holds a rally outside the Supreme Court on
Wednesday. The Supreme Court on Wednesday heard arguments in an
important disability rights case, the first of four disability
cases to be heard over the next week. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) BOSTON -- April 21, 1999 -- HKN-BRUINS-BOS, 4-21 --
Boston Bruins' coach Pat Burns looks at the scoreboard after the
Blackhawks scored late in the third period to tie the game at 3-3,
Tuesday night. The Bruins open their best-of-seven first-round
Eastern Conference series against the third-seeded Carolina
Hurricanes on Thursday. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 21, 1999 -- CIR-SESAME-STREET, 4-21 --
Tina Sharkey of Children's Television Network Online, with friends
from ``Sesame Street.'' Ms. Sharkey, who is 34, says the show
``invented one of the most important movements of the 20th century,
empowering families to get involved with their kids' learning.''
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 21, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-3, 4-21 -- Students console each other near a
makeshift memorial outside Columbine High School on Wednesday.
Worried about bombs and booby traps, specially trained officers
painstakingly checked the suburban Denver high school where over 15
people were killed Tuesday in the deadliest U.S. school rampage on
record. The bodies of the victims remained inside the school as
police conducted their search. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 21, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-2, 4-21 -- Students pray on a car that belongs
to a student who is missing and feared killed at Columbine High
School on Wednesday. Worried about bombs and booby traps, specially
trained officers painstakingly checked the suburban Denver high
school where 15 people were killed Tuesday in the deadliest U.S.
school rampage on record. The bodies of the victims remained inside
the school as police conducted their search. (Monica Almeida/New
York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- April 21, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1,
4-21 -- President Clinton bows his head in a moment of prayer for
the victims of Tuesday's school shooting, before his address to
White House volunteers on Wednesday. ``All of us are struggling to
understand exactly what happened and why. There is a deep desire to
comfort the grieving and counsel the children,'' the president
said. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
