<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-4, 4-21 --
Ethnic Albanian refugees from Gnjilane, in Kosovo, on board a bus
en route to the Neprostene refugee camp near Tetovo, Macedonia, on
Wednesday. Humanitarian agencies have had difficulties accessing
refugee camps in Macedonia, a country just southeast of
Yugoslavia's embattled Kosovo province. Macedonia, a former
Yugoslav republic itself, is fearful of upsetting its own delicate
ethnic mix by the influx of ethnic Albanians fleeing the violence
in Kosovo. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KUKES, Albania -- April 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-3,
4-21 -- A Chinook helicoptor with the Royal Netherlands Air Force,
part of NATO's humanitarian relief effort, is unloaded Wednesday
after arriving at the refugee camp housing Ethnic Albanians who
fled the violence in Kosovo. The helicopter was part of a group of
aircraft carrying five tons of food supplies for the refugees.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) KUKES, Albania -- April 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-2,
4-21 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees who recently arrived to the
refugee camp scan a list of other refugees on Wednesday who arrived
earlier hoping to find the names of friends or relatives. United
Nations officials say that the situation at the camp is turning
critical, with the chances of a crippling epidemic rising along
with the increasing danger of a Serbian attack. (Edward Keating/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) KUKES, Albania -- April 21, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES-1,
4-21 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees look on as helicoptor with the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees lifts off ferrying journalists
down to the Albanian capital of Tirana. A Chinook helicoptor, in
the background, with the Royal Netherlands Air Force and part of
NATO's humanitarian relief effort, landed minutes before carrying
food. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
