<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-MAIN22-COX     04-21 1490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-MAIN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harsh reality hits shocked Littleton, Colo.
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ After a lonely, dread-filled night, the grim
news finally came officially Wednesday afternoon for the families
of those killed in the Columbine High School shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Their cherished loved ones, twelve young students and one
teacher, wouldn't be coming home.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would the two angry boys, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold,
who barged into their school with duffel bags brimming with guns
and homemade bombs, writing a murderous page of history for reasons
this shell-shocked community is struggling to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in denial all day yesterday,'' said Michael Shoels,
father of Isaiah Shoels, one of the victims. ``But I knew yesterday
that he wasn't going to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   As squads of police gingerly picked their way through the
sprawling school building in a search for about 30 bombs left by
the teen-age assailants, hundreds of mourners gathered on a grassy
knoll near the school's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   They laid flower bouquets, hand-scribbled poems, Bible passages
and teddy bears in heaping piles near trees budding with spring
leaves. They gathered in circles, heads bowed, to pray and sing.
</P>
<P>
   They hugged and cried and ran across the grass among the milling
crowd to throw themselves at friends they feared would never walk
out of their school again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sense of it?'' said Trish O'Neill, whose daughter Becky
Beachy, 16, escaped unharmed. ``We can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Police took nearly 24 hours to declare the school building safe
after the four-hour melee began, mostly because fleeing students
had dropped hundreds of book bags and backpacks that had to be
gingerly inspected for explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran law enforcement officers blanched at the gruesome work,
saying they were surprised at the sophistication of the bombs, some
of which were rigged with timers. They were also appalled at the
carnage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a SWAT-team officer since 1980 and this was clearly
the most devastating, traumatic scene I've ever been a part of,''
officer George Hinkle told reporters. ``I hope to never see
anything like this again.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims were 11 males _ including the shooters, who
apparently killed themselves _ and four females. One teacher, Dave
Sanders, who also was coach of the girls' baseball team, was killed
after reportedly shoving students out of an opened doorway and
taking gunshots to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Several Columbine students tried desperately to stop Sanders
from bleeding to death by holding makeshift bandages to his wounds
and applying pressure for the more than three hours they had to
wait for help.
</P>
<P>
   When the attack started, a school resource police officer was on
duty at Columbine and returned fire at the assailants within
minutes, Jefferson County Sheriff spokesman Steve Davis said. An ad
hoc SWAT team was on the scene within 20 minutes, he added,
although it took more than 90 minutes to assemble the full SWAT
team and get them to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not release the names of the dead victims, saying
they wanted the families to have time to grieve in private.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three people, mostly students, were hospitalized with
wounds. Late Wednesday, five remained in critical condition and
five more in serious condition.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Denver metro area, churches held prayer vigils and
memorial services, opening their doors to a community still in
shock. Schools were closed.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy drew worldwide attention, with many overseas media
focusing on America's deadly history of gun violence. Reporters
from Europe, South America and Asia were at the scene. One Japanese
headline reportedly read, ``How sick is the gun society?''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton expressed his sorrow to the families of the
dead in a news conference, again decrying the violence that has
recently erupted in the nation's schools in similar, shocking
incidents in Arkansas, Mississippi, Kentucky and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Legislature, which happens to be debating a
controversial gun bill, held a moment of silence, then adjourned
out of respect for the victims. Professional sports events in
Denver were canceled.
</P>
<P>
   As in the wake of the other school shootings, the biggest
question _ and one nobody could answer _ was why.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Harris and Klebold targeted athletes and
minorities, laughing at their victims and using a racial epithet to
describe the one black victim, Isaiah Shoels. ``All jocks stand
up!'' one of the boys yelled during the attack. ``We're going to
kill every one of you.'' But District Attorney Dave Thomas said
there was no evidence that the killers targeted minorities, as some
students claimed.
</P>
<P>
   According to their friends, Harris, 18, and Klebold, 17, were
part of a loose-knit group called the ``Trench Coat Mafia'' and
often dressed in black, favoring leather and the long coats that
have been featured in numerous violence-filled Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   They were described alternately as loners who stayed to
themselves, or as rebels who reveled in their status as outcasts,
thumbing their noses at convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took some teasing, but everybody in high school gets
teased,'' said Josh Swanson, a senior who knew the boys. ``If
anything, the most teasing was for Dylan over his personal hygiene.
He didn't bathe sometimes, and he smelled pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Marsh, another student who was a member of the trench coat
group, said the boys did have a mean streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they liked you, they were the sweetest guys in the world,''
she told reporters. ``But if they didn't like you, you better watch
your back.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys played violent computer games for hours, friends said.
They also reportedly dabbled heavily in Nazi paraphernalia,
sometimes wearing swastikas. Harris set up an Internet home page
that spouted Nazi ideology and condoned violence. The shootings
took place on the 110th anniversary of Adolf Hitler's birth.
</P>
<P>
   But even friends couldn't fathom the hate that seemed to boil
out of the pair during their rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Woodman, a junior who was in the library when the gunmen
burst in, said she couldn't get their voices out of her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought it was funny,'' Woodman told ``Good Morning
America.'' ``They were just, like `Who's next? Who's ready to die?'
They were just, like, `We've waited to do this our whole lives.'
And every time they'd shoot someone, they'd holler, like it was,
like, exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys lived in upscale neighborhoods in Littleton, a
bustling, prosperous suburb on Denver's sprawling southwest border.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned school officials groped for answers on how they could've
prevented the tragedy, just as their counterparts have in other
cities marred by student shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could we let this happen?'' a shaken Howard Cornell, the
school district's security director, told ABC News. ``I don't think
anybody has the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ The gunmen's families would not speak to reporters, but both
issued statements Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thoughts, prayers and heartfelt apologies go out to the
victims, their families, friends, and the entire community,'' the
Klebold family said. ``Like the rest of the country, we are
struggling to understand why this happened, and ask that you please
respect our privacy during this painful grieving period.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris' parents said: ``We want to express our heartfelt
sympathy to the families of all the victims and to all the
community for this senseless tragedy. Please say prayers for
everyone touched by these terrible events.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone's initial estimate of as
many as 25 dead in the massacre was off the mark apparently because
the six SWAT teams that swept the building counted some victims
more than once. By early Wednesday, his deputies said the death
toll was 15.
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Rifle Association still plans to hold its annual
meeting in Denver next weekend, but will cancel all its seminars,
exhibitions and luncheons in deference to the school shootings in
Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy in Littleton last Tuesday calls upon us to take
steps ... to modify our schedule to show our profound sympathy and
respect for the families and communities in the Denver area in
their time of great loss,'' says a letter sent to NRA members in
Colorado. The letter was signed by NRA President Charlton Heston
and Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre and was released by the
Virginia-based NRA on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than a dozen federal agents from the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms focused on tracing the arsenal _ two sawed-off
shotguns, one handgun and one carbine, the White House said _ to
determine who licensed them, and how and where the teen-age
suspects got hold of such firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
