<HEADLINE>
DOW CLIMBS 132.87 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Strong profit reports helped fuel a rally in stocks
on Wednesday as technology and consumer issues appeared to regain
the leadership they long enjoyed. Stocks tied to the business
cycle, meanwhile, mostly paused after their recent run-up.
</P>
<P>
   The three main market gauges finished at their best levels of
the day, with the Nasdaq composite index posting a 3.3 percent gain
that, combined with Tuesday's rebound, wiped out Monday's 5.56
percent slide, the seventh worst on record. It was the index's
biggest two-day gain in three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 132.87 points, to
10,581.42, a record. The average is up 15.25 percent so far this
year. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index increased by 29.95
points, or 2.3 percent, to 1,336.12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market really has recovered very nicely from the earlier
tech weakness,'' said Mary Farrell, a senior strategist at Paine
Webber Inc. ``It's indicative of some underlying strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Another favorable sign, analysts said, was an impressive surge
in small-company stocks, which have long been out of favor. The
Russell 2000 index of smaller-company shares, which includes some
Internet companies but has not set a record this year, advanced 2.7
percent and edged into positive territory for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, which have been battered lately, continued a
rebound that began on Tuesday with solid earnings reports for three
drug makers. On Wednesday, Bristol-Myers climbed 5, to 64\, after
it reported better-than-expected profits and was raised to a
``buy'' at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer, which had traded as high as 150[ early last week, rose
4| on Wednesday, to 123].
</P>
<P>
   Profits at Coca-Cola eased, but by slightly less than Wall
Street had feared, and its shares rose 2 5-16, to 67 9-16, still
well below its high of 88 15/16 last July.
</P>
<P>
   But the real stars of the day were Internet and other technology
stocks despite a warning by Microsoft, down 1[, to 82, that some
companies may delay software purchases until next year because of
the expected year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm, which handily surpassed profit estimates, soared 54
7-16, to 195 1-16, after reaching 198, more than five times the
cellular phone maker's price in early October.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent jumped 4~, to 59[; Charles Schwab rose 11\, to 118; Texas
Instruments climbed 8}, to 108}; Motorola rose 4 7-16, to 80 3-16;
Amazon.com leaped 7\, to 179\, and Hewlett-Packard rose 3}, to 75[.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no end of commentary about how overpriced'' many
high-technology stocks have gotten, said Thom R. Brown, managing
director of Rutherford, Brown and Catherwood in Philadelphia. ``But
these things are roaring today.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM, which reported a sharp rise in profit after the close,
gained 2[, to 171~. Compaq Computer edged up \, to 24\, after
reporting earnings that met sharply reduced expectations.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, which is scheduled to report a profit on
Thursday, was the Dow's biggest gainer, rising 7], to 134~,
followed by General Electric, up 4\, to 113 9-16, and Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, up 4{, to 100}, after jumping 6 on Tuesday on strong
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rejuvenation of growth stocks in the latest two
sessions, some value-oriented money managers said they thought the
recent rotation into cyclical and smaller stocks had further to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earnings outlook is more positive'' than for technology,
said Richard E. Cripps, chief strategist at Legg Mason in
Baltimore. ``And the breadth of the value market has taken on a
better tone.''
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume subsided to a still-heavy
920.1 million shares, with 1,954 advancing issues versus 1,114
declining ones. A total of 52 stocks set new highs, while 22 had
new lows. On the Nasdaq, 1.13 billion shares changed hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
