<HEADLINE>
PANEL CONSIDERING REQUEST FOR MILITARY FUNDS TALKS ABOUT ECHOES OF
VIETNAM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans raised the specter of the
Vietnam War Wednesday at a hearing on President Clinton's emergency
request for more than $5 billion in military funds for NATO's air
campaign against Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen and Gen. Henry H.
Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, assured them that
the United States would not slowly slide toward a full-bore war in
the Balkans _ not without a great public debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely committed to making sure that we do not have
the kind of gradualism that happened during the Vietnam War,''
Cohen said. If months of bombing achieves no results, and a ground
war looms, ``We'll be up here in five months explaining it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton agreed that the United States would not go to war
without ``our eyes wide open,'' without ``a healthy debate'' and
without ``public support.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary and the chairman appeared before the House
appropriations defense subcommittee, the first panel to weigh
President Clinton's request for $5.1 billion in emergency funds to
finance NATO's air war. Shelton asked for ``swift approval'' of the
request; Cohen said the military needs the money ``tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   That appears unlikely. Congressional Republicans are divided on
whether to add a few billion dollars more to the emergency request,
or many billions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our most ardent defense hawks are running around with
charts and graphs demanding $28 billion,'' a senior Republican aide
said. ``Most of the leadership is around $10 billion. You might see
something above that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the president's request was adequate to finance the
American role in an intensifying air war until Sept. 30, the end of
the fiscal year. He suggested that the Pentagon would not reject
out of hand a few billion more. But Democrats will not support a
bill of the kind that the Republican hawks are pushing. And the
Republicans will not settle on the sum they will seek until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The argument over money is about politics as well as the conduct
of the conflict. Some Republicans on the appropriations panel
suggested that the conflict would become Clinton's Vietnam _ a
deepening military morass, fought in the name of human rights
instead of anti-Communism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
