u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-     04-21 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-VIOLENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACRE CALLED SIGN OF INADEQUATE MENTAL HEALTH CARE FOR YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ETHAN BRONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Child psychologists and other experts on youth violence said
Tuesday's killings in Colorado are evidence of a woeful lack of
mental health services for young people at a time of decreasing
family strength and increasing access to the tools of violence.
</P>
<P>
   They also said parents, teachers and students themselves ought
to be receiving training in the early detection of depression and
violent tendencies. But they added that the continuing stigma of
mental illness, and cutbacks in health insurance due to managed
care, were keeping society from looking frankly at the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true tragedy is that America refuses to recognize that
there are millions of teens and children with psychological
illnesses, which are as real as physical illnesses,'' said Dr.
Harold Koplewicz, director of the Child Study Center at New York
University.
</P>
<P>
   He added that tests were available to spot warning signs like
depression and isolation even in very young children, but that few
schools used them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a common theme to all of the shootings of recent
years,'' he said. ``You have a child who has had symptoms of
aggression toward his peers, an interest in fire, cruelty to
animals, social isolation and many warning signs that the school
has ignored. Schools do vision and hearing screenings. Doesn't it
make sense that kindergarten teachers learn how to screen for
aggressive behavior?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Suniya Luthar, a professor of psychology at Columbia
University's Teachers College, agreed. ``If we were able to get
teachers to receive even basic tips from professionals about such
things, we might go a long way to preventing violence, suicide and
drug abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, the federal government distributed a guide to safe
schools that outlined ways for administrators and teachers to
recognize potentially violent behavior. It also suggested measures
for school systems to take to prevent violence.
</P>
<P>
   Much emphasis was placed on tight community and family bonds to
schools, which, some administration officials believe, result from
smaller school and class sizes and high academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see all these issues as linked,'' said Bill Modzeleski, the
director of the Safe and Drug-Free Schools Program of the federal
Department of Education. ``A lot of the factors that put kids at
risk of using alcohol and drugs are the same as those that put them
at risk of violent behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis on Wednesday, Attorney General Janet Reno said
the only way to curb violence in schools was to give children the
support they needed and to train school authorities to spot
youngsters with potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she might push for more counselors in the nation's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   On April 1, a joint program of the departments of Education,
Justice and Health and Human Services was announced to award more
than $300 million in grants to 50 communities to help prevent
school violence.
</P>
<P>
   The grants will cover the purchase of security equipment like
metal detectors and will finance training for teachers,
after-school programs and the hiring of more mental health
professionals for schools, a move welcomed by counselors and other
mental health advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Modzeleski said about 5 percent of schools use walk-through
metal detectors and 10 percent use hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   While schools may decide to increase their physical security,
many violence experts argue that such an effort will have limited
effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that metal detectors will protect us is
shortsighted,'' said Dr. Mark Greenberg, a professor of human
development and family studies at Pennsylvania State University.
``Kids who want to kill will just shoot outside.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that with the growing number of families in which both
parents work, school systems needed to train teachers to be alert
to signs of emotional instability.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists are increasingly arguing that the developing field
of threat assessment, used by the Secret Service to track potential
assassins, can be applied to potentially violent students.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined in a Secret Service handbook, such assessments
involve looking for common patterns of behavior and experience,
including feelings of rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Bernice Berk, a psychologist at the Bank Street School for
Children in Manhattan, said parents needed to learn to be alert to
the anger and frustration of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long before adolescence, we need to be open to children's
humiliation and pain and discouragement,'' she said. ``Parents have
to be really willing to listen to this and accept expressions of
anger at home, whether they are tantrums or inappropriate
language.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that depression, which she called very prevalent, was
closely related to aggression. One is anger turned toward the self;
the other is anger turned toward others.
</P>
<P>
   A number of programs have sprung up around the country aimed at
helping children learn social communication and skills to cope with
frustration and anger.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee for Children, a nonprofit organization in Seattle,
offers a program called ``Second Step'' to teach violence
prevention to children as young as 4, using techniques like taking
turns and dealing with anger. The group says research shows a
marked decrease in aggression and hostility from children who have
been through the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
