<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      04-21 1759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION WONDERS `WHERE NEXT?' AS BODIES REMOVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF AND ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Tales of terror and heroism, marbled with a
thick vein of despair, began to emerge Wednesday from the
bullet-ridden, bomb-damaged high school where 15 people died in the
deadliest school attack in US history.
</P>
<P>
   As the residents of this Denver suburb wrapped themselves in
prayer and each other's arms, and the nation wondered why, and
where next, authorities began removing the bodies of one teacher
and 14 students _ two of them the suspected killers _ from
blood-spattered Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects, Eric D. Harris, 18, and Dylan Bennet Klebold,
17, misfits who dabbled in Nazi worship and other antisocial
behavior, allegedly vented their shared, murderous anger in a
Tuesday rampage that was at once viciously methodical and horribly
random. They died from apparently self-inflicted gunshot wounds to
the head, explosives attached to their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Before their deaths, during a chaotic hourlong siege, the two
masked gunmen allegedly killed eight male students, four female
students, and one male teacher whose body was found in a closet. At
least 22 others were wounded, and 16 people remained hospitalized
Wednesday, several in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities continued to withhold the names of most of the dead,
but parents of missing Columbine students huddled at a nearby
elementary school, awaiting the dreaded word and permission to take
their children home a final time.
</P>
<P>
   The killers had armed themselves with two sawed-off shotguns, a
semiautomatic rifle, and a handgun, along with several hundred
rounds of ammunition, said Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone.
Eight or nine spent cartridge clips _ each capable of containing 10
to 15 rounds _ were found in the school, as were numerous shotgun
shells. Another shotgun was seized from one of the suspects' homes,
along with a computer and other evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The two boys also came equipped with more than 30 homemade
explosive devices in three different forms: crude six- to
eight-inch hand grenades, foot-long pipe bombs, and propane
cylinders with timing devices. Several of the bombs were planted in
cars in the school's parking lot, and some of the hand-held devices
contained nails and other shrapnel, designed for maximum damage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the flood of new information, much remained in doubt.
Authorities said they did not know the source of the guns or the
bombs. They also were continuing to investigate the possibility
that other youths were involved. Stone said it might have taken
more than two people to carry the duffel bags that contained the
weapons, and District Attorney David J. Thomas said he suspected
``other people were at least aware'' of the plan and would be
prosecuted for failing to act to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any motive for this attack,'' Stone said, but
added a possible explanation: ``If these people are tied in with
one of these Hitler-type movements ... then our society is sicker
than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   No one else had been charged as of Wednesday night, and three
friends of Harris and Klebold were released after questioning
Tuesday, Stone said. Like the two suspects, the three are believed
to be members of an outcast clique called the ``Trench Coat Mafia''
that favors long black coats, military fatigues, and a disdain for
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The school Wednesday became a community mecca, with hundreds of
students and families arriving with flowers, many of them crying as
they placed them at the base of a tree as close to the school as
they could get without crossing the ubiquitous yellow police tape.
Students from Columbine's crosstown rival, Chatfield Senior High
School, created a 20- by 20-foot mural of prayers and well wishes,
festooned with flowers, then placed it on the Columbine lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Balloons and ribbons in blue and white _ the school colors _
appeared almost instantly throughout this city of 40,000. While
authorities updated hundreds of reporters about the investigation,
students formed huge prayer circles and turned a red Acura
belonging to one of the presumed victims into a shrine, complete
with candles, flowers, ribbons, and messages of love and loss.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Columbine might not reopen before the end of the
school year, though other Jefferson County schools were scheduled
to reopen Thursday with heightened security measures and counselors
on hand. ``It might be some long time before we get them back into
that school,'' Stone said. ``We've got a big mess in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardened local, state and federal authorities emerged shaken
from the school, describing a bloody scene in which they found
bodies mainly in the school's library _ 10 victims and the two
suspects were found there. The scene was made more surreal by
strobe lights, fire alarms and ankle-deep water from fire
prevention systems that were triggered when bombs exploded in the
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with witnesses and authorities suggest the gunmen
employed a carefully crafted plan in their assault.
</P>
<P>
   It began at 11:15 a.m., as half of the 1,800 Columbine students
attended classes and the other half spread out among the library,
the cafeteria and off-campus eateries. The school choir was
practicing a song planned for a graduation performance, and a gym
class was headed to the outdoor track.
</P>
<P>
   First, in either a mistake or an attempted diversion, the
suspects exploded a bomb on Wadsworth Avenue, a main road a
quarter-mile west of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at 11:30 a.m., two masked gunmen entered Columbine through
a student door near the cafeteria. Once inside, they tossed several
bombs, the explosions reverberating throughout the school. They
also sprayed bullets around a hallway and then inside the
cafeteria, wounding several students.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the school, students ran for exits, hid in storage
supply closets, and locked themselves in laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   After a few minutes, the gunmen walked upstairs to the library.
A teacher had already run into the library, warning students that
someone with a gun was in the school and they should get down. As
the students were scrambling from their seats, the gunmen entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in and said, `All you jocks get up. We're going to
kill all of you,''' said Aaron Cohn, a 15-year-old sophomore who
lives just two doors away from Harris's home. ``I heard a `crack,
crack,' and a kid fell to his knees. I'm pretty sure he was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one of the gunmen put what Cohn believes was a 12-gauge
shotgun to his head. ``I don't know why he didn't shoot. Maybe he
got distracted, maybe it was because he knew me,'' Cohn said. But
immediately afterward, the gunman walked over to a student hiding
under a library table and said, ``peek-a-boo'' then fired several
times.
</P>
<P>
   One of the killers then said, ``I hate niggers. Here's that
nigger we keep seeing running around the school.'' Then he fired
three shots, and the other asked, ``Is he dead, is he dead?'' To
which the shooter responded, ``Yeah, he's dead.'' according to
several accounts of the incident, which Cohn also witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Though witnesses say the gunmen focused on athletes and
minorities, authorities discounted that view and noted that only
one black student was killed, Isiah Shoels, who was shot three
times in the library. They declined to comment on the witness
accounts, citing the ongoing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   While the library shootings were taking place, police were
amassing outside the school. At least three sheriff's deputies,
including one stationed full-time at the school, exchanged gunfire
with the killers upon their arrival shortly after 11:30 a.m., said
Stone, the county sheriff. They did not pursue the gunmen into the
building, however.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the killers left the library and shot a teacher,
identified by witnesses as Dave Sanders. Several witnesses said
Sanders, in a characteristic act by a beloved teacher and coach,
pushed several girls to safety as he was being shot. ``He pushed my
friend out of the way and saved her life, and he got shot doing
it,'' said Kayley Boyle, 16, a junior.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours, students from a science class who had taken
refuge in a supply closet tried desperately but unsuccessfully to
save him.
</P>
<P>
   Two other victims, both students, were found dead outside the
school building. It was not immediately clear if they had been shot
there or had fled outside after being wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the ordeal, students inside the school used cell
phones to call police and media, whispering their frightened
dispatches and waiting for help.
</P>
<P>
   While the seige was under way, Klebold's father used an
intermediary to ask authorities if he could come to the school and
help. Thomas, the district attorney, said the offer was rejected
because it was not seen as helpful, partly because authorities were
not in communication with the gunmen. It was not clear how
Klebold's father knew the teen was involved.
</P>
<P>
   One SWAT team leader described arriving on the scene Tuesday
afternoon and seeing a sign in a library window that read, ``Help,
I'm bleeding to death.'' But he said he was unable to act, not
knowing whether hostages were at risk or how many gunmen were
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have had a band of terrorists in there,'' said Sgt.
George Hinkle of the Lakewood Police Department SWAT team, one of
seven that responded to the shootings. He later heard that the
sign's author was among the dead. On the other hand, he said, he
was able to position his armored vehicle under a second-story
window, helping a wounded student to climb to safety rather than
suffer a 20-foot fall or continued exposure to gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   SWAT teams did not approach what Hinkle called the ``killing
zone'' _ the library _ until roughly an hour after the shooting
began. He and other law-enforcement officials said acting sooner
could have endangered students and the SWAT team members. If a SWAT
team member were killed, it would have given the killers access to
more weapons, a bulletproof vest and a radio on which they could
have heard police transmissions, Hinkle and Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 1 p.m., when the gunshots had subsided, SWAT
teams began sweeping through the building, carefully avoiding
explosives. But by then, the gunmen were already dead and so were
their classmates and teacher.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen MacNamara of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
