<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA AND DEUTSCHE TELEKOM REACH AGREEMENT ON MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Two of Europe's largest telecommunications companies,
Telecom Italia SpA and Deutsche Telekom AG, reached a formal
agreement Wednesday night to merge in a share swap valued at nearly
$82 billion after the Italians obtained assurances that Germany
would not interfere in the new combined company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of the two former state-owned monopolies, which still
faces enormous obstacles, would be the biggest ever in Europe and
the second-biggest in history behind the $84 billion Exxon-Mobil
merger announced last year.
</P>
<P>
   The board of Telecom Italia approved the deal after the German
government, which still controls 72 percent of Deutsche Telekom's
shares, satisfied demands by Telecom Italia and offered written
assurance that it would not seek to influence the new combination's
business strategy and management.
</P>
<P>
   The merger, expected since Monday, would be the most
far-reaching in a recent wave of giant European combinations, as
companies maneuver to meet the challenges of globalization and
opening European economies.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the merger were to be announced at a news conference
on Thursday in London.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would be the second-largest
telecommunications business in the world, with revenue of $63
billion surpassed only by the Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp.
It would create the world's largest local phone service provider
and one of the biggest mobile phone companies. It would have
roughly 240,000 employees and a strong presence in Europe, Asia and
Latin America, though not in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scale is the main advantage,'' said James Thomas, a
telecommunications consultant with Arthur Andersen &AMP; Co. in London.
``In principle, it makes sense. It follows the rules of
consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger is subject to the approval of shareholders and of
Italian, German and European Union regulators. The companies said
they would also seek Securities and Exchange Commission approval in
the United States, which is required because the companies intend
to list shares in the American stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The German and Italian governments are likely to approve, seeing
the deal as necessary in the face of liberalizing
telecommunications markets and global competition.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia, in a statement, said the German and Italian
companies ``intend to integrate their activities giving life to the
world's second-largest telecommunication group.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was sought earlier this year be Telecom Italia's tough
new chief executive, Franco Bernabe, essentially as a defensive
strategy to thwart a $65 billion hostile bid for Telecom Italia by
its main domestic rival, Olivetti SpA.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti officials made clear Wednesday that they would continue
their bid and would seek approval from Italian securities
regulators on Thursday for documents to solicit shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti has bid 11.50 euros ($12.25) a share in securities and
cash for Telecom Italia, versus securities valued at 12.02 euros a
share for Telecom Italia in the deal with Deutsche Telekom. But
Olivetti officials are hoping that the complexities of the rival
bid, its size and regulatory uncertainties will sway investors
toward Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia's board had tentatively approved the deal on
Tuesday night after two days of meetings but made final agreement
contingent on a pledge by the German government, which would
control about 45 percent of the combined company, to limit its
voting rights. Telecom Italia was taken public last year, though
the Italian government retains a 3.4 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian demand appeared to have been met earlier Wednesday
when Germany's finance minister, Hans Eichel, in a letter to the
Italian Treasury, which controls Rome's stake, expressed support
for the merger and said it was the German government's policy not
to interfere in how Deutsche Telekom was run.
</P>
<P>
   That policy, he said, would also apply to the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   Eichel said Germany intended to proceed with a previously
planned sale of Deutsche Telekom shares, though only at a pace that
would not upset equity markets.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia said the deal involved an exchange of stock that
would give Deutsche Telekom shareholders a share of the combined
company for each share they now own, for 57 percent of the total.
For Telecom Italia, the exchange ratio is 1 new share for 3
ordinary shares or 5.61 nonvoting shares.
</P>
<P>
   If 90 percent of shareholders accept, the terms are sweetened
slightly to a ratio of 1 new share for every 2.9 ordinary Telecom
Italia shares, 5.5 nonvoting shares or 0.9 Deutsche Telekom share.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Deutsche Telekom's closing price of 36.08 euros
Wednesday, the deal values Telecom Italia's combined 5.26 billion
ordinary shares and 2.17 billion nonvoting shares at $81.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the deal does not include the 40 percent of Telecom
Italia's mobile phone subsidiary that the Italian company does not
own. If the merged company were to buy that as well, the value of
the deal would rise substantially.
</P>
<P>
   The shares of the new company would be quoted in Frankfurt,
Milan and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia shares have been suspended most of the week on
the Milan exchange pending news of the merger, but the company's
American depository rights traded on Wall Street have been hurt on
investor skepticism that such a deal would work. Deutsche Telekom
has likewise suffered; its price closed down 1.4 percent in
Frankfurt Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will bring together two of Europe's toughest
executives. Bernabe, 50, took over Telecom Italia in a management
shake-up late last year, after turning around the big Italian
energy group, Eni. Under the merger pact, he would be one of two
joint chief executives with Ron Sommer, 49, the Deutsche Telekom
chief. Sommer has been advised by Goldman, Sachs; Telecom Italia's
advisers include J.P. Morgan and the Credit Suisse First Boston
unit of Credit Suisse Group.
</P>
<P>
   The merger plan, which stresses equality to satisfy Italian
political sentiments, despite Deutsche Telekom's larger size,
foresees a German corporation with a 10-member supervisory board,
to set company policy and appoint management, evenly split among
Italian and German representatives. The board's chairman will
alternate each year between Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   If it proceeds, and full approval could take months, the deal
would have resounding effects through the industry. It was unclear
what name the company will bear, though German newspapers have
taken to calling it ``Telecom Transalpina.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
