<HEADLINE>
CAN IT HAPPEN HERE? ACROSS U.S., SCHOOLS WONDER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., N.H., N.Y., Mass., Ohio, Texas, Wash.)  (rk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Flags flew at half-staff; moments of prayer silenced
the halls; special assemblies gathered. But even more than posting
outward signals of distress over the killings in Littleton, Colo.,
schools around the country turned inward Wednesday with an
intensity inspired by no previous school mayhem, seeking solace and
answers and assurance.
</P>
<P>
   At Pelham Memorial High School in Pelham, N.Y., the principal,
Robert G. Shillito, distributed a letter to teachers Wednesday
asking them to ``pause to consider whether such an event could
happen here in Pelham.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we be better `tuned in' to those disaffected students in
our school who may be potential candidates for such acts?'' the
letter asked.
</P>
<P>
   Students in one creative-writing class at Pelham Memorial
composed poems about the killings, including one by a junior,
Georgia Cool, that asked, ``Do I have to look in the faces of my
friends and see potential murders?''
</P>
<P>
   In Lynnwood, Wash., a suburb of Seattle, students at Meadowdale
High School asked that the flag be lowered Wednesday, and the staff
focused largely on ``asking the students what could we do to
prevent something like that from happening here,'' said Norm
Hoffman, the principal.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said the school was trying ``to encourage students to be
proactive in preventing such a tragedy here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they know someone being humiliated or put down,'' he said,
``how do we deal with that? And if we know someone has violent
tendencies, how do we report that?''
</P>
<P>
   An English teacher at Meadowdale, Melodee MacWilliams, went so
far as to give her class a list of all the students in it, and to
assign them to write something ``kind and gentle and loving'' about
each one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about, what if someone sometime had just reached out
and said something great to one of these kids,'' she said,
referring to the Littleton killers. ``Would it have done something
great? Would it have made a difference? I had boys in my class with
tears in their eyes. They're getting it, that we are part of this
community, that we have responsibility for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. MacWilliams said the class was also interested in
brainstorming to try to explain the school shootings, from access
to computers to home abuse and prejudices.
</P>
<P>
   At Buckingham, Browne and Nichols, an academically demanding
private school in Cambridge, Mass., similar searching went on
Wednesday afternoon at a meeting of perhaps 40 students who chose
to get together in the library ``quiet room'' and discuss the
Littleton shootings, said Morgan Meade, the dean of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a fair amount of speculation about what would drive
someone to do something like that,'' Meade said. ``Is there a level
of anger or despair in students that they haven't experienced in
people they know? Is it a desire for fame or infamy? Is it the
parents of the people who do that, have they done something
wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, he said, ``I was saying that I thought probably
the most you could do was to try to recognize people who seemed to
be isolated and unhappy and connect to those people rather than
sort of responding to the vibes that those kids send out by pulling
away.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also some discussion of school safety, he said; as
there was in other schools like Indian Hill High School in
Cincinnati, where teachers gathered in part to get some extra
assurances on the school's ``intruder procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, schools seemed to be largely prepared on
how to deal with major crises like shootings, already too familiar
with the issues from past school violence and generally already
fixed for crisis training and management. A few reported taking
extra precautions, watching out for copycats and increasing
patrols, but most already had safety procedures established in the
wake of past incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, school reactions focused more on students' immediate
emotional well-being. Many reported issuing announcements that
counselors were available to all who wanted to talk. At Johnston
High School in Austin, Tex., the principal instructed social
studies teachers to discuss the shootings with students.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Cardenas, a senior, broadcast a commentary on the high
school's closed-circuit television in which he told his fellow
students, ``All we can do is hope for the best for the families of
the dead and work our hearts out to make sure this doesn't happen
here, to us.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar theme resounded at Bishop Brady High School in
Concord, N.H., which barely escaped its own shooting this January.
A student brought a gun and 500 rounds of ammunition to the small
parochial school, and was reported to have had a list of students
and faculty members he intended to shoot. But he was arrested after
another student reported him, said the principal, Jean Barker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the kids here were listening to the news and all of
a sudden started thinking, `Oh, gracious, this is what we
avoided,'' she said. The school held an assembly about the
shootings and devoted a morning prayer to the citizens of
Littleton, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Portsmouth, N.H., when the superintendent of public schools,
Suzanne Schrader, visited high school classes Wednesday morning,
every teacher was talking to students about the shootings, she
said, listening and offering support as they made remarks like, ``I
kept thinking, that could have been me, that could have been my
brother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
