A8170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITIES22     04-21 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-DISABILITIES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High court is cautious in ADA case
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Supreme Court justices Wednesday expressed
concern that the high court may do more harm than good if it rules
in favor of two Georgia women in what is widely considered to be a
landmark civil rights case for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The court heard arguments on whether the Americans with
Disabilities Act prohibits the unnecessary institutionalization of
the mentally disabled if doctors say they are ready for release.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia case was brought by Elaine Wilson and Lois Curtis,
two mentally disabled patients who sought release from Georgia
Regional Hospital in DeKalb County. They won lower court rulings
that require the state to pay for their mental health treatment in
a homelike setting, such as a group home.
</P>
<P>
   Both Wilson, 47, and Curtis, 31, came to Washington to hear
arguments on their case but were unable to get seats in the packed
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, more than 100 disability rights
activists, many in wheelchairs, rallied beneath huge banners that
read, ``Civil Rights Not States Rights'' and ``Don't Tread on the
ADA.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go get 'em, Elaine!'' Marcie Roth, a member of ADAPT, a
disability rights group, yelled to Wilson as she walked away from
the courthouse. ``Free our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the court's nine justices asked the women's attorney
for reassurance over the consequences of a court ruling that
requires states to move mentally disabled patients out of state
institutions and into community settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me is writing something which, as it works out in
the real world, leaves many who need to be in institutions turned
out and abandoned on the streets,'' Justice Stephen Breyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said that an estimated 70,000 people are now being served
in state mental institutions nationwide. Many need to be there, he
said, and if the court requires states to move mental health
patients into community settings, many who need the institutional
services may be released, also.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the possibilities,'' Justice John Paul
Stevens added. ``States, in order to avoid the risk of liability,
will push people out in that direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Gottesman, a Georgetown University law professor who
argued on behalf of Wilson and Curtis, said that mentally disabled
patients in state institutions can only be released when state
doctors say they are ready to go. And, in Wilson and Curtis' case,
state doctors had decided they should be released from Georgia
Regional, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overriding goal of the Americans With Disabilities Act is
to remove the barriers that prevent disabled people from gaining
access to the mainstream of society,'' Gottesman told the court.
</P>
<P>
   He added that if there is ever a dispute over whether a mental
health patient should be released from an institution, court
precedent dictates that the state's mental health experts be given
deference on that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Since their lawsuit was filed in 1995, both women have been
released from Georgia Regional. Wilson shares an apartment in
College Park with a roommate; Curtis lives in a group home in
Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   The case is the first of four the high court is considering this
month that will help define the legal boundaries of the Americans
With Disabilities Act. A decision in the Georgia case is expected
by late June.
</P>
<P>
   The ADA, signed into law in 1990, opened the workplace to
persons with disabilities and required the removal of the physical
barriers that inhibited their access to public facilities.
</P>
<P>
   A good portion of Wednesday's hourlong arguments involved
justices peppering attorneys with hypothetical questions as to what
constitutes actual discrimination under the law. But Justice Sandra
Day O'Connor sought to steer the arguments away from that and focus
on the exact meaning of a regulation that requires public services
and programs be offered ``in the most integrated setting
appropriate to the needs'' of people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this case actually turns on is the interpretation of the
regulation,'' O'Connor said. ``Isn't that what this boils down
to?''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Downing, assistant attorney general for the state of
Georgia, agreed that it did and said Georgia believes that Title II
of the ADA ``applies to even-handed treatment of the handicapped as
opposed to the nonhandicapped.''
</P>
<P>
   To say it requires states to pay for the placements of mentally
disabled patients in community settings is too liberal an
interpretation of the law and not what it says, Downing said.
</P>
<P>
   Gottesman and Assistant Solicitor General Irving Gornstein,
representing the Clinton administration, told the justices that
Congress intended the ADA to be interpreted much more broadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isolation and segregation in an institution is a pervasive
form of discrimination,'' Gottesman said, adding that even the
state agrees that it is ``much, much more cheap to treat these
people in a community setting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
