<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CHOICE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1,058 kids in Georgia winners of tuition aid
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two of America's wealthiest businessmen will pay about
half the private school tuition for 1,058 of Georgia's poorer
children who were lucky enough to win the scholarships in a massive
national lottery announced Wednesday to promote the politics of
school choice.
</P>
<P>
   The media event at the New York Public Library, announcing the
selection of 40,000 of 1.25 million applicants for a total of $160
million over four years, highlighted the apparent hunger of many
low-income families to opt out of public schools they see as
disorderly, unnurturing and scary. The program, which pays for four
years of a child's education, represents a new type of corporate
investment in education, on the theory that marketlike competition
will shake up the lowest-performing public schools, especially in
inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old debate is over,'' said Ted Forstmann, a financier
known for corporate buyouts and chairman of the Children's
Scholarship Fund. ``These families have ended it. In anybody's book
this is a thunderous demonstration of dissatisfaction with the
present system _ and of the demand for alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The winners are not necessarily poor or dissatisfied. For
example, Gwendylon Smith, a corporate account executive for
BellSouth Entertainment in Atlanta, won a CSF scholarship for her
daughter Juanita, 6, a first-grader at Atlanta's Collier Heights
Elementary School. Smith will look into private schools with
tuitions ranging from $3,000 to more than $10,000, although
Juanita's scholarship will only be as much as $1,700. With the same
cap and a sliding scale of income restrictions, poorer families get
75 percent of tuition, wealthier families 25 percent. Parents must
contribute part of tuition _ on average, $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the American system, to have choice,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta alone, 13,798 applied after heavy advertising and
word-of-mouth excitement; 380 won the grant.
</P>
<P>
   While some corporate leaders in Georgia are investing in this
side of reform, the overwhelming bulk of private contribution to
education in Georgia is still with improving public schools by
raising standards, said Tom Upchurch, president of the Georgia
Partnership for Excellence in Education, sponsored by foundations
and business. ``Most of these folks believe we have to raise all
boats,'' Upchurch said of businesses that donate to education in
Georgia. ``They're concerned about those that are left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The CSF, also led by Wal-Mart heir John Walton, has celebrities
and civil rights leaders on its board, including former Atlanta
Mayor Andrew Young and Southern Christian Leadership Conference
head Martin Luther King III, who doesn't necessarily support tax
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
