<HEADLINE>
BORDERS' NEW CEO SUDDENLY QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Tenn., Fla.)  (bl)  
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just a little more than five months after boasting about hiring
Philip Pfeffer, a longtime book industry executive, as its chief
executive, Borders Group Inc. unceremoniously announced his abrupt
departure Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company, the second-largest bookseller in the nation after
Barnes &AMP; Noble, also said that its first-quarter earnings would be
4 cents to 5 cents a share, lower than analysts' estimates of 7
cents. On the news, shares of Borders fell $2.4375, or 14 percent,
to $14.625.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeffer's departure was so sudden and surprising that several
top executives were not even at the company's headquarters in Ann
Arbor, Mich., for the announcement. The executive who handles
investor relations was away, so the chief financial officer faxed
news releases describing what the company called Pfeffer's
resignation. The executive who deals with inquiries from the news
media was on vacation, so an independent agency fielded questions
about the management shuffle that resulted in Pfeffer's departure
and chairman Robert DiRomualdo's return as interim chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, all I can say is that it just wasn't a good fit and we
want to move on,'' said DiRomualdo, declining to elaborate. Borders
said it would take a one-time after-tax charge of 4 cents a share
in connection with Pfeffer's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   As late as last week, Pfeffer was still seen as firmly in
charge, appearing at meetings to discuss detailed strategies for
the company's activities. Pfeffer, whose company voice mail was cut
off Wednesday, did not respond to messages left at his apartment in
Michigan or at his permanent home in Tennessee, where his family
has remained over the years since he left his position as chief
executive of Ingram Distribution Group to become president and
chief operating officer of Random House Inc. in New York and then
to head Borders.
</P>
<P>
   Borders hired Pfeffer in November, less than a week after its
rival, Barnes &AMP; Noble, announced a $600 million purchase of Ingram
Book Group, the nation's largest book distributor, which is part of
Ingram Distribution. With his knowledge of distribution and book
publishing, Pfeffer was seen as an able leader for Borders, which
is trying to catch up with the two leaders in electronic
bookselling, Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pfeffer came to Borders after clearly being passed over
for the chief executive's job at Random House when the company was
acquired by the media conglomerate Bertelsmann AG and joined with
Bantam Doubleday Dell. At Random House, he was criticized for
having a tendency to be a micromanager, but at Borders he had
barely had enough chance to absorb the company culture, since he
spent so much time traveling to its far-flung outposts.
</P>
<P>
   One Borders employee said the resignation came as a shock to
much of the corporate staff, but that there had been hints that
Pfeffer was being reined in by his bosses.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the employee said, in the winter, DiRomualdo, who
maintains a home in Florida, started attending more meetings along
with Pfeffer.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's announcement, it was DiRomualdo who conducted
sessions with several hundred employees to explain management
changes, which also included the promotion of Cedric Vanzura as
president of Borders On-Line, and to detail strategies involving
the promotion of retail stores and the company's Web site
interchangeably.
</P>
<P>
   An employee who was there said Pfeffer's resignation did not
come up during the meeting, even though he had been an enthusiastic
supporter of the concept that the company likes to call ``retail
convergence.''
</P>
<P>
   DiRomualdo said in a telephone interview that he was prepared to
stay on as chief executive for as long as it takes for a new search
committee to find a leader with an ``open mind'' to preside over a
company with interests in both electronic commerce and retail
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, analysts were hard pressed to evaluate what Pfeffer's
exit meant for the future of the company _ except that uncertainty
was not good for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Turnof Fox, an analyst at J.P. Morgan Securities, said
the changes highlighted the company's need to accelerate
``superstore growth and raise the visibility of Borders.com.'' But
that is a difficult task for anyone to achieve, she said, noting
that, given Pfeffer's short tenure, ``it would be very unfair to
blame him for coming in below expectations _ his job is not to
guide analysts to certain numbers.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
