<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMISTS-ECONSCENE-     04-21 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMISTS-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: UNEMPLOYMENT'S NATURAL RATE MAY HAVE A MIND OF ITS
OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Economists are compulsive naysayers _ professionally dedicated
to tweaking anyone naive enough to overlook the fact that good
things have a cost and not all good things are affordable or
possible. This spinach-eating mentality partly explains why they
failed to predict the relentless good news in the 1990s, during
which the growth rate of productivity rose and unemployment and
inflation rates fell by half.
</P>
<P>
   That felicitous combination was supposed to be impossible.
Driving unemployment down was thought to drive inflation up, and
economists ridiculed anyone, especially politicians, who denied the
vicious trade-off. By the end of the decade, economists find
themselves without an explanation of high productivity or low
unemployment, the keys to economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   A discipline in crisis? Not really. Just because economists,
like physicists, do not have a Theory of Everything, that doesn't
mean they cannot explain a lot about what has happened in the 1990s
_ such as the increasing concentration on unemployment rolls of
people who are permanently out of work.
</P>
<P>
   Economies change, with academic theories following close behind.
In the 1930s, Keynes taught the profession that government could
spend its way out of a recession. True enough, but the sense that
economists could manage endless prosperity did not survive the
rising inflation of the 1960s wartime economy. Tight labor markets
led to rising wages, which, in turn, led to higher prices. Paul
Samuelson and Robert Solow of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology taught the profession the logic of the Phillips curve,
the inescapable trade-off between unemployment and inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But even that formulation proved overly optimistic. Inflation in
the economy, propelled by loose monetary policy, did not just jump
to a higher level and stay there. Inflation accelerated, rising to
higher rates each year. Economists began to preach a tougher
message. There was, alas, no permanent trade-off between inflation
and unemployment. If government tried to drive unemployment below
its so-called natural rate, it would accelerate inflation,
threatening monetary stability and eventually forcing the Federal
Reserve to crack down. Enter Paul Volcker, the Fed chairman who
broke the back of the 1970s inflation spiral by throwing the
economy in deep recession (and throwing President Jimmy Carter out
of office).
</P>
<P>
   Economists forever warn against advice by Pollyannas who urge
the Fed to stimulate and then stimulate some more. The natural rate
dictates how far the Fed could go in generating jobs. By the end of
the 1980s, some economists thought the natural rate hovered around
7 percent. Others argued for 6 or 6.5 percent. Liberals hoped for 5
percent. Almost no one thought it could be any lower.
</P>
<P>
   Until now. Last year joblessness fell to 4.5 percent. Some
economists called on the Fed to tighten monetary policy to ward off
inflation before it could take hold. Alan Greenspan, the Fed
chairman, chose instead to wait for inflation to rise before he
cracked down. It did not, so he did not.
</P>
<P>
   Today, unemployment is under 4.5 percent and inflation is
 &UR; falling &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Professor Robert J. Gordon of Northwestern University attributes
much of the favorable inflation data to special events of no
long-term significance _ falling food, oil, import and medical
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Professors Alan Krueger and Robert Shimer of Princeton and
Lawrence Katz of Harvard estimate that the natural rate probably
fell by about 1 percentage point, in part because of the aging and
growing stability of the labor force and the rising use of
temporary workers by employers.
</P>
<P>
   The largely unnoticed lesson of the Katz-Krueger data is that
almost the entire drop in unemployment, from around 9 percent early
in the decade to under 4.5 percent now, is from the ranks of the
short-term unemployed. Students, spouses and laid-off workers find
jobs quickly. Those who remain unemployed are people who have a
hard time finding work at all, presumably because they have a
physical or mental limitation.
</P>
<P>
   This finding colors policy responses. Temporarily unemployed
people need job-search assistance. The economically disadvantaged
need expensive training and government subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Solow and Krueger, under the auspices of the Russell Sage
Foundation and the Century Foundation, are putting together a team
of economists to pursue the unanswered questions. How low is the
sustainable rate of unemployment, and can monetary and fiscal
policies maintain it or push it even lower?
</P>
<P>
   As for monetary policy, says Professor Robert Hall of Stanford,
``the 1990s have taught central bankers here and abroad that the
best policy is to set clear targets for inflation and stick by
them.'' The task is hard because monetary policy operates with long
lags. That means the Fed must make predictions about the state of
the economy a year into the future. One, but hardly the only,
factor in that prediction is where the Fed thinks the unemployment
rate is relative to the natural rate.
</P>
<P>
   But with or without knowledge of the elusive natural rate, the
Fed can and does make continual assessment of inflationary
pressures. Professor Hall argues that if the Fed convinces traders
in financial markets that inflation will be low and steady, the
economy will gravitate toward the lowest possible unemployment
rate.
</P>
<P>
   Smart policy, by this argument, reveals the natural rate. Smart
policy does not, Hall says, need prior knowledge of the natural
rate. That may be the most optimistic spin on policy making since
Keynes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
