u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     04-21 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SCHOOL MISFITS, `JOCKS' FREQUENTLY THE ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Petitpas is cq; a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a cliche of every high school sports movie from ``Peggy
Sue Got Married'' to ``Varsity Blues.'' Think of bully Biff in
``Back to the Future.'' Every day students are jealous and afraid
of the football stars. Too often, the student-athlete elites make
matters worse by teasing the weak, the pimply, and the uncool.
</P>
<P>
   But there is nothing cliche about murder in a high school
corridor, and for the first time there's a hint that the
traditional scholastic caste system may have played a part the
killing spree that left 15 dead at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   While officials counted bodies and spoke of ``outcast'' boys,
our nation wondered about some of the preverse motivation behind
this latest act of bloodshed. To the best of anyone's recollection,
this was the first time ``jocks'' were cited as targets in a school
carnage.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that members of the now-infamous ``Trenchcoat Mafia''
hated minorities and may have chosen the anniversary of Adolph
Hitler's birth for the date of their shooting spree. But a new
wrinkle surfaced as student survivors spoke of the rebel group's
hatred for the boys and girls who starred in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to the young voices of Columbine survivors:
</P>
<P>
   Nada Alami, a freshman, said, ``All I know is that they hate
jocks and stuff.'' Senior Denee Taylor said, ``They got picked on
all the time by the jocks and other people, saying things like `Why
do you wear black? Can't you change your clothes?' I heard (one
suspect) shot a black guy right in the face, and that they went
after other jocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Beard told CNN's Larry King that Trenchcoat members
``talked about how jocks, how all the football players, were in a
world of their own, thinking they were on top of everything and
nothing mattered to them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to witnesses, during the attack, one of the killers
yelled, ``All jocks stand up! We're going to kill every one of
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctor Albert J. Petitpas, director of the Athletic Counseling
Program at Springfield (Mass.) College, said, ``Often athletes are
seen as an over-privileged minority. They get the glory and the
tangible rewards. They have the most revered status among their
peers and you can imagine a group feeling alienated would resent
that.''
</P>
<P>
   High schools are divided into cliques of jocks, cheerleaders,
A-students, average kids, criminals, and misfits. Rent ``The
Breakfast Club.'' It's the definitive cinematic explanation of
American high school strata. Gathering one specimen from each
clique _ like some kind of high school Noah _ a detention
supervisor punishes a wrestler, a prom queen, a brain, a
delinquent, and a disheveled girl who appears incapable of uttering
a declarative sentence. The students know that the teacher sees
only the stereotype, not the person. This is how kids get labeled.
It is the genesis of the self-fullfilling prophecy that plagues so
many of our young people.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in Littleton can never be explained or justified,
but it appears to be the ultimate act of revenge from a group that
felt ridiculed, excluded, and bullied.
</P>
<P>
   One Columbine student described the Trenchcoat Mafia as,
``nerds, geeks, and dweebs trying to find someplace to fit in.''
Another student, Bree Pasquale, who narrowly escaped death, said,
``He just put a gun to my head and asked us if we wanted to die.
(He) started laughing and said, `I'm doing this because people made
fun of me last year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It would appear that some athletes were shot because they were
among the ones who bullied the weak.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor Judy Van Raalte, an associate professor of psychology at
Springfield (with a specialty in sport psychology), said, ``There's
no research database for this, but I think student- athletes can
become targets, and there are several reasons. They are seen as
privleged. They have the clothing and the uniforms and the
letterjacket. Sometimes there's special considerations regarding
schoolwork. They are part of a high visibility clique. Sometimes
there's a certain cockiness, or a way of treating other students
which could contribute to it. This is not true of all athletes, but
it is true of some.''
</P>
<P>
   Celtic guard Ron Mercer, who graduated from Oak Hill Academy
(boys and girls) in Virginia in 1995, said, ``I didn't experience
that sort of thing. Maybe because it was a private school. I didn't
feel we had that many cliques. But certain people, certain athletes
carried themselves in a different way and maybe in this case, these
guys took it out on all the athletes as a group.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia 76er veteran Rick Mahorn, a product of Weaver High
School in Hartford, Conn., said, ``I was more of a student in high
school. I didn't even play basketball until my senior year. But
it's not athletes and non-athletes. People are people, man.''
</P>
<P>
   High schools will always have cliques. It's been going on since
long before poodle skirts, burger stands and jukeboxes. Jocks rule.
Jocks are cool. And sometimes jocks are cruel. Meanwhile, kids who
might grow up to become Bill Gates are nerds. At a vulnerable age,
they are made to feel weak, stupid, and ugly. But no one was
prepared for this, and no one can excuse it.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, the cliques were just stupid and mean, an awful
part of high school life. But then came the bloodshed, the heinous
revenge of the nerds.
</P>
<P>
   No lesson here. We already knew that size, speed, and muscle are
no match for sawed-off shotguns, semi-automatic rifles, and
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist; material from wire services
was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
