<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-EARNINGS22-COX     04-21 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke profit down 13% for quarter
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Coca-Cola Co., suffering its first quarterly
decline in case sales in more than a decade, reported Wednesday a
13 percent drop in first-quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize our short-term performance is not what you're used
to and not what you expect,'' Chairman M. Douglas Ivester told 600
shareholders at its annual meeting here. ``It does mark a rare
occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has been hit hard by recessions in many parts
of the globe, actually earned a penny more per share than Wall
Street analysts had been predicting.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company's stock climbed 3.5 percent Wednesday
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola earned $747 million, or 30 cents a share, vs. $857
million, or 34 cents a share, in the first quarter of last year.
Net operating revenue fell 1 percent to $4.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Unit case volume, defined as the number of 24 eight-ounce
servings sold by bottlers to retailers, also dropped 1 percent
worldwide. Last year, by contrast, it rose 14 percent in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke is weathering one of the more difficult macroeconomic
environments it has seen in over a decade,'' said Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter analyst Andrew Conway. ``We'll get one more challenging
quarter, and then I think there will be some volume and earnings
growth, which will lead to better stock price performance.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, Conway predicts the stock will rise to
$75 a share. He thinks worldwide volume growth will be flat in the
second quarter after rising 10 percent in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, worldwide volume will rise 3 percent to 4 percent
in the third quarter and 5 percent to 6 percent in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca-Cola still vigorously supports their business around the
globe, which tells you they're managing the process, instead of
having the process manage them,'' said Marty Romm, an analyst with
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   While volume grew 1.5 percent in the United States in the first
quarter, it was hurt by rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some short-term consumer sticker shock,'' said John
Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest. But he expects
U.S. volume to increase in the next two quarters after consumers
get used to the higher prices, which averaged about 2 percent in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Coca-Cola and its bottlers are reducing prices in
Brazil and Russia, where turbulent economies are hurting case
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are monitoring consumer behavior and adapting our
tactics,'' Ivester told shareholders at the uneventful, 90-minute
annual meeting, where there were few negative comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though global economic conditions are dampening our
volume and earnings growth during the first part of this year, our
long-term growth potential remains unchanged,'' Ivester said. ``Our
system has never been better equipped to convert that potential
into long-term value.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predict Coca-Cola will earn $1.40 a share in 1999,
which would be the same as last year, or higher by a penny or two.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
