<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTHDAY22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lighten up packaging to cut down on trash
 &HT;    By Eric Sundquist
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On this Earth Day, there's finally a good answer to
the old checkout-line question: ``Paper or plastic?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer: ``It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   At least it doesn't matter very much, environmentally speaking.
The kind of grocery bag you choose is far less important than what
you put into it. Boxes, bottles, cans and other heavy packaging are
the real landfill cloggers.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing just 10 common consumer products with lightweight
packaging, the average household can keep up to 286 pounds of
packaging a year out of the trash, the Michigan-based environmental
group Use Less Stuff reports.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a breakfast cereal in a plastic bag rather than a
bag-lined box, for example, would save that household nearly nine
pounds a year. Buying soft drinks in plastic bottles instead of
boxed aluminum cans would save 19 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the group's related conclusions runs counter to
conventional wisdom. ULS urges shoppers to buy the lightest, most
flexible packaging _ even if it's not recyclable. ``Light makes
right,'' declares ULS newsletter editor Robert M. Lilienfeld.
</P>
<P>
   That's because heavy, rigid packaging, such as glass bottles,
requires more energy to make and to truck to stores. Recycling
requires even more energy _ if the material gets recycled at all.
Compared to a heavy bottle, a light _ unrecyclable _ juice box is
cheaper to ship and takes up less landfill space.
</P>
<P>
   Many lighter-packaged goods also are cheaper. Cereal in a bag
would save a family $65 a year compared with cereal in a box.
</P>
<P>
   Through most this century, manufacturers have increased
packaging with their products, in part to make the products more
attractive on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   But some have cut back. Lilienfeld cites Proctor &AMP; Gamble as a
leader in reducing packaging on laundry products, such as Tide
detergent, which it sells in lightweight ``refill'' bags and
bottles. For those still troubled by paper vs. plastic, Lilienfeld
has this advice: If you live near a waterway, go with paper, so
plastic won't accidentally end up in the water. If you're
land-locked, the environmental harm is less with plastic bags _
particularly if you use them to avoid buying trash-can liners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
