<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC GOLFER ROSALES TAKES ON PAC-10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's hidden from view most of the time, two
dolphins blissfully swimming together on Jennifer Rosales' right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Like most things, Rosales simply decided she wanted a tattoo and
got it. No questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get one and feel the pain of getting one. I almost
died,'' Rosales said. ``I think my mom will freak out if she finds
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably no more or less than USC's golf coaches would if they
knew their franchise player has already gone bungee jumping and
identified skydiving as her next pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   They were already uneasy when Rosales went skiing for the first
time last month, right in the middle of golf season, and bruised
her leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very adventurous. She'll try everything,'' said her
sister, Michelle. ``She wants to go skydiving but I won't let
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosales, and her go-for-broke attitude, is not your typical
golfer. And that's partly why she has become one of the best in
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not thinking knock it close to the pin,'' USC women's
golf coach Andrea Gaston said. ``She's thinking about knocking it
in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach will usually tell me to just lay it up,'' Rosales said.
``I say, `No, I'm going to go for it.' I'm a gutsy player.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with Rosales' success. Certainly, few
20-year-old college golfers have experienced her fame. A native of
the Philippines, she was regarded as a national hero even before
she won the 1998 NCAA individual championship.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers refer to her as the ``queen of Asia's fairway,'' or
the ``darling of the president,'' because former president Fidel
Ramos is among her admirers.
</P>
<P>
   She won the country's amateur championship five straight times
between the ages of 14-19, and has won tournaments in China,
Malaysia and Hong Kong. Although she loves the attention, she has
to become a completely different person when she returns to the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back home, I have to dress up every time I go out. Here, I
dress any way I want,'' Rosales said. ``Here, I can be myself.
Nobody is watching me.''
</P>
<P>
   The native press can also be unforgiving if Rosales performs
below expectations. She learned that lesson in December, when she
unexpectedly lost the country's amateur championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press gave me a hard time. They said I gained weight,''
Rosales said. Newspaper stories referred to her as ``Chunky
Jennifer,'' although she weighs only about 120 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love me or hate me. It was pretty tough to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   USC has had no complaints with Rosales. She is ranked No. 2 in
the country in the Collegiate Golf Rankings, and will try to win
her first Pacific-10 individual title beginning today at Stanford.
Next month, she will try to defend her NCAA title in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even believe it right now. It's still like a dream
come true,'' Rosales said about winning the championship last year.
</P>
<P>
   The title capped a stressful season for Rosales. She left her
family for the first time when she enrolled at USC last spring.
Once she arrived, she had to balance academics with playing golf
for USC, while also trying to fulfill commitments playing for her
country.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, she nearly went back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, I'm just going to die,'' Rosales said. ``My first
semester was pretty hard. I'm glad I stayed or there would have
been no NCAA championship for me.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason Rosales remained is her sister. Michelle had already
moved to Southern California, and provided support and a familiar
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very big adjustment,'' Michelle said. ``We're pampered
in the Philippines. We had like three or four nannies to do
everything. She had to learn to cook, to wash her clothes. She had
to adjust pretty fast.''
</P>
<P>
   To everything except school, that is. Rosales plans to turn pro
after the NCAA championships, even though her sister and Gaston
would prefer she return for her junior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so done,'' Rosales said. ``My career is golf. I can't
picture myself sitting down at a computer. It's just not me. I'd
rather teach golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosales is so consumed by the sport that she named her cat
Slice. And one of her dogs is named O.B., or out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston thinks Rosales would benefit from another year at USC
before joining the LPGA tour, but knows that her star player is
virtually guaranteed endorsement deals because of her popularity at
home and her NCAA title-winning performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer just loves golf. She has not seen the value of
education for herself,'' Gaston said. ``I don't feel the value of
education in her country is being totally encouraged. But I
remember when you're 20 years old, you don't always listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosales admits she is easily distracted and doesn't have the
discipline to be a dedicated student.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I have a hard time saying no,'' Rosales said.
``Even if I have plans to study and someone says let's go out, I
say, `OK, I'm in.'''
</P>
<P>
   There are advantages to this mindset. Rosales does not get
intimidated by other golfers and says she almost never gets nervous
on the course. Other golfers have actually been afraid of her when
she wears her trademark black shoes and Oakley sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I play good when I'm under pressure.
I'm in a zone.I was dealing with pressure since I was 13. That
helped me a lot,'' Rosales said. ``When I'm at the tee box, I feel
I'm on top of the world. No one can intimidate me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
