<SLUG> BC-THQ-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOON LIKELY TO AID THQ EARNINGS, ANALYSTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. -- ``Rugrats,'' wrestling and higher revenues
are expected to provide a 32 percent boost to videogame maker THQ
Inc.'s first quarter earnings due out today.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus of analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. expects the
Calabasas-based company to earn 75 cents per share, on sales of
approximately $72 million, compared to 57 cents per share in the
like period one year ago.
</P>
<P>
   THQ develops and publishes titles for Sony, Sega and Nintendo
game consoles. Though best known for its World Championship
Wrestling games, the company last year lost that lucrative license
in a bidding war to competitor Electronic Arts and has since
shifted much of its resources to other titles, including games
based on the popular ``Rugrats'' children's television program.
</P>
<P>
   Under its contract with WCW, THQ must stop marketing games with
the well-known label this summer. But the gamemaker has already
signed a deal with the smaller World Wrestling Federation to market
games featuring that group's characters beginning in November.
</P>
<P>
   THQ's stock is trading at a lower multiple of earnings than
other companies in its sector, in part because of concern over the
loss of the WCW license, which at one point accounted for more than
two-thirds of the company's sales. THQ shares have a
price-to-earnings ratio of 16.6, compared to an industry average of
just under 30. But analyst Anthony Gikas at U.S. Bancorp Piper
Jaffray said such investor worry is misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look back at 1997 and 1998, THQ published two wrestling
games a year, one at the start and one just before the holiday
season,'' Gikas said. ``They're doing exactly the same thing this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gikas, like most of the seven analysts following THQ, considers
the stock at its current price to represent a buying opportunity.
THQ shares closed up 62.5 cents Wednesday at $23.50.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
