<SLUG> BC-NEWHALL-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWHALL LAND'S EARNINGS PREDICTED TO BE PLEASING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALENCIA, Calif. -- Analysts expect few surprises when The
Newhall Land and Farming Company, Santa Clarita's predominant
developer, releases its quarterly earnings today.
</P>
<P>
   Sutro and Co. Inc., the only research firm that actively tracks
Newhall Land, estimates the Valencia-based company will post
earnings of 26 cents per partnership unit for the quarter the ended
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The company posted earnings of just 1 cent a share in the first
quarter of last year, but a major land sale accounted for almost
all of this quarter's expected increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on track for an excellent 1999,'' company spokeswoman
Marlee Lauffer said Wednesday. ``We're continuing to experience
strong activity in every area of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those earnings are the result of the March sale of
Newhall Land's last large parcel in Cowell Ranch, a developing area
of Northern California. Company officials said the $10.5 million
sale would contribute about $8 million, or 24 cents a partnership
unit, to quarterly earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Newhall Land partnership units -- which trade like stock but do
not grant voting rights -- were up 25 cents to $26.875 Wednesday.
The units have been boosted in recent days by a general upswing
among real estate stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're on track,'' said analyst Katherine Flores, a
Sutro and Co. associate. ``I expect it to continue with the rest of
the real estate recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Flores estimated the company would earn 64 cents per unit next
quarter, fed mainly by revenues from residential lot sales and a
pending $31.8 million sale of a luxury apartment site.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hendrickson, an analyst at Los Angeles-based B. Riley and
Co., said the value of the company's assets are a more important
indicator of its health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not focusing on the bottom-line number,'' he said.
``We're looking at the value of their assets and the value they're
building for shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutro and Co. estimates the company's net asset value at $35.60
a unit.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
