<HEADLINE>
REVENUE RISE FORECAST AT 20TH CENTURY INDUSTRIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODLAND HILLS, Calif. -- Auto insurance giant 20th Century
Industries Inc. is expected to report before the markets open today
that first quarter earnings rose nearly 4 percent compared with the
like year-ago period, in large part on the strength of new business
in three states it added to its market area.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodland Hills-based company is expected to report that the
company's net income for the period ended March 31 was $28.9
million, or 33 cents per share, compared with last year's $27.9
million, or 34 cents per share. The per-share results would be
lower because the company has 5.1 million more common shares
outstanding this quarter than it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues are expected to hit $219.5 million, up 2 percent from
last year's $215.1 million, despite some rate decreases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business is growing and we have taken a rate decrease in
California of 6.8 percent and in Arizona of 9.7 percent for
competitive reasons,'' Ric Hill, the company's vice president of
corporate relations, said late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in mid-December, 20th Century began operating in
Nevada, Oregon and Washington. ``But the first quarter of 1999 is
when we actually did the business,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of actual earnings, (we're) above last year,'' Hill
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of 20th Century rose 6.25 cents Wednesday to close at
$16.8125. New York-based American International Group, the largest
U.S. insurer by market value, owns a majority stake in 20th
Century.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
