<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fortune looks at sex on company time
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The National Inquirer has nothing on America's
mainstream business press these days, judging from the latest cover
stories.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune (May 10) says corporate America is ``addicted to sex,''
and this is creating costly problems from sexual harassment to
cybersex on company time to expense account abuse on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my patients are CEOs or doctors or attorneys or
priests,'' the director of an Arizona clinic tells Fortune. ``We
have corporate America's leadership marching through here, and
they're paying cash because they don't want anybody to know.''
</P>
<P>
   While most industries are affected by work-related sex problems
to some degree, Fortune says a few stand out, especially Wall
Street. At the same time, recovery programs for people with a
problem are proliferating, says Fortune, whose May 10 edition goes
on newsstands Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Business Week (April 26) profiles another type of
``scandal on Wall Street'' in its latest cover story.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes at the traditionally quiet and clean American
Stock Exchange, the magazine says a six-month investigation shows
this institution to be ``beset by price-fixing, conflicts of
interest and illegal trading _ made possible by a climate of lax
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   P.O.V. (May) offers advice to the hapless employee who is at the
mercy of a boss who is also ``a psychotic, disorganized,
manic-depressive, power-mad control freak.'' Defensive maneuvers
range from transfer to another department, to flattery, to tuning
him or her out. Remember, the magazine says, ``nobody ever said the
workplace was fair. Your goal should simply be making it more
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth considering ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Many small investors have been introduced to stock market
investing through 401(k) plans, but Kiplinger's Personal Finance
Magazine (May) says you still have to work at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a Wall Street wizard to make a 401(k)
plan work its magic, but you need a plan,'' says the magazine.
``You can't leave something this important to happenstance or
guesswork.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bloomberg Personal Finance (May), meanwhile, has a solution
for investors torn between putting money in big stocks (market
values of $100 billion or more) or small stocks (less than $1
billion). Try midcaps, especially those that are listed in the S&AMP;P
Midcap 400 index.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do many of them outperform the larger stocks of the S&AMP;P
500, many get big enough to be added to the 500-stock list. When
that happens, institutions suddenly take an interest and become
buyers of those shares, bidding up the price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Technology stocks have taken something of a drubbing recently,
but they have a record of outperforming the market over a longer
period. That, says Individual Investor (May) is why ``tech funds
are sprouting all over, and there's one for every taste.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
