<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARNINGS-MARKETPLACE-     04-21 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARNINGS-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS PROVE HAPPY SURPRISE FOR WALL STREET
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First-quarter earnings reports are pouring in, and they are
pleasing. Citigroup beat Wall Street estimates by 16 percent. IBM
had a robust quarter. Boeing pleasantly surprised. International
Paper's earnings fell less than expected while its executives
pointed to rising paper prices and returning demand in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Even Exxon, which experienced a sharp drop in earnings because
of plummeting oil prices in January and February, beat analyst
estimates by a penny. Similarly, Coca-Cola's revenues and profits
did not fall as much as had been feared, giving its stock a lift
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Positive earnings surprises are running higher than the
historical average, with about half the 500 companies in the
Standard &AMP; Poor's index of large companies reporting, according to
IBES International and the First Call Corp., which track earnings
projections and results.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend continues, earnings this quarter could grow 9
percent to 10 percent, according to First Call. That pace would
make the quarter the first with above-average earnings growth since
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But even more significant is the steady rise in earnings
forecasts for all of 1999 by Wall Street strategists.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt, the overall economic outlook has improved both in
the United States and abroad. There are signs of a turnaround in
Asia, battered since the devaluation of the Thai baht in 1997.
European central bankers have cut interest rates to spark growth.
Investors are betting again on emerging markets, and Brazil seems
to be getting its problems under control just months after it
devalued its currency.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, higher earnings are looming for the oil industry
since oil prices have risen sharply in recent weeks. And better
results than expected last quarter for American industries, like
paper, and for cyclical companies that thrive when the economy is
strong are causing financial analysts to reassess.
</P>
<P>
   The brightening picture is encouraging investors to take a
longer view and providing signs of support for the stock market in
the months ahead. And the overall rise in expectations is
distracting from some of the big disappointments, like the earnings
shortfall at Compaq Computer and Intel's weak first-quarter sales.
</P>
<P>
   In just five months, Bruce Steinberg, chief economist at Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co., has moved from forecasting a 5 percent decline in
operating earnings for the S.&AMP; P. 500 in 1999 to an increase of 8.5
percent. Douglas R. Cliggott, U.S. equity strategist at J.P.
Morgan, is now predicting an 8 percent jump. Stronger than expected
growth at home and abroad caused him to jettison his measly
forecast of 2 percent earnings growth last fall.
</P>
<P>
   And corporate profits for 2000 are looking good, a fact that
should buoy investors, who bet in large part on what a company is
expected to earn in the years ahead. In fact, Abby Joseph Cohen,
the co-chairwomen of the investment policy committee at Goldman
Sachs &AMP; Co., puts earnings growth next year at 8 percent, slightly
stronger than this year's upwardly revised 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   All this rosy talk has obscured the stock market plunge of last
fall and the third quarter's decline in operating earnings, the
first quarterly decline since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But as the selloff early this week in growth and technology
stocks indicates, the question remains whether these improved
earnings projections are enough to support the high cost of stocks.
IBES, which gauges the attractiveness of stocks based on corporate
earnings and interest rates, shows stocks at their highest
valuation since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Even with higher earnings, ``the market will still be too
expensive,'' said Byron R. Wien, U.S. investment strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. He estimates that the S.&AMP; P. 500 index
is overvalued by about 26 percent, a level that in the past has
signaled a stock market correction. Another cautionary note may be
seen in the declines in the shares of Exxon and Microsoft on
Wednesday even though both companies reported numbers that were
better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, confidence begets confidence. An improved earnings
outlook may encourage investors to ignore warning signs, as they
have in the past. The Leuthold Group's major trend index for the
stock market has blinked red since June 1998, with a brief
exception from Nov. 9, 1998, to Feb. 8, 1999, when the stock market
was recovering from last fall's 19 percent drop in the Dow Jones
industrial average and the 30 percent plunge in the Nasdaq
composite index from its high.
</P>
<P>
   And if the recent investor moves out of technology and growth
stocks result in a broadening rally in the stock market, some
strategists will become more confident about the outlook, despite
record high valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McManus, the equity strategist at NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities, predicts that a good first quarter will just spur
analysts to increase their earnings expectations more for the rest
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The actual rate of earnings growth is not that important, he
said. Instead, it's the ratio of positive surprises to negative
surprises that matters, he said, ``because a surprise in earnings
is what drives analysts to revise their expectations upward and
that, in turn, can help drive the stock higher.''
</P>
<P>
   According to First Call, the earnings estimates for the paper
and aluminum industries have already been revised upward.
International Paper is now expected to report 1999 earnings of
$1.03 a share, up 23 percent from the estimate before the company
released its first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   McManus and Cliggott of J.P. Morgan also tend to ignore the
overall earnings growth for the S.&AMP; P. 500. They consider it
misleading because the index is weighted in favor of big names,
like Microsoft, General Electric and Exxon. And the earnings
performance of these few companies can overshadow the general
trend.
</P>
<P>
   For example, overall S.&AMP; P. reported earnings rose 9.2 percent
in the fourth quarter of 1998 from a year earlier. But when
calculating the average by giving each company the same weighting,
earnings fell 2.5 percent, according to Bloomberg News, indicating
that many more companies had earnings declines. (Reported earnings
are the actual profits reported. Operating earnings, which most
market strategists and analysts use, strip out one-time changes and
other factors that may distort the longer-term trend in a company's
earnings.)
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, more companies are healthier financially,
according to Bloomberg. Reported earnings for the first quarter are
up 5.5 percent when weighting each company in the S.&AMP; P. equally
and 17.4 percent when favoring the returns from the big stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The one caveat, of course, is that the improving earnings
picture is based on an economy that keeps humming. If growth is so
strong that inflationary pressures build the Federal Reserve may
have to rein in the economy by raising short-term interest rates, a
move that almost always punishes stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell J. Held, the co-manager of U.S. economics at Salomon
Smith Barney, is not worried about the Fed raising rates this year.
But he says a rate hike could come next year. And if it does, he
said, ``that is when the market gets hit, and the higher the
valuation, the sharper the fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
