<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ATROCITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPULSION OF KOSOVARS TO BE TOTAL, U.S. SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New evidence indicates that Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic intends to sweep all of Kosovo and not allow
ethnic Albanians to remain even in the province's most sparsely
populated areas, the State Department's top authority on atrocities
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   David J. Scheffer, the U.S. ambassador at large for war crimes
issues, said in an interview that he had received clear evidence
overnight that Serbian forces had savagely attacked remote villages
in eastern Kosovo and had expelled Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, some officials had speculated that after ethnic
Albanians had been routed from the central and western parts of
Kosovo, Milosevic might try to resolve the conflict by suggesting a
partition that would allow him to control most of Kosovo and allow
Albanians to remain in the eastern towns like Gnjilane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to be demonstrated now that there is a final
solution to ethnic cleansing,'' Scheffer said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It is a total ethnic cleansing campaign. Even those
areas that up to this point have not been hit the hardest are now
being hit. They are going through the backwater area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is eager to publicize accounts of
atrocities, since the brutality against Kosovo's Albanians is the
main rationale for NATO's bombing of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Scheffer said the evidence he received on
Wednesday, based on aerial photographs and interviews with refugees
in Albania and Macedonia, included these examples of Serbian
violence against ethnic Albanians:
</P>
<P>
   _ Serbs have begun systematically executing young men in a way
that makes it appear they died in battle.
</P>
<P>
   _ The estimated number of Albanian Kosovars who have been killed
and buried in mass graves has reached at least 3,700. Last week, a
NATO spokesman put the figure at 3,200.
</P>
<P>
   _ The number of residential areas that have been burned or
otherwise destroyed by Serb forces since late last month now totals
at least 500, 100 more than the figure announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees who have recently fled from Kosovo report that in many
places, Serbs have rounded up young Albanian men, forced them to
run a few hundred yards and then shelled them or gunned them down,
Scheffer said.
</P>
<P>
   This method of execution, he said, ``creates forensic evidence
that would allow the Serbs to say they were collateral casualties
of military operations.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, there has been little coordination among those who
have questioned refugees about potential war crimes, including
officials from the United States and other NATO countries and
scores of private relief workers. And there has been no clearing
house for their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Scheffer said, a uniform questionnaire is being used for
the interviews, and the United States and the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe are developing a database for
the material. The information will be turned over to the
International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20 or 25 U.S. government officials or people on
contract to the government are among those conducting the
interviews, Scheffer said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, analysts who review photographs taken from
satellites and spy planes have received additional training to spot
evidence of possible war crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
