<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-EARNINGS22-COX     04-21 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-EARNINGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analysts want details on Compaq problems
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Since Sunday's ouster of Chief Executive Eckhard
Pfeiffer, Compaq Computer Corp. Chairman Ben Rosen has stressed the
need for better execution if the troubled Houston-based giant is to
return to a position of leadership in the fast-changing computer
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, when the company reported a first-quarter profit of
$281 million that was in line with Wall Street's diminished
expectations, Rosen added a surprising perspective on what he
called the ``unacceptable'' performance that apparently sealed
Pfeiffer's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had set a more aggressive plan than was appropriate,''
Rosen said during a conference call with reporters. ``That was the
main reason for the shortfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Compaq had projected first-quarter profits of
$534 million. Two weeks ago, it shocked Wall Street when it
announced profits wouldn't be nearly as much, sending its stock
diving and helping prompt Pfeiffer's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter ended March 31 was $9.4 billion, up
nearly 66 percent from a year ago. That jump reflects added
revenues from Digital Equipment Corp., which Compaq acquired last
summer for about $9 billion. The $281 million in profit translated
to 16 cents per share, compared with 1 cent last year. Before the
April 9 earnings surprise, Wall Street had expected 32 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said Wednesday the overly optimistic forecast for the
quarter was hurt because of slowing growth in PC demand. Yet that
is a perennial first-quarter challenge for most PC makers because
buying slows dramatically after the holiday season. He also blamed
intense price cutting for corporate customers, which analysts
believe was started by IBM.
</P>
<P>
   That Compaq could have missed its earnings projections by so far
a margin _ and the lack of detail about the shortfall _ only added
to Wall Street's current uncertainty about the company.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street brokerage companies manage billions of dollars in
clients' money. They rely on senior management for information
about plans to improve weaknesses and for guidance on a company's
performance in upcoming quarters.
</P>
<P>
   They'll have to wait for those details from Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like throwing darts,'' said Art Russell of the Edward
Jones securities company in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said Wednesday, as he did earlier in the week, that the
three-man team of directors who will guide Compaq until a new CEO
is named needs more time to identify exactly what needs fixing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having been in office now for 48 hours, we're examining every
aspect of the company,'' he said. ``Our plans are to speed up
decision-making and make the company more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some good news in Wednesday's report.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it now supplies more than a third of the
servers that power World Wide Web sites, sales of its new
entry-level servers exceeded expectations and its sub-$1,000 PCs
are profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any positive to be taken . . . it's the PC
business is alive and well,'' Russell said. ``Their consumer
business grew 30 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, analysts agree that the company's core strategy of
selling a range of products, from cheap PCs to powerful computers
that cost hundreds of thousands of dollars, while augmenting the
business with global computer services, is sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are still No. 1,'' said Lou Mazzucchelli an analyst
with the Gerard Klauer Mattison securities company in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
