<HEADER>
A8211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NET2     04-21 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NET22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House panel OKs bill to put candidates' finance data on Net
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texans would be able to use the Internet to take
a look at the campaign contributions of legislative and statewide
candidates under a bill a House committee approved Wednesday. A
similar bill awaits floor action in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Under current rules, candidates can file their campaign finance
records in written form, and they aren't available on the Internet.
Interested Texans have to trek to the Texas Ethics Commission in
Austin and sift through piles of paper to get the information.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill, filed by Austin Democrat Sherri
Greenberg, argue that making the records more accessible will
better equip voters to make educated choices. It also will make
candidates more accountable for the money they collect, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voter has a right to know where a candidate's getting his
or her money from. If I receive a donation and I accept that
donation, then I have no right to complain about people knowing
about it,'' said Rep. Tom Uher (D-Bay City).
</P>
<P>
   ``People can see it and they can determine whether that is a
contribution from some entity that they can support or not
support,'' Uher added.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation failed last session, partly because of
concerns that requiring electronic filing by computer disc or modem
would place a heavy burden on less well-funded candidates who
aren't computer-literate. But ever-expanding access to computers
and the Internet, coupled with some exceptions in Greenberg's bill,
assuaged those concerns. The bill exempts candidates who aren't
using a computer in their campaigns or who collect or spend less
than $20,000 in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
