<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8216 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-LWHIGH22-COX     04-21 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-LWHIGH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `It could happen anywhere,' principal says
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Principal David Cantley's heart sank when he
heard the news of the nation's latest _ and most staggering _
school massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about it, my feeling was, `There, but for the
grace of God, go I,' '' the 61-year-old veteran administrator at
Lake Worth High School said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened in Colorado could happen anywhere, anytime. I
always have it at the back of my mind. You prepare for the worst
and pray for the best,'' Cantley said.
</P>
<P>
   Ripples of amazement swept through the 77-year-old school
Wednesday as students, teachers and administrators all attempted to
take in the sheer enormity of the Colorado bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   Students are asking themselves and each other what might have
triggered the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   They are looking at their own classmates with new eyes.
</P>
<P>
   They are wondering if a shooting spree like the one that took
place Tuesday could happen here _ and some have reluctantly
concluded that it could.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about it, I felt, man, that stuff's horrible,''
said Bobby Gilbert, a senior at the school. ``But it can happen at
any high school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't trust nobody,'' agreed Jimmy Aguirre, a junior.
``They ought to arrest everybody in that gang. They ought to be
asking the parents questions. And yes, it could happen here. It
could happen anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre spoke during the early lunch period at the high school,
in a cafeteria ringing with loud, excited voices and laughter. When
someone exploded a paper lunch bag, a newspaper reporter flinched,
but the students themselves seemed to take it in stride. There are
more than 2,600 students in the school _ so many that the first
lunch period starts at 10:25 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Worth High first opened its doors in 1922. It is situated
atop a sandy white rise of ground near Interstate 95, and its
Mediterranean-style, cream-colored buildings, with their shady
porches and sunny walkways, have a cozy, academic, sheltering feel
to them.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, two police officers are on duty every school day
here, and a third, equipped with a walkie-talkie, watches the
nearby I-95 overpass for suspicious traffic approaching the campus.
Two teachers rove the grounds continually, on the lookout for
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The school is not equipped with metal detectors, and the
students themselves see no need for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids can break into anything,'' said Jenny Wagner, a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   There was a shooting here three years ago, when two nonstudents
came onto school property and picked a fight. One of the intruders
was shot in the stomach. The bullet exited his back and wounded a
female student standing behind him, Cantley said.
</P>
<P>
   While there are loners and misfits at Lake Worth High, they
don't terrify the students _ at least not Elatia Mann, a freshman.
``They just keep to themselves, singly,'' she said. ``There'll be
one way over here, and another one way over there. But they aren't
in a gang or anything, like these kids in Colorado with their
trench coats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think what happened there could happen here,'' said
John Dandrie, a senior. ``We've got so many races, so many
minorities at this school, we're all used to each other. We can all
talk to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Sentiments like these are welcome to the ears of Cantley, a
plain-spoken West Virginian with 30 years' experience in education,
19 of them spent at Lake Worth High.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have an announcement this morning, or a moment of
silence, or anything like that,'' Cantley said. ``I didn't want to
get in there and rile feelings up even more. We let the teachers
discuss it with the students if the students wanted to. We're
preparing a big sympathy card for the students in Colorado, and
we're going to mail it out to them, after we've gotten as many
signatures as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we could protect these students any more than
we're doing, except to surround the school with razor wire. But can
you just imagine how those parents in Colorado feel, being called
up and asked to come down and bring their child's dental records?''
Cantley trailed off, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a theory about this. When this thing settles out, I
will tell you what you will find. You will find some kids who never
were part of their school. They didn't get on any team. They didn't
belong to a drama club or the band. They never learned to win and
lose and be part of a larger effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never experienced the glory of being a winner at
anything. Activities give a kid something to look forward to. They
fill a void in the heart. These children, it sounds like they never
had their moment in the sun, so they decided to have their moment,
in their own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
