</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA ANNOUNCES 13 PERCENT FIRST-QUARTER DROP IN NET INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing a recent pattern of weak results, the Coca-Cola Co.
said Wednesday that its first-quarter net income fell 13 percent as
the company struggled to expand its business.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of Coke concentrate sold worldwide declined 1
percent, as did revenues, the company said. But expenses rose 5
percent, to $1.953 billion from $1.857 billion in the first quarter
of 1998, diminishing earnings, which were $747 million, or 30 cents
a share, down from $857 million, or 34 cents, in the comparable
quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every one of Coca-Cola's regional markets reported flat
or declining volume. The exception was North America, where case
volume rose just 1.5 percent, well off the 6 percent increase for
the first quarter of 1998. The company said higher prices,
instituted in many markets at the start of the year, were
responsible for the drop in sales.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wall Street bid up the shares $2.3125, to
$67.5625, largely because there were some signs that the company's
troubles were bottoming out.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the bad news had been shared with analysts last month.
But several analysts still expressed surprise at the extent of
Coke's difficulties in certain regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very discouraging trends in the North American
market,'' said Skip Carpenter, a beverage analyst for Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, adding that he was perplexed by the weak demand
for Coke products. Sales of concentrate to restaurants, sports
arenas, movie theaters and other public places, rose just 1 percent
in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Branca of Lehman Brothers said he was concerned
about the future. Coca-Cola spent heavily for the volume it
achieved, he said, and such spending will only increase as the
company tries to drive volume overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke is certainly going to have the volume, but at what
cost?'' Branca said. Bottlers are starting to want to raise prices
around the world to try to increase their returns _ something
Branca said Coke wants to prevent. ``Rather than international
bottler retail hikes, which would slow concentrate volume growth,
we expect Coca-Cola to fund much of that differential,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company spent $1.2 billion on marketing support and
infrastructure payments for its largest bottler, Coca-Cola
Enterprises, in 1998. Branca said the company, in similar fashion,
will have to ``dramatically increase its spending levels
overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's chairman and chief executive, M. Douglas Ivester,
announced the results to an audience of generally friendly and
supportive investors at the company's annual meeting in Wilmington,
Del., Wednesday morning. He described ``a rare but real
gravitational pull against our sales and volume'' because of
recessions around the world, and vowed that the company would
bounce back quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect business conditions to start improving as we move
into the second half of the year,'' Ivester said.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported that case volume fell 4 percent in Latin
America in the quarter, compared with a 19 percent increase in the
first quarter of 1998. Volume in Brazil was down 10 percent, and in
Venezuela and Colombia, the combined volume plummeted by 24
percent. Ivester said the company ``intends to keep investing in
Latin America to enhance our business system during the current
economic crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Price cuts are planned in Thailand, Germany and South Africa,
the company said Wednesday, but Branca predicted those would
further erode Coca-Cola's profits.
</P>
<P>
   Volume in the Middle East and Far East was flat, and in Europe,
it declined 2 percent. Volume in Africa, one of Coca-Cola's
smallest regional markets, declined 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest growth came from the company's Minute Maid unit, a
small fraction of overall sales, where volume rose 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And there were glimmers of improvement in some areas. Carpenter
of Donaldson, Lufkin said, for example, that sales during the
Easter holidays were stronger in Germany and some parts of Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Conway, a beverage analyst for Morgan Stanley, also
expressed optimism: ``We're approaching the bottom. You still need
a flashlight, but the tunnel has a little more light.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
