<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BEEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS THREATEN BAN ON U.S. BEEF IMPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The European Union's executive agency
threatened Wednesday to ban beef imports from the United States, a
move that intensifies a long-running feud over beef from
hormone-treated cattle.
</P>
<P>
   European agriculture authorities in Brussels said they had found
traces of growth hormones in imported American beef, which violates
a European prohibition. The officials said they could start
blocking all beef imports as early as June 15 if the United States
did not address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint comes in the middle of a much bigger trade brawl
over Europe's basic prohibition on beef laced with growth hormones.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has fought the ban for years, arguing that
there is no scientific evidence of health risks from such beef.
Most American beef producers feed growth hormones to cattle to make
them grow faster and bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva-based World Trade Organization, which has legal
authority over such trade disputes, agreed with the United States
in 1997 and declared the ban illegal because the European Union had
not made a convincing scientific case about health risks.
</P>
<P>
   But the European Union kept its rules in place, arguing that it
had the right to carry out new scientific studies. The World Trade
Organization is scheduled to take up the issue again on May 13,
deciding whether the Europeans are violating its earlier rulings.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, though, European officials added a new twist. In a
recent check of current American beef imports, which are supposed
to be hormone-free, officials in Brussels said about 12 percent of
the samples contained enough hormone residue to indicate that they
came from cattle raised with hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Kiely, an agricultural spokesman, said a ban on American
beef would be proposed to take effect on June 15. In the meantime,
he said, European officials would try to reach an agreement with
their American counterparts on ways to make sure that exports are
in fact hormone-free.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the beef industry said the European Union
announcement Wednesday was simply a negotiating tactic. ``It's just
very interesting timing,'' said Julie Bousman, a spokeswoman for
the National Cattlemen's Beef Association. ``The bottom line is
that beef produced with growth hormones is safe. There's no reason
for them to stop any imports.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of trade involved is relatively small, about 7,000
tons a year worth about $20 million, because most American beef is
already blocked by the hormone rules. Europeans buy about 400,000
tons of hormone-free beef a year, Kiely said, most of it from
Eastern Europe and South America.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over hormones reflects an increasingly contentious
trade relationship between the United States and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans recently won a protracted battle they took to the
World Trade Organization over banana-import restrictions, but the
two sides are squabbling over when American penalties were to take
effect.
</P>
<P>
   They are also arguing over a European complaint about jet-engine
noise, and the Europeans are planning to restrict planes fitted
with noise mufflers, contending that the devices are inadequate.
The biggest impact of the restriction would be on American aircraft
manufacturers and suppliers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-WEB22-COX     04-21 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-WEB22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web a sounding board for sadness, anger
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Colorado high school gunman Eric Harris
may not have felt accepted in the halls of Columbine High, but he
was apparently right at home navigating the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Harris had at least two identities on America Online. Under the
names rebldomakr and DAMMISSED1 he penned an AOL ``member profile''
quoting violent passages from the shoot-out-style computer game,
Doom.
</P>
<P>
   In a space for a personal quote, Harris chose ``Quit whining,
it's just a flesh wound _ Kill Em ALLLL!!!!'' He listed his hobbies
as playing Doom and ``being cool.'' And he said he worked part-time
at a fireworks stand.
</P>
<P>
   His profile was still available late Tuesday, but by 10 a.m.
Wednesday it and another thought to belong to the other gunman,
Dylan Klebold, had been removed. America Online has offered to
share computer records with the FBI that might be relevant to the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Also circulating on the Internet, a Web page supposedly
constructed by Harris. Before authorities could remove it, the page
had been copied and posted at another Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The page reportedly features lyrics by obscure German rock band
KMFDM (Kein Mehrheit Fur Die Mitleid, which, roughly translated,
means ``No Pity for the Majority.''): ``I have come to rock your
world/ I have come to shake your faith/Anathematic Anti-Christ/I
have come to take my place.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no tellng if the page was authentic (an AOL spokeswoman
said hoaxes are common after big news events), but it made the
rounds on the Internet, passed like a grisly electronic trophy.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, the Web on Wednesday was a place
where people gathered to try to make sense of the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly 24 hours after the killings, the tone in the AOL chat
room named ``Crisis in Littleton'' was confused, angry and
vengeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was a parent of a student at Columbine High,'' wrote
one person signed on as Blue19blue. ``I would shoot the gunmen for
being such jerks if they weren't already dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue, you're the kinda person who caused them to do that,''
replied AustinMojo.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE DIFFERENCE WITH ME IS THAT I RECOGNIZE IT,'' Blue19blue
snapped, using capital letters as the ultimate in on-line chest
thumping.
</P>
<P>
   A couple clicks away were a dozen more chat rooms, with names
such as ``COLORADO KILLINGS'' and ``School shootings.'' It all
added up to a beehive of verbal jousts. One moment a wounded soul
would request a moment of virtual silence in the room. The next, a
mischievous teen-ager would hurl electronic insults and sexual
slurs aimed at shattering the reverence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these reactions are totally normal,'' said Paula
Statman, president of the KidWise Institute in Oakland and author
of ``Raising Careful, Confident Kids in a Crazy World,'' an advice
book aimed at parents of Net-savvy teens. The Internet, she said,
is becoming an emotional refuge for those who can't seem to deal
with such horrific events.
</P>
<P>
   At www.parentsplace.com _ a site usually aimed at new mothers
and the frustrated parents of teens _ women discussed the fear and
dread of the mothers in Littleton, who waited Tuesday afternoon to
hear word of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Needleman, vice president of parentsplace.com, said the
site tried be a sounding board without appearing to capitalize on
the deaths. By late Wednesday, the site had about two dozen
postings from frazzled moms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blame others as well as myself because we all have a hand in
raising each other's children whether we know it or not,'' wrote a
woman identified only as glendakaye.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we send our children out there, how are they treating
others? Are they being unkind and creating monsters or are they
extending a hand in fellowship?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
