<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TO GET SUPPORT OF SEATTLE MAYOR, OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The presidential campaign of former Sen. Bill Bradley
will gain the endorsement of Seattle Mayor Paul Schell on Thursday
morning, and a contingent of about 15 state legislators will show
their backing at a dinner Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   After months of low-key visits, Bradley will bring his
presidential campaign to a state that has traditionally smiled on
reformist, insurgent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there is a certain genuineness about Bradley that I
instantly related to. Maybe it's not smart politics, but my job is
to support the person who would make the best president,'' said
Schell, America's first big city mayor to endorse Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Ed Murray, D-Seattle, another Bradley backer, added:
``He brings a level of thinking about where we need to be as a
party, a society and as a nation that we must have in the
Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Vice President Al Gore, the Democrats'
front-runner, on Wednesday professed not to be worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley has little or no support in the Congress,'' said Rep.
Norm Dicks, D-Wash., who is co-chairing efforts to line up House
Democrats behind Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke and King County Executive Ron Sims have declared
their support for Gore. Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., has worked
closely with Gore and is expected to back him in advance of a vice
presidential dinner in June.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley could be highly competitive in a state that has just
moved up its presidential primary to Feb. 29. He left the Senate in
1997 after 18 years representing New Jersey, and has since written
a book and taught at Stanford and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was in Seattle last January on the day that he announced
he was running for president, quietly making his case to a luncheon
of prominent Democrats at the Seattle Hilton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time New York Knicks forward has argued that it is time
for Democrats to move on from the Clinton-Gore administration.
``The case for a new beginning is self-explanatory,'' he told the
January lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Gently lampooning the president, Bradley added: ``One of the
things I would do is not talk as much. Now you have the president
driving every evening news cycle.... I wouldn't depreciate the
value of my words by talking all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The themes have found resonance among some Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has indicated a willingness to go outside the traditional
interests of the Democratic Party to build the coalition we need in
the future,'' said state Rep. Jeff Gombosky, D-Spokane, a Bradley
supporter.
</P>
<P>
   The list of sponsors of Bradley's dinner on Thursday night
includes six Seattle-area business leaders who also have given
money to Republican Sen. Slade Gorton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has tirelessly courted Washington, beginning in his 1988
presidential campaign but particularly over the past two years. He
has been in the Seattle area seven times since January of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Schell has been on hand to greet Gore on most of his visits. But
the mayor argued on Wednesday that Bradley would be the better
Democrat to tackle urban issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings intelligence, compassion and he understands issues
of racism,'' Schell said.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks argued, however, that Gore has done heavy lifting on
Northwest issues and will show his hands-on involvement with local
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to run a very vigorous campaign here, talking about
his record helping with environmental issues like the Northwest
forest plan and his work on recovery of salmon,'' Dicks said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
