<HEADER>
A8225 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-     04-21 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15 BODIES REMOVED FROM SCHOOL IN COLORADO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Fla.) 
(Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to correct juniors to seniors; UPDATES 14th
graf with bodies being removed from school; other updates
througout; story now in 2 takes.) (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As parents waited in agony nearby and police
squads searched for explosive booby traps inside, authorities
carefully made their way through Columbine High School on Wednesday
where they found the bodies at least 15 people killed by gunshots
or homemade pipe bombs in a massacre Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dead were the two members of the senior class who are
believed to have unleashed the carnage before turning their guns on
themselves. They were found shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve of the dead, including both suspects, were found in the
school's library, said the Jefferson County sheriff, John Stone,
who added that there were so many weapons and explosive devices _
including 30 bombs, a semi-automatic rifle and pistol and two
shotguns _ that investigators were still unsure how they got it all
inside the school. They may have hidden it during several trips or
they may have had help, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   David J. Thomas, the district attorney, at a press conference at
the school Wednesday afternoon, said there are two or three active
separate investigations of a Web site connected to the suspects in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a Website for some time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said that investigators are looking at eight to 10 people
who might have knowledge of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is evidence to suggest that other people were at
least aware of what was going on. There were a lot of devices. They
took a long time to construct and a lot of people were familiar
with the web site.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said a computer had been seized at a suspect's house, and
they were tracing the e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   But an even more unfathomable set of questions surrounded the
motivations of the two suspects, 18-year-old Eric David Harris and
Dylan Bennett Klebold, 17, who were described by many students
Wednesday as members of a self-styled group of loners and outcasts
who called themselves the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' after the long black
coats they wore and shared a fascination with violent video games
and a antipathy toward the more popular students who they referred
to as ``jocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Harris and Klebold were arrested last year for breaking
into a car, and parents of another student at the school said that
they had complained to authorities last year about death threats
made by Harris against their son. Nonetheless, school authorities
and many students insisted Wednesday that they never seriously
considered either young man to be inclined toward the horrific
violence let loose here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident set off a national bout of soul-searching and
debates over whether the killings were spurred by easy access to
guns or by the violent images on television and in video games to
which America's children are routinely exposed.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said in Washington that ``all of us are
struggling to understand exactly what happened and why.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings also had immediate political reverberations as
well: In at least three states, including Colorado, sponsors of
legislation expanding the rights to carry guns withdrew those
measures Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities were still so concerned about the possibility of
more danger that all of the bodies were not removed from the school
until Wednesday evening.Some were so unrecognizable that parents
were asked to bring dental records of their missing children to the
school.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll, which represents the largest school massacre in
the country's history, was a downward revision from the possible 25
deaths that the authorities had said on Tuesday. But it was unclear
whether it would rise again as the search inside the school
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the dead are male, including at least one teacher and
one black student whom the killers had shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen people are still hospitalized, 11 of them in serious or
critical condition, according to a spokesman for the sheriff's
office.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, under sunny skies that turned slate grey with an
approaching storm Wednesday afternoon, students gathered near the
high school for any news about friends still officially listed as
missing. Many were crying or clutching flowers that they brought to
a makeshift memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even imagine walking into that school right now,''
said 17-year-old Dara Ferguson, a junior, who had three friends
whom she feared were dead. ``I don't think I ever want to set foot
in there again.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Jefferson County School District said that
the building, with hundreds of bullet holes and several inches of
water that came from sprinklers that went off after the bombs did,
would remain closed for the rest of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama and Florida, the school shooting prompted lawmakers
to postpone consideration of bills that would prohibit cities and
counties from suing gun makers for the cost of gun violence. The
bills, similar to others passed around the country, were introduced
at the behest of the National Rifle Association to protect the
firearms industry from liability suits.
</P>
<P>
   But at least some politicians said that the violence might have
been averted if someone else had been armed at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had there been someone who was armed, in this particular
situation, in my opinion, it may have stabilized,'' said Minnesota
Governor Jesse Ventura, who supports loosening restrictions on
concealed handguns. ``I believe it supports conceal and carry
because of the fact that what happens when a group of unarmed
individuals are confronted with people with weapons like this, you
have no defense.''
</P>
<P>
   And Charlton Heston, president of the National Rifle
Association, said the incident showed that there should be armed
guards in the nation's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been even one armed guard in the school, he could
have saved a lot of lives and perhaps ended the whole thing
instantly,'' he said in Los Angeles on Wednesday. There was, in
fact, an armed guard at the school and he exchanged fire with one
of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Littleton, a Denver suburb where spiffy new housing
developments and shopping malls are rising out of former farmland
that backs up to the foothills of the Rocky Mountains and where
many parents say they moved to enroll their students in good and
safe public schools, grief and shock were pervasive Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the dead began to filter out Wednesday evening,
though the authorities said they were not prepared to release an
official list. The families of Rachel Scott, 15, and Isaiah Shoels,
18, said that their children had died in the shooting and a
teacher, William David Sanders, was widely identified as the
faculty member who had perished.
</P>
<P>
   Shoels, who was black, was apparently singled out for killing,
according to some of the students who survived the library rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seemed to seek him out,'' Joshua Lapp, a senior at the
school who dove for cover with other students in the library.
``They went past a row of desks and one of them said, `Look,
there's that little nigger.' Then there were three shots and one of
them said, `Is he dead?' and the other one said, `Yes, he's dead
all right.' ''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Woodman, a junior who was also in the library at the
time, told ABC's ``Good Morning America'' program that the two were
laughing as they went about their killing binge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just, like, they thought it was funny,'' said Miss
Woodman. ``They were just, like, `We've waited to do this our whole
lives.' And every time they'd shoot someone, they'd holler, like it
was, like, exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   In the killers' arsenal, found Wednesdayat several places in the
school, were 30 bombs, including several constructed from propane
gas cylinders, a 9 mm semiautomatic rifle, two pistol-grip
shotguns, one handgun and at least 100 rounds of ammunition, said
Stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
