<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAREEM RUSH JUST ONE OF BRUINS' QUESTION MARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Recruit Kareem Rush could select a college as
early as Friday _ or he could wait until mid-May. He has narrowed
his choices to UCLA, where he'd join his big brother JaRon, and
Missouri, where he'd be two hours from his Kansas City home.
Although Rush's grandmother, Jeanette Jacobs, has insisted he'll
sign with UCLA, the Bruins aren't sure.
</P>
<P>
   Why should they be? Around Pauley Pavilion, nothing is certain.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball program that in recent years has given us
Blazergate, Schea Cotton's ephemeral appearance, Jim Harrick's
dismissal, Jelani McCoy's departure, Baron Davis' knee and a spate
of surprising victories and predictable postseason defeats ... is
once again in flux.
</P>
<P>
   The chaos began soon after UCLA's first-round loss to Detroit,
with a testy team meeting. Coach Steve Lavin, who became very
emotional during the meeting, later described the players as
``salty'' and attributed their mood to the first-round exit.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't about Detroit. It was about the sporadic offense,
the lack of teaching in practice, the revolving lineup and an
inconsistent substitution pattern _ all things Lavin must correct
to make the Bruins a consistent top-10 team. Even the players know
it. Will the coaches correct the problems next season?
</P>
<P>
   Lavin's new six-year rollover contract, which keeps him at UCLA
until 2012, should help. Relieved of the daily pressure to keep his
job, Lavin can sacrifice temporal goals for long-term success. He
can use early-season games to develop the bench, for instance,
without fretting that defeat will cost the Bruins a 20th win and
prompt a coaching search. Whether they win 18 or 28, he's here for
the duration.
</P>
<P>
   The contract drew skepticism from Lavin's peers and several
prominent UCLA boosters, who questioned what he had done to deserve
the coveted rollover clause. ``It makes you wonder what kind of
deal he'd get if they actually ran an offense,'' one UCLA booster
said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Although the contract came days after the team meeting, it had
been in the works for weeks _ at the request not of athletic
director Pete Dalis, sources said, but vice chancellor Peter
Blackman, who oversees the athletic department and likes Lavin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Bruins are committed to a comparable deal for
football coach Bob Toledo. When Lavin got his mega-contract after
the Elite Eight run in 1997, UCLA gave Toledo a salary bump despite
his 5-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin isn't going anywhere, but that's not necessarily true of
several players. Here's a look at the pressing issues, some of
which might not be resolved until summer.
</P>
<P>
   Baron Davis: Don't read too much into his postseason silence.
According to several non-UCLA sources close to Davis, he has not
reconsidered his decision to leave school. In the next three weeks,
Davis will announce his intentions to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Rush: The first thing to know is he's not that good. He's
not as good as Ray Young and he's certainly not as good as JaRon.
He's a solid jump shooter and decent athlete who plays UCLA's
deepest position, wing guard. But he's blood, and the Bruins
believe signing Kareem will keep JaRon around an extra year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Something else to consider: If Kareem signs with Missouri, the
Bruins move one step closer to landing Fresno wing guard DeShawn
Stevenson, the state's top junior. He has UCLA on his short list
and playing time on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   JaRon Rush: Regardless of Kareem's decision, it's difficult to
imagine JaRon bolting for Missouri. That would not only require
sitting out a year, it would delay his NBA dream. The energetic
Rush can't sit still for five minutes, much less five months. Rush
likes UCLA and loves playing with childhood friend Earl Watson, but
the Bruins are worried members of Rush's inner circle _ especially
his Kansas City girlfriend and her mother _ will pressure him to
move closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Reed: A sophomore forward who averaged 16 minutes and was
often lost in the rotation, Reed is mulling a transfer. He sees Dan
Gadzuric, Jerome Moiso and Matt Barnes _ all freshmen _ and wonders
where the minutes are. In addition, the Bruins pursued (and missed)
two top recruits, Carlos Boozer and Justin Davis, who play Reed's
position. That didn't do much for his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Assistants Mike Holton and Jim Saia: Despite being Harrick's
hire, Saia is justifiably concerned that his peers view him as
Lavin's high school buddy, not a solid young coach. Saia and Holton
tried and failed to land the head coaching jobs at San Diego State,
Washington State, Nevada-Reno and Pepperdine, and there aren't many
vacancies left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
