<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSSALE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds sale will have `no impact' on another Ohio team
 &HT;    By Marc Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The sale of the Cincinnati Reds to a group of the
team's limited partners Tuesday should result in ``no impact
whatsoever'' on Dayton's Class A baseball team that will operate in
the Midwest League next season, according to John Allen, Reds'
managing executive.
</P>
<P>
   The local team, owned by Mandalay Sports Entertainment, will be
stocked by the Reds, who have been working diligently on
strengthening their scouting department and development of players
over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Murphy, president of the Dayton team, also said the
ownership change would not affect his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for baseball to come to Dayton, we needed to be
affiliated with the Cincinnati Reds,'' Murphy said. ``They supply
us with the team. We're keeping our focus on the city of Dayton.''
</P>
<P>
   With the gradual restocking of the Cincinnati scouting staff,
the Reds think they can supply plenty of players for the Dayton
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made some really great strides in the last three
years,'' Allen said. ``I don't know if there's going to be a
significant increase in that area, and I'm not saying we're going
to short cut it, but we're getting very close to where we need to
be as far as the number of minor league teams we need to have and
what we're doing in the international market in the Dominican and
Mexico and that market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to keep up with what we started.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the Reds have added 15-20 new scouts over the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that has done is give us the ability to do more cross
checking, especially as we get ready for the amateur draft in
June,'' Allen said. ``We want our top scouts to see our draft picks
as many times as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, the first year Schott took over as president and chief
operating officer of the Reds, the team had a general manager, four
people in charge of scouting and player development, 18 scouting
supervisors, 19 scouts and four consulting scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Reds have 14 people involved in scouting and
player development, three cross checkers, 19 scouting supervisors
and 19 scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said three years ago, when he joined the team, there were
only ``about 15 full-time scouts'' on the payroll. Now, Allen
believes his team has a nearly full compliment of scouts who can
evaluate talent for the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our market, you can't afford to buy a $10-15 million power
hitter or a pitcher Kevin Brown,'' Allen said. ``You try to re-sign
a few of them, but you can't re-sign them all. You've always got to
make sure you have players in the pipeline so you can replace (free
agents). That's what this is allowing us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the Reds have yet to establish an organizational
structure, but, ``You look at the quality of our partners, they are
all very successful business people. Knowing those limited partners
like I do, I think it's nothing but positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
