<HEADER>
A8230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-21 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS' PROBLEMS RUN DEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the day Ernie Grunfeld's head would roll, like
another loose ball eluding a sore-kneed Knick, he awoke to the
latest explosion set off by his own failed chemistry test.
</P>
<P>
   It was a somewhat predictable source manning the back page of a
New York tabloid, the combustible talent for whom he had gone out
on a teetering limb. Latrell Sprewell more or less thanked Grunfeld
and Dave Checketts for forgiving the P.J. Carlesimo incident by
treating Jeff Van Gundy's sixth-man deployment of him as
provocation for verbal assault.
</P>
<P>
   This time, via his hired mouthpiece, Sprewell figuratively
choked the coach.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is a gasping team in a dying season. As a
fresh addition to a rotting core, Sprewell has not been working
out, in the Grunfeld-inspired tradition of Larry Johnson, Chris
Childs, Allan Houston and Charlie Ward. Checketts, the Madison
Square Garden president, had to do something, if only for the sake
of showing his superiors he was doing something.
</P>
<P>
   He ``reassigned'' Grunfeld and sent his friend and now former
team president on an all-expenses-paid scouting trip to Europe. He
fined Sprewell $25,000 for his agent's outburst. With playoff
tickets out in the mail, he demonstrated a Clintonian touch on
going the way of the prevailing wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you spend what we've spent on talent, to be a .500 team
is unacceptable,'' Checketts said. ``Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the more desired punctuation is a hyphen, Checketts
still not wanting to grade these Knicks on their declining test
scores. He hopes the scant remainder of this run-on season may yet
bear post-season fruit and a few rich-in-proceeds playoff dates.
While that might secure his own vocational standing with the
television moguls who own the Knicks and already interred Rangers,
nothing short of the conference finals is likely to spare the
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no winners today,'' said Checketts, quashing the
notion that Van Gundy had trumped Grunfeld in their silly
intramural feud. ``This is not a show of confidence in anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Firing Van Gundy eight games from the end of the regular season,
much less sooner, would have been too great a concession to the
likes of Sprewell. And as Van Gundy will be remembered mostly as
the coach hired to make Patrick Ewing happy, his dismissal would
have been the impetus for the limping center to call it a season,
eliminating all post-season hope.
</P>
<P>
   If Checketts has studied his Garden history, he will allow the
next hierarchical appointee _ if he isn't an all-purpose savior in
the Pat Riley mold _ to select his own coach. That way, at least
until the team fails to meet future expectations that are directly
related to the exorbitant price of a ticket, the front office will
not set the same sad example as have Van Gundy and Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's agent, Robert Gist, was right about one thing, when
he said that the ``anxiety and hostility'' had made a deteriorating
situation that much worse. In the middle of the Knicks' late-season
swoon, priorities were skewed, the locker room reportedly a bazaar
for the crusading and the crude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization,'' Checketts said, ``was not on the same
page.''
</P>
<P>
   This is nothing new, dating all the way back to the Red
Holzman-Eddie Donovan years, and right on through the ill-fated and
in some cases shotgun marriages of Dave DeBusschere and Hubie
Brown, Al Bianchi and Rick Pitino, Riley and anyone who didn't bow
upon request.
</P>
<P>
   Did Checketts err in choosing the less threatening Grunfeld over
Riley in their 1995 struggle for control? Riley may have been
going, one way or another, but there is no way to defend Grunfeld's
subsequent record, especially the Charles Oakley-for-Marcus Camby
trade, which made perfect sense except in the context of the
previous moves. Foremost among them was the dubious 1996 decision
to plow on with Patrick in the pursuit of one title, a high-level
judgment that falls at Checketts' feet.
</P>
<P>
   For everything else, Grunfeld deserved to go, at least to
Europe. As for Checketts, he will ultimately be judged in the court
of corporate opinion, based on financial reports none of us have
access to. To blame him for miscalculations on the upsides of
Childs and Ward, among others, is almost as absurd as the
condemnations of him for booking a heavyweight title fight that
turned into a farce.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld rose in this organization from player to broadcaster to
assistant coach to general manager to the big boy job itself. He
survived in the Knicks' front office for a decade, and his time had
obviously come. He is a good man. We wish him a good flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
