<SLUG> BC-REYNOLDS-EARNINGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reynolds earnings rise
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Strong earnings from the automotive division and
improved performance in the business forms division helped Reynolds
and Reynolds Co. boost fiscal second-quarter earnings 15 percent
from the same period last year, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton-based document management company said it earned
$30.4 million in the quarter ended March 31, or 38 cents per share,
compared with $26.4 million, or 32 cents per share, for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Second-quarter sales increased 5 percent to $392 million.
</P>
<P>
   Business forms revenues were $186 million, slightly ahead of
last year's $184.1 million but significantly better than the last
three quarters, company officials said. Meanwhile, automotive
division revenues climbed 9 percent to $196.4 million for the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our record results were driven by continued strength in our
automotive division and substantial improvement in both revenues
and margins in our business systems division,'' said David R.
Holmes, chairman, president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Equity analyst Gregory Gieber with Brown Brothers Harriman said
the results exceeded Wall Street's expectations. ``Finally in the
business forms area they have their act together. . . that area is
improving nicely and the other part of their business is doing
well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds spent about $14.5 million repurchasing 791,300 shares
during the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (NYSE: REY) stock closed Wednesday at 20 11/16, up 1
13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
