A8241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNBEAM-EARNINGS22-CO     04-21 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBEAM-EARNINGS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunbeam loses $898 million in '98
 &HT;    By David Sedore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Sunbeam Corp. said Wednesday it lost $897.9
million _ a rate equaling nearly $2.5 million a day or more than
$102,000 an hour _ on sales of $1.8 billion for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the total loss, nearly $311 million,
occurred during the fourth quarter when the company generated about
$515 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Sunbeam earned $38 million on revenue of about
$1.1 billion in 1997, and during the fourth quarter that year, it
earned $9.5 million on revenue of $262 million.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the magnitude of the losses, Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Jerry Levin was optimistic about Sunbeam's
future.
</P>
<P>
   He said many of the company's bottom line problems were one-time
expenses or related to excess inventory built up during the
two-year tenure of former CEO Albert J. Dunlap who was fired last
June. Dunlap, who is out of town, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Levin also warned that the progress Sunbeam has made over the
past nine months might not be reflected financially until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of what we've done,'' Levin told analysts during a
conference call Tuesday. ``Without doubt Sunbeam is a better
company than it was the last time we spoke (in December). There are
many encouraging signs. Unfortunately, 1999 can't show Sunbeam's
full potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin cited $30 million in positive cash flow during the
quarter, plus the elimination of the company's excess grill
inventory as evidence Sunbeam is heading in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   However, analyst Tom Burnett of Merger Watch said the company
still has more than its share of problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the company still has a lot issues ahead, the bank
lender issue, the SEC review and the late filings with the SEC,''
Burnett said. ``They're not out of the woods by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam previously announced it would be late filing its annual
report with the Securities and Exchange Commission largely because
it had to restate earnings for 1996 and 1997. The SEC also is
continuing to investigate Sunbeam's accounting, and the company
just received a one-year extension of the deadline to comply with
the terms of its $1.7 billion bank loan package.
</P>
<P>
   Levin also said that while the company has no immediate plans to
sell off any of its businesses, it might do so in the future.
Sunbeam makes a wide array of consumer products, such as toasters,
electric blankets and scales. It has about 350 employees at its
Boca Raton headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings report had little impact on Sunbeam's stock (NYSE:
SOC), which closed at $5.50, down 6 cents a share. It had traded as
high as $31 last April.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam's losses included an operating loss of $796 million.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Bobby Jenkins said much of the losses
included one-time or unusual expenses, such as a $62 million
write-down in the value of First Alert, one of the companies
Sunbeam bought last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
