A8242 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILLER-WEB-SITE-LADN     04-21 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-WEB-SITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATE TRACKERS SAY THEY FOUND TRENCHCOAT MAFIA ONLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Researchers with the Simon Wiesenthal Center said
Wednesday that they stumbled upon a ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' Web site
weeks ago as they were tracking hate groups on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Believed to belong to the Columbine High School group, the site
contained disturbing poetry and was linked to anarchist Internet
pages, but the researchers saw nothing suggesting a violent
assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no indication that this was a dangerous site from
people planning something,'' said Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean and
founder of the Los Angeles center. ``If there had been, we would
have taken action immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Hier and others at the center said the site's links suggest that
members of the group may have learned bomb-making techniques from a
digital subculture of hate.
</P>
<P>
   They called on Internet companies to voluntarily screen out
sites that promote hatred or teach weapons construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've reached the big leagues,'' Rabbi Abraham Cooper said.
``Don't tell me you're just the cable guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Students Wednesday said that such Web pages are easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell you what you need to buy, what temperature to cook
it at,'' said Devin Hasselquist, 14, a middle school student from
Diamond Bar.
</P>
<P>
   He and other students visiting the center said the blame for
such easy access lies with the people behind the individual sites,
not the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever wants to put it on there, it's their fault,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wiesenthal center officials said they tried to access what they
believe is suspected gunman Eric Harris' America Online Web site
Wednesday, a page separate from from the Trenchcoat Mafia site
found weeks ago. Researcher Rick Eaton said although they believed
the site was Harris', they could not confirm it with America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   An AOL spokeswoman told The Associated Press she couldn't
comment on whether it was linked to Harris but said material
relevant to the shooting would be forwarded to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Although the purported Harris site had been shut down by
Wednesday morning, the center's researchers had earlier found
attached to it a detailed and methodical guide to making pipe bombs
and napalm.
</P>
<P>
   The document's author, whose identity could not be determined,
researchers said, offers such tips as covering the floor with
newspaper when working with firework powder for bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . if you have a big black stain on yer carpet, mom and dad
might ask some questions,'' the document says.
</P>
<P>
   Even more disturbing is a discussion of ways to lace bombs with
shrapnel to maximize casualties. The author reports he tried fixing
nails onto the outside of some pipes and is saving that batch for
an upcoming event.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . since they won't be used until NBK it'll be kind of hard
to report the results. You might try asking the survivors if they
got a good look at the bomb before it went off and then the
remains!'' the document reads. The document does not explain what
``NBK'' means.
</P>
<P>
   The documents could have been linked to the site after Tuesday's
shooting but that would have required someone to know the owner's
password or to have hacked into the account, Eaton said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
