<HEADER>
A8329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ETHNIC-CONFLICTS     04-21 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ETHNIC-CONFLICTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING ETHNIC TENSION FROM TURNING VIOLENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editorial Observer) 
(af) 
 By TINA ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 22: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the world is permitted any nostalgia for Communism, let it
note that alongside the many horrors was the virtue of a relative
measure of ethnic peace. It is often so with empires _ and when
they fall, the ethnic, religious and nationalist conflicts they
smothered with their harsh repression can erupt. The fall of
communism, and the end of American and Soviet sponsorship of
political wars in the Third World, have made these ethnic conflicts
into the face of war today, exemplified by the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But not every nation with a tense mix of ethnicities has slipped
into violence. Romania and Hungary, two nations that border
Yugoslavia, are trying to manage conflicts surrounding the
Hungarian minority in Romania peacefully. The same is true with the
Hungarian minority living in Slovakia. Many former Soviet nations
are arriving at democratic ways to deal with the large Russian
populations in their midst. Latvia, for example, has now agreed to
remove most barriers to citizenship for the one-third of its
residents who are ethnic Russians. And while several ethnic
enclaves of the former Soviet Union, like Chechnya and the ethnic
Armenian region of Nagorno-Karabakh, have fought separatist wars,
many other enclaves have not.
</P>
<P>
   History was one thing that made Yugoslavia different. In the
Balkans, the ebb and flow of empires over the centuries _ Ottoman,
Austro-Hungarian and others _ left a long cycle of killings and
revenge. The identity of each ethnic group, particularly the Serbs,
was largely shaped by memories of victimization, military defeat
and humiliation, leaving people susceptible to hate propaganda.
This is not just ancient history, as World War II saw mass killings
of Serbs at the hands of Croats and, to a far lesser extent,
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Yugoslavia that emerged from the war was a multi-ethnic
state, with high rates of intermarriage. The country's strongman,
Tito, who was half-Croat and half-Slovene, permitted no public
discussion of ethnic tensions. Communist ideology promoted
universalism. Class, not ethnicity, mattered. ``Brotherhood and
Unity'' was Tito's slogan. He balanced the demands of various
ethnic groups, and used Yugoslavs' consciousness of their
victimhood to unite them as a small country standing up to Stalin.
He also used repression, clamping down on various outbreaks of
Serbian, Croatian and Albanian nationalism and purging or jailing
the leading proponents.
</P>
<P>
   The positive side of Tito's control was that people felt secure
that they would not become ethnic victims. But after his death in
1980, the rules changed. Yugoslavia was governed by a rotating
presidency, and there was constant uncertainty about whether the
next ruler would have a particular ethnic tilt. The new leaders
also permitted Serbs, always the largest and most powerful group,
to express their grievances in public.
</P>
<P>
   The single most important factor in Yugoslavia's violence,
however, was the emergence of Slobodan Milosevic, a leader willing
to destroy his country to keep himself in power. Ethnic conflicts
do not explode on their own. They are exploited by ruthless leaders
who want power, land or treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Milosevic threatened non-Serb minorities such as
Croats and Bosnian Muslims, who then seceded from Yugoslavia. But
since the new nations had Serbian minorities, Serbs grew nervous,
allowing Milosevic to use propaganda to exploit their fears and
turn them into killers.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic had the tools to do this, because Yugoslavia never
shook off its Communist system. The same powerful and
well-controlled structures Tito used to repress nationalism _ the
party, Interior Ministry, army and media _ were intact and
available for Milosevic to employ in the service of hate.
</P>
<P>
   Other ethnically mixed nations of the former Communist world
have been more fortunate. Few other ethnic groups in the region can
match the Serbs for their sense of humiliation and victimization _
sentiments that unscrupulous leaders can turn into hate. The
Hungarians in Slovakia and Romania, for instance, worry about
agricultural policy and establishing a university in their
language. They do not worry about mass killing.
</P>
<P>
   Political factors also matter. While Milosevic promised Serbs a
better life through ethnic cleansing, the leaders of Hungary,
Romania and Slovakia held out the promise of joining Europe. These
leaders were essentially told that they had no chance of NATO or
European Union membership until they solved their ethnic problems.
Similar statements helped persuade governments of the Baltic States
to treat their Russian minorities more justly. It is not only the
heavy hand of imperial rule that can impose ethnic cooperation. In
most circumstances, the desire for democracy and economic growth
can do the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
