<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-VICTIMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLER'S FRIENDS TELL MOURNERS OF THEIR SHOCK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ After the keening of bagpipes, fresh tears
and a few prayers, the parish priest at Light of the World Catholic
Church turned the microphone over to the audience Wednesday in
hopes that it would prove cathartic for a community grieving the
loss of 14 students and a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The people hardest hit by Tuesday's school massacre came
together with parents and teachers for a prayer service at a
Catholic church little more than a mile from the deadly campus
scene. Many teen-agers arrived locked arm-in-arm, while others came
with their parents and _ most ominously _ some ashen-faced parents
arrived, accompanied by no children.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience were stunned, however, when two young girls
took their turn at the front of the church and introduced
themselves as friends of one of the shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both knew Eric Harris,'' said red-eyed Nicole Markham,
nodding to her friend, Kristen Thiebault. ``We didn't see any signs
of this. We're just sorry they did this!'' she cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all lost friends yesterday,'' added Thiebault. ``Some of
them committed suicide,'' she said, referring to Harris and his
partner, Dylan Klebold, who walked into the school Tuesday armed
with several types of guns and explosives, killing 13 and wounding
23 before taking their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not know they were capable of this. They were just the
sweetest guys on earth,'' Thiebault said. ``All of our friends are
still trying to figure this out, to figure out how they could have
done this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Markham, draped her arm around her daughter's shoulder
and asked the group not to assume the kids who are being referred
to as the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' had any knowledge of what was
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any of these kids knew anything about it they wouldn't have
been in school getting shot at,'' Markham said. ``I don't know what
to say. We don't know why they snapped. Don't hold it against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbine students say the suspected shooters were isolated by
their own choices, courting contempt with their outrageous clothing
and makeup and hateful rhetoric. They were, by many accounts,
picked on and ridiculed. If Tuesday was about getting even, many of
the survivors are apparently struggling with questions about their
own culpability.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the young people who spoke talked about the societal
divisions within their high school, how they had previously judged
and been judged by appearance and popularity. ``I'm never going to
do that again,'' weeped one girl. ``I want to know all of you!''
</P>
<P>
   But students like Harris and Klebold reportedly saw one group as
their particular enemies _ the student athletes they dismissed as
``jocks.'' Senior Eddie Olson knew he was in the enemy camp, and it
was eating at him that he ran to safety when other kids ended up
taking the bullets he thinks were meant for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' he said. ``I didn't find out until later that the
people who did this were going after people like me,'' Olson
sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry I ran out of there when I was part of the group
being targeted,'' Olson said. ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged Vietnam veteran, proudly wearing the medals he'd
earned, stepped up to warn the Columbine students not to swallow
their emotions as he had upon returning from the carnage of war.
Seek the help and counseling that's out there, he urged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about your age when I was in Vietnam,'' he said. ``When
I came back there wasn't no help,'' said the man, who did not
identify himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let 20-some years go by. I wasted my life with drugs and
drinking. Don't let this happen to you!''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Columbine students are still wearing obvious signs
of shock. ``I'm not eating, not sleeping,'' confessed 15-year-old
Andrea Launer, who was ``stuck in the lunch room'' when the
shooting started. Most of the students who died were trapped either
there or in the library.
</P>
<P>
   She collapsed into tears, explaining that she had a good friend
in intensive care with a gunshot wound to the head. She and her
friends trudged up the hill together toward Light of the World
Catholic Church, looking for solace.
</P>
<P>
   Denver-area community groups and churches were scheduling prayer
services and memorials to support the Columbine kids and their
families. But the kids also were working to heal themselves, with
spontaneous expressions of emotion all over this little community.
</P>
<P>
   At midafternoon, large crowds of teen-agers began gathering at
Clement Park (near the high school) to hug each other and share
their agony involving the 15 people who they are beginning to
accept have died. Some of them sang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; An hour after dark, with a spring storm blowing through,
people were still streaming into Clement Park to leave mementoes of
sorrow and affection for the children of Columbine High. It was
raining, but many people stood with the cold rain falling softly on
their faces, blurring the tears that just wouldn't stop.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy bears, high school trophies, poems and hundreds of
bouquets of flowers are growing by the hour. About 100 people
formed an impromptu silent prayer circle at midevening. Some stood
wrapped in blankets, some had coats and many stood with bare heads
and raw emotions.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk, people were gathering in Civic Center Park in downtown
Denver, as well. Denver Mayor Wellington E. Webb echoed the
concerns that are being repeated throughout the small community
surrounding Columbine High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``As adults we send out children to school because we want them
to be safe and learn and take our place. As students, we go to
learn, to enjoy a special youthfulness that comes but once in a
lifetime,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for many, that life ended abruptly and tragically and even
for those who continue to live, they will see and remember
something that will be with them for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Denver area residents came together Wednesday evening because,
in many cases, they didn't know what else to do, he said. ``We know
we feel better when we're around each other. But we also know we
have to find a way to resolve our conflict with others in
nonviolent ways.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
