<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harvey shows he'll attend Florida
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUTHBERT, Ga. _ Secrets don't stay secrets for long in this
small Southwest Georgia town, so there was very little suspense
Wednesday when Randolph-Clay High School star Donnell Harvey signed
a basketball scholarship with the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But the signing did little to rob from the excitement, as the
normally quiet and reserved Harvey put on a well-choreographed show
for the small gathering of classmates, teachers and media
representatives who attended his news conference in an auditorium
at the high school. Dressed in black pants, black shirt and a
colorful tie, the 6-foot-8, 220-pound Harvey stood on the stage,
read a long prepared statement and, after announcing his intention
to sign with the Gators, pulled out a blue Florida T-shirt, a white
cap with a big Gator on the bill and a stuffed Gator toy.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey donned the cap and T-shirt and then pressed the toy's
paw, which made it play the Florida fight song. Moments later,
Harvey played the song again, led the audience in doing the ``Gator
chomp,'' then said, ``If you're not part of the Gators, then you're
Gator bait,'' he said, reciting an oft-repeated phrase of football
coach Steve Spurrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to me,'' Harvey said, ``to attend a university
where I would have the opportunity to play in the Final Four of the
NCAA (Tournament),'' said Harvey, the Naismith and USA Today
national player of the year who averaged 23 points and 14 rebounds
as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   According to school officials, Harvey, who chose Florida over
Auburn, Georgia and Clemson, has qualified for admission to
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey did reveal some details about his decision, saying he
always thought that he would play at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when I truly thought that I would wear the
red and black and play for the Bulldogs,'' Harvey said. ``The
turning point was when Jumaine (Jones) announced he was turning
pro. I always had the idea of me and Jumaine being on the same
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
