<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-CANES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House not packed for Hurricanes
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Too often this season, Greensboro, N.C., has had a
problem. When the Hurricanes arrive, everybody evacuates.
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina Hurricanes, the NHL's biggest secret, open the
playoffs tonight against the Boston Bruins at the Greensboro
Coliseum. If you care, that puts you ahead of most in Greensboro,
approximately a 90-minute drive from the team's home base in
Raleigh, where a new arena for the team is still under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   The nomadic existence has not been pleasant for players, who
received a weather upgrade when the team moved from Hartford but
took a step back in fan support. Carolina drew a league-low average
of 8,188 this season. Team officials were so pessimistic about
attendance this season that they reduced the Coliseum's capacity
from 21,000 to 11,059 by masking the upper level with a black
curtain. The curtain will remain in place for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business, if you have just one empty seat, you're
disappointed,'' said general manager Jim Rutherford, who long
played in hockey-crazed Detroit. ``But if people really understood
our situation, they would see our fans are good fans for going
through all that travel.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the spin from management. But after the team drew only
6,790 to a late-season game against Washington, left winger Gary
Roberts said, ``If we have only 6,000 fans in our building for the
playoffs, I think maybe we should play all the games on the road.
Obviously, it was disappointing to the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes remain optimistic about the Raleigh market. But
they are resolved to starting next season with a seven- or
eight-game road trip, Rutherford said, while the arena is
completed, after several construction delays. Carolina will not go
back to Greensboro, which showed itself to be a minor-league market
that won't embrace NHL ticket prices for the short term.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been all bad for the Hurricanes. They benefited from
playing in the weak Southeast Divison by winning the title with a
modest record of 34-30-18. With it came a No. 3 seed and home-ice
advantage, despite the worst record of Eastern Conference playoff
teams. The Bruins were 39-30-13, although the teams split their
five-game series (2-2-1).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
