<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the bag
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley and Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Allen Doyle, winner of PGA Seniors Championship:
</P>
<P>
   Driver: King Cobra.
</P>
<P>
   Fairway woods: Callaway Hawkeye 3-wood; Taylor Made Raylor.
</P>
<P>
   Irons: Titleist DCI 962.
</P>
<P>
   Wedges: Titleist DCI 962 PW; Vokey Design LW; Ping Eye2 SW.
</P>
<P>
   Putter: Scott Cameron by Titleist.
</P>
<P>
   Ball: Titleist Tour Prestige 90.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEGROWN: GEORGIANS ON TOUR
</P>
<P>
   LaGrange's Allen Doyle is the hottest story on the Senior PGA
Tour. His win Sunday in the PGA Seniors Championship in Palm Beach
Gardens, Fla., a major championship for the over-50 circuit, was
his second of the year and pushed him to No. 1 on the Senior Tour
money list with $666,724. The largest paycheck of Doyle's short pro
career ($315,000) _ he was the oldest rookie in PGA Tour history at
age 47 _ came after a final-round 64 that defeated Vicente
Fernandez by two strokes. It was the lowest final round in PGA
Seniors history and even included a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow senior Dana Quigley said, ``Allen Doyle played maybe the
greatest round of golf he'll ever play in his lifetime, especially
on a course like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle has no rest in his immediate future. He's playing in
Charlotte this week, Birmingham next week and in Atlanta for the
Nationwide Championship at The Golf Club of Georgia the week after.
</P>
<P>
   Marietta's Joe Inman tied for 11th at Palm Beach National, at
5-under-par. Jim Dent of Augusta tied for 34th at 4-over.
Marietta's Larry Nelson, after opening with a 76, tied for 43rd.
Former champion Larry Mowry of Cumming tied for 55th.
</P>
<P>
   _ PGA Tour: Sea Island's Davis Love III had to withdraw from the
MCI Classic because of back problems.... Former Marietta high
school player Bob Tway tied for eighth, three strokes back on a
final-round 67, and earned $75,000. Larry Mize of Columbus tied for
27th at 3-under, slipping through a final-round 74. Scott Dunlap of
Alpharetta tied for 32nd at 2-under.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nike Tour: Vidalia's Paul Claxton was the low Georgia finisher
at Shreveport, tying for 14th, five shots behind winner Bob Heintz.
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA MAKES PRO DEBUT
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a time for Spain in the world golf picture. First,
Jose Maria Olazabal wins a second Masters. Now Sergio Garcia, after
finishing as the low amateur at the Masters, makes his pro debut in
the Peugeot Spanish Open in El Prat, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old Garcia's final practice round for the tournament
was his last as an amateur. He teamed with Seve Ballesteros to win
a friendly 2,500 peseta match against Olazabal and Miguel Angel
Jimenez. And how's this for irony? While not as spectacular as
Justin Rose's last shot as an amateur at the British Open last
July, Garcia chipped in from 50 feet for a birdie at the 18th, then
officially turned pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that he will have a great career and that one day he
will be a Masters champion,'' Ballesteros said.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, making his first appearance since Augusta, said, ``The
press are thirsty for him, but I just don't think we should push
him. I know I'm asking for an impossible thing here, but if we
leave the kid alone he will have more chance to improve as a player
and mature as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   CHARTING THE CHICK-FIL-A
</P>
<P>
   Charting the Chick-fil-A Charity Championship 1992-98
</P>
<P>
   _ Lowest 18 holes: 63 (9-under) , Sherri Turner, Round 3, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lowest 54 holes: 201 (15-under), Laura Davies, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consecutive top-10 finishes: 3, Liselotte Neumann (1994-96),
Dottie Pepper (1994-96).
</P>
<P>
   _ Most rounds in the 60s: Dottie Pepper 10 of 22.
</P>
