</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-KARRIEWEBB22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Webb finds winning touch
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At 24, Karrie Webb might appear a bit young to be
reinventing herself. Four years ago, she was the Australian rookie
who won the LPGA money title. She won five tournaments over the
next two seasons, a model of consistency who rarely finished out of
the top 20 in any tournament and no worse than fourth in annual
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But last winter, Webb decided a change was in order. She usually
vacations Down Under, away from her clubs, but instead she spent
time working with her coach and analyzing her swing. She switched
to cross-handed putting, and instead of ``going in blind'' to what
her swing might produce in the first few tournaments, she couldn't
wait to see how her hard work would pay off.
</P>
<P>
   With a dominance akin to David Duval's, Webb has won three of
her seven tournaments and will try to add another one this week at
the Chick-fil-A Charity Championship in Stockbridge. She hasn't
been surprised at her great play, just at how quickly she has
resumed being the player to beat each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ride the wave as long as it goes,'' Webb said
Wednesday, ``and when I'm not playing as well, hopefully it won't
be that long before I am again.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb has played 22 of 27 rounds under par, for a scoring average
of 68.67 strokes per round. With rounds of 63-67-64-68 at the
Australian Ladies Masters, she set the LPGA scoring record for 54
and 72 holes. Her winnings of $486,996 places her almost $200,000
ahead of Juli Inkster. Her worst finish is eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Webb always has been a consistent ball striker, hitting 77
percent of her greens in regulation this year, but in the past she
has gotten discouraged by missed birdie opportunities and a finicky
putter. Trading in her Odyssey blade for a Scotty Cameron model,
Webb also switched the position of her hands in her putting grip.
Cross-handed putting once was considered a touring pro's most
desperate measure, but today plenty of players use the style. For
Webb, the result is a more consistent roll and more putts made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I was a bad putter, just streaky,'' she said.
``This year's been different: I feel I have made more than my share
of putts, which is the key to why I've shot so low.''
</P>
<P>
   While Webb said she felt fine about her last two seasons, that's
not the word on Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone commented that she was disappointed in how she
finished last year, and I think that made her mad and gave her more
goals inside,'' said Nancy Lopez, who knows what it's like to be in
the zone that Webb occupies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything just seems easy,'' is the way Lopez describes it.
``The game seems very, very simple almost. The hole looks big, the
fairways wide, and you can't do anything wrong, and so you play
very aggressively.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had all parts of my game there every week,'' Webb said.
``There's not been one part of my game that I didn't want to face.
I've never gone through a period as long as this where everything
seems right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
