<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NATIONAL-NOTES22-     04-21 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NATIONAL-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough year on Tour for caddies
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley and Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Caddies have become an endangered species on the PGA
Tour. Tiger Woods last month dumped Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan, who
worked with him since his pro debut in 1996. Mark O'Meara is
through with Jerry ``Higgy'' Higgenbotham, who was on the bag for
two major championships last year. Jim Furyk parted with Steve
Duplantis and quickly pulled Fluff off the unemployment line.
</P>
<P>
   That's a looper getting a new looper, if you're keeping score at
home.
</P>
<P>
   The latest victim is Lorne Duncan, who carried Jesper Parnevik's
clubs. On Sunday at the MCI Classic, Duncan got a harsh lesson in
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   After the final round, Parnevik was asked by PGA Tour rules
official Slugger White if he had, as someone claimed, used his
glove to brush away something from his putting line. Parnevik said
he could not recall doing it, but Duncan jumped into the
conversation to say that he had. Parnevik fired Duncan on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The smart caddies are the ones who maintain low profiles,
realizing they are one bad read or wrong club from a desk job.
Woods' new caddie, Steve Williams, has an understanding with his
boss not to conduct interviews. On the range this week at
Greensboro, many caddies have taken a similar approach.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago John Daly fired Greg Rita, now with Scott Hoch,
supposedly for going behind his back to try to work for Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The most pivotal caddie breakup of recent years was David
Duval's amicable parting with Jeff Webber on the eve of the 1997
PGA Championship at Winged Foot. Duval hired Mitch Knox, a former
caddie master at Atlanta National Golf Club. In two years, Duval
has won 11 times in 35 events.
</P>
<P>
   Day gets in focus
</P>
<P>
   Glen Day used to be known for the time he took to finish a
round, earning the nickname ``All Day.'' Quickening his pace, Day
was noticed for the pin, featuring photos of two daughters, on his
cap. On Sunday at Hilton Head, Day earned his first PGA Tour
victory Sunday by defeating Payne Stewart and Jeff Sluman with a
35-foot birdie on the first hole of a playoff. Now, he could become
famous for his malapropisms. Describing the burden lifted by the
victory, he said, ``Now I don't have to deal with that astigmatism
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   PGA Seniors on move?
</P>
<P>
   Allen Doyle's amazing final round considered, crowds last week
at the PGA Seniors Championship in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., looked
more like your standard Nike Tour event. The total gallery for the
entire week was estimated at 25,000. With numbers like that at the
PGA of America's headquarters town, something has to change. You
can expect the tournament to be moved to a later point in the
spring and to different courses around the country. Moving it also
would allow the recently snowed-out Tradition a kinder spot on the
calendar.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
