<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-KHABIBULI     04-21 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-KHABIBULIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE IS ON KHABIBULIN IN PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He's enjoyed his finest season as an NHL goaltender,
winning a personal-best 32 games and posting a career-best 2.13
goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nice. What else''?``''
</P>
<P>
   His position coach, Benoit Allaire, set a preseason goal for him
to finish statistically among the top five starting goalies in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   He did it. Right on the nose, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, yeah. And what else has he done lately''?``''
</P>
<P>
   He's only 26, a virtual baby in the cut-throat world of
goaltending, where the stars don't hit their stride until reaching
30. But his 126 wins are the most in franchise history, his eight
shutouts this a year are a franchise record, and his 20 career
shutouts also are the organizational standard.
</P>
<P>
   So where are the ultimate accolades for Coyotes netminder
Nikolai Khabibulin?
</P>
<P>
   `` He still must prove himself''.``''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has played well and he's an important member of our team,''
said Bobby Smith, Coyotes' general manager. ``But as I said before
_ and he doesn't need any more pressure on him _ but to be
considered a successful goaltender, you have to be successful in
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it sounds cold. It also a hockey fact. Witness Khabibulin's
coach, Jim Schoenfeld: ``He is growing as a goaltender. The
greatest test _ and how we are all judged _ is based on our playoff
performance and we'll know that in a couple of weeks. He's a young
guy thrust into a No. 1 position very early who has handled it very
well. Now it's time for him to take it to the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin's performance, more than any other factor _ including
Jeremy Roenick's glass jaw _ is the key to the Coyotes winning
their best-of-seven, first-round playoff series against St. Louis,
and for the franchise to reach the second round for the first time
since 1987 and the second time in its NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it. And he's ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty confident,'' said the Russian, who posted a
32-23-7 record this season. ``I think I'm more confident because
after those three other losses in the first round, I just realize
that it is the same game pretty much.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to see anything different because you don't want
to put extra pressure on yourself. You try to think it's just
another game, try hard and play your best and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Bulin Wall' recalls his other playoff ousters vividly. He
started all six games three years ago when Detroit sent his team
packing. He started every game two years ago while introducing
Phoenix to the playoffs, as the Coyotes lost in seven games to
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Last year tendinitis in a knee limited his playoff action to
three games and part of another, as Detroit dumped the Coyotes in
six games again. Yet, he did emerge with his first winning playoff
record at 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted Niki to concentrate on quality of performance
instead of quantity this year,'' Schoenfeld said. ``It has been a
game plan since training camp and one that we were able to follow
through with because of the fine play of Jimmy Waite early in the
season, and because of the play of Mikhail Shtalenkov since he
joined us.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going in fresh and off a shutout (2-0 over Dallas
Saturday) which certainly won't hurt him. He knows that all season
long he was able to compete with the best goaltenders in the NHL
and on many occasions beat them. He feels good about his game and
he's looking forward to the playoffs. He has challenged himself,
which is good. When an athlete challenges himself he throws his
whole heart into reaching that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The 63 games he appeared in during the year was his lightest
workload in the last three seasons. He played in 72 two years ago
and 70 last year, which included a streak of 60 consecutive games
over the two seasons. Management thought it played a significant
role in his knee problem and with his consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking the helm for the final 26 games of the 1995 season
at 22, his goals against average has decreased each year, going
from 3.41, 3.13, 2.83 to 2.74 and, finally, this year's 2.13.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence has improved a lot since when I first came to
NHL,'' Khabibulin. ``I felt pretty confidence in myself before this
year, but especially this year. I was kind of thinking about the
type of season I've had and was thinking it wasn't bad, and this
year the (statistical) numbers are good, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I know the way I'm playing works and I can stick with it
regardless of whatever happens. But it's not just confidence, it's
also experience I've gained. Older players and older goalies have
been in the game more and because of it, they have a better chance
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin, whose mastery of English has grown three-fold this
year, said he now has something else to rely on, a factor that was
absent during his youthful start in the NHL. That is maturity,
which should serve him better in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little more mature than I was back then,'' he said, the
traces of a smile forming on his lips. ``I'm probably playing
better, too. Otherwise, why am I here for four years and not
playing any better?
</P>
<P>
   ``My techniques are better. My reading of the game is better.
I'm probably mentally tougher, too, in terms of preparation for a
game, during the game and then way I react when I allow a few goals
and have a bad start. It seems a little easier now than back
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Few have ever doubted his ability. It's his consistency that was
under a microscope entering the season, as Schoenfeld, alluded to
earlier. The lighter work load and more rest has helped to solve
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a more consistent goalie,'' Smith said. ``He has
always been capable of the great game, but I think he has given us
a chance to win when he hasn't been on his best game this year.
It's an important part of goaltending. You just can't win when
you're playing great.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, will it be a more secure Khabibulin that the Blues
will face?
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what you mean by secure,'' Khabibulin said. ``Even
if I have a bad game I know I'm not a bad goalie. I can play good.
And, if not, I know I can come back, if not the next game, then a
game later I'm going to play good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a bad stretch. Our team did. I did, too.
Everybody, even the great players, have bad games. The difference
is the more experienced and better players comeback quicker. As a
goalie, it's hard to stop some of the great players. I have to be
realistic. I'm not going to do it everytime.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
