<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-GUNMEN-HNS &LR;      04-21 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-GUNMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO AFFLUENT TEEN MISFITS LIKED ADOLF HITLER BUT `WEREN'T EVIL' 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ It could be that they were social misfits
bearing a grudge at having been insulted once too often by their
more popular peers. Or maybe they were two teen-agers from affluent
families who simply got caught up in a morbid, violent gang. It
could also be that they were racist neo-Nazis on a mission to
eradicate those they hated.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever twisted motives compelled Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan
Klebold, 17, to systematically gun down a teacher and 12 fellow
students at Columbine High School on Tuesday will probably go to
the grave with them.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who knew the two teen-agers well were at a loss to
explain why they did what they did. Why they apparently singled out
sports players and gunned them down. Why they singled out a black
student simply because of his race and killed him. Why they passed
over some terrified students and poured bullets into others.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Tuesday's tragedy, the worst massacre on a
school campus in U.S. history, students and parents gathered on
Wednesday at a park near the school, laid flowers at the foot of a
tree, hugged and cried, and tried to make sense of it all.
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that Harris and Klebold were members of a
small, loosely knit group of misfits who called themselves the
``Trenchcoat Mafia.'' They wore long black coats, black boots and
black clothes. They played violent computer games. They liked to
listen to the music of U.S. shock rocker Marilyn Manson. They liked
German heavy metal bands. And they thought Adolf Hitler was pretty
cool.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that, said Eric Veik, a 16-year-old friend who
attended a video class with Harris, explains why they snapped and
assaulted the school with semi-automatic weapons, shotguns and
home-made pipe bombs, killed 13 people and then themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it was that caused them to do this,'' Veik
said, his eyes red from crying. ``Eric and Dylan are very bad for
what they did, but they had a sense of heart. They weren't evil
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Veik said he and Harris had recently collaborated on a video
project and that he had gone to Harris' home in an upper
middle-class Littleton neighborhood to see if it was a suitable
location for the project. He would not say what the subject of the
video was because he didn't want people ``to get the wrong
impression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to make so much of this group they hung out
with that everything will now be seen in those terms,'' he said.
``Consider this: If two people at the school were huge ecology
people and they went and did something like this, then everybody
would say that all environmentalists are crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Veik said that at its height, the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' group to
which Harris and Klebold belonged had about 15 members.
</P>
<P>
   But at least 10 of those had graduated from the school last
year. Harris and Klebold were pretty much the heart of those
members who were left, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the street of single-family homes where Harris lived,
neighbors also were trying to find reasons Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Good, whose son Matthew knew the two but who wasn't
particularly friendly with them, said his son had learned late
Wednesday that some of his friends were among the dead and that he
was going to need some time to work things out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt always thought there was something not right about
Eric,'' Michael Good said. ``We have three children and getting
them to school in the mornings can be quite tough so we suggested
to Matt that he get to know Eric so they could carpool to school.
But he thought Eric was a little strange and he made him uneasy.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents of both Harris and Klebold were in seclusion
Wednesday and would not talk to reporters. But they released
statements through their lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Klebolds' statement read: ``Our thoughts, prayers and
heartfelt apologies go out to the victims, their families, friends
and the entire community. Like the rest of the country, we are
struggling to understand why this happened and ask that you please
respect our privacy during this painful grieving period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harrises said: ``We want to express our heartfelt sympathy
to the families of all the victims and to all the community for
this senseless tragedy. Please say prayers for everyone touched by
these terrible events.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts Harris and Klebold were close friends,
intelligent youths who treated their teachers with respect. One
student said Harris planned to go into the military.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' father is a retired Air Force pilot, and Harris lived at
the Air Force base in Plattsburgh, N.Y., from 1993 to 1996, moving
to Littleton after that.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew them said Harris was the more strident of the
two, more brazenly displaying his Nazi symbols. He was a fan of the
German techno band Rammstein and would spend hours playing violent
on-line combat games.
</P>
<P>
   Harris apparently established a Web site that included detailed
directions for making pipe bombs and contained disturbing images of
guns, bombs and a conquering figure standing over a pile of skulls.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold, they said, was more of a follower.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold drove a beat-up BMW with a sticker for the hard-rock
band Nine-Inch Nails. He liked sports, and was a big fan of the
Boston Red Sox, said Andrew Beard, a fellow student. But he hated
``jocks'' in school who teased him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dylan said he hated the jocks, and how they could walk over
people and thought they were tough,'' Beard said.
</P>
<P>
   John House, 17, a senior, said he refused to associate with
Klebold after he joined the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went bowling with him, and when he would do something good,
he would shout, `Heil Hitler!' and throw up his hand,'' House said.
``It just made everyone mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County officials said that in January last year Harris
and Klebold got into trouble when they broke into a car.
</P>
<P>
   They were charged with auto criminal trespass with intent to
commit theft and were placed in a juvenile probation program.
</P>
<P>
   But despite this brief brush with the law there were no obvious
signs that these were two boys headed for major trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Some students said they were a tragedy waiting to happen. But
just as many said they were part of a bunch of ``dweebs'' who stuck
to themselves, forming groups of like minds so they could fit in
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But that still doesn't explain why Harris and Klebold set about
amassing an arsenal of bombs and weapons and went berserk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several things I've heard could point to a reason,'' said
Michael Good, ``but in the end, none of it makes any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
