r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-PLAYOFFS-     04-21 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-PLAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO MORE EXCUSES'  
 COYOTES MOLDED FOR RUN AT CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the decision was made during the Winnipeg Jets'
final season in Canada to cut the payroll and trade away
high-flying scorer Teemu Selanne, the franchise that soon would
become the Phoenix Coyotes took on the form of a shapeless heap of
clay.
</P>
<P>
   New owners brought it to life by bringing it to a Valley oasis.
They put a face on it by changing the name, the colors, the logo.
Management gave it charisma by trading for the colorful Jeremy
Roenick, then gave it strong legs to stand on by signing war horse
Rick Tocchet as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the sculpture took shape. Another trade brought U.S.
Olympic defenseman Keith Carney. It grew in a huge way last summer
by luring defenseman Jyrki Lumme away from Vancouver and grew again
with the addition of left wing Greg Adams from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   And once the Coyotes re-signed their heart and soul, rugged
captain Keith Tkachuk, to a three-year deal, the project was almost
complete. A little more shaping and one more powerful stroke, and
owner Richard Burke and General Manager Bobby Smith could pull the
curtains and unveil a team they felt could challenge for the
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Burke, who split business ties with partner Steven
Gluckstern, Smith made it happen. He scoured the league for added
depth and insurance, where a platoon of veteran role players now
sit and await his call. He solidified the backup goalie position by
trading for the experienced Mikhail Shtalenkov. He injected more
help on the blue line by acquiring J.J. Daigneault, then Jamie
Huscroft and then Stan Neckar.
</P>
<P>
   But the move many felt put them over the top was the trade that
sent Brad Isbister to the New York Islanders at the trading
deadline for high-scoring center Robert Reichel, the No. 2 man they
needed behind a rejuvenated, rededicated and reborn Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just talking with Shoney (Coach Jim Schoenfeld) about
that,'' Tkachuk said, ``about how we finally get into position
where we build a strong team here, we go out and have a real good
year, we get fourth place and home-ice advantage. We get all these
great free agents, Lumme, this and that, Tocchet, trading for
Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was building and it can take years to do that and
then . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And then one disturbing and violent hit from the Dallas Stars'
Derian Hatcher turned a statue of hope into a one-armed Venus de
Milo. When the Coyotes lost Roenick to Hatcher's jaw-breaking
check, it was like losing their right arm.
</P>
<P>
   So the Coyotes won't have their leading scorer for the playoffs
after a season in which they finished 39-31-12 and ended up with
the most points (90) in their 20-year NHL history. It was a
crushing blow, but it must be dealt with as they prepare for their
best-of-seven, first-round series against the St. Louis Blues,
which begins tonight with the first of two games at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts. It does hurt,'' said Tkachuk, who led the club with
36 goals and had 68 points, four fewer than Roenick. ``But it
doesn't mean we can't get past this first round and more. But it is
a little frustrating when you build for the past couple years to
get where you want to be and a guy like Derian Hatcher goes out and
does something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, the Stars' 6-foot-5 captain, was suspended for seven
games. Will the Coyotes live to play at least that many games or
beyond in the postseason?
</P>
<P>
   Certain things have to happen. Much of it starts with Tkachuk, a
three-time All-Star and one of the league's best and strongest
power forwards. Tkachuk drew criticism during the team's playoff
series loss to Detroit for what many viewed as a substandard
effort. He didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's Tkachuk who's issuing the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no more excuses,'' he said. ``I don't care if we've
got 10 guys out of the lineup. We have to find a way to win. We
feel we can win the first round, plus more. We must win. That's
what it is. And this is where it starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk will attempt to replace Roenick himself, moving from
left wing to center on the club's No. 1 line. Right wing Dallas
Drake moves to the left side and Schoenfeld, at least to start,
will try Shane Doan on the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if Shane's going to keep up this pace. That's a
question mark for us. But maybe this is his time,'' Schoenfeld
said.
</P>
<P>
   If it is, it will allow the Coyotes to keep their second line of
Adams, Reichel and Tocchet together, which would be a major plus.
Just as important would be having someone else step up and take
center stage with a breakthrough postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different season. It's amazing,'' Tocchet said. ``The
playoffs are a time when you can make your mark somehow. It can be
a guy who had an average season or didn't do well and all of a
sudden, the guy might come up out of nowhere. There's always
stories like that in the playoffs. If we have one, hopefully he can
shine, whoever he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it'll be Doan, the strapping 22-year-old who just finished
his fourth NHL season. He had six goals and 16 assists, numbers
that would look great after a couple playoff rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it'll be defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky, who turns 23 next
month and yet already is a veteran of five NHL seasons. He's made
huge strides this season in his own zone, but still can't seem to
please everyone. It's been a rocky year in many ways. If anyone
deserves to steal the show in the playoffs, maybe it's him.
</P>
<P>
   But it probably will do the Coyotes better if the person who
rises above everyone else is goalie Nikolai Khabibulin, who set
career highs with 32 wins and eight shutouts and appeared in his
second straight All-Star Game. If he can outshine Grant Fuhr, who
enters the playoffs on an incredible hot streak, the Coyotes have a
realistic shot to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Even without JR.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play smarter, though,'' Khabibulin said. ``I
think we play hard, but sometimes we don't really think when we're
on the ice. It seems like we play all right and then all of a
sudden, there's a bad play or a bad mistake in our end and it gets
us down. We have to eliminate those and just play smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Like they did at the start of the season, when they rattled off
a 14-game unbeaten streak and went 17 games allowing two goals or
fewer, the third longest streak in the NHL's modern era. But just
getting past the first round won't satisfy this bunch, Tocchet
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the attitude that if we win in the first round,
we've done our job,'' he said. ``We want to go far. This team was
assembled to do something special. . . . There's always a team in
the NHL that's a Cinderella story and goes somewhere. When all the
cogs are right and everybody steps up, you never know what can
happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
