<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-NCAA-WOMEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LITTLE HEIDI` GROWS UP
 &HT;     ELITE GYMNAST VAULTS BACK FROM SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ In one breath, Heidi Hornbeek downplays her
return to the NCAA Gymnastics Championships.
</P>
<P>
   But the 22-year-old knows better. She has as many academic as
athletic honors and has earned a degree from Arizona in
physiological sciences. To be here competing today _ and, if she is
successful, Saturday for a second event title - is a triumph of
medicine and will.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months ago, when Hornbeek started back from experimental
shoulder surgery, she collapsed on her head attempting a simple
handstand mastered at age 7. ``All her strength was gone,'' UA
Coach Bill Ryden said. ``The most basic movement became a chore.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ryden said, the Glendale redshirt senior has 90 percent of
her abilities back. She is the top-seeded all-around performer who
is not from a team qualifier and is in a rotation with
second-seeded UCLA this afternoon at the Huntsman Center.
</P>
<P>
   The first session also includes Arizona State, bidding for a
third consecutive Super Six team final appearance; and Stanford,
with Katy Herbert of Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   The evening session includes host Utah, with Angie Leonard of
Tempe; Nebraska, with Amy Ringo of Phoenix; and Laura Moon of
Scottsdale, competing at-large for Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heidi will be going up every event after their (UCLA's) best
girl,'' Ryden said. ``There could be worse situations to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornbeek went through the worst long ago.
</P>
<P>
   When Jon Wang, UA orthopedic surgeon, presented her case to a
group of his peers, he was told to forget it. The idea of drilling
a hole in her hip and fusing that bone into the shoulder to replace
cartilage, then reattaching ligaments was speculative enough for
someone moderately active. But for an elite college gymnast, it was
considered folly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to decide,'' Hornbeek said. ``I could have taken a
medical (redshirt), still kept my scholarship and be in med school
now. But I'm very glad I went through it. I've grown so much. My
freshman year, I don't think I enjoyed the sport, but it paid for
school. Now I've learned to love the sport in a way I never thought
I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into the joy of gymnastics always has been a challenge
for the perfectionist Hornbeek, whose abilities have drawn
attention for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get too serious, then I start not having fun,'' she said in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Trained under Dan Witenstein at the Arizona Sunrays, Hornbeek
was the first alternate to the 1992 U.S. Olympic Trials. Continuing
as an international gymnast until '96 was not an option because of
a deteriorating back, so Hornbeek opted for college, becoming UA's
second national champion with a perfect 10.0 score on floor
exercise in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But by the fall of 1998, she could not lift her arm above her
shoulder because of inflamed cartilage. And so the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took her two seconds to decide,'' Ryden said. ``Quitting is
not in her nature.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was six months with her arm immobilized, then
intense rehabilitation to regain range of motion. All that came
before her handstand flop on Day 1 in the gym in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty ready to throw in the towel,'' she said. ``I felt
like I was completely starting over. For a month or two, I thought,
`This stinks, maybe I'll just do one event.' Then I started doing
giants on bars, and I thought, `I can do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ryden said progress was minimal during the second half of 1998.
When competition began in January, Hornbeek was nowhere near her
former self. Still, she put up a decent 38.125 all-around score in
the season opener and pushed that total in her last two meets to
39.375.
</P>
<P>
   Hornbeek is ranked 17th nationally in the vault. At the Region 3
Championships, she tied for second all-around and shared the
balance beam title. The high marks came despite watered-down
routines on all but vault to accommodate the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very comfortable with what I'm throwing, but they're not
the tricks I want to be doing,'' Hornbeek said. ``My focus next
year will be to do the biggest tricks I can.''
</P>
<P>
   With a season remaining because of missing 1998 as a redshirt,
Hornbeek will finish her career as Nikki Beyschau of Sunrays begins
hers. Also from Glendale, Beyschau grew up in the considerable
shadow of Hornbeek, 4 feet 6 at age 14 and now all of 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different Heidi,'' said Ryden, who calls Hornbeek buff
because of her weight training even though she balks at the
description. ``She's much more mature. She doesn't look like this
little pixie. She's very cut and incredibly strong.''
</P>
<P>
   And doing a floor routine to Metallica, about as far as possible
from the`` Grease'' routine that won nationals.
</P>
<P>
   Hornbeek said, ``I've always had cute music and been little
Heidi, and that really wasn't me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
