<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8392 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-PITCHING-RITUALS-     04-21 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PITCHING-RITUALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING ON A GAME FACE 
 PITCHERS' RITUALS RANGE FROM WARRIOR TO WEIRD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Todd Stottlemyre crawls into a mental foxhole and
prepares for warfare.
</P>
<P>
   It is his pitching day, and that means don't bother trying to
talk to the Diamondbacks' right-hander. Even if you're Mrs.
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   ``My poor family,'' Stottlemyre said a day before a recent
start. ``I'm really a little on the irritable side. I don't like
talking too much. It's a stay-away day.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll maybe utter a ``Hey'' to a fellow pitcher and go over
strategy with his catcher. But, other than than, forget it.
Stottlemyre is locked in. Ready to fire, visualizing in his head
the pitches he's going to make that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pitch once every fifth day, it's your day to
perform,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A bad day is a bad week for a starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when that fifth day rolls around, the clubhouse
creed before games among media members and, in many instances,
teammates, is keep a distance, give him his space, spare yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable for any pitcher to be unapproachable,''
said Valley resident Andy Hassler, who pitched in the big leagues
as both a starter and reliever from 1969 to '85. ``If you go to a
lawyer who is getting ready to plead his case to the Supreme Court,
the last thing you want to do is talk to him. He'd probably chew
your head off.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Phillies Manager Terry Francona can pretty much
tell hours before a game whether his ace, former Shadow Mountain
High pitcher Curt Schilling, is going to go out and dominate
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's on edge, I feel better about him pitching,'' Francona
said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Diamondbacks starter Andy Benes' pre-game ritual is
opening mail. He'll do that for about 45 minutes before each of his
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tends to relax me,'' he said. ``It alleviates any tension
I might have.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he's not soliciting interviews, Benes doesn't become
Mr. Hyde on the day he pitches. His demeanor is the same at home,
no matter which day it is, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm out there, my 3-, 4-, and 5-year-olds don't know what
this is all about,'' he said. ``They just see me as Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   There are workouts in the weight room, cardio workouts, sprints,
off-day pitching from the mound, research, studying hitters,
studying film of themselves. They'll eat certain foods on their
pitching days. Some stick with proteins: hamburgers and steaks.
Others prefer pasta. Some may sleep in the training room. Some may
listen to Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   No pitcher is the same. Each has his own method, mad or not, to
enhance his performance when the ball is handed to him.
</P>
<P>
   Some don't give away anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not telling,'' Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown
said about how he prepares. ``It's my secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers pitcher Charlie Hough, now the club's pitching
coach, sees a dramatic change in how pitchers prepare between
starts since the days he floated knuckleballs to the plate for
batters to guess at in the '70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Work, work and more work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's a workaholic,'' Hough said. ``These guys see how good
the hitters are getting, so they're going to find ways to have an
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   What was Hough's secret when he pitched?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have one,'' he said. ``I didn't think about it. I
just kind of went out there and pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when left-hander Brian Anderson was a starter, he
said he didn't have any superstitions on the days he pitched,
although he said he would stand and stare at the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Once the minute hand clicked to :42 for a 7:05 or 1:05 game,
that was Anderson's time to take the ball and start warming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right at that number,'' Anderson said. ``That should give me
enough time. That's it. Other than that, I'm pretty easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter has been around long enough to know that
pitchers march to a different drummer, that some can be wackier
than others, and that you don't question something that works.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, while managing the New York Yankees, the first day of
spring training, Showalter heard the brrrrr of roller blades racing
down the corridor outside his office. He opened the door and there
went his ace closer, John Wetteland, looking like Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, recently acquired from the Montreal Expos, had made
the Fort Lauderdale, Fla., training facility parking lot his own
personal playground. How was Showalter going to explain that to the
boss?
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of thought, `What are we going to do?''' Showalter
said. ``I figured I was going to hear from George (owner George
Steinbrenner) about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was part of Wetteland's pre-game conditioning, and Showalter
learned to deal with it, just like the facial hair that Randy
Johnson brought to the Diamondbacks this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, whatever makes them a better pitcher,''
Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Some are quirkier than others.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers coach Rick Dempsey, who spent 24 years as a major league
catcher, has worked with so many pitchers with superstitions he
can't begin to count them. But, in '88, when he was at the tail end
of his career catching for the Dodgers, he saw a pitcher, Brian
Holton, with one of the strangest routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't so much pre-game as it was warming up,'' Dempsey
said. ``You couldn't hand him the ball. You had to drop the ball in
front of the mound. He'd pick the ball up, walk around to the back
of the mound. He'd take five swipes on the rubber with his left
foot, five swipes with his right. He'd walk around the mound and
address the ball in a proper manner, then he'd be ready to start
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy was amazing with how you had to sit in the same spot
on the bench. He'd lay his glove down at the same angle. Everything
was a routine.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs television analyst Steve Stone not only ate at the
same pancake house when he was pitching for the Baltimore Orioles,
but insisted on eating with the same newspaper reporter every time.
It worked for him. In 1980, he won 25 games and the Cy Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody on the Diamondbacks is that superstitious.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Darren Holmes, who once started in his career, finds
nirvana by strumming Nirvana songs and others on his electric
guitar before games.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers are different, because they need to be mentally sharp
every day, not knowing when they're going to be called out of the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days before a start, you get a little uptight, anxious to
get out there,'' said Anderson, who is naturally hyper. ``As a
reliever, you can't afford to be anxious every day, so you're a
little more loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Music is a good way of relaxing and getting charged up.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Scottsdale-resident Ron Davis, who pitched from 1976 to '90
with the Yankees, Minnesota Twins, San Francisco Giants, Chicago
Cubs and in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Every time he came in from the pen with the Twins, he was
serenaded with the song, ``Eye of the Tiger,'' which played over
the public-address.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant, get out there and get aggressive, get mean, get
ugly, whatever it takes to get them out,'' Davis said. ``Get out
with an attitude, an attitude of meanness.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Johnson and Stottlemyre bring that attitude to the
Diamondbacks' staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost put myself into a war-like state,'' Stottlemyre said.
``I found that is where I get the most out of myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like game day. Nothing substitutes for one
hour before you're going to pitch, the feeling you've got in your
gut. To me, there is no other feeling like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't get in his way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
