<HEADLINE>
PITCHER MAKING RIGHT MOVES IN TUCSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks bullpen showed signs of stabilizing during this
homestand, but pitcher  &UR; Nelson Figueroa is showing early signs in
Tucson that he's ready to make the jump if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, he started and yielded one hit in seven innings.
In his first start, he pitched five innings and gave up only one
hit, a home run for his only earned run in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   A starter for the Triple-A Sidewinders, Figueroa, who was born
in Brooklyn and turns 25 on May 14, said he sees himself as a
middle reliever should he get the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be able to get the opportunity to be up and show
what I can do,'' he said. ``I can't worry about what's happening up
there. I don't look at who I can replace up there. I'd go crazy, if
I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather just do what I can down here and keep getting
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa, who said all five pitches are working well, has struck
out 14 and walked five.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gamer,'' said  &UR; Bobby Dickerson, the organization's
minor-league field coordinator. ``He's done all that we can ask of
him to start the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he's a potential guy who can come up here. It's just
a matter of getting more innings, more consistency.'' &QL; 
Feeling at home &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Korean pitcher  &UR; Byung-Hyun Kim was having more trouble adjusting
to American life than hitters, until a family that owns a Korean
restaurant in El Paso recently took him in. That's helped diminish
some of the 20-year-old's homesickness, Dickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   An interpreter is staying with Kim, who had not given up a run
in three appearances for the Double-A team before Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got above-average, major-league stuff, but it's very
tough on him leaving his country,'' Dickerson said.  &QL; 
Snake bites &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Amaury Telemaco, on a rehabilitation assignment at
Triple-A Tucson, has shown improvement with his velocity but has
struggled getting out hitters.
</P>
<P>
   In 5 innings, Telemaco has hit three batters, yielded seven hits
and has a 7.94 ERA. He must be activated by May 7 or put on
waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Three minor-league pitchers will be coming to Phoenix soon to
have their arms checked for soreness. They are right-hander  &UR; Brad
Penny (Double-A El Paso) and left-hander  &UR; Brian
 &UR; Shouse (Triple-A Tucson) for shoulders, and left-hander  &UR; Troy
Brohawn (Tucson) for an elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Penny, who was the California League Most Valuable Player last
year at Class A High Desert, has allowed 10 earned runs in 13
innings, walked six and lost two decisions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
