<SLUG> BC-BBO-PITCHING-COMPUTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHERS BYTE ON TECHNOLOGY  
 COMPUTERS GROW POPULAR AS AID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's more than two hours before game time, and
Philadelphia Phillies pitcher Curt Schilling sits at his locker
stall, a laptop computer at his fingertips, clicking onto his video
library.
</P>
<P>
   He watches himself pitch against select Diamondbacks from last
season. He checks the pitches that Tony Batista drove for a double
and Matt Williams lined into left field, and figures how to pitch
them differently for his next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll watch film the four days between my starts,'' said
Schilling, a Shadow Mountain High graduate who has hooked in with
the latest technology in search of an edge. ``It's very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Bank One Ballpark, inside the home team's clubhouse,
relievers Gregg Olson and Darren Holmes input information into
their computer programs that they say keep themselves on top of the
game's most dangerous hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, before the Diamondbacks take the field, Olson calls
up the file on every hitter he might face.
</P>
<P>
   His post-game ritual includes logging in every pitch he made. He
brings his computer on the road. He uses it on the airplane, in his
hotel room, in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Olson keeps the pitch sequence, the location, how hard the ball
was hit, if it was hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always kept notes,'' he said. ``I try to give myself an
idea of what I'm going to throw the batter. I'll try to pick up
what hitters do and how to pitch to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, who was acquired from the New York Yankees in a trade
during the spring, said he always charted everything on paper.
Olson, he said, helped him put it on a computer. But Holmes
emphasizes the hitters and their tendencies, not so much his
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll put down the situation I faced the hitter in, what the
count was, what was the score, the inning,'' Holmes said. ``I'll
see what the hitters did, if nobody was on base, if they were
patient. I'll see if they were swinging at a breaking ball in the
dirt. That's big.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said he got into charting everything with paper and pen
from former Colorado Rockies teammate Dante Bichette. They played
on the same teams together between 1991 and '97. Holmes recalls how
Bichette had a chart of every pitcher he's ever had to face in the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he's such a great hitter,'' Holmes said. ``(San
Diego Padres outfielder) Tony Gwynn does the same thing. Great
hitters do that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a constant chess match. And the catchers play a big role.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Kelly Stinnett said he'll go over lineups with the
pitchers every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``How guys swing the bat, who's hot, who's not, what kind of
success we've had against them,'' Stinnett said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the physical work for starters are the days between
their turns in the rotation. There is weight lifting and running.
Pitching coach Mark Connor said the second day after a start is
usually a throw day off the mound to get the feel for it and work
on mechanics and location and to keep their arm strength up.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson is an exception, Connor said. Johnson throws on
the third day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just feels it has a better feel going into his next
start,'' Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   The starter usually takes it easy on the fourth day. Connor
said, for some pitchers, he has to constantly reassure their
confidence. For others, there's no need to soothe egos. For a few,
you leave them alone to their laptop.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to it, the day you pitch might be the
easiest of them all, not pressure-wise, but physically,'' said
left-hander Brian Anderson, who made the transition from starter to
reliever in the spring. ``Those other four days are really used to
beat yourself up, keep yourself strong and in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   And when things are going good, that next start feels like
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when things are going bad, it feels like 10 days between
starts,'' Anderson said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
