<HEADLINE>
SALVAGE SEASON BY TRADING INJURED STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF CADE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, ye who shed crocodile tears, know ye no shame?
</P>
<P>
   Calls of condolences, NONE of them sincere and most probably
coming from Dodgers fans, poured out this week to fantasy owners of
 &UR; Barry
 &UR; Bonds and  &UR; Jim Edmonds. Bonds is out at least 2{ months and Edmonds
is out four months after both underwent surgery _ removing all hope
for many fantasy league owners.
</P>
<P>
   No one wishes harm to a player, but in a league of 12 owners,
it's a safe guess that 11 aren't too upset when a star gets hurt.
That old comforting line applies, ``Better you than me.''
</P>
<P>
   A loss of Edmonds is painful enough. He hits 25 to 30 homers,
drives in 95 runs, bats .300 and makes highlight-film catches each
night.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Bonds, even in an all-star league, is devastating.
There is no hope of recovery. Bonds is one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to salvage the season is to maybe trade those
players for two or three players of lower stock but who at least
will play every day _ and that only works in a keeper league. It's
hard to part with such superstars, but there are more than a few
ambulance chasing bottom feeders who will happily take them. &QL; 
Closers aren't safe &QL; 
Closers. Who knows what's going on with them?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jeff Montgomery's days as Royals closer could be over.
</P>
<P>
   He upset Manager  &UR; Tony Muser last weekend when he pitched around
White Sox slugger  &UR; Frank Thomas with two on, two outs and a two-run
lead. The next batter singled home two runs, the Royals eventually
lost and Montgomery blew what is known in the biz as a room-service
save.
</P>
<P>
   When asked, Muser reportedly said the Royals weren't pitching
around Thomas _ that with two outs and a two-run lead, you have to
get Thomas out. Of course, ``Monty'' said he'd pitched around
Thomas in that situation no matter what anyone says.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Montgomery pitched three innings in a non-save
situation. That's a lot more than a closer throws.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just a tiff, but if you have Montgomery, it might be
time to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's  &UR; Tom Gordon is out for two weeks because of an injury.
 &UR; Derek Lowe picked up a save in his place Tuesday night. Does that
mean he'll get the next chance?
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's  &UR; Robert Person handed a save opportunity to  &UR; Graeme
Lloyd over the weekend. So his spot could be shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's  &UR; Jeff Brantley has had swelling in his shoulder.
He tried to pitch through that last year and wrecked his season.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cubs have to wonder if ``the Shooter,''  &UR; Rod Beck, has
spent all of his bullets. &QL; 
Out of the gate &QL; 
 &UR; Kevin Stocker will not lead the American League in hitting and
 &UR; Rich
 &UR; Aurilia will not win the National League Triple Crown, but you
might get somebody else to believe they will.
</P>
<P>
   Once these laddies start getting more at-bats, their numbers
will return to normal. That goes for pitchers, too. But lots of
owners don't look beyond the present, especially when things are
going bad. They see  &UR; Chuck Finley's 7.94 ERA and fear he is washed
up.
</P>
<P>
   But those who exchange Finley or maybe  &UR; Rick Helling for  &UR; Bobby
Witt are wasting their money.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, those with  &UR; Ron Gant have reason to wonder. He
has three hits and 14 strikeouts in 39 at-bats. If he ever turns it
on, it'll be incredible, but that's a big if. &QL; 
Too good for Rivera &QL; 
This sounds nutty, but don't be surprised if  &UR; Mariano Rivera ranks
near the bottom for saves.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the Yankees are too good for their closer. When
they win, they win big. Rivera may have fewer save opportunities
than normal. The Yankees have eight wins and Rivera has one save.
At that rate, he'd finish with 16, a stunning number for an owner
counting on getting three times that many. &QL; 
Gotta love 'em &QL; 
How about those D-Backs?
</P>
<P>
   All projected as bargains, although perhaps not in real life,
 &UR; Jay
 &UR; Bell, Luis Gonzalez, Bernard Gilkey, Matt Williams and &UR; Tony Batista
have created value for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy owners are watching the D-Backs much more closely, which
wasn't the case a year ago. &QL; 
Ouch! &QL; 
Everybody and their dog has been out chasing the ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Bonds, Edmonds, Gordon,  &UR; Will Clark, Rick Reed,
Francisco
 &UR; Cordova, Mark Gardner, Joey Hamilton, Scott Hatteberg, Dave Hollins
and even  &UR; Cal Ripken went down in the past week. Good luck in your
scramble to replace them.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that you are not alone. Practically everybody
has somebody who is hurt. Most of the injuries cancel out. What
doesn't cancel out is who you replace them with.
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, good luck. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
