<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS GET CHOICES ON SPENDING U.S. AID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Minn., Md., Texas, Ohio, Del., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress overwhelmingly approved legislation
Wednesday that gives states and local schools more flexibility in
how they spend more than $10 billion in federal education money
each year. President Clinton immediately said he would sign the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the Education Flexibility Partnership Act, or Ed-flex,
the legislation passed 368-57 in the House and 98-1 in the Senate,
with only Democrats voting against it.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are trying to show their support for education, and
the Republicans in particular are concerned about demonstrating
that they are more than the party of impeachment. And in many ways
the legislation was the fruit of Republican efforts to scale back
the federal government's role in education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bipartisan work on this legislation shows we can and must
work together to improve our nation's schools,'' Clinton said in a
statement. He then called on Congress to enact his proposals to
hire more teachers and rebuild schools.
</P>
<P>
   The final bill did not include a measure proposed by Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., that would have allowed
schools to divert money for hiring teachers to programs for
disabled students. Clinton had threatened to veto the measure if
Lott's provision was included.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had broad support among educators, including the
organization representing state education commissioners and the
nation's largest teachers' union, the National Education
Association. All 50 governors also endorsed it.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have asserted that the legislation would allow schools
to divert money from the neediest children. ``This piece of
legislation will actually be a step backward,'' said Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., who was the lone senator who voted against the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which began as a pilot project in 12 states,
will allow all states to waive certain federal rules so schools
will have more leeway in how they spend the nearly $11 billion they
receive each year for seven different federal programs.
</P>
<P>
   States would have to apply to the Department of Education for a
statewide waiver. Once that was approved, individual school
districts could ask their state education agencies to be released
from various regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, for instance, which is enrolled in the pilot
program, schools used federal money earmarked for teacher training
to hire additional teachers, thereby reducing class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Other states in the pilot program, including Texas and Ohio,
were allowed to reduce their federal paperwork requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Jack MacDonald, an official with the Council of Chief State
School Officers, says he expects most states will apply for
waivers. ``It makes sense to allow states to tailor-make their
programs to their needs,'' he said. ``The legislation tries to make
it much easier for states to pull together their federal resources
and target them in ways they couldn't formerly do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Thomas Carper of Delaware, a Democrat, who was a major
supporter of the bill, said he wanted his state to apply for
waivers to reduce paperwork requirements and to reallocate federal
money to reduce class sizes and expand prekindergarten programs.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Alan Ray, a spokesman for the state Board of
Regents, which oversees education policy, said the education
commissioner, Richard Mills, supported the concept of increased
flexibility because it would allow schools to take money from
underused federal programs and direct it toward more pressing
needs.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, a school where there are reading problems
might be able to take money intended for technology programs and
use it instead to hire tutors or increase training for reading
instructors.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that Mills had not decided whether New York should
apply for a waiver, saying he wanted to insure that the program
would protect the poorest children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2335EDT &QL; 
