<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-PLAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCH-UP PLEASES BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Don't blame the St. Louis Blues for wanting to do
everything in their power to make sure they met the Jeremy
Roenick-less Coyotes in the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the past three years, they have faced the Detroit Red
Wings in either the first or second round. Each of the past three
years, the Red Wings eliminated them. And after the two-time
defending Cup champions gorged themselves at the trading deadline
by picking up the likes of Chris Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson and Wendel
Clark, well, you figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we'd like to avoid Detroit,'' Blues right wing Scott
Young said. ``That's a reasonable statement for any team in this
conference. It's just that Detroit is so strong. If you look at
what they did at the deadline and what they did over the last two
years, nobody wants to play Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a knock against Phoenix. Even without Roenick,
they've got a lot of good leaders on that team and in no way are
they going to be an easy team to beat in this playoffs. Nobody
thinks that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes feel the same way about the Blues (37-32-13), who
finished strong to catch and move ahead of the Mighty Ducks of
Anaheim and nab the fifth overall seed in the West. They don't get
the respect of a Detroit, a Dallas or a Colorado, but make no
mistake, this isn't a team many clubs want to play, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all starts with the defensemen, Al MacInnis and Chris
Pronger,'' Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk said. ``One of them's
always on the ice and they're both a pain in the butt. MacInnis,
because of that huge shot of his and Pronger, because he's so big
and it's tough to get the puck by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of their blueliners and Coach Joel Quenneville's patient
but efficient system in the neutral zone, the Blues led the NHL for
most of the season in fewest shots against.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis went 11-4-4 in its final 19 regular-season games. The
power-play and penalty-killing units rank near the top of the
league. The Blues don't have a slew of superstars they don't even
have Brett Hull any longer but they think they have all the
necessary components to get past the Coyotes and not have to deal
with the Red Wings for at least the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to be a very competitive series,'' Blues
enforcer Tony Twist said. ``The difference in styles will be
energetic. There might be a clashing, they're might be a meshing.
Everything changes in the playoffs. Attitude changes. Drive
changes. Everybody's desire to win picks up about 10 notches, so
it's hard to equate how it's going to equal out when the end of the
day comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Detroit, it's been a pretty lackluster postseason
for us the last three years. I believe internally, we have a lot to
prove. We'd like to see ourselves graduate out of that Detroit funk
and make ourselves a competitor and a contender for the Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues will ride veteran goalie Grant Fuhr for as long as the
36-year-old can tolerate it. Fuhr, who captured five Stanley Cups
during the Edmonton Oilers' heyday with Wayne Gretzky, Mark
Messier, Jari Kurri and the rest, has undergone three surgeries on
his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   He returned after the latest one on March 13 and promptly
started in 15 of the Blues' final 17 games, winning 10 of them.
After St. Louis dispatched the Coyotes, 6-4, last week, Fuhr spent
nearly an hour in the visitor's training room icing down his sore
and tender knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting there,'' Fuhr said. ``Back-to-back games are a
little tough, but for the most part, it's been pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Twist said the Blues have all the confidence in the world in
Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think without a doubt, giving his recent surgery, he's been
playing with a lot of vigor and he's not nearly as sore as he used
to be,'' Twist said. ``His performance speaks for itself. He's 36
years young. He's not playing like he's anywhere near 40, I'll tell
you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another key player in the Blues' season, All-Star center Pavol
Demitra, isn't playing like your typical 24-year-old in just his
second full NHL season. The Czech Republic native, who won Olympic
gold a year ago in Nagano along with countrymen Robert Reichel and
Stan Neckar of the Coyotes, wound up with a team-high 89 points on
37 goals and 52 assists.
</P>
<P>
   He also scored a team-high 14 power-play goals and 10 winning
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pavol Demitra. There's a guy who's definitely made the season
enjoyable for us,'' Twist said. ``We were missing some scoring
after losing Brett Hull (to Dallas via free agency) and Pavol
picked up the pace and he's been a real pleasant . . . I don't want
to say surprise, because it's not a surprise, I think it's been a
pleasant forthcoming. I didn't expect this consistency from him,
but I'm hoping it carries on.''
</P>
<P>
   Demitra, acquired in a 1996 trade from Ottawa in exchange for
Christer Olsson, is a little surprised himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always waited for a season like this, but I never
expected it would be right now,'' he said. ``I'm playing with some
great guys and the coach is giving me a lot of ice time and on the
first power play. When you play with Al MacInnis, Chris Pronger,
(Pierre) Turgeon and all the guys from our team, it makes the job
so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   If MacInnis doesn't win the Norris Trophy, somebody should
launch an investigation, Demitra said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues are peaking. They enter the playoffs on a roll. And
they just got veteran winger Geoff Courtnall back from a concussion
that sidelined him for most of the season. Until he's totally free
and clear of any leftover cobwebs, the Blues have the luxury of
skating him on their fourth line.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought all this was possible without Hull, who
for a decade ``was'' the St. Louis Blues?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different atmosphere now,'' Twist said. ``I want
to say not all of it is positive (without Hull around), but a lot
of it is. Hully's Hully. He's enjoyable in his own way. I enjoyed
having him around. But as goes with this game, you've got to move
on.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
