<HEADLINE>
PRONGER READY FOR TKACHUK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's the only sure thing about this first-round
playoff series:  &UR; Chris Pronger vs.  &UR; Keith Tkachuk will be the best
match-up on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I'm thinking about,'' Coyotes forward Tkachuk said.
``I'm already having nightmares about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch for contact and lots of it when the two square off tonight
in Game One at America West Arena. St. Louis defenseman Pronger,
who always gets the responsibility of checking top opponents, will
be shadowing Tkachuk much of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pronger will probably be seeing a lot of him,'' Blues
Coach  &UR; Joel Quenneville said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, who is expected to make the move from left wing to
center, is not an easy shadow because he is gifted with strength
and finesse. But Pronger thrives in these types of showdowns and
has the instincts to make it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got more than him to worry about over there,'' Pronger
said. ``They've got a lot of potent players that put the puck in
the net. I don't think we can worry about just one guy.'' &QL; 
A joint venture &QL; 
Don't talk about Grant's tomb yet. Although  &UR; Grant Fuhr's age _ 36
_ is often pointed out these days, and critics are quick to bury
the goalie, he's one of the main reasons the Blues are in Phoenix
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Since Fuhr returned from arthroscopic knee surgery March 13, St.
Louis has gone 11-4-3, coming from eight points back to sneak past
Anaheim for fifth in the Western Conference standings. The Blues
avoided sixth place and a first-round match-up against two-time
champion Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a big part of our turnaround this year,'' Pronger
said. ``He's been a key to the way we've been playing lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Al MacInnis said, ``He's been the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr was 9-4-3 with a 2.11 goals-against average in the 16 games
he played in since his return. Before his knee operation, he was
7-7-5 with a 2.70 goals-against mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is, it has been a long time since the knee has
felt really good,'' Fuhr said. ``That's been the biggest boost.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a boost for St. Louis that Fuhr has a 15-1 career record
against the Phoenix/Winnipeg franchise during the playoffs,
although the goalie doesn't think history will play much of a role
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different team,'' he said. ``They weren't really
Coyotes then, they were Jets. Every year is a new year. We just
want to go out and get off to a good start.'' &QL; 
Player movement &QL; 
Quenneville has downplayed the move, but his decision to
separate &UR; Pierre Turgeon and  &UR; Pavol Demitra and place them on
separate lines has been effective.
</P>
<P>
   Demitra, as the second-line center, posted 10 goals and 23
points in the Blues' past 18 games. Linemates  &UR; Michel Picard and
 &UR; Lubos
 &UR; Bartecko also have played well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always mix and match when things aren't working out well,
and this turned out to be OK,'' Quenneville said. &QL; 
Color blind &QL; 
Quenneville acknowledged he's concerned about how his players will
respond to tonight's ``Whiteout,'' a tradition that started in
Winnipeg in which fans wear all white.
</P>
<P>
   But it's less the attire than the noise and intensity that
accompanies it that concerns the St. Louis coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be loud,'' he said. ``It's probably something
we're not accustomed to. You don't want to be distracted by it.
Hopefully, we can get energized and take advantage of it and keep
our exposure.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
