<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAIGNEAULT MAY MISS GAME 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 and BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes might be without defenseman  &UR; J.J.
Daigneault tonight when they open the first round of the Stanley
Cup playoffs against the St. Louis Blues at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Daigneault injured a hip flexor during Tuesday's practice, and
after further examination on Wednesday, team officials said it
won't be determined until pre-game warm-ups whether he can play.
</P>
<P>
   To guard against Daigneault's absence, the Coyotes recalled
defenseman  &UR; Brad Tiley from the Springfield Falcons of the American
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The team also learned Wednesday that defenseman  &UR; Gerald Diduck,
who has been out because of a broken foot since March 5, is still
at least two weeks away from returning to action, but defenseman
 &UR; Deron Quint resumed skating with the team for the first time since
suffering a concussion on April 1 in Edmonton. &QL; 
Shame on you &QL; 
A hot goalie in the Stanley Cup playoffs can do a lot for a team.
He can carry his club to the next level and beyond. That's what the
Coyotes are hoping from  &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin, who in turn could lift
the play of his teammates with a Conn Smythe-type postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when a goalie stands on his head, he kind of shames
you into another level,'' veteran right wing  &UR; Rick Tocchet said.
``After a period or two, you say, `This guy's keeping us in the
game, I better do more. I've got to play better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if shame is the right word. Maybe it's inspire.
You feel guilty. If a goalie's keeping you in it, game in and game
out, you feel guilty that you're not helping him. That's a boost
that a goalie can do for a team.'' &QL; 
Tickets remaining &QL; 
The Coyotes announced that 1,000 tickets remain for tonight's Game
1 at America West Arena and 1,500 remain for Game 2 Saturday at
noon. The team also said gates will open two hours before faceoff
throughout home playoff games and encourages fans to arrive early.
</P>
<P>
   Also, for $15 fans will receive a $10 ticket, a Million Fan
T-shirt, a white pompon and a gift certificate for a one
Whataburger. The package is available on the Internet at
www.phoenixcoyotes.com or by calling (480) 563-PUCK. &QL; 
Slap shots &QL; 
 &UR; Dallas Drake on moving from right wing to left wing with  &UR; Keith
 &UR; Tkachuk, who will center the line with  &UR; Shane Doan on the right:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a better right winger than I am a left winger, but
if you can't switch when you get to this level, there's something
wrong. It won't be a hard switch for me. The good thing about it is
I'm on my forehand a little bit more and I might get to shoot a
little more. I don't know if that's OK with (Tkachuk), though. I'll
have to ask him.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Jyrki Lumme has battled a sore shoulder throughout
the second half of the season and it still isn't 100 percent. But
the emotional rush of the playoffs will do a lot to dull the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the games start, it's a totally different story,'' he
said. ``I feel a whole lot better now, but it'll be even better
when we get going here.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Keith Carney, who played for the U.S. Olympic team
in Nagano a year ago along with Tkachuk and injured center  &UR; Jeremy
Roenick, said he gladly would accept another invitation to
participate if the NHL decides to suspend its season and allow
players to go again at the 2002 Games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. I'd love the chance to do it again,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
