<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCERNS ON PROFILING CONTINUE TO SIMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ A day after Gov. Christie Whitman vowed to
revamp the New Jersey State Police to end racial profiling, there
were few indications Wednesday that the governor's assurances had
eased the public furor over the issue or defused the political
threat it poses to her nominee to the State Supreme Court, Attorney
General Peter G. Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   After denying for years that troopers used race as the basis for
stopping motorists on the New Jersey Turnpike, the governor said
Tuesday that she was both disappointed and surprised to learn that
it was taking place. The administration released a 112-page
preliminary report, which included a plan to prevent the illegal
stops and searches.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leaders welcomed the governor's acknowledgement of
the racial profiling, saying it belatedly validates thousands of
complaints minority motorists have made for more than a decade. But
the executive director of the Black Ministers Council of New
Jersey, the Rev. Reginald T. Jackson, said the profiling report
still understated the breadth of the racial problems on the force
and failed to address the more complex problem of changing the
culture of the state police.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the New Jersey State House, where the issue has been
simmering for nearly a year, there were also signs Wednesday that
support for Verniero's nomination may be softening among the
governor's fellow Republicans. Sen. Jack G. Sinagra, said Wednesday
that he would oppose Verniero's nomination unless the attorney
general won the recommendation of the New Jersey State Bar
Association's Judicial and Prosecutor Appointments Committee.
</P>
<P>
   And in a move likely to heighten pressure on the governor,
Jackson also announced Wednesday that the Rev. Al Sharpton would
speak on Friday at a rally on the steps of the State House. The
rally will mark the one-year anniversary of an incident in which
troopers shot and wounded three unarmed minority men after a
traffic stop on the turnpike. Jackson said the protesters would
demand a public apology from Mrs. Whitman and present a list of
proposed changes to state police policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
