<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8414 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORSTMANN-SCHOLARSHIP     04-21 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORSTMANN-SCHOLARSHIPS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLARSHIP WINNERS GATHER IN CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Texas, Iowa, N.J.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few months ago, Sandy Lombardo saw a full-page
newspaper ad for a scholarship that promised to send his child to
the private school of his choice. Driven by his dissatisfaction
with the local public schools and a yearning for a better life
outside the neighborhood, Lombardo filled out the application,
mailed it off and forgot about it.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he got a call: Out of more than 1.2 million families
across America who applied for the 40,000 four-year scholarships
for needy students, his son, John Thomas, a 10-year-old in fifth
grade at Public School 71 in the Bronx, was a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Lombardo and his family were picked up by a stretch
limousine at their Bronx apartment, driven to the Grand Hyatt Hotel
in Manhattan for breakfast and dropped off at New York City's grand
old public library for a lavish celebration of their good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   To Lombardo, a strapping man hobbled by a back injury on the
job, the scholarship held out the promise that his son would not
repeat his own mistakes _ getting lost in a huge, uncaring factory
of a high school and ultimately dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an American dream come true for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lombardo's billionaire benefactors, Theodore J. Forstmann, a
Wall Street financier, and John T. Walton, heir to the Wal-Mart
fortune, presided Wednesday as the Lombardos and 32 other
low-income families from as far as Baltimore, Iowa and Dallas,
celebrated winning the scholarships. The New York ceremony was one
of 37 held simultaneously across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the public relations brouhaha, it was clear that
Forstmann's and Walton's immense wealth and charity, and the
dream-come-true of people like Lombardo, had put public education
on the defensive. The sheer volume of applications illustrated the
deep discontent of low-income families with the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In the two-and-a-half-hour New York ceremony, attended by an
assortment of business, political and civil rights leaders, the
word vouchers _ the code for the political movement toward taxpayer
financing of private schools _ never came up. But it was in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Walton compared the response to his scholarship program to the
labor, suffragist and civil rights movements. Andrew Young, the
civil rights leader and former U.N. representative, invoked Rosa
Parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the words of the old Negro spiritual: Great Day!'' Young
thundered, addressing the audience of about 300 families, business
and political leaders. `I don't think when Rosa Parks sat down she
knew what she was doing. I know that the students who had the first
sit-ins didn't know what they were doing. I don't think John Walton
and Ted Forstmann knew what they were doing. I still don't think
they know what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, making a brief appearance, noted that
168,000 New York City residents _ nearly a third of those eligible
_ had applied. Saying that schools chancellor Rudy Crew had made
improvements, he nonetheless added, ``That's a remarkable number of
parents and children who want to be in a school other than the
school that they're in.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy for Lombardo to dismiss the talk as politics. ``Then
again, the school system is a lot of politics,'' he said. ``You
can't run away from that.'' But he did not so readily dismiss the
importance of the scholarship to his son.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to send John Thomas to Mount St. Michael, a Catholic
school, which he expects will promote values and discipline. ``If
he could go into a yeshiva, and it's just as good, so be it,''
Lombardo said. ``It's got to be better than what the system is. He
needs guidance, he needs the right school, he needs a teacher.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lombardo, unable to work because of the back injury, feeds his
family of three small children with his disability payments. He
said he had not yet been told how much money his son would receive,
though he knew the scholarships will be between $600 and $1,600.
But he said he would do whatever it took to raise any shortfall in
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Carol Madden, who lives in Hillside, N.J., said she was
a product of the public schools but believed that they had gone
downhill in the years since she had attended. Her daughter Alyssa
is just finishing kindergarten, she said, and has learned very
little.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Madden wants to send Alyssa to the Kent Place School, in
Summit, N.J. ``You have entree to a lot of things if you graduate
from that school.''
</P>
<P>
   A single mother, she already works two jobs. She will take a
third job, she said, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarship has cracked open a door, she said, ``and I'm
going to kick it open _ by whatever means necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Her only regret, she said, is that she had to choose between her
two children _ Alyssa and Moneisha _ when she applied. She picked
the younger child, who is just starting out. Moneisha, who is 10,
understands, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is tough,'' Ms. Madden said. ``They love each other, and
nobody said it was going to be easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
