<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY SHARES CLIMB AS STOCK RALLY CONTINUES
</P>
<P>
   Strong profit reports helped fuel a rally in stocks as
technology and consumer issues appeared to regain the leadership
they long enjoyed. Stocks tied to the business cycle, meanwhile,
mostly paused after their recent jumps.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite index posted a gain of 79.44 points, or 3.3
percent, to 2,489.08. Combined with Tuesday's rebound, that wiped
out Monday's 5.56 percent slide. The Dow Jones industrial average
climbed 132.87 points, to 10,581.42, a record. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index increased by 29.95 points, or 2.3 percent,
to 1,336.12.
</P>
<P>
   BREAKING AN INTERNET MONOPOLY
</P>
<P>
   America Online was one of five companies chosen to compete with
a government-backed monopoly in the lucrative business of assigning
Internet domains. The surprising choice introduced a seemingly
formidable competitor to the business and prompted questions about
whether smaller companies would ever effectively compete.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS CHIEF RESIGNS ABRUPTLY
</P>
<P>
   Just a little more than five months after boasting about hiring
Philip M. Pfeffer, a longtime book industry executive, as its chief
executive, Borders Group unceremoniously announced his abrupt
departure. The company, the second-largest bookseller in the nation
after Barnes &AMP; Noble, also said that its first-quarter earnings
would be 4 to 5 cents a share, lower than analysts' estimates of 7
cents.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN OFFERS PLAN TO AVOID RISK
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of the Treasury Robert E. Rubin outlined a modest
five-point American plan for warding off the kind of financial
crisis that rocked three continents over the last two years. But
his proposals, which President Clinton endorsed on Tuesday, fell
well short of creating the new ``global financial architecture''
that many policy makers debated in the heat of the crisis in
emerging markets last fall.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ POSTS DISMAL EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Confirming the bad news that led to the ouster of its chief
executive this week, Compaq Computer announced that it earned half
of what analysts had expected only two weeks ago. The company's
chairman and acting chief executive called the results unacceptable
but declined to provide much information to illuminate the sources
of Compaq's problems or to outline its path back to financial
health.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's first-quarter earnings declined 13 percent,
continuing a recent pattern of weak results.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam, still struggling with the effects of excessive
inventories and heavy debt, turned in another round of poor
results.
</P>
<P>
   SEC CHARGES PAIRGAIN SUSPECT
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission accused Gary D. Hoke Jr.,
an employee of Pairgain Technologies, of stock price manipulation
in connection with a fake news report about a takeover of Pairgain
that was posted on an Internet site. The charges echo the federal
fraud charges filed against Hoke last week.
</P>
<P>
   A PLEASANT ECONOMIC CONUNDRUM
</P>
<P>
   Economists find themselves without an explanation of a
felicitous combination that was supposed to be impossible: higher
productivity with lower unemployment and inflation. Michael M.
Weinstein: Economic Scene.
</P>
<P>
   BAN IS THREATENED ON U.S. BEEF
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's executive agency threatened to ban beef
imports from the United States, intensifying a long-running feud
over beef from hormone-treated cattle.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKE-UP AT CREDIT SUISSE
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston replaced Andrew Stone, one of the
pioneers of the $250 billion commercial mortgage securities market,
as head of its real estate finance business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
