<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS INQUIRY ON 2 ARRESTS IN THE SLAYING OF AN OFFICER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ Federal authorities have started an
investigation into possible civil rights violations in the arrests
of two men during the tangled search for the killer of a police
officer in Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were mistakenly identified by witnesses in the case.
The officer, Joyce Anne Carnegie, was shot as she investigated
three robberies on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, Terrance Everett, 24, who contends that the
arresting officers beat him in his home on April 10, was held on
murder charges for six days before detectives verified his alibi
and released him. The other, Earl Faison, 27, a lifelong asthmatic,
collapsed and died in the Orange Police Headquarters on April 11,
less than hour after an Orange patrolman ordered him from a cab.
The cause of Faison's death is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney for New Jersey, Faith S. Hochberg, began the
investigation into events surrounding both arrests earlier this
week, a spokesman, Michael Drewniak, said Wednesday. Drewniak
declined any other comment, saying the investigation was still in
its preliminary stages.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, after the weekend arrest of a fourth suspect in the
case, the Essex County prosecutor, Patricia A. Hurt, defended the
performance of law enforcement authorities in the early stages of
her office's investigation of Officer Carnegie's shooting. Ms. Hurt
said Everett, Faison, and a third man arrested early in the
investigation, James Coker, 29, of Newark, all matched witnesses'
descriptions of the murderer _ a bald-headed black man with a
goatee.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrest on Saturday of the latest suspect, Condell
Woodson, 25, of Newark, on murder charges, Ms. Hurt said detectives
were satisfied that none of the three arrested before him were
implicated in either the three street robberies that Officer
Carnegie was investigating at the time she was shot or in her
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hochberg's investigation does not involve Coker, Drewniak
said. He declined to explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Coker was arrested on drug charges. There have been no
allegations that he was beaten during his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   During her news conference on Monday, Ms. Hurt said she had
asked the New Jersey Attorney General, Peter G. Verniero, to
supersede her office in the Everett case and investigate his
charges of being beaten by members of a law enforcement task force
who arrested him. She has not asked Verniero's office to
investigate Faison's death.
</P>
<P>
   Faison's father, Earl Williams, charged last week, after viewing
photographs of his son's body, that he was beaten to death by
Orange police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt's office said last week that the Essex County Medical
Examiner's office had ruled out kicking, strangulation or beating
as a cause of Faison's death. But it said it could not determine
the cause of death until chemical and other tests were completed.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
