<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRUNFELD-N     04-21 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-GRUNFELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BOAT ROCKS, GRUNFELD IS PUSHED OVERBOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Someone had to be held responsible for the Knicks'
plunge into mediocrity this season, their perilous flirtation with
missing the playoffs and the organizational rifts that had
developed over the shortened season. Wednesday, on the heels of a
four-game losing streak, Ernie Grunfeld became that person when
Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts dismissed Grunfeld
from his position as team president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The change came with eight games remaining in the regular season
and the Knicks facing the prospect of an idle post-season for the
first time in 12 years. It came after a two-month dispute between
Grunfeld and coach Jeff Van Gundy over how to use personnel that
had resulted in mistrust between them and that had filtered down to
the players. In addition, several other problems had arisen
involving on-court and off-court issues, cloaking the team in
controversy as it enters the most crucial phase of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts will assume Grunfeld's responsibilities immediately in
an attempt to eliminate the rifts, get the team back on the same
page and refocus them on the goal of making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a power struggle that was won by somebody,''
Checketts said in a news conference at Madison Square Garden.
``It's never one loss or losing streak. That's not how you make the
decision. It was much more of the continued direction where
critical people throughout the organization did not support the
mission. And there was a division, clearly, and I hold them and
myself responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld, who accepted a position as a special consultant with
the Knicks, had been the team's general manager for eight years.
Yet his close relationship with Checketts did not insulate him from
blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I am very disappointed with the news,'' Grunfeld
said in a statement. ``In sports, as in life, things change. Today
it is my turn for change.''
</P>
<P>
   After Checketts arrived at the team's practice facility in
Purchase to discuss the change with the team, Van Gundy declined to
comment on the situation. Van Gundy is expected to remain as coach,
but his job is considered in peril if the Knicks continue to slide.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, Grunfeld tried to prod Van Gundy into playing
Marcus Camby at the beginning of the season in order to justify the
trade of the popular Charles Oakley and rationalize the $48 million
contract extension he signed Camby to in mid-March. There were also
issues of mistrust after an NBC report March 14 cited sources as
saying that Van Gundy could be fired if he lost to Charlotte that
day. Several members of the organization believed Grunfeld was the
source of that report. And Grunfeld resented the implication.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between Grunfeld and Van Gundy has not been
well-concealed. In an interview Wednesday, Sprewell's agent, Robert
Gist, said the acrimony had disrupted the players. Although he
tempered his comments in comparison to the more strident ones that
were published in Wednesday's New York Post, Gist said he felt
Sprewell was not being utilized to his fullest because of the
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any backbone in the leadership there,'' Gist said
Wednesday. ``Guys are looking over their shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they wanted Latrell, it was a spur-of-the-moment decision
to bring him there. All of a sudden there was a chance to get
Sprewell and they didn't consider where they were going to play
him. They never told him he'd be playing sixth man for them. I
asked Ernie that question specifically a month ago, `Did you say to
him he'd be coming off the bench or that he'd be playing small
forward?' He told me that they would do whatever it takes to win.
Please, spare me the speeches.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Checketts told Grunfeld of his decision to demote him
in a long, emotional dinner Tuesday night, he awoke to Gist's
comments in The Post on Wednesday morning. Just a few days earlier,
Charlie Ward had distributed an article written by Reggie White,
the NFL star who retired this year, that outlined reasons for
banning female reporters from the locker room. Also, the league had
contacted the Knicks about a reported incident of sexual harassment
between Larry Johnson and a team public relations director, Lori
Hamamoto. The culmination of all of the incidents involving players
Grunfeld had assembled, on top of a losing streak that had left the
team at 21-21, presented an image of a team in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   When Checketts arrived to meet with the team Wednesday
afternoon, he pulled Sprewell aside and told him that he held him
accountable for his agent's remarks in The Post. He fined him
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say I'm upset by our record and where we are as an
organization, it's about things like the Larry Johnson situation or
Latrell's agent ripping Jeff and Ernie, I'm not standing for
that,'' said Checketts, who also advised Ward that he was not to
use the locker room as a pulpit for his opinions. ``They say
winning builds character and losing reveals it. Well, as we've
started to lose more than we should, the organization has come
apart a little bit. I'm going to try to step in and see that that
doesn't happen anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts will take every aspect of the team _ from the way the
talent performs to the way Van Gundy coaches _ under his watch
through the remainder of the season and into the off-season. At
some point, he will decide if Van Gundy's job is safe of not. Van
Gundy would not comment on Grunfeld's demotion Wednesday, but one
team official said that if he survives as coach, he will no doubt
ask for more personnel control.
</P>
<P>
   If Checketts decides to clean the slate and begin anew, he could
pursue Phil Jackson as a coach and general manager. If Van Gundy
remains, Checketts may elect to bring in a general manager to work
with him, someone like former Raptors general manager Isiah Thomas
or Utah's general manger, Scott Layden.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts insisted that his decision to remove Grunfeld from his
position was not an order from ownership. Although there have been
times when Checketts remained patient with the state of his team
during this lockout-shortened season, he said the decision to
demote his long-time friend was his.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
