<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0529 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-RACE-PROFILING-N     04-21 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RACE-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 RACIAL PROFILING IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, April 22:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman and Attorney General Peter Verniero of New
Jersey have belatedly acknowledged that state troopers have
improperly stopped and searched black and Hispanic motorists on the
New Jersey Turnpike because of their race. But both officials
largely avoid broader questions of the state police culture and
leadership. Whitman, who harbors senatorial and national ambitions,
needs to exert a firm hand in demanding true systemic reform before
this issue becomes a turning point in her career. For starters, she
should withdraw her nomination of Verniero to the New Jersey
Supreme Court because of his tardiness in rooting out racial
profiling in the state police, an agency that his office oversees.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints have been voiced for years about New Jersey's use of
race-based traffic stops in trying to make drug arrests. In 1996 a
state judge ruled that troopers had engaged in a ``de facto''
policy of targeting blacks for stops and arrests on the southern
part of the New Jersey Turnpike. But the controversy escalated last
year after state troopers shot three unarmed minority men who were
traveling on the turnpike to a basketball clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has said that racial profiling is not tolerated by her
administration, but her response to complaints has been muted and
dismissive. Even after she dismissed the state police
superintendent for offensive remarks linking drug trafficking to
specific minority groups, she reiterated her contention that
illegal profiling was not widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a two-month investigation, an interim report issued
by Verniero this week concedes that the problem of racial profiling
is ``real _ not imagined.'' Some state police have engaged in
``spotlighting,'' or shining their headlights into cars to
determine the race of the driver, and in ``ghosting,'' or
falsification of records to conceal the disproportionate number of
minority motorists stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier evidence showed that 46 percent of those stopped by the
police on a southern stretch of the turnpike were black, even
though only 13.5 percent of the motorists on that stretch were
black. The new report found that although minority drivers made up
less than half the motorists stopped, they represented 77 percent
of those searched.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general has finally taken some corrective action.
He announced the indictment of two troopers for falsifying the race
of drivers they had stopped in an effort to cover up illegal
targeting of minorities, and he said he would drop the state's
appeal of the adverse 1996 judicial decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Verniero report offers some sound recommendations, notably
an early warning system to help supervisors spot the use of
profiling, detailed reporting of stops and searches, more training
and new guidelines spelling out the criteria to be used in traffic
stops. But reforms of law enforcement tactics will be effective
only if there is equal attention paid to changing attitudes and to
a police culture that has allowed illegal practices to flourish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-21-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990421.0530 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIULIANI-POLITICS-NYT     04-21 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATORS RALLY TO GIULIANI CANDIDACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing a possible challenge to his likely bid for
the Republican nomination for the Senate back in New York, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani came here Wednesday to an orchestrated display of
Republican support by senators who proclaimed Giuliani the
strongest candidate the party could field in the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   From a news conference to a dinner with wealthy Republican
donors, Giuliani ate, drank and chatted with Republican senators
who praised his record and in some cases explicitly endorsed him,
as cameras and microphones recorded the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The three hours of festivities seemed designed to dissuade Rep.
Rick Lazio, a Republican from Long Island who has also expressed an
interest in his party's Senate nomination, from entering the race.
Lazio's possible candidacy does not sit well with many Republicans
who prefer that Giuliani be spared a primary before entering a
contest where his opponent could be Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani have both said they are considering
running for the seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lazio is clearly not as well known or as well financed
as Giuliani, a number of Republicans said they believed he could
pose a strong challenge to the mayor in a Republican primary. That
is because he is generally more conservative than Giuliani, comes
from a part of the state which votes heavily in Republican
primaries, and enjoys at least the encouragement _ if not the
explicit support _ of Republican Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The confluence of events Wednesday hinted at the kind of
pressure Lazio could face if he officially enters the race. But in
a caustic statement his office issued even before Giuliani's plane
had landed in Washington Lazio showed no sign of retreating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who will elect the next senator of New York are New
Yorkers,'' Lazio said. ``The ultimate judge of a senator is his
ability to legislate. It's not how much press one gets or how well
a person grandstands.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani declined to comment on Lazio's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday night's dinner with $10,000 donors to the
Republicans' senate campaign committee, Giuliani drew applause as
he said he would welcome a contest with Mrs. Clinton as a way of
exploring the differences between the two parties on a number of
issues including private school vouchers, which Giuliani supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get the chance to run for the Senate against Hillary
Clinton, you're going to see a very strong division in terms of
philosophy: I will be in favor of people and she will be in favor
of government,'' he said. ``It would be a very, very classic
battle, which I would love to undertake.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Giuliani's standing among Republican primary voters in
New York, he clearly appears to be a favorite son here. A committee
of Republicans including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and Sen.
Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., head of the National Republican Senatorial
Committee, presided over an afternoon reception for Giuliani that
was attended by about 250 people, many of them lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``No contribution required,'' the invitation said, making it an
unusual political event in Washington, but one which nonetheless
gave the mayor a chance to meet with people who could write him
checks later on.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, while noting that his committee would not take a
position in a New York race, signaled his own position through his
remarks and by appearing with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every reason to be enthusiastic about the prospect of
Mayor Giuliani running for the Senate,'' McConnell said. ``He can
win. The surveys clearly indicate that.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who will have to leave City Hall in 2001 because of
term limits, made a similar observation. ``I see this as the
opportunity to have the best chance of having a Republican win in
the state of New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who showed up to see Giuliani praised him as well.
``I think he lives up to the good things I've heard about him,''
said Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C. Thurmond was one of the hosts of
Wednesday's reception, but said he had not endorsed Giuliani
because ``he hasn't asked me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
