<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SHOOTING 1ST LEDE WRITETHRU 

</HEADLINE>
 WRITETHR-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: Corrects totals in 4th graph; corrects .9 mm gun to 9 mm
gun in 16th graph 
 
POLICE REMOVE 15 BODIES FROM SCHOOL SHOOTING SCENE 
 
By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
and LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ After a gut-wrenching, room-by-room search by
bomb experts and crime investigators, the bodies of 14 teens and
one adult were finally removed from blood-spattered Columbine High
School late Wednesday, scene of the worst school shooting in
Colorado history.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 15 dead were the two gunmen, identified as senior-year
students, who attacked faculty and fellow students Tuesday with
bombs and gunfire before killing themselves in a second floor
library.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was devastating. I've been a cop for 27 years and a SWAT
officer for 11 years and this was clearly the most devastating and
traumatic scene I have ever seen,'' said Sgt. George Hinkle of the
Lakeside Police SWAT team, among 100 officers called to the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The victims included a computer teacher who coached the girl's
basketball team, 10 male students and four female students. Family
members had endured a nearly 24-hour wait before they were told
whose bodies were lying inside. Authorities withheld names
Wednesday although some families confirmed some victims.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen, who began the rampage at about 11:30 a.m., killed
two students in the parking lot. The two, wearing black trench
coats and masks, detonated handmade bombs and shot students at
point-blank range with shotguns and semiautomatic rifles as they
roamed the school for several hours. Many students were trapped
inside as the ordeal unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen were identified Wednesday as Eric David Harris, 18,
and Dylan Bennet Klebold, 17, seniors who belonged to a social
group calling themselves the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.'' Other students
said the two collected guns, disliked athletes and minorities and
appeared infatuated with Nazi lore. Officials said Wednesday they
had no evidence minorities were specifically targeted.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the two gunmen, in statements issued by their
lawyers, expressed regret to the victims' families and the
community and said they were struggling as well to understand what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen kept SWAT officers at bay until almost 4 p.m. while
many of the school's 2,000 students hid under desks, in closets and
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Wednesday that 16 of the 23 wounded remained in
seven area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Although investigators believe Harris and Klebold acted alone
inside the school, investigators were questioning about eight to 10
fellow members of the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was some evidence to suggest that there were
some other people that were aware. I think we have to pursue
vigorously, at least for the time being, that there were other
people involved in the planning,'' said District Attorney David J.
Thomas of the First Judicial District.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the school and in automobiles in the parking lot
authorities found 30 home-made explosive devices, including Molotov
cocktail-type bombs with matches as fuses and two-foot-long propane
tanks wrapped with nails and attached to pipe bombs. More
bomb-making materials were found in searches of the gunmen's homes.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Sheriff John P. Stone said some of the bombs
were built with timers and designed to spray nails and shrapnel. He
said investigators had not determined if some of the bombs had been
hidden in the school before Tuesday's rampage or how the two
carried their arsenal into the school without being detected.
Witnesses said the two carried duffel bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not something that was done overnight,'' Stone said.
``There was a lot of time planning this sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also seized a sawed-off shotgun and a computer
from the home of one of the gunmen. Stone would not describe the
material found to make the bombs, but said the items were commonly
available.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said eight or nine semi-automatic magazines were found in
the school along with numerous spent shotgun shells. The bodies of
Harris and Klebold were found within a few feet of each other with
undetonated bombs nearby. A 9 mm semiautomatic rifle, two shotguns
with their stocks sawed off and a semiautomatic pistol were at
their sides.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the gunmen were in the library where most of the
carnage took place. Of the 13 victims killed, including Dave
Sanders, the coach, 10 were in the library. The body of the coach
was found in a closet near the library.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Davis, Jefferson County Sheriff's spokesman, said the
investigators were unable to begin the grisly task of examining the
crime scene until after bomb experts swept through the school and
surrounding area searching for undetonated bombs.
</P>
<P>
   One problem was the hundreds of backpacks left behind as
students fled the school.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said SWAT officers from various police departments were
inside the school within 20 minutes of a report of the shooting,
but were hampered by a lack of information about the assailants or
their numbers. About 15 minutes before the shooting began, he said,
a bomb was exploded away from the campus as a diversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 2,000 students in there and no way to identify who the
suspects were,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said three deputies _ exchanged gunfire with the suspects,
including deputy Neil Gardner, assigned as security at the school,
who remained inside during the ordeal. The other two deputies,
Deputy Paul Smoker and Lt. Terry Manwaring, exchanged gunfire with
one of the suspects when he appeared on the roof of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Hinkle said his officers had little information to act on by the
time they arrived at the scene at 12:46 p.m. Upon arriving, he said
his officers first spotted a sign in a window that read, ``Help,
I'm bleeding to death.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a student was holding his arms out of the window of the
second-story library and that the boy was rescued when an armored
car pulled underneath the window and two SWAT officers grabbed the
boy out of the window.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckle said he was unprepared for what he saw when he came upon
the crime scene. He said students and teachers were coming out of
closets, under desks and classrooms as officers made their way
through the school's halls. Officers found students calling for
help on cellular phones or using computers.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers described it as a scene from Dante's Inferno.
</P>
<P>
   Hinkle said he found two areas where propane bombs had been
detonated and the cafeteria floor was under four inches of water
from the school's indoor fire sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we train, we train for EDPs, (emotionally disturbed
people) and it is so rare to have multiple EDP suspects,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of students and supporters gathered at a media staging
area at a nearby park to leave flowers and notes for the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Other students held a vigil at a red Acura car belonging to
Rachel Scott, a junior at the school and one of the victims in the
rampage, crying as they leaned on the car hood draped with flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Jessica Cave, a 16-year-old sophomore who hid in
a small science storage room with 25 to 30 other students for three
hours. The room was at the end of a stairway leading to the
cafeteria on the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right on the other side of the wall,'' she said of the
gunfire erupting in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   She said the students, standing shoulder to shoulder, remained
quiet with a teacher standing at the door using her body as a
barricade until they heard SWAT officers in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Viek, a senior who shared a video production class last
semester with the two suspects, said he gave police three videos he
had made with Harris and Kebold that he described as action-type
movies, but declined to give specifics about their content or
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their videos they were always in their trenchcoats. They
always wanted to be the intimidators. They always wanted to be the
good guys going after the bad guys. They wanted to be the heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the two were loners who liked to listen to German music.
He said they would joke about planning a prank for the Class of
1999 and mentioned that Adolf Hitler's birthday was coming in a few
months. The attack happened on the birthday.
</P>
<P>
   He said he never thought about their plans as more than a
harmless prank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shocked at what they did yesterday. I did not think they
would do what they did yesterday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down here in the suburbs where things are a little quieter
there aren't too many people who want to stand out. They wanted to
stand out.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials said all schools in the Jefferson County Public
School system would reopen today, except Columbine. School
spokesman Rick Kaufman said all the schools were swept for
explosives and that security will be beefed at the entrances of
schools in the district, the largest in Colorado with 140 schools
and 89,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle DiManna, a math teacher and a 1989 graduate of
Columbine, said returning will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't imagine going into my classroom and seeing the
missing seats,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unnerving in some ways. I really want to go back there,
but in some ways, emotionally I don't want to go back there. The
innocence of Columbine High School is gone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she remembers the prom assembly last Friday when
Principal Frank DeAngelis reminded students to be careful on prom
night and talked about the students killed in accidents in previous
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to put another memorial on the wall at
Columbine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Baumgart, a 17-year-old senior who was in Klebold's Boy
Scout troop, said the tragedy extends beyond the loss of lives and
will be carried among the living at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my last day of high school to be that day. It
will be hard but I don't want that to be the last day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NYT-04-21-99 2317EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
