<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8450 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-790&AMP;ADD-NYT     04-21 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: TIDBITS THAT SURVIVED EDITING  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hum in publishing is a book about itself, written by Michael
Korda, who is editor in chief at Simon &AMP; Schuster and with this
book is also sort of the minstrel of the business. At any rate the
anecdotes of his publishing reminiscence, amusing, often wry and
exhilaratingly frank, are being talked about and laughed over
wherever those in the industry gather and someone in the crowd has
actually read the page proofs and is sharing favorite stories.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years a few publishers, editors and agents have become
celebrities similar to, although not quite as excitably visible as,
some famous writers and movie and television executives. So with
the strong word of mouth that this book is getting, the hope by its
publisher is that it will not only interest the natives of the
publishing community but will also have the crossover appeal that
some movie-mogul memoirs do.
</P>
<P>
   The book is ``Another Life: A Memoir of Other People,'' a title
that is precisely accurate if not exactly succulent or stirring.
Its publisher, Random House, has a first printing of 40,000 copies,
which shows considerable faith that the fun of the book and the
publicity it will get will carry it beyond the slender confines of
the industry it covers. The book is scheduled to be in stores next
week.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other books about the incestuous world of
publishing, but none as informative with serious stuff and at the
same time as insouciant as Korda's. The most prominent previous
publishing memoir probably was ``At Random: The Reminiscences of
Bennett Cerf'' (Random House, 1977), which was constructed after
Cerf's death from an oral history in which he had participated and
from his diaries and scrapbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Cerf, a founder of Random House and a true publishing innovator,
was perhaps the first celebrity publisher, having been at the same
time a television game-show panelist. His book was a bland but
charming collection of froth.
</P>
<P>
   This look at publishing was followed in 1991 by Charles Scribner
Jr.'s ``In the Company of Writers: A Life in Publishing''
(Scribner), which was also based on an oral history and was much
meatier and more strapping than Cerf's book. Two years later
Scribner published his second book, ``In the Web of Ideas: The
Education of a Publisher.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about it. There are fewer objective histories of book
publishing than there are of television, which by comparison is in
its infancy. Korda's book is subjective in that he is the glue that
binds the chain of tales together, and he is often at the core of
an anecdote. But essentially Korda is telling his own story through
his experiences with others, which is what the book's title is
about. Thus, we meet writers like Jacqueline Susann (a forthcoming
movie about her is based on one of several pieces from Korda's book
that appeared in The New Yorker), Harold Robbins, Graham Greene and
Tennessee Williams. Korda is a legendry editor, having been at
Simon &AMP; Schuster for 40 years, and an editor who the publisher of
his latest book, Ann Godoff, said ``could edit a novel on the
telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another Life'' was edited by another celebrated editor, Robert
Loomis, and thus it's not surprising that he writes, too, about
other storied publishing executives, including Robert Gottlieb, the
publisher Richard Snyder, Cerf and Max Schuster, a founder of the
house that bears his name.
</P>
<P>
   There is a gleeful, sometimes acid bite to many of Korda's
stories, although he said that ``the last thing I wanted to write
was a mean-spirited book.'' Schuster, for instance, is reported as
being so shy and befuddled that when he was middle-aged and went to
ask a widow for permission to marry her daughter, the woman thought
he was proposing to her. She accepted, and Schuster married the
wrong woman. Of Snyder, for whom he worked and who remains one of
Korda's best friends, Korda wrote that ``one guessed, too, that his
bark and his bite were likely to be equally unpleasant.''
</P>
<P>
   Susann told Korda that ``you're a big-shot editor, but you dress
like a bum.'' She then turned to her husband and manager, Irving
Mansfields, and ordered, ``Give him your blazer, honey.'' The
cashmere blazer had just arrived from the tailor, had 18-karat gold
buttons and sleeves as long as a chimpanzee's arms. Mansfields
couldn't bear to part with it, but the author was not to be
contradicted. ``Bunching the material up behind my back,'' Korda
writes, Susann said: ``It fits fine. It looks great on you, doll.''
Mansfields had tears in his eyes, but gave up the jacket.
</P>
<P>
   As Korda said in an interview, ``people should read my book and
giggle and laugh.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, this is a serious book, and on one level it is an
objective history of book publishing, even if Korda often uses
himself as the jar around which he weaves the industry's
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Book publishing was always a restricted industry, ``a bit like
entering a rather stuffy and self-important club,'' he writes,
adding that one who entered it had ``the satisfaction of being
among well-educated gentlemen of your own persuasion, pursuing an
old, even noble profession.'' It wasn't until the late 1920s and
the 1930s that there was more than one publishing house owned by
Jews, for instance. Then came major houses like Simon &AMP; Schuster,
Random House and Alfred A. Knopf, all founded by Jews who, Korda
writes, were serious businessmen but ``thought that publishing
ought to be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The welding together of pieces of the industry into large
multinational companies could be, but certainly ``isn't necessarily
a bad thing,'' he said in an interview. ``If you buy Knopf, why
would you change it if you bought it because you liked it?''
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``There is somehow a personality that a house had from
the beginning that was replicated by every generation even if the
people there didn't know how it got there. Younger people get it.
There's a certain look to a Knopf book that's unchanged since 1948
or 1958.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go to Random House it's different than Simon &AMP; Schuster
in exactly the way it was different in 1958,'' he continued, adding
that Random House was ``always more manicured, less messy, less
cartons in the halls, freshly painted. The amazing thing about S &AMP;
S is that despite being bought and rebought and resold and being
processed into smaller parts from a larger entity, the spirit of
the place is the same, and was set by its founders. Now I get it. I
realize it's the way it is because that's the way it's always
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Allan Poe once famously wrote that, ``K--, the publisher,
trying to be critical, talks about books pretty much as a
washerwoman would about Niagara Falls or a poulterer about a
phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not Korda, who is a publishing romantic and, like many
romantics, has a lusty ego. Wednesday he called and said of his
book, ``I just reread it, and I giggled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
